<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8976 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-HOUSTONOPEN-HNS &LR;      04-30 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOUSTONOPEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
THE WOODLANDS _ David Duval's presence looms so large these days
that even his wannabes end up leading golf tournaments.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eric Booker laughed about stealing pages from the playbook of
golf's No. 1 player, but it was no joke what he did Thursday during
a two-hole, 4-under-par stretch that launched the PGA Tour rookie
into the lead of the Shell Houston Open.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back eagles, including an ace at the 189-yard 16th hole,
staked Booker to a one-shot lead after the opening round at the
Tournament Players Course at The Woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to be David Duval out there,'' Booker said in
regard to how he handled the pressure of a rare day atop the leader
board. ``I was thinking, `How would David do this?'''
</P>
<P>
   But nobody did it better than Booker, whose 6-under-par 66 put
him in front of University of Texas product Omar Uresti, who had
shot a 5-under 67 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, those were the best rounds on a day that featured
excellent scoring opportunities. While more than half the field (87
players) shot par or better, nobody could post an embarrassingly
low score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course was as scoreable as I've ever seen it,'' said David
Sutherland, who was in a seven-man logjam at 68. ``That's the word
we use out here. Courses aren't `easy.' They're `scoreable.'''
</P>
<P>
   Semantics aside, Booker was his own man after a sluggish start.
Starting on No. 10, he was 1 over par after five holes, then had
lightning strike twice with the eagles as he went 6 under par in a
five-hole span. He sliced another stroke off par the rest of the
way and put himself in a dubious position. Leading any tournament
after one round means nothing. In Houston, it means even less. No
first-round leader has won this tournament since it moved to the
TPC 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it was that easy all the time,'' Booker said of his
eagles. ``But I'm a good player. I'm out there to shoot 66 every
time I tee it up.''
</P>
<P>
   To say the least, Booker isn't a household name. He is a former
teaching pro at Warwick Hills in Michigan, the site of the Buick
Open. Booker saved his pennies and played the Nike Tour for the
past two years. He finished fourth on that tour's money list in
1998, which qualified him to play on the PGA Tour this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got detoured,'' Booker said. ``When I finished college,
I started playing professionally and just didn't have any money, no
financial backing to take it to the level I wanted. So I decided I
was going to have to put the clubs up and go to work. I was a club
pro for four years to make enough money to feel like I could go out
and play.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years of modest earnings on the Nike circuit, Booker
has hit it big the past two years. He finished in a fourth-place
tie at last year's Buick Open, a tournament he played via a
sponsor's exemption. Earlier this year, he led after the second and
third rounds of the Honda Classic before finishing in a tie for
third.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to go some to top what he did Thursday in a 30-minute
stretch of sensational ball-striking that saw him account for
one-third of all the eagles on the course. Despite recovering from
mild flu symptoms he has had the past few days, Booker hit driver
and 5-wood to 25 feet on the 521-yard 15th. The putt was the first
of several lengthy rolls that he would stroke into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Then he bombed in the 5-iron on the 16th, a dandy way to go from
1-over to 3-under in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   However, a bigger surprise than Booker's quick turnaround was
the fact nobody lit up the TPC.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the course was virtually defenseless, there were
lots of scores under par _ 58 to be exact _ but nobody went
nuclear. Still, if you weren't red, you were pretty much dead in
the first round. Behind the seven golfers tied for third at 68, 13
more fired 69s, including the intimidating likes of Steve
Elkington, John Daly, Jeff Maggert and Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of surprised nobody shot lower than they did,'' said
Hal Sutton, among the group at 68. ``I can't say enough good things
about the condition of the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, with ice-cream course conditions and only a light
breeze ruffling the trees, scores plummet like a breakaway
elevator. At the least, there's usually one or two really low
scores. Not so on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Uresti looked for the longest time like he would own the lead.
Numerous players fired at him after he had posted his early 67.
Sutherland, John Cook, Fred Funk and Cameron Beckman all got to
5-under during their rounds but fell back.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Uresti played more tournament golf than anybody else
on the PGA Tour, teeing it up in 35 events. Only a handful of
touring pros play more than 30 times a year.
</P>
<P>
   Scaling back is one of his priorities. A few more rounds like
Thursday's, when he shot 32 on the front nine, might make playing
less often a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played more events than anybody, so I've been on the road
a lot,'' said Uresti, an Austin resident. ``That's why it's good to
be back in Texas. It feels like home, really. I love it here.''
</P>
<P>
   He would like it even better if he could camp out on the leader
board for the rest of the week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
