<SLUG> BC-CAR-CAL500-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURTON IN A LANDSLIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER AND PAUL HELMS  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ There's a good reason Jeff Burton, who sits atop the
NASCAR Winston Cup point standings, clinched first quarter voting
for the prestigious Driver of the Year Award.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, with 10 of 12 first-place votes, more than doubled the
point total for runnerup Jeff Gordon, 102-48. NHRA Winston Drag
Racing Series standout John Force was third. Through the first nine
Winston Cup races of the season, Burton leads Dale Jarrett and Jack
Roush teammate Mark Martin in the points race going into this
weekend's NAPA California 500 at the California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has been very forceful in saying Burton, winner of six
races in 164 starts, is the best driver on the circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Car knowledge, his car knowledge makes him the best,'' said
Martin. ``That sounds weird, but if you took a bucket of parts and
threw it out in the garage for all the drivers to put together,
he'd put together a winning race car before most. When you can do
that, you hold your future in your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   CAMERON ON POLE: Austin Cameron was pleasantly surprised to see
what a little extra practice time can do. It meant a career-first
pole for Cameron in qualifying Thursday for the Winston West
California 200 at the California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron's lap time of 39.853 seconds with a qualifying speed of
180.664 mph edged Ken Schrader's 39.854 and 180.659 and put the
reigning Winston West Rookie of the Year in the front row for
Saturday's race. Cameron also set a California Speedway record,
beating Schrader's 1998 qualifying speed of 179.623 mph by a full
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just floating right now,'' Cameron said. ``I don't want to
get too excited because we still have a race to run. We have a race
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron said he was one of 10 Winston West drivers who came out
to Fontana last week for a practice session. He said the quick
times his car posted then gave him confidence for Thursday's
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew coming in we had a pretty good shot at it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Chase and Rick Carelli finished third and fourth and will
start from the second row.
</P>
<P>
   FULL GARAGE: When Roger Penske built the California Speedway,
many questioned why he had enough garage spaces for 102 cars.
They're not asking that this weekend. The car count this weekend at
Fontana is more than 102 cars.
</P>
<P>
   There are 48 Winston Cup entries, almost 60 for the Busch Grand
National race and 40 in Winston West. What's a promoter to do? Put
them outside.
</P>
<P>
   All the Winston West entries are without a garage area, not an
unusual occurrence in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done this before,'' said series spokesman Kevin Green
about the open air pits. ``And it's not the first time our guys
have come in, unloaded and qualified in the same day.''
</P>
<P>
   $20 MILLION BILL: Bill Elliott, who stunned NASCAR in 1985 by
winning the initial Winston Million, can reach the $20 million mark
in Winston Cup career earnings this week at Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the McDonald's Ford just needs $32,451 this
weekend to join Dale Earnhardt and Jeff Gordon in the exclusive
club. Now in his 24th season, it took Elliott eight seasons to win
his first million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did it all go?'' Elliott asked. ``It's sure a long way
from the $640 I earned at my first race (Rockingham, N.C. in 1976).
I never had a clue in the beginning that this sport would grow to
this level.''
</P>
<P>
   GETTING GROOVY: Ernie Irvan has run four races over the Fontana
track, two each in Winston Cup and Craftsman Trucks. He's excelled
in the trucks, finishing fourth (1997) and second (U98).
</P>
<P>
   The Salinas native is confident fans will see side-by-side
racing all weekend. ``You can definitely run two-wide,'' said
Irvan, who drives the M&AMP;Ms Pontiac and co-owns the Federated Ford
with Boris Said behind the wheel. ``The groove changed from the
very bottom to where you can run a little higher, similar to
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it starts to get like the way it is designed, we are
going to see some good racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan also believes rule changes concerning spoilers will create
more downforce, which will result in quicker times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track records are probably going to fall. If that is the case,
we are going to race better too.''
</P>
<P>
   LEADING DRIVER: Who's the all-time mileage leader in competitive
events at the California Speedway? Would you believe Michael
Waltrip?
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of the two racing brothers, Michael has driven
1,592 miles in four events. He has competed in both Winston Cup
races (highest finish was 11th in the 1997 inaugural) and both
Busch Grand National races (highest finish was fourth in 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Second in mileage is Terry Labonte, who has driven in five of
the nine races sanctioned by NASCAR. Labonte has driven in two
Winston Cup and International Race of Champions along in addition
to the first Busch race.
</P>
<P>
   His best finish was second in the 1997 California 500. Dale
Jarrett and Randy LaJoie have also raced five times on the Fontana
track. Outside of IROC competition, Jarrett's best finish was
eighth in the 1997 California 500 while LaJoie was 10th in the 1997
Busch race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
