<HEADLINE>
TEXAS: DEMOCRATS SAY BUSH IS WAFFLING ON GUNS  
 NEVADA: ANOTHER SENATE RACE HEATING UP  
 CALIFORNIA: DEMOCRATIC FEUD RAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the Colorado school shootings, just about
every presidential candidate, announced and otherwise, has voiced
an opinion on what should be done to control such violence,
including whether there should be more gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   The White House hopefuls have spoken and then moved on to other
issues, with little debate, even though the proposed solutions
differ widely. But down in Texas, a state with its own special
history when it comes to firearms, Gov. George W. Bush, the leader
of the Republican pack, has sparked sharp debate with his take on
the need for new laws, especially those on gun sales.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say Bush is waffling, trying to duck a real stand for
as long as possible, a charge they have leveled at him on other
issues, as have some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the shootings, the House Public Safety Committee
in the Texas Legislature killed a bill that would have required a
background check on every person seeking to buy a gun at any of the
500 or so gun shows and gun flea markets held in Texas every year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the next day where he stood on the bill, the governor, who
committee members said had previously taken no stand, said he
favored background checks. The statement led state Sen. Royce West
of Dallas, a Democrat who is sponsoring a similar measure, to
challenge Bush to work to revive the House measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given his popularity in Texas, he has the power to resurrect
that bill,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor countered that the bill was ``flawed,'' but offered
no specifics, and argued that in any case there was not enough time
left in the legislative session to pass it. Then he suggested that
perhaps Congress should take up the matter.
</P>
<P>
   What did West think of a call for federal intervention by a
Republican presidential hopeful? ``I'm not going to get into
presidential politics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief sponsor of the House bill, Rep. Debra Danburg, a
Houston Democrat, did not hesitate to jump in. ``Smells like
presidential politics to me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the editorial page of the San Antonio Express-News
opined: ``Gun control has a new sense of urgency. And Governor
Bush, who soon may find a new sense of urgency in his life, must
decide where he stands on this controversial issue. Bush's waffling
does not bode well for a presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Senate Race Heating Up in Nevada
</P>
<P>
   When Sen. Richard H. Bryan of Nevada announced in mid-February
that he planned to retire next year, he jolted Democratic hopes for
regaining control of the Senate, or at least reducing the
Republican majority. Hardly any Democrat up for re-election looked
more like a sure winner. So with Bryan out, how is the race shaping
up?
</P>
<P>
   Of the Democrats thinking about jumping in, the strongest
appears to be the state attorney general, Frankie Sue Del Papa. Not
only is she a proven vote-getter in a statewide race, but many
state and national Democratic leaders are pushing her candidacy,
hoping to scare off all other Democrats, heading off a primary that
would be divisive and would chew up campaign money badly needed in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, the strongest candidate appears to be
John Ensign, the former congressman who came within 428 votes of
unseating a Democratic veteran, Harry Reid, in last year's Senate
race.
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans are considering the race, raising the
possibility of a costly, divisive primary. Most prominent among
them is Rep. Jim Gibbons, who represents the largely rural Second
Congressional District and who says he will make a decision by
early summer. He is not as well known as Ensign and would probably
have trouble matching Ensign's campaign organization and money. But
political pros do not count him out.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent poll on the race, conducted last weekend by the
Mason-Dixon organization for the Las Vegas Review-Journal, found
Ensign leading Ms. Del Papa 45 percent to 40 percent in a general
election match-up, with 15 percent of voters undecided. In a Del
Papa-Gibbons match-up, the contest was a dead heat, with each
candidate getting 42 percent of the vote and 16 percent of the vote
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks at this point as if it will be as hot a race as it
was last year,'' Brad Coker, the poll director, told the
Review-Journal, referring to the 1998 Reid-Ensign contest.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, which covered 631 registered voters and had a sampling
error of plus or minus 4 percentage points, did not test Ensign and
Gibbons in a theoretical Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Feud Boils in California
</P>
<P>
   The feud rages on between California's two top elected
officials, Gov. Gray Davis and Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante. The two
Democrats pledged a partnership when they took office last January,
but that was before Davis rejected Bustamante's strong suggestion
that the state not appeal the court decision killing the statewide
proposition mandating an end to state aid for illegal immigrants,
most of them Hispanic. Bustamante is the state's highest elected
Hispanic official.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the latest: Top Bustamante aides on Monday got a message
from the governor ordering them to give up their nine coveted
parking places near the Capitol. Construction crews needed the
space, the message said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bustamante people complained that they were being punished
for their boss' opposition to the aid proposition. The governor's
people flatly rejected the complaint _ and the order stands.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the president pro tem of the State Senate, the
ever-ready-to-brawl John L. Burton of San Francisco, weighed in,
siding with Bustamante in a hearing over whether to build a new
Governor's Mansion. His take: ``I can support a Governor's Mansion
if there are parking places for a lieutenant governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
