<HEADLINE>
HOW WILL LAKERS REVIEW RAMBIS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The calendar shows three games left in the regular
season, and an uncertain future after that point for the Lakers,
whose postseason prospects have to be considered shaky.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly uncertain is the future of coach Kurt Rambis, thrust
into the job on an interim basis Feb. 24 when Del Harris was fired.
When the season ends, whether in the first round in two weeks or in
the Finals in June, Rambis' performance will be evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   That review will be based on a season in which the rookie coach
had to weather the Dennis Rodman fiasco, a major trade and an
insane, compacted schedule that allowed for almost no practice
time.
</P>
<P>
   A fair basis on which to evaluate a coach?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as long as you understand that there are expectations
that a team can have, as long as those expectations are real,
that's a judge of whether a coach can bring the best out of a
ballclub,'' Rambis said. ``Does he have the time to do that? Does
he have the willingness of players to listen to him? I know the
players listen to me, I know the players want to do the right
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had no practice time to get anything accomplished. I
don't care what anybody says _ you can't tell players to do
something and expect them to do it without going over and over and
over it again in practice to build up those consistent habits. And
that's something that interim coaches in any situation don't have a
lot of time to do. And especially in this situation, with this
season, because there is no practice time.''
</P>
<P>
   For one of the few times this season, the Lakers had
back-to-back practices this week, and they were regarded as their
two best sessions this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had had practices like that all year long, I know we'd
be far above where we are right now,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean he's letting himself off the hook, nor
will he say he's entirely satisfied with his own performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the type of person I am. I'm never satisfied with
what I've done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Passing fancy: Kobe Bryant is oft-criticized as a me-first
player, but the statistics show otherwise. He's second on the team
in assists, averaging 3.7 per game before Thursday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant has led or tied for the team assists lead in 16 games
this season, including six times in a recent eight-game span. He
had five by halftime Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way that's gonna help us grow, help us be a better
team,'' Bryant said. ``Kurt is always on me about being a great
all-around player. That's what I'm trying to do. That's what I'm
trying to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been more of accepting a different challenge,'' he
said. ``I'm just getting better at it. The more you do something,
the better you get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
