<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-MOM-FOUND30-C     04-30 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-MOM-FOUND30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mom charged with abandonment
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer and Christian Davenport
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Texas _ Tina Marie Cornelius knew her son and
daughter were injured but abandoned them in a creek anyway,
authorities charged Thursday _ the same day that mourners sang
``Jesus Loves Me'' at a funeral for the children.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius ``observed Amanda and Dominick when they were injured
and lying in the creek bed or ditch,'' according to court papers
filed Thursday in Williamson County. She told an investigator
``that she left the children . . . and thought they were alive when
she left. She indicated she did not go back to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators who found Cornelius in Corpus Christi on Wednesday
brought her back to Georgetown, where she was charged with two
counts of abandoning a child. She remained jailed Thursday night in
lieu of $200,000 bail and faces up to 20 years in prison on each
count if convicted, said Williamson County District Attorney Ken
Anderson. A grand jury will consider additional charges, Anderson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious crime, and it needs to be thoroughly
investigated, so that if any additional charges are filed, that
they will stand up in court,'' Anderson said. ``There is no time
now to be rushing into judgment or making snap decisions or doing
something out of an emotional reaction to a very emotional
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies have said Amanda Lee Miller, 3, was suffocated and her
brother, 2-year-old Dominick Cornelius, died of a fractured skull.
They were found April 19 in Brushy Creek south of Hutto. The court
documents did not say _ and authorities would not discuss _ who
injured the children or took them to Brushy Creek or when they were
taken. Sheriff's investigators have said they believe the bodies
were left in the creek near County Road 137 within hours of being
discovered by a Round Rock couple on an afternoon picnic.
</P>
<P>
   The break in the search may have come Tuesday, after Cornelius
went to a Corpus Christi welfare office to check about benefits,
according to Mauricio Alaniz, a Corpus Christi man who said he
spent almost five days with Cornelius before her arrest. Alaniz
said investigators started questioning his relatives about
Cornelius within hours of her trip to the welfare office, where she
used his mother's address and his sister's phone number. Alaniz
said Cornelius tried to change the personal identification number
for her Lone Star Card, which is used to purchase food and receive
other welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Later that afternoon, law enforcement officers arrived at his
mother's home, saying they were looking for Cornelius in connection
with a child abandonment case, Alaniz said. They found her the next
day at the apartment of one of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators would not discuss the specifics that led them to
Corpus Christi and Cornelius' arrest, but Anderson said the lead
came from basic investigative police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There . . . was some very, very boring, very tedious police
investigative techniques that are used to locate people in very
short periods of time,'' Anderson said. ``It was one of those
techniques that actually led us to where she was. It's just one of
those old-fashioned police things that they do occasionally that
actually pays off and most of the time it doesn't, but that's why
we do it routinely.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherron Heinemann, a spokeswoman for the Texas Department of
Human Services, said the agency's investigations unit cooperates
with law enforcement in ``specific situations'' when agencies make
inquiries into a recipient. She declined to say whether the
department had been contacted by the FBI or Williamson County law
enforcement agencies about Cornelius. She also declined to comment
on whether Cornelius had applied for a Lone Star Card.
</P>
<P>
   From Austin to the bay
</P>
<P>
   According to several witnesses, Cornelius danced at an Austin
topless bar, Expose(accent), on April 20 _ the day after her
children were found. Alaniz said Cornelius told him she arrived in
Corpus Christi on April 21 or 22 and spent a few days on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Alaniz, 31, said he met Cornelius at a carnival April 25 _
Saturday _ and said they spent time at a motel and at the homes of
his friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Alaniz said Cornelius told him she had suddenly decided to leave
Austin after a spat with her boyfriend. So he said she packed up
her bags, got in her car and headed south on Interstate 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was in San Antonio, saw a sign for Corpus Christi and took
that route,'' Alaniz said. ``I just thought she was looking for a
new life. . . . She said she liked me and wanted to stay here and
get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   His sister, Becky Alvarado, 30, met Cornelius and said Thursday,
``I asked her how you could just pick up and leave like that. I
mean, she had no job, no friends, no money. She had nothing here.
And she said, `You've got to think positive.' Those are her exact
words.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius sold $400 worth of mechanic's tools at a pawn shop for
$40, Alaniz said. Cornelius had been taking mechanics classes in
Austin before dropping out earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Alaniz said that Cornelius told him she was adopted and had no
family. Later, after he heard from relatives that Austin officers
wanted to question Cornelius, ``She mumbled to herself, `I don't
know if they are dead or alive.' She said that three times.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaniz said he found a box Cornelius left at his sister's
apartment. In it, he and his sister said, were photos of two
children, a pair of black baby shoes, and a purple infant hat.
Alaniz, who said he was questioned by Texas Rangers and Corpus
Christi police for about four hours, said he turned those items
over to police.
</P>
<P>
   After questioning Cornelius for several hours at the Corpus
Christi Police Department, investigators brought her back to
Georgetown late Wednesday night, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Children's funeral
</P>
<P>
   News of the abandonment charges against Cornelius answered only
some of the questions that have been asked by her family, said
Raelee Cornelius, a cousin in Big River, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's horrible. I don't know why she or anybody would
do that,'' she said. ``She's my cousin. It's difficult to think
about. She's a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Cornelius lived with her cousin's family in the months
following Amanda's birth, Raelee Cornelius said.
</P>
<P>
   About the time charges were being filed against Cornelius, two
tiny white caskets draped with pale pink roses stood at the front
of the Cook-Walden/Chapel of the Hills funeral home near U.S. 183
in Williamson County, where about 80 people filled the pews. A
double-heart shaped arrangement of white carnations and photographs
of the children flanked the gold-trimmed caskets.
</P>
<P>
   In the lobby, artwork by the children, including a sheet of
construction paper with Amanda's name spelled out in macaroni, hung
on the wall, next to a collection of photographs of the toddlers
laughing and playing.
</P>
<P>
   As the service began, a small choir sang a capella arrangements,
including ``Mr. Golden Sun,'' one of Amanda's favorites, and
``Jesus Loves Me,'' which the little girl liked to sing with her
step-grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Some wept quietly during the service, which drew family, friends
and workers from the Briar Patch Children's Center across the
street, where the children had attended day care. A few uniformed
deputies stood at the back of the chapel.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Phil Ware of Westover Hills Church of Christ thanked
the Williamson County Sheriff's Department and the day-care center
for their compassion, and told the audience the children were now
someplace where they were safe and loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amanda and Dominick have made us better because we all know
that they deserved better,'' Ware said. ``In that sense, the length
of Amanda and Dominick's lives extends far beyond the length of
their days.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
