<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON SETS THE STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG PADILLA  
 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ Jeff Gordon might not have the Winston Cup points
lead, but he definitely hasn't lost his intensity.
</P>
<P>
   The driver who has set the standard for all others on the NASCAR
circuit is constantly thinking of what he can do to further
establish his dominance, barely taking time to have a little fun at
a local arcade.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was at another one of those public relations stops
Thursday, delighting a crowd of chanting onlookers as he rallied in
the closing laps to defeat fellow NASCAR drivers Jeff Burton, Ward
Burton, Mike Skinner and Bobby Labonte at, of all things, a NASCAR
video game.
</P>
<P>
   When Gordon spun out late in the 20-lap race and fell into last
place, it looked like racing's Wonder Boy just having another
bad-luck afternoon that has plagued his season. But as the crowd
began chants of ``Gordon, Gordon ...,'' the two-time defending
NASCAR points champion began to weave his way through traffic for
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be a sign of things to come for Gordon, who is fifth in
the points standings despite winning two of the first nine races
this season?
</P>
<P>
   All Gordon could really think about afterward were the two
crashes and the blown engine that have spoiled three real races
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do is try to get top-five (finishes) and try to win
races,'' Gordon said, apparently uninspired by his video-game
heroics. ``We have pressure on ourselves to win every race, or we
won't win the championship. We have run our own races and get the
top fives and wins every once in a while. But we cannot afford to
have problems like we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon expressed a little jealousy over the good luck of points
leader Jeff Burton, who had white smoke pouring out of his car
Sunday as the field approached the starting line of the DieHard 500
at Talladega, Ala. But at full speed, Burton's car ran well enough
to finish 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here (Burton) is, and it looks like he's blowing up on the
first lap,'' Gordon said. ``Then he comes back, and everything is
fine. These are the things you have to work out to win the
championship. Those are the things that aren't going our way, and
that's just the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gordon frets, Burton just plans on taking things as they
come. He and Gordon are the only NASCAR drivers to win two races
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the pressure is on the team that came in as favorites,''
Burton said of Gordon. ``The No. 24 team is not the only team to
beat for the championship, though. He's the favorite, but he's not
the only one.''
</P>
<P>
   If he as the only one, Gordon wouldn't mind. In fact, he would
welcome it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to be the guy that everybody is chasing,''
Gordon said. ``(Dale) Earnhardt has been there, (Bill) Elliott has
been there, (Richard) Petty has been there. That's were you want to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not there right now (this season), and I want to be. It's
early in the season, though, and we still have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   If last season is a fair indicator, Gordon's spot in fifth place
is actually a positive. He was fifth at the same time last season
and cruised to the points championship with a strong second half.
It was a point that Gordon's crew chief , Ray Evernham, made sure
his driver understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good about keeping me positive if I ever get down,''
Gordon said. ``We won 10 races after the (Coca-Cola) 600 in May, so
I think we're fine. We have only won three races up to May. Racing
wins are what we look for.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory in Sunday's California 500 at California Speedway
would give Gordon two victories in the race's first three years.
Gordon won the first race in 1997 and was fourth last year. It
would also give him three victories by the beginning of May and put
him on the same pace he was last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good track, but it's hard to say what will happen this
weekend,'' Gordon said. ``I feel good about the performances we've
had. I feel it's a good track for us. We should be able to finish
in pretty good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory should also stop the, `What's wrong with Gordon?'
questions. For most drivers, just winning the Daytona 500, as
Gordon did to start the season, would be enough to consider it a
good season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a year like we had last year, it's real easy to
look at this season and say, `You're having a bad year,''' Gordon
said. ``We've had two wrecks and a blown engine that have been
horrible for us. We're looking at it and saying, `It's unfortunate,
and we're not having a great year but yet, we're fifth in points.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We're setting there going, `How in the heck are we fifth in
points?'''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it has been a good-luck season after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 24 team, they run good, they make their own luck, a
and you can make your own luck, too,'' said Bobby Labonte, who is
one spot ahead of Gordon in the points standings. ``You look at
their team and figure the luck they make is their own because they
are competitive week in and week out.''
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Gordon is till dealing with a little self
doubt. And it could be enough for other drivers to move in and grab
the title that Gordon has held for three of the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team right now is performing excellent,'' Gordon said. ``I
feel like we're competitive and in better position than we have
been team-wise in along time. It doesn't help that I've destroyed
two cars. That doesn't help. That will leave you behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep this where we run good for two races and crash,
we'll never rebound. You have to have good fortune to win the
championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
