<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON GIVES SONICS CASE OF SUPERSTAR-ITIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Members of the splendid Los Angeles Lakers teams of
the 1980s not only shared five championships but an almost
universal disdain for their star center, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   The aloof, often sullen Abdul-Jabbar was the apparent opposite
of sweet-faced, ever-smiling Detroit Piston leader Isiah Thomas,
except that Thomas was even more disliked on his team and around
the league.
</P>
<P>
   The 1979 champion Sonics watched in dismay the following year as
star guard Dennis Johnson became what coach Lenny Wilkens termed a
cancer, trading him to the Phoenix Suns for Paul Westphal, whose
foot injury made his Sonic career 36 games and the trade the worst
in club history.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest jerk of the 1977-78 season? Elvin Hayes, who also helped
the Washington Bullets win the NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird often went days without speaking to some of his
Boston Celtic teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Most basketball fans know that as much joy as he brought to
fans, Michael Jordan was pure hell on many of his teammates, as
well as franchise staffers. Jordan once so infuriated mild-mannered
Steve Kerr in practice that he punched the demi-god.
</P>
<P>
   This is life at the top of the NBA, as well as all major sports.
Medical clinics abound with cases of severe chappings that occur
among those around ultracompetitive superstar athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Not always, but a lot more than most fans know.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the sexist joke about women? ``Can't live with 'em,
can't live without 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Change it to superstar jocks, and the saying is much more apt.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have an acute case of superstar-itis. It isn't new,
really.
</P>
<P>
   Losing, however, is.
</P>
<P>
   The combination erupted Wednesday in Portland when Gary Payton
flashed his barely dormant anger after a 35-point loss in which he
contributed seven points.
</P>
<P>
   Although Payton now claims he was having a private conversation
with his agent, he is far too savvy to claim obliviousness to the
media hordes swarming the locker room when he said loudly, ``I
don't care about this (expletive) no more. I'm tired of this.''
</P>
<P>
   By itself, the remarks are only intriguing. But in context of
the long-building boil over the worst Sonic season in a decade,
fueled partly by the private grumblings of Payton and his agents
about the club's direction and his future, the tantrum was
revealing.
</P>
<P>
   His agents, brothers Aaron and Eric Goodwin, have been careful
to buff Payton's often belligerent image, which is fine by the
Sonics, who need all the help they can get to compensate for a
slapdash team and atrocious, post-lockout NBA hoops that have left
KeyArena one-third empty at times.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no disguising the fact that Payton frequently can
be a pain in the butt to friends, teammates, staffers and media, as
well as John Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   But since he's also the toughest guy who's ever worn Sonic
green, as well as among the most talented, and since everybody on
the team and within organization is afraid of him, the man goes
unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   Without Shawn Kemp to share headlines and without coach George
Karl to attract attention, Payton's ego and sense of entitlement
are unchecked and overwhelm any judgment he may have about the
consequences of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Payton has indeed made an effort to be publicly diplomatic,
mostly by being either bland or unavailable to media. And given how
much of the burden he has borne this ghastly season, he rates some
slack.
</P>
<P>
   But Payton risks burning up his basketball capital with reckless
self-indulgence, particularly when he's been lousy in two of the
last three games, not to mention being sub-par in up to 10 more
games this short season.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath of the Portland debacle was when the Sonics most
needed leadership. They are desperate to win their last four games,
starting Friday night against Denver, to avoid the humiliation of
missing the playoffs a year after they won a division title with 61
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the organization spent the day furtively
spin-doctoring, which included a rare practice-facility visit from
owner Barry Ackerley, whose mere presence testifies to the fact
that the stakes are higher than a mere playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   The departures of the popular Kemp and Karl have already robbed
the Sonics of sizzle. Stories of Payton's discontent, coupled with
poor personnel decisions and poorer play, further jeopardize the
sellouts and suite sales that have kept the Sonics in the black and
KeyArena off the taxpayers' backs.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's outburst comes not long after his acid blistering of
teammate Vin Baker during a practice. While Baker's play improved
immediately thereafter (before his latest injury), damage was done
to their friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are on decent terms, one Sonic insider put it this
way: ``Gary went too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal on Thursday made a similar point a different way:
``Gary's greatest strength (ultra-competitiveness) is his biggest
weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   However mercurial his play and volcanic his temperament, the
Sonics can't get along without Payton. But getting along with him
would be a lot easier if he breaks with the superstar stereotype
and considers consequences ahead of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
