<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-SCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 EIGHTH GRADERS CHARGED AFTER TALK OF BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They seemed the most unlikely of conspirators: five
eighth graders in an accelerated academic program who shared a love
of computers and never had so much as a blemish on their
disciplinary records.
</P>
<P>
   But their conversation about blowing up their Brooklyn middle
school during commencement exercises in June, overheard late in the
school day on Wednesday by at least three girls, sounded menacing.
And so one girl reported what she heard to a dean at their school,
McKinley Intermediate in the Bay Ridge area.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, one boy was found to be carrying handwritten
notes, on unlined white paper, that diagramed a series of crude
explosive devices, believed to have been copied from the Internet
or a computer disk. In the margins, and in a piece of notebook
paper found on a second student, were the names of a dozen students
and three teachers, preceded by phrases like ``knock him out cold''
or ``kill.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials said on Thursday that the plot might well never
have been consummated, and that no bomb-making materials were found
in initial searches of the student's classrooms or homes. But no
one was prepared on Thursday to label the plans a hoax or a prank.
The students' words, at least, were strong, and these are acutely
tense times in the corridors of the nation's schools.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when schools in more than a dozen states have reported
intercepting plans for attacks loosely modeled on the one that left
15 people dead in Littleton, Colo., last week, officials at
McKinley were leaving nothing to chance. Rather than handle the
matter behind the closed doors of the principal's office, with a
stiff punishment of detention, the school immediately called in the
police.
</P>
<P>
   The five students, all friends and all 13, were arrested just
after the last bell on Wednesday and charged with second-degree
conspiracy, a felony. However their cases are resolved _ they are
to be tried as juveniles in Brooklyn Family Court _ aides to
Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew said that they would probably not be
permitted back at McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb instructions, according to someone who saw them,
contained lists of chemicals like aluminum powder, magnesium and
Ajax that could be used to make a ``chlorine fuse bomb'' or an
explosive with ``American MK 85 firepower.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make napalm,'' someone scribbled at one point. ``Ask if
you need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though no bombs were found, McKinley had the distinct feel on
Thursday of a school that had undergone an attack, not dodged one:
wading through a phalanx of perhaps 20 police officers, at least 20
guidance counselors and psychologists fanned out into classrooms.
By the end of third period, every student who showed up for class
had had some form of counseling, as had their teachers and many of
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   School administrators were heartened that attendance was high:
they said that 82 percent of the school's 1,250 students showed up
for classes on Thursday, only 10 percent fewer than on an average
day. Some students in the eighth grade, though, reported classes
that were half full.
</P>
<P>
   Outside McKinley, a high-performing junior high school that
sends one out of four eighth graders to selective high schools like
Stuyvesant and Brooklyn Tech, the mood wavered from anxiety to
relief to disbelief that a collection of students generally
dismissed as ``nerds'' would have pursued such plans to the point
of putting them to paper.
</P>
<P>
   Though the authorities withheld the identities of the five
suspects because of their ages, their names had raced through the
eighth grade on Thursday as if in a game of telephone. ``He's so
nice,'' Nataliya Shpits, 13, said of one suspect. ``He's the
sweetest guy. I can't believe he'd be involved in something like
this. He used to sit next to me in Spanish class.''
</P>
<P>
   Though neither the police nor the city's Corporation Counsel,
which prosecutes cases in Family Court, offered any motive on
Thursday, a number of students said that the suspects had absorbed
an inordinate share of teasing, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Cuevas, 13, said he had been told by someone who saw a
copy of the ``hit list'' that his name ranked near the top. He was
hardly surprised. He said that once or twice he had smacked one of
the suspects on the back of the neck. ``Like this,'' he said,
pulling his index and middle fingers together. ``I also do a
wrestling move called the spear on him,'' Charlie added. ``It's
like a tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Beladi, 13, said that although most of the suspects had
simply withstood such attacks, one boy in particular had responded.
``He'd write on his tray in the cafeteria, `The end is near,'
`pain,' and `death.'''
</P>
<P>
   All five boys were participants in an elite advanced placement
program, in which they took courses for high school and, in some
cases, college credit, school officials said. ``They're good
kids,'' said Vincent Grippo, the superintendent of Community School
District 20, where the school is situated.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said that school and law enforcement
officials should be commended for treating the matter as seriously
as they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it was serious,'' the mayor told reporters.
``Planning like that is in and of itself very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said that it would be up to the authorities to
determine ``exactly how far they had gone, how far they were
willing to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
