<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9013 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-30 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
22-RUN SALUTE AS M'S MAKE HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Dawn was setting in on the party for the ages, and
David Segui, never comfortable as a wallflower, hadn't had any fun.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners first baseman shared a laugh with designated hitter
Edgar Martinez as the M's batted in the eighth inning Thursday, but
it was nervous laughter. Every Mariner batter besides those two had
gotten a hit by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't very funny,'' Segui said. ``I want to get a hit no
matter what, but you definitely want to join in on the party.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the eighth, Raul Ibanez singled. Martinez
followed with a hit. Then Segui dropped a single to center, scoring
Ibanez and breaking the Mariners' single-game record for runs
scored.
</P>
<P>
   The M's treated every thousandth fan to a run at the Kingdome. A
crowd of 22,078 saw their team punish the Detroit Tigers, 22-6,
breaking by three the previous club record for runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners trailed, 6-1, before putting up 21 unanswered runs.
Eleven came in the fifth inning, setting another M's mark. A grand
slam by Ken Griffey Jr. capped the fifth, and he added a solo homer
in a six-run sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' said third baseman Russ Davis, who had five runs
batted in. ``It's a good time. You don't want to be on the other
side of it, though, and we've taken our share of lumps like that.
But it's good, because we haven't been hitting as a team like we're
capable of. It was nice to see everyone come out and swing the bats
like that. There was no giving up until the very end.''
</P>
<P>
   The early innings showed no signs of what was to come, and even
the historic fifth started off routinely. With one run in and a man
on first, the slow-footed Martinez hit a sharp grounder to third
baseman Dean Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have drawn it up any better,'' said Tigers manager
Larry Parrish _ except Palmer bobbled the ball, losing the double
play, allowing a run and cutting Detroit's lead to 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Then, to paraphrase Rick Rizzs, everybody scored.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Dave Mlicki walked Segui to load the bases. Reliever
C.J. Nitkowski walked pinch-hitter Jay Buhner, bringing the M's
within two. Another reliever, Mel Rojas, hit Davis, making it 6-5.
A Tom Lampkin sacrifice fly evened the score at 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the M's had five runs in the inning on only two
hits. Two singles, a walk and a Griffey slam later, they had their
11 runs. Rojas stayed on to allow 11 runs, the most by any reliever
since the Chicago White Sox' Tom McCarthy in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Nitkowski, who faced just one batter, who took the
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever,'' he said. ``I pitched just as bad as everyone else
did _ I just didn't do it for as long. The wheels just came off for
one day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, for once, had some wheels of their own. New
leadoff hitter Brian Hunter started the game with an infield
single, drew several pickoff throws as he took a lead, then stole
his first base of the year. He would add two more hits, both in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter was with the Tigers when they beat the M's Monday and
Tuesday, holding Seattle to just one run. He was traded Wednesday
in time for the Mariners' 8-6 victory, and with the win, Hunter had
a series sweep. He's glad to be in Seattle, and not just because
the proximity to Vancouver, Wash., allowed him to drive home in
time for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing against these guys, you see how hard they hit the
ball,'' said Hunter. ``It really is incredible. It's a lot better
to be on the same team, because it's almost funny. I laugh at it, I
really do. It's sick _ they hit the ball so hard. Instead of having
to hold it in and put my head down, you can laugh at it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow newcomer Rafael Bournigal, who had two doubles and tied a
career high with three RBI, was another joyous parade participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had so much respect for these guys when I played
against them,'' said the shortstop, signed Tuesday from the Texas
Rangers' Class AAA team. ``I would always look at the way they hit
for some tips. It's just great to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone got in on the act. Second baseman David Bell hit his
sixth home run. Outfielder Matt Mieske hit his second. Buhner got
up only twice before leaving with a pulled hamstring, but he had a
double.
</P>
<P>
   All that hitting, and starting catcher Dan Wilson missed it. He
had the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we were swinging the bats and scoring runs, you want
to be out there,'' Wilson said. ``But there will be more days like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 23 years of the Mariners, there never had been one like
that before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
