</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OWNER REFUSES TO RULE OUT MASSACHUSETTS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (rk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ The owner of the New England Patriots, Robert
K. Kraft, refused a demand Thursday night by Gov. John G. Rowland
of Connecticut that the team reject a last-minute stadium offer
from Massachusetts, but Kraft said he would continue working with
Connecticut for now.
</P>
<P>
   The men left the Capitol by opposite entrances at 11:30 p.m.,
after a tense meeting that lasted nearly four hours. The ambiguous
outcome was a bitter disappointment for Connecticut officials, who
had repeatedly implored Kraft to make a public statement about his
stadium plans as the rival bid by Massachusetts began to
crystallize in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   But these officials said Patriots executives had always begged
off, saying they were concerned about offending someone.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft went into Thursday night's meeting with his own concerns.
Consultants to the Patriots have determined that Connecticut cannot
have the environmental problems with the site solved within the
project's budget or in time for the stadium to be ready for the
2002 season, according to officials involved in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's target for finishing the project had already
slipped one year from 2001, and further delay imperils the state's
contract, according to the negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut officials shuttled in and out of the talks in the
governor's office, looking alternately annoyed and worried.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Kraft left open the possibility that he would
accept the offer from his home state. ``Our goal has always been to
play in a stadium in downtown Hartford in the year 2002,'' he said.
``That was the spirit of our discussion tonight, and as usual it
was very frank and candid.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft and Rowland made brief statements but refused to take
questions. Rowland said, ``My commitment has not changed. The
Patriots' commitment to play here in 2002 has not changed.'' As he
left, Kraft ignored a question about what would happen if that
deadline could not be met.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Gov. Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts and the
leaders of the state Legislature there said they had agreed on a
$70 million subsidy package in an effort to keep the Patriots in
Foxboro, just south of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Although the offer was far less generous than Kraft's signed
contract with Connecticut, it gave him the chance to remain in a
major market and avoid disrupting his team's fans.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, according to his aides, had become ``fed up'' with the
uncertainty bred by Kraft's silence, which organizers of the
Massachusetts effort had taken as encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Rowland essentially ambushed Kraft by arranging
a meeting at the Capitol and then summoning television cameras to
wait outside his office.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that Rowland's office was announcing a news
conference with Kraft, Patriots officials said they believed that
the meeting was to be private and that no statement was planned.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was to begin at 3 p.m., but Kraft was more than two
hours late. He came by chartered airplane, and his staff cited
mechanical delays. At one point, the governor called Kraft's Boston
office and offered to meet him halfway, but Patriots officials
declined.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland then left the Capitol on what his staff called personal
business, and Kraft had to wait more than an hour for him.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft ignored questions as he entered the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In the meeting, according to his aides, Rowland had planned to
demand a ``definitive statement'' about the Patriots' stadium
plans. Otherwise, the aides said, the governor would be convinced
that Kraft was looking for a way to remain in Foxboro.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Kraft has a chance to break his contract with
Connecticut without paying a penalty. That will be 30 days after
Connecticut supplied a report showing its progress in preparing the
stadium site.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in both states said they would be surprised if Kraft
walked away from his Connecticut deal before the Massachusetts
offer had been enacted by the Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
