<HEADER>
A9027 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SAFETY-2N     04-30 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SAFETY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE AFTERMATH OF LITTLETON, COPYCAT THREATS AND CONCERNS FOR
SCHOOL SAFETY
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS for new 2nd, 21st and 22nd grafs on developments in New
Jersey school district)  (sw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 14-year-old boy was charged with murder in Canada, five
Brooklyn youths were accused of conspiracy, a pipe bomb was found
in an Oklahoma school and school districts across the nation were
on heightened alert on Thursday as bomb threats, talk of hit lists
and fears of more violence in the wake of the Littleton, Colo.,
massacre continued to ripple outward.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, all schools in the Hillsborough district in
Somerset County were ordered closed for Friday after several
students received E-mail messages warning: ``If we think what
happened in Colorado was bad, wait until you see what happens at
Hillsborough Middle School on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine days after the horrific shootings at Columbine High School,
there were new reports of threats, of schools evacuated, of police
officers patrolling in hallways, of young people being arrested or
suspended on suspicion of plotting to blow up their schools or to
kill or maim their classmate-enemies.
</P>
<P>
   As the last of the victims' funerals unfolded in Littleton on
Thursday, many Americans were talking about school safety, gun
control, the effect of violence in movies and video games and a
disturbing series of crimes that could have been touched off by
malicious or disturbed copycats.
</P>
<P>
   But actual violence and real bombs have been rare,
law-enforcement officials and educators say, and what has been
stalking the schools is an inordinate fear of death _ largely
fueled by the terrible images of Littleton _ that has reached
epidemic proportions in a nation that seems to have no choice but
to overreact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to react to every little thing now because we can't
separate the real from the imagined,'' said Pat Lewis,
superintendent of the school district in Coalinga, Calif., where
two boys were arrested this week for saying they wanted to blow up
their schools. ``We take no chances. Safety comes first.''
</P>
<P>
   In an atmosphere of extraordinary tension, daily calls from
worried parents have soared in thousands of schools across the
country; teachers have begun to lock classroom doors after tardy
bells; guards are being posted in schools at night to watch for
skulduggery, and dark trenchcoats like those worn by the killers in
Littleton are being banned, with violators suspended or arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the strains, people with real or fanciful grudges have
taken advantage of the tragedy by making anonymous bomb threats by
phone, by leaving apocalyptic notes in school bathrooms or on the
Internet. Some websites have foretold widespread school attacks for
Friday, the anniversary of the death of Adolf Hitler. Authorities
have said they had to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, teen-agers have been branded as snitches for voicing
suspicions or telling of overheard threats, while students have
been arrested for casual remarks made on a school bus, or threats
mumbled in response to a teacher's reprimand. Most students have
been warned in recent days that even joking about bombs and guns
will land them in a police station.
</P>
<P>
   But in a nation with some 50 million students in 108,000 public
schools in which violent deaths have been extremely rare and
declining for years, the turmoil and anguish in the aftermath of
the killings in Colorado appeared to be necessary, both as a
precaution and a catharsis, some law-enforcement officials and
education experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Littleton, less than 1 percent of the schools across
the country have experienced a violent death on campus in the last
seven years,'' June Arnette, associate director of the National
School Safety Center, in Westlake, Calif., said. ``You're talking
about numbers too small to generalize.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added: ``Since Littleton, there has been a ripple
effect. Schools everywhere are in a panic mode, receiving bomb
threats, threats of terrorist attacks. Nobody can ignore those
things. Whether or not schools are safe is not the issue. It's the
perception of safety at this point that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools were still the safest place for kids outside the home,
Ms. Arnette said, but she added: ``We did witness what happened at
Columbine and we can't feel we're totally insulated. We can't hide
our head in the sand and say it's not going to happen here, so
let's not become complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to be the rational of school and law-enforcement
authorities in dozens of states and thousands of school districts
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Diego area, where one suburban high school was
evacuated because of a bomb threat on Thursday, police officers
were on patrol in and around 560 schools with 461,000 students, and
school administrators said they were taking Internet threats on the
anniversary of Hitler's death seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, daily calls to a state Education Department safety
hotline have jumped 40 percent since the Littleton killings,
officials said. Some have told of students wearing black trench
coats, but most have told of students bullying or using threatening
language or of notes, some containing purpored hit lists of people
to be killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something going on all around the state,'' said Jeff
Hodges, the school safety coordinator for the Georgia Department of
Education. ``We have kids taking advantage of a tragic situation.
You have to follow up and take it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In Richmond, Ill., a town of 450 near the Wisconsin border,
Police Chief Charles E. Weidner said a 17-year-old was suspended
from school, and might be expelled, for talking about making a pipe
bomb. ``Don't come to school on Monday, you're too pretty to die,''
the youth told a girl. As the story spread, the police received 10
calls about the boy, and a bomb squad swept through his school and
home, finding nothing harmful. ``The kid was very apologetic,'' the
chief said. ``I feel sorry for him.''
</P>
<P>
   There were dozens of more serious threats in the Chicago area.
At a private school in suburban Oak Lawn, a 15-year-old was
arrested after telling two girls he was going to kill the principal
and a student and plant bombs in the school. He was arrested on a
juvenile misdemeanor charge. Rumors of a planned shooting led to
the cancellation of a pep rally at another school, in Carol Stream,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   In Taber, Alberta, a town southeast of Calgary, a gunman too
young to be identified was charged with the murder and attempted
murder of two 17-year-olds Wednesday in an incident eerily like the
Colorado killings. And in Enid, Okla., a pipe bomb was found in a
school bathroom, though no one was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In Hillsborough, N.J., all of the district's schools were
ordered closed as a precaution for Friday _ and possibly into next
week _ after students received E-mail threats against a middle
school, School Superintendent Robert Gulick said. No bombs were
found, but officials said the schools would not reopen until the
source of the e-mail messages could be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are serious stressful times,'' Gulick said in a letter
to parents. ``We ask that each family use this opportunity to have
a serious discussion with their children. Please reassure them that
safety at school is our number one priority.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, N.Y., five 13-year-old boys, all eighth-graders who
were charged on Wednesday with conspiracy to blow up the McKinley
Junior High School, were released to their parents. The boys were
overheard discussing a bomb plot, and, after being turned in by a
fellow student, were found to be in possession of a bomb-making
manual, though no explosives were uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   But in Fairport, N.Y., near Rochester, the police said they
confiscated gunpowder, propane and bomb-making books at the home of
a 12-year-old sixth grader who they said had been plotting for some
time to blow up his middle school. The boy was suspended, but is
unlikely to face criminal charges because ``it isn't illegal for a
kid or an adult to possess any of the equipment or items he had,''
Police Chief Brian Page said.
</P>
<P>
   In Danforth Junior High School in Wimberley, Texas, where four
eighth-grade students were charged last week with plotting to blow
up the school, life was beginning to return to normal, despite the
presence of a bomb-sniffing dog in the corridors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody overreacted,'' Megan Baker, 15, a ninth-grader,
said. ``I think it was just the wrong time. People would have let
it go if it hadn't happened so soon after the thing in Colorado.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
