<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICSHEAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS BEAT HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ They were cool. Almost too cool. You wanted to know if
the Celtics realized what they had done. You wanted to know if they
had grasped their season sweep of the Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers haven't done that. Neither have the Hawks nor 76ers,
playoff teams all of them. But the 19-28 Celtics went to Miami
Arena Thursday night, won, 107-96, and can now talk trash about the
Heat to their buddies. They can say, ``They've got a bunch of
scrubs on that team; we own them. Check our (3-0) record.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one did that Thursday night. Nope. They were cool. Why
not gloat?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play it this way,'' Dana Barros explained.
``Otherwise you would say, `Look at them getting all excited about
beating Miami.' You know, like we didn't expect to win. So, we've
got to show some pride.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed after he said that. He was near a stat sheet that
showed his 27 points, 8 assists, and 5 steals. That sheet also
showed Paul Pierce's career-high 31 points (although it did not
point out that two of Pierce's three blocked shots were on 3-point
attempts, which rarely happens). And then there was Ron Mercer's 19
points, 7 rebounds, and 6 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Really, everyone wearing green and everyone associated with
players wearing green had a right to be excited. Not just because
they beat the Eastern Conference's top team three times. But they
dropped 31 points on Miami in the first quarter and a staggering 40
in the third. That's right: 40 points. On April 10, the Bulls came
here and scored 49 points in 48 minutes. The Celtics managed 40
points in 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since we started passing the ball, we are a different
ball club,'' Rick Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because good passing leads to open shots which,
inevitably, leads to good shooting. The Celtics took seven
3-pointers in that decisive third quarter and made them all. We are
not talking about ambiguous, his-foot-was-on-the-line 3-pointers,
the kind that are replayed from 10 angles. One of Pierce's 3s was a
25-footer. And then there was a 24-footer by the rookie. Damon
Jones threw in a 24-footer. When the Heat started to get a little
too close, Jones and Pierce made eye contact and, ``Damon told me I
should go back door if they played that way. They did, and the pass
was right there.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. The pass was there and Pierce jammed it through the
hoop. The high point of the quarter was an 89-68 Boston lead. There
were a few smiles on the Boston bench after that _ and some boos
for the Heat _ but the Celtics aren't going to get too excited.
</P>
<P>
   They should.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply thought we had our heads handed to us,'' Heat coach
Pat Riley said. He wasn't finished: ``We just could not stop
them.'' And: ``Their perimeter people actually kicked our butts.''
</P>
<P>
   Barros made Hardaway look like a CYO All-Star trying to keep up
with a pro. The King of the Crossover Dribble often had his dribble
destroyed by Barros, who forced him into nine turnovers. Afterward,
Barros said Hardaway probably did some things that he wouldn't do
in 100 games. Hardaway agreed. He also had a message for the
Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be excited,'' he said. ``They deserve it. They
played harder than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   And although Pitino took on the cool demeanor of his players,
saying that the 3-0 mark against the Heat doesn't mean much,
Hardaway knows better. He knows Riley. He knows that when Riley
sees green he sees red as well as Red. He knows that a loss to
Boston in 1999 is just as bad as one in 1989 or 1984, even if
Boston Garden and its allegedly rigged showers have gone away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me,'' Hardaway said. ``Pat will have us ready for them
next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, all Riley could do was watch the Celtics shoot
with no fear. Alonzo Mourning was on the bench wearing glasses and
a very stylish suit. He has a fractured orbit in his right eye. For
the 15,200 fans here, that meant they had to watch P.J. Brown at
center.
</P>
<P>
   It was a close game for a while (52-51 at the half) because
Clarence Weatherspoon was posting up at will, good for 17
first-half points. But The Spoon, who was a Celtic for a few days
in the summer of '97, had only 2 points the rest of the night.
Neither he nor anyone else could recover from that crazy third
quarter. The lead was cut to 6 midway through the fourth, when the
Heat offered everything they had. But less than a minute later, the
Celtics had the lead back up to 11.
</P>
<P>
   A win over the Heat? 3-0. Pitino over Riley. This is a big deal,
right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's a big deal,'' Pierce said, saying what his
teammates were feeling. ``They are at the top of the division and
we've beaten them three times, so there is no doubt we have the
potential to be in the playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
