<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICNOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR OUT FOR SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Celtics coach Rick Pitino said Thursday night that Greg
Minor is most likely out for the season. The guard caused both team
trainers to head to the court when he grabbed his right hip and
fell in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very serious injury,'' Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics won't be sure how serious it is until this
afternoon. They took X-rays of the hip Thursday night but, trainer
Ed Lacerte explained, ``because he's in a fair amount of pain, it's
difficult to do a complete evaluation on him here.'' The X-rays
showed that somehing was happening with the hip, but Lacerte said
the specifics are unclear because ``you have to get the muscle in
the area to relax so you can put him through some testing.''
</P>
<P>
   Minor was sent to New England Baptist Hospital Thursday night.
He will have an MRI, CAT scan, and X-ray this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Replays of Minor's fall showed that Dan Majerle was nearby, but
it didn't appear that Majerle and Minor collided. Since the
Celtics' injury list is already full, the team will not make any
roster moves for the final three games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anything left after that?
</P>
<P>
   The Heat should have known it was going to be a long night when
Walter McCarty threw in a lefthanded, 11-foot hook shot in the
first quarter. Shortly after the shot, official Hue Hollins
approached Cedric Maxwell at the scorer's table and said,
``Lefthanded?'' . . . There were some boos from the Miami Arena
crowd, but one of the biggest cheers was for legendary Dolphins
coach Don Shula, who attended the game . . . Alonzo Mourning's
injury and the Heat's poor start forced Pat Riley to revise his
policy. He had said that he would play only eight players for the
rest of the season; he wound up using nine. One of them, though,
was not former Celtic Marty Conlon . . . There was a minor
commotion in the fourth quarter. Keith Askins fouled Paul Pierce
hard at about the same time Terry Porter began jawing with Vitaly
Potapenko. Askins was given a technical . . . Pitino was pleased
with Ron Mercer's 19-point, 7-rebound, 6-assist night. ``He had
some open 17-footers and passed them up to somebody else for a
3-pointer,'' the coach said. ``And that's the first time I've seen
that out of him.'' Mercer also played more minutes than anyone on
the court (45) and attempted more shots (20) . . . Heat fans
weren't just groaning about the 107-96 loss to the Celtics Thursday
night. When Indiana beat Charlotte, it nearly guaranteed that the
New Yorkers would get into the playoffs. (The Knicks now lead the
Hornets by 1 1/2 games and own tie-breakers.) If the Knicks wind up
in the eighth spot and the Heat remain first, guess which teams
will meet in Round 1? The teams also play Wednesday, the last day
of the regular season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
