<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS EARN IMPRESSIVE WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Memo to the LAPD: Call off the missing persons
search. Turns out the Lakers are alive and well. And living large.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing a recent trend toward inexplicably uninspired play,
the Lakers pounded the Portland Trail Blazers, owners of the NBA's
best record, into submission Thursday night at the Forum for a
108-89 rout that ranked with the best all-around performances
they've had this season.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry scored a season-high 22 points off the bench,
making 6 of 8 attempts from 3-point range, and Shaquille O'Neal
scored a game-high 38 points as the Lakers defeated the Blazers for
the first time in three tries.
</P>
<P>
   The victory guaranteed the Lakers no worse than a fifth-place
seeding in the Western Conference playoffs and a definite date with
the Houston Rockets in the first round. With the Rockets losing to
Dallas, the Lakers also moved within a half-game of Houston for the
fourth seed, and home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   With the way the Lakers have played the last few weeks _ running
up a 2-6 record and a pair of three-game losing streaks, routinely
dropping games by double digits and surrendering 100-plus points _
the commanding victory was as sorely needed as it was surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that marathon team meeting two days earlier got a few
things ironed out after all. Everything changed, and there was no
mistaking it.
</P>
<P>
   You could see it in O'Neal's grim-reaper expression and his
punishing 22-point first half. You could see it in O'Neal's dive
over the press row for a loose ball on offense, and in Derek
Fisher's diving, rolling snare of another on defense. It was
evident in spindly Travis Knight's tug-of-war steal from the burly
arms of Arvydas Sabonis.
</P>
<P>
   And you could see it in the return of the Lakers' fast break,
left for dead during the recent slump but good for eight points in
the first half _ including a behind-the-back pass from Kobe Bryant
to O'Neal for a dunk and a 270-degree spinning jam from Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, O'Neal even made 14 of 17 free throws to go with 12-of-19
field-goal shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it was everything coach Kurt Rambis expected after the
Lakers' marathon team therapy session Tuesday and two days of
intense practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect more energy and enthusiasm. I definitely expect
that,'' Rambis said. ``That will take care of a lot of things and
get us headed in the right direction. When the fatigue sets in and
the adrenaline wears off, though, we still have to play better
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   An improved showing against the Blazers was not entirely
unexpected. After all, this was the third meeting in 17 days, and
in two previous defeats, both in Portland, the Lakers had cut their
loss margin from 27 points to six. It seemed to be only a matter of
time before they made up the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that we had made improvement (between the first two
games). We did a lot of things we talked about doing,'' Rambis
said. ``I thought we made steps in the right direction up until we
went to Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the start that the Lakers had rediscovered
something in their recent pair of intense practices. For the first
time in eight games they led at halftime, and by a healthy nine
points, 54-45.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, wearing a predatory expression from the opening tipoff,
slammed home 22 points in the half, three points better than his
entire game at Houston three days earlier. But the entire lineup
looked re-energized as the Lakers made 51.3 percent of their shots
and a rejuvenated defense held the Blazers to 39.5 percent
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Damon Stoudamire staked Portland to a quick 5-0 lead to open the
game, and it looked as though it might be another one of those long
nights. But the Lakers kept their heads, even as the Blazers took
as much as a seven-point lead, 31-24, early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then some invisible switch was flipped, and the Lakers quickly
morphed into the Lakers of old. A 10-2 run, fueled by a 3-point
play and a dunk from O'Neal, gave the Lakers the lead, 34-33.
Portland stayed within a point until the Lakers put together a 13-5
run _ with 3-pointers from Derek Fisher and Glen Rice and four
points from O'Neal _ to finish out the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
