r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-REFORM-LADN     04-30 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-REFORM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBYING GROUP SEEKS TO DEFEAT MANAGED CARE BILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ California's main HMO lobbying group proposed an
industry reform package Thursday in a preemptive strike against
more than 150 managed care bills working their way through the
state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, presented in San Francisco at a gathering of
industry officials, encompasses many of the changes under
consideration by state lawmakers. But the plan falls short of
calling for HMO liability, or the right of patients to sue their
health plan for malpractice, which critics say is key to reform.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the association's reform list is the creation of a new
agency to regulate managed care, removing the responsibility from
the Department of Corporations. ``We're not saying who it should
be,'' said Walter Zelman, president of the California Association
of Health Plans, ``but it shouldn't be the Department of
Corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   The DOC has a broad mandate, including the regulation of
securities firms and other financial institutions. A new body
should be set up ``to regulate HMOs and only HMOs so people know if
they have a problem this is who they should call,'' Zelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Also part of the health plan group's proposal: guaranteeing
independent, external review of medical necessity decisions;
streamlining grievance procedures; and requiring that only
physicians or other qualified medical personnel be permitted to
deny care. ``Only a doctor should be able to deny what another
doctor has requested,'' Zelman said.
</P>
<P>
   The association said it recognized the need for reform,
admitting it has lost the trust of consumers. But Zelman said the
more than 150 health bills under consideration by the Legislature
offer a pell-mell approach to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, managed care critics said Thursday's proposal
falls short and is an attempt to head off more stringent steps
being considered in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gesture,'' said Jamie Court, head of the patient
advocacy group Consumers for Quality Care. ``It may help a little
but doesn't include the one thing they need _ the leverage to force
HMOs to approve costly necessary treatments or face legal damages.
This is all carrot and no stick. If there's one thing we've learned
it's that the HMO industry does not behave without sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in the Democrat-controlled Legislature also appeared
reluctant to endorse the industry plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial reaction is one of skepticism because this is a
reform proposal coming from within an industry that has
historically attempted to obstruct reform measures,'' said
Assemblyman Martin Gallegos, D-City of Industry, who chairs the
Assembly Health Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me they're simply jumping on the train that's
already left the station,'' Gallegos said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
