</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT RANGERS, 5-3
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Early on Thursday afternoon, a veteran member
of the New York Yankees _ the team with the $84 million payroll and
the 24 championships and the rich tradition for organization _ was
asked this: ``Who is going to manage your team Friday?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he replied, after a lengthy pause.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees' interim chaos didn't involve two ailing men with
deep roots in baseball and even deeper emotions, the situation
might have seemed comical. But it is bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer, the interim manager, said he will continue running
the Yankees until Joe Torre returns to the dugout, probably
sometime in the next week.
</P>
<P>
   This declaration comes less than 24 hours after he held an
impromptu team meeting following Wednesday's loss and sadly told
his players that he intended to retire after Thursday night's game
against the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the confusion had little effect on how the Yankee
players go about their jobs. Ramiro Mendoza held off the Texas
Rangers for eight innings and earned a 5-3 victory, getting 17
ground-ball outs in the first seven innings with his dynamic
sinking fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees' second baseman, opened the game
with the team's first inside-the-park home run in nearly three
seasons: his line drive skipped past center fielder Tom Goodwin and
rolled to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, seeing immediately that he had a chance to circle the
bases, sprinted the rest of the way, going across the plate with a
headlong dive and then returning to the dugout to catch his breath.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez put the game a bit further out of reach in the
third inning by banging a three-run home run _ his third in two
days _ off the 39-year-old Mike Morgan, who entered the game with a
4-0 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 14-6, and Zimmer, who had intended to fly home
to New York on Friday, will instead accompany them to Kansas City,
where they will play a four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who is recovering from prostate cancer surgery and had a
checkup in St. Louis on Thursday, will have breakfast with Zimmer
on Friday. Whenever Torre returns to his post as the Yankees'
manager, Zimmer says he is ``going home'' to tend to his painful
right knee, which may have to be replaced. Zimmer would not say
that he will retire or that he will quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going home,'' he said. ``I don't know what that means,
except that I'm going home.''
</P>
<P>
   Interpretation is required for a great deal of what has occurred
within the Yankees' organization since Torre was told of his
prostate cancer. With his knee hurting badly, Zimmer had
arthroscopic surgery and was recovering in bed at his Florida home.
When it was determined Torre had cancer, the Yankees' principal
owner George Steinbrenner went to Zimmer's home and all but dragged
him out of bed, telling him he was needed to manage the team.
Zimmer, 68 years old and deeply loyal to the many friends he's made
in his 51 years in baseball, agreed to fill in despite his pain.
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmer and Steinbrenner clashed over the handling of Hideki
Irabu at the end of spring training and, as a result, Zimmer
publicly chastised Steinbrenner, who promised that Zimmer would be
autonomous. Since then, the two have barely spoken, while the
Yankees have won 14 of their first 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   Some former Yankee managers would have preferred that
Steinbrenner remain out of touch, but Zimmer, who is sensitive and
likes to feel appreciated, has been bothered that Steinbrenner has
not called him, according to others in the organization. When
Zimmer was asked whether it was true, he declined comment, adding
that he has had 51 years in the game and didn't want to burn any
bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``George has been good to me,'' Zimmer said, generally. ``He
don't call me. He can do what he wants. In the meantime, I'll do
what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the pain in Zimmer's right knee has worsened. He
had another magnetic resonance imaging test on the joint Wednesday,
and late in the afternoon, a doctor reconfirmed that Zimmer's knee
is in bad shape.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer will try wearing a new brace once it is delivered in the
next few days, and if that doesn't work, Zimmer intends to have his
knee replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer has said for the better part of a month that if his knee
continued to hurt, he would retire once Torre came back. He
mentioned this to his wife, Soot, Wednesday afternoon, but at that
time he apparently had no plans of saying anything to the players.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's game churned his emotions: the Yankees had a 4-1
lead, and in the middle innings, others say, the first base coach
Jose Cardenal made a suggestion in the dugout to Orlando Hernandez,
who was pitching. Zimmer told Cardenal to leave Hernandez alone,
and an argument flared for perhaps 10 seconds. (Cardenal on
Thursday denied that he had any argument with Zimmer. ``Zim and I
are friends,'' Cardenal said, smiling)
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees went on to blow the lead and lose, 8-6, and as the
team trekked into the clubhouse, Zimmer decided to tell the players
that he would retire after Thursday night's game, after 51 years,
and he called a team meeting. ``Last night I had a feeling when the
game was over,'' Zimmer said on Thursday. ``Something hits you and
you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer, however, had not informed Brian Cashman, the Yankees'
general manager, of his intentions, nor had he spoken in specific
terms with Torre about Torre's timetable. After returning to the
hotel late Wednesday, Zimmer called Torre, who told him that
although he would join the Yankees in Kansas City, he wanted to
acclimate himself to travel for a while before taking over. Cashman
did not know of Zimmer's post-game meeting until Thursday morning,
when he was called by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   In telling the players he was retiring before speaking to Torre,
Zimmer acknowledged, he may have ``jumped the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Zimmer's plans are both clear and fuzzy. He will manage the
Yankees until Torre comes back, and then he will go back to his New
York home.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he will rest his knee and then return, Zimmer is not
certain. But Zimmer fought back tears repeatedly when speaking with
reporters on Thursday, and sounded like someone ready to end a long
and loving relationship with baseball.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
