A9041 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     04-30 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS ROMP   17-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Andy Sheets hit a first inning grand slam and helped
the Angels overpower Toronto 17-1 Thursday night at Edison Field
before 18,346 fans.
</P>
<P>
   For the Angels the win marked a smooth finish to an otherwise
tough four-game series with the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike their previous wins this week, no last minute
heroics were required. Anaheim relied instead on the long ball, and
got home runs from Sheets, Randy Velarde, Tim Salmon and Troy
Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   From the first pitch, Angels took to beating up on Blue Jay
starter Roy Halladay. He came into the game with a 2-0 record and a
0.00 ERA. By the time he was taken out after pitching just 2 1/3
innings, Halladay had given up 11 runs, all earned, on nine hits.
He took the loss and dropped to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill got the win for the Angels to improve his record to
1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks began early as it seemed that Halladay couldn't
find the plate in the first inning. On those rare occasions when he
did, he got nailed.
</P>
<P>
   It started innocently enough with a walk to Orlando Palmeiro.
Second baseman Velarde followed up with a hard shot down the third
base line and into the corner for a double that scored Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mo Vaughn came to the plate and knocked in Velarde with a
single. Darrin Erstad, Glaus and Matt Walbeck subsequently reached
base, loading them for Sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets responded with a grand slam. The third of his career and
the Angels' third this season. In his second at bat of the inning,
Palmeiro reached on a single. Velarde flied out to center to end
the first.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson began things for the Angels in the third with a
lead off double. Halladay then walked Walbeck. Palmeiro's single
drove in Anderson. Velarde brought home three runs with a homer,
and put an end to Halladay's outing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the inning wasn't over. Toronto reliever Steve Sinclair was
able to get Vaughn to strike out, only to give up a solo home run
to Tim Salmon to make the score 12-0
</P>
<P>
   Toronto got their first run on the board when DH Kevin Witt
homered off Hill in the top of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Hill began to weaken in the fifth. He gave up walks to Shannon
Stewart and Alex Gonzalez and Tony Fernandez to load the bases with
two outs. He got out of the inning when Mark Dalesandro flied out
to Anderson to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels put one more on the board in the bottom half of
the inning. After Palmeiro was hit in the back with a Sinclair
fastball, Velarde reached on a walk. Vaughn singled to drive in
Palmeiro for the Angels' 13th run of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the sixth, Erstad led off with a double. Glaus brought
him home with a towering 430-foot home run to run the score to
15-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh a Salmon double off reliever Dan Plesac with two
out brought home Velarde for the Angels' 16th run.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets came up with bases loaded and no outs in the eighth and
sacrificed home Glaus from third for his fifth RBI of the night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
