<HEADER>
A9042 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     04-30 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
THE big, bad Dallas Mavericks were back in town Thursday night.
Except, once again, they weren't that bad, were they?
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're still awfully big, though. Too big for the Rockets, it
appears.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Don Nelson may be the master of weird basketball
science, but his use of 7-6 Shawn Bradley as, to quote Rudy
Tomjanovich, ``a goalie'' was sound strategy by any measure.
Bradley, whose wingspan is roughly that of a B-52, tends to be a
disruptive defensive force even when he's simply standing around.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, better make that a deadly force.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bradley's bony, oversized knees, which are about
chest-high to a normal person, almost destroyed Charles Barkley's
hip two years ago. Now, he has added Hakeem Olajuwon to his list of
innocent victims. Olajuwon's left thigh was the loser in a
collision with the humongous fella in the second quarter, and he's
going to feel the painful consequences through whatever's left of
the season, playoffs included.
</P>
<P>
   Dream went on to play the entire third period in hopes of
getting the damaged muscle to loosen up, but the minute he sat
down, it went into a spasm. He returned for only 21 seconds of the
final quarter and was later led to the locker room to start
treatment. Trainer Keith Jones has been charged with working
miracles on him.
</P>
<P>
   Team doctor Walt Lowe called the contusion high up on Olajuwon's
leg a ``deep one'' and conceded there was ``almost no chance''
Hakeem would risk playing against Utah tonight _ as if this eagerly
awaited Western Conference showdown would have been of much real
consequence even with both teams at full strength.
</P>
<P>
   There are apparently no important games anymore, not when
everybody can woof up the joint on any given night. Even the Jazz
had dropped four of six before thumping Golden State in Salt Lake
City on Thursday evening. As for the Rockets, when you can't begin
to handle a Dallas at home, worrying about potential postseason
strategic matchups and thinking about delivering messages to your
fellow, ho-ho, elite teams seems rather silly.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rockets may yet turn themselves around and win another
world championship _ their second one four years ago sprang from a
similarly lackluster regular-season finish _ they've given us no
reason to believe it's going to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mavs wreck you twice on your own floor in a nine-day
span, you aren't exactly primed and ready for the playoffs. Bear in
mind Nelson's lads have won only four road games all season.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any solace in Dallas 91, Houston 81, it's that the
Rockets at least revealed momentary bursts of hustle on defense,
something they hadn't done in the last Mavericks defeat or
subsequent losses to the Clippers and Suns over the weekend. Rudy T
gave his lads bonus credit for effort, but maybe he was just being
nice because he was tired of griping about their lack of same.
</P>
<P>
   How depressed could Tomjanovich have been by such a step
backward after having his spirits buoyed by the blowout of the
Lakers on Monday night?
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks, still a minus-11 to .500 despite winning three in
a row, are going nowhere next week except back on vacation after
what amounts to a 90-day work year. Yet they won the second and
third quarters against the Rockets by a 25-point margin.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to paint a happy face on such a fact when the
second season is less than two weeks off. But all right, let's hear
Tomjanovich try to nonetheless. He made the effort. The least we
can do is listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was good,'' he said. ``I thought we played good.
They didn't sneak up on us this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course they didn't, Rudy. The Mavs had led by as many as 26
points here on April 21. Who could forget such an ambush?
</P>
<P>
   And if the Rockets' defense was so good, why did they manage
just three steals? Dallas, in turn, picked Houston's pocket 12
times, and the Rockets' 16 turnovers (compared to the Mavericks'
season-low six) led to 18 points for the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-point game, that can be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of problems, Dr. Lowe suggested only half-kiddingly
that the league require Bradley to start wearing knee pads, for the
protection of those around him. He has the most dangerous body
parts since Bill Cartwright retired his elbows.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably prudent to stay as far away from Bradley as
possible, particularly so close to the playoffs. Barkley, however,
took a no-fear posture and grabbed a game-high 16 rebounds, five
more than the guy who stands a foot taller than him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're scared,'' Barkley said, ``get a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Rockets have one. Antoine ``Big Dawg'' Carr
figures to replace Olajuwon tonight, guaranteeing several
delightful run-ins with his old friend, Greg Ostertag. At least
that should be worth the price of admission, no matter how dreary
the proceedings may be otherwise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9043 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAVS-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      04-30 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Perhaps the Rockets had not taken the Mavericks lightly last week
after all.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nah, they did. That is what made their latest loss to the
Mavericks so troubling, and far more frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   With that warning and their postgame self-flagellation to drive
them, the Rockets went after the Mavericks on Thursday night with
newfound respect and energy, and still struggled even to be
competitive, losing 91-81.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets lost more than just a second home game to the
Mavericks, their fourth Compaq Center loss to a Texas rival this
season. Their lead over the Lakers has been shaved to a half-game
for the home-court advantage in their now-certain first-round
playoff matchup with the Lakers, with the Rockets hosting the Jazz
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets also lost the comfort of last week's
didn't-play-hard alibi.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't sneak up on us this time,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said, taking no joy from the realization. ``We were prepared. Our
defense was a lot better. We ran the break better. We couldn't
score on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' defense was much better, but nothing special,
especially before Tomjanovich called off the double teams and chose
to live with the Rockets' inconsistent but more effective basic
man-to-man.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, their offense betrayed them. The Rockets never solved
the Mavericks' traps. And with Mavericks giant Shawn Bradley
patrolling the paint, they got next to nothing inside.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley caught Hakeem Olajuwon with a knee to the left
thigh, he left Olajuwon able to play just 12 minutes in the second
half and score only second-half two points. The injury rendered
Olajuwon, who has not missed a game this season, questionable for
tonight against the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   But more than even that concern, the Rockets found themselves
flailing helplessly behind a decided and traditional also-ran with
the Jazz looming tonight and the playoffs in just 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse for us to play the way we're playing this
close to the playoffs,'' said Rockets guard/forward Sam Mack, who
was asked to carry the Rockets' offense through much of the fourth
quarter. ``We have to turn it up and turn it up fast. We don't have
time to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   But with four losses in their past five games, the Rockets seem
to be losing time. If Thursday's performance is to be believed,
their defense might not have been as poor as in last week's losses,
but it was far from good enough to make a playoff run, or at this
point to believe it will turn around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready for this game,'' said forward Scottie Pippen,
who had 16 points and six assists to lead the Rockets. ``We didn't
shoot the ball particularly well. The defense we played was in
spurts. We are struggling to pick up our defensive intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a concern to us. We know teams are coming in and
scoring a lot of points against us. We have to increase our
defensive intensity. We're not playing good basketball lately, and
we're not playing enough defense to beat teams down the stretch. We
have to come out and see what's important to our ballclub, which is
to come out every night and play really aggressive defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're allowing teams to come at us instead of being
aggressive. We're letting them drive down our throats. We're not
going to go too far if it doesn't pick up. We're not going to just
flip a switch and it will all be on and everything will be working
as it should.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Rockets' problems might have been less
troubling, if only because they were unique to playing Bradley and
the Mavericks. For most of the night, the Rockets were sloppy
against the traps, ineffective inside and off-target outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was coming,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We worked on it.
We walked through it. We scrimmaged against it. We knew, `This is
where our shots are coming from.' The way that they scrambled out
there and used Bradley as a goalie, really, was frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   But down by 14, the Rockets came out firing in the fourth
quarter and made a run. Mack and Cuttino Mobley nailed consecutive
3s, but the Rockets did not begin to make a move until they turned
up some defensive heat and worked for better shots.
</P>
<P>
   Mack took over. He missed his next two shots, but when he began
to use quick moves to free himself for jumpers, he scored eight of
the Rockets' next 10 points, interrupted only by a Pippen steal and
drive to a layup.
</P>
<P>
   But as quickly as Mack had heated up, he cooled down, missing
three consecutive shots. The Rockets went instead to Charles
Barkley inside, who scored four quick points.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Trent drove for four quick fourth-quarter points during
Mack's run, finishing with 20. And with 52.1 seconds left, Michael
Finley hit a fadeaway from 22 feet at the shot-clock buzzer, to
match Dirk Nowitzki for a game-high 22 and push the lead back to
10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
