   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-YUGO-ARMY (Washington) _ By triggering a ``rally around
the flag'' effect in Serbia, five weeks of NATO bombing has had the
unintended and unwanted result of uniting the Yugoslav army around
the defense of its country, according to senior NATO and American
officials. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INFRASTRUCTURE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ NATO's five-week
air campaign against Yugoslavia's military, intended to change
President Slobodan Milosevic's policies toward the southern Serb
province of Kosovo, is also destroying Yugoslavia's civilian
industrial capacity and infrastructure, including its highway, rail
and communications networks. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-VOICES (Undated) _ Before the gunshots rang out
during fifth period at Columbine High School on April 20, students
there were busy with the everyday life of American teen-agers. Now,
after a massacre that took 15 lives, they wonder where they and
their school go on from here. A roundtable in which Columbine
students discuss the shooting and their relationships. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS (Undated) _ It appears that the two young
shooters in Littleton got guns the same way most criminals get
guns, not by stealing them but by someone legally buying them. By
Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-TECTONICS (Undated) _ A telling magnetic pattern in the
ancient surface of Mars appears to show that the planet in an early
epoch churned with internal heat, shifting sections of the crust
and other powerful forces remarkably like the geology of Earth
today, scientists reported. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FROG-WARNING (Undated) _ Frogs with multiple limbs and other
deformities have been reported more and more often in recent years,
feeding worries that the frogs are bellwethers of some looming
environmental apocalypse. Two new studies reported in the journal
Science tomorrow conclude that at least some of the frog
deformities are the result of natural parasites in the wild. By
Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLUB-MED (Cancun, Mexico) _ Club Med, the Paris-based company
credited with originating the ``all-inclusive'' vacation, fell on
hard financial times through much of this decade. But Club Med is
now combating its old reputation as a dated swingers' paradise by
offering cultural and literary forums and by renovating its
villages. Attendance is rising, and analysts say Club Med is
finally heading in the right direction. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   REALESTATE-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Until now, Warren Buffett's
best-known real estate gamble was on a bank. Now, the Omaha
billionaire is betting on real estate again. And investors are left
to wonder if he has correctly spotted the bottom _ this time in
real estate stocks _ or if he is he early again. By Richard A.
Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HEDGE-FUNDS (Undated) _ Hedge fund managers, who half a year ago
were beside themselves that regulators might clamp down on their
freewheeling partnerships in the wake of Long-Term Capital
Management's near collapse, are breathing easier. A long-awaited
government report Thursday did not propose, for now, any direct
regulation of hedge funds. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   YOGIBERRA-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Some 35 years after he stopped
playing ball, Yogi Berra is having something of a renaissance as a
pitchman. By Patricia Winters Lauro.
