<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9066 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     04-30 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS ROMP TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ As if attempting to erase the demons of the past week,
the Angels came out swinging Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the team closed out a wild four-game series
with Toronto on a high note _ a 17-1 win before 18,346 fans at
Edison International Field.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have come at a better time for manager Terry
Collins, who watched his team battle back for a win Monday, lose
big Tuesday, then squander a 10-run lead Wednesday, only to be
saved by an eighth-inning Mo Vaughn home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real different type of game where all our players
were swinging the bats,'' Collins said. ``It was the kind of game
we needed to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with a loss by the Texas Rangers to New York, the win
puts the Angels two games behind in the American League West. This
weekend the team will face the Chicago White Sox in another
four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike their previous wins this week, no last-minute
heroics were required. Anaheim relied instead on the long ball,
getting home runs from Andy Sheets, Randy Velarde, Tim Salmon and
Troy Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill went seven innings for the Angels and got the win to
improve to 1-1 on the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I beat Toronto and it's a good
feeling,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's near-fiasco wasn't too far from his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you think about that,'' Hill said. ``Maybe that's
why I walked eight guys.''
</P>
<P>
   From the first pitch, the Angels offense took to beating up on
Blue Jays starter Roy Halladay. He came into the game with a 2-0
record and a 0.00 ERA. By the time he was taken out after pitching
just 21/3 innings, Halladay had given up 11 runs, all earned, on
nine hits. He took the loss and dropped to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks began early as it seemed that Halladay couldn't
find the plate in the first inning. On those rare occasions when he
did, he got nailed.
</P>
<P>
   It started innocently enough with a walk to Orlando Palmeiro.
Second baseman Velarde followed up with a hard shot down the
third-base line and into the corner for a double that scored
Palmeiro. Then Vaughn came to the plate and knocked in Velarde with
a single. Darin Erstad, Glaus and Matt Walbeck subsequently reached
base, loading them for Sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets responded with a grand slam, the third of his career and
the Angels' third this season. In his second at-bat of the inning,
Palmeiro reached on a single. Velarde flied out to center to end
the first.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson began things for the Angels in the third with a
leadoff double. Halladay then walked Walbeck. Palmeiro's single
drove in Anderson. Velarde brought home three runs with a homer and
put an end to Halladay's outing.
</P>
<P>
   But the inning wasn't over. Toronto reliever Steve Sinclair was
able to get Vaughn to strike out, only to give up a solo home run
to Salmon to make the score 12-0.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto got its first and only run on the board when DH Kevin
Witt homered off Hill in the top of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Hill began to weaken in the fifth. He gave up walks to Shannon
Stewart, Alex Gonzalez and Tony Fernandez to load the bases with
two outs. He got out of the inning when Mark Dalesandro flied out
to Anderson to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels put one more on the board in the bottom half of
the inning. After Palmeiro was hit in the back with a Sinclair
fastball, Velarde reached on a walk. Vaughn singled to drive in
Palmeiro for the Angels' 13th run of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the sixth, Erstad led off with a double. Glaus brought
him home with a towering 430-foot home run to make it 15-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, a Salmon double off reliever Dan Plesac with two
out brought home Velarde for the Angels' 16th run.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets came up with the bases loaded and no outs in the eighth
and sacrificed home Glaus from third for his fifth RBI of the
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
