<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEAK PICTURE OF KIDS, GUNS PAINTED BY STUDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Seventy-nine percent of people murdered by children
die by gunfire and most of the time the victims know the killer,
according to the Children's Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In a report titled ``The State of America's Children,'' released
Friday, the fund said guns are widely available to children in
their homes, through ``straw purchasers'' and on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Marian Wright Edelman, founder of CDF, urged churches and
families to unite to give young people a sense of stability and
belonging _ and push for gun control, health insurance, child care
and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are guns the only unregulated consumer products in
America?'' Edelman asked during a session at CDF's national
convention in Houston. ``We regulate toy guns and teddy bears, but
we do not regulate a product that kills 4,600 children a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelman urged support for legislation that would limit the
availability of guns and make safety devices mandatory. She
applauded Atlanta, Miami, New Orleans and four other cities that
have filed lawsuits seeking to force gunmakers to pay the costs of
gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those suits also seek to force the industry to adopt
some gun-sales measures and to put locking devices and other safety
devices on guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not enough to grieve about Littleton. We must do
something about regulating this very dangerous product,'' Edelman
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the fund's report, gunfire kills a child every two
hours. In most cases, it says, children are murdered by adults, but
nearly a third of the 4,600 deaths _ 1,309 during 1996 _ are
suicides.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends domestic-violence counseling and conflict
resolution centers in schools and pushes a series of gun control
initiatives adopted in Los Angeles, which it says resulted in a 30
percent decline in homicides in the first six months of 1998 while
homicides in the surrounding county declined only 1.6 percent over
the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Those initiatives included limiting the number of handguns that
could be bought by an individual to one per month, a measure aimed
at stopping ``straw purchases'' by individuals who resell guns to
minors, criminals and others not legally able to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   The report says Texas ranks second only to California in the
number of children killed by guns, and more children died of
self-inflicted gunshot wounds here than in any other state.
</P>
<P>
   Children have little trouble obtaining guns because they can
borrow or buy them. The report says 40 percent of American families
have a gun in the home.
</P>
<P>
   The Brady Law permits individuals to forgo instant criminal
background checks if they buy firearms from gun show exhibitors,
many of whom are not licensed to make retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Anderson, 18, reportedly bought two shotguns and a carbine
at a Denver-area gun show that were used by Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold in last week's deadly assault at their Littleton, Colo.,
high school.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston, tried unsuccessfully to
have state law changed to require instant background checks for
people who buy guns at gun shows. President Clinton made a similar
proposal in the wake of the shootings at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances of the youngsters are the victims in 54 percent of
cases; 10 percent of the time it's a family member, and 36 percent
are strangers, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   Children are more than twice as likely as adults to be
assaulted, robbed or raped _ and 30 percent of the time the
perpetrator is a schoolmate, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   Edelman also pleaded with lawmakers nationwide to increase
funding for programs to ensure the safety and well-being of
children, such as after-school programs, child care, education and
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Although she said Texas has made some strides in education, she
criticized the state for its high child-poverty rate and lack of
initiative in health care.
</P>
<P>
   Tops on Edelman's ``to-do'' list for Texas legislators is
increasing the number of children covered under the federally
funded Children's Health Insurance Program.
</P>
<P>
   Signed into law in 1997, CHIP provides health insurance for the
children of the working poor. Edelman said Texas ranks last _
behind every state and the District of Columbia _ in the percentage
of children covered by health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Texas House moved a step closer to establishing
a state-supported children's health insurance program to help
low-income residents under age 19. The House unanimously approved
the plan, which now goes back to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Edelman said the age of each child in the family should not
determine individual income cutoff levels for CHIP eligibility.
That could mean that an 11-year-old would be insured, while a
13-year-old sibling would not, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, she said, also ranks near the bottom in the percentage of
mothers who receive no early prenatal care and in the percentage of
children _ 1.5 million, or 26.9 percent _ who are poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to invest in other people's children if we want to
protect our own,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
