<HEADER>
A9086 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FROGS-PARASITES-SFCHR     04-30 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROGS-PARASITES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DISCOVERY OF PARASITES IN FROGS MAY SOLVE ENVIRONMENTAL PUZZLE  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A parasite that favors the hindquarters of
tadpoles may be a key culprit in one of the most troubling
environmental puzzles of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Schoolchildren in Minnesota helped set off nationwide alarms in
1995 when they discovered gross deformities in frogs during a field
trip with their teacher.
</P>
<P>
   All told, reports of missing, malformed or extra limbs have been
reported in 36 species of amphibians from 42 states.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators responded by first looking into such possible
causes as pesticide runoff, microbial infection and depletion of
the ozone layer, which protects against ultraviolet radiation that
can scramble DNA in frog embryos. Now, there is evidence
implicating a different suspect _ the lowly trematode, a parasitic
flatworm no bigger than the period at the end of this sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In two papers released Friday in the journal Science,
researchers said that even the most horrible-looking deformities
may be a natural element in worm survival strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The trematode carries out one stage of its reproductive cycle in
the gut of predatory birds that dine on frogs. By damaging the
hind-limb buds when the amphibians are sprouting legs, the worm
seems to turn frogs into sitting ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we suspect is that those frogs with the deformed hind
legs are more likely to get eaten by a predator,'' said Pieter
Johnson, a research associate at Claremont McKenna College and lead
author of the companion study.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who began his research as an honors thesis at Stanford
University, surveyed 35 ponds in California's Santa Clara County
from 1996 to 1998, finding four with severely abnormal Pacific tree
frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Water tests failed to detect pesticides or other pollutants, and
frog eggs collected from the ponds developed normally in the
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The four ponds turned out to be the only ones among the 35
checked which had populations of a certain aquatic snail that also
serves as a host of the suspect flatworm.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's experiments produced clear evidence that the
trematodes produced the same types of deformities in the lab as
were seen in the wild. Even more striking, the parasites invariably
headed for the hindquarters of the infested tadpoles, forming cysts
near the limb buds.
</P>
<P>
   Just how that can produce deformed limbs is uncertain.
Researchers said it could be simply mechanical displacement of the
limb-bud cells, but another possibility is advanced biological
warfare: The parasites may produce a chemical that mimics a growth
factor involved in frog-leg growth.
</P>
<P>
   Separate field experiments led by Stanley Sessions, a
developmental biologist at Hartwick College in Oneonta, N.Y., found
evidence corroborating previous lab results suggesting trematodes,
rather than a class of chemicals known as retinoids, were almost
certainly the cause of a certain type of hind-limb deformity.
</P>
<P>
   Pollution may explain why some frogs have other problems, such
as matching deformities affecting limbs on both sides of their
bodies. But only the parasites fit the evidence in some of the more
startling cases of frogs with mismatched, missing or extra legs.
</P>
<P>
   Pollutants may be the root cause if it turns out that frog
deformities are in fact becoming more common, as many experts
suspect. Robert Drewes, a prominent frog specialist at the
California Academy of Sciences, keeps a 20-year-old specimen of a
six-legged bullfrog from Fresno on a shelf in his San Francisco
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that these kinds of anomalies have always occurred,''
he said. ``The question is whether they are increasing at a higher
frequency, and if so, what may be causing that.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be due to a naturally occurring cycle, but the cycles may
also be disrupted by such factors as fertilizer runoff, which may
affect the water inhabited by frogs in ways that favor the
naturally occurring parasites.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbing declines in amphibian populations around the world
are still unexplained. Many factors are suspected, including the
introduction of alien species that could be driving frogs into
waters more heavily infested with parasites. Just what's at play is
``a genuine scientific controversy'' that will not be settled by
the latest round of research alone, said David Wake, a professor
and curator of herpetology at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   While the frog debate rages on, many scientists have focused
their attention on the astonishing lifestyles of the parasites
examined in the latest studies.
</P>
<P>
   At an early stage of their development, the trematodes emerge in
huge numbers from the bodies of aquatic snails, creating clouds of
wiggly creatures known as cercariae.
</P>
<P>
   Each cercaria has a chemosensory apparatus it must use to sniff
out a tadpole within about 12 hours. When they find the
hindquarters of the tadpoles, the worms go into a resting state,
forming cysts that seem designed not to kill the host outright, but
rather produce a freakish, slow-moving morsel for whatever
predatory bird happens to wade by.
</P>
<P>
   The cysts dissolve in the digestive tracts of the birds, after
which fresh supplies of worm eggs are produced. If the bird should
defecate in water containing sufficient hordes of snails, the cycle
can start anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trematode life cycle is a wonderful thing,'' Sessions
said, adding ``It seems custom-made to produce frogs with deformed
legs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 0259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 03:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9088 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARS-CORE-SFCHRON &LR;      04-30 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-CORE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MARS ONCE HAD VERY HOT CORE, INTENSE MAGNETISM IN CRUST  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surprising evidence from a spacecraft flying in orbit around
Mars suggests that the planet was once much like Earth is today _
with a hot dynamo at its core, intense magnetism in its crust and
massive continental plates adrift on its surface.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a possibility that deep rifts cleaving the beds of
early Martian oceans between the continents harbored primitive
life, said some of the astonished scientists as they speculated
about the implications of their findings.
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence reported Thursday comes from the discovery of a
series of broad magnetic stripes frozen in the rocky Martian
surface and stretching halfway across the planet. The stripes were
detected and measured by the Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft now
orbiting from pole to pole to create the first high-resolution map
of the entire planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty incredible observation, and we're all blown
away,'' said planetary astronomer David Mitchell at the University
of California's Space Sciences Laboratory in Berkeley, a member of
the spacecraft's magnetometer team.
</P>
<P>
   The report on ancient Martian magnetism is being published
Friday in the journal Science, and it indicates that Mars was much
different when it first formed from the dust and gas surrounding
the early sun about 4 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Early Mars must have had a molten, iron-rich core that acted as
a dynamo to create a major planetary magnetic field, like the Earth
has now, according to Mario Acuna of NASA's Goddard Space Flight
Center _ the principal investigator of the magnetometer project
aboard the spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   The planet's north and south magnetic poles must have reversed
themselves every few thousand years as the hot internal dynamo
rotated, he and his colleagues believe. The dynamo cooled down and
died after no more than a few hundred million years, the
researchers have inferred from the remaining surface evidence,
leaving remnants of the magnetism frozen in the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of a series of broad bands of magnetism _ each
about 20 miles wide and more than 1,600 miles long _ was a total
surprise because it means that Mars in its earliest times was much
more like Earth is today than previously suspected.
</P>
<P>
   On Earth, the discovery about 40 years ago of similar bands of
magnetism at ``spreading centers'' between the vast continental
plates of crust on the ocean beds was the epochal confirmation of
the long-held but then still-controversial theory that Earth's
continents have been ponderously moving and reforming during eons
of geologic time.
</P>
<P>
   That tectonic motion is responsible for some of the Earth's most
furious activity _ its catastrophic earthquakes and its furious
volcanic eruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Molten magma from the earth's interior constantly wells up in
the vents at those spreading centers to move the continents even
now, and the magnetism frozen in that material bears witness to the
fact that Earth's interior dynamo is still active.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it seems, the earliest days of Mars may also have been
marked by a hot rotating dynamo in its interior and by epochs of
continental drift and intense magnetism _ although it most likely
ended when the dynamo cooled and died some time before 3.9 million
years ago, according to the scientists monitoring the spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at Mars today, Mitchell noted, the planet reveals
striking differences between its northern and southern hemispheres.
The northern half, with its vast smooth plains, lies well below the
average height of the planet's entire surface, and appears much
younger than the highlands of the southern hemisphere, which are
heavily scarred with impact craters and wide channels.
</P>
<P>
   But across the southern hemisphere, the Global Surveyor
spacecraft found the broad bands of magnetism akin to Earth's,
which appear somewhat like the bar codes on grocery packages.
</P>
<P>
   The particles of magnetism, generated by the interior dynamo
billions of years ago, were frozen into the rocks as they cooled
from a molten state, and in each band discovered by the spacecraft,
the magnetism points alternately north and south _ evidence that
polar reversal occurred on the planet just as it has done  &LR; for
millions of years on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence left on Mars of the kind of sea-floor
spreading that still occurs on Earth, because the Red Planet's
surface was so furiously churned up by impacts from huge meteorites
and asteroids during its early days. And Mitchell said Thursday he
does not think it's likely that ``hydrothermal vents'' beneath the
oceans ever existed on Mars to harbor living organisms as they do
on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   But to Norman F. Ness of the University of Delaware's Bartol
Research Institute, the idea is not at all impossible. ``It seems
an inevitable conclusion that sea-floor spreading could have
occurred during the earliest history of Mars,'' Ness said, ``and if
so, it could have produced deep-sea vents that were able to harbor
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Acuna too speculated that the early days of Mars saw oceans with
deep seabed vents where life might have existed and fossils might
eventually have been churned up to the fractured surface during the
long years of meteorite bombardment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 0311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9093 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LAWSUIT-SFCHRO     04-30 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LAWSUIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CAMPBELL TO FILE SUIT OVER KOSOVO CONFLICT  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., plans to file a
federal lawsuit Friday to force the Clinton administration to
either declare war against Yugoslavia or withdraw U.S. forces from
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing forward with his argument that the White House has
failed to abide by the Constitution and the War Powers Act,
Campbell will bring his legal action two days after the House on
Wednesday rejected two measures that would have done the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by about 10 other lawmakers, Campbell's suit will seek to
compel President Clinton, under Article I of the Constitution, to
halt U.S. military engagement in Yugoslavia because no declaration
of war exists. The suit will also charge that the administration is
in violation of the Vietnam-era War Powers Act, which prohibits
military action without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has defined the military operation in Yugoslavia
in such terms as an ``armed conflict'' rather than a war, and also
argues that, in any event, Clinton is operating under the authority
granted to him in the Constitution as commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for the suit are murky. Campbell acknowledged that
the Supreme Court has traditionally ``dodged the issue of war.''
But he said the judge who might hear the case, U.S. District Judge
Harold Greene, was generally favorable to a similar case brought in
1990 by former Representative Ron Dellums, a Democrat from Oakland,
against President George Bush during his commitment of U.S. forces
to the Persian Gulf War against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Greene ruled that the case had not yet reached the
``constitutional impasse'' necessary for the judicial branch to
intervene because the House had not voted on the matter. But Greene
ruled favorably on several other grounds, including recognition of
Dellums' standing to bring the case, and ruling that the courts
could not refuse to decide the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush eventually secured congressional approval, but he had begun
assembling troops before doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said the House votes _ which he forced by invoking the
War Powers Act _ cleared the way for his lawsuit and mostly
buttressed his case.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's resolution to declare war was overwhelmingly rejected
by the House, 427 to 2. Had Congress declared war, his suit would
have no grounds; but the House vote now clears the way to go ahead
with his legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's measure calling for an immediate military withdrawal
of U.S. troops from the region was also rejected, 139 to 290, which
he acknowledged hurts his argument for compelling a withdrawal
because Congress passed up a chance to demand that the troops be
sent home.
</P>
<P>
   But the House also, to wide surprise, rejected by the narrowest
possible vote _ 213 to 213 _ a Democratic alternative that would
have shown symbolic support for the administration action in Kosovo
by authorizing the air war, now in its fifth week.
</P>
<P>
   And the House passed, 249 to 180, a Republican alternative that
requires Congress to approve any commitment of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The votes to require congressional approval for ground troops
and the failure to authorize the air war aid his case, Campbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the House had authorized the bombing, the president would
have won in any lawsuit, but it did not,'' Campbell said. And
although the vote to require approval for ground troops is ``not
legally significant,'' in Campbell's view, ``it is powerful in
showing Congress has grave reservations.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans' refusal to support the conflict does not
mean they are unwilling to pay for it. Thurday, a day after they
refused to support NATO's mission in the Balkans, House Republicans
sought to add billions of dollars to the emergency appropriations
bill that will pay for the U.S. role in the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee approved a $12.9 billion
spending bill that contains about $7 billion more than Clinton was
asking for. Republicans said the extra money is needed to beef up a
military that was in a depleted state even before the Yugoslavia
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution invests Congress with the sole power to declare
war, but ever since World War II, presidents have ignored the
requirement, relying instead on their constitutional authority as
commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   During his arguments to the House, Campbell, a former professor
of constitutional law at Stanford University, cited an
authoritative source on the Constitution holding that the framers
``did not want the wealth and blood of the nation to be committed
by a single individual.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
