<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 03:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9094 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUNA-RULES-SFCHRON &LR;      04-30 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUNA-RULES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WHITE HOUSE LOOSENS `DOLPHIN-SAFE' TUNA RULES  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration relaxed standards for
``dolphin-safe'' tuna Thursday, deeply dividing the nation's
environmental groups and earning the enmity of two Democratic
California lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daly announced that mature tuna
caught by large, encircling nets could now be considered
dolphin-safe, a departure from rules that prevailed for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will allow Latin American fishing fleets _
particularly those of Mexico _ to sell tuna that was banned in the
United States under dolphin-safe rules adopted in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmental groups say the new standard will help
international efforts to protect dolphins and other marine life.
But others say it will lead to more dolphins being killed as they
get caught in nets.
</P>
<P>
   Most major tuna processors in the United States _ including
processors of Chicken of the Sea, Starkist, and Bumblebee brands _
said they will require suppliers to provide tuna caught under the
old rules.
</P>
<P>
   The change follows a congressionally mandated study by the
Commerce Department's National Marine Fisheries Service that
concluded there is no definitive proof that encircling mature tuna
with large nets results in significant dolphin mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old rules, only eastern Pacific tuna caught by
encircling schools of juvenile fish or by laying nets under piles
of floating debris could be considered safe.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins typically school with large, mature tuna, shunning
younger fish. And while tuna typically hang under floating logs and
mats of seaweed, dolphins don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was that the old rules were allowing the
destruction of great numbers of juvenile tuna, and that's bad for
the tuna stocks,'' said Scott Smullen, a spokesman for the
fisheries service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were also huge amounts of by-catch _ nontarget species
like sharks, billfish and sea turtles _ coming up with nets set on
debris,'' said Smullen. ``The average was seven to 15 tons of
by-catch'' each time the net is cast, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smullen said that increased vigilance among the tuna boats has
greatly reduced dolphin mortality, and that even tougher
regulations will be applied under the new labeling requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international fleet now has a stake in playing by the
rules,'' he said. ``We're going to have observers on every boat.
We've already gone from 133,000 dolphin kills in 1986 to 2,000 last
year, and we believe we can ultimately bring it down close to
zero.''
</P>
<P>
   The new labeling requirements _ which will go into effect in the
fall _ have split the nation's environmental community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be seen as consumer fraud,'' said Mark Berman, a
spokesman for Earth Island Institute, a San Francisco environmental
organization that has long lobbied against fishing methods that can
harm marine mammals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to once again allow the slaughter of thousands of
dolphins,'' Berman said. ``The only standards that truly protect
dolphins are the old ones, and we'll continue to fight for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman said processors of 90 percent of the tuna sold in the
United States will continue to abide by the old rules. ``We're not
going to see dolphin-deadly tuna in this country again, no matter
what Commerce does.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gerry Leape, the ocean campaign coordinator for Greenpeace
U.S., said the new regulations are appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foreign fleets have already voluntarily reduced their
dolphin kills greatly,'' Leape said. ``They're entering into a
binding agreement to reduce them even further. And they've agreed
to extremely tough regulations on sustainable tuna quotas and
by-catch reductions.''
</P>
<P>
   Leape said the U.S. consumption of tuna has dropped dramatically
in recent years, meaning that American consumers no longer have the
power to dictate terms on tuna fishing methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need these international agreements if we're going to
continue to make progress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer and Rep. George Miller, both California
Democrats, have denounced the new rules, claiming they are based on
faulty science. In a letter to Commerce Secretary Daly, Miller
argued that there is no evidence that dolphin populations are
rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer's spokesman, David Sandretti, said, ``Given the amazing
success of the old rules, she simply feels there is no need to
change them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
