<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9267 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-BIBLE-$ADV02-     04-30 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-BIBLE-$ADV02-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISUSING SCRIPTURE FOR NARROW GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pinched and pernicious spirit of religious exclusivity made
a recent appearance in Alabama, and it's instructive to see what
this new effort to misuse the Bible reveals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago a court there stopped an effort to create a
small town in which organizers wanted to use the Ten Commandments
and the teachings of Jesus as their only laws. There would be a
voluntary mayor, with the 600 residents of the new city of
Brooksville composing the city council. Citizens would provide
their own protection through some kind of community watch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The judge was fortunate. He was able to throw out this
boneheaded bid on grounds unrelated to its theological naivete
because representatives of the 160 people who signed a petition in
favor of forming the town (versus 380 against) failed to meet even
the minimum standards state law requires for an incorporation vote.
But he said they can try again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One special bit of oddness was that none of the supporters
showed up for the court hearing, though 20 opponents did. Beyond
that, the Associated Press reporter who covered the event in nearby
Decatur was unable to find the four men behind the incorporation
effort, despite trying to contact them at home and work. Maybe
they've moved to one of the Middle East theocracies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A possible insight into what motivates them, however, came from
the mayor of Priceville, a small town within which much of what
would become Brooksville now is located. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One of their big issues,'' says Mayor Melvin Duran, ``is that
we won't let them shoot guns off their back porch.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe that's all there is to this. But let's not easily
dismiss the group's proposal that the Bible be the only lawbook.
The Bible has been misunderstood and abused in countless ways for
centuries. Because Jews and Christians view scripture as God's
word, the Bible often has become a weapon to beat others into
submitting to some narrow theological view. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Disclosure: As a mainline Christian, I believe that the Bible
is God's authoritative word for my life and an unparalleled witness
to God's creating, saving and sustaining action. But I'm not among
the literalists, who argue that every word in the Bible is
historically and scientifically inerrant.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One problem with designating the Ten Commandments and Jesus'
teachings as the only laws is trying to take what was written long
centuries ago and apply it to today. It can be done, but not
without serious study. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when one of the Ten Commandments says in the King James
Version of Deuteronomy 5:17, ``Thou shalt not kill,'' Jews and
Christians must decide whether that's meant as an eternal and
inclusive prohibition against killing humans (including those in
prison for murder), quail, ants, germs and goldfish or whether it
means something short of that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Jesus tells a rich young ruler in Luke 18:22 (of the New
Revised Standard Version) to ``sell all that you own and distribute
the money to the poor,'' is he also giving that order to Christians
today? Or is he speaking a larger truth for which his counsel to
the ruler is just the vehicle? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A similar question must be asked of the Jesus teaching that says
if your eye causes you to sin pluck it out, and if your hand is
similarly guilty, cut it off. Will the people of Brooksville
mutilate themselves to atone for their inevitable sins or, instead,
will they be selective about which teachings of Jesus to take
literally? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the current issue of ``Theology Today,'' the Rev. Eugene
Peterson, whose popular paraphrase of the New Testament is called
``The Message,'' has a wonderful essay about the Bible called ``Eat
This Book.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only when we ingest the Bible through rigorous interpretative
study, he says, can it form us into truly spiritual people.
Christians, he says, ``do not simply learn or study or use
Scripture; we assimilate it, take it into our lives in such a way
that it gets metabolized into acts of love. . .'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's the rub for folks who want to create Brooksville. They
are using scripture for narrow purposes. Ultimately, sacred writ
doesn't allow that, for not only do we read it, it reads us. In
that way God's word (not unlike the way the Bible says God's spoken
word created the world) forms people who can live together in
healthy community without needing to hide behind theocratic walls
of fear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Sunday, May 2, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
