<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-$ADV02-     04-30 1989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN EUROPE, HIGH-FLYING SUPPORT FOR NATO AIR STRIKES GETS SHAKIER
CLOSER TO THE GROUND (TROOPS)
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trims.
 &HT;    With EUROPE-DATA-1STLD-$ADV02.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRESDEN, Germany _ Theodore Rieger remembers Europe's last war,
particularly two days near the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   At about 10:30 on the night of the first day, dazzling flares
began floating down from the sky over Dresden's baroque spires and
towers. It became bright as day, bright enough for people on the
ground to see the bombay doors open on the bellies of the aircraft
above.
</P>
<P>
   In two waves, more than 750 British warplanes dropped more than
2,600 tons of explosives and phosphorus, heating the city center to
nearly 1,800 degrees. The inferno sucked the oxygen from the nearby
air, causing hurricane-force winds.
</P>
<P>
   Just after noon the next day, more than 300 American B-17s came
to finish the work with 771 tons of explosives. Nearly 40,000 men,
women and children were killed during the attacks of Feb. 13-14,
1945.
</P>
<P>
   Once known as Florence on the Elbe, the destruction of Dresden
was so complete that officials at the end of the war wondered if it
wouldn't make more sense to bulldoze its remains rather than trying
to rebuild it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, my wife and I lived,'' says Rieger, then a worker in
a munitions factory. ``But we were the lucky ones.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, these two days have revisited Rieger, now 92.
</P>
<P>
   Each night he watches the war in Yugoslavia on television. Each
morning, he switches on the radio for updates. Through the day he
reads newspapers seeking meaning to what he has heard and seen.
</P>
<P>
   The news is breaking his heart. ``When I see what is happening
today, I ask myself again and again, 'Is there no other way?''' he
says during a visit to a meeting place here for elderly people.
``Can't people learn anything? Don't they remember?'' he asks. His
gray-green eyes, magnified by powerful glasses, go still. ``I have
to admit that I doubt the human race.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Europe's political leaders express unusual resolve in
their commitment to bring Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
heel, people in the streets and cafes are not so homogenous in
their views as the war progresses through its second month.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, NATO's attack has enjoyed widespread support. People
who live in the alliance's countries support the attack by a
two-to-one margin, polls show.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Europeans also express profound regret over the war and
concerns about where it is leading them -- including fresh fears of
a confrontation between Russia and the United States or a even
third world war.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the surface of support for NATO rests considerable
uneasiness over the prospect of invading Yugoslavia with ground
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Substantial majorities in Germany, Italy and Greece oppose a
land war, a reality that could force leaders into the unenviable
position of choosing between the imperatives of NATO solidarity and
political viability.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the scale among big European powers are
Britain and France. Majorities in both countries favor sending in
the tanks and troops, polls show.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, Jacques Bousquet made coffee for his first
customer for the day at his cafe in Boulogne-Billancourt, a Paris
suburb. ``You know, nobody wanted this,'' he says, filling a small
white pitcher with hot milk for the coffee. ``Maybe there should
have been more talking, maybe there should have been more
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this diplomacy was going nowhere, nowhere,'' he says. ``If
NATO did not act, it would be as a joke. Now I don't think
Milosevic is laughing. Maybe a few thousand tanks and NATO soldiers
would make laugh a little less.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bousquet -- repeating a sentiment often expressed
in France -- says he would be happier if Europe weren't so
dependent on the Americans. ``This is for Europe to sort out, no?''
he says. ``The Americans are the only superpower, and Europe is
weak -- so I guess we have no choice. But one day, will America
rule the world?''
</P>
<P>
   He responds to his own question with a groan.
</P>
<P>
   Such misgivings seem to nag at France, which long has had a
love-hate relationship with the United States. ``The Americans are
our allies,'' the leftist news magazine L'Evenement du Jeudi said
in a recent editorial. ``But they must not become our bosses, our
brains, our memories.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, these concerns have not dampened French enthusiasm for
the NATO attack. ``I think the shift in French public opinion has
been noticeable and I would even say spectacular,'' said Dominique
Moisi of the French Institute for International Relations. ``The
key element is probably the images of refugees on French television
and a kind of humanitarian reaction: We can't allow that to take
place.''
</P>
<P>
   With strong support at home, British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has been the most hawkish of NATO leaders. His ministers mince no
words in their daily assault on Milosevic, whom they portray as a
mini-dictator in the mold of a fledgling Adolf Hitler. One poll put
support for a ground war in Britain, which has been struggling for
its identity in post-Cold War Europe, at 54 percent -- second only
to France. Indeed, people in Britain seem impatient with NATO for
taking so long to roll the tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that if NATO's major powers decide to
invade Yugoslavia, the shakier members will howl but not stand in
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't expect any country to exercise a veto if the U.S.,
U.K. and France are ready to go in,'' said Michael Clarke, the
director of Defence Studies at King's College in London. ``The fact
of the matter is that I cannot imagine that Germany would be
opposed, but Germany would be divided.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, such a division could be perilous to the fragile young
coalition government of German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
Left-wingers among Schroeder's Social Democrats for weeks have
urged NATO to end its bombing campaign. The junior coalition party,
the ecologist Greens, also are deeply divided on the issue and
would need little impetus to pull out of the coalition causing the
government to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's tenuous hold on power at home is often seen as the
driving force behind his efforts to find a way end the war. In
early April, Germany floated a peace plan, which fell short of U.S.
demands, and Schroeder has taken an assertive role to engage Russia
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, who was an anti-war activist in the 1968 student
uprisings in Europe, has held his government together by arguing
that Germany's interest in NATO is more important than the
country's concerns about the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd expect Schroeder to continue doing what he has done,''
Clarke said. ``He'll tell the other parties that they cannot gamble
with NATO's future.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Opinions in Germany, which is engaged in its first military
action since World War II, tend to be colored by history.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people had done something similar against Hitler in 1933,
much would not have happened,'' said Angela Brauer, a partner in a
Berlin yachting school, who supports the NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Brauer, as with many others interviewed, sees an analogy between
the Nazi's treatment of Jews and the Serb forces' treatment of
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. ``In the beginning of the '30s, Germany
started isolating the Jews, and nobody did anything,'' she said.
``The same would have happened to the people in Kosovo if NATO had
not reacted.''
</P>
<P>
   She would support a ground war, but she is in a minority. More
than 60 percent of Germans oppose a ground war. Opinion in the
formerly socialist east tend to be more solidly against the war,
while people in the west tend to share closer feelings to those of
France and England.
</P>
<P>
   Across Germany, opponents of the war have taken to the streets,
but the demonstrations have been peaceful -- so far. In mid-April,
between 7,000 and 10,000 people held a silent march here in Dresden
against the war.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Among NATO's allies, only Greece has virtually unified public
opinion. Unfortunately for NATO, it's against the war.
</P>
<P>
   Greece already has ruled out its participation in a ground war.
``Greece will not participate in a ground intervention and will
even disapprove of it,'' Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou
said in an interview published Thursday in a Paris daily newspaper.
``We are uncertain of the effectiveness of such an operation. No
one thinks NATO would be unable to win, but the consequences would
be terrible for the co-existence of the people of the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Greeks worry about being entangled in a wider Balkan war and
find kinship with Serbs as fellow Christian Orthodox, whose leaders
often promote age-old paranoia about losing ground to Muslims and
bowing to the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek government has so far managed to balance dissent by
stressing its obligation to NATO and its desire to improve
relations with the rest of Europe. Greece is eager to please the
Western European powers with an eye toward being admitted to the
Euro club with its single currency and unified monetary system.
</P>
<P>
   However, with NATO attacks continuing and talks of ground troops
being heard more and more, tensions in Greece are rising, making
the task for the government even harder.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the opposition turned violent. In Athens, a woman was
killed and a man was seriously injured Tuesday in a bomb attack on
a hotel by a leftist group protesting NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, hundreds of Greek railway employees and Communist
Party members in the port city of Thessaloniki briefly detained a
train carrying NATO tanks and British soldiers to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Such scenes are unsettling reminders of the region's bloody past
and ancient conflicts that sparked the first world war and went
essentially unresolved after the second. People also find it ironic
that the confrontation that never materialized during the Cold War
-- a direct fight between the United States and Russia -- could be
unleashed by the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a high probability that Russia will become more
involved,'' said Domitilla Sagramos, a Russia expert at King's
College in London. ``Russia may become even more involved almost
involuntarily -- the way NATO is being moved to consider a ground
war it didn't expect at the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five years after the end of the last European war, Dresden
is still rebuilding. Scaffolds stand around over the ruins of the
Church of Our Lady, whose great dome once dominated the city's
silhouette. In 1993, the city began a 13-year campaign to rebuild
the church.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, Matthius Griebel also remembers the Dresden
firebombing, but he interprets its lessons differently.
</P>
<P>
   He views the war in Yugoslavia as an attempt to stop the kind of
forces that could lead to a wider European war or a world war, and
by implication, more Dresdens.
</P>
<P>
   He was 8 during the bombings and remembers huddling with his
mother and three brothers and sisters in their cellar as thunderous
explosions rocked the city.
</P>
<P>
   He feels pangs of sympathy when he sees the children cowering in
Belgrade, but he sees the other children, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Serbian family that has to go into the cellar every night
is terrible, but what about the people in the refugee camps, with
no papers, no possessions and worried that they will never go
home?'' asks Griebel, now the director of Dresden's city museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for it all is sitting in a fine drawing room in
Belgrade with fine furniture and fresh flowers,'' he said. ``The
reason is Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
