<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What passed for news Ohio man's most `traumatizing' experience
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The news choppers soared. The print reporters
scribbled. The neighbors came out on their porches to say, ``He was
quiet,'' ``He was a loner,'' and ``He seemed like a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   In what almost seemed like a cosmic commentary on news in the
modern age, it turned out to be turkey skin, the suspected ``human
remains'' that preoccupied Dayton press and police for the better
part of Monday. The most probed and photographed turkey skin in
poultry history, but turkey skin nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bob Shepas, 48, upstanding citizen and homeowner,
sweated under the intense glare of suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal started about 5 p.m. Monday, shortly after Shepas
came home from work. A couple of guys from Roto-Rooter had been out
the day before to take care of a sewage backup in his basement.
</P>
<P>
   When a water department truck pulled up, he hoped workers had
come to inspect the sewage problem. Next thing Shepas knew, police
cruisers and TV news trucks converged on his Shroyer Park home.
</P>
<P>
   Shepas works as a mental health counselor and has a master's
degree in counseling, but he was about to witness human nature in
bizarre new configurations.
</P>
<P>
   Police presented a search warrant and asked Shepas to come
downtown to answer a few questions. It was surreal: How could this
be happening? Roto-Rooter workers, it turns out, tipped off police
after finding the turkey skin. The men told Shepas they suspected
it could be human remains, but he wasn't worried; the gunk looked
like chicken skin to him. So he made light of it, played along,
cracked a joke or two about throwing the bones out the back window.
</P>
<P>
   Now police tape blocked access to a nearby street, and TV crews
broadcast top-of-the-hour reports from ``the grisly scene.'' The
experience ``was traumatizing, overwhelming _ an all-pervasive
feeling of dread and amazement,'' Shepas said. ``So much manpower,
money and effort was being expended to follow up such a flimsy
lead. I understand the community is a little paranoid since the
Kettering girl disappeared, but this was a very blatant
overreaction.''
</P>
<P>
   A detective or two could have accomplished the job, Shepas said:
``Instead, they just brought out the whole cavalry.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, ``My neighbors said nice things about me to
the press, and the people who know me have been very supportive,''
Shepas said. ``That has been a blessing to know I'll have people
who will stand by me in this kind of storm.''
</P>
<P>
   It was from TV, not police, Shepas said, he learned the case was
closed. His clothing hasn't been returned. ``I'm still in the
dark,'' he said. ``I've heard nothing from the police about the
status of the case. My house is trashed. There has been no
followup, no apology, no nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dayton police spokeswoman Carol Johnson, ``This poor man, I
do understand his concern. We did have a responsibility to follow
up any possibilities. Everybody is doing what they're supposed to
do, and unfortunately he got caught in the middle of this mess.''
Johnson said the police department owes Shepas some ``closure and
an explanation for why we did what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the media coverage, Shepas shrugged, ``It's a daily
entertainment package, and they call it the news.''
</P>
<P>
   All this over globs of turkey skin _ nothing even from his own
kitchen _ that backed into his sewer.
</P>
<P>
   Shepas doesn't cook.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
