<HEADER>
A9275 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN01-COX     04-30 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I hereby resign from the Information Age
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Last winter, when we were planning our
nearly monthlong excursion to Australia, New Zealand and the Fiji
Islands, my wife came up with what she thought would be an easy and
economical way to stay in touch with folks back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you get your laptop rigged for e-mail?'' she
suggested. I have a laptop computer I use to write and transmit my
column to the newspaper when I'm out of town.
</P>
<P>
   I was reluctant to accept her suggestion. For months, and
despite public ridicule, I had refused to be caught up in the
electronic mail craze. I was perfectly content to communicate
through the post office by what S.J. Overstreet derisively refers
to as ``snail mail.''
</P>
<P>
   After checking the cost of overseas telephone calls, I agreed to
sign on with America Online. Barbara Allison, who must have gone to
Georgia Tech, agreed to install the necessary software in my
laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara assured me I would have no trouble sending or receiving
e-mail in a foreign country. All I had to do when we got to our
hotel room in Sydney, or wherever, was plug in and let the computer
dial the preinstalled local access number. It wasn't that simple.
</P>
<P>
   In foreign countries electrical outlets and telephone jacks
aren't the same as ours. You need adapters. After an afternoon of
telephoning and walking streets, I located adapters that let me
connect without causing a major electrical explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The laptop made a few growling noises and then started talking.
``I'm sorry. The number you have dialed has been changed. Please
hang up and try again.'' By the time I got the new access number,
at a cost of several calls, we were finished with Sydney and on the
way to Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, we were introduced to a phenomenon called the
Internet Cafe. They are all over Australia and New Zealand. When
you buy a large cup of coffee you can use the house computer for
free e-mail. If you don't want coffee you can e-mail for an hour
for about $3.50 in American dollars. I was happy to catch our
granddaughter online in Fayetteville for a back-and-forth chat, and
even happier to give up on the laptop.
</P>
<P>
   While we were away, everybody I know and many I don't found out
I was on e-mail. They sent humorous messages to each other
commenting on my belated emergence from the Pony Express era. They
sent copies of their messages to me.
</P>
<P>
   E-mailers, I discovered, compile lists of hundreds of other
e-mailers. When one sends an e-mail, a single keystroke forwards
the message to everyone on the lists, and finds its way to all the
other lists. Hundreds, perhaps thousands, of e-mails are soon
flying back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks I've received jokes, poems, book excerpts,
travelogues and Bible passages from folks I haven't heard from
since Harry Truman was in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted from sorting e-mail on the off-chance an important
message might slip through, I was agreeable when my wife suggested
a few days' R&AMP;R in St. Simons.
</P>
<P>
   I carried the laptop along to write my column and transmit it
back to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   When I sat down to write, strange things happened. A paragraph
suddenly disappeared. Mystery messages popped on the screen.
Halfway through, a large America Online icon, in multicolors,
superimposed itself over my prose. ``Welcome!'' declared the laptop
voice. ``You've got mail.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't want mail. I wanted to finish my column and go to the
beach. I shut the machine and took a walk. Sometimes these things
will fix themselves if left alone.
</P>
<P>
   When I tried to crank the laptop the next morning, nothing
happened. I pushed the restart button. A light flashed. The
normally blue screen turned half yellow and half black. The
keyboard didn't respond.
</P>
<P>
   I telephoned Dave McLean, the newspaper's computer guru, to see
if he could tell me what was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think my e-mail may have done it?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happens all the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I retreated to an old and long discarded Wal-Mart typewriter,
dug out of a closet. It still works. Consider this my formal
resignation from the world of e-mail, the Internet, Web pages,
access numbers and other hindrances of modern technology.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
