<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN2 _ My column on the recent school massacre
brought a number of e-mail comments from readers, agreeing or
disagreeing, that there's no crueler society than school cliques.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some excerpts. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Dispatches from dreamsville: A playground in
the woods One of an occasional series in which readers share with
Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray their memories of growing
up in small-town America. Back then, or at least the way we
remember it, life was like a dream. ``My mother died in 1942 when I
was a year old. In 1944, Daddy and my Cherokee stepmother and I _
red-haired and freckle-faced _ moved from Texas to our 10-acre farm
in Clay County, Fla. My four half-brothers were born during the
next 10 years. Our nearest neighbor lived a couple of miles away,
so we entertained ourselves. We had radio, but no TV until the late
1950s. A railroad track ran along our piney woods farm. We'd wave
to the train engineers, and they'd wave back. Mom said that
whenever a train was late during the night, we children would wake
up because we had not heard the train whistle in our sleep.''
(Clifton, Daily Sentinel) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ In my school, any jock caught
pushing around a weaker student would be challenged by other jocks.
Jocks were not bullies. We were the good guys. To act as bullies or
hoods would screw up a good thing. Is it possible that these
black-clad Trenchcoat Mafia killers were modern-day hoods who
attempted to bully and terrorize other students with their Nazi
swastikas and talk of guns and killing? (Rowland Nethaway is senior
editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ Here's a wild suggestion: Try
being a role model yourself instead of expecting other people to do
it for you. As much as we all hate to admit it, the problem isn't
outside influences that affect our children, but the influences we
give our children from the inside. (Latham, Marshall News
Messenger) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ For months, and despite
public ridicule, I had refused to be caught up in the electronic
mail craze. After a recent bought of computer blitz, I formall
resign from the Information Age. (Jim Minter is a former editor of
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The news choppers soared. The
print reporters scribbled. The neighbors came out on their porches
to say, ``He was quiet,'' ``He was a loner,'' and ``He seemed like
a nice guy.'' In what almost seemed like a cosmic commentary on
news in the modern age, it turned out to be turkey skin, the
suspected ``human remains'' that preoccupied Dayton press and
police for the better part of Monday. Meanwhile, Bob Shepas, 48,
upstanding citizen and homeowner, sweated under the intense glare
of suspicion. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ There's a book us white folks need to read but
black folks can skip. Black folks already know why there's such a
grotesque disproportion of their young men in prison. And, no, it's
not because African Americans are natural-born crooks; that's
talk-radio tripe. It's in good part because the relentless
inequities of the criminal justice system are geared, however
unintentionally, to produce that disproportion. The book is ``No
Equal Justice.'' It is by David Cole. He brings a disturbing _ and
what ought to be an urgent _ message. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVES THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ We began the '90s in hot pursuit of one
dictator, Iraq's Saddam Hussein, but did not succeed in ridding the
world of him. Already, we had Panama's Manuel Noriega in a Miami
jail, nabbed by U.S. troops who actually invaded Panama by the
thousands to get their hands on him. But there are so many more
despots to pursue. Libya's Moammar Khadafy is one, Syria's Haffez
Assad another and Yugoslavia's Slobodan Milosevic another;
Milosevic being the present focus of attention. (Howard Kleinberg
is a columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVES THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVES THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
