furniture-making. I have nothing but admiration for chairmakers,
and even more for ones like Langsner who do it the hard way _
taking the thing right out of the tree. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY .
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-GUNS _ The images from Littleton, Colo. _ like those
from Arkansas, Mississippi, Kentucky and Oregon _ raise difficult
challenges for people of faith who live in a society that says
freedom requires access to firearms. There is a mystique about
firearms apparent at today's meeting of the National Rifle
Association in Denver and earlier this year when more than 1,400
exhibitors displayed their wares in the Georgia World Congress
Center at the industry's largest trade show. Guns evoke passion and
raise moral dilemmas, such as those being played out in debates in
Colorado over concealed weapons and those in Georgia about
Atlanta's plan to sue gun manufacturers. The debates also go on
among people of faith. We explore the issue. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   TORAH-PURCHASE _ One hundred twelve years ago, a Jewish
congregation danced through the streets of Yemen's capital carrying
their new Torah to the synagogue. They had waited years for the
Jewish scribe to painstakingly pen the Old Testament on narrow
panels of heavy goatskin parchment sewn together with catgut. As
the synagogue doors parted in Sanaa, the jubilant crowd paraded in,
never dreaming their sacred text would one day enter something
called cyberspace, destined for Austin. An interesting reader about
how a small congregation found its historic Torah on the Internet
and bought it on eBay. (Perkes, Austin American-Statesman). FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-PARTY: 30,000 hard-core Star Wars fans invade Denver
for the first ever Star Wars celebration and we are there. By
Saturday, people will have a clear idea of what's cool and what's
not. Cummings will rendevous with people from the Dayton area at
mid-day to compare notes on the Celebration, on the Star Wars night
life, etc. Will attempt to hook up with a photog at about noon to
shoot one or two local types whooping it up. Also should have some
accounts of major events such as the appearance of the guy playing
Darth Maul. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 25. WITH PHOTOS (from
Grand Junction Daily Sentinel).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (l) LIfestyle and (a) General News categories FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   DALLASAUSTIN _ Like TLC, the pop trio he has been closely
attached to from its start, Dallas Austin has been up, way down,
and on the climb again with the success of TLC's ``FanMail.'' In a
Q&AMP;A we discuss what record producer Austin (Madonna, Michael
Jackson and the Rolling Stones) did during his down time, why he
only has one artist on his new Freeworld label and the talk that he
wouldn't be involved in TLC's latest project because - as Lisa
``Left Eye'' Lopes said on the radio _ he was too expensive.
(SoMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS . FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   APPALACHIA-MUSIC _ ``The Tennessee Waltz,'' familiar worldwide
as a Patti Page pop hit, a wedding favorite, state song of
Tennessee, and comfortable old country, touches untolds millions.
But for E.P. (Slim) Stewart, 70-something, it resonates most
deeply. He is the brother of Redd Stewart, the man who co-wrote the
song with Pee Wee King. E.P. , who still plays fiddle and guitar,
remembers when old-fashioned country music was the music of
Appalachia. (LeeMay, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
