<HEADER>
A9281 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN01-COX     04-30 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who were the bullies?
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The motive behind the massacre at Colorado's
Columbine High School is being attributed to a feeling of ostracism
by the two young killers who especially hated the school's
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   As a former high school jock, I have a hard time relating to
this experience.
</P>
<P>
   These two teens went to a huge suburban school. I went to a
small-town school. The times have changed. Still, some things
surely remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   At my school, the students would assemble in the gym at the
beginning of each school year to get our marching orders for the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
   There were no student handbooks. In the days of manual
typewriters and hand-cranked mimeograph machines, it was a lot
easier to call an assembly to pass along information.
</P>
<P>
   We were told everything the administrators, teachers and coaches
thought we needed to know.
</P>
<P>
   During these introductory assemblies, the coach would talk about
the athletic prospects for the coming year, which, with hard work
and student body support, would be good.
</P>
<P>
   The coach would introduce the players for the coming season's
football team. We had been sweating through full-pad practices for
weeks before school started. We felt that we deserved the applause.
</P>
<P>
   As a jock who played every sport every year, I often felt that
the attention given to athletes was out of proportion to any actual
importance. Not that I complained, of course.
</P>
<P>
   I recall taking the field and looking at the band members
dressed in silly-looking uniforms, the cheerleaders dressed in
considerably better-looking uniforms and all the students and
adults in the stands. I couldn't figure it out. Didn't these people
have something better to do?
</P>
<P>
   Those of us on the field got to play a game, which often was
fun. What all those other people were doing, I wasn't sure. Not
that I complained.
</P>
<P>
   The two young gunmen at Columbine High School evidently hated
jocks because jocks picked on them.
</P>
<P>
   I can see why some people and fellow students would think that
jocks get too much attention. I felt the same when I was a jock.
</P>
<P>
   Honor students like my brother, who was elected to head a
national scholastic honorary society, were never cheered during an
assembly for acing a test. No glory for brains.
</P>
<P>
   There were cliques even in small-town schools. But if jocks
could be considered a clique, they would not have been the ones who
picked on weaker students.
</P>
<P>
   The three basic social groups in my 1950s-era high school were
jocks, hoods and brains. There was some overlap with the jocks and
the brains, but very little with the hoods.
</P>
<P>
   Hoods seldom had the guts or the ability to play sports. But
hoods had plenty of courage when it came to pushing around weaker
students. Jocks protected weaker students from bullying hoods. It
was our pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   In my school, any jock caught pushing around a weaker student
would be challenged by other jocks. Jocks were not bullies. We were
the good guys. To act as bullies or hoods would screw up a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than black trench coats, the hoods in my school wore
black leather motorcycle jackets with the collars turned up. They
also wore black steel-toed engineer boots and their hair slicked
back in greasy duck tails.
</P>
<P>
   They liked to hang out together in groups, smoke and try to look
and act tough. The acting-tough part included picking on weaker
students.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that these black-clad Trenchcoat Mafia killers
were modern-day hoods who attempted to bully and terrorize other
students with their Nazi swastikas and talk of guns and killing?
</P>
<P>
   Modern-day jocks, however, can't stop bullets and bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. His columns
appear on Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail:
RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
