<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, April 30, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for the weekend.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PROSTITUTES-CRIME (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco Police
Department has created a new investigative unit to deal exclusively
with crimes against prostitutes. The Crimes Against Prostitutes
unit, believed to be the first of its kind in the nation, is
designed to focus on violent predators who attack prostitutes as
well as dealers who supply them with drugs and pimps who often
force them to stay on the street. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-SIETE (San Francisco) _ Seldom has a single gunshot echoed
so long and so far. The bullet that killed San Francisco Police
Officer Joseph Brodnik, 30 years ago Saturday, took a life and
ruined a family. It also sparked a political movement and changed
the way a Latino community thought of itself. By EMILY GURNON.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BUDGET (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Higher salaries, bonuses and
huge stock market earnings among some California taxpayers will
pump an estimated $3 billion in taxes into the state treasury,
prompting lawmakers to salivate over how to spend the windfall. By
ROB SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   LACKLAND-AFB (San Antonio) _ The Air Force in August will seek
private bids to take over base operations at San Antonio's Lackland
AFB, a move that could affect more than 1,600 civilian jobs. Most
jobs at the base, known as ``The Gateway to the Air Force,'' would
transfer to the private sector in a cost-cutting move, although an
unknown number of jobs also could be eliminated. By DAVID
HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-LAWSUIT (Houston) _ Three people from Houston have filed a
federal lawsuit challenging the constitutionality of a Texas law
that prohibits the direct shipment of wine to a Texas residence
from out of state. The law also prohibits the transportation of
more than three gallons of wine across the state line. By ED ASHER.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLICS-DEATH-PENALTY (San Antonio) _ The National Federation
of Priests' Councils is urging bishops and priests to convey to
parishioners that the death penalty is wrong. ``Sadly, many
Americans _ including many Catholics _ still support the death
penalty out of understandable fear of crime and horror,'' says
Daniel Misleh, a policy adviser with the U.S. Catholic Conference.
By SUZANNE HOHOLIK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BARBECUE-TEXAS (Lockhart, Texas) _ To call Edgar Schmidt a
latter-day King Lear might seem ridiculous. He was, after all, the
owner of a barbecue joint. But then again we're talking about
barbecue, more specifically Central Texas barbecue, arguably the
best in the state, which to most around these parts means the best
in the world. By THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader has a question about plants
with holes in the leaves. The readers asks, ``Will you tell me why
insect is attacking my crops? By KATHY HUBER
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ To encourage employees to stay,
employers are offering ``staying bonuses.'' They're especially
popular, sometimes called ``pay to stay,'' when one company buys
another and critical people must be kept. They're also used to meet
deadlines for projects such as the millennium bug. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Notebook computer design is
beginning to have a greater effect on desktops. Since space is at a
premium in most homes and workplaces, a smaller desktop system has
appeal for many people. Here's a look at a desktop system that
closely resembles a portable PC, and an excellent portable that
could easily replace many home desktops. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-ONLINE (Undated) _ A reader discovers another problem
with duplicated file names in Windows 98 _ ``ghost drivers'' in the
Device Manager. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   RETAILERS (San Francisco) _ If you think clothes all look alike
and the same stores are on every corner, it's not your imagination.
Just 10 companies control nearly half the U.S. clothing sales,
according to a report by The NPD Group, a market research firm. By
VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-CHILDREN (Undated) _ From books children learn about real
people who influence _ in tiny or giant ways _ their young lives.
Many of those books fill community and school libraries, waiting
for a school assignment on the explorers or the Revolutionary War
or American Indians. Some parents relegate biographies and other
books about real people to assignments. What a shame. Biographies
and stories about real people can inspire children. By JANE P.
MARSHALL.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-PUNK (Undated) _ It's 1985, and guys like Stevo
(Matthew Lillard) of ``SLC Punk!'' have all but had it with the
commercial dilution of punk's squalid grandeur. So what's he doing
soapboxing near the information kiosk in a Salt Lake City mall? He
delivers an impassioned, intermittently funny soliloquy into a
low-angled camera. He's fired up, but neither Stevo nor the film
acknowledges that he's ranting from within the bastion of his
contempt. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-ELECTION (Undated) _ Of the many vividly evocative
truths to surface in ``Election,'' the one that gives the most
pause comes during the student body candidates' debate. Tammy
Metzler (Jessica Campbell), school weirdo and darkhorse
presidential candidate, tells Carver High's adolescent electorate
that the contest is more or less only about the candidate's egos
and putting a victory on their college application. They should
vote for her: She doesn't want to go to college. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-COLUMN (Undated) _ May sweeps is becoming less about the big
network blockbuster _ because they don't know how to do it right
anymore, or maybe no one cares _ and more about cliffhangers and
the end of old stalwarts. Like on May 19, when ``The Nanny''
mercifully leaves the airwaves. The world is finally free of Fran
Drescher. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Timing can be everything in
love, and so it is at Audubon Canyon Ranch. Show up in mid- summer,
fall or winter, and well, you'll not only find the gate locked, but
nothing beyond worth trying to get a peep at anyway. But arrive now
. . . the gate is open, and beyond? Well, let me tell you about the
birds and the bees. Especially the birds. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ iMacs sure get them good product
placement. Whenever we see one on TV, we look over our shoulders
proudly at ours. We halfway expect him to be looking at his brother
on TV, too. We've decided it's a him because he's bluish. The color
is important. When you tell people you have an iMac, they always
ask what color you have. We got bluish because that's all they had
the first week they came out. By ROB MORSE
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WAR (Watsonville, Calif.) _ Hitherto, war has meant
sacrifice. And the men who led people into war had to convince them
that it was worth the sacrifice. The Clinton Doctrine changes all
that. Now war will mean only a willingness to kill _ not a
willingness to die. No sacrifice, other than financial, is
required; therefore, no soldiers or citizens need to be convinced.
By FRANK BARDACKE.
</P>
