<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9283 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD01-COX     04-30 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chairmakers earn a seat at the head of the class
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Drew Langsner, the North Carolina guru of green wood
working, is out with a handsome new book called ``The Chairmaker's
Workshop.''
</P>
<P>
   Published in hardback by Lark at $35, one should not be misled
by the generality of the title.
</P>
<P>
   I have often mentioned that chairmaking is really the most
difficult and exacting of all areas of furniture-making. A chair
must withstand more abuse than any other piece of furniture, yet it
is expected to look graceful and serene.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, it's a failure if it isn't comfortable. Thus I have
nothing but admiration for chairmakers, and even more for ones like
Langsner who do it the hard way _ taking the thing right out of the
tree.
</P>
<P>
   There is scarcely an tool or an evolution in all of woodworking
that is not required to build a Windsor chair from green wood.
You'll need the tools of the tree-cutter _ chainsaw, ax, peavey and
cant hook _ and the river's tools: wedge, sledge, glut, froe and
maul.
</P>
<P>
   For preparing all the pieces, and shaping those which are not to
be turned, you'll need a drawknife; perhaps several in different
sizes and shapes. Drawknives are not as easy to find now as they
once were. They are, however, still just as hard to use. An expert
can do wonderful things with a properly sharpened drawknife, but
there is a definite learning curve.
</P>
<P>
   The use of a drawknife requires a shaving horse, and I don't
recall ever seeing a ready-made one. You'll have to build one
yourself, but it's not a big deal. You'll also probably want a
heavy leather apron so as not to disembowel yourself while you're
learning to use the drawknife.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the hollowing and the inshave and the travisher,
required for shaping the concave seats of the Windsor chair.
Langsner devotes a page to the making of a travisher, which is used
for the final finish work. Then you have the tools for making
mortises _ you can use an electric drill here _ and more arcane
tools for forming tenons, both straight and tapered.
</P>
<P>
   Langsner provides instructions on making several other useful
tools, including a tapering plane and a type of bow saw that allows
the blade to be rotated to any angle. Since most Windsow chair
rungs and spindles are turned, you'll need a lathe and basic
spindle-turning tools.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these chairs also involve bent wood, so you'll have to
make a steamer and learn to bend the stuff. Fortunately, the pieces
are generally small enough so as not to require an army to get the
job done.
</P>
<P>
   Langsner's book is absolutely comprehensive. It covers various
styles and techniques, and how to deal with mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
