<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9308 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      04-30 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SPRING IN SOX' STEP IN APRIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It would be foolish to condemn the Red Sox for
failing to duplicate the drama of last April, when they won nine
games with late-inning comebacks, seven in their last at-bat,
including Mo Vaughn's theme-setting walkoff grand slam in the home
opener.
</P>
<P>
   That was baseball at its unscripted best, with improbable
scene-stealers like The King, Jim Leyritz, and where-have-you-gone
Midre Cummings hitting dramatic home runs while the marquee names,
Vaughn and Nomar Garciaparra, produced nightly as the Sox raced to
an 18-8 record, setting a club record for wins in April.
</P>
<P>
   But it's one thing to expect the unexpected on a nightly basis.
It's quite another to wonder, with justification, where all the
excitement has gone so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   Come-from-behind wins? As the Red Sox close out the month Friday
night in Oakland, trying to stay above the break-even point with an
11-10 record, they can point to only one victory so far in which
they trailed. That was the opener, April 5 in Kansas City, when the
Royals jumped to a 2-0 lead in the first inning, an advantage they
held for exactly two more Sox at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other times this season, Sox opponents have scored first,
and the Sox have lost all seven.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the Sox ran off 14 wins in 15 games, including two
seven-game winning streaks. This April, the Sox reeled off wins in
their first five games, on the road against Kansas City and Tampa
Bay. Since then, they're 6-10, and have won back-to-back games just
once, last weekend against the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   And remember, this was supposed to be the soft part of the
schedule, with the Indians the only team with a better-than-.500
record among the Sox opponents in the first 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   But already, the Sox have lost three in a four-game series
against the expansion Devil Rays _ in Fenway Park, no less _
followed that by dropping two of three to the Tigers in Detroit,
and needed Wednesday's 9-4 win to avoid being swept by the Twins in
the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   After returning home from a four-game set this weekend with the
A's, the Red Sox will confront a stretch that includes two games
against the AL West-leading Texas Rangers, a three-game reunion
next weekend with Mo, six games against the Yankees, seven games
against the Blue Jays (who at the moment are ahead of the Sox in
the AL East), and three more games with the Indians, this time in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   How to explain the difference from one April to another? Let's
count the ways:
</P>
<P>
   --Run production: Everybody knew that the Sox would miss Mo, but
the dropoff has been precipitous. Last April, the Sox scored 138
runs in 26 games, an average of 5.3 a game. This month, the Sox
have scored 83 runs in 21 games, 3.9 a game.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who hit two home runs for the Angels Wednesday night
(and no Sox player has homered twice in a game so far), had a huge
April last year, batting a team-best .364 with a team-high seven
home runs and 21 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Only Garciaparra had more RBIs last year at this time; he had
22, with five home runs and six stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar's numbers so far this season: no home runs in 56 at-bats,
six RBIs, two stolen bases. Garciaparra had his fewest RBIs in a
month since becoming a regular; even last May, when he missed 16
games with a separated shoulder, the Sox shortstop still drove in
eight runs. Of his 16 hits so far this season, 13 have been
singles.
</P>
<P>
   That trend can't continue, though it reflects on how completely
Sox opponents have targeted Garciaparra, in the absence of Vaughn,
as the one player they will attempt to neutralize at all costs.
Garciaparra will adjust, but it may take time.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Jose Offerman has picked up some of the slack, batting
.349 with 29 hits and 16 extra-base hits, all team-leading figures.
But last April, the Sox had four players who had scored 15 or more
runs in April, led by John Valentin's 19. With one game left to be
played, only Offerman (12) and Troy O'Leary (11) are in double
figures in runs, while Valentin, who scored 113 runs in 1998, has
just seven so far.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary leads the club with six home runs; no one else has more
than two. At this rate, the Sox will finish with 115 home runs, or
an astounding 90 fewer than they had last season. The Tampa Bay
Devil Rays ranked last in the league last season with 111.
</P>
<P>
   --Batting with runners in scoring position: Don't blame
Offerman; he's batting .455 (5 for 11) with runners in scoring
position, while Jeff Frye (.385), Mike Stanley (.357), Garciaparra
(.353), and Damon Buford (.333) have done their share.
</P>
<P>
   But take seven other batters in the Sox lineup _ O'Leary, Jason
Varitek, Valentin, Trot Nixon, Darren Lewis, Reggie Jefferson, and
Donnie Sadler _ and their combined average with runners in scoring
position is .168 (20 for 119). Lewis, who has been dropped from the
No. 2 spot in the order, is batting just .120 (3 for 25) in RISP
situations.
</P>
<P>
   --Pitching: As proud as the Sox are of their pitching to date _
a league-leading ERA of 3.62, a full point below the league average
of 4.75 _ the difference from a year ago isn't as marked as the
drop in offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox bullpen, for example, has four saves; Tom Gordon had
three wins and nine saves by himself in April last season. Bret
Saberhagen and Pedro Martinez are off to great starts, just as they
were a year ago; but Tim Wakefield (1-3, 7.36 ERA) hasn't had this
bad a month in nearly two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   --Injuries: Garciaparra has been slowed by elbow and hamstring
injuries. Gordon has been MIA for two weeks and counting with an
elbow injury that remains worrisome, as has catcher Scott
Hatteberg. Saberhagen, who didn't miss a start last season, is
missing one Friday with shoulder problems, a constant concern.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sox can take comfort in anything, it's that no team has
separated itself from the pack, not even the Yankees. The Orioles
are a bust, Vaughn was part of the injury epidemic in Anaheim, the
Mariners lost Alex Rodriguez, and every team short of the Yankees
has obvious flaws. Whether the Sox can overcome theirs to keep pace
with the better teams is a question that was left unanswered in
April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
