<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9324 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-TROOPS-$ADV02-C     04-30 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-TROOPS-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. TROOPS IN HAITI FACE DANGERS AS INSTABILITY MOUNTS
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim.
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROIX-DES-BOUQUETS, Haiti _ The latest sign that U.S. troops are
increasingly in danger from the very people they're here to help
came abruptly at dawn on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of soldiers had assembled near the front gate of the
American military compound known as Camp Fairwinds for an early run
in the already steamy Haitian heat.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, gunshots rang out.
</P>
<P>
   Within 20 minutes, unidentified gunmen separated from the
Port-au-Prince compound by a barbed wire fence had sprayed the area
twice with a flurry of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the gunmen's aim was lousy, and no one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   But the commander of U.S. troops in Haiti, Col. Charles Morris,
said it wasn't the only brush with danger American soldiers have
faced in Haiti, where growing violence and instability pose
significant threats.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Cox Newspapers last week, Morris
recommended the United States end its permanent deployment in
Haiti, echoing concerns expressed last February by the commander of
American forces in Latin America, Gen. Charles Wilhelm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is more unstable now than it was six months
ago,'' said Morris, who has commanded the troops here since last
fall. ``Incidents of violence are up.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments made by Wilhelm -- and echoed now Morris --
concerning the quiet peacekeeping mission not far off Florida's
shore come as congressional Republicans step up their attacks on
President Bill Clinton's conduct of the war in Kosovo, a place some
4,700 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The comments also present a major challenge to a foreign policy
that Clinton administration officials have held up as an example of
the way in which U.S. military forces can be used to help resolve
instability and ethnic conflicts in the post-Cold War period.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there's mounting opposition to the U.S. presence here,
where the Parliament has passed a law ordering foreign troops off
Haitian soil -- although it has not been enforced.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, key Republicans portray the mission in Haiti as a
failure and have called on Clinton to remove the troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our soldiers are down there with giant bull's-eyes on their
backs, and they need to be pulled out, and right now,'' said U.S.
Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., chairman of the House Intelligence
Committee. ``This is supposed to be a peacekeeping mission yet
these folks are at risk in an increasingly dangerous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Clinton administration has yet to present a clear
exit strategy in Haiti or immediate plans for the withdrawal of
troops.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1994, Clinton ordered 20,000 U.S. troops to Haiti
to remove a brutal military dictatorship and restore President
Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has often hailed the mission as a foreign
policy triumph. Since 1994, the United States has poured $2.2
billion into this tiny Caribbean nation to promote economic
development and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the U.S. troops withdrew after a year, some 500
soldiers remain in Haiti, mostly performing humanitarian duties
such as drilling wells, building schools, and providing medical
care, at a cost to U.S. taxpayers of $22 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say the troops are a stabilizing force
and a ``visible manifestation'' of U.S. support for Haiti's
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sort of signal would it send if we pulled the troops out
now?'' asked one State Department official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But about 175 of the soldiers do nothing but protect the other
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   And many work quietly in safe, rural areas -- generally chosen
because of their isolation -- where most Haitians don't see them.
</P>
<P>
   In the rural community of Merger, just outside Port-au-Prince,
about 21 U.S. soldiers stand guard outside a small church in which
29 other soldiers provide medical care to sick Haitians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to make sure nothing happens to the medics,'' said
one guard, Pfc. Jay Webb of Statesboro, Ga. ``Most of the people
out here though are pretty nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, in recent months, a wave of crime, politically
motivated shootings, and allegations of police brutality have swept
over Haiti as politicians struggle to restore the government after
a 22-month political impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more people who are armed here than there used
to be,'' Col. Morris said. ``You see people walking on the streets
with weapons in their trousers.''
</P>
<P>
   President Rene Preval tried to resolve government gridlock by
dissolving the Parliament in January and appointing a new prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   But civil unrest has only swelled.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a spate of violence has rocked Port-au-Prince since
April 20, when a youth activist named Michelange Philistin(CQ) was
fatally shot, allegedly by police.
</P>
<P>
   And just last week, three Haitian legislators who had taken
refuge in the Chilean Embassy here after receiving death threats
fled for the United States with their families.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the atmosphere became so tense in January that he
was forced to upgrade so-called ``threat conditions'' at the
American military compound.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has cut back on liberties for the soldiers,
restricting where they go, and requiring them to travel in large
groups.
</P>
<P>
   He's closed one of only two entrances to Camp Fairwinds, and
erected several walls of sandbags, behind which soldiers could
duck.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly U.S. troops are confined to their heavily fortified
military compound, an insular environment complete with a weight
room, a swimming pool, an all-you-can-eat mess hall and
air-conditioned plywood barracks.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the protection of U.S. forces is his top priority,
but it's a job that's not as easy as it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, he said U.S. soldiers have been fired upon. He
also said that they've been increasingly threatened -- sometimes by
various political factions -- particularly on local radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what American soldiers do and where they go,'' said
one ominous-sounding warning from a caller opposed to the U.S.
presence.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Last February, Wilhelm, who leads the U.S. Southern Command,
told the defense subcommittee of the House Appropriations Committee
that troops have been unable to establish stability and that he
feared for their safety in an increasingly volatile country.
</P>
<P>
   He recommended the United States discontinue its permanent
presence in Haiti, and replace it with periodic visits to sites
mostly outside Port-au-Prince, where most unrest occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, key Republicans asked Clinton to withdraw the
troops.
</P>
<P>
   In an April 22 letter to Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., Clinton said
he is committed to reducing the U.S. presence in Haiti, but offered
no timetable for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he'd approved a modest reduction in force strength
last August, although officials at the U.S. Southern Command say
the number of troops has not changed.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to the military's new fiscal plan, the U.S.
presence in Haiti will remain constant throughout the year 2000 as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts on Haiti argue that the time for withdrawal has
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The troops are not in any position to prevent Haitian society
from falling apart,'' said Jocelyn McCalla, executive director of
the New York-based National Coalition for Haitian Rights. ``They
are a token presence that is not even appreciated by the Haitian
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris said many of the tasks performed by U.S. soldiers could
be performed by U.S. aid organizations.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said it's disappointing that the U.S. military has
almost no contact with the Haitian government.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a representative of the Haitian government has yet
to attend a ribbon-cutting ceremony to mark the opening of a
U.S.-built facility -- despite countless invitations -- even a
recent opening for a completely rebuilt elementary school within
view of the National Palace.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Ira Kurzban, the Haitian government's Miami-based legal adviser,
said Haiti does appreciate U.S. efforts to restore democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the issue of the continuation of foreign troops in Haiti,
in light of its history, has always been a sensitive subject,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Haitians resent the last U.S. occupation of Haiti between
1915 and 1934, which some say left the country even more unstable
than before, and so are wary of the current U.S. presence as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't know what these troops do in Haiti that the
Haitians themselves can't do,'' said Micha Gaillard, a leader of
the socialist National Congress of Democratic Movements in Haiti.
``Not much of anything as far as I can tell.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sgt. Joseph Riddle of Columbus, Ohio, one of 50 Marines
putting the finishing touches on a five-building school compound
southeast of Port-au-Prince, said the troops are making a
difference, at least in the lives of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are really going to appreciate this school,'' he
said. ``All of us really are doing everything we can to help.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
