<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9401 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHOLICS-DEATH-PENAL     04-30 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLICS-DEATH-PENALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC GROUP PRESSES OPPOSITION TO DEATH PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUZANNE HOHOLIK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Opposition to the death penalty is an issue all
priests should preach from the pulpit to their congregations.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message the National Federation of Priests' Councils
sent Thursday as part of their week-long conference in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Misleh, a policy adviser with the U.S. Catholic
Conference, said the nation's bishops and priests need to convey
the message to parishioners that the death penalty is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, many Americans _ including many Catholics _ still
support the death penalty out of understandable fear of crime and
horror,'' he said. ``We hope they will come to see, as we have,
that more violence is not the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   About 300 people, mainly priests and bishops, attended the
annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The statement of the U.S. Catholic Conference administrative
board echoes remarks made by Pope John Paul II during his visit to
St. Louis in January. The pontiff called for an end to the death
penalty and clemency for a convicted murderer in Missouri who was
awaiting execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human life must never be taken away, even in the case of
someone who has done great evil,'' Pope John Paul II said at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   After the pope's appeal, Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan commuted
Darrell Mease's death sentence to life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Catholic Conference officially has opposed the death
penalty since 1976, the same year capital punishment was reinstated
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a controversial issue. Many Catholics support the death
penalty to the tune of 70 percent,'' Misleh said. ``A lot of hearts
and minds need to change. We're hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   Changing the hearts of American Catholics will require a strong
message from priests and bishops to the faithful, who often receive
clerics' views in opposition to abortion, said Bud Welch of
Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm finding that all bishops believe the death penalty is
wrong, but we need them to say it in a statement that it is
wrong,'' said Welch, who travels the country talking about ending
executions. ``We're their flock. In the past, the bishops haven't
shown leadership on the death penalty and I think they should.''
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong critic of capital punishment, Welch changed his mind
briefly after the bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building
in Oklahoma City, where his daughter, Julie, and 167 other people
were killed in the 1995 attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw them (defendants Timothy McVeigh and Terry
Nichols), I said `What's the point of a trial? Let's fry them,'''
he said. ``I honestly would have killed those two men in the month
after the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Welch only wants for the pair to spend the rest of their
lives in prison. McVeigh was sentenced to death by injection on
murder and weapons charges. Nichols was convicted of conspiracy and
involuntary manslaughter and will spend life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Along with opposition to executions, Misleh added that priests
also need to provide help for crime victims through education,
advocacy and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be a community set on preserving life,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9408 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-30 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INTERNET IS HERE, AND IT'S BLUE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There he was, an exact twin of our new child,
and he had a role on the amusing new ABC sitcom ``Norm.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just a bit part, but what do you expect for a little guy
who's only 10 months old? He sat on a desk in an office, just as
another of his brothers had sat on a desk in the NBC sitcom ``Just
Shoot Me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a talented and cute little family, the iMacs, and their
cyberlogical parents down in Cupertino sure get them good product
placement. Whenever we see one on television, we look over our
shoulders proudly at ours. We halfway expect him to be looking at
his brother on TV, too.
</P>
<P>
   We've decided it's a him because he's bluish. The color is
important. When you tell people you have an iMac, they always ask
what color you have. We got bluish because that's all they had the
first week they came out.
</P>
<P>
   We're suckers for cute. We almost got one of those new VW bugs,
too. The iMac looks as if it could grow up into a VW bug, but thank
God it won't. It's cheaper and it can take you more places. You
just have to admit you're not a geek and you don't care if you have
a non-macho computer.
</P>
<P>
   Man, the world really has changed since the days of pocket
protectors. Computer geeks are macho. They're as aggressive as
jocks and as snobby as preppies _ and often richer.
</P>
<P>
   They're still geeks, though, so the hell with them, except when
you want them to come over and debug your VW bug computer.
</P>
<P>
   This is how technophobic I am, or used to be: The iMac sat on
the table looking cute for most of the past year before I used it.
My wife drove it around the Internet, learned how to paint with it,
made business cards with it and wrote stories on it.
</P>
<P>
   She played a heck of a lot of Nanosaur.
</P>
<P>
   I made excuses about having to use terminals at work. The real
reason I'm technophobic is because of the computer course I had to
take 30 years ago. It involved FORTRAN and punch cards I always got
mixed up.
</P>
<P>
   Until a week ago, when I started mainlining on-line, I liked the
idea of the computer revolution, the way a citizen of Moscow in
1917 might have liked the idea of a revolution, but not the idea of
interfacing with Bolsheviks.
</P>
<P>
   Last cloudy weekend, the iMac called to me. I answered its siren
beep and started surfing the Net. Sorry, geeks, we technophobes are
out there stumbling among you. And some of us know grammar even if
we don't know code.
</P>
<P>
   Here are three good reasons to be late coming to the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   _ One: You're too old to want to join a conversation group with
any of the anonymous idiots spouting off on every topic under the
icons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two: You know exactly what you want to read. You can skip the
conspiracy sites, the hate sites and the sites with bomb-making
instructions _ the sites always covered in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three: You don't have to wait hours for graphics to download
the way you used to on AOL. Now you just get flashing ads for
hardware and software. And books.
</P>
<P>
   If you avoid the lame amateur sites, you can get in all kinds of
places for free. My wife regularly goes down to Stanford
University, without having to drive, and checks out papers by
academics. It's just like grad school without the pretense of
showing up.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend I read the Times of both New York and London. I
went to the Library of Congress. I looked up Charlie Trotter, just
to see if his precious cooking show really was from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   I read my cousin Steve's rock reviews in the Boston Globe. I
checked out hotels in New York, the Associated Press wires, and
spied on dozens of exhibitionistic people and chickens on various
Webcams.
</P>
<P>
   OK, those Webcams were lame sites. I have to admit I'm a voyeur
who likes to skulk around in my kiddie car of an iMac and its AOL
automatic transmission.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of using my iMac, the downside is becoming
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   I like the Internet, but I'm still not so sure about e-mail. For
one thing, the Serbs can bomb me at home. They don't bomb with what
you'd call pinpoint accuracy, and they use spam instead of high
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   In the news biz we call this pro-Serb propaganda ``Yugospam,''
and it's been flooding the e-mail networks of newspapers. I didn't
get too much, but at least one newspaper address was hit by 200
megabytes of Yugospam, including a single e-mail of 2.3 megabytes.
Just for comparison, ``Moby Dick'' is 1.3 megabytes, and that
includes one bite that swallowed Ahab.
</P>
<P>
   I can't believe I'm talking about megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   The other potential downside of my iMac is e-commerce. I made my
first purchase on the Net, a round-trip ticket to New York.
</P>
<P>
   After I made the electronic reservation, I immediately called
Delta to see if it worked. The ticket agent said everyone calls
after booking their first e-flight.
</P>
<P>
   A flick of the mouse, and you can get all the ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   Punch in the credit card number, and you're done. Really done.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
