<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUND THE ALARM! BETTER YET, SET IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Recently, I lost all the programs that I had
downloaded. I had a free program that made my computer make my
phone ring at any designated time. I wanted to tell my girlfriend
about this because she has trouble getting up in the morning, but I
haven't been able to find it anywhere since I brought my computer
back up. Can you help me?
</P>
<P>
   _ Busy Signal
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BUSY: You may be interested in a little technological
innovation that fundamentally changed the way civilization
developed. Its inventors called it ``a clock,'' but you can be sure
the marketing division is hard at work coming up with a snappier
name that focus groups everywhere will love. Something like
``Timemaster SX 2000'' would be my guess.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Clock 2.0 had an amazing enhancement that may solve your
problem. It actually combines an alarm and a clock! I forget what
they called the finished product, but I'm sure marketing will come
up with something infinitely more memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Stop over-teching. Maybe your girlfriend has trouble getting up
because she can't bear the thought of facing another day with
somebody who thinks it's way cool to turn a $3,000 computer into an
alarm clock. Alarm clock! Yes, that's what they called it. I knew
I'd remember it sooner or later, even though ``Sleepender X9'' has
been growing on me.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I hate these here 'puters, but I need to ask
someone with intelligence (?). I suffered a severe crash and had no
choice but to reformat the hard drive. Ever since, I can't run a
disk scan. The message is that some other program is running. There
is nothing running, unless the gremlins are working overtime.
</P>
<P>
   _ Downtown Donna
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DOWN: That's not a gremlin. That's just Bill Gates. He
forgot to wear his lifts.
</P>
<P>
   I know you reloaded from a recovery CD-ROM provided by your
computer manufacturer rather than the Win95 original CD. My guess
is that your original crash hammered your machine a lot harder than
you thought, making even the recovery disk goof up. Or maybe it
loaded stuff you really don't need.
</P>
<P>
   Windows can have all sorts of stuff going on behind the scenes.
Usually, the only way you know about it is if you have a bunch of
dinky little icons in the System Tray in the lower right corner of
your screen. If you've got more than a volume control there,
something else is running.
</P>
<P>
   In Win95, go to the ``Startup'' folder in Programs and see if
anything is loading. Or try un-installing everything you don't need
from the ``Add/Remove Programs'' icon in the Control Panel. See if
anything is on the ``Load'' or ``Run'' lines at the top of the
Win.ini file. But don't go messing with the Registry (which is
where these things are probably loading) unless you know what
you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   You nuked the computer once. Do it again, but buy Win98 and
customize the installation to fit your needs.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: We're so close to the year 2001, yet so far
away from HAL 9000. Would you address that?
</P>
<P>
   _ Starry-Eyed
</P>
<P>
   DEAR STARRY: It can only be attributable to human error. There's
one big problem with visionaries like Arthur C. Clarke and Stanley
Kubrick: Their grasp far exceeds our reach.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay has just picked up a
fault in the AE-35 unit. He can be reached at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101, or fax: (817)
390-7257. Hey, can anybody open these pod bay doors? His real name
is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
