<SLUG> BC-TV-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEEPS DREAMS ARE UPON US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How's this for the cosmic stars lining up
perfectly: It's sweeps, and ``Cops'' is celebrating its 400th
episode Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that _ you guessed it _ the episode involves a domestic
disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   March 3, 1987. That was the debut of ``Cops,'' which has spawned
many imitators, but is still the king. This show's conception and
ongoing run says all you need to know about America and television.
</P>
<P>
   May sweeps (the period when ratings are taken for television
stations) is becoming less about the big network blockbuster _
because they don't know how to do it right anymore, or maybe no one
cares _ and more about cliffhangers and the end of old stalwarts.
Like on May 19, when ``The Nanny'' mercifully leaves the airwaves.
There will be a big United Nations celebration at the conclusion.
The world is finally free of Fran Drescher.
</P>
<P>
   Except in syndication.
</P>
<P>
   On May 24, say goodbye to ``Mad About You.'' Whoops, our
mistake, you already waved goodbye two season ago, when it was
``Mad at You.'' They never should have had that baby.
</P>
<P>
   We won't be watching the teary finale unless Paul Reiser and
Helen Hunt address the camera and tell the truth: ``We're sorry for
making our sitcom into a drama. We know you were looking for
laughs. And we also apologize for being so self-absorbed. Thank
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Also going off the air that night: ``Melrose Place.'' Talk about
a show that overstayed its welcome by about four years. ``Melrose''
is about as must-see as ``Matlock.''
</P>
<P>
   Going, going, gone: ``Home Improvement'' calls it quits on May
25. Of this year _ not 1992. That was when it was creatively dead,
in case you were confused.
</P>
<P>
   Where is all this bitterness coming from, you ask? Where is the
usual sunny delight? Answer: If you don't stay diligent, then a
network like CBS thinks it's fine to air ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine
Woman: The Movie'' on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   To which we say: No. That's not allowed. If you cancel a show,
you don't bring it back as a two-hour movie.
</P>
<P>
   What's next, a miniseries on ``The Secret Diary of Desmond
Pfieffer''?
</P>
<P>
   TV Guide put Calista Flockhart on the cover and basically threw
soft slabs of butter at her, using the spotlight to dismiss as
meaningless the attention tabloids pay to her weight and other
issues, and saying that she is, in her words, ``fierce.'' Her show
is on Fox. Rupert Murdoch owns Fox and TV Guide. You be the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Religious broadcaster Pax TV is turning the brilliant show
``Ballykissangel'' into its own version, ``Hope Island.'' This
could be a trend. Take existing shows and then sand them down for
the family values crowd.
</P>
<P>
   We can just see it: ``Cops'' becomes ``Ministers of Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Pax is also delivering some specials, and they have, curiously,
a Fox tone to them: ``The Bible's Greatest Secrets Revealed.'' And:
``The Bible's Greatest Miracles: The Proof!''
</P>
<P>
   We only wish that were a joke. What will be next on Pax:
``Lazarus! Caught on Tape!'' ``Mary Magdalene Like You've Never
Seen Her Before!'' ``When Pharaohs Attack!'' ``World's Deadliest
Burning Bushes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratings for ``South Park'' are down. Way down. We could have
told you that months ago. That show's done. Long live the
``Powerpuff Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Something to think about when you're upset about not getting a
raise at work: You're not alone. Kevin Sorbo, star of ``Hercules:
The Legendary Journeys,'' is threatening a walkout. That could open
the door for De Niro.
</P>
<P>
   Hercules wants a pay hike. Mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   You want underappreciated? King World Productions gave the green
light to another year of the ``Roseanne'' talk show and a lot of
affiliates booed.
</P>
<P>
   At least she's coming back. Howie Mandel got the ax. The head of
Paramount domestic TV, which distributed the show, called Howie's
low numbers ``a head scratcher.'' No, the truly mystifying part was
that someone said, ``Let's give Howie Mandel a talk show'' in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Also dead and gone: ``Hard Copy.'' We should all be running
around drunk with glee, but ``Inside Edition'' is still alive and
more poisonous than ever.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 years with CNN, Peter Arnett split _ the fallout from
the channel's famed ``Tailwind'' embarrassment. Word inside CNN is
that he was more scapegoat than responsible party and held out long
and hard, but got the cold shoulder at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   CBS smartly pulled an episode of ``Promised Land'' _ which is
set in Denver _ that was about a shootout in a high school.
</P>
<P>
   CBS was going to cancel ``Chicago Hope,'' then David Kelley said
he'd write the season finale, plus next season's opener. CBS
renewed the show.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
