</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CAN BUILD A LEGACY BY MAKING WAR ON VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton this week uttered what could have been, and
still could be, words to build a legacy on: ``We have to redefine
the national community so that we have shared obligation to save
children's lives, and we've got to get out of this crazy denial
that this won't make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, those words are merely associated with Band-aid
proposals sparked by the school shooting that left 15 people dead
in Littleton, Colo. Adults _ most obviously parents _ would face
federal charges for letting minors possess guns that are later used
in shootings. Sales at gun shows would be banned.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking gun shows is good, but is far from a direct attack on
handguns. And anyone who has considered the concept of parent
responsibility in tragic cases realizes that there can be no clear
court definition of such responsibility. It is not only liberals
saying this, but even family-values conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if a kid drives the family car into a crowded store?''
asked Robert Knight, director of cultural studies at the Family
Research Council. ``Should the parents be held liable? You have to
look at it case by case. Not every parent is negligent because a
kid has turned out to be a bad apple.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows there is no one answer for the tragedy. But
instead of searching for clues, we get copouts like this from House
minority leader Richard Gephardt: ``The answer will not be found in
state legislatures or in the halls of Congress. The answer lies
somewhere in the hopelessness and the hateful hearts of the
children who have lost their way.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is true, then we have already succumbed to the nihilism
that afflicted Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. Evidence of that was
last week when Clinton sent Vice President Al Gore _ instead of
himself _ to Colorado to deliver a forgettable speech. We know
Clinton must watch Kosovo, but throughout much of the 1980s and
'90s, 5,000 children a year died from gunfire, a pace giving us
more bodies at home than lost in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   No American president has behaved as if this carnage was as
important as saving ethnic Albanians. Littleton offers Clinton that
chance. It gives him a chance for a lasting legacy.
</P>
<P>
   No issue is as ready to be dealt with across political lines.
Ending violence requires big government and family values. It
requires parental vigilance and government funding to encourage a
sense of community. It requires individual responsibility to
identify the Eric Harrises and Dylan Klebolds among us and a
collective responsibility to say that handguns, which make violence
so much more fatal, are no longer acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The centrist Clinton gained office in 1992 professing to get
beyond ``the brain-dead politics'' of Democrats and Republicans. So
far, centrism has meant minimal vision. But now, with suburbs
waking up to the idea that wealth does not guarantee safety or
community, no time is better for the biggest of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   If we really love children, there is no reason to settle for a
United States where kids are 12 times more likely to die from
gunfire than in the rest of the developed world. Clinton can start
by doing what Britain and Australia did after similar tragedies. He
can ban or dramatically restrict new handgun sales and devise a
buyout plan for the weapons already out there (hunters can have
their rifles, but only during hunting season).
</P>
<P>
   On the violence-in-culture front, the president could start
treating the producers of violent movies, television shows, and
video games the way we treat tobacco. Make it clear that they are
an adult product. Banish all TV shows where people die from
violence to past the 10 or 11 p.m. news.
</P>
<P>
   Tax the makers of violent video games so such games become more
expensive and less attractive. Give violent movies an R rating
instead of PG-13. We consider it mandatory to ask teen-agers to
abstain from sex. We should include violent shows as well.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could use Littleton to an ironic advantage. It would be
a perfect opportunity to press for popular support to give schools
the tools to turn cliques into communities. Clinton, to his credit,
has proposed tripling the federal budget for after-school grant
programs to $600 million. But he needs much more, since only 5 to
10 percent of middle school students have access to such programs.
No one wants the government to be a nanny. This is to help schools
and civic organizations hire people who can nurture youth while the
parents _ or parent are working.
</P>
<P>
   Violence runs so deep in the American blood that no president up
to now has had the courage to wage an all-out war on it. But we are
at a crossroads. Cities are suing gun makers. Missouri just voted
down concealed handguns. The once invulnerable National Rifle
Association is rapidly isolating itself with its inflexible defense
of gun ownership and by stubbornly going ahead with its Denver
convention, near Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, a politician who always wanted the maximum applause
for minimal risk, the opportunity has never been better to create a
lasting legacy. The community he wants to redefine is sick of guns.
It is coming out of denial. All the community needs is a president
who is dedicated to making a difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
