<HEADLINE>
ABC DERBY CLOSEUP CAMERA IS A LATE SCRATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC has scrapped plans to use a camera mounted on a car that
would have driven along Churchill Downs' inside turf track during
the Kentucky Derby, citing its inability to test the equipment and
the chilly reaction it received from Derby officials.
</P>
<P>
   The camera would have provided viewers with a closeup of the
race. ABC director Craig Janoff said the most dramatic images would
have occurred in the back stretch, where the wide-open field of 20
steeds will jockey for position. Similar devices have been used in
Europe and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ABC will still have plenty of images of the 125th Derby. It
plans to use 40 cameras. One camera that will not be used is the
jockey-cam, a 1-pound camera attached to a jockey's helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Derby officials were hesitant to use it again. ``Some of the
horsemen certainly have their superstitions,'' Janoff said. ``They
don't want anything unusual or different on their jockeys or
thoroughbreds.''
</P>
<P>
   The car-mounted camera had caused a certain amount of pause
among the thoroughbred community. Some of their concerns might have
been assuaged had ABC been able to test the equipment. But rain
prohibited the network from experimenting.
</P>
<P>
   ABC remains undaunted in its pursuit of visual enhancements. ``A
lot of our innovations weren't approved the first time around,''
said ABC producer Curt Gowdy Jr. ``There's no disappointment. We
will just keep moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime's `got game'
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime will air the first WNBA game of the season June 10 at 8
p.m., when the Houston Comets play the Orlando Miracle . . . ESPN
and ESPN2 will air 20 Arena Football League games, starting with
the defending champion Orlando Predators at the Iowa Barnstormers
Sunday at 3 p.m. ESPN will broadcast five regular-season games and
a playoff contest while ESPN2 has 11 regular-season games and three
playoffs. ABC Sports has the Arena Bowl Aug. 22. Mike Gleason and
Merril Hoge will work the booth . . . Pam Shriver joins HBO Sports
as a reporter and analyst for Wimbledon '99 . . . HBO collected
eight Emmys last week and appears to be on track to gain at least
another one. The cable company has started production of ``Fist Or
Freedom: The Story of the '68 Summer Games.'' The documentary
explores arguably the most powerful moment in sports in the 20th
century, when Tommy Smith and John Carlos stood on the victory
stand after placing first and third, respectively, in the 200
meters with their black-gloved fists in the air. The show airs in
August.
</P>
</TEXT>
