<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9439 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-BOS &LR;      04-30 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICK ZITO THINKS HE HAS TWO FOR THE ROSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Can a late-bloomer win the Run for the Roses?
Nick Zito is coming into Saturday's 125th running of the Kentucky
Derby with two budding stars, Stephen Got Even and Adonis, but both
are question marks because of a lack of seasoning. Stephen Got
Even, who appears the more talented of the two, has raced only four
times, while Adonis has gone to the post on just six occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I preach patience,'' said Zito. ``I tell the owners to be
patient. Patience is the key to horse racing. This game will humble
kings. You try to put the sport in perspective. All you can do is
work hard and hope to have the opportunity to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Got Even, a son of the powerful A. P. Indy, who this
year was one of the nominees to the Hall of Fame, is owned by
Stephen Hilbert, president of a financial services company in
Indianapolis, and will be ridden by Chris McCarron. Stephen Got
Even will break from post No. 4 and is 12-1 in the morning line.
Adonis, a son of Chris S., is owned by Ernie Paragallo, a New York
investment banker who specializes in buying yearlings and
2-year-olds and reselling them, and will be ridden by Jorge Chavez.
Adonis will start from No. 1 and is 30-1 in the line, but was
considered good enough to avoid the five-horse mutuel field.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two horses had what we call `2-year-old problems,' ''
said Zito. ``Horses go through growth stages and they get things
that slow them down, like bucked shins (inflammation of the tendon
sheath over the leg bone), and so forth. Stephen Got Even is a big
horse, and it's tougher with big horses. When you're dealt cards in
this game, you can't throw them back in. You're dealt a certain
hand, and you have to deal with the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Got Even has won all three of his starts this year, most
recently an impressive score in the Gallery Furniture at Turfway
Park March 27. In the Gallery, he ran his last quarter in :23 4/5,
an outstanding move, but the five-week gap between the Gallery and
the Derby is not considered ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five weeks is neither good nor bad for him,'' said Zito. ``All
I know is that he's won his last three, all of those races have
been spaced, and he's a great horse. I was a little surprised by
the ease with which he won the Gallery, but, knowing he was a great
horse, I was not that surprised. We're enjoying every moment with
him. We're really pleased with the position we're in. We haven't
missed a day of training with either horse since January. Stephen
Got Even has met the challenge as well as any horse I've ever
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Zito, 51, that's saying a lot since Zito also
trained both Strike the Gold, who won the Derby in 1991, and Go for
Gin, who won the Rose Run in 1994. ``Stephen Got Even is a
tremendous athlete, he's ripped,'' continued Zito. ``He's a
physical specimen. He's in the same league as my two Derby winners.
This is a big-league bred horse (out of Immerse, a Cox's Ridge
mare). It's just wonderful what he's been able to do. He's done
what any great horse does.''
</P>
<P>
   No horse has won the Derby without having run as a 2-year-old
since Apollo in 1882. A streak of 117 years will get a trainer's
attention, and it is almost an unwritten rule that a conditioner
with a top 2-year-old colt will try to get at least one race into
him before he turns age 3.
</P>
<P>
   Zito saw to it that Stephen Got Even and Adonis each made one
start last year, debuting them both on the same day. ``They both
ran Nov. 28 at Aqueduct,'' he said. ``Stephen Got Even finished
second (in the second race), and Adonis finished fifth (in the
ninth). It has always been on my wish list to start all of my
2-year-olds in August at Saratoga, but you have to do what you
can.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Bob Baffert, who is trying to become
the first trainer to win three consecutive Derbys, has the horses
to beat in General Challenge, likely entrymate and top filly
Excellent Meeting, and Prime Timber. But Zito will take his best
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baffert's try at a triple is quite something,'' said Zito.
``It would be an amazing feat. He's in a great position with the
1-2 finishers in the Santa Anita Derby (General Challenge and Prime
Timber). But I like our position, too. We have two wonderful
horses, and they've each won a major prep (Adonis won the Wood
Memorial at Aqueduct April 10). It's three days before the race, my
horses are in great shape and you can't ask for more than that. Of
course, you have to be lucky, too. Things have to go just right. I
think the other trainers know what kind of horse Stephen Got Even
is. But, we have to see (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   This Derby is full of good horses who are grinders. They fight
hard every step of the way, but they lack brilliance. If Stephen
Got Even is, indeed, a ``great'' horse, as Zito says, then he will
win the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the season The Groom is Red, owned by Celtics coach
Rick Pitino and trained by Zito, was considered a serious Derby
contender. He had won the Champagne Stakes at Belmont as a
2-year-old, but he has been unable to do much since. Hovever, Zito
has not given up. ``He's doing fine,'' said Zito. ``He's healthy
and we're looking at the Peter Pan (May 23 at Belmont Park) and the
Belmont Stakes. I think he'd have a shot at the Belmont distance (1
1/2 miles).'' Pitino has purchased some nice young horses. ``He's
got some 2-year-olds we really like,'' said Zito. ``He's got five
2-year-old colts, and one filly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
