<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LONG TERM, MOVE OUT MONEY MARKET, GOLD FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 02, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both public school teachers. Through 403(b)
and IRA accounts, we have been able to accumulate a portfolio
slightly in excess of $1 million to augment our retirement. I
retired last June at the age of 58 and my wife will retire at age
55 in June of the year 2002. It is our plan then to take
distributions from our savings at the rate of 5 percent per annum,
with the balance of the funds going to our heirs upon our deaths.
My wife will be receiving a pension from the state retirement
systems, and I am currently receiving pensions from the U.S.
government and the state retirement system. Our problem is that we
are not sure as to the proper distribution of our holdings. We have
always managed our own portfolios and have been relatively
aggressive in our investment choices. Although we are somewhat
concerned with protection of principal, we do not want to be left
behind by any expanding market either. Our current holdings are all
with Fidelity, and they are distributed thus: money market, 21
percent; Dividend Growth, 21 percent; Fidelity fund, 14 percent;
Equity Income, 11 percent; Aggressive Growth, 6.7 percent;
Retirement Growth, 6 percent; bond funds, 7.6 percent; Japan Small
Company, 4.3 percent; Convertible Securities, 3.3 percent; Capital
and Income, 2.3 percent; Select Gold, 1.5 percent, and a trading
account representing 2 percent. Are there any recommendations you
would make?
</P>
<P>
   R.L., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. Given your purposes, this portfolio doesnt need much
tinkering. I would suggest only one definite change, and a couple
of changes you might -- or might not -- want to make.
</P>
<P>
   As I'll bet you have already guessed if you have read very many
of these columns, the definite change involves the money market
position. Given that you make it clear that you view this as a
long-term portfolio, designed to deliver your desired income stream
for the balance of your life and then to pass to your heirs, the
money market holding is much too conservative for my taste. I would
move the entire position into intermediate-term bond funds such as
Mortgage Securities, Intermediate Bond or Government Securities
funds. Ifyou feel strongly that you want an ultra-conservative
holding to represent a bedrock for this portfolio, at the minimum
you could move to Fidelity Short-Term Bond fund, although I would
prefer the intermediate-term funds for a long-term portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Second, I view the small position in the Select Gold fund with a
jaundiced eye. I tend to view precious metals funds with favor only
as short-term trading positions for people who believe big changes
loom in the gold markets on a fairly near-term basis. If you look
at the long-term records of this fund -- a 9.52 percent five-year
average annual loss and a .39 percent average annual loss over a
decade -- you'll see what I mean. So unless you fall into the
category of a person who believe gold is about to take a big jump,
I'd cash out of this one, moving the entire proceeds into the
Capital and Income (or junk bond) fund. (And if you do believe that
gold is about to leap forward, your position is too small to do you
much good.)
</P>
<P>
   The effect of these two moves would be to take the fixed-income
side of the portfolio to a level somewhere in excess of 35 percent,
compared to a current level around 34 percent. (I can't be more
precise because your stated allocations add up to 100.7 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, I wish I saw a little more diversification on
the stock side. With the assumption that your trading account is
dominated by large-cap domestic stocks, I come up with less than 10
percent of the portfolio that represents a diversification away
from either large-cap stocks or fixed-income issues. I suggest you
establish some representation in the small-cap universe, and also
take a position in the excellent Fidelity Select Health Care fund,
drawing the cash to make these moves from any one of your three
large-cap balanced funds -- Dividend Growth, Fidelity Fund, and
Retirement Growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In your column of April 4 you mentioned that Vanguards GNMA
fund, in which I have some money, carries some risk. I am
interested in knowing what the risk would be so I may act
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   B.R., Encinitas, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Most fixed-income funds carry three kinds of risk. First
comes credit risk -- the chance that the institution or people who
stand behind the borrowings might default on the payments. Second
comes interest rate risk; this is the chance that interest rates
might rise, causing the value of the fixed-income securities you
hold to fall. And third is prepayment risk, which is the chance
that the borrower might prepay the loan -- usually at a time when
it is to the borrowers advantage and your disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Ginnie Mae funds carry no practical level of credit risk. The
portfolio of a GNMA fund is made up of securities representing
bundles of federally guaranteed mortgages. The government not only
stands behind the principal payments on these mortgages, but also
the interest payments. Thus the only real level of risk here is
that the government either reneges on its promise or goes bust. To
my view, thats fantasy, not risk.
</P>
<P>
   Interest risk is another story. While the government guarantees
payments of interest and principal on these bonds, it cannot and
does not guarantee their market value. Like other fixed income
holdings, the value of GNMA securities reacts inversely to interest
rates, which means their value rises as interest rates fall, and
their value declines as interest rates rise. When interest rates
make large or sudden jumps, these funds can follow suit, showing
very substantial gains or losses. Worse, this market behavior often
occurs when investors are only worried that interest rates might
change.
</P>
<P>
   If you look over the long-term results of your fund, you can see
the results for 1994, when the fund lost .95 percent; during that
year there were no substantial changes in interest rates, but there
was a lot of worry that there might be; accordingly the fund was
pushed into the red (albeit not as deeply as the average 4.02
percent loss for its intermediate-term government bond fund peers).
Typically when interest rates turn around, or when people stop
worry about them, the GNMA funds make up the lost ground. Thus in
1995, when it appeared rates would remain stable, Vanguard GNMA
came back with a 17.04 percent total return, effectively making up
for the lost ground of the year before. Such behavior is why I
never recommend GNMA funds for short-term holdings; they work best
only when the owners can take a long-term view and ride out the bad
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The third element of risk is prepayment risk. Since the
individuals who have taken these mortgages can prepay at any time,
the owners face the risk that falling interest rates, which should
have caused their holdings to rise in value, will have a different
effect -- causing the mortgage borrowers to refinance, thus sending
the portfolio manager out to replace the prepaid mortgages with new
securities. When that happens he or she is faced with the
possibilities of either buying replacement securities with lower
yields or paying a premium price to buy securities with the same or
better yields -- either way bad for the funds shareowners.
</P>
<P>
   The whole question of duration is a complicated one for GNMA
owners and fund managers. Although these securities are backed by
traditional mortgages with maturity dates ranging from 15 to 30
years, the common experience of mortgage lenders is that the
average mortgage is paid off in about seven or eight years. Thus
when we consider prepayment risk for GNMAs, it's the risk that
lower rates will cause prepayments to go beyond the normal level.
</P>
<P>
   But you can take consolation in this: When interest rates are as
low as they are now, its pretty unlikely that rates could fall far
enough to make refinancing attractive to very many mortgage
borrowers. Moreover, when you view that prepayment risk, consider
also that GNMA funds tend to yield about one half of one percent
more than a comparable government-securities fund which doesn't
carry the prepayment risk. Thus, you are being paid an extra return
for bearing this risk.
</P>
<P>
   In summary, the risks that GNMA funds carry make them poor
short-term investments unless you are a market pro, but they are a
fine conservative holding for a person with a long-term viewpoint
-- say 10 years or more -- and with the stomach to ride out the
bumps. And bear in mind, when the bumps come, it doesn't mean the
income stream stops -- the interest checks keep rolling in through
good times and bad. Thus I consider GNMA funds a fine investment
for people seeking a steady and solid income stream -- and Vanguard
GNMA is one of the best of the group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
