<HEADER>
A9444 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     04-30 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN ONE WAY TO UNSTICK WINDOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 02, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The painter painted the outside of my windows so heavily that
they are painted shut, and I can't open them. I can't make them
budge from the inside, and cannot get to the outside frame because
the aluminum storms were closed after painting. How in the world
can I open them before I croak from the heat?
</P>
<P>
   TOO HOT in Dorchester
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah yes, the window that has been painted shut. The paint that
oozed between sash and jamb may not have dried completely in those
tight spots, making it hold the sash even more, almost like glue.
But never fear, there are answers, but none easy.
</P>
<P>
   On the inside, you can take off the side stops, the thin strips
of wood nailed or screwed onto the jamb, and which are holding the
bottom sash in place. With these stops off, you can wiggle the
bottom sash back and forth (toward you and away from you), to break
the paint bead, allowing the window to open. This is the easiest
and least complicated way to do it, but doesn't always work.
</P>
<P>
   The other way: Remove the aluminum storms. It is a simple matter
of removing the screws along the window's border, and pulling it
off carefully, breaking the caulk that was applied when the windows
were installed.
</P>
<P>
   With this access, with a utility knife, cut the paint bead
wherever the sash and the jamb meet. Insert a pry bar under the
sash, between sash and sill, and pry up. Pry with two bars, to
prevent the sash from slanting and getting even tighter.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have the sash free, scrape off the paint where it
seeped into the joints. Let the remaining paint dry.
</P>
<P>
   Before putting storms back in place, scrape off caulk left on
the wood casing (frame), apply a fresh bead of caulk on the face of
the casing on three sides of the opening, then apply the storm,
using the original holes for the screws; this will allow proper
positioning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house has a full set of wood storm windows that really are
not working wery well; they leak and they are the very devil to
take down and put up twice a year. The house is 80 years old. Would
it be acceptable to replace those wood storms with aluminum triple
track ones? The main windows seem in pretty good shape, so I don't
think it is necessary to replace them.
</P>
<P>
   RUTH SHASSMAN, West Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It certainly would be acceptable, in fact desirable,
especially since the main windows are intact and presumably well
weatherstripped and glazed. Putting up new, high quality aluminum
storms will cost you a little more than $100 per window. Do not opt
for the $30 or $50 bargains sold in larger lumber stores; they do
not work very well. The top grade aluminum storm (painted brown or
white) is, in my opinion, Harvey Industries' True Channel,
virtually airtight. They are usually installed by contractors, but
you can order them custom made (to fit your windows) through any
local lumber store, and install them yourself. However, the
installation charge is minor, so you might as well have someone put
them up for you.
</P>
<P>
   That $100 or so per window for new quality storms is half to a
third the cost of replacement sash for your main windows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The reglazing of my bathtub is very nice, but the plumber
scratched it. My husband painted the scratches with a latex epoxy
paint, but it is a little yellowish against the pure white of the
regazing. How can we disguise the scratches?
</P>
<P>
   DOROTHY SHUSTER, Brighton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Try to find the reglazers so they can do the repairs. Short
of that, you could sand the scratches ever so slightly, and apply a
white appliance patch-up enamel. Apply very thin coats and hope for
the best.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am siding my house with white cedar shingles, which I like
better than red. I also like stains; is there any difference in
staining red or white cedar? If I let the white cedar weather to
that silver color and don't like it in a few years, can I stain it?
</P>
<P>
   J. B., Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you can stain over weathered white cedar, and I suggest
you use a semitransparent stain; the color is your choice. Only one
coat is needed, and in five years you can do it again; only one
coat at time. The advantage of white cedar in this case is that you
will get no cedar bleed through the stain; cedar bleed is the
depositing of the color (of red cedar) on the stain by water.
</P>
<P>
   Staining red cedar is different. If you stain it a light color,
those brown stains can occur. One way to fix this is to apply a
dark stain; you may still get the stains but they won't show.
Another way to avoid the cedar bleed is to apply an oil-based
primer, then a stain; but the stain must be a solid color stain;
two coats are needed. There is a risk in this latter technique; a
primer and solid color stains can peel; not as much as paint, but
still the possiblity is there.
</P>
<P>
   So you have a lot of choices, some with problems, some not. The
choice is yours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
