u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-SHEIK-BOS &LR;      04-30 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-SHEIK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUBAI SHEIKH BRINGS DIFFERENT STYLE TO LOUISVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ His words were not sparse, but neither were
they generous, when Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum stood outside Barn
45 in the chill morning air at Churchill Downs Thursday and
explained why he was here.
</P>
<P>
   The media who had gathered around the Sheikh knew exactly why he
was here; simply because he was rich enough to do it. No more and
no less. But skepticism dripped from the American questioners.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Mohammed will have two horses in Saturday's Kentucky
Derby, Worldly Manner and Aljabr, and neither has raced this year
in the American definition of a race. Questioner after questioner
attempted to educate the Sheikh that this race, this Kentucky
Derby, cannot be won this way.
</P>
<P>
   English bookmakers have quoted odds of 5-1 on Worldly Manner
because the Sheikh is so respected there; here in Louisville, the
Sheikh's two horses will have odds of 15-1 or more because
Americans know American ways of training horses; the Sheikh's ways
could not be more different.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done this often,'' said the Sheikh. ``We have brought
horses from Dubai to the (European) classics and they have done
well.'' Very well, to be precise, as Godolphin Stable horses have
been among the most successful in Europe for years.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the memory is still fresh in Louisville of how the
Sheikh brought in his Swain for the Breeders' Cup Classic last
November, and Swain _ who finished third by less than a length _
lost a race he should have won if European jockey Frankie Dettori
had kept a straight run through the Churchill Downs stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have taken the Sheikh to task for supposedly hiding his
Derby horses, but he said gently that this was not so. California
trainer Richard Mandella agreed, saying he saw Worldly Manner and
Aljabr race in a private race the Sheikh put on days before the
Dubai World Cup in March ``and the caliber of that race was
excellent, up to the standards of top'' American races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect what Mandella said,'' said the Sheikh. ``Why do
people say they can't see your horses training when all the World
Cup people who were there (for the Dubai World Cup) were there to
see the (private) race. Why do they say they didn't see?''
</P>
<P>
   That private race, the Sheikh went on, ``was lacking only the
crowd. We made everything just like a race, but because we didn't
have the crowd, we had to put in the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Mohammed is a member of one of the richest families in
the world, the ruling family of oil-rich Dubai of the United Arab
Emirates. Money does talk, but seldom in these circumstances. From
time to time, mused Alistair Donald, the English head of the
International Racing Bureau, the Sheikh had been questioned in
formal press conferences, but seldom, if ever, like this. By an
American horde.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born on a horse,'' the Sheikh said, clad in a dark blue
sweater, the dark blue of his family's Godolphin stable. Godolphin
is a major force in European racing, but on the first weekend of
every May, to the Sheikh's chagrin, he would be in Newmarket,
England, for the 2,000 Guineas, the first race of England's Triple
Crown, followed by the Derby at Epsom and the St. Leger at
Doncaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, I wanted to be here for the Kentucky Derby,'' said
the Sheikh, pronouncing ``derby'' as the English do _ as in
``darby.'' ``I would ask my trainer, `Why don't we go to this great
race? The Kentucky Derby?' I've had 56 trainers, and I would ask
them why would they not come to Kentucky, and they would say, `No,
no, no' . . . all they cared for were the European classics.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, his words were generous, as the Sheikh opened up to
disclose his dream. He had videotapes of all the Kentucky Derby
races ever filmed, and he would watch them over and over, even
learning the words of ``My Old Kentucky Home.'' ``The sun shines
bright on my old Kentucky Home . . . Yes?'' said the Sheikh. ``It's
very emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was when Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum spoke of The Horse,
the animal who so long has meant so much to Arabia, that his words
flowed. Yes, said the Sheikh, the thoroughbred was created when
Allah himself blew upon the South wind and from the South wind the
thoroughbred was formed. And Arabia had the world's best horses for
hundreds of years before the West had seen even one.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of when he was a student at Cambridge University in
England 25 years ago, and one day he decided to go to the sales at
Newmarket and buy some horses. And when he returned to his
lodgings, ``the mother in the house where I was living asked me,
`Why do you go and buy horses?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It had been trying enough ``just to go to the sales ring, and
they had said to me, `Who are you? Where are you from? Give me your
card. Give me your address' and all of that.'' And it was worse
when he returned from the sales ring because the mother in the
house where he was staying said he was too young to know horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she didn't know where the (thoroughbred) horse is
descended from. She was only able to go back to Eclipse (a great
English horse of 125 years ago). And they said to me, `Why are you
buying horses. Why don't you stay in your tent with your camel?' ''
</P>
<P>
   To the English, to Europeans, to Americans, it is an accepted
fact that all thoroughbreds are descended from one of three horses
_ the Godolphin Barb, the Byerly Turk, and the Darly Arabian, three
stallions who the English say were imported to England in the
mid-1700s. Arabs argue the three sires were purloined.
</P>
<P>
   `` `No, no, no,' '' the Sheikh recalled saying to the woman in
the house where he was living. ``All the horses are descended from
horses I have back home. They were surprised . . . there were
arguments for three months. I said to them, `If you can find just
one (thoroughbred) horse in the world who is not descended from an
Arab horse . . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   It is so because horses were so beloved in Arabia, so necessary
for survival in Arabia, the Sheikh said. Even before the Crusades
when Europeans discovered these horses, ``in Arabia a man would
travel as far as 1,000 miles just to breed his horses to a top
sire. For safety reasons, they needed good horses in Arabia, they
needed good horses to run away (from enemies), to disappear
sometimes or to fight. The blood of these horses of Arabia, when
they mix it with European horses, it became the thoroughbred.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arab loves the horse. He loves the falcon, he loves the
dog, the Saluki and when he has only a little bit of food, first
they give it to the horse and then they give it to the children.
It's the life of an Arab.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum will have his two horses in
the Kentucky Derby, and he will have two horses in the 2,000
Guineas at Newmarket. On Sunday in Newmarket, he may have as many
as three horses in the 1,000 Guineas at Newmarket, the first race
of the English Triple Crown for fillies.
</P>
<P>
   And he would not speak of how he enticed jockey Jerry Bailey to
ride Worldly Manner, when Bailey might have had his pick of many in
the field. The rumor is that the Sheikh guaranteed Bailey some
$75,000, which the winning jockey will receive. ``This is
private,'' said the Sheikh when delicately asked of the rumor. ``We
don't talk about money.''
</P>
<P>
   But he would talk on and on about horses, about how he decided
last year to come to the Derby and how he will return here next
year and four or five more years with Godolphin horses to attempt
to win ``this great race.'' If he fails after five years of trying,
maybe ``we will change our mind about this race.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he should win, ``then I will fly over the moon,'' said
the Sheikh. He may be worth billions, he may fly jets and
helicopters and be vital to his government, but most of all, he is
as much in love with The Horse as any Arabian of the last 1,000
years. His stable has trainers all throughout Europe, but it is the
Sheikh who does much of the training; and, of course, ``I have the
final word on training.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his horses have been belittled for their preparation and
talent. Ah, but it is not the first time, said the Sheikh. ``We did
well at the sales until we brought in experts,'' he quipped. ``And
it is when we brought in the experts to tell us what to do that we
went down.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the Sheikh has learned a lesson as old as Arabia. An
Arab does not have to be told when a horse is a horse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
