<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC THE MENACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The most enduring lesson of politics is this simple nostrum:
If you wait long enough, you eventually find yourself on the same
side of some issue with folks you've bitterly opposed on others.
</P>
<P>
   Today is such a day. I rise to align myself with the editorial
page of The Wall Street Journal on the issue of one Milosevic,
Slobodan, archfiend of the Kosovo Crisis. Thursday's editorial
rationale for the elimination of Milosevic's reign over his fellow
Serbs is a clearheaded summing up of this dreadful manipulator's
disgraceful record.
</P>
<P>
   For a dozen years he consolidated his power with methods
Stalinesque. He seized the Kosovo issue by the rhetorical throat in
1987, and the dozen years since have now culminated in the
uprooting of more than a million Albanian Kosovars.The editorial
aims to justify the newspaper's previous call for ``the ouster of
Slobodan Milosevic from the Serbian government.'' Here in one
paragraph is the argument that trumps isolationist calls to
forswear military intervention out of the conviction that the
Balkan peoples are always at each others' throats, and we should
steer clear of the carnage:
</P>
<P>
   ``The passing conventional wisdom is that these primitives,
after living for generations as neighbors and intermarrying, woke
up one morning and decided to kill each other over ancient wrongs.
Close attention to the history of the region since the fall of
communism, for example by European leaders and publics now
supportive of a military response, shows quite a different picture.
To wit, that of Slobodan Milosevic assiduously fanning the flames
of national and ethnic hatred for his own advantage, and reaching
new heights of cruelty and duplicity in dealing with his neighbors
and world leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Let me not lapse, after doffing the cap in the Journal's
direction, into a recounting of instances where I've parted company
with that crew over yellow rain, Clinton, Starr, blah blah. And I
will bite this quivering lip before amplifying any suggestion that
if Clinton had not been preoccupied with saving his butt from Starr
and the Journal's motorcycle gang of Clinton-haters, the president
might have done more to prevent the ethnic cleansing debacle.
</P>
<P>
   No one in leadership in the West fully comprehended the
depravity of Milosevic. We are all chastened by the emergence of
this mass murderer, inciter of mass rape, and nationalist scourge
of Biblical scope. Many in the West oppose the NATO bombing. Like
Clinton, Tony Blair, and the other heads of state linked in the
NATO coalition, I think it inescapable that we respond to the
sacking of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Blair mentioned early on, in responding to a parliamentary sally
claiming the NATO bombing actually worsened the situation, that
some 2,000 Kosovars had perished before the first NATO ordnance
landed. The Journal editorial recounts Milosevic's persistent
bloodletting through 10 long years of more or less uninterrupted
warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan reminds me of the loopy Knight in ``Monty Python and
the Holy Grail,'' whose belligerent swordplay is incapable of
protecting him from the enemy's retaliation. Whiff, goes an arm;
off comes a leg; zap, there goes another arm; the remaining limb is
next excised. What's left is a silly torso-less head mouthing empty
threats, oblivious to his diminished estate.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has whittled his own people down to a rogue state,
diminished in area, numbers, reputation, economy, and moral
respect. For the Serbs to rally to his cause, to don their target
stickers and shout defiance at Western TV crews, to proclaim
innocence and beg pity for their plight, leaves the most important
piece of the puzzle missing still. Why are the Serbs not mindful of
their leader's persistent violations of norms of civilized
behavior? Can they be ignorant of the depradations against the
Albanian Kosovars?
</P>
<P>
   For every Serb civilian killed by an errant NATO bomb, there are
a hundred dead Kosovars. For every Serb family deprived of housing
by some of NATO's inevitable ``collateral damage,'' there are a
thousand refugees evicted by Serb bayonets. For every Serb
homestead damaged by NATO warplanes, there are hundreds of Kosovar
homes looted and burned by Serb marauders.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot sustain a modern society, like the Europe that was
envisioned last New Year's Eve, with the introduction of the Euro,
and the consolidation of economic and governmental power that it
represented, with a Hitlerian regime pillaging the Balkans.
Milosevic had to be stopped. The nascent democracy movement in
Serbia had next to no success; the force had to come from outside
the Serb community.
</P>
<P>
   The war is not pretty. The West has inherited the dispossessed
Kosovars, a million strong, and the cost of restoring them to some
semblance of a secure lifestyle will be extremely expensive. But
the alternative _ allowing this crackpot to destabilize every
entity around him _ was costlier still.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal is right: the departure of Milosevic from the scene
is much to be desired. He may not be indicted yet, but he is a war
criminal. He and his ghastly lieutenants should not be welcomed in
any civilized country unless wearing handcuffs. And should a lucky
piece of NATO ordnance find him some night as he sleeps, so much
the better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
