<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE, FIDELITY TOUTS RELIABILITY INSTEAD OF FLASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments wants to be the Volvo of the on-line
brokerage world.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston company's new ad campaign, launched this week, is
built around the theme of reliability. The not-so-subtle point is
that in a field where other on-line brokers may be fly-by-nights or
have computer systems that fail, Fidelity is the one you can count
on to execute your trades safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have a reliability record other competitors
don't,'' says Stephen Cone, head of marketing at Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises a question: Is being Volvo the right image to have
in a business where many of the customers would seem to be Corvette
types? Competitors like E-Trade and Ameritrade are bombarding the
airwaves with edgy, irreverent ads that make fun of the traditional
financial establishment. In one Ameritrade ad an embarrassed jogger
admits to friends that she still invests in mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave Fidelity? ``Their strength, their brand,
is also a challenge,'' says Alex Stein, a principal with Gomez
Advisors, a Concord consulting firm. ``Fidelity is identified with
trust: `You can rely on us to manage your investments.' That is
very different from the message you want to send to on-line
investors who tend to be confident and self-directed customers.''
</P>
<P>
   On-line investing is exploding. In a research report, US Bancorp
Piper Jaffray said that electronic trading volume climbed 49
percent in the first three months of the year. The same report
found that the industry added another 1.2 million accounts in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is participating in the boom, and its own numbers are
even rosier than those in the Piper Jaffray report. With 2.8
million accounts and more than $200 billion in assets, Fidelity is
already the nation's second-largest discount broker. Charles Schwab
is far and away the leader. Most surveys place Fidelity further
back in the pack when size is measured by daily on-line trades.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Fidelity customers were making 25,000 trades a day;
today they are making 80,000. More than 70 percent of the trades
are executed electronically, up from 20 percent two years ago.
According to Cone, Fidelity is signing up 20,000 new brokerage
customers a week, 60 percent of whom already do business with
Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   The consulting firms that track on-line brokerage generally give
Fidelity high marks. In a recent survey of electronic traders
conducted by Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass., Fidelity was
selected as best in the industry. Fidelity scored highest in a
category called confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are one of the few brokers who have yet to have a major
computer failure,'' says Michael Gazala, a Forrester analyst.
Gazala says customers also appreciate the fact that they can
contact Fidelity by phone or in person if there is ever a computer
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester found that Fidelity was most popular with what it
called ``long-term investors.'' People who think of themselves as
traders, especially active traders, preferred Suretrade and Datek,
two low-cost competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean Fidelity is stuck with the fuddy-duddies like us
while all the young and cool investors flock to the competition?
</P>
<P>
   No way, says Cone. ``It's a fantasy that you have to be young
and hip to use the Internet,'' he says. ``The Internet is widely
used by people in all age groups.'' Fidelity's own numbers show
that an equal percentage of customers in all age groups trade
electronically. In fact, says Cone, it is the youngest customers _
those in their 20s _ who are most likely to want some human help in
executing their trades.
</P>
<P>
   Cone says Fidelity's biggest problem in brokerage is its fame as
a mutual fund company. ``It's a challenge when you are so well
known for one thing to get known for something else,'' he says. The
fact that Fidelity is privately held, not publicly traded, also has
hurt, says Cone, because the company is often left out of stories
that focus on the big run-up in stock prices of competitors like
E-Trade and Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   The current campaign should help raise Fidelity's profile. The
television ads produced by Hill Holliday are short and punchy. The
best one, a 15-second spot, flashes the words: ``On-line trading is
like the Old West.'' Then you hear the sound of guns going off
followed by the words: ``The slow die first.'' The tag line for the
ads is, ``Every second counts,'' suggesting that you need someone
reliable to handle the job.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity won't say how much it will spend on advertising, but
Cone concedes it will be much less than the estimated $150 million
E-Trade is expected to spend over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Says Cone, ``We will have to be smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
