<HEADER>
A9457 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMAZON-EXCHANGE-ART-B     04-30 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-EXCHANGE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET REVENGE FOR ENTREPRENEUR AMAZON.COM MADE MILLIONAIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Stig Leschly still remembers the rejection his
business plan got when he entered a Harvard Business School
competition last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judges wrote that I had little business experience, none
of it relevant to starting an Internet company, that my idea was
not unique and the financial opportunity not large enough to
attract investment,'' said the 29-year-old Danish-born
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, he ignored the judges' advice and formed
Exchange.com, an Internet company that brings together buyers and
sellers of rare or out-of-print books and old music recordings.
</P>
<P>
   This week Leschly got sweet revenge when Amazon.com, the
nation's largest Internet bookseller, said it will acquire the
company for a reported $200 million in stock, making him a
multimillionaire in barely seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the dizzying market for Internet startups, the speed
with which Leschly went from tinkerer to tycoon is startling.
Barely seven months after starting the firm with one employee in a
leaky warehouse, Leschly's alliance with Amazon.com catapults him
to the forefront of the fast-growing on-line collectibles business.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bezos, Amazon's founder and chief executive said the
acquisition was ``a win for Amazon.com customers because it further
increases our selection of rare and obscure items.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bezos nor Leschly would disclose the precise amount
until the acquisition closes next month. Exchange.com was one of
three companies that Seattle-based Amazon.com said it was buying
Monday for a total of $645 million in Amazon stock.
</P>
<P>
   Leschly is ``remarkable for his age, both in his intellect and
his vision which will help build the management team at
Amazon.com,'' said George Conrades, the former chairman of BBN Inc.
and a partner at Polaris Venture Partners, whose $4.5 million
investement launched the company.
</P>
<P>
   Polaris' funding help attract $8.5 million more from Accel
Partners, a Silicon Valley venture firm; the Washington Post Co.;
and individual investors including Mitch Kapor, the founder of
Lotus Development Corp., plus Leschly's family. Leschly's father,
Jan, is chief executive of SmithKline Beecham PLC, the large
pharmaceutical company.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father thinks the Internet is a town in Minnesota,''
chuckled Leschly, whose mother is a dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Leschly, whose only trace of Scandinavian heritage, besides
azure blue eyes and ash-blond hair, are the clogs he wears around
his spartan Cambridge office, said he got the idea to start the
company in May 1997 while still a student at Harvard University,
where he was pursuing both law and business degrees. Leschly
graduated from Harvard in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A music lover with a penchant for Louis Armstrong records,
Leschly said he was in a used record store in Cambridge when he
picked up a copy of Goldmine, a trade publication for buying and
selling old vinyl records and used compact disks.
</P>
<P>
   Having just obtained an Internet account, he had begun to
realize that the World Wide Web was a way of bringing people and
products together. Leschly said he saw an opportunity that could
appeal to collectors while also helping dealers who often travel
the country to reach customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want an old Charlie Parker jazz recording or the B-side
of a Rolling Stones disk that, for example, may have only been sold
in Japan, you could find them on the 'Net rather than blindly
calling up record dealers,'' Leschly said. He also envisioned the
same concept appealing to secondhand and antique booksellers, and
other dealers of collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing $75,000 from his family and friends, he rented space
in an aging warehouse in Allston with a leaky roof and began to put
together a business plan along with a prototype of the software.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, he and Sri Rao, a software designer who previously
worked at Firefly, the Internet company acquired by Microsoft Corp.
last year, obtained $2 million from Polaris Ventures to build their
on-line marketplace to bring together music buyers and sellers.
</P>
<P>
   There is no charge for buyers to browse the company's database
of 9 million books _ double the size of Amazon.com's listings _ and
three million record listings. Buyers can telephone or e-mail the
seller, who lists the price, shipping costs, and form of payment.
After the transaction, Exchange.com collects up to 8 percent of the
purhcase price from the seller. Leschly said the average book price
is in the $35 range, although one leatherbound first edition of
``Winnie the Pooh'' by A.A. Milne is available for $2,000 while
some vinyl records go for $16 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the power of eBay and realized I had to move fast,''
said Leschly, referring to the spectacular growth of the Internet
auction house, whose stock price has risen almost tenfold since
October. The San Jose, Calif.-based eBay now has a market value of
almost $27 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By focusing narrowly on old music and antique books Leschly has
attracted nearly 3,000 dealers, who every evening update their
inventory on Exchange.com's two Web sites, MusicFile or Bibliofind
_ the latter acquired by Leschly in January.
</P>
<P>
   One music seller, Edward Smith of The Record Finder in Glen
Allen, Va., says using Exchange.com has turned the business focus
around from relying on storefront sales and a limited market to
reaching a worldwide audience using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all but closing our `real world' store and selling
music solely on line through our company's mail-order catalog,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of creating the book software, Leschly learned of
Bibliofind, a struggling Internet exchange service for buyers and
sellers of antique books that was run out of Great Barrington by
its founders, Michael and Helen Seltzer. The middle-aged couple
realized the technical demands and the capital required to enhance
the site were more than they could handle and sold Bibliofind to
Exchange.com.
</P>
<P>
   As for Leschly, he now has a new challenge. Under the Amazon.com
agreement, he must relocate the Cambridge company to Amazon.com's
Seattle headquarters within the next two months, which also means
uprooting about 25 of the 31 employees. For a boy whose family
emigrated from Denmark to Princeton, N.J., when he was 9 years old,
the move is no big deal. But ``it's a touchy situation with my
girlfriend,'' Leschly said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
