<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9459 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-30 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDUBON RANCH ABOUNDS WITH AVIAN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUDUBON CANYON RANCH, Calif. _ Timing can be everything in love,
and so it is at Audubon Canyon Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Show up in midsummer, fall or winter, and well, you'll not only
find the gate locked, but nothing beyond worth trying to get a peep
at anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But arrive now ... the gate is open, and beyond? Well, let me
tell you about the birds and the bees. Especially the birds.
</P>
<P>
   Especially great blue herons, great egrets and snowy egrets.
</P>
<P>
   The feature show at Audubon Canyon Ranch is romance for these
huge, beautiful birds, from start to finish, from the first shy
calls to kicking junior out of the nest. In the middle comes
courtship, building a home, making some babies, hatching them, then
sending them off for future education, and it is happening from now
through early July.
</P>
<P>
   Checking in this week, so far there are nine blue heron nests
here, one with chicks already, and also 14 nesting pairs of egrets
in various stages of courtship, including a few just making eyes at
each other, and wondering, ``Is that the one?''
</P>
<P>
   There is a perfect spot to watch all this _ that is, an official
viewing point to see all kinds of shenanigans and mind-lightening
foolishness in the nests high in redwood trees, just across the
canyon. To reach it requires about a short but steep walk, usually
about 20 minutes for most. The ranch guides always provide spotting
scopes.
</P>
<P>
   Audubon Canyon Ranch is located on the Marin Coast off Highway
1, with the entrance 3 1/2 miles north of Stinson Beach. There is
no entry fee, though a small donation is requested. It has become
one of the most popular outdoor classrooms in the San Francisco Bay
area, with about 5,000 youngsters making the trip here each year.
It is open now to the public only on weekends and holidays through
July 1, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., and reserved for visiting students on
weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a great trip for anybody. And though bird-watching
doesn't flip everybody's pancake, here you not only get to see
large and regal herons and egrets but get to see them in action.
</P>
<P>
   The great egret is snow white and thin, and is about 4 feet
tall. Its cousin, the snowy egret, is also pure white, but about
half the size. From the near-perfect vantage point at the ranch,
you can watch them across a canyon doing their thing in giant nests
atop redwood trees. It can be a spectacular show that you will
never forget.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with a nervous glances from afar, then proceeds with a
few tentative squawks. If you watch this closely, there are times
the egrets just seem to look at each other for a spell, as if they
are trying to figure out if this is the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, somebody has to make a move, or nothing happens,
right? End of movie. What often occurs here is that Mr. Egret will
make a cautious overture, offering a single twig to its potential
mate, as if asking, ``Do you wanna?'' If there is no response,
well, no deal. But if Ms. Egret gets a twig of her own and offers
it in return, the silent answer is, ``Yes, I wanna,'' and off they
go to make a nest, often starting with those first two twigs.
</P>
<P>
   That is what is happening here now for the egrets, and there
appears to be plenty of ``I wannas.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the nearby blue herons look like something right out
of Jurassic Park, like pterodactyls lifting off with their huge,
labored wing beats, their wingspans ranging to seven feet.
</P>
<P>
   With their young hatchlings in the nests, ma and pa heron often
will make trips to nearby Bolinas Lagoon for food. Upon return of a
parent, Junior will grab its beak, which triggers a motor response,
where the undigested goodies are regurgitated all over the nest.
</P>
<P>
   What could be more fun for Junior and his brothers and sisters
than to pounce on the treats and gobble them up as if it's their
first meal? Well, in some cases, it is their first meal.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, what's for lunch? As spring progresses, and the
young birds gain size, strength and feathers, the viewing evolves
to another tradition that might be called ``Bon Voyage'' or
``Goodbye Maybelline.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in mid-June, you can see the young birds standing in
the nests, practicing stroking their wings as if simulating the
flying experience. They are already big, and it is like watching
Mark McGwire take practice swings in the on-deck circle.
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky, you may even see them stray out on a limb.
</P>
<P>
   But then they look down. They see the ground down there about
100 feet below and figure, ``Nah, back into the nest. Say, Mom,
when's dinner?''
</P>
<P>
   At first, mom puts up with it. Then she gets a little irritated.
Then she gets angry, and it's time for the heave-ho.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, the adult herons often just kick the kids right
out of the nest with a push. The youngsters quickly discovers that
gravity wins. They have about 10 seconds to figure out how to fly
before the ground suddenly arrives. Since bird skeletons are
extremely rare on the forest floor, that must be enough time to
figure out the correct behavior response. Wish my kids could learn
that fast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For information, phone Audubon Canyon Ranch at 415-868-9244.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
