<HEADER>
A9460 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-30 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S LIBRIAN TO THE RICH AND FAMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To call him Bill Gates's librarian would be missing the point.
For the past several years, rare-book and manuscript expert Kenneth
Rendell has been assembling one of the most astonishing collections
ever put together. And yes, his client is the Microsoft chief
executive, who keeps many of the treasures in his lakeside trophy
home outside Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell has never discussed his relationship with Gates _ but
he's left plenty of hints lying around. Wired magazine recently
reported that Rendell ``builds entire collections'' and ``will buy,
install, monitor, and update'' a complete library. The magazine
didn't mention Gates, but in a 1997 interview with The Seattle
Times, speaking from his home on the windward side of Maui, Rendell
more or less confirmed that his frequent trips to Seattle come at
the behest of Gates. (Other meta-rich Microsofties, including
in-house ``visionary'' Nathan Myhrvold, are also Rendell's
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   What a commission! Gates loves ``The Great Gatsby'' and has
procured four first editions. (There's a quote from ``Gatsby''
emblazoned above the library's shelves.) The private-school grad
also seems to favor preppy romances. He has first editions of J. D.
Salinger's ``The Catcher in the Rye'' and John Knowles's Phillips
Exeter-based homoerotic classic, ``A Separate Peace.'' Not to
mention some way serious stuff: Isaac Newton's workbooks and
Leonardo da Vinci's Codex Leicester, which Gates acquired at
auction five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Working out of a former bank building in South Natick, Mass. _
he uses the vault to store valuables _ Rendell has built an
impressive empire that includes an East Side Manhattan gallery and
a world-class private collection of World War II memorabilia. He
experiences sporadic bursts of fame. Rendell played a leading role
in debunking Newsweek's bogus Hitler ``diaries,'' and more recently
he was identified as one of the dealers asked to authenticate the
fake Marilyn Monroe-John F. Kennedy ``correspondence.'' (He
didn't.)
</P>
<P>
   But Rendell doesn't want to become famous as Bill Gates's
librarian _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meet the author
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Geographic Traveler magazine and Web site
(ngtraveler.com) has a quiz called ``Where's Melissa?,'' which
challenges readers to divine the whereabouts of peripatetic travel
scribe Melissa Rossi. Latest clue: ``Small taverns in this city's
suburbs announce the arrival of `Heuriger,' the year's new wines,
by hanging a pine branch above their doors.'' But because the
magazine is edited well in advance, the readers are trying to guess
places Rossi has been. Right now, she's in Jamaica Plain (a Boston
neighborhood), bored out of her mind and awaiting her next
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   I like everyone I don't know very well, and Ms. Rossi certainly
qualifies. She's been on the lam for the past few years, mainly
avoiding Seattle, where she wrote a nightclubs column for the
Seattle Weekly under the name Babs Babylon. Things got hot for her
in Gatesville when she published a book entitled ``Courtney Love:
Queen of Noise; A Most Unauthorized Biography.'' Before the book
came out, grunge-rock goddess Love was hoping Rossi would undo the
damage of a Vanity Fair profile that accused the singer of taking
drugs during her pregnancy. That proved not to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Love is now raising her daughter in Los Angeles, and Rossi is
writing her next book, tentatively titled ``Global Party Crasher.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   News from the West
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Second mortgages coming due in Pulitzer Hollow? How else to
explain the literary fecundity in the Williamstown-Williamsburg
corridor of western Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Kidder's ``Home Town,'' about Northampton, will hit the
stands any day now. Ditto for Joe McGinniss's comeback effort,
``The Miracle of Castel Di Sangro,'' about a small-town Italian
soccer team. (The PH mafia sticks together: McGinniss's friend
Roland Merullo puffs ``Miracle'' on the Amazon.com site, without
revealing their entanglement.) John Katzenbach's just-published
``Hart's War,'' a courtroom thriller in a World War II prison camp,
is getting good reviews, as will, I suspect, ``Ladies' Man,'' the
forthcoming novel from PH diva Elinor Lipman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
