<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9463 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COACH-MAURICE-2TA     04-30 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COACH-MAURICE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL MAURICE COMES OF AGE BEHIND THE BENCH 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In his view, the glasses are strictly a concession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only wear them behind the bench, and this is the first year
I've done it,'' says Paul Maurice. ``The boss wants me to, and you
don't want to piss off the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Not when the boss sees them as a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wears the glasses behind the bench because he should,''
says Jim Rutherford. ``He can't afford to lose another eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice resisted for three years, but what's the use in arguing
with the high command? He is in fact virtually blind in one eye,
and besides, the boss is old enough to be his father. Of course,
that's not much of an achievement; most of his peers are old enough
to be his father.
</P>
<P>
   Just turned 32, the baby-faced Maurice has established seniority
as the youngest head coach in the National Hockey League. And one
thing the glasses don't do is make him look any more grizzled. ``I
wish some team would hire somebody younger,'' he sighs.
</P>
<P>
   Not much chance of that. Maurice has held the unwanted
distinction for four years, ever since Rutherford, the Carolina
Hurricanes' president-general manager and Maurice's patron since
his teens, created shock waves _ and much skepticism _ by placing
him in charge of an NHL bench. The bench was in Hartford at the
time, and Maurice, not yet 29, didn't think he had any business
telling the Whalers what to do: ``The first day on the job, I turn
the corner in the locker room, and the first player I see is Brad
McCrimmon, who started playing in the NHL when I was in seventh
grade.''
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out that the father figure knew best.
</P>
<P>
   That's been evident in the first round of the Stanley Cup
playoffs. Not only does Maurice have the Hurricanes locked in a
surprising 2-2 tie with the Bruins in their best-of-seven Eastern
Conference quarterfinal, but he has conducted himself with the
aplomb and savvy of an old hand, not a postseason novice. More than
anything, Maurice seems to be enjoying this experience to the
ultimate.
</P>
<P>
   But self-deprecation is as much his calling card as youth. He
insists that his apparently supreme comfort level is a convenient
mask _ like the one he wishes he'd been wearing when an errant puck
struck him in the right eye during a junior exhibition game,
costing him his central vision, effectively ending his playing
future, and accidentally starting him on a path toward a coaching
career at age 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly isn't a party,'' he says. ``I'm learning as
much as I can going through it. Every day isn't Christmas. My worst
time of game day is 2 or 3 o'clock. I go through every bad thing
that can happen, worry about whether I've got the right guys in the
right places. That's when my stomach is in knots.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the reason I'm enjoying this series is that a big part of
my job that other coaches have to go through is already done in the
locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   This is typical Maurice. He deflects the accolades for the
Hurricanes' robust, hard-nosed approach to his assistant coaches _
Tom Webster, his onetime junior coach; Randy Ladoceur; and Steve
Weeks. And he credits owner Peter Karmanos and Rutherford with
having brought in the type of veteran players _ seven of whom are
at least as old as their coach _ to facilitate off-ice chemistry.
Ron Francis, Gary Roberts, Kevin Dineen, Keith Primeau. People like
that. The more input they provide, the easier it is for Maurice to
recede into the background, to exert unobtrusive authority. He
hates being front and center, though his glib, ultracasual public
demeanor belies that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I told you how uncomfortable I am having a story done on
me?'' he says. ``It's the kiss of death, man. I've got two little
kids to support, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   He's smiling as he says that, but there is a germ of truth to
the sentiment. ``My job right now is to make myself small,'' says
Maurice, closing his thumb and forefinger together to indicate what
he'd like to have you believe is his tiny place in the scope of
things. ``I don't want to take the credit away from them'' _ he
gestures to the players' dressing area and the assistants' office _
``because they're the ones who deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   That diffidence may be a handy device, but it borders on the
ridiculous. The fact is that the once wretched Whalers have become
the hard-charging Hurricanes, champions of the Southeast Division,
playoff entrants for the first time in seven springs. And Maurice
hasn't been an innocent bystander.
</P>
<P>
   ``His poise, character, and leadership are special,'' says
Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The boss first noticed those traits in his role as director of
hockey operations for Compuware, the software giant Karmanos
founded at age 29 before branching out from thinkpads into junior
hockey and eventually the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rutherford who selected Maurice in the Ontario Hockey
League junior draft 15 years ago. He was a bit concerned at the
time because Maurice didn't show for the draft and Rutherford
wondered whether he had opted to play college hockey instead.
</P>
<P>
   No need to worry. The defenseman from Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario,
hadn't attended the draft because he didn't know there was a draft.
``I was playing Midget house hockey,'' says Maurice. ``I saw my
picture in the local newspaper one day, and it said I was a draft
prospect. I said, `What's this all about?' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's the type of blithe approach Maurice took to hockey,
making his lightning ascendancy even more unlikely. He wasn't
committed to the game as a career; it was a nice recreational
pursuit while he studied finance at the University of Windsor,
where he is one semester shy of graduating. ``I promised my parents
I'd get a degree,'' says Maurice, the son of career teachers and
the brother of a surgeon and a mechanical engineering student. ``I
just didn't say when.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his father, Denis, and mother, Dolores, had encouraged
him to accelerate his educational endeavors as a youngster so that
he could explore other avenues when hockey beckoned. ``I have been
blessed with wonderful parents,'' he says. ``They encouraged me to
do what I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he didn't consider hockey his calling. ``My father asked
me once at 18 if I'd considered coaching,'' recalls Maurice. ``I
don't know if he thought he saw something in me or whether he'd
seen me play and thought I sucked.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, playing was not a long-term option. The eye injury
before his first junior season with the Windsor Spitfires had
robbed him of all but his peripheral vision, meaning an NHL career
was out of the question, even though the Philadelphia Flyers made
him the last selection in the entry draft when Maurice was 18.
``No. 252,'' he says. ``They're still bragging about that. Of
course, when I did get to the NHL and looked around at the players
on the ice, I realized I never would have made it with two good
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
