<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9470 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONG-KONG-BOS &LR;      04-30 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWDED HONG KONG WORRIED BY PLAN TO ADMIT MIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Hong Kong is Earth's most crowded place, a territory
one-third the size of Rhode Island, with seven times the
population. And it may soon have to open its borders to 25 percent
more people, an influx that could put an unbearable strain on this
prosperous but jam-packed city.
</P>
<P>
   Locals were up in arms Thursday over a government announcement
that more than 1.6 million people _ nearly one-fourth of Hong
Kong's population of 6.8 million _ will be allowed to move here
from mainland China over the next 10 to 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine a place more congested than this, where
everyday life demands elbowing through packed subways and
overflowing sidewalks amid forests of towering housing projects.
The World Bank this week ranked Hong Kong the world's most densely
populated area, with 6,375 people per square kilometer _ compared
with 29 people per square kilometer in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hong Kong has always been a city of immigrants. Successive
waves of mainland refugees from the 1949 Communist Revolution,
1950s famines, and the Cultural Revolution of the 1960s and '70s
built Hong Kong from a relative outpost into a global
manufacturing, trading, and financial capital. Today it boasts one
of the highest per-capita incomes in the world _ higher than its
former colonial master, Great Britain _ and the second-largest
monetary reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's greatest challenge since it returned to Chinese rule
in 1997 may not be the threat of losing its political freedoms, but
the difficulty of maintaining its prosperity and quality of life
while accommodating a new flood of migrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I visualize a future where every inch of space is crowded with
people,'' said Fiona Szeto, 24, a public relations executive.
</P>
<P>
   But others say that the real problem is not the sheer number of
prospective arrivals, but that the government does not have a plan
for accommodating them. After all, Hong Kong was barely inhabited
when colonizers arrived in 1851; half of today's residents are
migrants from China, and the other half are descendants of earlier
immigrants. And although much of Hong Kong is park land or zoned to
forbid building, only 16 percent of it has been developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radio talk shows and certain people are making too big a deal
of this,'' said Leo Chung, 25, a financial analyst. ``A lot of us
think Hong Kong is a refugee city, built by people who sneaked
across the border. We can afford to accommodate these new people.
And it's not just an economic issue, it's a legal issue and a moral
issue. These are children of Hong Kong people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's post-colonial constitution, the Basic Law, grants
any child of a permanent resident the right to live here. A January
appeals court ruling held that even illegitimate children and
children born before their parents acquired Hong Kong residency
have that right.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a huge waiting list of prospective immigrants from
China, it is common for families to wait 20 years or longer to be
reunited. Hong Kong's Court of Final Appeal ruled three months ago
that that was unfair, and that all eligible children must be
allowed to emigrate within a ``reasonable period.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling angered local authorities and mainland officials who
fear too many migrants could ruin a city that Beijing wants to
maintain as a showcase of free enterprise and a funnel for
investments to flow into communist China.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate that more than 1.6 million are eligible migrants is
based on a government survey of 10,000 local households. The survey
estimates there are 692,000 mainland children of current Hong Kong
residents, and another 983,000 children of people who will become
residents within seven years.
</P>
<P>
   But some observers questioned the figure Thursday, noting that
it far exceeds previous estimates. After both the 1991 and 1996
census, the government said there were about 320,000 children of
Hong Kong residents living in China.
</P>
<P>
   Many social workers and liberal politicians said the government
is trying to whip up panic so that people demand that the court
overturn its ruling or that China limit residency rights. Legal
scholars warn that overturning a court ruling would violate
judicial independence, and that amending the constitution is a
slippery slope; residency rights could be cut today, political
freedoms could be curtailed tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no avoiding the fact that if the government's new
estimates are true, a crush of migrants will create tremendous
challenges. Already, 150 Chinese migrants enter Hong Kong each day,
and 44 children enter the school system. There is a six-year wait
for public housing, even with 50,000 new units being built a year,
and the government estimates the number of people on waiting lists
would triple with the new migrants.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment at 6.2 percent, the territory may not have
jobs for the expected migrants. Seventy percent of the eligible
children have been waiting so long to come here that they are now
adults, and about half of them have a high school education or
less. Fewer than 10 percent are professionals, according to Regina
Ip, the secretary for security.
</P>
<P>
   Ho Sau-lan, a legislator, said the government was
``irresponsible to present the problem without any solutions.'' Ho
said schools with a Hong Kong curriculum could be built over the
border in nearby Shenzhen; some 200,000 domestic worker jobs held
mostly by Filipino women could be phased out to make way for
Chinese maids, and housing could be built on Lantau Island, which
is five times the size of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Hong Kong offers greater freedoms and human rights
than China, she said, it will remain a magnet for mainland
immigrants. ``At the end of the day, Hong Kong is just a city; we
can't absorb all of China. The answer lies in the democratization
of the mainland. Right now we have one country with two systems. We
need one country with one good system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
