</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The U.S. economy expanded at the
surprisingly strong annual rate of 4.5 percent in the first three
months of the year, the government reported today. While a slowdown
from a torrid 6 percent pace in the fourth-quarter, the
first-quarter gross domestic product was well above what had been
predicted on Wall Street. The growth was accompanied by an uptick
in inflation measures, raising concerns that there still exists a
link between strong growth and an eventual resurgence in inflation.
By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INVEST (Tosno, Russia) _ Russia's economic turmoil last
summer confirmed American companies' worst fears about Russia: it
is too unstable to do business there. But a number of Western
multinationals _ Caterpillar, Nestle, Lucent Technologies and
others _ have since decided to go deeper into Russia rather than
pull out. Many have picked areas where the local government
supports business, regardless of broader upheaval in Russia. In St.
Petersburg and the surrounding region, for example, six American
projects are expected to bring more than $500 million of direct
foreign investment over the next 18 months. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ Russia's finance minister says the
renegotiated $4.5 billion loan agreement with the International
Monetary Fund will enable the country to more easily reschedule
billions of dollars in Soviet-era debts, and is a sign of increased
Western confidence in Russia. But he offers little assurance that
economic changes demanded by the IMF as part of its new agreement
will win parliamentary approval. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:20 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 8 points, the Nasdaq composite index up 18. In
Europe, stocks were modestly higher, while Tokyo stocks closed down
1.42 percent. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MERGER (Madrid) _ Folo on the $13.4 billion offer by Repsol,
Spain's largest oil company, to buy the remainder of Argentina's
YPF and thus create the world's eighth-largest oil company. By Al
Goodman.
</P>
