<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; SATURDAY &LR; , May 1.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
Terrell Davis, the Broncos star running back, who in the wake of
John Elway's retirement, has taken up a new sport: bowling. With
Bubby Brister and not Elway at quarterback for Denver, Davis will
likely become even more of a workhorse for the Super Bowl
championship team. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-ROYALS (Kansas City) _ N.Y. Yankees at Kansas City,
8:05 p.m. ET start. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-GIANTS (New York) _ San Francisco at the Mets, 7:10
p.m. ET start. By Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NETS-ORLANDO (Orlando, Fla.) _ N.J. Nets at Orlando, 7:30
p.m. ET start. By Chris Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ Game 5 of the
Devils-Penguins playoff series, with the teams tied at 2-2. By Joe
Lapointe.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-ISLES (Garden City N.Y.) _ The Islanders name a star from
their glory days, Butch Goring, as their latest coach. The hiring
was done by Mike Milbury, their embattled general manager, meaning
that he will stick around for another season. By Tarik El-Bashir.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-DERBY-BET (Lexington, Ky.) _ At least for two minutes on
Saturday, Dallas Keen, Akiko Gothard, Dallas Stewart, Scotty
Schulhofer and Elliott Walden, will be linked together in the 125th
running of the Kentucky Derby. Their horses _ Valhol, K One King,
Kimberlite Pipe, Lemon Drop Kid and Ecton Park _ have been lumped
together in the race's mutuel field. For horse racing aficionados
that means Churchill Downs oddsmaker Mike Battaglia determined
these five horses were the least likely to win in a crowded
20-horse field. The horses are grouped that way out of necessity _
the Churchill tote board can handle only 14 betting interests. For
casual fans, however, necessity means sort of a Sam's Club bargain
opportunity. Think of it as buying in bulk _ a $2 bet on No. 14 in
the program brings five horses for the price of one in one of the
most wide-open fields in Kentucky Derby history. By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   More Derby as needed.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ATLANTA (Atlanta) _ The organizing committee for the 1996
Atlanta Olympics will release some of the files pertaining its bid
selection process for the Summer Games. By Jere Longman.
</P>
