<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-BRITAIN-BOS &LR;      04-30 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-BRITAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN SHEDS JUNIOR PARTNER STATUS WITH US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Once mocked in UN quarters as the ``little
poodle'' of US diplomacy for its slavish obedience to US foreign
policy, Britain, it seems, is shedding its status as America's
junior partner on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   While the personal relationship between British Prime Minister
Tony Blair and President Bill Clinton remains strong, Britain has
demonstrated an increasing determination to go its own way, even if
it means clashing with its trans-Atlantic ally.
</P>
<P>
   And Washington finds itself following as often as leading, as
Britain asserts leadership in global trouble spots, from Kosovo to
Libya.
</P>
<P>
   While Blair has attracted attention for pressing Washington to
deploy ground troops, Britain has struck out on its own in other
areas. Britain paved the way for Washington's first face-to-face
talks with Libya in nearly a decade. And in recent weeks, London
has demonstrated rare independence on its Iraq policy, spearheading
an effort to dismantle the UN Special Commission, the weapons
inspection unit responsible for disarming Baghdad, and to replace
it with a new inspection team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of agreement between the US and Britain
from a strategic standpoint, but tactically the Brits are going
more and more their own way,'' said James Placke, a former US
diplomat who tracks Iraq and Libya for Cambridge Energy Research
Associates. ``Until recently, British people I talked to would
accuse Blair of being a Clinton lapdog. I haven't heard those
comments for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say that Britain is filling a vacuum left by an
administration preoccupied with the domestic political agenda and
distracted by a year of political scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the British-American relationship resembles a mature
marriage in which each partner has a unique identity and opinion.
Whatever the case, it remains clear that the vaunted ``special
relationship'' will be tested as the two allies grapple with some
of the most vexing challenges of the post-Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's activist foreign policy team has been received with
ambivalence by the Clinton administration, but its skill has
impressed many in the US foreign policy establishment. Some have
portrayed Blair as a liberal version of Margaret Thatcher, the
conservative British prime minister who urged President George Bush
not to ``go wobbly on me'' on the eve of the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   ``True leadership comes from the gut. You know what you have to
do and you do it,'' said Allan Gerson, a senior analyst at the
Council on Foreign Relations, who tracks Libya. ``I think Blair has
that; he's been operating from the gut and Clinton has been playing
catch-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerson and other observers say that London played the lead role
in laying the groundwork for Libya's handover of two suspects in
the 1988 bombing of Pan Am 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy allowed the administration to gauge public reaction
to the idea of holding a trial in the Netherlands under Scottish
law before officially embracing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a big player and the government needed us to go along
with it,'' said George Williams, the president of the Victims of
Pan AM Flight 103, an association of victims' families that
ultimately backed the trial. ``If not, they wouldn't have been able
to go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   While US officials ultimately followed Britain's lead on Libya,
they have been reluctant to endorse British maneuvering over Iraq
policy. Although Britain's warplanes continue to accompany US
fighters on bombing raids in the no-fly zones of northern and
southern Iraq, London has shown a greater desire than Washington to
reach a diplomatic solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Despite opposition from Washington, Britain and the Netherlands
introduced a proposal into the UN Security Council earlier this
month to create a new weapons inspection unit to replace a UN arms
control unit that was recently tainted by revelations that it was
used as a cover for US spying.
</P>
<P>
   The British proposal, designed to break an impasse in the
15-nation Security Council, would enable Iraq to more easily import
essential humanitarian goods and permit foreign investment in
Iraq's devastated oil infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, so far, has exhibited little interest in
compromising with Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   UN officials say that Britain's departure from US policy on Iraq
reflects a fundamental clash of interests.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the United States is seeking greater freedom to
use military force against its adversaries, Britain is seeking to
preserve a role for the Security Council, where it is one of five
countries with veto power, in overseeing international peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brits came to the conclusion long before the US that
UNSCOM will never go back into Iraq, but they wanted to keep the
ball moving,'' a senior UN official said. ``They realize that their
seat on the Security Council maintains their status in the world as
a major power.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain's assertiveness has developed quietly, but steadily,
since Blair came to power in May 1997, after a landslide victory
over the conservatives. With a strong mandate, he has exercised
influence even in the most remote parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Britain has dispatched military trainers to
rebuild a defeated national army in the former British colony of
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   But it is in the Balkans that Britain is taking its greatest
risks.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington last week, on the eve of the NATO anniversary
commemoration, Blair and Clinton held their own summit in which the
British prime minister made a case for deploying ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually accused of subservience to big cousin Bill, Blair had
this time reversed the role,'' The Observer, the London newspaper,
saidthis week. ``By the end, Blair had become the crusading hawk of
the NATO alliance, called by some in Washington last week `the
leader of NATO.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Blairite,'' said Ivo Daalder, the former chief Balkans
specialist at the US National Security Council, now at the
Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are very interested in foreign policy and they
want to do the right thing. They are making the decisions that the
United States is not willing to take,'' Daalder said.
</P>
<P>
   Daalder also recalled that NATO began its hunt for war criminals
in Bosnia shortly after Blair came into power. On July 10, British
SAS commandos made their first arrest of Bosnian war criminals. The
man apprehended was the former police chief of Prijidor, Simo
Drljaca. Then, one of the region's architects of ethnic cleansing,
Milan Kovacevic, was sent to The Hague to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the late summer of 1997, Britain decided at a Cabinet-level
meeting that the humanitarian crisis in Kosovo could be solved only
through military means. Britain urged the United States to threaten
air power and to be prepared to use ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which mirrored the thinking of the Clinton
administration's most hawkish Cabinet member, Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright, received a chilly response from the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to us and we turned them down flat on the ground
troops,'' said Daalder.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the British may have the last word. While the White House
and Pentagon continued to insist that the air war will prevail
alone, President Clinton said last week that he supported NATO's
decision to draw up contingency plans for a ground war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
