<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9489 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NRA-MEETING-BOS &LR;      04-30 1787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-MEETING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBDUED NRA SHIFTS GEARS AS GUN CONTROL CALLS GROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ To herald its annual convention here this weekend, the
National Rifle Association plastered this city with billboards of
its rifle-bearing president, actor Charlton Heston, and the almost
biblical injunction: ``Join me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a rollicking revival meeting, coming on
the heels of an expected triumph over Colorado gun-control
measures. Instead, that hoped-for victory has evaporated and the
billboards have vanished. The NRA will meet Saturday with nothing
to celebrate, unwelcome guests in a city angry about gun violence
and griefstricken by the Columbine High School massacre, just 10
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The rare defensive crouch by the normally aggressive NRA is the
clearest of many signs that momentum has shifted, for the moment at
least, in the debate on gun control. Already, several states have
sprung into action, moving to tighten access to guns or backing
away from the gun-rights' agenda. Now, the question for advocates
on both sides is whether the Columbine shootings, for all the
horror they caused, for all the questions they raised, will be
remembered as marking a seismic shift in the debate or a mere
hiccup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something different about this event, whether it was
just the scope of it, the firepower that these kids had, or the
fact that we all watched it on television,'' said Kristen Rand,
director of federal policy for the Violence Policy Center, a
gun-control organization in Washington. ``The focus on gun control
seems to be more immediate and more lasting than in previous school
shootings and other deadly gun events.''
</P>
<P>
   Also raising the volume, she said, are reports at least one of
the guns used in the murders was purchased at a gun show, where
weapon sales involving unlicensed dealers and private buyers can
occur outside regulatory safeguards, Rand said. A top priority
among gun control advocates is to use the Columbine killings as
Exhibit A in closing that loophole.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of gun-owners' rights said they expect the
anti-gun fervor to quickly fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbine is obviously an enormously beneficial short-term
tactical advantage to the gun ban groups,'' said David Kopel of the
Independence Institute, a conservative think tank in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the brevity of that advantage is underscored by the fact
that President Clinton politicized this tragedy even while funerals
are still going on,'' he added. ``The fact that he couldn't wait a
week until the children were buried indicates what a very small
window of opportunity this is.''
</P>
<P>
   Kopel said he believes it will soon dawn on Americans that, as
tragic as the shooting was, making new laws would not change a
thing. Gunmen Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold had already broken
something on the order of 20 existing laws, he said, ``and to think
they wouldn't have perpetrated the crime if they had to break one
more law is ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, though, the deaths of 12 students and one teacher,
serious injuries to a dozen other students, as well as the suicides
of Harris and Klebold, have sent a shiver of reaction through state
legislatures. Some have taken quick action on stalled gun-control
bills and others have quietly pulled back measures favored by
gun-rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   On the federal level, the Littleton shootings have refocused the
Clinton administration. The president last week offered a
milti-pronged gun reform package _ including a three-day waiting
period, a crackdown on gun shows, and a measure to place blame on
adults whose guns are used by children. However, its fate is
uncertain in the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Local governments are also lining up to join the list of cities
that have followed in the path of anti-tobacco activists by suing
gun makers and dealers for the damage caused by firearms. Detroit
this week became the seventh city to file suit, and at least a
half-dozen others, including Boston, are considering legal action
as well. Colorado Gov. Bill Owens added his voice to the chorus,
saying he would veto a bill that would have barred local entities
from suing gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Another telling indicator of the public mood is the reaction
seen by Richard Feinberg, who runs an Internet gun-dealing site
from his Norton, Mass., home. He said sales have skyrocketed,
yielding his best week in memory. Feinberg said he sold roughly 40
guns, most of them paramilitary-style weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are afraid the gun-control types are going to take
their gun rights away from them because of what happened, so
they're rushing to buy them now,'' Feinberg said. Another factor,
he said, was ongoing fear among some that the end of the millennium
could be a time of social unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are frightened of our government, I guess because our
government doesn't trust them,'' Feinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the biggest surge of gun-control sentiment has
been in Colorado, a state usually viewed as being squarely in line
with the gun-owning tradition of the West.
</P>
<P>
   First, lawmakers here withdrew a bill to eliminate most local
gun regulations, notably Denver's ban on assault weapons. The NRA
had expected that bill to be passed in time for its convention, so
manufacturers and dealers could display the hottest new forms of
firepower. Now, with the law still on the books and the fear that
any gun show would be a public relations disaster, the NRA weapons
exhibition has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Equally damaging to Second Amendment activists, the shootings
derailed an expected victory for the NRA's ``right-to-carry''
agenda, legislation that would have allowed licensed Colorado gun
owners to carry concealed weapons. The expected passage of that law
had been seen by the NRA as a chance to rebound from its
disappointment two weeks ago in Missouri, where $3.7 million in NRA
spending was not enough to convince voters to lift that state's
concealed weapons ban.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, the Colorado governor, had supported lifting the
concealed weapons ban, but the bill was pulled from consideration
after the shootings. Few here expect it to be reconsidered anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's happened over the last year or so, with all the
school shootings, not just Columbine, the American people have
grown angry,'' said Joe Sudbay, director of state legislation at
Washington-based Handgun Control Inc. ``I don't think they'll be
silent anymore, and I think they'll start demanding that
legislators respond to them and not the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   Other states have, in fact, responded to the shootings by quick
legislative action. One day after the carnage, Arizona's governor
vetoed a bill that would have prevented localities from filing gun
suits; a similar bill in Florida that had been expected to pass was
pulled off state House calendar, though it is moving ahead in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the legislature killed a bill that would have closed
the gun show loophole, but Republican Gov. George W. Bush later
said Congress should do so on a national basis.
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki moved to toughen penalties for gun
crimes, and Illinois Gov. George Ryan backed a move to require
parents to store guns with trigger locks or in locked cabinets to
prevent access by children.
</P>
<P>
   But not all states are moving in the same direction. One day
after the shootings, the Nevada Assembly voted to take away local
governments' right to sue gun makers. And, with the gun lobby
retaining deep-rooted ties to key state legislators, there is a
strong likelihood at least some of the tabled measures will be
revisited when the furor dies down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't change anything long-term,'' said Michael Yacino,
executive director of the Gun Owners Action League, based in
Northborough, Mass. ``People will realize that we need to focus our
attention on criminal behavior, and as we saw by what happened out
there in Colorado, if we were to blame just guns, then we'd also
blame propane tanks and matches and other things these killers
created.''
</P>
<P>
   On the federal level, Clinton's package includes calls for
background checks on all gun sales, including those at gun shows;
raising the legal age for handgun possession from 18 to 21 in most
cases; and holding adults responsible when children use their
firearms to cause injury or death, in cases when the adults
knowingly or recklessly allowed the child access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can pass it all if the American people want it badly
enough,'' Clinton said when announcing the package. ``And we don't
need to go through another Littleton for the American people to
want it badly enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But several Republican leaders in Congress quickly characterized
the proposals as a knee-jerk, politically motivated reaction that
would not solve the problem. They urged a focus on the media and
broader cultural issues, as well as a broad look at the causes of
teen violence.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control activists also noted pessimistically that not even
the fatal shootings of two US Capitol police officers last summer
was seen by Republican leaders as a clarion call for greater gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   NRA officials said they will have no comment about the anti-gun
surge until Saturday's meeting. In a letter to the reported 2.8
million members, Heston and another NRA leader said the group
wanted to show sympathy and respect to community. ``Our spirits
must endure this terrible suffering together, and so must the
freedoms that bring us together,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Mayor Wellington Webb had asked the NRA to cancel its
convention altogether, even offering to reimburse the group for any
losses. NRA officials declined, saying they are required to hold an
annual members' meeting by the New York state law under which the
group is organized.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to scaling back the convention from three days to
one, the NRA scrapped a planned reception for US Rep. J. C. Watts
of Oklahoma, the fourth-ranking Republican in the House and a
sometime spokesman for the NRA. Saturday's session will feature
just two scheduled speakers, Heston and NRA executive vice
president Wayne LaPierre.
</P>
<P>
   The convention had been expected to attract 22,000 NRA members
and pour $18 million in the local economy. City and tourism
officials said they had no idea how many would show up. An anti-gun
rally outside the convention promises to win nearly as much
publicity, and possibly as much support, as the NRA meeting itself.
</P>
<P>
   As for the NRA conventioneers who do find their way to Denver,
in the place of billboards with Heston, they will find public
service ads touting the American Red Cross.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
