<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COACH-MAURICE-2ND     04-30 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COACH-MAURICE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... two good eyes.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One good eye meant that junior hockey was the limit of Maurice's
playing horizons. He tried to cling to it as long as possible,
remaining with Windsor as an overage player, one of the few times
he's been senior man in the locker room. But midway through his
fourth season, the Spitfires were forced to make a personnel
decision because of junior limits on overage players. Maurice was
the casualty. ``Jim and Tom Webster cut me off at the knees,''
Maurice says with a laugh. ``There's no other way to put it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shield of humor he often employs, Maurice was deeply
wounded at the time because he desperately wanted a shot at the
Memorial Cup, emblematic of junior hockey supremacy, and the
Spitfires were a top contender. They gave him a couple of options _
they could work a trade with Oshawa, where he could end his playing
career, or he could stay with Windsor as a 21-year-old assistant to
Webster. He chose the latter, but again, there was no grand design
to his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be a fun way to stay in hockey and make a
little money while I was at university,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford saw more to it than that. ``Paul had been our captain
since his second year,'' he recalls. ``As I got to know him as a
person and player, I felt he was someone I wanted to bring into our
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the long haul. Maurice considers his two major achievements
``being born to the parents I have and being taken in by Compuware
as if I were family.''
</P>
<P>
   Taken in and moved up. In a hurry. Compuware acquired an OHL
expansion team, the Detroit Junior Red Wings, in 1988, and five
years later, at age 26, Maurice became head coach. In his second
season, he took the Wings to the Memorial Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got blindsided. By now, Rutherford was running the
misbegotten Whalers for Karmanos, and he handed an assistant's job
to Maurice. Who went kicking and screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a junior head coach at 26,'' he says. ``I was in no
hurry to be an NHL assistant. When he asked me, I thought, `Wow,
what a huge step that would be.' I didn't think I had a lot to
offer Paul Holmgren (Hartford's head coach). Then I thought about
it a little more and I figured I'd have time to develop, that I
wouldn't be expected to make a huge impact.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case for long. Twelve games into the 1995
season, Holmgren was cashiered despite a 5-6-1 record _ lofty by
Whaler standards _ and Rutherford again turned to Maurice. Who
again needed a great deal of persuading.
</P>
<P>
   On the night Holmgren was fired, Rutherford sat down at his
kitchen table with Maurice into the wee hours. ``He said he wanted
to be an NHL coach someday but that he wasn't sure that was the
time,'' recalls Rutherford. ``He was in no rush to be a head coach.
He listened to me and finally said, `If that's what you want.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford had emphasized to Maurice that NHL head jobs aren't
everyday items, that he could turn down the offer at 28 and still
be waiting for another at 58. But that wasn't the deciding
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being drafted by Compuware had been a huge factor in my
life,'' says Maurice. ``When people treat you that well . . .
Taking the job was a matter of common sense. I thought they had a
master plan for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The clincher came the next morning in the parking garage beneath
the Hartford offices when the arriving Maurice encountered the
departing Holmgren. ``He'd heard I didn't want to take the job,''
says Maurice. ``He told me, `You'd be crazy not to.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Maurice wondered whether he'd been crazy not to say
no. ``I was trying to figure out which door to walk into in each
building that first year,'' he says. ``They'd ask me, `What time do
you want the plane to leave?' I'd say, `How the (expletive) should
I know?' I was just happy to be on the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that was the larger issue of how the boy boss would be
regarded by players he'd watched as a kid. ``I thought about how
people would take him because of his age,'' says Rutherford. ``It
was something we had to watch for.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice, too, was wary. ``I'm sure they were saying, `Who's this
kid?' '' he says. ``I know that's what I would've been saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Those misgivings turned out to be more anxiety than reality,
according to Maurice, and Rutherford concurs. ``When we did our
end-of-the-year reviews and sat down with each player
individually,'' he says, ``every one of them felt Paul should be
the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment wasn't always widespread. Maurice, who is in the
final year of a contract that pays him $300,000 this season, had to
develop a deaf ear and a thick skin during the first three years on
the job, when the Whalers/Hurricanes just missed the playoffs each
time. ``After three years of must-win games, of seeing myself fired
so many times in print,'' says Maurice, ``I've grown immune to it.
I don't worry about that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was enduring calls for his youthful head, Maurice had
to deal with the major disruption caused by Karmanos's acrimonious
departure from Hartford for a region where the customer base can't
necessarily tell a hockey puck from a chaw of tobacco. For good
measure, the Hurricanes have been forced to become transients in
their own home, playing in Greensboro and practicing 75 miles away
in Raleigh, where their new arena is being completed. ``It took us
a year and a half just to develop a game-day routine,'' says
Maurice.
</P>
<P>
   But he considers that upheaval almost his salvation. ``The fact
of the matter is, if we'd stayed in Hartford, I wouldn't have
survived,'' he says. ``I don't think you can miss the playoffs
three years in a row in the same city and survive. The media won't
let you.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no risk of that now. As much as he might want to
downplay his role, Maurice has overseen the development of a team
of grit and promise. Even he grudgingly acknowledges, ``I think
I've done a little better job each year.''
</P>
<P>
   After an extended baptism under fire, he's got about everything
he could want. Though he probably wouldn't mind a few gray hairs.
To enhance the look with the glasses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
