<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9497 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-ARTIST-ART-2ND     04-30 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-ARTIST-ART-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 QUINCY, Mass.: ... computer software.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Around that time, she hooked up with a few artists who had
founded the Electronic Civil Disturbance Theatre. That connection
led to notoriety: Her prophecy about being recognized came true,
but the public attention came first for her political activity
rather than her art endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the group call themselves ``hacktivists,'' people
who engage in political activism in cyberspace. Using a program
called Floodnet (written by Karasic), the group staged 10 on-line
``sit-ins'' last year to support the efforts of the Zapatistas in
Mexico. Floodnet enables a user to repeatedly request access to a
targeted Web site, such as sites run by the Pentagon and the
Mexican government, bogging down the server and potentially denying
access to other users.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karasic views the Floodnet attacks as a kind of performance art
similar to demonstrations in ``flesh space.'' ``If we had a civil
disturbance at Neponset Circle, you wouldn't be able to get to my
house,'' she explains. ``But you wouldn't think that those people
should be arrested. A sit-in means that someone is going to be
inconvenienced. We're trying to push the limits of political
interaction on line.''
</P>
<P>
   But others question that logic. An FBI representative says that
the use of Floodnet could be a federal crime, since it is illegal
to intentionally block access to an Internet server.
</P>
<P>
   The Floodnet project is over for now _ and Karasic seems a bit
relieved. ``Hacktivism got all the attention, and we, as
individuals, got lost,'' she says, noting that her son worried that
law enforcement officials might drive up and arrest her. ``The
artwork got lost, dimmed by all the media attention.''
</P>
<P>
   But now the art is center stage. Karasic is director of the
on-line gallery for the cyber arts festival, a wide-ranging event
at venues all over the region for the next two weeks. Her work will
be featured in two group shows at the festival, one at the
Bromfield Gallery and the other at the Attleboro Museum. The
Attleboro piece is based on Samuel Beckett's ``The Lost Ones,'' a
tale about 200 people who march around and around in a cylinder,
trapped for eternity. Beckett's characters repeat a single refrain:
``For the passion to search is such that no place may be left
unsearched.'' The installation will have an audio component of
overlapping voices repeating those words in different languages,
including the computer speaking Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, all of Karasic's art has been created to be
exhibited solely in cyberspace, in e-zines and on-line galleries.
``The Lost Ones'' marks a breakthrough. ``It's the first piece I've
done in flesh space,'' she says. ``It's different from Internet
performance art. People can walk up to it; it's tactile. You don't
have to be in cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   The materials for the project are all over Karasic's house. In
the living room, she is constructing a giant cylinder out of wire
mesh fencing. She is building 200 miniature figures that will line
the periphery of the cylinder; they're made out of decidedly
low-tech material. ``It's Crayola modeling clay,'' she says. At the
center of the cylinder, viewers will see a computer that depicts
the same scene using a virtual reality program.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can identify with it without any knowledge of
computers,'' Karasic says. ``It's a cylinder. It's so primitive.
People are comfortable with it. It's almost like a temple in a way.
I'm not trying to say it's a religious experience, but I think it
talks to people in a way that is subconscious but also physical.
When you're working in cyberspace, you're talking about technical
stuff. If people have baggage about the computer, it can be a
negative experience. This is different.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And digital art _ cool as it is _ can be somewhat alienating to
the uninitiated. ``I hate to say it, but in a way, it's elitist.
First of all, you have to have this,'' Karasic says, fingering her
keyboard. ``You can't go the library and say, `I want to be part of
an Internet performance that's going to take place at midnight in
New York.' And you also have to understand enough to know how to
use the technology. And on top of that, it's kind of weird and
offbeat. People don't understand what's going on, and most people
go, `What are they talking about?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Cyberarts Festival is aiming to bring the esoteric into the
mainstream. And that's a good thing, says Karasic, who is on the
festival steering committee. Her son is more enthusiastic about her
cyber career now that she's being recognized as an artist rather
than a hacktivist. ``I'm a typical suburban mom out here in
Quincy,'' she says, laughing. ``My son says that his friends look
at my blue hair and my weird clothes and he just says, `Oh, my mom
is an artist.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The weird clothes _ mostly black on black, clunky boots, a bit
of leather _ came with the career switch. ``I couldn't have blue
hair at Fidelity,'' she says. But she wears her new identity
naturally, proving her own maxim that people have more than one
persona.
</P>
<P>
   All the attention, however, is daunting. ``It's freaking me
out,'' she says. ``Someone warned me that it can be bad if it moves
too fast, but what can you do?'' After all, it wasn't that long ago
that Karasic was walking the corporate walk. The art world is not
exactly the most inviting place for newcomers, but in a short time,
she completely rewrote her professional story. How did it happen?
Karasic mulls it over, then comes up empty, her face displaying a
look of wordless wonder.
</P>
<P>
   But a few days later, she zaps off an e-mail, using her favorite
medium to communicate a response she couldn't come up with in flesh
space. ``It is such a new frontier, that there are no rules,
traditions, standards, or gatekeepers,'' the e-mail says. ``So I
have become something of an authority, simply by combining my tech
skilz, living in cyberspace, and linking with artists who have
established themselves in cyberspace. Oh, and the New York City
digerati tend to like me _ that helps a lot . . .'' Another happy
moment, that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Boston Cyberarts Festival web address is
http://www.bostoncyberarts.org.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
