<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9498 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-ANGELS-BOS &LR;      04-30 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ANGELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT LIVES CAUGHT IN THE CARNAGE OF BATAAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WE BANDS OF ANGELS 
The Untold Story of American Nurses Trapped on Bataan by the
Japanese 
By Elizabeth M. Norman 
Random House, 327 pp., illustrated, $26.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As images of desperate Albanian refugees and NATO bombs sear the
senses, readers of ``We Band of Angels: The Untold Story of
American Nurses Trapped on Bataan by the Japanese'' cannot help
being struck by an eerie feeling of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 years ago, war generated the same horrific tales of
lives mangled and torn apart, and in writing about nurses trapped
in the Philippines during World War II, Elizabeth Norman captures
its gritty, surreal texture with as much eloquence as the best
writers on the Balkan front lines. And Norman, having spent eight
years interviewing nurses who were still alive in the 1980s, gives
us an even richer, more nuanced picture of war than today's hurried
correspondents can.
</P>
<P>
   A registered nurse herself, and a historian of nursing, Norman
tells the story of Bataan with authority, compassion, and an
unusually clearsighted view of the American military. She hooks
readers from the start by beginning her tale in the fall of 1941,
when war seemed a distant rumor for the military personnel
stationed in the Philippines. Life there was halcyon, Norman
writes, ``with Filipino houseboys, maids, chefs, gardeners and
tailors looking after every need . . . cocktails and bridge at
sunset, white jackets and long gowns at dinner, good gin and
Gershwin under the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Dec. 7, the Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor, and hours
later, the bombs began to fall on American military bases in the
Philippines. Until then, very few of the 99 Army and Navy nurses
had seen combat duty and they ``found themselves almost overwhelmed
by the slaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman is adept at sketching the nurses caught in the carnage:
Helen ``Cassie'' Cassiani, a farm girl from Bridgewater, Mass.,
whose Italian parents immigrated to the United States around the
turn of the century; Ruth Marie Straub, a quiet Jewish woman from
Milwaukee whose diary entries provide the most compelling snapshots
of the horror and deprivation these women were to go through; and
Red Harrington, a spirited woman who had been abandoned as an
infant and raised by a farming couple in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   She weaves the life histories of these and other women into her
larger tapestry, creating an often gripping narrative. Ruth Straub,
for instance, is one of the first nurses to suffer a tragic loss;
on the troop transport over to Manila she had met an Army pilot who
wanted to get married in the Philippines. She convinced him to wait
until the war was all over, but he was one of the early casualties
of the Japanese bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Straub, however, doesn't find out about his death until days
later, and she is devastated by the news: ``It doesn't seem to be
true. They took me back (to the hospital) as a patient. Luminal
(the sedative phenobarbital) every four hours. Why, why, why. . . .
Others have carried on bravely, and I must too. Glen would want
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Straub does carry on, and she is among the 51 Army and Navy
nurses who are trucked into the densely wooded peninsula of Bataan,
on the southwest coast of Luzon Island, to help care for the
retreating American force. Norman creates a vivid picture of the
Bataan jungle and the primitive open-air conditions doctors and
nurses labored under as they cared for the growing number of
wounded soldiers, in the face of constant bombardment by the
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some wards looked like tropical greenhouses, with beds set
between trees and under palm fronds, a tangle of vines hanging
close overhead. . . . At nights, (the nurses) worked under blackout
conditions, using flashlights or kerosene lamps painted blue. . . .
Wild pigs would brush against their legs, and geckos, those small
lizards with suction-cup feet, came diving out of the trees. One
night a nurse hiking between beds was smacked in the forehead by a
snake swinging from a branch.''
</P>
<P>
   For these nurses, the worst tragedy was being forced to abandon
hundreds of wounded soldiers on Bataan while they, solely because
they were women, were evacuated across the bay to the volcanic
island of Corregidor, where an underground maze of tunnels had been
built into the rock. They later learned that at least a third of
the men left on Bataan died during the infamous Bataan death march
to Japanese prisoner-of-war camps.
</P>
<P>
   Life for the surviving nurses, of course, was no picnic, either
on Corregidor or back in Manila, where most of them eventually
ended up after being captured by the Japanese. Many of them
suffered the effects of severe malnutrition, and had to watch as
men, women, and children around them starved to death from
inadequate rations as the war drew to a close.
</P>
<P>
   My only complaint with ``We Band of Angels'' is that Norman
doesn't know how to end her story. Instead of stopping at the end
of the war, with the nurses getting a heroines' welcome back in the
States and then promptly being forgotten, she insists on
chronicling their lives up to the present, in dry, almost
footnotelike prose. For some reason, Norman is not able to capture
the drama of ordinary life with the same vivid brushstrokes she
uses in describing war. As a result, the story of one of World War
II's most dramatic but little-known chapters finishes with a
disappointing fizzle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
