<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ENTRAPMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE MIX OF LOVE, LARCENY IN GLOSSY `ENTRAPMENT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ENTRAPMENT 
Directed by: Jon Amiel 
Screenplay by: Ron Bass, William Broyles 
Starring: Sean Connery, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Ving Rhames, Will
Patton, Maury Chaykin 
Running time: 112 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some language, sensuality, violence and drug
content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Entrapment'' is a silly millennial heist movie that gets by on
its high gloss and the star power of Sean Connery and Catherine
Zeta-Jones. Her sexy turn opposite Antonio Banderas in ``The Mask
of Zorro'' has certainly earned her a shot as an art thief who
agrees with Connery's veteran lone wolf and wary partner in crime
that the only way they can work together is to have no personal
involvement. After they tune up by removing a valuable Chinese mask
from a castle, they get really serious about stealing $8 billion
from a bank in Malaysia during a window of opportunity provided by
a Y2K computer security check.
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledge their age difference in what, considering the
circumstances, is pretty droll style as Connery glumly recalls
reveling in money when it was something you walked away with, not
something you downloaded. You've got to love Connery. No facelifts,
no hairpieces, no lying about his age (he's 68) except in the film,
when he endearingly tells Zeta-Jones his character is 60. Like it
would make a difference. Like his lordly and luxury-loving
character isn't going to wind up falling for this woman who brags
of her seductive capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Connery in the '90s is something like Cary Grant in the '60s, a
little creaky, but still dripping with style. He's still more than
game as he chases swag and the glamorous woman he tries to persuade
himself he swore off. Unlike Grant, he also projects warmth and
ruggedness, so what's not to like? As for Zeta-Jones, Connery knows
what he thinks audiences will like. As one of the film's producers,
and the one calling the shots, he photographs at length her pretty,
leotard-clad butt twisting its way through a cat's-cradle of laser
beam alarms not once, but twice, once in rehearsal at his baronial
castle, and again for real.
</P>
<P>
   They may spend the film telling themselves it's not about love,
but about larceny. But of course it's about both. It's also about
our relying on Connery to have enough taste and discretion to
handle the inevitable sex in a dignified yet plausible way. It's a
thing he does lately by allowing his vulnerability to the aging
process to show. In contrast to Zeta-Jones's radiant physical
confidence, he allows the incursions of time to show in little
telltale ways, like the occasional shortage of breath or shortfall
of panache when they're dangling from a steel support beam hundreds
of feet above the street.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the film's strokes are provided by others _ Will
Patton's off-center FBI man, Ving Rhames' even more off-center
gadget supplier, Maury Chaykin's over-the-top decadent fence. But
in the end, ``Entrapment'' is about the savvy packaging of sexual
allure and Connery's canny way of looking sadder but wiser while
acknowledging with rueful little grunts and glances the hold it
still has on him. ``Entrapment'' is a throwback to Hollywood's
glory days, not so much in its glamorous thief routines, as in the
kind of information so authoritativiely conveyed by an big aging
star persona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9503 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-IDLE-BOS &LR;      04-30 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-IDLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THUMBS-DOWN TO SLACKER HORROR SPOOF `IDLE HANDS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
IDLE HANDS 
Directed by: Rodman Flender 
Screenplay by: Terri Hughes, Ron Milbauer 
Starring: Devon Sawa, Seth Green, Elden Henson, Jessica Alba, Fred
Willard, Connie Ray, Viveca A. Fox, Jack Noseworthy 
Running time: 90 minutes 
Rated: R (horror violence and gore, pervasive teen drug use,
language and sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Roger Corman drudge Rodman Flender and his young lead,
Devon Sawa, bring all the energy and twice the gore they need to
``Idle Hands,'' their would-be horror goof, but only about half the
material. The result is an anemic take on slacker obliviousness. It
at least gets off to a comically outrageous start as Sawa's stoned
dropout, Anton, doesn't even notice that his parents have been
slaughtered in Halloween-themed style. Or that he's the one who did
it. Well, not him exactly. The film is based on the premise that
Anton's left hand doesn't know what his right hand is doing until
it does too much.
</P>
<P>
   Demonic possession is the reason Anton's right hand has been
doing wrong. After he realizes what it has been up to, he spends a
lot of time trying to grab it with his left hand as it takes on a
lethal life of its own. Up it pops, Dr. Strangelove-style, as Anton
looks horrified and tries to head it off. At one point, he grabs a
cleaver and chops it off. But that scarcely slows the hand down. It
murders Anton's goof-off buddies, Seth Green's Mick and Elden
Henson's Pnub, and then goes after his girlfriend, Molly, played by
Jessica Alba. The buddies rise from the dead and slide into the
couch potato mode in front of Anton's TV. Why this option is not
extended to the dead parents is not made clear.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pnub holds his severed head in his lap, it, too, takes
on a life of its own, the most amusing in the film, which mostly
relies for comic effect on moments such as a cat gnawing on a
eyeball. By the time druid priestess Viveca A. Fox hits town in
search of the hand, it already has taken off to do some damage at
the big school dance, and does. But by this time a pall of
diminshing returns has settled over ``Idle Hands.'' Flender and
Sawa try to cover for it by overstating their limp material. This
does nothing but expose its nothingness all the more glaringly. If
the hand had any sense, it would have pulled the plug on this one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
