</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOAH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOAH' TAKES THE WRONG COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
NOAH'S ARK 
Starring: John Voight, Mary Steenburgen, F. Murray Abraham, James
Coburn, Carol Kane, Alexis Denisof, Mark Bazeley, Jonathan Cake,
Emily Mortimer, Sydney Poitier, Sonya Walger 
Directed by: John Irvin 
On: NBC 
Time: Sunday and Monday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the start of NBC's ``Noah's Ark,'' we're warned that the
biblical story has been altered ``for poetic effect.'' But that
would be wishful thinking on the part of the filmmakers, including
producer Robert Halmi Sr., the demigod of TV event movies, because
there is nothing in this stubbornly prosaic creation that's even
nearly poetic. Like those folks we call ``people pleasers,''
``Noah's Ark'' is the kind of bland product that so desperately
wants to be liked that it ends up as a sanded-down thing, stripped
of any outstanding qualities. It steers clear of the intensities of
religious parable and philosophy, opting instead for godawful comic
shtick and trite romantic antics. Typical of this trivialized
telling of the great flood is F. Murray Abraham's Lot, a joker who
Rodney Dangerfields on about his nagging wife: ``I usually take her
everywhere with me because it's easier than having to kiss her
goodbye.'' Thud.
</P>
<P>
   How to characterize ``Noah's Ark''? Picture in your mind a
Disney animated feature from a classic, in the manner of
``Alladin.'' Then imagine a live-action remake of that cartoon, and
you've got the flippant and twice-removed tone of ``Noah's Ark,''
which airs Sunday and Monday at 9 p.m. Because it has an epic theme
and one of those international casts that help in the European
marketing, NBC is hawking the two-parter as this season's
``Merlin'' or ``Gulliver's Travels,'' two successful Halmi
projects. But ``Noah's Ark'' doesn't come close to those movies,
either as TV-sized history or visual accomplishment. As it turns
the end of the world into a whimper, it even fails to exploit the
potential for eye-popping stylizations in the animals who arrive to
be saved. As they march two by two onto the wooden vessel, the
elephants and monkeys and mice are characterless beings who remain
mostly invisible during the voyage to salvation. There's no ``Dr.
Dolittle'' playfulness, and only a dash of National Geographic-like
awe. Other effects opportunities are also botched, including an ark
that's as impressive as a giant log and a sea of volcanic lava that
evokes electrified tomato soup.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Voight is the man of the four hours, a sullen Noah with long
gold-gray locks. He's the least annoying presence in the cast,
although he is required to veer awkwardly from mensch to
self-righteous whiner, and in one scene he does a cute Tevye-like
dance that may send you searching for your Dramamine. In the
movie's silly interpretation of the Bible, Voight's Noah has chats
with the displeased Lord about the decadent people of Sodom and
Gomorrah, who have orgies of sex and liquor. The big guy is given
voice by Voight himself, with ``Do not arouse the wrath of the
great and powerful Oz'' intonations and frivolous comments like ``I
would like a second opinion but who could I ask?'' God tells Noah
about the forthcoming apocalypse, and soon Noah and his family, as
well as Lot and his wife, are fleeing the doomed Sodom with orders
not to look back. Lot's wife is played as a shrew by Carol Kane,
and when she turns into a pillar of salt, and Lot breaks off a
finger, you may find yourself thinking about potato chips. Kane is
supposed to be humorously primitive, but she's only grating. She's
one of the three cameo actors _ along with Abraham and James Coburn
_ who fail to charm in their scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Steenburgen is an odd choice for Namaah, Noah's wife. It's
not just that she can't shake the 20th-century affect, since this
adaptation aims for a contemporary feel. She's just too anxious to
be an Earth Mother, too fiesty to be the docile little woman, too
intelligent to be bonking people over the head with frying pans in
moments of tired slapstick. The timing of her delivery is off,
particularly in part one, and when she goes mad during the ark's
``Waterworld''-ish voyage in part two, you may wonder if she's
joking. The three dashing British actors who play Noah and Namaah's
sons are also out of place. These fellows belong in tights in
Sherwood Forest, and not in a story about the failings of mankind.
Their love games with the three young women on the boat are
tedious, as they try to steal kisses behind the watchful eye of
Noah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noah's Ark'' might have been more fun if it's mistakes had
been even bigger, if garish casting errors had been made and
irreverent jokes had been lobbed. Too bad no one put Mel Brooks at
the helm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
