   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MORAL-HAZARD (Undated) _ About two years ago, Matt Hazard and
three of his buddies got together to form a new, hard rock band in
Minneapolis. At a loss for what to call themselves, they settled on
Moral Hazard. It's an apt name because, simply put, moral hazard
describes any situation, though usually used to describe a
financial one, in which risky behavior is encouraged because risk
takers believe they will be bailed out of mistakes by a third
party. Think Asia and Russia here. But morally hazardous situations
may also crop up outside of the narrow confines of the financial
world. Take pitchers and designated hitters in major league
baseball, for instance. By Timothy L. O'Brien. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   PATTERSON-RACE (Cambridge, Mass.) _ A profile of Orlando
Patterson, a professor of sociology at Harvard who is one of the
most provocative thinkers on the status of blacks today. By Steven
A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Edward Rothstein looks at ``New
World Symphonies: How American Culture Changed European Music'' By
Jack Sullivan. (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   COMICS-THREAT (Undated) _ Amid the nation's focus on violence
and video games, a look back at a time when when comic books were
said to be ruining America's youth. By Sarah Boxer. (900 words)
</P>
