<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9537 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-30 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING TALENT IS BOTTOM LINE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago, companies became more defensive about losing
their star employees to competitors and began offering them bonuses
if they'd just stay.
</P>
<P>
   Energy companies, desperate to keep their sought-after
geologists and geophysicists, were forking over as much as $50,000
if the technical wizards would only sign a two- or three-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, retention bonuses have become more commonplace _ and
more sophisticated. Sought-after job applicants, who automatically
ask if the job comes with a signing bonus, are now inquiring if the
job comes with a retention bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The ``pay to stay'' bonuses also are popping up when two
companies merge. The buyer, eager to ensure the transition will go
smoothly, often will give choice employees a bonus if they agree to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Savitsky, senior consultant in strategic rewards for
Watson Wyatt Worldwide in Dallas, said she has seen staying bonuses
as high as 50 percent of salary but they are more typically 10 to
20 percent of base pay.
</P>
<P>
   When a company is sold, employees naturally focus on finding
another job, she said. A stay bonus helps to counterbalance that
tendency.
</P>
<P>
   Stay bonuses also have become a condition of employment that can
resemble indentured servitude, however well-paid.
</P>
<P>
   One large Houston employer saw several of its key executives
quit to go to work for competitors, so the company ``offered'' its
senior executives a three-year contract with an iron-clad
noncompete agreement, said Stephen Newton, managing director of
Russell Reynolds Associates, an executive recruiting firm in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A year before it's set to expire, an executive is asked to sign
another. If an executive refuses, it shows his hand that he plans
to leave the fold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PAYING FOR COMPLETION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A number of companies also are offering stay bonuses to
employees who can complete a critical project _ often
computer-related _ by a particular deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Savitsky said she is working with a West Coast company that was
struggling with keeping motivated software developers long enough
to work out the bugs in their computer programs.
</P>
<P>
   The company offered the software developers between $20,000 and
$30,000 each if they completed the project in four months. So they
locked themselves in a room and they got the job done, Savitsky
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a company pays a stay bonus based on the culture it
promotes, and for the high-tech industry, that's a culture of fun.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the spirit, one software company sent its three
top developers, who worked around the clock debugging a major
project, to Tahiti for two weeks, Savitsky said. They didn't go
together, however. They were sick of each other. But the bonus did
keep them on the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the stay bonuses can backfire if other employees get
jealous. In the high-tech industry, it's part of the culture for
people to talk about the perks they get.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's important to communicate what kind of skill the members
brought to the table and what they earned for the organization,
Savitsky said. It helped that the CEO who gave out the cash bonuses
for completing the project on time also gave everyone an extra day
off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SMALL CHANGE DOESN'T RATE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Schaeffer, vice president of human resources for Apache
Corp. in Houston, said stay bonuses that focus on the completion of
a specific task work the best if the project has a beginning and an
end and is outside an employee's regular job responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The money also has to be sizable enough to retain a key employee
_ it takes about $5,000 to have much of an impact, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Metamor Worldwide, the information technology consulting firm,
doesn't put much stock in retention bonuses. It pays them to the
employees of the firms it buys because it wants to retain that
intellectual capital _ but as a regular part of the business, it
says they're not that important.
</P>
<P>
   While compensation is important, it's more important for
employees to work on challenging projects, get plenty of training,
work with good managers and work with the latest technology in a
fun environment.
</P>
<P>
   Metamor, for example, has Foosball tables in the offices, said
Ken Johnsen, president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude is what has kept turnover down to 15 percent a
year when the industry average is more like 25 percent, he said,
noting that Metamor employees are not mercenaries going from job to
job in search of higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
