<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY ECONOMY CREDITED FOR CALIFORNIA TAX WINDFALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Higher salaries, bonuses and huge stock
market earnings for some Californians will pump an extra $3 billion
in taxes into the state treasury, prompting lawmakers to salivate
over how to spend the windfall.
</P>
<P>
   California received $53 million in checks from taxpayers on
Thursday alone. So much money is flowing into the coffers that
budget writers already have counted an unexpected $1.6 billion for
the month of April, the main tax-paying month. An extra $300
million came in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``They assumed there would an economic slowdown,'' said Sandy
Harrison, spokesman for the Department of Finance, ``and in this
case, exactly the opposite happened. The economy continued to
expand.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid this news, the state Senate approved Thursday the first
draft of the $78.8 billion budget for 1999-2000 _ a record in size
and timing. It has been 13 years since the Legislature sent the
governor a budget by the June 15 deadline, and Gov. Gray Davis has
been leaning on lawmakers to hurry the process.
</P>
<P>
   The document faces significant revisions in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   The budget story has been the same for the past few years, with
lawmakers being surprised each spring with huge windfalls.
</P>
<P>
   The first major tax influx after the early 1990s recession was
spent by Davis' predecessor, Pete Wilson, and the Legislature on
reducing the number of students in elementary school classes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Legislature cut car registration fees last year,
some Republican lawmakers are looking at $1.7 billion in additional
tax cuts, lower college fees, sending money back to local
governments and shifting a major portion of the gasoline tax toward
fixing roads.
</P>
<P>
   The budget is one of the only places where Republicans have
leverage in the Legislature because it takes a two-thirds vote to
approve the document. Democrats have a majority in both houses, but
not enough votes to pass the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly and Senate Democrats and Davis are urging caution when
it comes to drastic tax cuts, however. The governor, a Democrat,
has already said that his Republican predecessor and the previous
Legislature spent too much money.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bustamante, a spokesman for Davis, said increasing the
amount of money in reserve, more dollars for education and a pay
raise for state employees are the administration's priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a guy who is going to be far more prudent
in the way he spends taxpayer dollars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While some lawmakers think the estimated $3 billion windfall is
inflated, they contend most of the money may already be eaten up
because Davis' first budget draft in January vastly underestimated
some expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature found out, for example, that California schools
enrolled 60,000 more students than expected, which will cost the
state an extra $277 million.
</P>
<P>
   Others want to boost funding for Medi-Cal and other health
insurance programs for poor families.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President pro tem John Burton, D-San Francisco, told
lawmakers Thursday that it was ``better to invest in infrastructure
than a piddling tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting to see when the dust clears how much of that
money is spoken for,'' said Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San
Francisco, chairwoman of the Appropriations Committee, ``and I
certainly want to squash discussions of an additional tax break.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican senators released a plan Thursday that would,
among other things, spend $500 million to again cut
car-registration fees. Car taxes were cut 25 percent this year, but
the next reduction, of 12.5 percent, isn't projected to happen
until 2001. The GOP wants the cut now.
</P>
</TEXT>
