<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTEBOOK DESIGNERS DECIDING SMALLER IS BETTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Notebook computers have long been trying to attain the power and
capabilities of desktop systems. Only recently, though, have
portables finally been muscular enough to be considered as desktop
replacements.
</P>
<P>
   And in an interesting development, notebook design is beginning
to have a greater effect on desktops. Since space is at a premium
in many homes and workplaces, a smaller desktop system has appeal
for many people.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at a desktop system that closely resembles a
portable PC, and an excellent portable that could easily replace
many home desktops.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sony Vaio Slimtop, $3,000, Sony Electronics. In the summer of
1996, Compaq Computer Corp. introduced a startling new design that
featured a 12-inch flat-panel screen attached to an undersized PC
case. It included some impressive features _ including a multidisk
CD changer and a wireless mouse _ and an equally impressive price
tag. With its 166-megahertz Pentium chip and 16 megabytes of
memory, it sold for a hefty $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its groundbreaking design, it was way overpriced and
didn't take off. The model was discontinued the next year, and of
course became a hot seller after Compaq lowered the price in a
clear-'em-out sale.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the Presario 3000 lives on in the Sony Vaio
Slimtop, a desktop system that borrows heavily from notebook
computer design. Unfortunately, like the Compaq model, this one
also costs too much. But it's cool, nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   The case for the Slimtop looks like a closed, full-sized
notebook computer. You can either stand it on its side, or lay it
flat on a desk. The system comes with a separate 14.1-inch
active-matrix display, with small speakers mounted on each side.
</P>
<P>
   The design is full of intriguing touches. For example, the
keyboard's wrist rest turns into a keyboard cover.
</P>
<P>
   I tried the PCV-L600, which comes with a 500-megahertz Pentium
III chip, 128 megabytes of memory, a 10.8-gigabyte hard drive, a
24X CD-ROM drive and an ATI Technologies Rage Pro video card with
four megabytes of video memory.
</P>
<P>
   It also uses Sony's new Memory Sticks, which are small plastic
sticks that contain extra memory. Slide one into a slot near the
floppy drive, and you can use it for storing small files.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the case's small size, the Slimtop is expandable. It has
a PC-card slot, for the credit-card-sized devices usually
associated with notebook computers, and an internal PCI slot.
</P>
<P>
   The Slimtop was not the fastest Pentium III system I've used. In
fact, it underperformed most 450-megahertz Pentium II systems.
</P>
<P>
   The display is probably the most impressive aspect of this
computer. It was bright, sharp and comfortable to look at for long
periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   This would be an excellent system for someone with a lot of
money and not much desk space. But given that you can get a more
muscular desktop system for two-thirds the price, the design's
``wow'' factor just doesn't cut it. A better deal may be the
PCV-L400, which comes with a 400-megahertz Pentium II chip, a
smaller hard drive and 64 megabytes of memory, for $2,300.
</P>
<P>
   _ Presario 1900, $2,800, Compaq Computer Corp. You almost didn't
get a chance to buy the Presario 1900 notebook computer. It
originally was under development by Digital Equipment Corp.'s
notebook team, and when Compaq acquired Digital, the group that
makes Compaq's business portable line, the Armada, wasn't
interested in it.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the consumer group knew a good thing when it saw it
and staked a claim. That's good, because this is the best notebook
Compaq currently offers, in either its business or consumer lines.
</P>
<P>
   The 1900 is sold via Compaq's Web site, as a configure-to-order
system. I tried a model with a 333-megahertz Pentium II chip, 64
megabytes of memory, a four-gigabyte hard drive, a 13.3-inch
active-matrix display, a 2X DVD-ROM drive, a built-in 56K fax
modem, a NeoMagic 256-bit graphics card with only 2.5 megabytes of
video memory, the usual complement of ports and slots and a
portable version of Compaq's Internet keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The 1900's case is rugged and very versatile. The solid case
feels like it could take a beating. The DVD and floppy drives are
in a wedge that snaps onto the bottom of the computer. Remove them,
and it goes from being a full-function multimedia system to a thin,
light road warrior's machine that's about five pounds and just 1.2
inches thick.
</P>
<P>
   The full-sized keyboard has an excellent feel to it and is well
laid out. The responsive touchpad includes a rocker button that
lets you scroll vertically in most programs, an excellent feature
for browsing through deep Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   This is a speedy computer _ it handled everything I threw at it.
The display was bright and easy to see, even in low-power mode.
</P>
<P>
   I've got only two complaints about the Presario 1900. Given that
it's a machine aimed at consumers, including home users, it should
have had a joystick port, an omission I suspect stems from its
origins as a business portable at Digital. Also, since it comes
with DVD, it should have a TV-out feature so you can plug it into a
television set to watch movies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
