<HEADLINE>
`GHOST DRIVERS' ON WINDOWS 98 SHOULD BE DELETED IN SAFE MODE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have discovered another problem with duplicated file names
in W98 _ ``ghost drivers'' in the Device Manager. It seems that
multiple operating system installs create one or more duplicate
devices in Device Manager that can only be viewed in Safe Mode.
Usually this only creates problems during shutdown, especially on
Compaq Presarios. Whenever PCs exhibit shutdown problems or
unexplained illegal operations or page faults, I bring up the
system in Safe Mode and check Device Manager for duplicated
devices. If they exist, I delete the second one. Shutdown problems
or unexplained system errors usually disappear afterward. I do not
know why or how these ``ghost devices'' get installed, but they do
create operational problems.
</P>
<P>
   A: I checked in with Microsoft's technical support, which
confirmed what you're saying. But don't be so fast in deleting just
one of those entries _ you don't know which is the real one, and
which is the ``ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   The technician I spoke with said it's best to remove both of
them while in Safe Mode. Then, when you reboot into Windows' normal
mode, the operating system should re-recognize the drive and
install the right driver.
</P>
<P>
   If you remove just one, and it's the wrong one, then Windows
might add another duplicate. Often, the ghost driver is a
historical artifact, an old entry without a driver to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   Why it shows up in Safe Mode, though, remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The technician said the problem is not confined to Presarios _
Microsoft has seen this issue on different kinds of machines.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, to get into Safe Mode, hold down the CONTROL key
after the computer does its test of the memory and various drives,
and before the operating system starts. You'll get a menu that lets
you choose Safe Mode as one of the options.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there log files on Windows 98 that show what files have
been used and when? Are there the same kind of files for Web
browsing? I know about the history area in the various browsers,
but are there files as well on the hard drives that contain Web
browsing info? I've had someone snooping recently on my computer
and I want to know how to delete these files if they exist.
</P>
<P>
   A: There are files that show which files have been used on a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   If you look in the Windowsapplog folder, you'll find a series of
files that have the names of your applications. As you use the
applications, the contents of these are updated. They are used by
the Windows 98 disk defragmentation application, which puts the
most-used programs on the fastest part of the disk. The defragger
uses these files to determine which programs get the most use.
</P>
<P>
   The History entries found in both Netscape Communicator and
Internet Explorer appear to be the only places where Web browsing
is tracked. The latest versions of these programs _ 4.51 for
Communicator and 5.0 of Internet Explorer _ both allow you to
easily clear your entries. Look in the settings or preferences
menus in these browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, TweakUI, the configuration applet that is found on the
Windows 98 CD, includes a tab called ``Paranoid'' that lets you
erase your history and other ``tracks'' you may have left.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, be aware that the folder called Temporary Internet
Files includes HTML pages and graphics from the pages you've viewed
online using Internet Explorer. If you use Communicator, look in
the Communicator folders on your hard drive for a subfolder called
Cache for these stored files.
</P>
<P>
   They are there to speed up your Web access, so your browser
doesn't have to download graphics and pages that have not changed
since you last looked at them.
</P>
<P>
   Again, these can be deleted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
