<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, May 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The Yugoslav capital cleans up
after the heaviest night of bombing yet. Army headquarters and the
Interior Ministry were hit. A civilian area of city was
accidentally hit, but no one was killed. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Belgrade) _ Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian
envoy, is to meet Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, today
and perhaps Ibrahim Rugova, an ethnic-Albanian leader. Meanwhile
the Yugoslav Foreign Ministry says that Belgrade could accept an
international force for Kosovo if the U.N. Security Council
authorizes it _ but only an unarmed force. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JACKSON (Belgrade) _ Jesse Jackson tours Belgrade, hopes
to see the three U.S. POWs. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MASSACRE (Kukes, Albania) _ A harrowing account of a
recent massacre in Kosovo as told by its sole survivor. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO briefing on its stepped-up bombing
campaign, including an admission of an accidental hit in a Belgrade
residential area. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, stories on NATO's effort to
recover the initiative in the information battle over Kosovo, a
separate on the day's developments from the Pentagon and reports of
sexual assaults on refugee women.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PROTEST (Beijing) _ The Chinese government issues warnings
to all agencies and work units that the Buddhist Law cult may hold
more demonstrations this weekend. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   COMOROS-COUP (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ The army of the
Comoros Islands announced that it had overthrown the government of
the Indian Ocean state. The coup comes amid efforts of the island
of Anjouan to declare its independence from the Islamic republic.
By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLORADO SCHOOL SHOOTING &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Ledeall on the
shootings: Authorities are increasingly on the defensive about
their actions or non-response to warnings about Eric Harris's
threats. Other developments. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-BACKLASH (Boston) _ Teen-agers dressed in black and
regular outcasts report a backlash against them. Both peers and
parents are snitching on them; computers are being taken away,
other teens shun them even more. One 18 year old senior in
California, who dresses Goth, said that other kids now look at him
and say ``Oh, are you going to come to school and shoot us all up
or what?'' Even his mom, who has been understanding of his dress
asked: ``What is the difference between you and them?'' The answer
from the kid: ``I haven't killed anyone yet.'' By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-CLINTON (Washington) _ With its plan for a White
House meeting on media violence, the administration continues its
effort to navigate the currents of public opinion on school
shooting in Colorado. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-EMMISSIONS (Washington) _ The White House is preparing new
emissions standards on air pollution from trucks and sport utility
vehicles. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The U.S. economy expanded at the
surprisingly strong annual rate of 4.5 percent in the first three
months of the year, the government reported today. While a slowdown
from a torrid 6 percent pace in the fourth-quarter, the
first-quarter gross domestic product was well above what had been
predicted on Wall Street. The growth was accompanied by an uptick
in inflation measures, raising concerns that there still exists a
link between strong growth and an eventual resurgence in inflation.
By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INVEST (Tosno, Russia) _ Russia's economic turmoil last
summer confirmed American companies' worst fears about Russia: it
is too unstable to do business there. But a number of Western
multinationals _ Caterpillar, Nestle, Lucent Technologies and
others _ have since decided to go deeper into Russia rather than
pull out. Many have picked areas where the local government
supports business, regardless of broader upheaval in Russia. In St.
Petersburg and the surrounding region, for example, six American
projects are expected to bring more than $500 million of direct
foreign investment over the next 18 months. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-IMF (Moscow) _ Russia's finance minister says the
renegotiated $4.5 billion loan agreement with the International
Monetary Fund will enable the country to more easily reschedule
billions of dollars in Soviet-era debts, and is a sign of increased
Western confidence in Russia. But he offers little assurance that
economic changes demanded by the IMF as part of its new agreement
will win parliamentary approval. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:20 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 8 points, the Nasdaq composite index up 18. In
Europe, stocks were modestly higher, while Tokyo stocks closed down
1.42 percent. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MERGER (Madrid) _ Folo on the $13.4 billion offer by Repsol,
Spain's largest oil company, to buy the remainder of Argentina's
YPF and thus create the world's eighth-largest oil company. By Al
Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Lewis's ``Abroad at Home.''
</P>
