<SLUG> BC-BARBECUE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLITTING HEIRS OVER TEXAS BARBECUE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOCKHART, Texas _ To call Edgar Schmidt a latter-day King Lear
might seem ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   He was, after all, the owner of a barbecue joint, a hard-working
sort known around this plain-spoken town as ``Smitty.''
</P>
<P>
   But then again we're talking about barbecue, more specifically
Central Texas barbecue, arguably the best barbecue in the state,
which to most around these parts means the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting atop this pyramid of superlatives is the century-old
Kreuz Market, a barbecue landmark that Schmidt bought in 1948 with
the blessing of the Kreuzes themselves and ran for nearly four
decades before selling the business to his sons, Rick and Don.
</P>
<P>
   But like Shakespeare's Lear, Schmidt divvied up his kingdom.
While the business went to his sons, he left the venerable red
brick building and downtown property to his daughter, Nina Sells.
The seeds of a Shakespearean tragedy, Texas-style, were sown.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Rick Schmidt will move Kreuz Market about a
half-mile north on State Highway 183 to a soon-to-be-constructed
building of brick, metal and wood on a patch of farm land. His
sister gave him no choice, he said, offering him a five-year lease
instead of the 20-year deal he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants this place for herself,'' said Schmidt, whose
brother Don is now retired from the family business. ``I offered to
rent it, to buy it, to make improvements on it. She said, `I ain't
interested in you long term and I'm not gonna sell.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sells describes the fallout in different terms. The building
needed repairs to meet code, she said, but her brother (she calls
him Mr. Schmidt) wanted to expand the dining room instead. Then
last year, Sells said, Schmidt delivered an abrupt
``sell-or-I-leave'' ultimatum through the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were problems I thought we needed to work out before we
extended the lease,'' said Sells, who is the Caldwell County clerk.
``He went to the press thinking public opinion might force me to
sell the building to him, but I decided to stick it out.''
</P>
<P>
   With Kreuz (pronounced Krites) &UR;  &LR; Market relocating, Sells plans
to open a barbecue joint called Smitty's in its place, a tribute to
her father. But to patrons of Kreuz Market this is no solution at
all, because at Kreuz everything is the way it was, and that's the
way folks like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow it's not gonna be right,'' said a somber Jim McGill,
working on a piece of sausage, a hot link, or just plain ``hot,''
in Kreuz vernacular. Kreuz Market makes 3,100 sausage rings every
day, cools them overnight, then reheats them over the pits before
serving them the next day.
</P>
<P>
   At Kreuz Market, tradition matters. Patrons come, as many as
2,500 on Saturdays alone, to devour beef shoulder, chops, prime rib
and sausage. Entering from the gravel parking lot at the rear,
folks are met by an open fire of post oak logs and smoke-tarnished
walls.
</P>
<P>
   There are no plates, just butcher paper, no forks and no side
dishes, save whole tomatoes, avocados and the like. Folks come for
the meat. Which is why there is no sauce, either.
</P>
<P>
   They get crackers or bread, a choice to be made after a 16-year
veteran named Ella weighs their barbecue and slaps it on two sheets
of paper. The purists take crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons eat in a long, smoke-stained hallway, an adjacent dining
room and another upstairs, all of which featured cabbage knives
tethered to the tables until just recently. (Now Kreuz Market
grudgingly supplies plastic knives.)
</P>
<P>
   So revered is the restaurant, and so honored the dining ritual,
that the place is often invoked in spiritual terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Texas is the holy land of barbecue,'' said the
American-Statesman, in a lengthy tribute last summer, ``then the
Kreuz Market is its most hallowed shrine, beef shoulder its blessed
sacrament.''
</P>
<P>
   Kreuz Market dates back to Aug. 20, 1900, when a son of German
immigrants named Charles Kreuz bought property on the Lockhart town
square. Seven months later, Kreuz Market opened its doors, selling
meats and cooking what was left over on the pits out back.
</P>
<P>
   Today Kreuz still features a meat market, but barbecue is what
people come for, thinking nothing of a 60-mile round trip for lunch
from Austin or its surrounding communities. Some come from out of
state to sample the glistening barbecue, still others from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have not had the chance to experience this have
missed a better part of living,'' said John Reagan, as he carved up
a pork chop and drank a Shiner Bock, the preferred beer at Kreuz.
Big Red _ in a bottle _ is the even more popular nonalcoholic
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes down good with sausage,'' said Sam Samarippa, savoring
the red cream soda. ``That's the way I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Few really understand the family dynamics that threaten the
rituals of patrons like Samarippa. Was Rick Schmidt simply sore
that his sister inherited the building? Did Sells squeeze her
brother out of the property in an attempt to grab his share of the
local market?
</P>
<P>
   ``This might look like our intention,'' said Sells. ``But it
really is the result of Mr. Schmidt's decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   A more pertinent question here in the Texas barbecue belt is
whether the Kreuz faithful will forgo the character of 208 S.
Commerce St. for hunks of tender shoulder, or the other way around.
Will they stay true to Rick and his slabs of pork chops or Nina and
the celebrated building?
</P>
<P>
   That may depend on how quickly a brand-spanking-new barbecue
joint can evolve into a hallowed shrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just gonna have to do it right,'' said Schmidt. ``We're
just gonna have to do the best we can to keep the feel we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Or it may depend on whether Sells can cook top-notch barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   She is leaning toward a menu that includes beans and potato
salad, which is almost certain to create a backlash among Kreuz
purists. Even so, the draw of the old building is powerful, and her
joint is likely to challenge her brother's share of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Sells enters the highly competitive arena with her husband, Jim,
who has placed first in Lockhart's Chisolm Trail Cookoff the last
two years. Jim Sells and his sons are recent blue-ribbon winners in
contests in Luling and Lubbock, impressive credentials even in
barbecue's Ivy League.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmidt is unfazed. So confident is he that he is building
the new Kreuz Market with twice the barbecue pits as the old one
and room for 700 patrons. As for tradition, Schmidt is considering
starting the fire in the new joint with embers from the old one,
which is how Kreuz Market starts up the pits every day and manages
to boast an unending fire.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt reckons the walls of his new place will be smoked up in
a matter of weeks, giving the new joint plenty of atmosphere. Even
so, he said, the draw of Kreuz Market has always been the barbecue,
not the building.
</P>
<P>
   Cook it, Schmidt said, and they will come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got plenty of competition,'' he said. ``One more without
experience doesn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
