<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE PESKY BUGS EATING PLANT LEAVES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: All of my plants have leaves with holes. Will you tell me
what insect is attacking my crops?
</P>
<P>
   A: I am seeing damage from two pests in our garden _ slugs and
fuzzy caterpillars that are falling from the overhead trees. Both
eat similar holes in leaves. Search carefully among your plants for
the culprit in your garden.
</P>
<P>
   The fuzzy caterpillars have whitish hairs along their sides and
could be one of the tent caterpillars I have a problem with every
spring but not at other times of the year. The various tent
caterpillars only have one generation. Whatever type, the
caterpillars have eaten the edges of coleus and punched holes in
the sweet-potato vine. They don't seem that picky. I usually just
squish them, but you can treat with Bt (``Bacillus thuringiensis'')
if you spot any caterpillar in your garden.
</P>
<P>
   The slugs are often difficult to spot, but they are deep in the
plants or on the backsides of the leaves when at work. Otherwise,
they hide under stones and bricks and beneath pots. I picked up a
potted geranium recently and found many tiny slugs thriving in the
moist dark.
</P>
<P>
   Slugs eat holes right out of the middle of the leaf or eat the
edges. These I hand-harvest as long as that's reasonable, but I
have resorted to DE, diatomaceous earth and even snail and slug
bait when infestation threatens an entire crop. You'll need to
reapply either of these products after a heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will ruellia make a good ground cover? Lamium?
</P>
<P>
   A: `Katie' ruellia is a good ground cover for sun or shade. This
clumping perennial is less than a foot tall, with slender, long,
arching leaves. Root-hardy, it will return after a freeze, but in
mild winters such as this year's, little damage is done to the
foliage.
</P>
<P>
   `Katie' produces petunialike, purple blooms for months. Bloom
time begins sooner, of course, after a mild winter, since plants do
not have to regrow. There is also a pink flowering form.
</P>
<P>
   This easy-to-grow plant spreads and produces numerous offspring
from seed. I simply pick the seedlings if they pop up where I don't
want them.
</P>
<P>
   `Katie' ruellia has a taller cousin commonly called Mexican
petunia. It matures to a height of about 3 feet, and it, too, can
be used as a taller ground cover. It does best in sun. Once dense,
it can be quite attractive, but you will need to corral it or
you'll have a sea of ruellia.
</P>
<P>
   Lamium, or dead nettle, is a perennial ground cover, often with
variegation. Height is a foot or so. Lamium needs shade and a
fertile, moist but well-draining soil. Although it is most
attractive, I have found it less vigorous in our garden, but
perhaps you will have better luck. You could first try it in a
small area container to see how it does in your garden.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a large Arizona ash that is 27 years old and produces
thousands of seeds every year. I have three other Arizona ash trees
that do not produce seeds. Is there anything I can do to stop
production of these seeds?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some ashes are pesky seed producers. The only way I know to
stop seed production is to cut down the tree that is producing the
seed. The nonproducers in your garden could be male trees.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you please give a brief refresher course on African
violets? I'm having trouble getting my plants to bloom.
</P>
<P>
   A: Try the following basics and see if your plants don't
respond.
</P>
<P>
   Light is a prerequisite to year-round African violet blooms. Any
area of your home that receives bright, filtered light will do. An
east window, where the plants will get some morning sun, is ideal.
</P>
<P>
   African violets will grow and bloom under fluorescent lights.
Double-tube fixtures are recommended. The lights should hang 8 to
10 inches above the foliage and be turned on 12 to 14 hours a day.
African violets do prefer dark nights.
</P>
<P>
   Overwatering is a major cause of houseplant death. Use wicking
to avoid this problem. With this system, the soil absorbs water via
a string extended from the hole in the bottom of the pot to a
reservoir of water. It's an especially good watering system to use
if you're going to be away for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Clean the reservoirs with household bleach and water once a
month or when algae begins to form. It's a good idea to replace the
wicks when you repot.
</P>
<P>
   African violets also may be watered from the top, or from the
bottom by adding water to the saucer. Use room-temperature water,
and water when the soil is somewhat dry to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   Once a month, water from the top to leach built-up salts.
</P>
<P>
   By using a wick and reservoir system, you can water and
fertilize simultaneously. Use a diluted, balanced fertilizer per
instructions on the package. If your plants have adequate light but
aren't flowering, you may need to fertilize more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   A sterilized, lightweight, soilless potting mix will allow
aeration and good drainage and discourage disease. Plastic
containers discourage salt buildup.
</P>
<P>
   If you're comfortable, your African violets will be comfortable,
because these plants like room temperatures. Ideal temperatures
fall in the 65-to 70-degree range at night and 5-10 degrees warmer
during the day. If it gets too warm, your plants will react by
growing spindly, and the few flowers that are produced may drop
before attaining good size. Good air circulation is most important,
as is enough humidity _ within the range of 40 percent to 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
