<HEADER>
A9562 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-$ADV02-C     04-30 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SERBIAN-AMERICANS FEEL HOMELAND'S PAIN
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 2
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    With photos
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARMA, Ohio _ The morning sun shines on this well-kept Cleveland
suburb and ignites the brilliant color of the stained glass windows
in St. Sava Serbian Orthodox Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Christ himself in luminous bloom along the southeastern wall
dominates the stout architecture of the Eastern rite church. But
again this Sunday, He fails to brighten a preoccupying somberness
inside.
</P>
<P>
   America is at war with Serbia, which for the people of St. Sava
means their home is at war with their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Dispatches from friends and family living under threat of NATO
air strikes in Yugoslavia spread through the congregation, a
cornerstone of one of the largest Serbian-American colonies in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   And bred within it, by the details about lives and jobs brought
down in Yugoslavia along with the bridges and the buildings, is a
powerful sense of confusion and frustration over what is happening
and how little they seem able to influence it.
</P>
<P>
   Insular and suspicious, they are desperate to be advocates for
peace, but feel hamstrung by the portrait of their nationality as
aggressive, unyielding and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with being a Serb,'' said John Petkovic, an
entertainment columnist for The (Cleveland) Plain Dealer, ``is that
every time you say something you're challenged with these
all-or-nothing propositions: `So are you saying you favor ethnic
cleansing?'''
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is no. But the long answer, and it gets very
long as it weaves through centuries of Serbian resistance to a
parade of aggressors, is that ethnic Albanians, Serbians and
Croatians have employed equally menacing tactics in the generations
of feuding that precipitated this war.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look at one point in time and say, `These are the
good guys and these are the bad guys,''' said Alex Rakic, an
attorney. ``We think it's horrible what's going on, but you need to
see the whole story. We just feel like Serbia's been picked as the
loser in the break-up of Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   The heritage of the Serbian people is on display in Parma,
centered on the church, stoked with a fearsome pride built over
centuries of hostile occupation and brutal turf warfare. Little by
little, they have pressed the epic battle of Kosovo Polje in 1389
into the consciousness of America to help explain why Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic remains immovable after five solid
weeks of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The battle of Kosovo Polje, in which the Serbians made a heroic
but losing stand against the Ottoman Empire, is the foundation of
Serbian belief in the rightness of their refusal to consider ceding
the region of Kosovo to ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   In Serbian homes here in Ohio, almost without fail, hangs a
painting called Kosovska Devojka. Cleveland Serbs say you'll find
it in every Serbian home in America. The title means Kosovo Girl.
The image depicts a woman giving aid to a lone surviving Serbian
soldier lying amid the bodies at Kosovo Polje, For a people whose
American descendants in Cleveland often teach their children
Serbian before they learn English, you almost can't overestimate
the symbolic value of a simple wall decoration.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, Rakic says, if America awoke one day and heard that
Mexican-Americans realized they were a majority within the city
limits of San Antonio, site of the Alamo, and decided to claim it
as a new, independent state. Imagine it. Well, Kosovo means more to
Serbia than the Alamo means to most Americans, but no American
would support an armed insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to understand,'' Rakic's uncle interrupts as he
walks through the living room, ``the Serbs cannot afford to lose
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Each night of the week now since the bombing began,
Serbian-Americans assemble at Public Square in downtown Cleveland.
In the shadow of the Gothic-looking Tower City Center, they circle
a patch of green grass contained by a city of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Some nights, the crowd is bigger than others. It's hard to
sustain a protest on a daily basis and mostly the TV and newspaper
people have stopped showing up. On the other hand, the Friday night
fish fry at St. Sava Serbian Orthodox Church _ a separate parish
from the cathedral _ sells out week after week and with each event
another few thousand dollars is cobbled together for humanitarian
relief. Of Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But the struggle for attention is one of the most challenging.
Last Sunday, on the last day of NATO's 50-year anniversary summit
in Washington, a bleary-eyed group at St. Sava's still was
recovering from an overnight bus ride. Members of the group rode
into and out of Washington in 24 hours just to stage a protest
while the diplomats were in town, but a small slip of paper, news
coverage of their demonstration, has them all awake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see this?'' a man huffs. ``Two-thousand? They say we had
2,000?''
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, he wants you to know. Cleveland alone sent 500 or
more. Add Chicago and Detroit, two other cities with large colonies
_ their word _ of Serbian-Americans, and you've hit 2,000 without
considering any other town.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Park Service told them the crowd was between 10,000 and
15,000, which only fuels their sense of dismay _ and suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you wonder,'' Rakic says. ``Why not state the correct
number?''
</P>
<P>
   Around St. Sava, they're starting to talk about forming a
committee to organize rebuttals to media accounts. When U.S. Rep.
Dennis Kucinich, a Democrat who represents this area and is of
Croatian descent, visited for a question-and-answer session, a
woman in the group asked if they should hire a public relations
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Kucinich offered his congressional office as a clearinghouse for
information, but the Serbian Unity Congress is likely to move
forward with a public relations professional, said its president,
who lives in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all we talk about,'' said Milosh D. Milenkovich,
president of the congress. ``This is not something that's going to
resolve itself. All the Serbs are changing their way of life as a
result of this.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a fault line, a split in the Serbian-American
community, it is in what they believe of the atrocities the Serb
military is accused of committing in Kosovo. Generally, those like
Milenkovich who were born in Serbia and became U.S. citizens, are
dismissive of the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Milenkovich doesn't believe the tales of rape or executions,
noting as do others around him that all the films of refugee camps
show an abundance of the able-bodied young men the Serbs are
supposed to be targeting. He is certain the Albanians fled NATO's
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   American-born Serbs are more willing to believe some of the
horrors. But they question the scale and are puzzled by the rush to
assign blame. After all, through the 1980s, the Serbs were the ones
being driven from Kosovo by Albanian coercion, violence and, as The
New York Times once wrote, rape. And the Serbs, too, were the
victims in 1995 when Croatian forces conducted a brutal sweep of
the Krajina region of Croatia. More than 200,000 Serbs were driven
from their homes and resettled in some of the same towns now under
NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize there are things going on over there being
committed by people of our nationality,'' said Joan Jakovich. ``But
where were you when my family was being ethnically cleansed?''
</P>
<P>
   Jakovich sells retail displays and her husband, an accountant,
is president of St. Sava Cathedral. She said her 80-year-old great
aunt was among those forced out of Krajina, and never was heard
from again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of go through your whole life trusting the
government,'' she said, ``but when you grow up and become
personally involved in something you kind of feel ashamed to be
American.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakovich was the talk of the church recently for having finally
punched through the telephone roulette to say a few words during a
CNN call-in show. The congregation was watching and knew it was her
the minute she was on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone watches CNN, even though they hate it. They consider it
no less a tool of the Clinton White House than Belgrade television
_ bombed off the air by NATO _ was to Milosevic. They tune in
endlessly, seeking new information they're not likely to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the soccer stadium in Pristina? In the first few days
of the conflict, American media broadcast and published rank rumor
that a soccer stadium had been converted into a concentration camp.
Turned out it wasn't true, but the damage to Serbians was done.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for the bombing of a refugee convoy a few weeks
ago. Though a NATO fighter accidentally dropped the bombs, the
Pentagon plowed through the first day's news cycle saying they
believed it was a Serbian MiG.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think structurally the media is free,'' said Petkovic of the
Plain Dealer, ``but intellectually is another story.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is their hope?
</P>
<P>
   Peace. They hope President Clinton will stop insisting that the
only option for peace is capitulation by Milosevic, because they
don't think it will ever happen. They hope NATO will suspend the
bombing just long enough to make one serious attempt at diplomacy
because the offer at Rambouillet was, like Clinton's current
demands, simply too rigid and too unfair to be considered a serious
effort at peace.
</P>
<P>
   And they hope to get on television. Around their offices they
say they have succeeded in converting a few gung-ho bombers and
they'd like to find the forum to reach more of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you just get them to question,'' Jakovich said,
``that's a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
