<HEADER>
A9570 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-DRUG-LAWS &LR;      04-30 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-DRUG-LAWS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRICT DRUG LAWS YIELD AN OVERDOSE OF PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ANDREAS TZORTZIS  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At least three times a night, Terrence Stevens needs
someone to roll him over in his cell. He also needs help turning
the page of a book and has to use his left hand to grip his right
when he spoons food into his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Crippled since the age of 2 by muscular dystrophy, Stevens, 32,
is an anomaly at the Green Haven Correctional Facility, an hour
north of Times Square by car. He requires a 24-hour attendant,
usually another prisoner, and bed rails on his cell bed. So far,
Stevens has served six years of a 15-to-life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was convicted of possessing more than four ounces of
cocaine, stashed in a duffel bag next to his seat on a Greyhound
bus in 1992. Under strict laws initiated by former Gov. Nelson
Rockefeller in 1973, the amount automatically earned him 15 years
in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   To proponents of such laws, Stevens is a good example of how
effective the laws can be in ridding the streets of drug dealers
for long periods of time. To advocates seeking to change the
sentencing guidelines, however, Stevens is serving a possible life
sentence for a crime that merits far less.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockefeller drug laws will be 26 years old in May. Denounced
as Draconian by a host of judges, ex-state senators and advocacy
groups, a movement to change the laws has gained momentum over the
past year. Under the laws, anyone convicted of possessing four
ounces or more of cocaine or heroin or selling two or more ounces
of the drug receives an automatic minimum sentence of 15 years in
prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   The strict laws are a major reason why the New York prison
population has grown by more than five times since their inception.
Worse, say opponents, the laws require small-time nonviolent
offenders to serve their sentences in maximum security prisons
alongside rapists and murderers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in there with all kinds of people,'' said Regina Stevens,
Terrence's mother. ``He can't do anything to defend himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever his brother, sister or mother come to visit, guards
often make Stevens wait for hours because searching him takes more
effort than they want to expend, said Alice Byrne, a private
investigator who is looking into the circumstances surrounding the
conviction of Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ought to triple the years he's been in there, because of
the circumstances he's been under,'' said Byrne, whose office is in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents assert the laws have effectively snared repeat drug
offenders and cleared the streets of most drug dealers. Seeking to
debunk the myth that drug felons are ``harmless victims of the
system,'' the New York District Attorney's Association published a
study in February this year. In analyzing the prison population,
the study found that 70 percent of prisoners incarcerated for drug
felonies were second-time offenders.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for change contend that the laws do not get the
drug kingpins they were originally designed to catch. Too often,
said Alan St. Pierre of the Marijuana Policy Project, the laws
catch the small-time users and sellers who do not have the
resources to fight incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Anthony Papa, barrel-chested and burly. A paintbrush
looks like a matchstick in Papa's thick hand. Lifting weights at
Sing Sing prison in upstate New York afforded Papa protection from
potential attackers. Wielding a paintbrush gave him his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Papa wasn't well-acquainted with art until he went to prison in
1985. The exposure came only after Papa delivered an envelope
filled with four-and-half ounces of cocaine to undercover police
officers conducting a drug sting.
</P>
<P>
   The bust came during a slow month for his radio repair business
in the Bronx. With a wife and young daughter to support, Papa was
amenable when a bowling partner he knew dealt drugs approached him
with $500 and asked him to deliver a small envelope of drugs to a
buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Papa, a first-time offender, went to court and lost. He was
mortified at the thought of going to prison but under the
Rockefeller law he received a 15 years-to-life sentence. Once Papa
went behind bars, an inmate named Indio gave him watercolors, a
paintbrush and guidance. Over the next 12 years, Papa earned two
bachelor's degrees and a master's degree and created 36 paintings,
all about prison life.
</P>
<P>
   When one of the pictures, ``15 Years to Life,'' a self-portrait,
was shown at the Whitney Museum of American Art in 1994, Papa's
story began getting coverage in the press. The attention eventually
helped gain him his release.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Papa, 44, has a two-inch thick packet of press clippings
about his work as a painter in prison and as an advocate on the
outside. He works as a clerk in the patent law office of Fish &AMP;
Neave, which, he points out, is only a block away from Rockefeller
Center. The packet is stored in a file drawer in his windowless
office, where the click of the gray door closing still reminds him
of his cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell into the role of the Zeitgeist,'' Papa said
philosophically, explaining his current role as a key figure in the
push to change the drug laws. ``It came about and I just fell into
it. I became the poster child'' for the controversy over mandatory
sentencing in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The stories of people like Stevens and Papa are what advocates
use to lobby state senators in hopes they will apply more pressure
on Gov. George Pataki to change the laws. An organization called
Families Against Mandatory Minimums plans to hold a family lobby
day sometime this spring, featuring relatives of inmates imprisoned
under the Rockefeller laws who will hold press conferences and
speak to legislators in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time is ripe for reform,'' said Therese Derikart, the
organization's New York director. Derikart has a case file bursting
with stories like Papa's. Her clemency file, she said, is still too
thin.
</P>
<P>
   The movement, begun some years after Rockefeller signed his name
to the laws in 1973, has gathered momentum in the last two years,
said Robert Gangi, executive director of the Correctional
Association of New York, a non-profit prison watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, proposals to ease penalties by state politicians in New
York do not go far enough for the advocacy groups. Despite
suggesting he would change the laws when he took office, Pataki has
taken few steps in that direction. When state legislators discuss
the laws, Gangi said, talk will most likely center on the state
budget rather than changing sentencing laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics always overwhelm the issue,'' he said. ``It poisons
the well from our standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe it is the lucrative lure of prison construction in
their districts that keep many of New York's legislators straddling
the fence. Building a prison brings automatic jobs and revenue to
the neighboring cities. Already there are 69 prisons in New York
state, according to the Department of Corrections. Pataki's 1999
budget includes construction of a new, 750-cell maximum security
prison in Malone, N.Y., according to Families Against Mandatory
Minimums.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have plenty of money to build more prisons,'' said Brian
Frankel, a lawyer and high school friend of an inmate named Eric
Marsh, who is serving a 15-to-life sentence at the Eastern
Correctional Facility in Napanoch, N.Y., for allowing his apartment
be used during a sale of 2.2 ounces of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   In carefully scripted prose, Marsh, like Papa before him, has
written letters to lawyers, politicians, judges _ anyone who will
listen. Now in his ninth year of incarceration, Marsh has worked
inside the prison as a teacher's aide, received a bachelor's degree
in psychology and served in the facility's Jewish Synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to belabor the point of my trial,'' he wrote in a
recent letter to Derikart. ``But the sentences that were given in
my case, were extremely disproportionate to the crimes involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel put it another way: ``This guy is a political
prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Andreas Tzortzis is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
