   &UR; e-mail ws52 &LR; columbia.edu &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; web site http://cns.jrn.columbia.edu/ &LR;  This week's stories:
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN MARKET _ On a recent Saturday, Betty Delacruz leaned
against a wall at the Knickerbocker Live Poultry Market and waited
for her two chickens and three quail to be killed, plucked, and
gutted. Now she shops, sometimes twice a week, at the
Knickerbocker, which for 62 years has catered to several immigrant
cultures in Brooklyn. Each has its own idea of what makes good
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN EYES _ More and more Asian women are seeking plastic
surgery to make their eyes like more western.
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN STUDENTS _ Colleges and universities in the United
States are getting fewer students from Canada, thanks to the
exchange rate on money.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG LAWS _ The Rockefeller drug laws will be 26 years old in
May. Denounced as Draconian by a host of judges, ex-state senators
and advocacy groups, a movement to change the laws has gained
momentum over the past year. Under the laws, anyone convicted of
possessing four ounces or more of cocaine or heroin or selling two
or more ounces of the drug receives an automatic minimum sentence
of 15 years in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   ELEPHANT MANURE _ Elephant manure, pungent and plentiful, is
rich in nutrients, perfect for gardeners to use as fertilizer after
a half-year of composting. For more than 20 years, the Ringling
Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus has given away the pachyderm
panacea to horticulturists, who report gigantic flowers and rapid
vegetable growth as a result. Zoos around the country also sell the
powerful dung. High-grade exotic manure has even reached the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC ISLAM _ Some Hispanic-American women who become Muslim
do so for love, having met a Muslim man. Others are searching for
tranquility. Whatever the reason, for Hispanic-American women,
embracing Islam is not easy. Adjusting to a new dress code,
lifestyle and the language of the Koran, Arabic, can take years.
</P>
<P>
   MEAN COMEDY _ There is little to laugh about at some open-mic
nights at comedy clubs, which amateur stand-ups use it as a venue
for venting.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY PROMOTION _ ``Everybody parties,'' said a member of one of
New York's most active event promotion teams. ``It's all about
making sure everybody is having a great time. It's not all fun and
games, trying to throw parties in New York, but somebody's got to
do it, right?'' Apparently, more and more young entrepreneurs think
so. Black Diamonds Entertainment and other events groups, like
ProLinks Incorporated, Net2 and Partners in Soul, hold parties
several nights throughout the week at New York clubs like NV, the
Metronome, Vivid, Cream and Nell's, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   SUBWAY MUSICIANS _ For subway riders, the buskers' presence
provides a pleasant background noise and a diversion during rush
hour. But for the musicians, the underground stage provides more
than the $80 to $150 they can earn in five hours; it is a chance to
be in the public's eye, and to gain some recognition, which could
lead to a grander stage. Pete Seeger, Woody Gutherie and, according
to legend, Tony Bennett all performed underground.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIAN FUTURE _ Commentary: Since the presidential elections
in Nigeria in late February, Western leaders, diplomats and
scholars now talk about Africa's most populous country in rhapsodic
terms. They don't speak of a failed state with a seeming propensity
to self-destruct. Rather, they gush about a strategic country on
the cusp of renewal.
</P>
</TEXT>
