<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9573 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-ELEPHANT-MANURE &LR;      04-30 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ELEPHANT-MANURE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUMBO DUNG DELIVERS POWER TO FLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By STAN CHOE  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine monstrous roses, 400-pound pumpkins and
tomatoes the size of grapefruits. These are not fairytales or
wishful thinking but products produced by what some people call the
greatest manure on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Elephant manure, pungent and plentiful, is rich in nutrients,
perfect for gardeners to use as fertilizer after a half-year of
composting. For more than 20 years, the Ringling Brothers and
Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus has given away the pachyderm panacea to
horticulturists, who report gigantic flowers and rapid vegetable
growth as a result. Zoos around the country also sell the powerful
dung. High-grade exotic manure has even reached the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the greatest stuff on Earth,'' said Pete Cimini, the
stable master at Ringling Brothers. ``It's pure manure, no
additives. Miracle-Gro ain't got nothing on Ringling.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the circus's 14 elephants eats 150 to 250 pounds of hay
per day, along with various grains, fruits and vegetables. While
the notion that elephants love peanuts is myth, they do favor
pumpkins and watermelons. They also drink 30 to 50 gallons of water
each day. They need to eat and drink this much to sustain their
weight, which can range from 8,000 to 20,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of their prodigious intake, they produce elephantine
amounts of manure _ up to 500 or more pounds per day in extreme
cases. Each pellet of elephant waste is about the size of a
volleyball and weighs between eight-and-a-half to 10 pounds.
Because elephants digest only about 40 percent of their food, their
dung is rich in nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   As the circus makes its circuit around the country, it gives
away the elephant manure at stops where demand for it is high.
Anyone who wants some can call and pick some up. Demand for dung is
greatest in Houston, Cimini said.
</P>
<P>
   People in Houston regularly begin to line up for the fecund
fertilizer the night before the giveaway, Cimini said. So many
gardeners come that the circus has two uniformed police officers to
handle the crowd, he said. The circus also rations out the manure,
one five-gallon bucket per person.
</P>
<P>
   The giveaways usually occur around lunchtime. Most of the people
in line are ``Ma and Pa Home Depot-type people,'' Cimini said.
``But always look for people with ties or high heels, looking over
their shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   The circus does not deliver. Gardeners must find their own way
to get the manure home. ``They bag their own, box their own, have
trucks ready to haul,'' Cimini said.
</P>
<P>
   Elephant manure is so popular that some have resorted to theft
to get it, Cimini said. At a stop in Atlanta in 1997, ``We had a
Mount Everest, actually a Mount Ringling, of manure. It was 15 feet
tall and as wide as one of the circus rings. The next morning, I
went out to check up on the pile, and it was not even a foot
high.'' The night before, a circus employee had seen a dump truck
driving away from the compound.
</P>
<P>
   The manure was never recovered. ``What is the world coming to
when you steal someone's dung?'' Cimini wondered.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popularity of elephant manure, it is still so
plentiful _ and renewable _ that 99 percent of the circus's stock
ends up going to the landfill, Cimini said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx Zoo in New York does not give away any of its elephant
manure, because of Board of Health regulations, said Rosanne
Thiemann, an employee in the curator of mammalogy's office.
</P>
<P>
   The National Zoo in Washington, though, packages the manure of
some of its herbivores _ elephants, giraffes and rhinos, among
others _ into a product named Zoo Doo. The Zoo Doo does not include
the dung of carnivores, as it is poisonous.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-pound bag costs $6, while a souvenir bucket of 15 ounces
costs $5, said Rick Reichley of Friends of the National Zoo. ``Zoo
Doo is the ultimate in recycling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo Doo helped Joe Mills, a photographer from Falls Church, Va.,
to grow ultimate pumpkins. Mills set the pumpkin record in
Washington, D.C., 1997 with a 408-pound pumpkin, named Boo-Da 1,
with the help of Zoo Doo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zoo Doo is a gourmet manure,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the gourmet dung, Mills bested his record the
next year with Boo-Da 2, a 470-pound pumpkin. Mills had a 500-pound
pumpkin, but an animal ate it before it could be officially
weighed. ``I just know it was something that had fairly big
claws,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo Doo exists on the Internet, as well. The name Zoo Doo is
licensed by a company in Memphis, Tenn. It has an agreement with
the National Zoo, allowing it to use the name. The Zoo Doo company,
which blends the dung of many different herbivores, can be found at
www.zoodoo.com. The company's website boasts:
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the vitamins elephants eat, Zoo Doo is like a
multivitamin for the garden.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Stan Choe is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
