<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9575 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-MEAN-COMEDY &LR;      04-30 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-MEAN-COMEDY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT OPEN-MIC NIGHTS, COMEDIANS LOSE THE GAG REFLEX 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ALEX LANE  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As an open-mic night wound down on a recent Wednesday
at the Collective Unconscious club in Manhattan, a stand-up comic
named Steve Y walked onstage and set up a video camera, saying he
was taping his set for his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Then he took out a pistol loaded with hollow-point bullets,
spewed a string of nonsense, and held the gun to his head.
</P>
<P>
   Y didn't pull the trigger, and he said it was just a joke. But
the six or seven staff members and performers left in the room were
worried enough to get him off stage, take him outside, and talk him
into giving them the gun.
</P>
<P>
   Gunplay is rare at these shows, but it's safe to say the
incident was not exactly a surprise to anyone who knows the scene.
Open-mic nights, which take place just about every night of the
week somewhere in lower Manhattan, have long been the first step in
a career in stand-up comedy. But these days, comedians say, the
amateurs seem less interested in starting a career than in working
out their aggression. Open-mic nights have become the dark
underbelly of stand-up comedy _ desperation, anger, downright
oddness and occasional violence take the place of gags and jokes.
Nowhere is it clearer that humor is often born of pathos.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point,'' said Jen Miller, who hosts the weekly
open-mic night at Collective Unconscious, ``open-mic comedy is
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   She explained, ``The comedy boom of the '80s is over,'' and the
entertainment industry is less interested in comedians than it was
a few years ago. So there are fewer pros-in-training on the amateur
circuit _ many of today's open-mic performers are leftovers who see
their six minutes on stage as a mini therapy session.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a young, fresh group of people who are starry-eyed
and happy with their jobs and their lives,'' Miller said. ``You
have a three-and-a-half-hour show that sucks because people are up
there doing their therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What scared me about the Steve Y incident was that it was that
one guy, but it could have been any one of 30 or 40 people I know
on the scene and I wouldn't have been surprised,'' said Sean
Conroy, a comedian and open-mic regular who has been at it for
about a year.
</P>
<P>
   A recent open-mic night in the dark back room of Bar None, a
tavern in Manhattan's East Village, offered a glimpse into this
strange, often gloomy world.
</P>
<P>
   There was ample low self-esteem: ``I'm just a jerk tonight, I'm
sorry guys,'' said a comic named Spiro who, like most, was not
getting any laughs. His audience _ as at many open-mic nights _ was
mostly comics waiting for their turn onstage. ``I'm a compulsive
loser and I'm just attaching myself to another hobby for two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   There was kookiness: ``I've got a date next week, and we're
going to Queens,'' said a comic named Gawi, who has an Elmer
Fudd-style speech impediment and often talks in non sequiturs.
``What do I do? Do I buy condoms beforehand? Do I wear green
underwear?''
</P>
<P>
   And there was plenty of misogyny: ``This is a great place to
bring a date, if you're going to rape her,'' said a comic who goes
by the name Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   For more traditional comics, the endless stream of kooks can be
too much to take. ``When I first started, I couldn't be in the room
unless I was performing, I just found it too depressing,'' Conroy
said. ``It's all these things, the racism, the homophobia, the
constant talk of raping and killing women.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy said he had learned to define deviancy down. ``After a
while you're like, 'Well this person's not psychotic, so at least I
can watch them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Comedians have always incorporated a politically incorrect
edginess into their acts, but many open-mic performers seem
genuinely hateful. Women are often the target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most stand-ups wouldn't know how to get a date if they took a
course,'' said Paul Mercurio, a writer and correspondent on the
Comedy Central cable channel's Daily Show. ``There's that
resentment, 'If I can't have you, I'm going to find something wrong
with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mercurio spent a year and a half on the open-mic circuit before
growing into television work. ``In looking back, it's kind of a
bizarre thing to put yourself through,'' he said. ``All comics have
problems, but lots of these people had so many more problems than
most people. It was kind of weird to try to be funny in such a
depressed environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the strangeness erupts into actual violence. Mercurio
remembers waiting to follow a whiny folk singer performing
``Blowin' in the Wind'' at one open-mic. During the song, a fight
broke out at the pool table, and a man got slashed with a
box-cutter razor blade. The slasher ran out, leaving the victim
grabbing his neck, screaming, ``He cut me! That guy cut me!''
Through all this, the folk singer played on undeterred. ``And you
can understand why,'' Mercurio said. ``Because you wait all week to
get the spot and you don't want to give it up for anything.'' When
the folk singer finished, the emcee called Mercurio to the stage as
police tended to the victim. Mercurio's first line was, ``I always
wanted to follow a slashing.'' This annoyed the victim, and a
wadded-up, bloody napkin flew out from the audience, hitting
Mercurio in the leg.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Pepitone, another comedian, said he's always slightly
nervous at open-mics, especially after the Steve Y incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned to be nice to everybody,'' Pepitone said. ``It
gets weird in these venues, these weird, dark, little places.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Alex Lane is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
