<HEADER>
A9577 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-NIGERIAN-FUTURE &LR;      04-30 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-NIGERIAN-FUTURE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MINES THREATEN NIGERIA'S PATH TO DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By WAZIRI ADIO  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the presidential elections in Nigeria in late February,
Western leaders, diplomats and scholars now talk about Africa's
most populous country in rhapsodic terms. They don't speak of a
failed state with a seeming propensity to self-destruct. Rather,
they gush about a strategic country on the cusp of renewal.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sweet but ironic turn. Only a year ago, Nigeria earned
the status of an international pariah, and looked like a Rwanda or
Bosnia waiting to happen. A new dispensation should kick in when
the election winner, Olusegun Obasanjo, a former military head of
state widely respected in the international community, is sworn in
as president on May 29. The ceremony will mark the end of 15 years
of continuous military rule.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerians and the outside world hope that this transition will
permanently do away with military rule, an aberration that has
plagued the country for most of its 38 years of independence. As
desirable and legitimate as this expectation is, the incoming
civilian administration might prove to be just another civilian
interregnum. Some odds suggest that the military might soon shoot
its way back.
</P>
<P>
   The sad legacy of long military rule might fuel an impatience
that could lead to instability. Under the military, Nigeria's
economy ran aground. The country earned at least $250 billion from
sales of crude oil, but its people reel in poverty. Per-capita
income is now under $250, down from the $1,200 of the 1980s. The
country's currency, the Naira, is now worth about one cent, down
from $1.25 in the late 1970s. A Nigerian head of state once boasted
that the country's problem was not money but how to spend it.
Bogged down by a $32 billion external debt, Nigeria is now one of
the world's 13 poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   Things are worse in human terms. Nigeria, the world's
eighth-largest producer of oil, cannot fuel its cars. About 50
percent of its 115 million population live below the poverty level.
Life expectancy is low, infant mortality high. Infrastructure is
either extinct or comatose. Telephone lines are mostly dead. Roads
are pockmarked. Water taps run dry. The electricity authority beams
darkness. A futile anger dilutes the puny smiles on the faces of
Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
   Many expect these dire circumstances to change with the exit of
military rule. Maybe. Apart from being saddled with this crushing
inheritance, the new administration will also confront great
expectations and will be hobbled by free-falling oil prices. Unmet
expectations can give way to despair and angst, which might send
the country back in the cyclical trap of military rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transition to democracy, of course, has to have tangible
meaning for people in terms of standard of living, sense of
security and economic opportunities,'' said Salih Booker, director
of the Africa Studies Program of the Council on Foreign Relations,
a New York-based policy group. ``If things don't happen as quickly
as people expect, they might say 'if democracy could be this bad
why not give us military rule.'''
</P>
<P>
   Having suffered for too long, Nigerians might not have the
patience for a gradual turn-around. And in Nigeria, the soldiers
are always waiting in the barracks.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of possible pretexts for the army to act.
</P>
<P>
   One, corruption, for which the country has achieved notoriety,
will outlive military rule. ``More money was spent in this campaign
than at any other time before,'' said Julius Ihonvbere, a Nigerian
who works as the program officer for governance at the Ford
Foundation in New York. ``These politicians don't see themselves as
philanthropists. What we might witness is the crudest looting in
recent times.'' The soldiers always take power under the pretext of
cleaning up the mess created by politicians, but end up out-looting
the politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Another dangerous signpost is the pervasive sense of alienation
reigning in parts of the country. Many in the southwest region of
Nigeria, from where Obasanjo hails, distrust him, viewing him as a
stand-in for the corrupt generals from the North. The elections
were shadowed by accusations of manipulation. The Ibos in eastern
Nigeria feel cut out of the present dispensation. The Niger Delta,
which produces the country's oil but is the least developed section
of the country, is full of angry people who feel left out.
</P>
<P>
   Many Nigerians clamor for change in the structure of their
country and for equitable allocation of resources. But it is
unlikely that the incoming administration will address these issues
_ the campaigns were empty on issues, heavy on bland
generalizations.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria could slip into a one-party state. The People's
Democratic Party dwarfs the other two parties and controls a
majority of seats in all levels of government. In a political
system where winners take all and incumbents are always difficult
to unseat, it is unlikely that one-party rule will be prevented.
And when people are frustrated with domination in Nigeria, they
embolden the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not yet morning on creation day,'' said Ihonvbere,
quoting Chinua Achebe, the Nigerian novelist who wrote Things Fall
Apart. ``I see this as a short break from military rule. It could
be a long one. But certainly not the end of military rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Booker said Western countries could prevent these scary
scenarios. ``They should emphasize to him [Obasanjo] the need to
form a government of national unity and put in place democratic
institutions and respect people's rights,'' he said. ``The West has
been too euphoric about the transition in Nigeria. Euphoria doesn't
help that country.''
</P>
<P>
   With a population that accounts for one-fifth of all the people
in sub-Saharan Africa, its human and resource endowments and its
strategic importance, Nigeria can still dance in the sun as a real
giant. But to realize the destiny its people and many outsiders
crave, Nigeria needs restructuring, revival, and reconciliation.
Only these, not just elections and twinkling rhapsodies, can ensure
that the military will not be tempted to inflict themselves again
on the country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Waziri Adio is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
