<SLUG> BC-CNS-CHICKEN-MARKET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRANTS FLOCK TO BROOKLYN CHICKEN MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By SANDRA YIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a recent Saturday, Betty Delacruz leaned against a
wall at the Knickerbocker Live Poultry Market and waited for her
two chickens and three quail to be killed, plucked, and gutted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone had six to 10 chickens in his yard,'' said Delacruz,
42, recalling life in her native Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Now she shops, sometimes twice a week, at the Knickerbocker,
which for 62 years has catered to several immigrant cultures in
Brooklyn. Each has its own idea of what makes good chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Vargas, 43, a car repairman from the Dominican Republic,
has a taste for sancocho, a stew concocted of chicken, spaghetti,
green plantains and yucca. It's important the bird doesn't fall
apart during up to two hours of cooking, he said. Tough old hens
can take it, but young chickens are ``no good for soup,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the early decades, mostly Italians, Germans and Eastern
Europeans came to the Knickerbocker, said owner Michael Lane. Now,
the clientele is mostly from South America, particularly the
Dominican Republic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other recent immigrants who make their way to the store hail
from China and Poland. And each group has its own idea of how fowl
should be picked and prepared.
</P>
<P>
   A Rumanian whose family raised about 60 chickens in Yugoslavia,
Stella Janca, 64, makes chicken soup up to twice a week. Leaving
her grocery cart in line, she peers into cages at chicken legs,
searching for the bony nodule on the back of the leg that tells
their age. Few have any. The vitamins and medicine in their feed
make them grow too fast, she said. The young are okay for goulash,
she said, but she is looking for a one-year-old for soup.
</P>
<P>
   Head, feet and body will serve as the base for the soup stock,
she explained. Following a recipe handed down through generations,
she will add parsley, carrots, onions, and homemade noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most customers, who let the poultry man select a bird,
Janca insists on feeling the chickens before deciding to buy. She
wanders from cage to cage, sometimes reaching in to pull a
squawking bird out. Now prodding, then gently squeezing the bird's
chest, she considers the chicken's soup worthiness. ``If it's too
skinny, it might be sick,'' she said. ``And if it's too soft,
there's too much fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacks of cages line the market walls. They contain rabbits,
ducks and quail, but mostly chickens. Four-month old broilers and
friers, far from a ceiling heater, huddle together for warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Cruz, 25, a dental technician from Bayside, Queens, buys
three chickens a week. His family of four, he said, can go through
one and a half chickens in one day. As Dominicans, they relish
arroz con pollo, a rice and chicken dish, and deep fried chicken,
Cruz said. If it's Monday, it's fried. If it's Wednesday, it's with
spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Tuesday, John Zhune, 46, bought five white chickens
for his Aunt Elba to roast, stew or boil for soup. In the
mountaintop town in Ecuador where he grew up, the family raised 100
chickens for themselves. Homegrown chickens are the best, the
Ridgewood, Queens resident said. Free to wander, ``they eat every
kind of little animal,'' he said. Insects, cockroaches, even mice
are part of their daily nutritional intake. The diverse diet makes
for more intense flavor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Proprietor Lane, who sometimes mans the cashier window, said his
chickens were free-range. ``Technically,'' he said, ``it just means
they can walk out the door.'' At the Knickerbocker, the door is
always propped open and cage doors are sometimes left wide open as
well. But few chickens choose to leave the confines of their cages
for the streets of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   When not in Ecuador managing real estate and visiting family,
Zhune grows nostalgic for pollo horneado, a family specialty. Back
home, his oldest brother Luis, 55, makes the dish by roasting
chicken with garlic, onions, and Coca-Cola for four hours in a wood
burning oven.
</P>
<P>
   Under the din of the market's fan, a babel of chirps, warbles
and ``bock-bock-bocks'' is punctuated by the occasional screech of
protest as a poultryman pulls a chicken out of a cage. Frayed old
egg layers, destined for someone's soup pot, jab beaks into each
other's faces.
</P>
<P>
   While 5-to-10-pound chickens are the most popular, said Manuel
Duran, 46, who has worked in poultry markets for almost 20 years,
preferences vary. Chinese and Latinos seem to prefer the red
spotted, grey rock pullets, he said as he stood by the scale
waiting for customers to appear, a white surgical mask propped on
top of his baseball cap. Many Chinese prize black-skinned chickens,
which they believe possess greater healing powers.
</P>
<P>
   To cut or not to cut, or even how to cut, all depends on the
customer. When Duran marks one of the tags wired to a bird's foot
with ``CS'', Claude Nance, 62, who has killed chickens at the
market since 1972, knows to treat the chickens ``Chinese style.''
The cut to the neck will be small and he won't remove the head.
</P>
<P>
   Central Americans from Colombia, Mexico and Ecuador also like
the head attached, Duran said. Mexicans do not want their chickens
gutted. Many Dominicans, partial to fried chicken, want the meat,
but do not want to be bothered with the head, feet, heart or liver.
They prefer the younger, white chickens. South Americans sometimes
ask that the chickens be cut into small pieces for stewing or
frying.
</P>
<P>
   Customers pay at a window, where a sign says ``Paga Aqui, Por
Favor Gracias'' and ``Please pay here. Thank you.'' A sign on the
wall lists specials: Gallinas Blancas or white hens, are five for
$11 and hens, red or amarilla, three for $12.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the market for the first time in 13 years, Gladys Roman,
47, who was raised in Puerto Rico, said she stopped her weekly
visits in the mid-1980s because of the smell. On a recent Saturday
morning, waiting outside the gutting room for her number to be
called, the Puerto Rican said she had come at her Italian
son-in-law's bidding. Her baby granddaughter's Italian grandmother
would make soup of the chicken she bought. Weeks later, Roman
recalled, the baby's cold and ear infection were gone in two days.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Sandra Yin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
