<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9579 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-SUBWAY-MUSICIANS &LR;      04-30 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-SUBWAY-MUSICIANS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC GOES UNDERGROUND AND SUBWAY RIDERS FEEL THE BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ADAM KRAMER  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Carolina Slim, wearing a long gray army coat and a
black fedora, looked out onto the subway platform under Times
Square. His foot moved to the slow rhythm of his guitar as he
squeezed out a blues tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way down in New Orleans, the prettiest girl I've ever seen,''
he sang as his student and sideman Ricky Gordon grated a piece of
metal up and down the washboard on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, one of the rush-hour commuters dropped
change into the white box at the pair's feet, and Slim would thank
them with a slow nod of his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing in the subway because of the crowd,'' Slim
said. ``Every car, some will stop, and you can get a few dollars,
then the next car and a few more. The reward is the people stopping
everything and listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Slim, 72, whose real name is Elijah Staley, is one of hundreds
of musicians whose music _ heard above the hiss and click-clack of
subway trains, the beep of turnstiles and the garbled voice of
loudspeakers announcing the arrival of another train _ radiates
through the underground catacombs that make up the subway system.
</P>
<P>
   For subway riders, the buskers' presence provides a pleasant
background noise and a diversion during rush hour. But for the
musicians, the underground stage provides more than the $80 to $150
they can earn in five hours; it is a chance to be in the public's
eye, and to gain some recognition, which could lead to a grander
stage. Pete Seeger, Woody Gutherie and, according to legend, Tony
Bennett all performed underground. Slim has played in commercials
and a Madonna video.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, 150 subway musicians are sponsored by the city
through a transit authority program called Music Under New York,
while other performers set up shop on the subway station platforms,
tunnels and mezzanines. They are from diverse backgrounds and play
a broad variety of music: African, blues, jazz and the drum beat of
sticks hitting plastic buckets are only a few of the sounds that
give the subway music its character.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking to make the musician rosters as diverse as
possible, in order to reflect the city,'' said Tim Higginbotham,
co-director of Music Under New York.
</P>
<P>
   Tim and his wife, Gina, have run the music program since 1993,
which celebrated its 10th anniversary last year. They are
responsible for scheduling performers at 25 locations throughout
the transit system and arranging the 150 weekly performances. In
addition, they are responsible for overseeing the roster of
musicians and auditioning hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   According to Higginbotham, the program books about 75 out of the
150 musicians who are a part of the program each week. The others
are out of town or have different gigs that occupy their time. Each
year, the program adds about 15 new musicians via an audition
process that involves playing before a panel of music industry
professionals. The musicians are judged on quality, variety and
appropriateness for the mass transit environment.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out on to the shuttle platform, Slim and his partner
surveyed the crowd, grinning and talking to the people with their
facial expressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look up at the people, look 'em in the eye,'' said Slim.
``Have conversations with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Slim, born in South Carolina, moved up to New York 48 years ago
after a stint in the army in World War II. Playing the blues since
age 9, Slim gave his first public concert at age 15. He has been a
part of the Music Under New York since its inception, playing two
or three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good,'' said Eliana Misan, who was listening to Slim
while waiting for a friend. ``It makes New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner from Slim, facing the entrance to the downtown
N and R trains and the Latin Music Store, Larry Wright, 24, drummed
on a pair of white plastic buckets. Wright was a freelancer _
someone not associated with Music Under New York. This means his
music, unlike those of his sanctioned colleagues, cannot be
amplified.
</P>
<P>
   Wright was discovered in the subway at the age of 15, when PBS
filmed a show about him and the plastic buckets he uses to make
music. Since then he has performed on Broadway in ``Bring in Da
Noise, Bring in Da Funk,'' on videos, in a Levi's commercial, and
now plays every Sunday at the Baggot Inn in Greenwich Village, in a
show called ``Keep Banging.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not for the money, it's giving back to the community,''
Wright said. ``Nothing wrong with coming down here and
practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright's usual spot was where Carolina Slim had set up, but out
of respect for his fellow street musician, he had moved around the
corner. Now after two hours, Wright was putting away his buckets
and closing up for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in the subway is something that they can never take
away, I got to keep coming back,'' Wright said. ``I like lifting
people's spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   At the return stop of the shuttle _ facing the steps that bring
passengers from the 4,5 and 6 trains _ stood a man with Fila
sneakers, black jeans and a black hat with a New York Yankees
emblem. Resting in between his legs was a tan and white bowl with
long stick shooting upward, which held the 21 strings he picked
with both thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Keba Bobo Cissoko, from Guinea Bissau, has been in the United
States for four years and has been playing in the subway for one.
He sings in his native language, Creolo, playing the instrument
from his country, the Kora. The elevated pitch and gentle rhythms
of his voice, which move at a fast pace as he keeps time with the
harp-like sounds emanating from his instrument, are not common to
America. But the messages his songs convey are cross-cultural. He
sings of travel, life, love and history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sing about everybody, about America,'' Cissoko said. ``When
you are traveling you have to talk about everything, about culture.
I am talking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the commuters rushing through the station paid little
attention to the black man with a smile from ear to ear. Most were
more concerned with filing in and out of the subway cars; a few
looked at his instrument as if it was from a faraway, unknown
world.
</P>
<P>
   Like most subway musicians, Cissoko likes singing in the subway.
He enjoys meeting different people; it is a way for him to be in
the public eye. Through public contact, he has been able to get
other jobs, like playing music for the Yoga and African dance
classes at The New York Sporting Club.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians of Music Under New York and the freelancers, who
make their living playing for people running through the vast
corridors that encompass the subway, are a mosaic of different
races and cultures. They represent the city, and are a part of New
York City's history, culture and lore.
</P>
<P>
   According to Higginbotham: ``The music in the subways adds to
the cultural mix of this town.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Adam Kramer is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
