<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9584 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LACKLAND-AFB-HNS &LR;      04-30 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LACKLAND-AFB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE TO SEEK BIDDERS FOR SOME WORK AT TEXAS BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID HENDRICKS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Air Force in August will seek private bids to
take over some operations at Lackland Air Force Base, a move that
could affect more than 1,600 civilian jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Most jobs at the base, known as ``The Gateway to the Air
Force,'' would transfer to the private sector in a cost-cutting
move, although an unknown number of jobs also could be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   At least one Texas partnership already has formed to bid on the
work at Lackland, the Air Force's only basic-training base.
</P>
<P>
   The first bidder to publicly disclose its intentions is EG&AMP;G
Technical Services, represented by EG&AMP;G Management Services of San
Antonio. The company already has a contract with the city of San
Antonio to redevelop Kelly Air Force Base into an industrial park.
</P>
<P>
   EG&AMP;G's main partner will be Boeing Service Co., based in
Richardson, Texas, a separate Boeing division from the aerospace
services operation that began aircraft operations at Kelly last
year. Kelly will cease being a base and will be turned over to the
city of San Antonio in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If the competition for a private contract doesn't meet the
government's standards, however, the Air Force will continue to
operate Lackland under its own contracting rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The private competition winner must beat the most efficient
government plan by 10 percent or more,'' said Rudy DiLuzio,
president and general manager of EG&AMP;G Management Services.
</P>
<P>
   According to Air Force information posted on the Internet, the
sweeping privatization contract would put into private hands
numerous operations at Lackland.
</P>
<P>
   They include civil engineering services, communications, grounds
and building maintenance, logistics, operations support, personnel
mission support and supply services.
</P>
<P>
   Some computer support and aircraft maintenance also likely will
be part of the package, along with the possible operation of the
air control tower for the Kelly runway that soon will be shifted to
the control of the Lackland installation next door, DiLuzio said.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force will continue to conduct the basic training
operations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to looking for savings by inviting competitive bids
from private industry, the Air Force also is studying its own
operations at Lackland, aiming to cut costs through reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Its new plan, when completed, will be compared with the best
private proposal, which must be 10 percent lower than the Air Force
benchmark cost to be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   DiLuzio estimated the civilian jobs affected would include the
more than 1,000 positions now at Lackland, plus about 600 civilians
scheduled to transfer from Kelly to Lackland in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force declined to confirm that figure Thursday. Several
spokesmen said more time was needed before the information could be
released.
</P>
<P>
   DiLuzio said his company's experience at Kelly would be an
advantage in the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an established track record,'' he said. ``We will
treat people fairly in offering working conditions, salaries and
benefits. We must be more than sensitive in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Job losses are possible, whether Lackland is operated by private
contractors or by the Air Force under a new plan, DiLuzio said,
declining to guess the magnitude of the work-force reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The possible value of the contract would be between $80 million
and $100 million per year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
