 ART ADV.: Photos with ONLINE-ARTIST, AMAZON-EXCHANGE and
COACH-MAURICE, and a graphic with ONBUSINESS-COLUMN are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GROUND-TROOPS (Rinas, Albania) _ American GIs say it's just a
matter of time before ground troops are involved in Kosovo _ and
the clock is ticking. ``They're chomping at the bit,'' says one US
officer. By Susan Milligan. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   US-BRITAIN (United Nations) _ Once mocked as the ``little
poodle'' of American foreign policy, Britain is asserting
leadership from Kosovo to Libya. With mixed feelings, Washington
finds itself following London more often than not. By Colum Lynch.
1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   HONG-KONG (Hong Kong) _ In a place that has always been about
space, Hong Kong will soon be crowded with many more residents _ up
to 1.6 million Chinese, a judge has ruled. By Indira A.R.
Lakshmanan. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NRA-MEETING (Denver) _ A rare defensive crouch by the normally
aggressive NRA is the clearest sign that momentum has shifted, for
the moment, in the gun control debate. By Michell Zuckoff. 1800
words.
</P>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE-REBORN (Providence, R.I.) _ Providence was reborn,
with a new downtown, artists, even a hit TV show. Then this: A city
corruption scandal that had all the markings of the old Providence.
By Francie Latour and Judy Rakowsky. 870 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- The war in Yugoslavia has produced
some odd bedfellows. By David Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Americans are sick of guns. All we
need is a president who is dedicated to making a difference. By
Derrick Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- Rare-manuscript expert Kenneth Rendell
has never discussed his relationship with Bill Gates _ but he's
left plenty of hints lying around. By Alex Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-ARTIST (Quincy, Mass.) _ Onetime programmer Carmin
Karasic reinvents herself as an on-line artist. By Patti Hartigan.
(2 takes) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   TV-NOAH (Undated) _ Like ``people pleasers,'' ``Noah's Ark'' is
the kind of bland product that so desperately wants to be liked
that it ends stripped of any outstanding qualities. By Matthew
Gilbert. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-IDLE (Undated) _ Rodman Flender and his young lead, Devon
Sawa, bring all the energy and twice the gore to ``Idle Hands,''
their would-be horror goof, but only about half the material. By
Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-ENTRAPMENT (Undated) _ ``Entrapment'' is a silly
millennial heist movie that gets by on its high gloss and the star
power of Sean Connery and Catherine Zeta-Jones. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-NAUGHTY (Undated) _ Hip-pop trio Naughty by Nature gets a
little too nice. By cindy Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-ANGELS (Undated) _ Readers of ``We Band of Angels: The
Untold Story of American Nurses Trapped on Bataan by the Japanese''
cannot help being struck by an eerie deja vu. By Alison Bass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON-EXCHANGE (Boston) -- Stig Leschly still remembers the
rejection Harvard gave his business plan last year. This week he
got sweet revenge when Amazon.com said it will acquire his rare
book and print company for a reported $200 million. By Ronald
Rosenberg. 1120 words. PHOTO
</P>
