<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS HANDFUL OF STORES DOMINATE APPAREL MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICOTRIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you think clothes all look alike and the same
stores are on every corner, it's not your imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 companies control nearly half the clothing sales in the
United States, according to a report released Thursday by The NPD
Group, a market research firm based in Port Washington, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are ultimately going to say, if store A, store B and
store C are all the same, why should I go shopping?,'' NPD Vice
President Kathaleen Mercer said. ``We can't continue to have the
sameness we all feel is in the marketplace right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey, based on 1998 statistics, reports the following
retailers _ in order of sales generated _ lay claim to 47 percent
of the country's apparel sales: J.C. Penney; Wal-Mart Stores Inc.;
Dayton-Hudson Corp.; Kmart Corp.; May Co.; Federated Department
Stores Inc.; Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.; Limited Corp.; Dillard's Inc.;
and the Gap Inc. The report did not release dollar figures.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, The NPD Group found the top 10 retailers controlled 35
percent of industry sales. All of the retailers listed were the
same with the exception of Macy's, which was named separately
because it was not yet owned by Federated, and the Gap, which did
not make the list.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10's increased share of the market is being attributed
to the flurry of retail consolidations this decade.
Cincinnati-based Federated bought Macy's, Bloomingdale's and the
now defunct Emporium. May Co. and Robinson's merged in 1992. And
Dillard's recently purchased Mercantile Stores Co. Inc., giving it
a strong hold of the South and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, stores like Wal-Mart and Target, a division of
Dayton-Hudson, have expanded and become more focused on apparel.
The Gap has diversified, with such offerings as BabyGap and the Old
Navy Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you've got a couple of stores that have very wide
reaching presence, it's very easy for them to make things look the
same,'' Mercer said. ``On the other side, as these retailers are
consolidating and building muscle, maybe they'll take more risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Other retail consultants were not surprised by the results, nor
did they find them disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco retail consultant Helen Bulwik was surprised those
10 companies didn't control an even greater percentage of apparel
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only consolidation of ownership. There are more stores
now than there were in 1990,'' she said, adding that consumers have
more choices. ``We probably have a more diverse selection than we
had nine years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it good or bad for the people? It's pretty irrelevant,''
said George Rosenbaum, chief executive of Leo J. Shapiro &AMP;
Associates, a Chicago-based market research firm that studies
buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum said specialty stores and smaller retailers are
capitalizing on consumer boredom with department stores, creating a
vibrant market for those retailers. ``For the talented independent
retailer with a point of view, times have never been better,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
