<HEADLINE>
KRAFT NEVER WANTED TO LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Sending for Connecticut and all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The decision everyone is waiting for isn't much of a decision at
all. Robert Kraft wants to keep his Patriots in Foxborough, in a
sweeping turnabout that signifies so much that is good and bad
about a man who inspires such respect and revulsion.
</P>
<P>
   It's delicious to think there's a dramatic decision at hand, the
kind of storyline on which reporters and politicos in this city
have always thrived. But be clear: NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue,
an agent of the owners, would not have negotiated a stadium deal
with political leaders in Boston if Kraft didn't want him
negotiating that precise thing.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to Kraft say he never wanted to leave, not the day
he signed with tears in his eyes and Connecticut Governor John
Rowland at his side, not now that acrimony has blossomed into
action in Foxborough. Recall Globe sports scribe Michael Holley's
description of Kraft at that November signing: ``He looked like a
man who was worried about the rent.''
</P>
<P>
   One Kraft intimate says that soon _ possibly Sunday, more likely
later in May _ he will step before the cameras in that Everyman way
he sometimes has and announce that the team will stay where it has
always belonged: Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   He will talk again about how a part of him died when the Boston
Braves moved to Milwaukee in 1953. He will talk about how his
intention in buying the Patriots back in 1994 was to stop them from
leaving town, not to move them out himself. He will talk about how
Boston, not Hartford, is his home. Always has been. Now it always
will be.
</P>
<P>
   When he speaks, Kraft, a generous philanthropist, won't have to
mention the most astounding part of his decision _ that he'll forgo
$374 million of Connecticut's money to spend a couple of hundred
million of his own to build a new stadium in Foxborough. For this,
in the papers, on talk radio, all across this city, he will be
deified, hailed again as a hometown hero. Much of his sentiment is
true, the glory deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along,'' said one Kraft associate, ``it's not
about the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not. But Kraft's legion of detractors paint a less
flattering portrait, saying the only thing more important to him
than money is the adulation that accompanies his ownership of a
professional sports franchise. The press coverage, the fans, are
like a narcotic, driving him to seek ever more.
</P>
<P>
   In Foxborough, Kraft used to board a golf cart before games and
drive among the tailgaters, slapping their hands and accepting
their praise. He had glass doors installed in his box so he could
step outside and toss hats to fawning fans.
</P>
<P>
   In matters of business, he is said to be ruthless, an
opportunist slow to lend a helping hand unless his own interests
are at stake. He once lashed out at a well-known civic leader as
``nothing but an employee, and if you were my employee, you'd be
fired.'' He launched legal action against restaurateur and former
racetrack owner Charles Sarkis as Sarkis was recuperating from
brain surgery. Connecticut, critics say, is just his latest victim,
another in a long list of foils.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very, very deceptive, dishonest person, and you can
quote me on that,'' Sarkis said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   All of this may work out fine for Patriots fans. In Hartford,
Kraft will need to summon every whit of ruthlessness to renege on a
deal that has so emotionally revived a city in dire need of
revitalization, its fervor captured in a banner Hartford Courant
headline the day after the deal was penned: ``Touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   His love of adulation, at least in Boston, will also have to be
true to walk away from the most lucrative such offer in the history
of the NFL, courtesy of Connecticut, for the relatively paltry $70
million proposal in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But Kraft associates say the decision awaits only the details.
They are waiting for the Massachusetts Legislature to pass the bill
that will make the proposal a reality. They are gathering all their
escape options from Hartford. They are mulling the idea of letting
NFL owners reject the move at their May 25-26 meeting. Old-line
owners, unimpressed with stadium handouts in small cities and
reeling from teams abandoning Los Angeles and Houston, are focused
on television viewership and its resulting revenues in major
markets like Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would someone walk away from a $374 million publicly
financed deal to go build your own facility on your own dime?''
Governor Rowland asked earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   That's a seemingly straightforward question with a complicated
answer _ an answer embodied in the complex motives of the New
England Patriots owner, Robert Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
