<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Clique and double-clique _ reader
e-mail
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My column on the recent school massacre brought a number of
e-mail comments from readers, agreeing or disagreeing, that there's
no crueler society than school cliques.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some excerpts:
</P>
<P>
   From Patricia Thompson, hkt-pat(at)lcc.net:
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I, when we were in high school in the early
1950s, got along with most everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember any of us being mean and ugly to the outcasts
and nobodies. But at that time none of us had much money, and it
made us more equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised to be kind to everybody and most of us lived in a
two-parent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, parents have a hard time teaching morals when they
don't have any themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   From Sara Krone, Krone(at)tempest.coedu.usf.edu:
</P>
<P>
   ``Your article should be required reading for students in all
schools through the country. Besides the troublemakers being
counseled, the 'cliques' should be counseled also.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody can't be friends with everybody, but ridicule and
taunting should never be tolerated against those who are
'different.'''
</P>
<P>
   From Christine Daniels, CrickleD(at)aol.com:
</P>
<P>
   ``What you failed to mention was the cold, hard fact that it is
not just peers who shun the 'misfits.' Many teachers and coaches
are guilty of doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   From Shari Crabtree, ctree(at)goodnet.com:
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of the problem is how these young men felt about
themselves. The high school years are so difficult for young
people, especially if they are not in one of the popular cliques.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the schools are part of the problem when they glorify
the athletes and barely acknowledge the scholars.''
</P>
<P>
   From Kevin McGehee, mcgehee(at)mosquitonet.com, who writes
McGeHee's News &AMP; Comment from North Pole, Alaska:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, heck, if I had known that being on the outs with all the
cool high school cliques could excuse mass murder, God only knows
what I could have gotten away with.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only I had been in high school 20 years later than I was,
that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, everyone who was 'dissed' by the jocks or
cheerleaders or chess team or whatever in high school, please raise
your hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a turnout. How many of you have ever committed mass
murder? Anyone?''
</P>
<P>
   From James A. Aiken, jaiken(at)alaska.net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that you are correct that these groupings in high
school can have devastating effects on children and society. You
are incorrect when you say that this behavior is left behind when
we become adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year the state of Alaska passed an anti-gay rights
amendment. The religious right produced a very nasty campaign, with
lots of out-of-state money, which demonized gays and lesbians,
providing yet another clique on have's hurting the have-not's.''
</P>
<P>
   From Dave Deufel, Ld637535(at)aol.com:
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody, and I mean everybody, would show consideration
for a fellow human being, this tragedy would not have taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have war on drugs, war on tobacco and now it's time to have
a war on this type of prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, here's a note that's being passed along through the
Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ``To everyone that reads this:
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Jayson Martin from Littleton, Colo. I would like
everyone to please say a prayer for the safety and healing of
everyone who was involved in this terrible tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one we can all agree with.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail him at
jmurray(at)lcc.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
