<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERMITES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF TERMITES ARE MUNCHING ON YOUR HOME, DON'T PANIC _ BUT TAKE
ACTION NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How to spot 'em:
</P>
<P>
   If you are ever going to see a termite, now's the time. They
swarm in the spring, at dusk, usually after a rain.
</P>
<P>
   Often, termites are confused with flying ants. There's a
difference: Ants have a pinched or thin waist; termites have a
thick waist. An ant's antennae are bent; a termite's are straight.
Ants have eyes; termites don't. Both have two pairs of wings, but
for ants, the pair closest to the head is longer than the second
pair. The termites' two pairs of wings are equal in length.
</P>
<P>
   Both ants and subterranean termites (the type of termite we have
in this area) swarm at this time of year. The swarm is made up of
reproductives, young insects mature enough to mate, seeking to
start new colonies.
</P>
<P>
   A subterranean termite swarmer is 1/4 to 3/8 inch long, black to
pale yellow-brown, with pale to smoky-brown wings that cover the
body when the insect is not in flight.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you missed the dramatic swarming moment. Here are the
telltale signs that termites have arrived: Mud tunnels along the
foundation of the house. Buckling paint or tiny holes in wood.
Wings or sawdust near windows, doors or garage. (Termites lose
their wings after swarming, their little way of saying, ``We're
here, have fear.'')
</P>
<P>
   There are 45 species of termites. Three are quite common in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Subterranean termites: These are the most prevalent, causing 95
percent of all termite damage, and are found in every state except
Alaska. They nest in the ground and enter the house through mud
tunnels or cracks as small as 1/64 of an inch. Because they need
moisture to survive, they constantly travel between the home and
the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Drywood termites: Typically found in humid southern coastal
regions. They attack homes through the air and gain entrance
through any gap, no matter how tight. They live in the wood, not
the soil, and need very little moisture to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Formosan termites: First entered the United States in Houston in
1965 and have traveled north and east. They have been discovered in
Atlanta and a few instances as far north as Denton County. They
look and act like subterranean termites, but because their colonies
are twice as large, they can eat more wood and cause extensive
damage in a relatively short time.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   How to kill 'em:
</P>
<P>
   Call a professional exterminator. There is no other way to
safely rid your home of a termite infestation.
</P>
<P>
   The professional pest-control company may suggest one
eradication method or a combination of these applications:
</P>
<P>
   Baiting systems: Monitoring stations are placed in strategic
locations in the ground surrounding a home. If termite activity is
detected, the monitoring devices are transferred into a bait tube
that contains a pesticide called hexaflumuron.
</P>
<P>
   Hexaflumuron does not contaminate the environment because it
does not penetrate the surrounding earth. Termites feed on the bait
and return to the colony to feed the colony members. This method
may require several trips for installation and monitoring. Control
may take from a few weeks to more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sub-slab method: A special tool or tube is inserted through
holes drilled in the concrete slab. The pesticide is injected
through the tube into the soil beneath the slab. Holes drilled in
the slab should be no farther apart than 12 inches in order to form
a chemical barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Trenching: A 6- to 8-inch-wide strip, 10 inches deep, is
excavated in the soil adjacent to the outside foundation wall on
slab homes. Homes on pier and beam foundations are trenched by
excavating soil in an area 6 to 8 inches wide around all piers and
pipes and along foundation walls. All the soil that is returned to
the trench has been treated with termiticide.
</P>
<P>
   Rodding: Involves the use of a long rod with a special tip to
penetrate the soil. The rod of pesticide is usually inserted about
every 12 inches. Rodding alone is not recommended, because gaps in
the treatment zone will occur. Rodding combined with trenching is
the conventional technique. Orkin uses a combination of rodding,
trenching and baiting, says company spokeswoman Susan Kirkpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   Foam: This is used to apply termiticide to hard-to-reach places
such as chimney bases, dirt-filled porches and sub-slab areas. It
is a relatively new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Tenting: This method is used to treat drywood termites. Your
house is covered with what looks like a giant circus tent, the
corners are laced up tight and then the interior of the house is
fumigated. This effectively kills all the termites in the house
buts does nothing to control subsequent infestations. Once the tarp
is removed it can take from a few hours to overnight for the
fumigant to dissipate. The extermination company uses a monitoring
device to check that all pockets have dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   Heat: This method is for drywood termites as well. Heaters are
used to raise the interior wall temperature to 140 degrees. It
takes several hours, but the heat does kill the termites. Freezing
systems work in a similar fashion, but they are not approved in
Texas as the house has to stay at a freezing temperature for
several days.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Survival tips
</P>
<P>
   According to John Chapman, an entomologist with Terminix,
termite damage usually is not covered by homeowner insurance
policies. Check yours now.
</P>
<P>
   Those who live in brick or stone houses are not spared either.
There is a great deal of wood in all houses, and termites will
penetrate through hairline cracks in concrete and mortar to get at
that wood.
</P>
<P>
   If you learn that termites are attacking your home, do not
panic. Do not let any company rush you into termite control
services. A delay of a few weeks will not make any difference.
</P>
<P>
   Deal with licensed, certified professionals. Their contracts
must include this information: Licensed and Regulated by the
Structural Pest Control Board of Texas, 1106 Clayton Lane, Suite
100 LW, Austin, TX.
</P>
<P>
   This agency warns customers not to use companies that base
prices on gallonage of material used, profess to have a secret
formula, have no listed phone number or claim to be endorsed by
Texas A&AMP;M University or any other state agency.
</P>
<P>
   No company will give cost estimates over the phone as the
treatment plans can vary wildly depending on the kind and size of
the structure and the amount of infestation. Solicit bids from
several reputable companies before you choose one.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Brooks, executive director of the Texas Pest Control
Association, says Texans should know there is a required three-day
cooling-off period to protect consumers in any home solicitation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
