r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINISTRY-HARRINGTON-T     04-30 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINISTRY-HARRINGTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHAPLAIN OF BOURBON STREET' RETURNS TO PULPIT AFTER STRAYING FOR A
DECADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAIME JORDAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ As the founder of a storefront ministry on
New Orleans' Bourbon Street, the Rev. Bob Harrington made his name
ministering to pimps, prostitutes and gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry led to fame and fortune, interviews with
``Hustler'' magazine and Phil Donahue, and public debates with the
now-missing atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, the ``Chaplain of Bourbon Street'' had 46
religious albums and nine books to his credit.
</P>
<P>
   But with the notoriety and riches also came frolic, Harrington
said. And that frolic led to his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   He had an affair that ended his marriage, and he left Bourbon
Street to become a motivational speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his calling haunted him.
</P>
<P>
   He would drive for miles to avoid passing a church steeple. He
would cringe if someone called him ``Brother Bob.'' And at every
hotel he stayed in, he would hide the Gideon Bible in the
night-stand drawer.
</P>
<P>
   It was on one of these nights, while staying in a Los Angeles
hotel, that Harrington thought about killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   And it was on that night that he instead began to reverse his
decadelong absorption with worldly affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pride, arrogance, self-centeredness and stubborness became my
method for living,'' Harrington said. ``Satan tossed me a pass, and
I grabbed it and ran for defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 71, Harrington is making a comeback. He has left Bourbon
Street, but this time he hasn't left God.
</P>
<P>
   He has relocated his organization, The Chaplain, to an
unincorporated area near the Fort Worth suburb of Mansfield, where
he plans to help Texans overcome sin and return to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans say, `Don't mess with Texas.' Well, Texans are messing
with God,'' Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   Since he returned to the ministry in the early 1990s, Harrington
said, his listeners can see and feel the change in him. He spoke
alongside The Rev. Jerry Falwell and other evangelists recently at
a revival in Branson, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that people want to hear my story, because every
family has someone who my life can touch,'' he said. ``People want
to know those who've been through it. I don't recommend anybody go
through this, but it rings the bell of credibility. This man knows
what he's talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime admirer Evelyn Linton, who was converted under
Harrington's ministry, said she and her husband prayed that
Harrington would return to his calling.
</P>
<P>
   Linton, 75, and her husband were two of Harrington's most famous
converts. They were the owners of a successful strip club in the
1960s in San Antonio, but after praying with Harrington, they gave
their lives to Jesus and closed the club that same day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people doubted him,'' Linton said. ``So many
of the ministers fall, like Jim Bakker and Jimmy Swaggart.''
</P>
<P>
   But Linton and her husband continued to pray for Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``God used him for us,'' she said. ``I knew it was for real. It
wasn't fake at all. You don't give up millions of dollars for
play.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, Harrington married Texas native Becky Birdwell, 48.
</P>
<P>
   The two met 30 years ago at a revival where Harrington was
speaking. Birdwell Harrington said she may have fallen in love with
him then.
</P>
<P>
   She also watched his decline from afar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very concerned about him when he was away from his
calling, because I know he was very unhappy,'' she said. ``His
ministry meant a lot to me. I rededicated my life under his
ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   His new life with Birdwell Harrington is far removed from the
turmoil and scandal of his past.
</P>
<P>
   They live in the country, where Birdwell Harrington raises
miniature horses.
</P>
<P>
   Remnants of Harrington's career line the walls of his home
office. The platinum and gold albums hang on the wall alongside
framed book jackets and photos of Bourbon Street and jazz
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Birdwell Harrington teases her husband about his move to the
country.
</P>
<P>
   While stroking her pet potbellied pig, Birdwell Harrington
shared a new joke between the couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Bourbon Street to the farm, now you can tell people you
are really `out standing in your field,' '' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
