A9635 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-STENCILING-TEX     04-30 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STENCILING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXI-STENCIL ART: ENAMEL WARE IS A FORGIVING PROJECT FOR BEGINNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stenciling is a very easy craft, if you have a good stencil.
Simone Smart's book not only explains stenciling methods in
thorough detail, but also includes 40 stencils. She shows how to
use them on floors, fabric, walls and tableware.
</P>
<P>
   Smart recommends enamel plates and bowls _ the kind you find at
camping stores _ as excellent first projects. ``They are
inexpensive; any slight chips that they accumulate add to their
charm; and, more importantly, as paints dry relatively slowly on
enamel, any mistakes can be wiped off.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you need to stencil enamel ware.
</P>
<P>
   Materials:
</P>
<P>
   Item to be stenciled
</P>
<P>
   Stencil
</P>
<P>
   Heavy paper
</P>
<P>
   Spray paint appropriate for metal (read manufacturers' warnings)
</P>
<P>
   Spray adhesive
</P>
<P>
   Masking tape
</P>
<P>
   Brown craft paper, or newspaper
</P>
<P>
   Drop cloths
</P>
<P>
   Baffle (A piece of stencil board or cardboard, folded into a
V-shape for easy handling. It is used for deflecting and softening
a jet of spray paint, or for protecting parts of the stencil from
the jet.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1. Practice stenciling before decorating your chosen surface.
Rolls of heavy paper provide an excellent surface to practice on.
</P>
<P>
   2. Make sure the surface to be stenciled is clean, dry and free
from dust. Smooth metal needs to be rubbed with steel wool so paint
can adhere.
</P>
<P>
   3. Spray the reverse side of your stencil with adhesive and
stick it firmly to the surface. If you are stenciling a rounded
surface, secure the stencil with pieces of masking tape as well as
adhesive. Protect the area surrounding your stencil with brown
craft paper, or newspaper, taped in place. Protect the floor with
drop cloths.
</P>
<P>
   4. For simple two-color designs, use masking tape to shield the
different areas of the stencil.
</P>
<P>
   5. Shake the can of spray paint for up to a minute, even longer
if the weather is cold. Test the spray on a piece of scrap paper to
make sure the paint is spraying smoothly and that you have the
right color.
</P>
<P>
   6. Hold the can about 10 inches away from stencil. Position the
baffle halfway between the paint and the stencil. Spray in short
bursts, of less than a second, directed at the top of the baffle,
and moving the can away from you. The baffle takes the first strong
hit of color and the trailing-off goes on the stencil. This will
take a bit of practice to get right.
</P>
<P>
   7. Try to spray two or three light coats of paint rather than
one heavy coat. A heavy spray is more likely to seep under the
stencil.
</P>
<P>
   As you effectively spray the baffle and not the stencil, the
baffle can become drenched with paint. If you are not careful, this
can drip onto your stencil. Replace the baffle or cut off the
soaked corner.
</P>
<P>
   8. Once your stencil painting is dry, it can be baked in the
oven to become dishwasher-proof. Follow the manufacturers'
instructions for baking.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Stencil Book'' by Simone Smart (Firefly, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
