</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAIN TEEN'S FAITH INSPIRES OTHERS AFTER LITTLETON TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cassie Bernall was asked if she believed in God. She said yes.
Then she was shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 17-year-old, one of the victims of the Columbine High
School horror in Littleton, Colo., is inspiring others nationwide
to stand up for their faith.
</P>
<P>
   Word about her confession of faith in the face of death is
spreading. Young people in Fort Worth praised her during a
discussion last weekend at Travis Avenue Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   One youth lauded Bernall and wondered whether he would have had
the courage to profess his faith in a similar potentially deadly
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered the same thing about myself,'' said Bob Ellis, a
spokesman at the West Bowles Community Church in Littleton, where
Bernall was active in the youth group. ``We all wish we would have
that kind of courage. But we will never know until someone is
pointing the muzzle of a gun at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said his church has been getting calls from around the
country praising Bernall's bravery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of her witness, it is causing many people to inquire
what this God is all about,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-six members of West Bowles Community Church's youth group
were in Columbine High School when the shootings and bombings
occurred. But only Bernall was killed.
</P>
<P>
   She was known for carrying a Bible to school and had given a
Christian testimony in church the Sunday before she was killed,
Ellis said. A videotape of the testimony was played at her funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the slayings may have been random, many believe
that Christians, athletes and ethnic minorities were targeted by
the gunmen, who were known to be fascinated by Nazism.
</P>
<P>
   One of those killed, Isaiah Shoels, 18, was an African-American
and an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Another, Rachel Scott, 17, also was a devout Christian who often
spoke of becoming a missionary. The Rev. Barry Palfer, senior
associate pastor of the Orchard Road Christian Center where she
attended, believes she also was killed for her faith.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Bernall was with other students in the library
when the gunmen walked in and sought her out. They asked her if she
believed in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said `Yes,' and those were her final words,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernall's parents issued a statement saying their daughter was
in God's hands. They said they were not surprised by their
daughter's actions in light of her strong commitment to her faith.
</P>
<P>
   Youth evangelist Josh McDowell mentioned Bernall's uncommon
courage when he spoke to more than 70,000 teen-agers at a youth
conference in Detroit last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere I go, I'm hearing about Cassie,'' McDowell said in
an interview after the conference, sponsored by Teen Mania
Ministries in Garden Valley, Texas. ``She is a true martyr for her
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell, a Dallas-based staff member of Campus Crusade for
Christ, said the deaths of the young Christians may end up having a
major impact in encouraging other young people to take God
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   He devoted one of the Detroit conference presentations to the
Littleton killings, asserting that one of its causes was the
emotional turmoil of today's young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just underneath the surface of most teen-agers _ including
church kids _ is a raging anger,'' McDowell said. Parents,
especially fathers, must show more love and attention to their
children, he said.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell said the young Christians killed in Littleton will be
missed by their friends and loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``But their deaths may end up doing a world of good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
