<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS SHOULD FIRE STERN FOR CRUDE REMARKS AFTER LITTLETON TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a supermarket in Englewood, Colo., last week, a woman waiting
in line to pay for her groceries suddenly started to cry. Soon,
others at the checkout counter began to tear up as well. This is
what life is like after Littleton. Routine errands can be
transformed by raw emotion.
</P>
<P>
   At around the same time, radio personality Howard Stern had this
to say about the Columbine High School massacre: ``A bunch of
good-looking girls go to that school. There were, like, really
good-looking girls running out of there with their hands over their
heads. Did those kids try to have sex with any of the good-looking
girls? They didn't even do that. At least if you're going to kill
yourself and kill all the kids, why wouldn't you have some sex?''
</P>
<P>
   There's a difference between freedom and license. No one denies
Stern's right to say these things. It is the law of the land that
he can say whatever he might. But if he said these things in your
home, or anyone else's home, or in the homes of the families and
friends of the massacre victims, he would be asked to leave and
never come back.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he did say these things in homes all across the Denver
area and, indeed, all across America, over the airwaves of the
Infinity Radio Network. He did so as Infinity's most highly valued
entertainment asset. And he did so as a de facto employee of CBS.
Infinity is 82-percent-owned by CBS, once known as the Tiffany's of
broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was immediate. The Rocky Mountain News called on
Colorado-based broadcast outlets to drop Stern's radio and TV
programs. The Colorado state Legislature passed a resolution
seconding this idea and demanding that Stern be censured for his
remarks. Disc jockeys on competing radio stations called for
Denver-area businesses to cease advertising on Stern's show and
called on the shock-jock to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   There was no apology. There was instead the usual complaint that
Stern's comments had been ``taken out of context.'' Stern himself
denied that his comments had been insensitive and attributed the
backlash to basic broadcast economics. ``We're getting ratings and
starting to get attention,'' he said, implying that the controversy
should be understood as a tactical thrust in the ceaseless battle
for market share.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Stern expressed no remorse and tendered no apology
was hardly surprising. He has made a career of bad taste and
offensive behavior. His radio and television programs are devoted
to it on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   What was surprising was that not one person from CBS said or did
anything to rebuke or even reprimand Stern.
</P>
<P>
   CBS President and CEO Mel Karmazin, who has shepherded Stern's
radio career, had no public comment. Leslie Moonves, the president
of the CBS Entertainment Group, had no public comment. And not one
single member of the CBS board of directors said one word about the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   This might be acceptable if Stern was just another deejay
looking for a headline. But he is not. He is, in fact, CBS's most
highly compensated ``talent.'' According to Brill's Content
magazine, Stern is paid almost $14 million a year for his services.
And he is a money machine for the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Howard Stern Show'' generates enormous revenues. He
delivers millions of dollars to Infinity's bottom line. As a
result, Infinity is beating Wall Street's expectations. Wednesday,
the company reported that its first-quarter net income rose 55
percent on exceptionally strong sales of advertising on its radio
stations and billboard properties.
</P>
<P>
   The company is now is looking for ways to increase the show's
audience. It is eyeballing deals with Internet companies to augment
its distribution. Among those who will approve the final decision
to amplify Stern's voice are members of the CBS board of directors.
They include Westinghouse Electric Corp. chairman Michael Jordan,
Bell Atlantic chairman Ray Smith, former Philadelphia congressman
William Gray, who now serves as the head of the United Negro
College Fund, former Secretary of Defense Frank Carlucci, and Aspen
Institute Chairman David McLaughlin. All of them have had
distinguished careers in their chosen professions and, by all
accounts, are fine people.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether these fine people will continue, by
their silence, to sanction Stern's conduct and whether, by their
consent, they will seek to expand Stern's reach. It is a question
of some moment.
</P>
<P>
   The country is at a crossroads. Either we begin to rebuild a
civil society or we don't. There is nothing we can do to bring back
those children killed in Littleton. But there are things that can
be done to make life in this country better.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is to put an end to a media culture that rewards
unacceptable conduct and encourages antisocial behavior. A good
place to start would be the dismissal of Howard Stern from the
employ of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
