<SLUG> BC-PROSTITUTES-CRIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SQUAD TARGETS CRIMES AGAINST PROSTITUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Police Department has created
an investigative team to deal exclusively with crimes against
prostitutes, whose illicit activity makes them easy prey for
thieves and assailants.
</P>
<P>
   The Crimes Against Prostitutes unit is designed to focus on
violent predators who attack prostitutes, dealers who supply them
with drugs and pimps who force them to stay on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Fred Lau said the new investigative unit did not
mean that the department condones prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prostitution is still illegal in San Francisco but we're
trying something different,'' Lau said. ``We're looking at the
picture and we see a group of women who are often victims of
violent crime ... That's something we will not tolerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lau said prostitution is a more complex problem than rounding up
street hookers every night. Deputy Chief Richard Holder, who
oversees the new unit, said getting women out of prostitution is a
social service task that the police can't do alone. There are women
who have been arrested 20, 30, even 50 times for prostitution or
related crimes, but still find their way back to the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to just look at this from a very narrow law
enforcement perspective,'' Holder said. ``What we've realized is
that we can't just make more arrests and think that will solve any
of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Lau said prostitutes are entitled to the same level of police
service as anyone else in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a form of community policing for a very vulnerable part
of the community,'' Lau said. ``If someone is sexually assaulting
any woman in San Francisco, it's a crime that we want to stop. It
doesn't matter if she's wealthy or living on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the sex workers and some prostitutes themselves
said they approve of the new unit but remain wary of the police.
</P>
<P>
   Gina, a self-described prostitute who would not give her real
name, said she welcomed concerns for safety. ``But I've been
hassled by cops so much. I mean, do they really care what happens
to me?''
</P>
<P>
   A criminologist who has studied serial killers and their
penchant for murdering street prostitutes said many of the women
don't report crimes against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an incredibly high-risk victim group,'' said Professor
Michael Rustigan of San Francisco State University. ``Street
prostitutes are the favorite victims of serial killers. These are
among the most vulnerable people in our society. They get raped
often. They get robbed often. The incidence of crimes against
prostitutes is huge. When one is found dead, I believe that is just
the small tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violent predators know that these women are not likely to
report crimes to police and if they do talk to police, they might
not be believed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The police unit was started on an experimental basis in December
and was unveiled this week. Since its inception, the Crimes Against
Prostitutes unit has investigated 24 cases, including several in
which women were kidnapped, assaulted, raped and beaten.
</P>
<P>
   So far, nine of the investigations have resulted in arrests and
several are still open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
