<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOP-ZETA-JONES-ART-$     04-30 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOP-ZETA-JONES-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZORRO'S GIRL OUTGROWS HER PETTICOATS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Neverrr trusht a naked woman,'' Sean Connery
counsels in his sibilant Scottish burr in ``Entrapment,'' the new
thriller about two thieves chasing the ultimate heist.
(italics)Eshpeshally,(end italics) he might have added, when the
woman is Catherine Zeta-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Connery's co-star, foil and _ inevitably _ love interest in the
movie has a way of parting men from their right minds.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's ``Mask of Zorro,'' Antonio Banderas disrobed her
with a few deft strokes of his sword, maddened by her fiery fencing
skills. Her May cover for Details magazine is a wet
head-and-shoulders shot designed to drive male readers to
heavy-breathing distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Much is suggested, but nothing revealed in Ms. Zeta-Jones's
steamy scenes on screen and in print. Just as well. Hollywood's
priorities have changed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   How an actress looks out of her clothes has become less
important than how glamorous she looks in them. There is the
head-to-heel scrutiny in the celebrity glossies.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar runway. The endless talk shows and commensurate
wardrobe calibrations. What to wear seems to have become almost as
important a question for a rising star as her choices in parts and
the men she is seen with.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Ms. Zeta-Jones, 29, rifled through the
closets in her suite at the St. Regis last Tuesday morning, at the
beginning of a publicity parade that will take her to Los Angeles,
Cannes, Madrid, Rio de Janeiro, Sao Paulo and Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   She had just flown in from Scotland the night before with her
brother, a publicity agent, and two trunks in tow that looked like
they might have needed their own plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do love clothes,'' Ms. Zeta-Jones said. Normally, she said,
she just takes a carry-on: ``I'd just roll up a few essentials,
throw in a few books and I'm off.''
</P>
<P>
   But you don't just roll up the wine-colored Dolce &AMP; Gabbana
dress she was wearing with strappy Gucci heels and double-decker
diamond earrings on loan from Fred Leighton. It was just one of
several interview get-ups she would change into and out of that
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This I'm going to wear on MTV today, with a little black tank
top,'' she said, plucking from the bedroom armoire a bright blue
floral print skirt by Christian Lacroix, and tossing it on the bed.
</P>
<P>
   For ``CBS This Morning,'' she said she was thinking cashmere.
``You don't want a figure-hugging thing on a breakfast show,'' she
said. In the end, though, she ended up wearing a figure-hugging
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana floral top and tight skirt on the show. (``I'm
going to tell you something you've probably never heard before,''
said Mark McEwan, her interviewer on the show. ``You're a very
beautiful woman.'')
</P>
<P>
   She started opening the drawers of the armoire. ``That's my
underwear drawer,'' she said. ``You don't need to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides having studied ballet, tap dancing, acting and judo, Ms.
Zeta-Jones is well schooled in the art of flirtation.
</P>
<P>
   Striding around the suite, her dress clinging like a second skin
(make that a first skin), she tossed her long black hair around and
exclaimed, ``Love that!'' in her strong Welsh accent. ``Zorro'' had
half the Spanish-speaking world thinking Ms. Zeta-Jones was one of
them. She isn't, though she does find similarities between her
``volatile'' Celtic temper and the Latin temperament.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion show continued. She laid out a clingy hippie
ensemble in crocheted cotton from Christian Lacroix for ``The Rosie
O'Donnell Show'' the following morning. ``I thought I'd give Rosie
a little shimmy-shimmy,'' she said, demonstrating. But the piece de
shimmy was her dress for ``The Tonight Show,'' where she was booked
on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cut to Jay Leno,'' she said, brandishing a long, burgundy
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana corset dress. ``It looks like underwear off the
hanger, but it's wonderful on.''
</P>
<P>
   Constrictive costumes are a trademark for Ms. Zeta-Jones, a
period piece veteran. She was first noticed at 19 in an overheated
television drama called ``Darling Buds of May,'' set in England in
the 1950s, which put her in ``pointy bras, big skirts and
petticoats,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Her stardom was confirmed when the British tabloids began
rummaging through her garbage for embarrassing dirt. A 1994
adaptation of Thomas Hardy's ``Return of the Native'' on CBS got
her a New York agent. Two years later, Steven Spielberg watched her
survive the CBS ``Titanic'' miniseries and placed her in his
production of ``Zorro.''
</P>
<P>
   Between ``Zorro'' and ``Entrapment,'' her most notable
appearance was as a presenter at this year's Academy Awards. Her
red strapless Versace gown met with approval from the fashion
gantlet. She has an ``affiliation'' with Versace, she said, but
relies on her personal stylist to find her clothes from other
designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wear anything just because it's hip or trendy,'' she
said. ``I need structure. I don't like flimsy things.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is she the kind of actress who slobs around in jeans and
sweats so people will think she's down-to-earth. ``I feel very
uncomfortable in jeans,'' she said. Her father, who owned a candy
factory in the Welsh town of Swansea always wore a suit and tie for
dinner. Boyfriends are expected to measure up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of them have dressed really well,'' she said.
``One didn't, and I thought I could change that, but of course you
never can.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Ms. Zeta-Jones itemize her wardrobe, you feel yourself
in the presence of a pro, a clothes race horse. ``I do think it's
important to try and get it together,'' she said. ``If people are
going to send you these things, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Like many beautiful women, she professes not to be. ``I've got a
broken nose,'' she said (from a childhood misadventure).
``Freckles. I have broken capillaries around my eyes, and my neck's
funny from an operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many women with amazing bodies, she professes not to work
out. ``Not much,'' she said. ``I walk fast. And from my dancer
days, I'm always flexing my muscles.'' During the interview, she
ate two chocolates and boasted that she had pancakes for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   As a photographer was about to start snapping her portrait, Ms.
Zeta-Jones's brother, Lyndon, told her that the host of a British
television show, Jill Dando, had been murdered the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew her,'' Ms. Zeta-Jones said, covering her mouth in
shock. ``How awful.'' Almost as abruptly, she snapped herself out
of it. ``Anyway, let's think about that in a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   She grabbed a springy Dolce &AMP; Gabbana dress and held it tightly
against her torso. ``I'm in my van Gogh period,'' she said. ``Ever
since I saw him in L.A., life has been more interesting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
