<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-EVANGELISM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANKLIN GRAHAM SEES A GENERATION `RAISED ON BLOOD' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Colo.)  (mk) 
 By KATHERINE LEE and MATTHEW MILLER   
 Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ Franklin Graham, son of evangelist Billy
Graham and a prominent evangelist in his own right, is making
Tuscaloosa the site of his only U.S. festival this year. The free
event at the University of Alabama's Coleman Coliseum began Friday
and ends Sunday. It is expected to draw at least 15,000 people on
each of the three days.
</P>
<P>
   Graham arrives here fresh from two places that have been much in
the news: Kosovo and Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is a very sad place,'' Graham said, relaxing with
peanuts and a Diet Coke in a hotel Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hundreds of thousands of people who have literally
had to flee within a minute's notice. Some have walked nine or 10
days. They've had to eat grass, tree bark, anything for
nourishment. They've lost loved ones. Their families have been
raped or killed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to question the president,'' Graham said, ``but
to what extent do we get involved? Is America the policeman of the
world? Why Kosovo and not Africa?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes that the bombing campaign will open up a
long military involvement in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the bombing stops tonight, it will be weeks before
anyone goes home,'' he said. ``There are landmines, booby traps.
There'll be problems for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Graham spoke last Sunday at the memorial service
for the students and teacher killed at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., and appeared on MSNBC Wednesday night with Vice
President Al Gore for a video town meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, an avid hunter, owns guns and has taught his own
children how to use them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns are a problem, but they are not the issue,'' he said. He
puts the blame squarely on violent films and video games, which he
says push children to expect ever bloodier entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is violence,'' he said. ``Where are we getting the
anger and hatred? How are we becoming desensitized to violence?''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, the father of four, said he has a device on his
television that blocks out anything more graphic than PG-13 films.
But he said such measures alone won't solve the larger problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are learning these behaviors,'' he said. ``They think
in order to be entertained, someone has to be raped. Someone has to
be beaten up. Someone has to be shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see much hope for this country. We're going to see
more police in schools. We're seeing a generation of children
raised on blood.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggests a sin tax on violence similar to the taxes already
levied on cigarettes and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit them in the pocketbook,'' he said. ``Make people pay at
the box office. If they pay $10 for a ticket and another $8 fine,
they may decide it may not be worth it. And let the money go to the
victims of crime. Put it back into society.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Tuscaloosa, Ala., News is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
