<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9683 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-ELECTION-     04-30 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ELECTION' BRINGS HIGH SCHOOL POLITICS TO THE CINEMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the many vividly evocative truths to surface in ``Election,''
Alexander Payne's disarming, dead-on second film, the one that
gives the most pause comes during the student body candidates'
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Metzler (Jessica Campbell), school weirdo and darkhorse
presidential candidate, uses her floor time to tell Carver High's
adolescent electorate that the contest is more or less only about
the candidate's egos and putting a victory on their college
application.
</P>
<P>
   They should vote for her: She doesn't want to go to college.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, her sentiments earn her the deafening gymnasium-wide
approval of her peers and the contempt of her two competitors, one
of whom is Paul (Chris Klein), her popular ex-football player
brother, the other is a heat-seeking success monger named Tracy
Flick (Reese Witherspoon).
</P>
<P>
   Tammy's observant truth is recognizable to anyone who's had to
suffer through a student government campaign in which the only
people who really cared about the election were the handful of
candidates and that one overworked teacher responsible for
organizing it.
</P>
<P>
   Rare was that kid who seemed to truly believe in the power of
student government. For most of us, the high school election didn't
seem to make sense because it was a public, organized campaign of
the politics of popularity that high school was all about. The
president never presided and the government never ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The film's droll touch is that Tammy only entered the race to
get back at the girl who broke her heart by dating Paul. She's as
wrong as she is right. With ``Election,'' Payne announces himself
as one of the keenest purveyors of the scattered pieces that once
was an American morality.
</P>
<P>
   For him, absolute good is as mythical and mythologized as
absolute bad. And he wades though the vast gray area in between
with aplomb, sagacity and a bracing lack of presumption, tempered
with unbridled suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   In his first film, the unlikely dark comedy ``Citizen Ruth,''
Payne moves a pregnant Laura Dern between fervent pro-life and
pro-choice factions for her benefit. Ruth Stoops was trash _ wily,
conflicted, survivalist, but she had the integrity of a loaded
garbage bag. But like the extremists who used her first, she was
fundamentally decent.
</P>
<P>
   So are the folks powerwalking through ``Election,'' whose
setting has made the clever move from the New Jersey of Tom
Perrotta's '98 novel to Payne's native Omaha, also the home of
Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, who wrote both his films with Jim Taylor, does a lot of
snooping around trash receptacles in ``Election'' as if that's
where the answers to life's mysteries had been thrown and only
Payne had the good sense to dig through them.
</P>
<P>
   The garbage is not where we meet Jim McAllister _ the history
and civics teacher and school council supervisor _ played by
Matthew Broderick in his most layered and resonant film stint that
puts him on the receiving end of the misery his Ferris Bueller
wrought principal Ed Rooney. But, slowly, he's drawn into it by
Tracy, a buzzing fly-trap of determined overachievement.
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious to the point of dementia, so driven she could run you
off the road of life, Tracy looks to be that extracurricular
zealot, simultaneously poised and out of control. As far as she's
concerned, the Carver High student body presidency is her divine
right. Her schoolmates agree: She's running uncontested.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. McAllister _ or ``Mr. M'' as he's greeted and addressed by
his students _ is put off by her bumper-sticker self-assurance and
the secret knowledge that she had a career-ending affair with his
best friend Mr. Novotny (Mark Harelik), the math teacher.
</P>
<P>
   So he recruits Paul the injured quarterback to run against her.
Tracy's flummoxed but more driven than ever. Then Tammy's 11th-hour
run sends everybody reeling and kicks the mayhem into ``Election.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, high school has become a marketplace for teenagers to
buy identities and show them off. In the movies, it's a glossy,
hormonal amusement park as superficially hodgepodge as a
refrigerator magnet. In the news, it's a bloodbath of nightmarish
proportions in which the faces, personalities and backstories are
lost in the sensationalist headlining of disaster.
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's many beauties is the graininess that gives the
classrooms and corridors the homemade quality missing from
distressingly overproduced TV cover stories and the new teen flick
of the week, as well as the cornfed American nuance disappeared
from a farce like ``Fargo.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the usually sexed-up or underused Witherspoon is born-again
as an actress of fierce, head-turning revelation in a
hell-for-leather funny incarnation of snappy drive that finally
releases her from the remuda of her pony-actress peers.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's satire has given her and Broderick a bizarro
Humbert-Lolita antagonism in which Tracy sexlessly goads Mr. M,
who's having his own problems at home, to derail her train.
</P>
<P>
   It obsesses him to the point of blindness. It's among the
shrewdly observed relationships that elevates ``Election'' to the
level of quotidian sublime even if Payne has to climb through the
trash to get there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
