</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-SMOKING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER TOUGH LAW, THOUSANDS OF KIDS FIND OUT THAT SMOKING IS
ILLEGAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Kristin Sullens was busted by a security
guard at The Parks mall in Arlington just as she stepped outside
and lit up.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco she smokes is not illegal, per se, but she is 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never crossed my mind that I might be arrested for smoking
a regular ol' cigarette outside the mall, on the way to the car,''
Kristin said.
</P>
<P>
   Even kids who can recite all the health risks are not always
aware that they are breaking the law when they light up cigarettes
or pop a pinch between their cheeks and gums.
</P>
<P>
   Under tough new Texas legislation, kids caught smoking can be
arrested, fined up to $250 and sentenced to an eight-hour tobacco
awareness course or to eight to 12 hours of community service. They
can also have their drivers' licenses suspended for up to six
months _ if they're old enough to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Since the law went into effect in January 1998, nearly 3,500
minors have been sentenced to awareness programs, 160 have had
their licenses suspended and hundreds of others have paid fines and
completed community service.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin can't remember how old she was when she started smoking.
She was smoking about a pack-and-a-half a day when she was busted
last month. She was given a $100 fine, which she avoided by
attending a tobacco awareness program instead. (The program cost
her $50.)
</P>
<P>
   She has since cut down to 10 cigarettes a day and is trying to
smoke even less. ``I'm tired of my clothes stinking, and my breath
_ and cigarettes are expensive,'' she said as she finished filling
in her workbook during the final session of her awareness program.
</P>
<P>
   The tough new law is part of a comprehensive approach to
reducing children's access to tobacco products. Senate Bill 55 also
restricts vending machines and outdoor advertising and prohibits
giving free samples or coupons to anyone under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Underage smokers say the new law is ``crazy'' or ``ridiculous''
and isn't going to stop anyone from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Harriett _ ``with two T's'' _ who asked that her last name not
be used, was busted for possession of tobacco after police officers
spotted a pack of cigarettes in her car, parked at a high school in
Richardson. ``I had heard from friends that they could bust you now
for possession of tobacco, but I couldn't believe they would really
do it,'' the 17-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
   She was a little put out that she couldn't just pay her $125
fine rather than attend a tobacco awareness program, which cost her
$50 plus eight hours of her time, in order to keep from losing her
driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, the fine may be dismissed, except in cases of
repeated offenses, upon completion of an educational program or
community service. Failure to attend the program or do the service
may result in suspension of the minor's driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very weird. If you get caught smoking dope, you can just
pay a fine, but if you get caught smoking a cigarette, you have to
go through a program like this. It's like they consider cigarette
smoking worse,'' says Harriett.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls smoking her first cigarette at age 11. ``Of course I
want to quit,'' she says. ``Who wants to look old and wrinkled? I
know all the health risks. My grandmother died of emphysema, and I
can remember her lots of times disconnecting her oxygen tank and
going into another room to smoke a cigarette so it wouldn't blow up
or start a fire or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Harriett has tried hypnosis, acupuncture, nicotine gum and
patches _ ``nothing has worked so far.''
</P>
<P>
   She received a second citation for underage smoking just three
days before starting her tobacco awareness class.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING AWARENESS CLASS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Petty is one of about 230 state-certified tobacco
educators in North Texas. The educators are volunteers, many of
them counselors or teachers, who undergo a two-day state-sponsored
program to become certified. They are paid with the fees they
assess for tobacco awareness programs ($35 to $60).
</P>
<P>
   ``Classes are set up to help the kids figure out what's driving
them to use tobacco _ what role the media is playing, what it's
costing them today,'' Petty says. ``One of the main things I try to
do is get them to think, to figure out for themselves why they
smoke and whether or not it's worth the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get them to think about how tobacco makes their breath smell
bad and their teeth yellow and how expensive it is _ cigarettes
cost $3 a pack. I try to get them to think about what all they
could buy with all those $3 packs they are smoking,'' Petty says.
``They aren't worried about getting heart disease in 50 years, but
they are concerned about bad teeth, bad smell and wrinkles.''
</P>
<P>
   He conducts smoking awareness sessions in the employee training
room at the Kroger food store at Loop 820 and U.S. 80 in far
southwest Fort Worth, where the manager decided tobacco education
is a worthy cause and donated the space.
</P>
<P>
   The training room is also where the store's salesclerks are
taught about the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Any store clerk who sells tobacco to a minor commits a Class C
misdemeanor. Tobacco retailers are required to verify the age of
purchasers who look younger than 27. Fines for selling to minors
start at $500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids think the new law is aimed at them, but it comes down on
the retailers heavier than on the kids,'' says Barry Sharp with the
state Office of Tobacco Prevention in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get it out to the community that it is
against the law for minors to purchase, possess or use tobacco,''
says Rhonda Sweeney of the Texas Department of Health's regional
Office of Tobacco Prevention in Arlington. ``We know children are
experimenting with it younger and younger. When we have the
opportunity, we like to start at the kindergarten level, teaching
them about the damage it can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Texas Youth Tobacco Survey found that by sixth grade,
27 percent of public-school kids are already using tobacco. This
suggests that prevention efforts need to start earlier than grade
six, say state health officials. They hope to use part of the
mammoth $17.3 billion settlement from the state's lawsuit against
the nation's largest tobacco companies to expand prevention
efforts. But none of the settlement money has been allocated _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PUFF BABIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a much higher prevalence of smoking among children in
Texas than there is among adults.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they are in sixth grade, 27 percent of public-school
children say they use tobacco, according to the 1998 Texas Youth
Tobacco Survey. Eighteen percent of the sixth-graders _ most of
whom are 11 or 12 years old _ smoke cigarettes, while 5 percent use
smokeless tobacco and 12 percent smoke cigars.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they reach eighth grade, 36 percent say they have
used a tobacco product in the past 30 days. By high school, it
rises to 43 percent _ 51 percent among boys, 35 percent among
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Among Texas adults, 22 percent report using cigarettes, and 9
percent report smoking cigars.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
