<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9688 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-PUNK-HNS &LR;      04-30 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PUNK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SLC PUNK' GOES BACK TO THE GOOD OLD PUNK DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before floundering white boys turned to hip-hop as their muse
for rebellion, punk was their preferred lifestyle. Then it became
suburbanized, the subject of magazine cover stories and mainstream
fashion statements.
</P>
<P>
   The punks were disgruntled: Suddenly kids with Union Jack tees
and Mohawks were riding the escalator in the local galleria.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1985, and guys like Stevo (Matthew Lillard) of ``SLC
Punk!'' have all but had it with the commercial dilution of punk's
squalid grandeur. So what's he doing soapboxing near the
information kiosk in a Salt Lake City mall?
</P>
<P>
   He delivers an impassioned, intermittently funny soliloquy into
a low-angled camera. He's fired up, but neither Stevo nor the film
acknowledges that he's ranting from within the bastion of his
contempt. You can imagine our punk hero-preacher heading to the
Orange Julius to rinse out the post-sermon cottonmouth.
</P>
<P>
   But such is James Merendino's muddled, vexing, ultimately
engaging comic lament to the passing of a great, lost era in
American indie life. ``SLC Punk'' is part satiric essay and part
sobering drama that's often tidier, jokier and more childish than
the furious umbrage and fond nostalgia conjured by the film's title
sequence, which features a barrage of ska, punk and reggae album
covers.
</P>
<P>
   Merendino flirts with inefficacy in too many trite scenes of
us-vs.-them grandstanding and Lillard monkeyshining into the
camera. Though, Stevo allows Lillard, alas, to break on through to
the other side of his Jim Carrey-on-a-surfboard persona.
</P>
<P>
   Things begin in a reckless flurry of character intros,
exuberantly rendered anecdotes and the explanation of the social
hierarchy. Then, through both conceit and wimpiness, the movie
proceeds to wear out its welcome. Steve could leave his Salt Lake
City environs and go to Harvard law school like his unctuously
well-meaning dad (hugely funny Chris MacDonald). But he refuses to
sell out the way his former hippie parents did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sell out,'' his dad corrects. ``I bought in.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter; Stevo's not having it. Instead, he'd rather
hang with his best friend, ``Heroin'' Bob (Michael Goorjian) _ a
kid whose fear of needles keeps him doing the drug after which he's
nicknamed.
</P>
<P>
   Stevo is insouciant in an explosive, Matthew Lillard way that
gives Goorjian's pensive, searching expressions the complexity of a
Rubik's cube. He's what you keep your eyes on when Merendino's
storytelling bogs down.
</P>
<P>
   ``SLC Punk!'' doesn't get to where it seems to be heading until
Stevo and Bob drive to Wyoming with a guy named Eddie (Adam Pascal)
to buy beer. Merendino films the trip in exterior shots from the
American Western road. The moment is flashed with a momentary
brilliance and legitimate energy as they mount a rousing
retaliation against the liquor store clerk and its patrons, who
ridicule their weirdness.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of the three guys racing through the arid landscape to
their car situates them and punkness as a culture of angry
displacement, a way of life that's been pillaged akin to the
Indians whose Mohawks they've copped.
</P>
<P>
   It's handsome filmmaking that doesn't surface until the final 25
minutes during which Stevo and company's sense of marginalization
achieves the palpable, emotional import that's more expressive than
anything its characters' have to bitch about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
