<SLUG> BC-MICHAEL-DOUGLAS-ALUM-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGLAS VISITS CAMPUS NOT AS STAR BUT ALUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BEN HELLWARTH   
 Santa Barbara, Calif., News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ You could tell this was no ordinary
university lecture. Hundreds of students eager for a seat formed a
line in advance and filled the 900-seat venue.
</P>
<P>
   They had come to see Michael Douglas, a 1968 alum and later a
part-time area resident, who paid a visit Thursday to his alma
mater, the University of California at Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   When Douglas nonchalantly entered, stage right, the audience
exploded into applause that was more than just a warm welcome. The
thunder quickly turned into a standing ovation before Douglas had
said a word. This was not just the decorous display of admiration
you might find at a film festival. This was barely contained
bedlam, the kind of exuberant show of affection lavished on rock
bands as they take the stage, or, perhaps more accurately, on a
winning team that takes the field.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas is, in his way, UCSB's own one-man winning team, having
emerged from his days as a floundering freshman to reach the
pinnacle of superstardom. Many in the student audience, like
Gabriel Callahan, a 20-year-old film studies major, had come for
the chance to pick up tips from such a veteran Hollywood insider.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no ordinary insider. As revealed during an hourlong
question-and-answer session, the students clearly saw in Douglas
not just a star, but a former student, someone who walked the same
halls, strolled the same beaches, even lived in the same dormitory
and carried the same youthful dreams. Someone who might have been
like them.
</P>
<P>
   As one said: ``Thanks for coming back _ not as a superstar, but
as an alum.''
</P>
<P>
   After the boisterous welcome, Douglas, 54, mixed genial talk
about his professional experiences as an actor and producer with
personal reminiscences about his early days at UCSB. It helped that
one of Douglas' two on-stage interviewers was Stanley Glenn, now a
professor emeritus of dramatic art, who taught Douglas back in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment indicative of the conversational, often
light-hearted tone of the discussion that followed, Glenn handed
Douglas a script (``Michael has been a good sport about doing
this'') and had him re-enact a scene from his first UCSB role _ as
a messenger in the Shakespearean comedy ``Much Ado About Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Poignantly, that inauspicious campus debut had taken place in
the same Campbell Hall where Douglas spoke Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas was to read the lines just as he had at the time, Glenn
instructed, and the Oscar-winning actor obliged, breathlessly
reciting his elegant Elizabethan lines at a frantic tempo. It was
Shakespeare as auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas recalled how he had come running down the aisle, then
stopped just short of the stage, about where his father, screen
legend Kirk Douglas, was seated.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father turned to his friend next to him and says, `What did
he say?''' As his accomplished father left the theater, Douglas
recalled, he said, ``Thank goodness I don't ever have to worry
about my son becoming an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas explained that despite his family pedigree, he was not a
natural-born actor, and it took time to find his way. His raspy
voice needed work, as Glenn explained. Douglas was also forced to
leave UCSB temporarily because of failing grades. But, as Glenn
corroborated, the young actor worked hard upon his return to learn
his craft, eventually taking on bigger roles and winning campus
awards.
</P>
<P>
   Student questions were alternately personal (``What did you do
on the weekends out here?'') to strictly professional (the pros and
cons of acting and producing). A number of students prefaced their
remarks by thanking Douglas for his $600,000 donation that made the
public purchase and preservation of some land near the campus
possible.
</P>
<P>
   More often, though, students prefaced their remarks with words
of praise. A few took their praise a step further. Joseph
Priestley, a 23-year-old political science major, unfurled a ``Wall
Street'' poster, which Douglas came forward to sign. Jaime Nio, 27,
a business economics major, leaped onto the stage after asking his
question and had a friend snap a picture of him and his favorite
actor. Douglas again obliged, amicably and unperturbed. No one in
the audience seemed to mind, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very inspirational to see someone who graduated from this
program and made it,'' said Vanessa Luke, 20, who used the question
period to invite Douglas to see her in an upcoming campus
production of ``Waiting for Godot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's funny. He's got a great stage presence. He's got a nice,
easy quality about him, which is good to see for college students
because that's what we like,'' Luke said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Barbara, Calif., News-Press is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
