<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-JOVANOVIC-$ADV     04-30 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JOVANOVIC-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YUGOSLAV AMBASSADOR SAYS NATO BOMBINGS ARE A PRELUDE TO
OCCUPATION
 &HT;    With PHOTO
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 2
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ambassador Vladislav Jovanovic, a veteran diplomat
who is Yugoslavia's representative to the United Nations, believes
the Western media have failed to accurately portray his country's
side of the conflict in the Balkans. Speaking in English in his New
York office Thursday, he accused the United States of creating a
false pretext to start NATO bombing as part of a plan to eventually
invade and occupy Kosovo and all of Yugoslavia. He also said NATO
is intent on killing Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic if the
alliance cannot force him from power. Here are excerpts of
Jovanovic's interview with Cox Newspapers Washington bureau chief
Andrew Alexander:
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ Ethnic Albanian refugees are accusing Serb forces of
atrocities. Do you believe this is happening?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ Those stories (are part of a) media war by . . .some
sources that are extremely well organized. It is not possible for
all those stories to happen. There was intensified fighting between
our security forces against the strongholds of the KLA (Kosovo
Liberation Army), who are terrorists. Those strongholds were
concentrated in Albanian-populated villages. In order to neutralize
such strongholds, you have to use heavy arms and machine guns, and
you have to accept that there will be some casualties among
noncombatants because the (KLA) combatants live with their
families. This explains why there are a lot of destroyed houses in
those villages. And also, there are those (among Serbs and ethnic
Albanians) who try to take advantage of the war to settle accounts
with their neighbors or to plunder or rape. I can imagine that some
people engaged in this kind of private justice. And as a result of
this, certain cases of the mass graves could have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ NATO says its air strikes began in part because Serb forces
started ethnic cleansing in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A. _ There was no ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ So, in your view, what caused the NATO air strikes?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ When NATO started to concentrate troops on our frontiers,
our army started to take defensive positions nearby. And for that
reason only, the strongholds of the KLA (along the border) were
cleared by our forces. Q. _ Are you saying that NATO used your
army's action against the KLA as a pretext to start bombing?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ Yes. But even beyond that, the main reason was our
non-acceptance of the (latest) so-called peace plan. It contained
unacceptable things for us, including . . .giving up the
sovereignty of Kosovo and accepting the right of NATO to enter and
occupy it. For any self-respecting country, this would be
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ Regardless of what caused the flood of ethnic Albanian
refugees _ Serb forces or NATO air strikes _ how can Yugoslavia
expect them to return to Kosovo if they fear for their lives
without an international peacekeeping force?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ We repeatedly have invited them to return and told them
they will be safe. Already, slightly more than 100,000 have
returned and nothing has happened to them. But for those who
returned to (the Kosovo city of) Pristina, NATO began bombing the
city and it caused them to flee again.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ What do you believe is the NATO objective?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ America's first objective is to see NATO implanted into
Yugoslavia. Kosovo is the beginning. It is of strategic importance,
militarily, in the region. The American intention is eventually to
occupy all of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ NATO planes recently bombed one of Milosevic's homes. Is
NATO trying to kill him?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ I believe the policy of (the United States) is to do away
with President Milosevic by all means. Politically if possible,
physically if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ Your government estimates NATO bombing has caused at least
$100 billion in damage. If the bombing continues through the
summer, will Yugoslavia reach a point where it is defeated without
surrendering?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ This is the determination of NATO. It is a crime _ when you
deliberately destroy the fabric of a society in order to break
their will. (The goal) is to destroy for the sake of destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ What do you think the average American thinks of Serbs?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ They automatically associate the name 'Serb' with what they
are seeing in the media. Which is the result of systematic
brainwashing (by the Clinton administration through the U.S.
media). I have met a lot of Americans who react negatively to the
Serb name. But I have also met a number of common Americans _ a
doorman, a waitress, a policeman _ who all wanted to express their
sympathy with us because the mightiest country would exercise
deception against such a small country.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ Who are your allies in the world community?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ In your country, the term 'international community' is used
in one possessive way. You think it is those who join us or who
share our interests. In our case, Russia, Belarus, Ukraine and
China and India have taken a public stand against this. But there
are a number of other countries in Asia, Latin America and Africa
and some Arab countries who have criticized NATO for an act of
aggression that is unlawful. They are very concerned that if the
bombing of NATO succeeds, it will be the end of any
multilateralism. Any other country could be a candidate to be
subjected to the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ Milosevic is portrayed by Clinton and some Western media as
an evil dictator. On a personal basis, what is he like?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ He is an introvert, which is not always a good quality when
you need to be at public functions. He is intellectually arrogant
and shy at the same time. He is a modest man. You can only start to
explain something and with extraordinary speed, he performs his
capacity to differentiate from things that are unimportant. His
logic is so powerful that nobody can match him. As a man he is
absolutely warm and charming.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ What about reports that he has dark periods and can be a
heavy drinker?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ No. He drinks probably one whiskey a day. He is a very
virtuous man. He is a faithful family man. He doesn't like to hear
people making sexual jokes. He is so fond of his wife that I don't
think he's known any other women in his life. He used to be a
communist. But his mentality is not fit for him to be a communist.
He is very pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ Is it possible to negotiate a peace?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ I am afraid NATO and the United States government are not
ready yet for a settlement, because that settlement would require
compromise and they want to win the war. They want to occupy Kosovo
and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Q. _ Do you anticipate NATO ground forces?
</P>
<P>
   A. _ Yes, possibly. But it will be disastrous. They are not yet
convinced that they cannot win the war. They believe that
Yugoslavia will crack. Later, when they realize that their plans
cannot come true, then perhaps they will think about compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
