<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NITEOUT-CHRIS-EIGEMAN     04-30 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-CHRIS-EIGEMAN-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST EXIT FOR WHINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By LINDA LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Will it fit in the Subaru?''
</P>
<P>
   As repartee, the line doesn't have much of a Seinfeldian snap.
But it would do for a Thursday night in Brooklyn Heights as Chris
Eigeman, the frowning embodiment of New York angst in the sitcom
``It's Like, You Know,'' joined his wife and their best friends for
an evening out _ dinner, followed by a midnight trip to Home Depot
to buy a french door.
</P>
<P>
   Rewind. Chris Eigeman? Wasn't he the whining preppy in Whit
Stillman's film ``Metropolitan''? And in his new television show
(the last episode of the season will be Wednesday night on ABC at
8:30), isn't he the whining New Yorker who goes to California to
write about how awful it is, only to be seduced by the weather, the
wealth and the massage therapist with blinding white teeth? So
what's a Hollywood sitcom star doing in Brooklyn? He lives there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not Moomba kind of people,'' Eigeman said far more
jovially than any character he has played. He and his party were
pouring red wine liberally and considering the lamb on the menu at
La Bouillabaisse, a seafood bistro on Atlantic Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Eigeman, 34, though an acerbic cynic in front of the camera, off
camera seems more like a complacent yuppie in an upscale sitcom. In
``Metropolitan,'' they had a name for people like him: Urban Haute
Bourgeoisie.
</P>
<P>
   Eigeman's wife, Linda, is a producer at CNN. Their best friends
are Marvin S. Putnam, a lawyer, and his wife, Kerith S. Putnam, an
executive at HBO. In the last five years, the two couples, who at
one point roomed together in Brooklyn, have worked their way up to
separate apartments with views near the Promenade. The Eigemans now
even have a bathtub that holds four. ``Not that we've ever used it
like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They play suburbanites in Brooklyn, meeting once a week to
indulge in what they call ``50's bridge,'' where socializing is as
important as winning. ``You don't know the rules very well,''
Eigeman explained, ``and there's a great deal of drinking. If I'm
the dummy, I read Architectural Digest.'' When there's confusion
about the rules, one of them calls Ms. Putnam's mother in New
Jersey for advice.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the typical who's-your-surgeon Hollywood types.
Squeezed into a cramped table at the back of the bistro, the
couples talked about everything from MP3 technology to an article
in The New Yorker ``written by that chef,'' Ms. Putnam said.
``Don't eat the chicken!'' the others recalled. ``No well-done
meat!''
</P>
<P>
   Eigeman, trying to remember which Henry he played at Riverside
Shakespeare Company, said, ``It's not IV, V or VIII, and there's
not a VII, so it's got to be VI, by deduction.'' There was a
spirited discussion of Ann Jillian's sitcom in the early 1980s,
though no one could remember its name. ``French Maid''? ``Windows
on the World''? Finally, a bearded man at the next table shouted
out: ``It's a Living!''
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, the two couples piled into a Subaru Outback and
drove to Home Depot in Red Hook. ``It's the real man's Ikea,''
Eigeman said as he and Putnam began guy-talking about the french
door that Eigeman planned to install himself in the study. ``I have
a couple of chisels and a wood plane,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The women went off to buy mops and garbage bags while Eigeman
tested the fire extinguishers, and bought one. At the checkout
counter, he laughed at what he called the ``impulse items'':
20-inch circular saws and grout.
</P>
<P>
   Last seen, the french door was wedged into the Subaru and the
couples were headed back to the Heights. It had been, like, you
know, midnight at Home Depot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
