<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, May 2, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ If much about the murderous
shootings in Littleton, Colo., seemed alien and bizarre, at least
one part of the story seemed familiar: the world of jocks and
nerds, preps and geeks, winners and losers that defined life at
Columbine High. The incident and others like it have been viewed
through many prisms _ guns and violence in the media, values and
parenting. But the fact that such horrors keep playing out in high
schools tracks longstanding and growing concerns about what kind of
educational and social environments they provide. By Peter
Applebome. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-ECON-REVIEW (Washington) _ The central U.S.
foreign-policy conundrum: In an age when your military adversary
can also rank among your biggest trading partners, and when your
military allies double as your fiercest economic competitors, does
America want weak global neighbors or strong ones? The question
helps account for the bizarre crazy-quilt of U.S. foreign policy
these days, and is complicated by the fact that the world stage is
crowded with weak countries jockeying for global influence while
struggling with economic woes. By David E. Sanger. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OUTLOOK-REVIEW (Moscow) _ If Russia is the country it
seemed to be for 10 years after the fall of communism _ a nation
struggling to grow into a modern democracy _ then the West has a
long-term stake in its success. But if the real Russia is instead
the seething fury visible on the nightly news, the glory-mongering
defender of murderous hypernationalism, then its success looms
fearsomely as a threat. So the U.S. thinks of Russia mostly in the
short run. By Michael Wines. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   OBESITY-DRUGS-REVIEW (Undated) _ To the pharmaceutical industry,
the corpulence of America means a booming new market for diet pills
for the obese, practically served to the companies on a silver
platter by the government. That was evident last week when
Hoffman-LaRoche received FDA approval to sell Xenical, the first
pill to be approved since the government recalibrated its
definition of who qualifies as overweight. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-MISSING-REVIEW (Boston) _ As states track down former
welfare recipients to assess how their well-being has been affected
by stricter eligibility rules and work requirements, the question
of those not accounted for looms ever larger. They amount to more
than one-quarter of former recipients. And in the information wars
between state officials and advocates for the poor, this `missing'
category is becoming a weapon that both sides seek to wield. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-FEUD-REVIEW (Hollywood) _ In the hierarchy of values
here, money dominates. But no one likes to talk about it. While
it's normal to discuss intensely personal matters, money is not
mentioned because everyone is so obsessed with it. But now two key
players here, Disney chairman Michael Eisner and his former deputy
Jeffrey Katzenberg, are not only talking about money but they're
publicly attacking each other over it. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ As a case study in
politics and the development of government policy, the Republicans'
new Social Security plan belongs in the textbooks. It shows how
when politicians dig beneath the surface of a complicated topic,
they often learn that their ideological preconceptions are
unrealistic. By David E. Rosenbaum
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PARTY-REVIEW (Beijing) _ Communist Party chief Jiagn Zemin
and his aides are worried that the party is losing touch with the
masses, so they are trying to create a more relevant party via an
old-fashioned `rectification' campaign to promote ideological
conformity among the millions of cadres who purportedly run the
country, to re-invigorate the party and, not incidentally, to
assure Jiang a place in history. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIARY-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Kosovar camps and
shantytowns that have sprung up in Albania are filled with refugees
who can tell stories of a traumatizing odyssey. Among them is the
account of Skender Vehapi, a 47-year-old farmer who left his home
with his family eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ANTIWAR-REVIEW (Washington) _ In the debate over NATO's
bombing of Serbia, the voice of the American anti-war movement has
not been heard to any great degree. Once it was so loud that it
helped end the Vietnam War. But it may be heard soon if the war
widens. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WARCOSTS-REVIEW (Washington) _ For an air war that in the
eyes of many U.S. generals has been run on the cheap, tactically,
bombardment of Yugoslavia could go down as the most expensive
military campaign, bomb for bomb, in history. It's costing more to
kill fewer people. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-WAR-REVIEW (Washington) _ Debate over how the president
and Congress should share power in matters of war is as old as the
Republic. A look at the history of the debate, with particular
focus on the War Powers Act. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-REVIEW (Caracas) _ For Venezuelan voters, a nervous
honeymoon. Three months after he was sworn in as president, former
renegade Hugo Chavez continues to perplex and unnerve Venezuelans,
not to mention the rest of Latin America. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
