<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     04-30 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIFTING ALLIANCES IN CONGRESS ON MATTERS OF WAR AND POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Southern Exposure is a weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
(rk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUNGHLIN   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Oh, what a difference a war _ and a president _
make.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, when Congress debated whether to give President
Bush the authority to use force against Iraq, Republicans decried
Democrats who dared challenge the commander in chief on military
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to take this very serious and solemn act, we
must give the president, not 535 commanders in chief, the authority
to do it right,'' declared Texas Rep. Tom DeLay, criticizing
lawmakers who wanted to ``micromanage'' Bush's actions in the
Persian Gulf. ``For Congress to deny the use of force to back up
the world community's demands would make them meaningless. Force is
the only credible threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Now with a Democrat in the White House, Republicans are openly
challenging President Clinton's authority. And they don't seem to
care very much that other NATO countries have lined up against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to DeLay once more, this time griping about Clinton's
policy in the Balkans and suggesting that Congress ought to play a
bigger role in the military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should vote to forbid any deployment without congressional
approval,'' DeLay said, complaining that the administration ``has
played musical chairs'' in its use of forces and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The rhetorical flip-flop is striking. And Democrats are just as
guilty of tailoring their public position to suit their party.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Vice President Al Gore, who eight years ago was the
senior senator from Tennessee. Gore groused about Bush's military
policy, saying he ignored the role of Congress as the country
prepared for war against Iraq. ``There is much to regret at this
point,'' Gore said. Now, he is Clinton's biggest cheerleader as
Clinton defends the NATO-led strikes in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Not all lawmakers appear to be affected by party label, with
some demonstrating a fairly consistent philosophy when it comes to
matters of war.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sen. Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., took considerable heat
for his refusal in 1991 to support the use of force against Iraq,
saying the move to war was premature. In March, Hollings again
demonstrated his reluctance to send U.S. forces in harm's way,
refusing to support the airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   CHECK, PLEASE
</P>
<P>
   Alabama Rep. Spencer Bachus isn't too sure about this conflict
in Kosovo, but he is certain he doesn't want the United States to
be stuck with the tab.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative Republican was part of a group that pushed for
a provision that seeks to get NATO reimbursement for the
overwhelming share of the military costs the Pentagon is paying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only right to expect our NATO allies to shoulder a
greater share of the load,'' said Bachus. ``We must demand they pay
their fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   And if a member nation refuses to pay or offers the old check is
in the mail excuse, the legislative language would require the
president to report on the reasons why no reimbursement was made.
</P>
<P>
   BEAM THEM UP
</P>
<P>
   With satellite television dishes sprouting across the South
faster than strip malls, it is no wonder Southern lawmakers were so
anxious to get involved with the recent House passage of a bill to
protect the ability of satellite companies to offer local broadcast
networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this new competition will come better services at lower
prices, so the real winners will be our constituents,'' said Rep.
Howard Coble, R-N.C., who engineered the agreement on the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., another player on telecommunication
issues, was even more enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation will have a revolutionizing impact on the
marketplace,'' crowed Tauzin, praising the benefits to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, while the conflict in Kosovo might seem remote
to much of the public, members of Congress know almost all voters
have their own hands near the remote _ control that is.
</P>
<P>
   A BUG'S LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Escalating a fight with the Environmental Protection Agency, a
bipartisan group of lawmakers introduced a bill that would make it
harder for the agency to ban certain pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Regulatory Fairness and Openness Act of 1999, the
bill would direct the EPA to use ``sound science and a fair
implementation process'' in deciding whether to take some dangerous
pesticides off the market.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Allen Boyd, a Democrat, and Charles Canady, a Republican,
both of Florida, and Louisiana Rep. Chris John, D-La., are among
the bill's co-sponsors, many of whom come from districts with large
agricultural bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we certainly want dangerous chemicals prohibited, we
must ensure we do not use outdated, unscientific data to ban
products that family farmers depend on,'' Boyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups are expected to fight the measure, arguing
that the bill would only complicate efforts to introduce safer
growing practices to the American farm.
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
