<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORAL-HAZARD-2TAKES-N     04-30 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORAL-HAZARD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM ROCK MUSIC TO RUSSIA, HAVING A LIKELY RESCUER FOSTERS MORAL
HAZARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About two years ago, Matt Hazard and three of his buddies got
together to form a new, hard-rock band in Minneapolis. At a loss
for what to call themselves, they settled on Moral Hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guitarist wanted to get my last name in the band because
we thought it sounded cool, but every combination seemed kind of
lame,'' recalls the 19-year-old Hazard. ``But we were all in the
same high school economics class, and one day our teacher began
writing that term on the board and we said, `That's it.''' He adds,
``It's seems like a relevant term to society.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Rarely do dreary economic abstractions become fodder for
mainstream media accounts or occasional cocktail party chatter as
the concept of moral hazard has.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, moral hazard describes any situation, though usually
a financial one, in which risky behavior is encouraged because risk
takers believe they will be bailed out of mistakes by a third
party.
</P>
<P>
   Think Asia and Russia here. The international financial crisis
that erupted in Thailand and began tearing across the globe nearly
two years ago left the policy wonks who had to deal with its
consequences in a philosophic bind. Many lenders and investors had
plowed money into rapidly growing countries like Thailand,
Indonesia and South Korea in the belief that governments there
would always prop up certain key companies. But many of the
corporations were so larded with bad debt that the governments
couldn't keep them afloat forever. In Russia, feverish financial
speculation was fueled in part by the belief that the Russian
government wouldn't default on its bonds and by the perception that
Russia, with all its nuclear warheads, was too big for anyone to
let it fail.
</P>
<P>
   Investors badly misjudged the situation in all these countries,
lost money when economic meltdowns occurred, then stampeded for the
exits. That put all the countries in a squeeze. After all, it's
hard to keep food stocked in stores and an economy moving ahead
when nobody will lend you more money. So the International Monetary
Fund and the U.S. Treasury Department both advocated lending fresh
funds to these nations to get them over the hump and back onto the
happy track of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no!'' shouted critics of that idea. They said that if
the IMF and the Treasury Department gave more money to the
countries, both the countries and speculators would feel safe to
invest recklessly in the future because they knew they would be
bailed out. Classic moral hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When individual behavior is random and the downside is bid up
by implicit guarantees of being bailed out, you encourage risky
behavior,'' observes William A. Niskanen, chairman of the Cato
Institute, a libertarian think tank in Washington. Asia and Russia,
of course, aren't the only arenas in which moral hazard has reared
its ugly head.
</P>
<P>
   Other well-known cases of moral hazard at work include the
savings and loan debacle in the United States a decade ago, in
which owners of old-fashioned mortgage banks felt safe taking
fliers on dangerous real estate forays because the banks' deposits
were insured by the federal government. The government-led rescue
of the once high-flying hedge fund, Long Term Capital, also might
be morally hazardous if it encourages free-wheeling speculation
disconnected from the threat of financial ruin. Although no public
money was used to keep the fund afloat, critics said the Federal
Reserve's orchestration of the rescue sent a signal that some
funds, no matter how much gambling they indulged in, were too
important to fail.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance underwriters and their customers regularly engage in
morally hazardous transactions. Health insurers constantly weigh
what medical treatments they will cover, trying to decide if
coverage will induce patients to pursue elaborate and expensive
treatments that they don't necessarily need. The flip side of this
is, of course, insurers or HMOs that become so tightfisted and risk
averse that patients can't get treatments they surely need. Home
ownership also can be a morally hazardous proposition. People who
might otherwise avoid building homes in Malibu because of the risk
of fire and mudslides or in hurricane ravaged parts of the East
Coast might do so anyway because their home insurer picks up the
tab if their house is destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Morally hazardous situations may also crop up outside the narrow
confines of the financial world. Take major league baseball, for
instance. The American League, unlike the National League, has long
had a designated hitter rule that allows a team to substitute a
better batter each time their pitcher would normally step up to the
plate. And where is the moral hazard in that? It turns out that
American League pitchers tend to throw more bean balls at batters
than do their counterparts in the National League because, some
studies say, such risky _ even nasty _ behavior can't be punished.
The designated hitter rule keeps the bean baller safely away from
the plate, where an opposing hurler could otherwise launch
fastballs at his head in retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Still, timing is everything. While easy to spot morally
hazardous situations in retrospect, after the risk has surfaced, it
can be much harder to discern moral hazard _ or act on it _ in a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, as canny an observer of
financial markets as anyone in Washington, was attuned to the
ambiguities of moral hazard when he defended the effort to pump
fresh funds into South Korea in 1997 as that country edged toward
economic collapse. ``Look, I wouldn't spend a nickel to bail out
investors or creditors,'' he said at the time. ``The purpose of
this is not to help creditors; the purpose is to help Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   But he conceded that saving the country also meant saving
investors who had placed errant bets there.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly, say those who disdain relying on moral hazard as a hard
and fast standard. They say a more nuanced balancing act must be
struck between not encouraging risky behavior and forestalling an
economic crisis before it spins further out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people just say, `Oh, there's a moral hazard here,'
and rule out a whole range of actions that might be taken,'' says
Barry Bosworth, a senior economics fellow at the Brookings
Institution in Washington. ``I'm not saying we just disregard moral
hazard and charge ahead, but it is often the case in financial
crises that those who triggered the crisis don't pay at all;
average citizens do.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to avoid moral hazard is to establish better frameworks
for anticipating and reducing risks in a world where different
countries hew to wildly different ethical and financial standards.
Along these lines, Gordon Brown, Britain's chancellor of the
Exchequer, has called for improved financial disclosure, better
oversight and stronger ties between the public and private sectors
to stave off financial disasters in various parts of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Big central banks, if they're honestly run and efficiently
operated, also can be useful lenders of last resort when a crisis
looms. Bosworth points out that the United States banking system
operated for about 100 years without a central bank to act as a
lender of last resort during financial crises. So before the
creation of the Federal Reserve earlier this century, the country
frequently lurched from financial crisis to financial crisis, a
pattern that has largely disappeared here since the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Niskanen at the Cato Institute doesn't rule out
lending during a crisis if all somebody needs are a few bucks to
get them over the hump. But if larger problems such as corruption,
cronyism or wasteful economic policies exist when a bailout is
being considered, he is inclined to raise the moral hazard flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should respond in a crisis based on rules
established before the crisis occurs and not based on rules
negotiated during a crisis,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But others demur from this point of view, noting that pulling
the plug on a borrower _ even if it is the right thing to do in
terms of avoiding moral hazard _ can often make a bad financial
situation even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a game about getting the right balance between
systemic risk and allowing markets to function,'' said Morris
Goldstein, a former International Monetary Fund official and a
senior fellow at the Institute for International Economics in
Washington. ``I lean more to the case by case approach than to the
idea of laying out rules in advance. It's very difficult to lay out
an either-or rule because systemic risk can sometimes be
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some rock bands who share Goldstein's philosophy and
extol the virtues of benevolence if the threat of moral hazard
arises, especially when rules are not clear or maybe don't even
exist, like in the notoriously fickle and unfettered music
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we researched it on the Internet, moral hazard seemed to
be people whining about the U.S. helping out other countries,''
notes Hazard. ``But in the music industry you just can't make it on
your own, and you always need someone to bail you out if you're
going to make it. So that side of moral hazard has a lot of meaning
for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
