<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, May 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gradual warming trend over the Middle West will continue to
mount Saturday as the core of an expansive, stationary high
pressure system holds steady over the region. However, afternoon
warmth will be tempered near the shores of the Great Lakes, where
the uneven heating of land and water prompts cool air residing over
the lakes to push inland.
</P>
<P>
   With the stationary high over the Middle West interrupting the
upper-level winds that steer weather systems typically from west to
east across the nation, an orphaned area of disturbed weather off
the Southeast coast will remain nearly stationary, setting the
stage for clouds and pockets of rain and drizzle from the eastern
Carolinas to northeast Florida. Feisty ocean winds will average 15
to 25 mph along parts of the Carolina coast.
</P>
<P>
   After another chilly morning, the Northeast will warm to levels
above seasonal readings, though afternoon warmth will be tempered
near the Atlantic coast as developing sea breezes escort cool air
inland.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt over parts of eastern Colorado
and west Texas as a sluggish front and trailing jet stream
disturbance work in tandem to lift moist air from the Gulf of
Mexico. A few of the storms will become severe, with tornadoes or
damaging straight-line winds possible in isolated spots. Heavy rain
and flooding are also possible, while moderate to heavy snow will
fall above 9,000 feet in the some of the mountains of northeast New
Mexico and eastern Colorado. Meanwhile, high winds will buffet some
of the deserts of southern New Mexico and southern Arizona.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Blocking High &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under relentless sun, the risk of wildfires heightened across
Michigan the past few days. Meanwhile, flooding downpours doused
east-central Colorado. To the south, heavy snow blanketed the
mountains of northeast New Mexico. All three extremes were related
to a blocking high pressure system stalled over the upper Middle
West this week. Near the center of the sprawling high, evaporation
rates have been high, leaving the upper Middle West parched. On the
unyielding western flank of the high, a low pressure system came to
a virtual halt, setting the stage for recurrent rain and snow.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
