<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9745 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-ELECTIONS-$ADV     04-30 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-ELECTIONS-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION LEADER HOLDS SLIM LEAD IN PANAMA RACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, May 2) 
 
(Eds.: Also see: Panama-Blades) 
(Eds.: Last week is cq) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ If opposition candidate Mireya Moscoso
triumphs in Panama's presidential election today, analysts say it
would be a startling comeback and a touch of revenge for one of the
nation's most snake-bitten political families.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso floundered early in the campaign. But in a pair of
recent polls, she moved two points ahead of Martin Torrijos, the
candidate of the ruling Revolutionary Democratic Party, or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   Banker Alberto Vallarino is in third place.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso, 52, is the widow of Arnulfo Arias, who was elected
president of Panama three times. All three of his terms were cut
short by coups.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leaders of the final uprising against Arias in 1968
was Omar Torrijos _ Martin Torrijos' father _ who ushered in 21
years of military rule.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, said Peggy Scranton, a Panama expert at the
University of Arkansas, Moscoso and her Arnulfista Party believe
that their time has finally come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memories go back here, they really do,'' Scranton said.
``Surely, in the party's mind and in her mind, they are thinking:
`Now, it's my turn.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Moscoso and Torrijos often refer to the past, the
winner will begin a five-year term at a crucial moment for Panama's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Panama Canal treaties, the United States will turn
over full control of the waterway to Panama at noon Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   But there are lingering doubts about Panama's ability to
administer the canal on its own and to develop thousands of acres
of canal properties and military bases left behind in the American
pullout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country will be without `gringos' for the first time,''
said Gustavo Gorriti, an associate editor at the Panama City daily
La Prensa.
</P>
<P>
   But for most Panamanians, pocketbook issues have defined the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Under President Ernesto Perez Balladares, who took office in
1994, Panama has privatized the telephone and electric companies,
slashed import tariffs, and reformed the labor code to make it
easier for companies to hire and fire workers.
</P>
<P>
   Such policies have led to annual economic growth rates of
between 2 and 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, a flood of cheap imports has angered farmers and
factory owners. Unemployment is 14 percent. Many Panamanians say
the wealth has failed to trickle down.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel cheated,'' said Ever Chi Pardo, an economist at
the University of Panama. ``The economy needed fundamental changes
but it should have been done gradually.''
</P>
<P>
   A Panamanian businessman who did not want his name used put it
another way. ``The poor people hate the government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such indignation helped to scuttle President Perez Balladares'
drive last year to seek a second consecutive term. He wanted to
amend the constitution to allow re-election, but the initiative was
overwhelmingly rejected in a voter referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say the anti-government sentiment is now hurting
Torrijos, who served for four years under the current
administration as vice minister of government and justice.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is what Gorriti describes as a backlash against
party dominance. For 26 of the past 31 years, the Panamanian
government has been controlled by the military or the PRD, which
was founded by the military.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the PRD is Panama's largest party and has an impressive
get-out-the-vote machinery. If he wins, Torrijos is expected to
follow many of the government's policies.
</P>
<P>
   But in campaign appearances, Torrijos has tried to project a
softer, more caring image. He also has invoked the memory of his
father, a popular figure who spent heavily on public housing and
other social projects during his regime. Omar Torrijos was killed
in a 1981 plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can not create wealth and development without social
justice,`` Torrijos said last week at a huge rally in Panama City.
``The new Panamanian nation is an alliance between the people and
the government to defeat underdevelopment, poverty and injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Torrijos may have peaked too early. In recent weeks his
double-digit lead in the polls has evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   When the newspaper La Prensa published an opinion survey last
week showing that Moscoso had moved into the lead, PRD militants
bought 20,000 copies in a desperate effort to block its
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso married Arnulfo Arias in 1969 when he was already
Panama's most famous civilian politician. Arias won the presidency
in 1940, 1948 and 1968 and is believed to have won in the
fraud-tainted 1984 elections as well.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Arias died in 1988, Moscoso formed the Arnulfista
Party and narrowly lost the 1994 election to Perez Balladares. If
she wins, she would become Panama's first-ever female president and
Latin America's fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doors have been opened,'' Moscoco said at a press conference
last Friday. ``Now both men and women identify with us. And many
women feel that we are capable of doing the same job as men.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso paints herself as a populist and has promised to raise
tariffs, jumpstart local industry, and help farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But Panama is locked into a structural adjustment agreement with
the International Monetary Fund that runs through next year. That
will make it difficult for the incoming government to substantially
alter the nation's economic course, Pardo said.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso, who studied interior design at a Florida community
college, has no government experience and critics claim that she
has a poor grasp of economics and international affairs. During the
campaign, she refused to debate Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   Since losing the election five years ago, however, Moscoso has
made hundreds of visits to impoverished Panama City neighborhoods
and to rural villages, and such barnstorming paved the way for her
rise in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has worked like a dog,'' Scranton said. ``She has paid her
dues.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
