<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATORS TO DEBATE USING 'ALL NECESSARY FORCE' IN BALKANS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Friday reluctantly agreed to debate a
resolution allowing President Clinton to use ``all necessary
force'' against Yugoslavia, but the outcome seemed likely to be
another signal of congressional doubts about the war.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee sent the resolution,
sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., to the floor with no
recommendation on whether it should be approved. However, leaders
of both parties said they would move Monday to table, or kill, the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the House voted to require Clinton to seek
congressional approval before sending ground troops to fight in the
Balkans, and also declined on a tie vote to approve a resolution
supporting the U.S.-led NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., told fellow members of the foreign
relations panel he was concerned that when McCain's resolution came
up for Senate debate, critics of the war might counter it with a
proposal to tie Clinton's hands. The result would be confusing
signals ``sent around the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Coverdell contended, the debate was ``premature''
because Clinton has not announced plans to expand the air war to a
land operation. Indeed, the president has said he opposes ground
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Coverdell, also a member of the GOP leadership, said
the Senate would debate the resolution for about four hours Monday
afternoon. The leadership had planned to avoid taking up the McCain
measure altogether, but the Senate parliamentarian ruled that the
War Powers Act requires such resolutions to be considered by the
full membership.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the measure conceded that a majority of the
senators would vote to table their motion.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution prompted a hurried meeting of the Foreign
Relations Committee in cramped quarters off the Senate floor just
as members were fleeing town for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Senators sharply differed not only over the McCain proposal, but
whether Congress has an obligation to debate the Balkan air war,
now beginning its sixth week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, America is at war,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel,
R-Neb., a cosponsor of the McCain resolution. ``We in Congress ...
surely have some responsibility to step forward and address what we
believe should and should not be done and not duck that
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Congress of the United State buries its head on this
one,'' he added, ``why are we here?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., an anti-war activist in the Vietnam
era, countered that now was not the time to criticize the effort in
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret enormously what happened in the House,'' he said,
calling it ``gutless and craven'' for the House to vote not to
support the air war and then to propose $12.9 billion in emergency
military spending, twice as much as the president sought.
</P>
<P>
   But a Democratic colleague praised the House action against the
air war. ``The United States Congress has not supported the
bombing, plain and simple,'' said Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis. ``I
think it was a good vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
