A9750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN01-COX     04-30 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Releasing the Columbine victim inside all of us
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ She was standing on the sidewalk in front of
Longview High School. The woman, who looked to be in her 30s, was
holding her baby in one hand and clutching her little boy's hand
with the other. The look on her face reminded me of the looks on
the faces of war refugees. She was gazing longingly at the school.
</P>
<P>
   It was last Wednesday, the day our kids had been hearing would
be the day something bad would happen at their school: a bomb, an
armed assault, something. You name it, the rumor mill had churned
it out. It was the day that 700 of their classmates did not attend
class.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, according to LHS conventional wisdom, was the reason
school officials employed 24-hour security guards and an explosives
sniffing dog for an indefinite time. It was the day the statewide
minimum skills test was to be administered to ninth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, an 11th-grader, had not answered my queries for
several days about whether she wanted to attend school on that day.
I had told her I believed it would be safe but that I would never
require her to go somewhere that she was afraid to go.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn is a very methodical person. Her decisions are usually
carefully considered, and this was a big one. She had conferences
with me and with her friends who in turn conferred with their
parents. Some of the adults decided to keep their children at home;
others told their children there was no way they would allow them
to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't get my answer from her until Wednesday morning. The set
of her jaw told me as she sat in the living room waiting for me to
get ready: She was worried but she would not be bullied.
</P>
<P>
   We put her stuff in the car. We had a lot of stuff because
toward the end of the school day, she was to leave for a student
council convention in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering the student drop-off area, I immediately spotted
the principal on the front patio but far fewer kids than normal.
The usual din was absent. The principal good-naturedly asked what
in the world we were up
</P>
<P>
   to with suitcases, a cooler and a chocolate cake in tow. We
reminded her of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   As I returned to my car after many hugs and kisses and goodbyes,
I saw the faces of many of the students who were waiting for the
first bell to ring. They were worried, some looked afraid, others
looked confused.
</P>
<P>
   My heart ached for them but I also became angry that the insane
acts of people they would never know were placing such a burden on
our kids in Longview, themselves now victims of the senseless
rampage in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Close to tears, I walked down the steps and saw the woman on the
sidewalk. I had an appointment in another town and I was already
late, but I couldn't pass her by.
</P>
<P>
   In Spanish, I asked if I could help. Her voice shaking with
emotion, she responded, ``Tengo miedo.'' I'm afraid.
</P>
<P>
   I put my arms around this other mother, a stranger, and we
cried. Then we talked. She told me her daughter was a 10th-grader
and she too was determined not to be cheated out of even a day of
her education. We comforted each other. ``God is great,'' she said
in Spanish. We both knew in our hearts that our daughters would be
fine, but we too were victims of Columbine. Being a victim is not a
good feeling, it is maddening and it
</P>
<P>
   makes you very, very angry.
</P>
<P>
   My memories of high school are overwhelmingly positive and I
resent greatly the fact that last week will become part of my
daughter's remembrances. But I am determined to make sure she and
as many of her fellow students as possible have many, many more
good ones before they leave high school.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing you're a victim is painful, remaining one is shameful.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal. E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
