<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ In the latest mixed message from
Congress on the war in the Balkans, the Senate has set the stage to
take up a resolution Monday to permit the use of ground troops.
Senate leaders from both parties said Friday they would table the
measure. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ NATO'S launched its strongest
attack on the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade since NATO bombings
began March 24 , more than double the number of sorties normally
flown. It took place just hours after the Rev. Jesse Jackson
arrived on a peace mission in hopes of meeting Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and winning the release of three U.S. POWs
captured a month ago. Meanwhile, Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin
was in Belgrade Friday as well and immediately went into a meeting
with Milosevic. The former prime minister was continuing his effort
to narrow the gap between NATO and Yugoslavia after visiting Bonn
and Rome on Thursday. Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Story moving in the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Albania _ Several hundred refugees
crossed into Albania on Friday repeating tales of Serb police or
paramilitary units looting and burning their homes and telling of a
continuing Serb drive to expel them from their homes in the western
city of Prizren. Developing. (Kunstel, Cox News Service). 20. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPSQ&AMP;A _ RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ Fear is part of
preparing for war. It's something most of the of the 5,000 American
combat troops here won't talk about _ least of all with us
``pukes'' from the media. Staff Sergeant Kevin Boldin of the 1st
Armored Division(CQ) is an exception. At 29, Boldin has been there
and done it. So he doesn't mind opening up about what war anxiety
is like when you are young. (Albright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-ELECTIONS _ MIAMI _ As they do battle for votes in
Panama's May 2 presidential election, the country's leading
candidates are milking the mystique of their famous names. The
race's front-runner is Martin Torrijos, a graduate of Texas A&AMP;M
University and son of Gen. Omar Torrijos, the cigar-chomping
military ruler who became a national hero by negotiating the Panama
Canal treaties. Running second is Mireya Moscoso, the widow of
Arnulfo Arias, three-time president. The election comes months
before the United States is set to give Panama full control of the
Panama Canal on Dec. 31. (Emling, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   w/PANAMA-BOX _ MIAMI _ Data on Panama and information on leading
candidates. (Emling, Cox News Service). 10.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both pieces moved Wed. April 28.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN-POLLUTERS _ Gov. George W. Bush has received more
than $300,000 in presidential campaign contributions from employees
and lawyers who work for the state's top polluters, according to an
analysis of contributions to Bush's exploratory committee. Public
Citizen and other groups opposed to legislation that would allow
the companies to continue polluting say the donations allow Bush to
circumvent a ban on campaign contributions to state officials
during the legislative session. (McCarthy, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   JASPERTRIAL-GEORGETOWN _ The list of murder suspects who have
faced Williamson County juries and have felt their law-and-order
brand of justice reads like a Who's Who of Texas' Most Wanted.
Notably among them is Genene Jones, a Kerrville nurse sentenced to
99 years in prison for killing a 15-month-old child by injecting
her with a muscle relaxant. This summer, another Williamson County
jury could sit in judgment in another nationally-watched murder
trial. Lawrence Russell Brewer, 32, is one of three men accused of
capital murder for chaining James Byrd Jr. to a pickup and dragging
him to death. (Shah, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-BILL _ Texas Poll: Is the state against abortion or for
abortion rights? How important is the issue? Should parents be
notified of abortion to minors? Should there be a mandatory 72 hour
waiting period? (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION: Texas editors.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY _ COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Bill Bradley makes a road trip in
late April to a place that would not at first appear to offer him
the warmest welcome. But the Democratic Gov. Hodges will welcome
Bradley with open arms at a state Democratic dinner on April 30 to
send a message to Bradley's rival for the Democratic presidential
nomination. Believing that Hodges still little chance of becoming
governor, Vice President Gorte did nothing to help Hodges in last
year's campaign. This is payback time. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-SAFE _ RALEIGH _ Students want to attend schools that
are safe and free of fear. They want to stop the senseless violence
that is occurring in our nation's schools. On April 30th, 1,000
students travel to Raleigh for the Center for the Prevention of
School Violence's Fourth Annual S.A.V.E. Summit. Students Against
Violence Everywhere (S.A.V.E.) was initiated at West Charlotte High
School in 1989 following the tragic death of a student at an
off-campus party. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-FEAR _ ATLANTA _ By 3 p.m. metro Atlanta schools had had
numerous disturbances but no real instances. Several - three or
more - schools in two counties were dismissed early amidst bomb
threats. And in one county, 28 students and one adult has been
arrested over the last week or so for bomb threats and similar
activity. Other counties have had just an isolated arrest or two at
the most. (Schneider, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12..
</P>
<P>
   GUN-RUSH _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Local pawnshops are selling guns
quickly because of people's fear that it will be mass chaos at the
start of the New Year. (Freeman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-PREVIEW _ DENVER _ A preview of the Star Wars
celebration in Denver this weekend. Signing up and getting started
could be a nightmare in an event that seems to have outstripped the
organizers expectation. Will the celebration live up to
expectations? What possibly could? (Cummings, Dayton Daily News).
15. ETA 7 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-MADNESS _ A look at overall madness, focusing on toys
going on sale Sunday night, plans for local theaters to handle
madness, why the country and the net is going crazy, a talk with a
University of Florida ``Star Wars' scholar, etc. (Browning, Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHSMOG _ It once was the burden of industrial states in the
Northeast. But today all throughout the South, cities inundated by
more people with more cars mark the start of Smog Season. From
Charlotte to Birmingham, the South goes on ozone watch. The Great
Smokies are becoming the Great Smoggies. And Atlanta, planning
doomsayers have said, has become the next Los Angeles. A wrapup on
the beginning of the South's Smog Season. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
