<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0501-     04-30 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0501-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW REFUGEE OUTPOURING HITS ALBANIA, AS KOSOVARS FLEE SERB
CONSCRIPTION
 &HT;    700&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0501.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINA BORDER POINT, Albania _ A new outpouring of Kosovo
refugees crowded across the border day and night here at the rate
of 1,000 per hour Friday, arriving from a heavily populated area
where new threats of Serbian conscription drove them to risk the
trip they had feared making for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulances and mobile clinics veered up the twisting road from
Kukes city throughout the afternoon, as more and more people who
had walked at least part of the way arrived suffering from
exhaustion and dehydration under a pitiless sun and mountain winds
that blasted all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the nightmare we've been expecting,'' said Ray
Wilkinson, spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cleaning Prizren,'' he said, referring to the
municipal area of more than 100,000 people located about 15 miles
north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   And they appear to be cleaning it of professionals, according to
refugee agency officials. Serb police detained a doctor and six
nurses at the Prizren hospital Thursday morning, ``bundled them
into a vehicle and drove them to the Albanian border.'' They were
not given time to notify their families.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Kukes relief agencies scrambling to put up more tents
for the newcomers were hampered by the strong winds. Even the 100
new tents planned by the Red Crescent Society of the United Arab
Emirates and another 120 being raised by Medecins Sans Frontiere of
Belgium were expected to accommodate only about 4,800 people. More
than 11,000 crossed into Albania from 9 a.m. to 10 p.m. (local
time) Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said 50,000 will be coming,'' said Ahmad Alburainain,
head of the Red Crescent delegation trying to expand the UAE tent
camp. It had filled existing vacancies with 10 truckloads of
refugees by 2 p.m., and workers were struggling to raise the
additional tents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The local government has opened schools, the mosque and even
government buildings to hold refugees overnight in emergencies such
as this in past weeks. By nightfall, thousands of people were
sitting on the ground around the main city square and outside
packed refugee camps, or were waiting in parked cars to learn if
there was any place for them to sleep inside.
</P>
<P>
   More than 630,000 refugees have poured out of Kosovo province
since NATO airstrikes began March 24, including an estimated
373,000 into Albania, according to the U.N. refugee agency. Over
7,000 refugees arrived Thursday in Macedonia, the largest number in
at least two weeks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Families from Prizren -- Kosovo's second-largest city -- and
surrounding towns started arriving in Albania Thursday, but the
burst of humanity began around 9 a.m. Friday for a combination of
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband came yesterday. We separated because they were
taking up the men,'' said Hamensha Zyberi, a 28-year-old mother of
two who travelled from Prizren by bus Friday with her mother,
children and in-laws. They were sitting on a sparsely grassed
hillock just past the border checkpoint Friday afternoon, waiting
with thousands of confused others for transportation to Kukes or
anywhere safe.
</P>
<P>
   Like other refugees, she told that Serb police pounded on the
family's door Thursday and asked for the men of the house. They
said they would be back to get the men on Friday, as part of a
nationwide military mobilization, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many also were spurred to leave Prizren now because they had
heard Thursday night on the Kukes television station, which is
available in Kosovo a few hours a night, that people had made it
safely from Prizren across the border without harassment and
without teenaged boys and men being grabbed from their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave my husband's name, so I knew he made it all right,''
said Zyberi. The station routinely broadcasts names of Kosovar
Albanian refugees seeking missing family members or wishing to
deliver a message back to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Men from one family after another told of remaining in hiding
for weeks, fearing the Serb police would come for them any time.
Many said they have been sleeping fully clothed, and some men said
they normally slept in a basement or at different neighbors' homes,
slipping out only after dark to find a place that might be secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the house for three weeks,'' said Islam Abdullahu,
29. ``Women, only women can go out for supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces apparently were not only engaged in a military
mobilization, but intended to drive these people out. For the first
time in a couple of weeks they made available buses -- apparently a
fleet of them -- to carry the Kosovar Albanians from Prizren to the
down of Zhur, about two or three miles from the border crossing.
</P>
<P>
   The Abdullahu family began walking to Albania, but after a short
time said they and dozens of others were picked up by a passing
bus. The Serbian driver asked them to pay 30 Yugoslav dinars each
for the passage, which is a little less than $2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got very crowded,'' said Razije Abdullahu, the 29-year-old
wife of Islam. ``We were standing all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they walked the final miles from Zhur, pushing a stroller
with their two-year-old and a few provisions, and mostly carrying
their other boy of four years.
</P>
<P>
   Other families drove over in cars or tractors hauling carts
crammed with people. Hundreds, or possibly more, were reported
walking. Some elderly people, including a man reported to be 100
years old, arrived sprawled in wheelbarrows covered with blankets
and other emergency provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
