<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9766 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOS-SIETE-HNS &LR;      04-30 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOS-SIETE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'69 KILLING HELPED FUEL HISPANIC RIGHTS MOVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMILY GURNON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Seldom has a single gunshot echoed so long and
so far.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet that killed San Francisco police Officer Joseph
Brodnik 30 years ago Saturday took a life and ruined a family. It
also sparked a political movement and changed the way the Hispanic
community thought of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Brodnik, 41, was killed in a confrontation with several men he
and his partner suspected of burglary. The seven Hispanic suspects,
known collectively as ``Los Siete,'' became a cause celebre in the
Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   After a fiery trial, in which defense attorneys portrayed their
clients as the victims of racism and police brutality, and
Brodnik's partner as a drunken bully who called Hispanics greasers,
the suspects were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   The highly publicized case still reverberates on the streets and
among the police in San Francisco, including Brodnik's son, Bob,
who followed in his father's footsteps and joined the San Francisco
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's torn my family apart,'' said Brodnik, who was 20 years
old and in the Navy when his father was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It split us all up. I haven't seen my mother in 11 years.
That's just what it's done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brodnik declined to discuss it further.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the political climate at the time _ the protests against
the Vietnam War, the Chicano rights movement as well as the growing
immigration of Latin Americans to the city _ the trial had a
tremendous impact, said Carlos Cordova, acting chairman of the La
Raza studies department at San Francisco State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It created a cohesive movement and it became a catalyst for
many individuals to become organized and become very vocal,''
Cordova said.
</P>
<P>
   The case struck a chord in the community because, in 1969, the
mostly white police force often treated Hispanics _ especially
young people _ with suspicion and brutality, said Oscar Rios, the
brother of one of the defendants and now mayor of Watsonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were hanging around, riding around, (the police) would
stop you. Whatever they felt like doing to you, they would do it,''
Rios said.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the shooting, May 1, 1969, Joseph Brodnik and his
43-year-old partner, Paul McGoran, were tracking a group of
burglary suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The plainclothes officers stopped outside a home in Noe Valley
and questioned a group of young men who they believed were carrying
a stolen television.
</P>
<P>
   McGoran told investigators that he was jumped from behind,
knocked down and beaten. In the melee, one of the suspects got
McGoran's gun, and shot Brodnik, McGoran said. Brodnik was unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, lawyers for the young men told a different story.
</P>
<P>
   They said McGoran had accidentally shot his partner while aiming
the gun at one of the suspects. Six young men _ Jose Mario
Martinez, 16; his brother Rodolfo ``Tony'' Martinez, 20; Nelson
Rodriguez, 19; Danilo ``Bebe'' Melendez, 18; Jose Rios, 19; and
Gary Lescallet, 18 _ were arrested and charged with Brodnik's
murder. A seventh, Gio Lopez, was never apprehended.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Joseph Alioto wasted no time in condemning the murder.
Alioto declared an official day of mourning for the slain officer.
</P>
<P>
   News reports described the suspects as ``Latin hippie types''
who appeared at their arraignment ``shaggy-haired and roughly
dressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the community were convinced that the young men were
innocent and would not receive a fair trial, because of their race
and their politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there hadn't been any mobilization from the community, they
would have been railroaded and they would have ended up in jail,''
Oscar Rios said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids identified with (Los Siete), because for one of the first
times, there were young guys saying from the jail, hey, stand up
for your rights. Feel proud of being Latino. They became real
inspirations to a lot of us because they were strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Los Siete were College of San Mateo students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was threatening to the police because we were outspoken; we
were immigrants, but we were not as passive as the majority of the
immigrant population,'' said Reynaldo Aparicio, 51, a friend and
supporter of Los Siete. ``Once you spoke on your own behalf, you
were automatically thought of as a radical.''
</P>
<P>
   After the six were arrested, supporters organized fund-raisers,
protest marches and letter-writing campaigns on their behalf. They
started a Los Siete newspaper called Basta Ya. They showed up, en
masse, at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the jurors would walk out at the luncheon recess, the
halls and corridors were lined with people who (were) _ I suppose
you might call them _ counterculture types,'' said Thomas Norman,
former chief trial lawyer for the district attorney and the
prosecutor in the Los Siete case. ``They would shout at the jurors
as they went down the hall, phrases like, `Free Los Siete!' and
`You'd better free Los Siete or you'll be sorry.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The cops went on trial in this case,'' said Paul Cummins, who
was motivated to become a San Francisco district attorney after
sitting through the trial as a young law student.
</P>
<P>
   McGoran retired from the force after his partner was killed. He
died of a heart attack in 1987, according to his son, Paul McGoran
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the are at the heart of the case _ the Mission District _
is a different place. About 20 percent of the 140 police officers
at Mission Station are Hispanic, which makes a big difference in
how the department is perceived, said station head Capt. Greg Suhr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere you go, you can speak to somebody in their own
language ... People are much more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department is also more accountable to the community
because of agencies like the Office of Citizen Complaints, Cordova
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean it's perfect, but from 1969 there's been a
tremendous change,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0194 </DOCNO>
