</P>
<P>
   ``When the jurors would walk out at the luncheon recess, the
halls and corridors were lined with people who (were) _ I suppose
you might call them _ counterculture types,'' said Thomas Norman,
former chief trial lawyer for the district attorney and the
prosecutor in the Los Siete case. ``They would shout at the jurors
as they went down the hall, phrases like, `Free Los Siete!' and
`You'd better free Los Siete or you'll be sorry.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The cops went on trial in this case,'' said Paul Cummins, who
was motivated to become a San Francisco district attorney after
sitting through the trial as a young law student.
</P>
<P>
   McGoran retired from the force after his partner was killed. He
died of a heart attack in 1987, according to his son, Paul McGoran
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the are at the heart of the case _ the Mission District _
is a different place. About 20 percent of the 140 police officers
at Mission Station are Hispanic, which makes a big difference in
how the department is perceived, said station head Capt. Greg Suhr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere you go, you can speak to somebody in their own
language ... People are much more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department is also more accountable to the community
because of agencies like the Office of Citizen Complaints, Cordova
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean it's perfect, but from 1969 there's been a
tremendous change,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1810EDT &QL; 
