<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9789 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-$ADV0     04-30 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAILED MAN'S EXPOSE OFFERS UNFLATTERING PORTRAIT OF ATHEIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 2)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The book is titled ``Good Gawd, Madalyn.'' It
might better be called, ``Portrait of a Monster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To simply label Madalyn an atheist, racist, homophobe,
anti-Semite, etc, would be a tremendous misnomer. To her dubious
credit, Madalyn Mays Murray O'Hair is an equal-opportunity bigot
whose loathing of humanity is eagerly dispensed without
partiality,'' reads a typical passage.
</P>
<P>
   From flatulence to body odor, from petty cruelties and
hypocrisies to grand treacheries, the sins and social shortcomings
of the woman who was at the vanguard of court battles to remove
prayer and Bible reading from public schools are exposed in this
200-page unpublished expose.
</P>
<P>
   More important, it makes extensive use of internal documents of
the atheist movement to detail an elaborate plan to flee to New
Zealand at least a year before O'Hair disappeared in 1995 with her
two adult children and $500,000 in gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangements included packing up the 150,000 books and
pamphlets of the atheist library and sending them, using various
subterfuges via Houston to Kansas City, for eventual shipment to
New Zealand, according to the book.
</P>
<P>
   This issue is of more than passing importance to the book's
author, David R. Waters, who now sits in a jail in Austin, Texas,
on federal weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents are investigating his role in the disappearance of
O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and daughter Robin Murray O'Hair.
The three disappeared from San Antonio in late September 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, 52, has a criminal record that includes murder. But he
is not charged with any offenses relating to the disappearance of
O'Hair and the other two and denies any knowledge of their fate. An
alleged accomplice, however, has implicated Waters in their
murders, according to the testimony of an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Preston of Garland, the author who wrote the book with
Waters two years ago, said he was left with no clear sense of
Waters' involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that David is a very intelligent man and
speaks very well,'' Preston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was in prison for murder, and I think any sensitive man
with his criminal record would realize that if he knocked off
Madalyn, he would get caught, and that would mean the death penalty
for him,'' Preston said by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Waters speaks of O'Hair in the present tense.
</P>
<P>
   The book could be read as Waters' alibi: O'Hair and the two
children are alive and well in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   However, from another angle, there is ample material to suggest
he would not have mourned their death, foremost because he was
framed for a theft he says he did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the book, Waters, casting himself as yet
another victim of the O'Hair family, is about to plead guilty to
the theft of $54,400 in atheist funds in exchange for 10 years on
probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was caught between a rock and a hard place. If I went to
trial that afternoon, I would stand a better-than-even chance of
spending the rest of my life in prison. Or, (if I did) what I would
have once found unfathomable, namely, plead guilty, I'd be 100
percent assured of returning home with the woman who now stood
before me crying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He referred to Patti Jo Steffens, his long-time girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seared the very fibers of my being, but I did what was
necessary to insure that I went home with the woman I loved. I
pleaded guilty. Chalk up another victory for Madalyn Murray
O'Hair,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   After the plea in May 1995, Waters was sentenced to 10 years'
probation and ordered to repay the $54,400.
</P>
<P>
   The amount was later reduced to $15,000 when Waters shared with
Travis County officials some documents he admits in the book that
he purloined from Jon Murray's private files.
</P>
<P>
   The book is based on 14 months in 1993 and 1994, when Waters
worked for O'Hair in Austin, first as typesetter and then as office
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Preston said the copies of facsimiles, letters and other
documents that Waters provided him appeared authentic. But, he
said, he places no particular faith in Waters' veracity.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a case like this, I fall back on the old Hollywood saying,
`Never trust, never believe,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The book opens in February 1993, as Waters answers a classified
advertisement for a job at American Atheist General Headquarters in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   With a lengthy criminal record including murder, battery and
forgery, Waters had been unemployed for more than a year, dependent
on the income of Steffens, and he was willing to try anything.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Waters, who once beat someone to death, casts
himself as the wayfaring innocent as he signed up with O'Hair to
set type for her newsletter for $7 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Little did he imagine he was entering the twisted realm of a
woman he portrayed as a smelly, foul-mouthed bully who brooked no
second opinion or dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind conjured up visions of an environment rife with
intellectual debate and youthful philosophizing as to the meaning
of life and the existence of God. How (expletive) naive,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after, to his amazement and gratitude, the O'Hair
family did not fire him when they learned of his criminal past.
</P>
<P>
   ``That crap is history, kiddo,'' he recalls Madalyn telling him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we know you're not some (expletive) Christer sent
here to spy on us ... So, do your job, keep your mouth shut, and
you'll have a job here for as long as you like,'' he quoted her as
saying.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair later claimed she did not learn of his criminal past
until far later, after the $54,400 disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Waters account unfolds, this early encounter marked
one of the last times he felt anything but loathing and anger
toward O'Hair and her two adult children.
</P>
<P>
   Jon was a lisping, anal-retentive, foul-mouthed boor; Robin was
nasty; Madalyn was the unquestioned ruler of all that passed behind
the tinted glass windows of atheist headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was truly an enigma. She would discuss current events,
history, law, art, stamp collecting, literature and many other
subjects in a most knowledgeable and scholarly manner; yet she
exhibited a profound and almost sadistic glee in using the vilest
of language, often making a casual obscenity take on more revolting
overtones simply in the way she phrased her words, and in the tone
of voice she used,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, Waters records the fates of dedicated atheist
staff members who were fired by O'Hair on trumped-up issues to save
a few pennies, or who quit after being beaten down by the
capricious rule of the O'Hair troika.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote about O'Hair's derision toward her boards of
directors and her faithful members, and he marvels at her ability
to raise money while whining about hard times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed. And appalled. This shrewd, hard-as-nails old
woman controlled an empire consisting of a mere 2,081 members, and
yet she amassed millions of dollars in cash, bonds, property and
other assets. All the while she pleaded poverty,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Move over Bob Tilton, Jim Bakker, and all you other religious
hucksters ... Per capita, Madalyn had you all beat to hell,'' the
booklet says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
