<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, April 30. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JACKSON (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The three captive
American servicemen held by Yugoslavia talked on Friday with Jesse
Jackson and said that they are being kept in separate cells, have
no contact with each other or with other prisoners in the same
facility, were able to take a walk outside their cells only twice
during their monthlong imprisonment, but are generally well-fed and
have no medical problems. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MASSACRE (Kukes, Albania) _ A harrowing account of a
recent massacre in Kosovo as told by its sole survivor. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Ledeall on the
shootings: Authorities are increasingly on the defensive about
their actions or non-response to warnings about Eric Harris'
threats. Other developments. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ America's extraordinary economic boom _
the second-longest so far in more than a century and a half _ shows
no signs of flagging. Despite a decline in auto production and
another sharp deterioration in the nation's trade balance, the U.S.
economy grew at a surprisingly robust 4.5 percent rate this winter,
the government reported. That is the sort of heady pace usually
associated with the first, not the eighth, year of an economic
expansion and hardly the sharp slowdown from last fall's sizzling 6
percent rate that forecasters, including the Federal Reserve, were
expecting as recently as a couple of days ago. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-HEALTHCARE (Nashville, Tenn.) _ In one bold stroke,
Tennessee converted its Medicaid health benefits to managed care
five years ago and used the savings to cover people who couldn't
afford health insurance of their own or were too sick to qualify.
With 3 million people enrolled, its program, called TennCare,
became the most ambitious and generous government health plan in
the nation. But with TennCare's costs rising and Tennessee facing a
budget deficit, the program is facing retrenchment at the orders of
Gov. Don Sundquist. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   BROKERS-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The Justice Department has
opened a broad antitrust investigation into the practices of some
of Wall Street's largest securities firms in setting rates for
initial public offerings, federal officials and defense lawyers
said. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM (Hartford, Conn.) _ The owner of the New
England Patriots, Robert Kraft, refused a demand Friday night by
Gov. John Rowland of Connecticut that the team reject a last-minute
stadium offer from Massachusetts, but Kraft said he would continue
working with Connecticut for now. By Mike Allen.
</P>
