<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-COLLECTING-SPRIT     04-30 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-COLLECTING-SPRITE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTING: A BUGEYE'S (BORN AGAIN) LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PAUL DUCHENE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEIZER, Ore. _ Racers say, ``The older you get, the faster you
were.'' Rex Urban is making that boast come true for the Austin
Healey Bugeye Sprite, a 40-year-old sports car that in reality
never moved as quickly as it does in fond memories.
</P>
<P>
   In his four-man shop in this suburb of Salem, Urban, 44,
restores baby boomers' high school dreams. And he rebuilds the
British sports cars so that this time they really work _ and zip
right along.
</P>
<P>
   The speciality of his business, Mini Motors Classic Coachworks,
is the Sprite _ commonly called the Bugeye or Frogeye because of
its protruding headlamps. The Sprite was introduced in 1958 as an
entry-level sports car that used parts from two tiny commuter
sedans, the Austin A30 and the Morris Minor. The simple roadster
had a four-cylinder engine displacing only 948 cubic centimeters.
It had a one-piece hood-and-fender unit; side curtains instead of
windows, no exterior door handles, and a trunk with no outside
opening. But it was structurally rigid, handled well and could go
80 miles an hour while getting 30 miles to the gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Urban's fascination with Bugeyes began in high school. His
graduation present in 1971 was ``Bessie'' (named for its Oregon
license plate, BES 335), a blue 1960 Sprite that he still owns. He
had so much fun, he blew up the motor within a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother had an MG Midget and we had both cars apart in the
garage at the same time,'' he said. ``Everything was
interchangeable _ it was a revelation!''
</P>
<P>
   Urban later planned to import Sprites with Fiberglas bodies and
space frames _ tubular skeletons resembling bird cages, which are
exceptionally light and strong. Such cars have long been available
in Britain. But the American government wanted to classify them as
brand-new cars, requiring them to meet today's emissions and safety
standards. And the English manufacturer started worrying about its
liability.
</P>
<P>
   The coup de grace was delivered by a new, inexpensive sports
car, the Mazda Miata. ``The Miata sold for $13,000 back in 1991,
and we figured the space-frame cars were going to cost $25,000,''
Urban said.
</P>
<P>
   So he turned to rebuilding Sprites, Midgets, MGAs, MGBs and
``big'' Austin Healeys to customers' specifications. Some look as
they did when new; some are wildly customized.
</P>
<P>
   One of Urban's Bugeyes has been clocked at 120 miles an hour.
Like most, it has disk/drum brakes, adjustable shock absorbers,
competition axles and dual-bearing rear hubs that take the stress
off the axle.
</P>
<P>
   The four-cylinder engine is a 1,275-cc unit with electronic
ignition, high-performance camshaft and stainless-steel valves. It
is mated to a Nissan five-speed transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, while prices of fancy Miatas have reached $27,000,
his rebuilt Bugeyes start at $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bess is one of about 50,000 Bugeyes made in 1958-61 _ the first,
best-loved generation of Sprites. Most came to the United States,
and Urban estimates that half still exist, giving him plenty of raw
material for his rebuilt ``Super Sprites.''
</P>
<P>
   He has had hands-on experience in developing the details of what
works and what doesn't. For years, he raced Bessie successfully in
Sports Car Club of America races, though she is now semi-retired to
street use.
</P>
<P>
   In 20 years of working on British cars he reckons he has skinned
his knuckles on several hundred Bugeyes. He has totally rebuilt
about 50. ``I can do about three a year from the ground up, and I'm
booked through this year,'' he said. ``I could do many, many more
if I could get the help. It's so hard to find anybody who wants to
do this kind of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Urban is looking for practitioners of an arcane craft _ the
ability to ``panel beat'' and exactly re-create structural body
pieces. Such skills were common in the assembly of hand-built cars
in the past _ the kind that were driven to extinction by the same
mass-produced vehicles Urban is now repairing.
</P>
<P>
   At Mini Motors now, two cars exist as stripped shells. A
seven-year employee, Tom Birch, 33, is remanufacturing rusted parts
on a panel form that can create compound curves from a single sheet
of steel. By beating the panel over a metal wheel, a complete
fender can be created in one process. It takes a lot of time, but
is quite precise.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sprites are honeycombed with crevices that trap water and
dirt, making them prone to rust even in states like Oregon that do
not salt roads in winter.
</P>
<P>
   A restoration _ what the shop owner calls an ``Urban renewal'' _
includes a a body and chassis dipped in an acid wash to remove
oxidation, then sealed and and painted with urethane. Most people
elect to have the rear-hinged hood (which includes the fenders)
altered to tilt forward for better access to the engine. The
interior can be leather or vinyl, and Urban makes an exact copy of
the original factory hardtop for $850. He also offers a lockable
trunk-access panel behind the seats _ no small consideration in a
car without a trunk lid or door locks.
</P>
<P>
   Urban became friendly with the car's originators, Donald Healey
and his son Geoff, before both men died. From those contacts, he is
able to buy windshields and sidescreens from the original British
supplier.
</P>
<P>
   The original Bugeye had a 948-cc engine, but so far nobody has
wanted to keep it. ``I've got piles of them,'' Urban said. But he
is always on the lookout for 1,275-cc engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that Midget over there?'' he said, pointing to a '74 model
waiting to be repainted. ``We prey on those.''
</P>
<P>
   So why buy an Urban Sprite for as much as $20,000 instead of an
average Bugeye for about $5,000? ``I can build up to 140-horsepower
engines, but I build a really good 100-horsepower one. I've turned
96 miles an hour in a quarter mile, and with a five-speed
transmission I get up to 37 miles per gallon on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've never been beaten by a Miata. If I ever do, it's back
to the drawing board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
