<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOG-0501-COX     04-30 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOG-0501-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHITE HOUSE TO ANNOUNCE NEW AIR POLLUTION RULES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - President Clinton is expected to announce on
Saturday new clean air standards that would reduce the permissible
level of sulfur in gasoline and force most sports utility vehicles
to meet emission standards required of automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   By calling the four-wheel-drive vehicles ``trucks,'' car makers
have not had to account for pollutants such as nitrogen oxides and
smoke under limits set for automobiles under the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules are to be proposed by the Environmental Protection
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Although the White House and EPA were trying to keep details of
the rules from becoming public until Clinton was able to announce
them during his weekly radio program Saturday, environmental and
industry groups pieced together enough details to start issuing
reactions Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations said that if the rules are finally approved --
around the end of the year -- the new standards would:
</P>
<P>
   -- Require oil companies to reduce the sulfur content of
gasoline by enough to the meet in every state the standard already
set by California -- an average reduction of about 90 percent
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   -- Require car makers to reduce by an average of about 90
percent the emission of oxides of nitrogen, or ``NOX'', the key
ingredient of urban smog.
</P>
<P>
   -- Require that sports utility vehicles weighing less than 8,000
pounds be counted as cars for the purpose of computing overall
fleet average emission levels.
</P>
<P>
   NOX emissions would be limited to about 0.07 gram per mile under
the new rules, as opposed to 0.6 gram per mile currently permitted.
</P>
<P>
   The concentration of sulfur in gasoline, which varies widely but
averages around 330 parts per million, would have to go down to 30
parts per million, the current California standard.
</P>
<P>
   Frank O'Donnell, executive director of the Clean Air Trust, an
environmental group, said the timing under which sports utility
vehicles come under the federal emission limits would mean the
largest vehicles will not have to meet the toughest standards until
2009.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA is offering us a breath of fresh air,'' O'Donnell said,
``but we going to have to wait too long to inhale.''
</P>
<P>
   Motor vehicle manufacturers have generally supported removal of
sulfur from gasoline because the crude oil residue gums up
catalytic converters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can produce 21st century technology, but we need 21st
century fuel to use it,'' said Ed Lewis, a spokesman for the
Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Petroleum Institute and the National
Petrochemical &AMP; Refiners Association said a 90 percent reduction in
gasoline sulfur content would be ``unnecessarily costly.''
</P>
<P>
   The new standards were applauded by the Environmental Defense
Fund, the U.S. Public Interest Research Group and the National Lung
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
