<HEADER>
A9802 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     04-30 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOAH'S ARK' WON'T FLOAT YOUR BOAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Noah's Ark'' must have looked perfectly fine on paper. The
production arrives via Robert Halmi Sr.'s big, bigger, biggest
grinder, which has manufactured hits (''Merlin'') and misses (''The
Odyssey''). And he may very well have assembled the most decorated
cast in a TV movie ever, what with four Oscars and one Emmy spread
among the cast members.
</P>
<P>
   But from start to finish, ``Noah's Ark,'' premiering the first
of two parts at 8 p.m. CDT Sunday on NBC, is a complete and utter
mess. It takes the biblical story of Noah as told in the book of
Genesis and butchers the poor thing into little, unrecognizable
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar winner Jon Voight, bearded and with hair blanketing his
shoulders and back, portrays Noah as a committed wise man who never
wavers in his beliefs. When asked to vacate the sin-filled Sodom,
he does, only to watch the place burned to the ground by fireballs
raining from the heavens. When asked to build a boat large enough
for two of every animal, he does, escaping the 40-day, 40-night
flood that wipes out everyone _ except his loudmouth enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, enough scums of the earth survived in order to stage
a dramatic battle to take over the Ark. (Noah, his wife, three sons
and their girlfriends fend them off with pots and pans and other
weapons until God has enough and tidal waves drown the outlaws.)
</P>
<P>
   This happens on the second night, which veers even more off
course. ``Noah's Ark'' wants to tell an emotional story about what
happens to eight people stuck at sea. But it merely turns into a
low-grade ``Waterworld,'' in which the punks on water bikes are
replaced by pirates brandishing rotten teeth and spitting on one
another every time they speak.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of this band of merry men is Lot, played by Oscar
winner F. Murray Abraham, who is more comical than anything else as
a mangled-faced psycho.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Peter Barnes also included the role of an opportunistic
peddler, played by James Coburn, Oscar winner No. 3. He initially
turns up in Sodom, loaded down with all sorts of salable items,
which I suppose he lifted from the nearest gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as the Ark floats in the middle of nowhere, he turns up
on a boat filled with goodies, asking if they need to replenish
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth Oscar winner here is Mary Steenburgen, who plays
Noah's patient, trusting wife, Naamah.
</P>
<P>
   The Emmy winner? That's Carol Kane, who plays Lot's wife as a
yapping discontent who turns into a pillar of salt after disobeying
God's will by looking back as fireballs rained on Sodom. (Lot, ever
the nurturing husband, breaks off a finger and keeps it.)
</P>
<P>
   At least ``Noah's Ark'' is upfront with its, well, rewriting of
the Bible. Viewers will be told at the beginning that ``For
dramatic effect, we have taken the poetic license with some of the
events of the mighty epic of Noah and the flood.''
</P>
<P>
   For that alone, a friend of mine eager to see this miniseries
seemed disappointed, partly because she had plans of making it a
family event with her young children, filling the evening with
biblical discussion.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion is to skip it and read the few pages devoted to
Noah in the Bible instead. Book adaptations in general are
difficult creatures. In the age of ratings and profits, expecting a
network to stick with the essence of any classic, let alone the
Bible, is asking a bit much.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere this week:
</P>
<P>
   A six-hour documentary promises to change viewers' feelings
toward Europe. It travels from Norway to the beaches of Portugal to
offer a European vacation of a different beat. ``Wild Seas,'' (8 to
10 p.m. CDT Sunday, PBS) is the first installment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thug Life in D.C.'' (10 p.m. CDT Tuesday, HBO) Filmmakers Marc
Levin and Daphne Pinkerson go inside the D.C. prison system to hear
the stories of some of the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   This installment of the ``America Undercover'' documentary
series focuses on a 17-year-old who faces the possibility of 115
years behind bars if convicted of shooting a police officer and
murdering a teen-ager. He calls himself ``the definition of thug''
_ someone who is ready to do what it takes to get what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   The most disturbing thing about ``Thug Life in D.C.'' is the
hopelessness. Like many of the others, the 17-year-old grew up in
poverty and without a father. Most of the people he knew had served
jail time. Doing time is as much a rite of passage as graduating
from high school is for many others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down Will Come Baby'' (8 p.m. Tuesday, CBS) Meredith Baxter
stars as a workaholic mother who sees warning signs when a stranger
tries to move into her daughter's life, but who can't do much about
it until it's too late. Diana Scarwid] is the woman with more than
friendship on her mind, and Tom Amandes portrays the husband, the
most clueless person alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down Will Come Baby'' fails to move past the cliches. This is
ultimately a movie that CBS figures has enough of a provocative
premise to at least lure eyeballs. Baxter does her thing, playing a
strong-willed woman even while in emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
