<HEADER>
A9805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-IMF-NYT &LR;      04-30 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MINISTERS SAY A DEFERRED REPAYMENT PLAN IS CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Fresh from concluding a vital debt refinancing
agreement with the International Monetary Fund, top Russian
ministers said Friday that foreign creditors were close to agreeing
on deferred repayment of the country's Soviet-era loans.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the officials played down the political
disputes that the IMF agreement could cause within the Russian
parliament and the government. The IMF's terms commit the Russians
to making painful economic changes.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov said the deferment of $16
billion in payments on the Soviet Union's debt to foreign
governments and banks remained only to be ``put on the record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, all preconditions for such accords have been
created,'' Zadornov told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the IMF announced that it would release $4.5
billion in credits over the next 18 months so that Russia could
essentially pay the lender what it owes from past loans. The
collapse of the Russian economy in August 1998 resulted in a
default on $40 billion in domestic debt and pushed Russia to the
edge of default on much of its external debt.
</P>
<P>
   Russia needed an economic program approved by the IMF before it
could restructure the foreign debt it had inherited from the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Zadornov said a Russian government delegation in Washington this
past week had spoken to representatives of the governments and
banks that hold the Soviet debt, with encouraging results. But he
said that even if these creditors agreed to defer repayments over
the next two years, Russia's debt problems remained severe. ``We
will not be able to make foreign debt payments over the next 10
years according to the original schedule,'' Zadornov said.
</P>
<P>
   On a related topic, Zadornov said almost 89 percent of foreign
investors in Russian Treasury bills had agreed to final terms of
the domestic debt restructuring. Foreigners hold about $17 billion
of the total sum. The most notable dissenter to the deal is Credit
Suisse First Boston, which invested in Treasury bills worth about
$770 million at the time of the economic crash, according to
Zadornov. The minister said no special terms would be offered to
Credit Suisse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Russian government may find greater understanding
abroad about its difficult economic straits than at home. For the
IMF to release the loans, the government must adhere to the
economic program the two sides have developed. But the program
includes new taxes that will be hard to put into effect in an
election year. Parliamentary elections are scheduled for the end of
1999, and the presidential vote for the middle of next year.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the economic program rests in large part with the
Communist-controlled Duma, or lower house, which historically has
been hostile to IMF-related policies. The first deputy prime
minister in charge of the economy, Yuri Maslyukov, insisted Friday
that only a small portion of the IMF program required action by the
Duma. Maslyukov did not mention, however, that those measures were
perhaps the most critical.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, for Russia to fulfill its 1999 budget projections
it must raise more revenue through new taxes, which require
parliamentary approval. The IMF conditions call for an increase in
the export tariff on oil and significant increases in taxes on
gasoline and alcohol, which are sure to be unpopular among voters.
Moreover, they are expected to cause another round of inflation.
Since the August crisis, prices in Russia have risen 97 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
