<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-JOBS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE INVADERS, JUST A DESK AWAY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Texas, Maine, Md.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)In the compressed world of the office, little things
mean a lot. And when someone has an annoying habit or seems to
think that any kind of behavior is acceptable, co-workers can
suffer _ often in silence. And even when they speak up, their
protests can go unheard.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Fortune 500 company where Lynne Hawes of Mount Kisco,
N.Y., worked, her office was directly across a small hallway from
one occupied by a young woman who, as Ms. Hawes puts it,
``weaponized her telephone for daily battle for much of the working
day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Acoustics were unusually excellent and I didn't _ couldn't _
miss a sigh or syllable,'' Ms. Hawes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early morning's conversation began with her munching
donuts and slurping coffee while explaining to her mother that she
had come home at 20 past 12, not plenty past 12 last night, and
that her life was her business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next, she would call her girlfriend and passionately describe
the details of last night's date.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hawes would occasionally clear her throat or cough to
demonstrate how sound could travel _ but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her pitch was loud; emotion high; vulgarisms sprinkled
liberally throughout descriptions,'' Ms. Hawes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job was editorial, and I found myself writing inane
comments on the work I was reading, reflecting my co-worker's
hectic life, rather than critiquing appropriately the text I was
editing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lifted my phone and dialed her extension to ask her to
please close her door. She suggested I close my door.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the advertising agency where Jaime J. Jasso of San Antonio
worked, there was an otherwise ordinary account supervisor who
would walk through the art department and invariably break into
song.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worse yet, it was always the same song and (worse still)
always incorrectly sung,'' Jasso writes. ```Hey, hey for the
Monkees,' he'd sing, for no apparent reason other than (perhaps) he
was in a good mood. We could think of no other rational explanation
for the theme song of the late 1960s phenomenon to remain stuck in
his mind and surface so unexpectedly, so often.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, a co-worker and I drew him into an extended
conversation by asking him about the Monkees. Were they favorites
of his, or was there some other reason he was so obviously fond of
the group some 28 years after their popularity had peaked? Did he
know they were derisively referred to as the `pre-Fab Four'? Was he
even vaguely aware that by 1995 they were considered a bit passe?
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that he was not aware of either the fact that he
was singing out loud or that the Monkees were generally held in low
esteem (never mind that the (italics)correct(end italics) lyrics
were ``Hey, hey we're the Monkees''). But from that point on,
whenever we heard him sing his spirited version of the Monkees'
theme song, we would ask him about the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would seem to snap him back into focus somehow. At the
very least, he would leave our area immediately rather than endure
our questions.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like having a co-worker who has converted her
desk into her `toilet,''' writes Joyce Henckle of Bangor, Maine.
``Now I mean this in the true tradition of an Elizabethan novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, she says, who was `unlucky enough to arrive at work
early was subject to the just-from-the-shower look that was, in
over a half-hour of time, transformed into Madame Butterfly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This co-worker had every cosmetic resource known to humankind
at her disposal in her desk. We are talking a propane-powered
curling iron, an electrified magnifying mirror for those
hard-to-get-at eyebrow hairs, a hot pot to make oatmeal in every
morning and a loud selection of her favorite music to put her in
the mood for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever this behavior received comment, she reminded us that
even if she was at her desk, the workday had not yet started.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that she has put some 500 miles between herself and a
newspaper where some of her co-workers manifested a variety of
off-putting habits, Claire Papanastasiou of Baltimore can reminisce
and wax philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   She calls one of her office mates the Sneeze That Roared.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the newsroom would know when it would strike, but
when it did, hold on to your computers,'' she writes. ``The hardest
times were during the winters when this woman would sneeze like
Godzilla at least 15 times a day; no one would ever say, `God bless
you.' We'd say, `Thank God we survived that one,' or `What was the
Richter reading this time?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9811 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-CAP-NAT     04-30 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CAP-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        LEGIONNAIRE'S BACTERIA FOUND AT U.S. CAPITOL POWER PLANT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, April 30, -- Federal safety inspectors recently
found ``potentially hazardous'' levels of Legionnaire's bacteria at
the power plant that supplies heating and air conditioning to the
Capitol and Congressional offices.
</P>
<P>
   Despite warnings last year that bacteria levels must be
monitored at least monthly, no tests had been performed for the
last several months, inspectors said.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors from the congressional Office of Compliance issued a
citation last week to the Architect of the Capitol, the office
which oversees the power plant, for failing to conduct the tests
and exposing employees to the ``hazard of developing Legionnaire's
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no risk the bacteria could be sent into the Capitol or
congressional offices, inspectors said. But the bacteria, found in
a cooling tower at the facility, presented a risk to employees of
the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the architect's office said they had no knowledge
that any employee has contracted the illness. The office has 2,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
   For the next year, the architect's office must conduct culture
tests on the cooling towers at least monthly and submit the results
to inspectors, the citation said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legionella bacteria is ubiquitous and occurs naturally,''
wrote H.M. Franklin, administrative assistant to the architect of
the capitol in a response to the citation. ``The level that can be
causative of disease is a matter of medical disagreement. The
Architect of the Caitol has adopted a regimen to keep such
concentrations as low as practicable.''
</P>
<P>
   The first cases of Legionnaire's disease were discovered in 1976
when 182 people contracted a pneumonia-like illness at an American
Legion
</P>
<P>
   conference in Philadelphia. Twenty nine died.
</P>
<P>
   Legionnaire's victims may develop flu symptoms, or bronchial
problems. The disease varies in severity and can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Don Maddrey, a spokesman for the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees, the union which represents
employees of the architect's office, described the Capitol as a
``cess pool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe the working conditions at the U.S.
Capitol,'' Maddrey said. ``It's pretty primitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
