<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-BLADES-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALSA SINGER'S PARTY FORCED TO FACE THE MUSIC IN PANAMA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, May 2) 
 
(Eds.: Also see: Panama-Election) 
(Eds.: Last week is cq) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ Salsa star Ruben Blades doesn't like being
the warm-up act.
</P>
<P>
   But the Panamanian singer, actor and part-time politician, had
little choice last week when he took the stage at an outdoor rally
to endorse presidential candidate Martin Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   Torrijos, of the ruling Revolutionary Democratic Party, or PRD,
was the headliner because Blades' political party, Papa Egoro, has
virtually collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics blame Blades for trying to manhandle the party from
abroad as he goes about making movies and recording CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to run the party by fax from Hollywood,'' said Eric
Jackson, editor of the Panama News, a weekly newspaper. ``It's been
a big disappointment to many, many people.``
</P>
<P>
   Papa Egoro, which means ``mother earth'' in the Embera Indian
language, was formed in 1992. Led by Blades, the party projected a
youthful image and attracted thousands of Panamanians who had never
voted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Blades finished a respectable third place in a
seven-way presidential race, while Papa Egoro won six seats in the
congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt very satisfied,'' said Carl Nordstrom, the party's
vice president. ``In just two years, we showed that old-style
politics was over.``
</P>
<P>
   But after the campaign, Blades returned to his home in the
United States where he was distracted by a messy divorce, Nordstrom
said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Panama, Papa Egoro was also on the verge of a breakup.
Two of its six legislators were kicked out of the party because of
political disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of running its own presidential candidate this year,
Papa Egoro formed an alliance with the PRD, a traditional party
that has been plagued by corruption scandals and was closely allied
with former dictator Manuel Noriega.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Blades insisted on controlling Papa Egoro, said Raul
Leis, who resigned as the party's secretary-general in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``He once said that directing a political party is like
directing an orchestra,'' Leis said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many political parties, Leis said, Papa Egoro has been hurt
by its focus on a strong personality rather than strong ideas. That
appears unlikely to change soon.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about possible nominees for Panama's 2004
presidential race, Nordstrom said, ``Our candidate is and always
will be Ruben Blades.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
