<HEADER>
A9821 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUYINGART-TEX     04-30 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYINGART-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE INTIMIDATED _ BUYING A PAINTING IS MUCH LIKE BUYING A
FRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're at that happy point in life where you have a balance left
in your checking account _ not only after paying bills, but after
you've covered the ski trip and the kids' new iMac game, to boot.
Maybe, you say to yourself, it would be fun and intriguing to start
buying some art.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, you're thinking, you should have plunked down money to
attend the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth's big fund-raising
auction last month. It featured everything from Picasso to a pair
of bowls thrown by someone the art critic knew in college.
</P>
<P>
   But auctions, even when they're reliably conducted, aren't for
beginners.
</P>
<P>
   Where, then? You're just not sure.
</P>
<P>
   It's strange but true: A lot of otherwise savvy consumers turn
clammy and clueless when it comes to buying art. After all, art
possesses a mystique not associated with other commodities.
</P>
<P>
   So we have identified this simple strategy: Pretend, instead,
that you're buying a refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   First, do your homework. Visit established dealers and consider
various names or brands. Are you looking for reliability?
Innovation? Do some reading, find out background. Make sure you've
considered a variety of options.
</P>
<P>
   Decide what you want and what you can afford, and work with the
dealer who suits you best.
</P>
<P>
   When you make your decision, arrange financing. Then take it
home (or have it delivered) and install it.
</P>
<P>
   There, you didn't even break a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   So go forth. Acquire. And be prepared to enjoy for far more
years and in far more ways than any fridge _ Sub-Zero or not _ can
offer.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STEP ONE: DO YOUR HOMEWORK AND GO WINDOW-SHOPPING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are all kinds of artworks you can buy: American Indian
baskets; video installations; figurative paintings; assemblages of
coral, tin can and ballpoint pen.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, consider your options. Give yourself at least
three or four months to soak up gallery and museum shows, to read
and to talk with people you know who buy art.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, you may be looking for art to fulfill specific
requirements. Do you want something soothing and easy on the eyes?
Do you want something that fits your decor or stands on its own? Do
you want something that is sure to prompt questions or just minds
its own business?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people buy to enhance a room in their home,'' says Pam
Campbell, co-owner of William Campbell Contemporary Art. ``If they
become more serious about collecting, they start buying because
they are emotionally attracted to a piece.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened with Gregg and Mary Brauer, whose downtown
Fort Worth loft is studded with artworks they've bought over the
past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got started the way I think a lot of people do, with more
of an interest in decoration than art, per se,'' Gregg Brauer says.
``We had the classic bare-walls syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   As their tastes changed and matured, though, the Brauers started
simply buying what they liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when we bring it home, the art finds its own place,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STEP TWO: CONNECT WITH A DEALER WHO SELLS WHAT YOU LIKE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After you've been everywhere and seen everything, decide what
``you'' like. Never mind trends. Forget what your nosy neighbor
might say. Connect with the dealer whose inventory fits your taste.
</P>
<P>
   First-time buyers are best off with an established gallery or
private dealer. Auctions, hotel-room sales, catalogs and Internet
buying are fraught with uncertainties, even if you're an
experienced collector.
</P>
<P>
   When you identify your gallery, don't assume that all they have
is what's on the walls. The gallery owner should offer to bring out
material from the back room or from flat files.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, dealers can have works sent in for your
inspection, in which case all you're obligated to pay for is
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   If you see something you like, ask if you can have it held for a
few days, or have the right of first refusal. That way, you can
look at it two or three more times before you make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also will bring things to a client's home or office, so
they can live with them for a couple of days,'' Campbell says. If
you're a new client, she'll probably ask for a credit card imprint
but, again, you're under no obligation to buy.
</P>
<P>
   And please, please don't start buying art as an investment.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're buying museum-quality work, art is a poor
investment, says veteran Fort Worth collector Bill Runyon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the statistic I've seen is that only 2 percent of the
art that sells actually appreciates in value and stays up there,''
says Runyon, who moved from buying work by blue-chip artists to
taking his chances with promising new kids on the block.
</P>
<P>
   That said, price (as well as visual preference) is a good
guideline for beginning collectors.
</P>
<P>
   The Brauers quickly realized that first-rate works by emerging
local artists could be had for a fraction of what they'd pay for
inferior pieces by marquee names. So start with an inexpensive _
say $200 to $300 _ purchase of good quality as a
confidence-builder.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Campbell says, ``Just be yourself. Don't worry
about sounding ultra-sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Brauer puts it: ``There is no secret handshake you need
to know in order to buy a piece of art.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STEP THREE: BUY IT
</P>
<P>
   Most galleries accept credit cards, but just as many allow you
to pay for an artwork in installments _ at no extra cost. And most
of them allow you to take the artwork home before it's paid off.
</P>
<P>
   So, all things considered _ the low price of good local art, the
services a dealer can extend _ the decent thing to do is not ask
for a discount. Instead, think of a discount as a reward you may
earn (along with stuff like getting invited to special previews and
studio visits) after you've become an established client.
</P>
<P>
   What else?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if, after a few years pass and you continue
buying, some of your initial acquisitions seem too easy. This is
part of the territory. Your best bet is to await a local
fund-raising auction and donate such works to a worthy cause.
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
