<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, ZEDILLO TALK POLITICS AND DEDICATE NEW BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush stepped into the
international arena Friday to discuss politics with Mexican
President Ernesto Zedillo before the two dedicated a new bridge
across the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   The men, who met privately, discussed Zedillo's plans for the
further democratization of Mexico's election system and Bush's
thoughts on a run for the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was interested in my political plans, and I was in his,''
Bush said. ``I believe he is going to go down as one of the best
political reformers in Mexican history.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Zedillo praised Bush and President Clinton as
``friends for Mexico,'' but he made no further political comments.
Zedillo did not pass the mid-point of the bridge to cross into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential exploratory committee that was formed in March is
evaluating Bush's campaign prospects and raising money coast to
coast. But Bush reiterated that he would wait until the Texas
legislative session ends in four weeks before making any decisions
about running for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is going well, but first things first,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush focused on international relations in his public comments
during the dedication of the Veterans Memorial Bridge that links
Brownsville with Matamoros, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He told the crowd of about 1,000 people that Mexico and the
United States can solve more problems and create more jobs as
friends than as adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some in this world who would rather build a wall
than a bridge,'' said Bush, who was dressed casually in an
open-collar shirt against the South Texas heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bridge says even though we have problems we can solve them
in the spirit of friendship rather than animosity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The four-lane bridge, the 13th to dot the Texas-Mexico border
from Brownsville to Laredo, will serve as a direct connection
between U.S. 77, which will become Interstate 69, and a
six-to-eight lane loop in Matamoros.
</P>
<P>
   The structure, which cost U.S. state, local and federal
governments $68 million, is expected to relieve congestion
resulting from expanding cross-border trade.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo praised the bridge as an example of his country's
partnership with the United States and said he would work to expand
free trade with as many countries as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bridge serves as an example of the confidence and trust
between out countries,'' Zedillo said. ``Free trade has meant more
and better opportunities for all countries participating.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Zedillo met privately on the Mexican side of the border
in a brief ceremony to dedicate a customs booth there. Although the
two were side-by-side on a platform in the middle of the bridge,
Zedillo never set foot in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's term ends in 2000 and he has vowed to open the process
by which his successor will be selected. The presidency has been
dominated by the same political party, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, for more than 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he and Zedillo discussed a host of issues including
primaries in Mexico's coming elections, the global impact of
Brazilian economic woes and the challenges of raising teen-agers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
