<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAST CHICAGOAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 02, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, when Andrei Shleifer was a 25-year-old
assistant professor fresh out of graduate school, a postcard
arrived one winter morning in his mail in Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   On the front was one of of the iconic images of modern
economics: a photo of Milton Friedman and George Stigler strolling
together along a shady Hyde Park street. Seen from the back were
the long and the short of the Chicago school: two men who organized
a movement that had worn away the Iron Curtain through sheer force
of intellect.
</P>
<P>
   Penned onto the sidewalk next to the famous pair was a small
circle with an x in it.
</P>
<P>
   On the back was a note from Stigler.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is room for more on the sidewalk.''
</P>
<P>
   That summer Shleifer left Princeton for Chicago. He remained
there for nearly four years, long enough to prove Stigler right.
Then, at the age of 29, he decamped to Harvard and a full
professorship.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Shleifer found himself in the news when, as expected,
he won the John Bates Clark Medal, which is awarded every two years
to the most distinguished US economist under 40. Shleifer is 39.
</P>
<P>
   He thus joined a long list of stars who have won the prize in
the past quarter century: Kevin M. Murphy, University of Chicago
Graduate School of Business; David Card University of California at
Berkeley; Lawrence Summers, US Treasury Department; Paul Krugman,
Massachusetts Institute of Technology; David Kreps, Stanford
Graduate School of Business; Sanford Grossman, Wharton School of
the University of Pennyslvania; Jerry Hausman, MIT; James Heckman,
University of Chicago; Michael Spence, Stanford Graduate School of
Business; Joseph Stiglitz, World Bank; and Martin Feldstein,
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Joining a far longer list of potential stars who didn't win the
medal were MIT's Joshua Angrist, Princeton's Bo Honore and Alan
Krueger, and Harvard's Michael Kremer. The fuss in recent years
over the Clark medal has its critics: Imagine if baseball was to
pick only one Most Valuable Player and do so only every other year.
What kind of a guide would that be to the World Series of a given
year? What sort of tip sheet to the Hall of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, no denying that Shleifer makes good copy, if
only because the best mid-career US economist first set foot in the
United States at the age of 15. His parents emigrated to Rochester
in 1976, among the very first Jews permitted to leave the Soviet
Union under a set of new agreements. His father is an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   By 1978, Shleifer was headed for Harvard; his test scores were
off the map. A freshman friend, J. Bradford De Long, remembers an
introductory economics section led by an expert on the Soviet
economy _ and attended regularly by the alum of Moscow Math and
Science High School Number Two. ``Andrei has very good social
skills,'' says De Long.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Shleifer struck up an association with young
Lawrence Summers, then just starting out as an assistant professor
at MIT _ by citing five errors in a Summers paper, according to
legend. Shleifer graduated in math in 1982, and went straight on to
MIT.
</P>
<P>
   There were subtantial contributions from the very beginning. His
thesis (unpretentiously titled ``The Stock Market and the Business
Cycle'') became at least a pair of papers, one on ``implementation
cycles,'' the other on mis-pricing of companies whose shares are
included in widely followed indexes. He quickly formed a lasting
research partnership with Rob Vishny of the University of Chicago
Graduate School of Business that has been among the longest-lasting
and most fruitful in all of present-day economics.
</P>
<P>
   They made their first big splash in 1986 in ``Large Shareholders
and Corporate Control,'' pointing out the significance of a
frequently overlooked fact: that raiders inevitably participate in
the gains from their takeover bids. That put the pair squarely in
the middle of the discussion of the market for corporate control
that has percolated briskly for more than 20 years, ever since
Michael C. Jensen touched it off in 1979 with and article on
principal-agent relationships and ownership structures.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to weigh Shleifer's contributions, MIT's
Olivier Blanchard divided them into three broad categories of
enduring work.
</P>
<P>
   There were his explorations of corporate governance and finance,
of course, with his work on certain unpredictable and dangerous
imperfections in financial markets now seen to be especially
far-reaching.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a 1996 paper on the problems that fund managers would
face in moments of unforeseen crisis (``The Limits to Arbitrage'')
could be said to have anticipated with ``amazing prescience'' the
Long Term Capital Management crisis by two full years, according to
Blanchard.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the third strand, the theory and practice of the
transition from planned to market economies around the world, that
been Shleifer's greatest contribution, says Blanchard, adding that
``he may well be the most influential researcher in the field.'' Of
the Russian privatization in particular, Shleifer was the
intellectual father.
</P>
<P>
   It was he who hit on the idea of selling Russia's largest firms
to insiders at a discount, in the hope that managers later would
sell their windfall gains and surface further value. (The logic is
described in detail in his 1995 book with Vishny and Maxim Boycko,
``Privatizing Russia.'')
</P>
<P>
   If envisaging the Russian privatization is Shleifer's greatest
accomplishment, surely his role in its implementation is his
greatest private sorrow. From 1991 until 1997, he served as
official adviser to the Russian government, often supported by
funding from the US Agency for International Development. During
the latter part of the period, Shleifer's mentor Larry Summers
oversaw US economic policy towards Russia as Deputy Secretary of
the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Shleifer had married a young derivatives trader,
Nancy Zimmerman. In time she had become a well known hedge-fund
manager, making investments in, among many other things, Russian
debt. A student, Jonathan Hay, had become deeply involved in
rewriting the Russian securities laws. Hay's companion, Elizabeth
Hebert, had won a desirable license to sell mutual funds to
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   This web of palpable opportunties and possible conflicts tore
apart in 1997 when political maneuvering in Moscow led to
accusations in Washington: Shleifer lost his government contracts,
his official engagement to the Russian government, and Harvard
restructured its consulting activities.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Shleifer has thrown himself into research and
publishing activities, though he remains a principal of an
asset-management firm. A paper with Harvard's Edward Glaeser on
``Not-for-Profit Entrepreneurs'' is making the rounds. His widely
anticipated Clarendon Lectures on financial markets are due later
this year. A collection of lively essays with Vishny _ ``The
Grabbing Hand: Government Pathologies and their Cures'' _ is in the
stores.
</P>
<P>
   As MIT's Blanchard says, ``his value is neither in brilliant
theoretical insights nor in sophisticated models. He is very much
in the old Chicago tradition of building simple models, emphasizing
basic economic mechanisms at work, and looking at the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us to the Last Chicagoan. The same meeting of
the governing body of the American Economic Association that
conferred the Clark medal on Shleifer also nominated Sherwin Rosen,
a University of Chicago economist best known for his work on the
economics of superstars, to serve as AEA president next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the '90s have seen one Nobel Prize after another
conferred on economists at the University of Chicago, the decade
since Shleifer left for Harvard has not been an easy one for those
there still working on their reputations. Two of the department's
brightest stars have left: Jose Scheinkman for Princeton and Thomas
Sargent for Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Prescott, a leading exemplar of the Chicago style, has
begun commuting to the Windy City from Minneapolis, and of course
Eugene Fama, Gary Becker, and Robert Lucas remain active there. But
Robert Barro, Michael Jensen and Shleifer are at Harvard, and the
legion of talented economists who remain are either too young or
too old or lacking in the peculiar combination of clarity and
ambition that permitted Friedman and Stigler to put such a stamp
upon their age.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that the sidewalk is looking somewhat forlorn.
Unless they miraculously reassemble the mold, Sherwin Rosen is, as
his friends describe him, the Last Chicagoan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
