<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9829 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CASUALTIES-$AD     04-30 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CASUALTIES-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 2)  
 CIVILIAN CASUALTIES COULD RISE WITH ROCKET ARTILLERY, B-52s  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (News analysis)
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite NATO efforts to avoid civilian casualties
in Yugoslavia, the number killed could climb markedly once allied
forces step up the war with ferocious rocket and missile artillery
barrages and unguided bombs from B-52s.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the alliance's accelerated air campaign, 23 Apache
helicopter gunships, designed to take out enemy tanks, are
stationed in northern Albania, poised for combat over the embattled
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In order to protect the choppers, which are vulnerably because
they fly low, NATO commanders plan to clear a path for them in
Kosovo that will be free of Yugoslav air defenses. To produce the
fire-free zone, the commanders have placed 18 rocket launchers on
tracked vehicles along the Albania-Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   The launchers _ called Multiple Launch Rocket Systems (MLRS) _
are high-tech artillery designed to destroy radar sites and
surface-to-air missiles that might shoot down the choppers.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a minute, each MLRS can fire 12 rockets with a
range of about 20 miles. Once over a target, a single rocket lets
loose its deadly cargo of about 650 mini-bombs designed to kill
troops and destroy vehicles with shrapnel bursts.
</P>
<P>
   The MLRS also can launch two satellite-guided Army Tactical
Missile Systems, each with a range of 120 miles, which is greater
than the width of Kosovo, and each able to release 900 bomblets
over an area several acres wide. Some are equipped with a type of
mini-bomb that can destroy tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi troops in the 1991 Persian Gulf War nicknamed the MLRS
``steel rain'' because of its destructive force.
</P>
<P>
   While each of the cruise missiles that NATO forces have fired
over the last five weeks can blow up a building, MLRS rockets and
missiles are far more destructive. One of its rockets or missiles
can kill people over five acres.
</P>
<P>
   In its attacks so far, NATO estimates it has accidentally killed
about 100 civilians. The Yugoslav government claims the toll is
more than 600 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McNaugher, an Army expert and senior analyst here with
the Rand Corp., a military think tank, said many of the 800,000
ethnic Albanian refugees in Kosovo could get caught in a MLRS
barrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MLRS was very useful against an Iraqi force coming into
Kuwait, where it was military-to-military, and the danger of
civilian casualties was pretty low,'' McNaugher said, but in
Kosovo, he added, ``that's not the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I don't see how you use the MLRS to clear a path of
safety for the Apaches. There are hundreds of thousands of refugees
roaming around.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Posen, professor of national security studies at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, said an errant MLRS could
devastate a civilian population.
</P>
<P>
   ``This weapon drops hundreds of grenades on an area but it is
not with pinpoint accuracy,'' he explained. ``If you guess wrong
and the rockets end up in the wrong place, it's a horror show. This
is deliberately engineered to do a lot of killing in the open.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Hanlon, a defense analyst at Brookings Institution
here, said that in order to avoid killing civilians with the MLRS,
NATO planners will need finely detailed intelligence from commandos
and from spy planes called Joint-Stars surveillance jets (J-Stars)
so that the weapon can be targeted to the right area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be possible to find a (military) convoy with J-Stars,
but a tractor looks an awful lot like a personnel carrier or jeep
from J-Stars,'' O'Hanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if NATO successfully attacks Yugoslav conveys or radar
sites with the MLRS, O'Hanlon predicted that Serbian commanders
will quickly change tactics and intersperse military units among
civilians as they are already doing in parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
   The same concerns about civilian casualties apply to Pentagon
plans to drop unguided, or ``dumb,'' bombs against Yugoslav troop
concentrations from high-flying B-52 bombers. So far during the
conflict, the bombers have fired only cruise missiles, which
usually can be targeted with precision.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has also relied mainly on other precision-guided weapons
like the Tomahawk cruise missile and the television-guided AGM-130
bomb to destroy buildings, command centers, storage depots and
troop concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   McNaugher of Rand says NATO isn't likely to drop the
indiscriminate dumb bombs unless Yugoslav troops are out in the
open away from towns or refugee camps. ``I can only see using them
on targets in the middle of nowhere,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
