<HEADER>
A9836 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV02-B     04-30 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO AND CONGRESSIONAL PARTISANSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 02, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even by the low standards we have come to expect of this
lamentable edition of the US Congress, the performance of this
current collection of clucks and Claghorns over Kosovo is
remarkable for its cheap political partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   The US House of Representatives disgraced itself yet again
Wednesday when the members could not even decide whether to approve
or oppose the NATO bombing camaign that is the planet's most
important political issue of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Serb forces systematically massacred more than 100
male refugees kneeling at gunpoint in a farmer's field, the House
refused to support the NATO air effort. With US airmen risking
their lives nightly in a relentless bombing campaign which may yet
take a sad toll of American aircrews, the craven congressmen who
think politics is all that counts undermined what the majority
party's ringleaders privately sneer is ``Clinton's war.''
</P>
<P>
   Their cynicism is exceeded only by their opportunism, for the
same crowd prepared to approve twice as much extra money for the US
military as the President seeks. Coming off a year of fruitless
impeachment bombast, the 213-213 tie vote that refused to put the
House in favor of the US participation in NATO's intensive bombing
campaign was yet more proof that this Impeachment Congress is a
particularly inept assemblage of political mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   It is journalistic shorthand to cite ``the Republican-led House
and Senate,'' but there is next to no leadership visible in either
branch on anything but stick-it-to-Clinton votes.
</P>
<P>
   The tiresome partisanship that branded this new Congress during
the grueling impeachment imbroglio refuses to be quenched. New
Speaker Denny Hastert (R-Ill.) plays the chump as he sits by idly
to watch the brass-knuckle tactics of House Whip Tom Delay
(R-Tex.). This former exterminator is the most relentless
Clinton-basher of the Impeachment Chorus.
</P>
<P>
   It was Delay who engineered the failure of the NATO bombing vote
_ a measure fails if it does not gain a majority, and the tie vote
played into the hands of the GOP even though the muddled Speaker,
Hastert-the-Hesitant, voted a weak ``aye'' at the roll call's tail
end.
</P>
<P>
   Delay is more influential with Republican members than Hastert.
So fearful is the rookie Speaker of the right-wingers commanded by
Delay that he claims he didn't try to influence any Republicans
even though he himself voted meekly to back the NATO effort. How's
that for leadership?
</P>
<P>
   ``A low moment in American foreign policy,'' bellowed House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.), who looks more and more like
the fellow who'll seize the gavel from Hastert. ``A betrayal of
everything America stands for,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans don't know how to play the Kosovo question. The
only one of the 11 Republicans running for president who supports
the war is Vietnam hero Sen. John McCain of Arizona, whose
forthright argument for ground troops and a firm commitment to win
has moved him up in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The only New Englanders who voted against backing the NATO air
campaign were four Republicans, including the ususal suspects: two
from New Hampshire, Charles Bass and John Sununu, and Rep. Nancy
Johnson of Connecticut. They are the same three New Englanders who
broke with the regional pack to vote to impeach Clinton. Joining
them was Rep. Chris Shays of Connecticut, who'd voted against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As the nervous broadcasters of Serb TV waited for their next
transmitter tower to topple, they could brag that at least the US
House refused to go along with the NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about giving aid and comfort to the enemy. So Balkanized is
this Congress, if I may use the term, that it looks ever-more-likey
the GOP will lose the slimmed-down five-seat margin initially won
in the landslide '94 House election.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, the Democrats are divided as well. While 31
Republicans voted to support the NATO action, 26 Democrats
defected. Still, 181 Democrats voted to support Clinton's decision
on the air war, and 187 Republicans voted ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   It now appears that this Congress will be unable to overcome the
emotional riptides still swirling about the Congress even as an
ongoing, if undeclared, war changes the subject from impeachment.
It will take a decisive election and a shakeup of the current
congressional leadership to set things right in the divided House
that is this House.
</P>
<P>
   When a number of GOP presidential candidates assembled Sunday
(May 2) in Manchester, NH, for the state party's primary kickoff
dinner, missing from the lineup was this year's frontrunner, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas; last time's winner, broadcaster Pat
Buchanan, and the party's brandname war hero, Sen. McCain.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves, in alphabetical order, Lamar Alexander, Gary Bauer,
Elizabeth Dole, Steve Forbes, US Rep. John Kasich, Alan Keyes,
former Vice President Dan Quayle, and hometown Sen. Bob Smith. They
each got seven minutes of microphone time to do the following, as
far as I can anticipate:
</P>
<P>
   1. Schmooze the locals, being particularly attentive to local
Sen. Judd Gregg, whose organization is not worth antagonizing.
</P>
<P>
   2. Flog the hated Clinton (who just happened to carry New
Hampshire in the last two elections) and deny him any shred of
credit for the prosperous, inflation-free regional economy.
</P>
<P>
   3. Link Vice President Al Gore to all manner of perfidy in DC,
from Buddhist nuns to China policy to nuclear leaks.
</P>
<P>
   4. Blame Clinton-Gore for the moral decay that led to the
Colorado school shootings and many other evils.
</P>
<P>
   All the above are predictable political moves in front of a
partisan crowd. But what does a would-be president say about the
war? How do you package your policy in a couple or three
paragraphs? In front of a local political establishment that, in
Congress if not at the grass roots, is all anti-Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire Republicans have always worn their patriotism
on the sleeve, boasting of unmatched fealty to flag, veterans,
military spending, etc. etc. So how will they handle the fact that
their two congressmen just voted against the NATO campaign to halt
the massacres, and will shortly vote double the extra defense
spending the White House deems wise?
</P>
<P>
   How do you square that circle?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
