<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9847 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-TONY-BENNETT-ART-     04-30 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TONY-BENNETT-ART-3TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS HEART'S IN SAN FRANCISCO, HIS MONEY'S IN HIS SON'S HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, May 2)  
 (bl)  
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To Tony Bennett and his son Danny, it seemed just an
offhand comment. At a star-studded Christmas Eve dinner party in
1997 at the home of Tommy Mottola, then the president of Sony Music
Entertainment, Robert DeNiro turned to the crooner, who was 70 at
the time, and said, ``Hey, Tony _ there's a film I want you in.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Bennett, 45, who is his father's manager, said: ``A lot of
people say that kind of stuff. I didn't pay much attention.'' But a
year later, he received a call from Harold Ramis, director of
``Analyze This,'' a Warner Brothers comedy starring De Niro as the
leader of a crime family who seeks help from a psychotherapist.
Ramis, he said, offered his father $15,000 to sing ``Got the World
on a String'' in the movie's final scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harold tells me the whole script, and that the analyst and
DeNiro share a love of Bennett's music,'' recalled Danny Bennett.
``But they made a fatal mistake. They told me they had already shot
the film. So I'm like: `Hey, they shot the whole film around Tony
being the end gag and they're offering me $15,000? Frank Sinatra is
dead. There was Sinatra, and then there was Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Brothers said it ended up paying the elder Bennett
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   In most families, it is the son who relies on his father's
business expertise. The Bennetts have turned that traditional
relationship on its head. Tony Bennett might well be a
dulcet-voiced superstar, whose signature tune, ``I Left My Heart in
San Francisco,'' and other hits are entrancing Generation X'ers
today as they did their parents and grandparents years ago. But
when it comes to finances, he is out of his element _ as he is the
first to confess.
</P>
<P>
   And so he has found an unlikely redeemer: his own son. He first
turned to Danny 20 years ago for help in escaping financial
disaster. At the time, Tony Bennett's brand of pre-rock
balladeering was out of favor, his income had slowed and the IRS
was breathing down his neck to collect $2 million in back taxes,
the younger Bennett recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The singer's personal life was also in turmoil. His second
marriage was on the rocks, and to escape his troubles, he had
turned to cocaine and marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   When the IRS called his accountants to say it was starting
proceedings to seize his house, Bennett, as he put it,
``overindulged'' and had to be rushed to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   His son said: ``That was the day of reckoning. That is when he
called me up. I think that was a desperate move.''
</P>
<P>
   So the younger Bennett joined forces with his father, first
seeing that he did not lose his home, and then helping him climb
back to financial health. When the IRS debt was paid off in 1990,
the singer was still skeptical about his financial security. ``I
said, `Your head is above water,' and Tony said, `Really?''' the
son recalled, alluding to his father as Tony, as he always does in
business discussions to make the professional relationship as clear
as possible. ``I don't think he really believes it to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Danny Bennett oversees a nest egg of $15 million to $20
million for his father.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview in the singer's Manhattan apartment, which
overlooks Central Park, Tony Bennett seemed the very picture of
sensible prosperity. The furniture was comfortable but sparse, and
a David Hockney drawing of Bennett _ a gift to the singer from the
artist _ adorned one wall. Dressed in gray wool slacks and a plaid
blazer, Bennett sat on a sofa stroking his Maltese dog, ``Boo,'' in
his lap. His manner was polite though distant, a marked contrast to
his easygoing stage style.
</P>
<P>
   But he talked openly about a fear of financial ruin that has
pervaded his musical career. ``For 45 years, I had an ax over my
head,'' he said. ``I thought I was going to go bankrupt. I was
spending more than I was making, on advertising, publicity and
all.'' His managers weren't much help, he said, telling him, ``
`You owe so much money. You will never be able to pull out of it as
long as you live.'''
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong; Bennett did pull out, largely through the
efforts of his son. ``I realize how fortunate I am to have someone,
in Danny, that is truly looking out for my best interests and not
just in it for the money,'' the singer said.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Bennett must have seemed an odd choice to replace the
professional managers. At the time, he was a 25-year-old punk
rocker with long, dyed-blue hair. (``At least I had hair then,'' he
recalled.) He had never gone to college, and instead pursued his
dream of becoming a rock star. His father, he said, had no
objections.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out that the son was the mirror image of the
father: Tony's talent lay in art, not business, and Danny's lay in
business, not art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always the business manager for the bands I was in,''
the son recalled. One of his first moves as financial adviser to
his father was to suggest _ he never decrees _ a spending budget
for him and his wife, Sandra. Soon after, Danny's stepmother filed
for a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, the son crunched the numbers and wrote
the budgets while the father performed. To revive the singer's
career, he marketed him as a living American legend, a genial
master of his craft.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. By the early 1980s Bennett was making regular
television appearances on ``Late Night With David Letterman,'' a
program popular with college students.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, his ``Perfectly Frank'' album went gold, selling over
500,000 copies, and in 1993 he appeared with the Red Hot Chili
Peppers on the MTV Music Awards. In 1994 he joined Elvis Costello
and K.D. Lang on the popular cable TV show ``MTV Unplugged.'' Over
the last eight years, he has won seven Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   As his popularity zoomed, Bennett created a program with Sony
Music Entertainment called ``Live by Request'' on the A&AMP;E cable
network that showcases prominent singers. The program, which won an
Emmy in 1996, was an instant hit. When Bennett starred in the first
show, more than 1.5 million viewers called in requests for songs.
</P>
<P>
   The money followed the restored magic. Today, Bennett makes an
estimated 100 live performances a year, earning $50,000 or so a
concert, or about $5 million. An avid artist, he sells his
paintings and drawings for up to $80,000 apiece. His son, intent on
marketing his father's image wherever it will sell, has plans for
Tony Bennett furniture, Tony Bennett sheets and Tony Bennett
towels. Then there are the royalties from more than four decades of
recorded music, and even a commercial or two.
</P>
<P>
   It is Danny Bennett, in consultation with brokers at Gruntal &AMP;
Co. and Salomon Smith Barney, who decides how to invest his
father's money; his father's only rule is a ban on tobacco and
chemical stocks. About 70 percent of the singer's portfolio is
currently in tax-free municipal bonds _ conservative,
income-generating investments not unusual for someone his age. The
remainder is in an array of stocks. Once a month, father and son go
over a printout of the investments and other financial details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' the younger Bennett said, ``I show him what he is
making from the paintings and he goes, `A person could live on
that, huh?'''
</P>
<P>
   While his wealth might not seem much when compared with the
fortunes being made these days by some media superstars, it is a
comfortable sum for a man who was once close to bankruptcy.
Besides, Bennett leads a fairly austere life for a celebrity. True,
he likes to dress well and fly first-class. But he rents his
apartment, and has rejected his son's suggestion that he buy a
country place. And his girlfriend, Susan Crow, 33, is a
schoolteacher who keeps a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances say Bennett is surprisingly unpretentious. As a
result, when his finances unraveled, he wasn't blocked by false
pride from asking his son for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the stage, Tony is remarkably intellectually agile, though
he does not have anywhere near the vocal range or improvisational
gift of Ella and Mel Torme,'' said Jonathan Schwartz, the artistic
director of Lincoln Center's American Songbook series and
well-known disk jockey who currently has a program on WNYC-AM.
``Tony has the confidence in this part of himself. But one of the
things that Tony has known all his life are his limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a 1974 interview in The New Yorker, he discussed some
of those limitations. ``There are things I am searching for, but
they won't take a day,'' Bennett said. ``I would like to attain a
good keen intellect.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether such a perception of himself reflects humility, as his
son believes, or insecurity, as Schwartz believes, it has freed him
to throw his energies into his art. In that sense, Schwartz said,
it has provided a boost to his career. ``If Tony's low self-esteem
had been higher, it is entirely possible the music would have been
lower, fused as it would have been with arrogance and self,''
Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, the singer has always been exacting about his
craft _ a quality that goes back to his childhood in Queens during
the Depression. His father, a grocer born in Italy, died when Tony
was 9, and his mother supported her family by doing piecework as a
seamstress. And just as she would take home only the
highest-quality dresses to work on, so he would later sing only the
songs he thought were destined to become classics. ``Tony only
sings fancy dresses,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said pleasing his audiences was always more important to
him than making money. And in the old days, at least, a lot of
singers felt the same way, he said. He recalled seeing what he
called the ``financial log'' for the Blue Note, the legendary jazz
club where Fats Waller wrote the music to ``Ain't Misbehavin'.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a jam session in Harlem, and Fats Waller just came
down and wrote that song on a paper bag,'' he recalled. ``The log
showed that he was paid two bottles of gin. The song became a great
Broadway musical and made millions.''
</P>
<P>
   (Though jazz scholars say the anecdote is historically
impossible _ the Blue Note did not even exist when Waller wrote the
song _ they agree that such financial arrangements were not
uncommon.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Bennett said, in the 1950s and '60s, ``one of the
touches of class that singers had was they never spoke about
money,'' he said. The focus was on music, and ``whoever did the
best job rose to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred, Ella, they were the best,'' he said, referring to Fred
Astaire and Ella Fitzgerald. ``Integrity was as important as money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just make money, so what?'' Bennett added. ``It's like
the Chinese say about paper money: The rats eat it.'' Better to
have somebody overseeing his portfolio who cares about his money as
much as about his talent _ somebody, in short, like his son.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a child, Danny Bennett was surrounded by musical
celebrities. His home was often in a state of confusion, with his
father's musician friends coming and going. He remembers answering
the door when he was 8 to a guest who announced: ``I'm Dizzy.''
Thinking the unfamiliar visitor was having trouble standing up,
Danny asked, ``Would you like to come and sit down?'' Dizzy
Gillespie, the jazz great, did.
</P>
<P>
   Though his parents were separated when he was 10 years old and
he lived with his mother, he remained close to his father. When he
got the call for help in 1979, ``It was sad, but it didn't affect
me,'' the younger Bennett remembered, in large part because such
financial meltdowns were a staple of the music business.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His father had already learned the hard way that his son had a
better business sense than he did. In 1974, Tony Bennett wanted to
start an independent record label, but his son advised him against
it, pointing out that he would need a distribution arrangement with
a major label, which he lacked. Bennett went ahead, and the venture
failed. Several years later, he put his financial fate in his son's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   For Danny, working with the IRS was unnerving. ``You would make
all sorts of deals with them, and then all of a sudden I would have
to renegotiate the whole thing with new agents,'' he recalled. To
pay off the debt faster, he borrowed against his father's future
performance contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Resuscitating his father's career was equally tough. Though
Bennett had been recording to critical acclaim on lesser-known
labels in the mid-1970s, his earlier hits had been with Columbia
Records. Danny finally signed a new deal with Columbia in 1985,
aware that it would have more incentive to market new albums that
could promote sales of Bennett's older releases.
</P>
<P>
   Even before that, he sought to broaden his father's audience.
``Tony abhorred demographics,'' his son recalled. ``He believed he
could play to the whole family. I told him that in order to do
that, you have to go to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The first stop was the Letterman show. And after Danny Bennett
read a news article in The Boston Phoenix in which Bob Guccione
Jr., then the owner of Spin magazine, described Tony Bennett as
``the essence of soul,'' he got Spin to run a profile of his
father. After the singer's musical tribute to Frank Sinatra,
``Perfectly Frank,'' went gold in 1992, his son landed him the spot
on the MTV Music Awards.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the younger Bennett worked on straight salary. But as
his role grew, and he took over managing all aspects of his
father's career, he began to earn a potentially more lucrative
commission on his father's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   He has already parlayed that success into a wider business; his
entertainment-management company, RPM Music Productions, also
handles Elvis Costello, the pop music band Mike Viola and the Candy
Butchers, and Rasputina, an alternative-rock cello trio. He is
starting RPM Records as a joint venture with Columbia Records.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1992, Danny Bennett put most of his father's money
into tax-free municipal bonds, yielding 5.5 percent _ the
equivalent of 10.3 percent in taxable income for a New York City
resident. But in 1996, as Wall Street continued its long bull
market, he moved about 30 percent into such winning stocks as
Bristol-Myers Squibb, Merck, Sprint and Viacom _ and a few losers,
like National Semiconductor.
</P>
<P>
   He was an early believer in the Internet, buying Amazon.com and
Yahoo stock for himself and Microsoft for his father. ``I had
learned how to engineer and produce records,'' the younger Bennett
said. ``Computers are an extension of that. In the early 1990s I
was managing a band called Tribe on Warner Brothers. We set up a
Web address in 1992.'' He thinks he was the first to display a Web
address on a record album.
</P>
<P>
   While Tony Bennett is content to let his son handle his
portfolio, he likes to recall one of his own investment triumphs.
Years ago, he says, he was approached by his friend John Kluge, the
billionaire founder of the company then known as Metromedia Inc.,
the television and cellular phone conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Do you ever buy stocks?','' Bennett recalled. ``I
said, `Not really.' He said. `Buy my stock.''' So Bennett did,
sometime around 1970, and held onto it until Kluge called him one
day in the mid-'80s and advised him to sell. ``I had $5,000 worth
of stock at $3 a share. It ended up being $350 a share,'' a gain of
1,157 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While once a person had to have a million dollars to retire
nicely, today the level is a ``tenmillionaire,'' the younger
Bennett said. It appears that his father has passed that mark.
</P>
<P>
   But though the singer has curtailed his performance schedule
somewhat, he has no plans to sit back and clip coupons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you study the masters _ Picasso, Jack Benny, Fred Astaire _
right up to the the day they died, they were performing,'' Bennett
said. ``If you are creative, you get busier as you get older.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
