<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They Might Even Meet Alan Greenspan Himself &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It comes as no surprise that teen-agers would love to meet the
Chicago Bulls or the Spice Girls. But how about shaking hands with
members of the Federal Open Market Committee? Well, for high school
students in the final rounds Sunday and Monday of the Fed
Challenge, a sort of monetary-policy bee for budding
macroeconomists, the committee has star power.
</P>
<P>
   Teams in the finals, held each year in Washington, typically
portray members of the committee, which sets the nation's monetary
policy in discussions of financial conditions and debates over
whether to adjust interest rates. Then the teams are grilled by
judges recruited by the Federal Reserve, which runs the event.
</P>
<P>
   The students' knowledge sometimes amazes the judges. Lloyd
Bromberg, director of educational programs for the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York, who has been a judge for the contest in the past,
recalled one contestant who quoted from an arcane report by the Fed
bank in Kansas City, Mo. ``The judges looked to each other and
said, `I didn't read that article,''' Bromberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its fifth year, the contest shows evidence of changing
the way economics is taught. Several high schools around the
country offer college-credit courses that prepare students for the
Fed Challenge, according to Federal Reserve officials. A powerful
incentive is the prize money, provided by Citigroup: a $40,000
grant for the winning school, a $10,000 scholarship for each of the
five members of its team and $10,000 for their teacher.
</P>
<P>
   This year's finalists will meet some members of the committee
they have studied and portrayed _ and perhaps an even bigger
monetary star. It's not certain yet whether the Fed chairman, Alan
Greenspan, will be there this year, but Bromberg said that in 1997,
the students ``lit up,'' when Greenspan appeared to award the
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHAEL BRICK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Computers? Near the Laundry &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apartment complexes often boast of having pools and exercise
rooms. Now one development in Baltimore offers a different amenity:
a shared home office.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bonnie Ridge Apartments, residents can pay to use a
computer, a printer, a copying machine or a fax machine in an
office-like setting in the community clubhouse. The computers are
connected to the Internet, and there is even a hook-up for laptops.
Residents pay by swiping credit cards at the machines. It costs $5
a half-hour, for example, to use a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The operation is run by USA Technologies, which runs similar
business centers at hotels.
</P>
<P>
   _ SHELLY FREIERMAN &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
