<HEADLINE>
RATING VANS: WHO HAS THE BEST FAMILY ROOM FOR THE ROAD?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chrysler created the modern minivan, and for 15 years it has
successfully fended off the arrows of a pack of challengers. But
the rivals keep coming with ever more potent weapons, including new
vans this year from Ford and Honda (on the heels of improved
competition from General Motors and Toyota).
</P>
<P>
   But just as van makers figured out what customers want in a
family vehicle _ from extra doors to cup holders to secondary music
sources with headphone jacks _ the market has cooled.
</P>
<P>
   Although sales have picked up nicely this year, they remain
below their 1994 peak, and rebates and discounts are common. Sport
utility vehicles are one reason, and rebellion against the vans'
soccer-mom image is another.
</P>
<P>
   The minivan is ingenious because it allows families _ or soccer
teams _ to travel together while staying separate. Captains' chairs
give occupants their own padded thrones. Cup holders and storage
pockets are handy. Some vans even have separate rear climate
controls and audio sources with headphone jacks.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, there is plenty of evidence that designers are paying
attention to how minivans are used. Storage nets between the front
seats hold maps, sunglasses and large water bottles. Drawers
beneath the front passenger seat provide hidden storage. Honda has
a small tray that folds up for a meal on wheels or for use as a
desk. Juice box holders are common.
</P>
<P>
   And there are many ways to customize the seating; this year,
Chevrolet introduced a layout with eight individual seats. Removing
seats has become a science. Some slide forward to increase cargo
room in the rear. Some roll out on tiny wheels. Honda's third seat
folds neatly into the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Two contributors to this page _ who both have full schedules of
suburban child-shuttling _ recently tested five of the most popular
minivans and ranked them for their overall appeal. A few smaller
models were not included, like the Mercury Villager/Nissan Quest
twins, the Isuzu Oasis (which is virtually identical to the
last-generation Honda Odyssey) and the Mazda MPV, which is being
replaced this summer with an all-new model.
</P>
<P>
   Both reviewers were emphatic about their top two picks. Although
both were previously impressed by Chrysler's vans, the Plymouth
moved down their lists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
