BLEWSTER-GAFFES (Phoenix) - Slavery wasn't that bad; Native
Americans are stupid. Just another day at the office for Arizona
state Rep. Barbara Blewster. The Dewey Republican's latest gaffe
came in a conversation with Rep. Leah Landrum, one of two elected
African Americans in the Legislature. Landrum says she was offended
but not surprised. This, after all, is the woman who compared
homosexuality to cannibalism and told another colleague she doesn't
look Jewish because she doesn't have a hook-nose. Blewster has also
been peddling a book published in the 1880s on conservative
political philosophy. By CHRIS MOESER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SCHOOLS-THREATS (Phoenix) - School districts around the Valley of
the Sun bring in police, bomb-sniffing dogs and security guards to
try to assure parents that schools are safe, despite threats. By
JEFF NELSON. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SCHOOLS-JOCKS (Phoenix) - In the aftermath of the Littleton
shooting, we look into the culture on Phoenix area high-school
campuses to see if athletes are a breed apart, recipients of both
special treatment and resentment from their classmates. Do they
have an air of superiority? Do they contribute to an atmosphere of
intolerance? And will there be attempts made to break down some of
the walls? By KENT SOMERS. Story will move in the ``A`` and ``S''
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) - Overlooked and underappreciated, the
Mitsubishi Galant deserves a second chance, especially now that
sharp new styling and the addition of a decent V-6 engine brings it
up to speed with midsize favorites Toyota Camry, Honda Accord and
Ford Taurus. Upgrading the Galant is an important move for
Mitsubishi. The Japanese automaker, reeling from several years of
poor sales in the United States and on its home turf, needs a solid
mainstream hit. By BOB GOLFEN. Story will move in the ``L''
category. &QL; 
