<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAGE SET FOR SENATE VOTE ON KOSOVO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Foreign Relations Committee cleared the
way Friday for a showdown vote next week on a measure calling for
the commitment of NATO ground forces if necessary to help end the
Kosovo conflict as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the resolution calling on the president to use ``all
necessary force and other means'' sponsored by Sens. John McCain,
R-Ariz., and Joseph Biden, D-Del., was scheduled for a vote on the
Senate floor late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., served notice that they would
move to table the measure for different reasons to head off a final
vote. Such a vote would put the Senate on record as either opposing
or supporting a ground invasion of Yugoslav territory.
</P>
<P>
   If their motion to table passes, it would effectively kill any
further consideration of the measure for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Lott opposes the McCain-Biden resolution because he believes it
would give the president too much of a free hand in deciding how to
use U.S. forces without consulting with Congress. Lott favors a
bill passed by the House earlier this week that would withhold
funding for a commitment of ground troops unless specifically
authorized by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Lott had been trying to work out a compromise with Daschle that
would allow the House bill, and possibly one other measure, to be
brought up for a vote as alternatives to McCain-Biden. But
Republican aides said they doubted that any alternative would be
offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the feeling is, from both leaders, that the less
debate we have on this right now the better,'' said one GOP aide.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, meanwhile, told reporters that he supports the
McCain-Biden bill, but he believes it would be inappropriate to
debate whether to commit ground troops ``at this time'' because
President Clinton has ``admonished us to give the...(NATO) air
mission time to function.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, Daschle noted, has already spoken once on the allied
air campaign against the forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, voting in favor of continuing the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's an overwhelming sentiment that this is not the
time for the Senate to express itself in greater detail than what
we've already done,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why entertain the issue if it's not the reality, if it's
actually not contemplated by our military and NATO allies?'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Relations Committee voted 14-4 in favor of sending
the resolution to the floor, but it did not recommend whether
senators should pass or kill it.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said as the panel began
debate on the measure that he believes the McCain-Biden measure
``puts the cart before the horse'' because it calls for the use of
ground troops before Congress is asked by the president to
authorize it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate over this resolution is not about our policy in
Serbia. It is about proper constitutional order in time of war,''
Helms said. ``It is the president's responsibility, which he must
not be allowed to avoid, to seek authorization from Congress for
whatever military action he wishes to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Biden and McCain, however, insisted that their measure would
``strengthen the president's hand and NATO's hand'' in trying to
force Milosevic to end his brutal offensive aimed at ridding Kosovo
of its ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate panel was required under the terms of the 1973 War
Powers Act to consider the McCain-Biden resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The House was forced to vote on a similar measure last week
under the terms of the Vietnam-era act, which calls for the
president and Congress to agree when committing U.S. forces to
combat operations for more than 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Since the law was enacted, however, most presidents have chosen
to ignore it, taking the view that as commander-in-chief they have
the right to act unilaterally when committing U.S. forces to action
short of a major war effort.
</P>
<P>
   But that position was challenged Friday by a group of 17 House
members led by Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., who filed a lawsuit in
U.S. District Court in Washington asserting that the NATO campaign
against Yugoslavia violates the War Powers Act because it is likely
to continue well beyond 60 days. The allied bombing began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Administration officials state that it is likely that the
current hostilities will be protracted,'' the lawmakers said in
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The House members are asking the court to force Clinton to
either withdraw U.S. forces from the NATO operation or seek a
declaration of war from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, in an effort to invoke the terms of the War Powers
Act, introduced separate pieces of legislation several weeks ago
that would officially declare war against Yugoslavia and withdraw
U.S. forces from the Balkans conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures were rejected overwhelmingly by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's lawsuit drew support from two Democrats as well 14
other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by his office, Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas,
called Clinton's commitment of U.S. forces to the Balkans without
the explicit consent of Congress a ``reckless action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This president has violated the law and must be taken to
task,'' said Paul. ``It is a shame that Congress has not done more
to stop the president from this destructive course.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
