A9869 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-MINIVANS-$     04-30 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-MINIVANS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SKEPTIC TO ADMIRER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LEONARD M. APCAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had not cared much for minivans, preferring the handling of
even a station wagon over these boxes on wheels. Then I took a
family trip in a Plymouth Grand Voyager, hauled home a Christmas
tree on the roof of a Toyota Sienna and took some Cub Scouts
camping in a Ford Windstar.
</P>
<P>
   Now I have to concede that there is no better way for adults or
children to travel long-distance. As I contemplate making a
cross-country trip with my two children, my wife has suggested I
get a mental checkup. I suggest we get a minivan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. HONDA ODYSSEY. After years in the back of the pack, Honda has
sprinted to the pole position with a wider, longer, superbly built
van that has surprisingly good handling. The new Odyssey maneuvers
and corners as well as some good sedans, and it has the most
horsepower in this group.
</P>
<P>
   The top-line EX has two power sliding doors. The third-row seats
disappear into the floor, a smart idea borrowed from station
wagons. With those seats up, there is a deep well that keeps gear
from shifting.
</P>
<P>
   But good luck finding an Odyssey, and forget about getting a
discount; with supplies tight, dealers expect full price. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. FORD WINDSTAR. Safety counts, and among minivans, only the
Windstar and Odyssey receive the government's top five-star
crash-protection rating. The Windstar also has optional side air
bags and a sensor that signals when the van is about to back into
something. But even with better rear visibility, there are blind
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Ford now offers power sliding doors on both sides and two V6
engines. While handling and acceleration are good, the bigger
engine is the most noisy in this group. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. PLYMOUTH GRAND VOYAGER. Except on fancy models,
DaimlerChrysler makes buyers pay extra for features that most vans
have as standard equipment: map pockets, storage bins, adjustable
headrests and other comforts. Handling is acceptable, but no longer
better than Honda's or Ford's. The brakes felt spongy and stops
seemed slow.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the van was a comfortable hauler for a weekend trip to
Vermont. An overhead console included a trip computer _ something
some others did not have. The sliding-door tracks were neatly
disguised. But the 3.3-liter V6 had the fewest horses and was
sluggish on highway merges. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. CHEVROLET VENTURE. The LS test model was a competent people
mover in every way, and in fact just missed third place. Side air
bags are standard, and it can be ordered with seats for eight. But
the middle three seats did not have armrests and passage to the
two-part rear bench was very tight.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy's automated door has safeguards to prevent children from
opening it accidentally but it seemed needlessly complicated. In
fact, the door often closed halfway and then bounced back.
Acceleration and cornering were good, and the sport suspension
improves the handling while firming the ride. In contrast with the
others', the Chevy's brakes chattered on hard stops. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. TOYOTA SIENNA. Here is evidence of how fast the minivan
market moves. The Sienna was new for 1998, but the competition has
already blown by it with more space and better rear access. There
are other signs that the Sienna is not up to date: The third seat
is cramped, the middle seats cannot be removed and there is no
raised ``theater seating'' like the other vans'. But typical of
Toyota, the Sienna is solid and well-built.
</P>
</TEXT>
