<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLLUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALIST ACTIVISTS ACCUSE BUSH OF TAKING INDUSTRIAL
`PAYOFF' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Environmental activists Friday accused Gov.
George W. Bush of taking a $169,400 political ``payoff'' for his
presidential campaign from air-polluting industries that have bills
pending before the current Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks like this was a business transaction
between the governor's office and industry,'' said Peter Altman,
director of the Sustainable Energy &AMP; Economic Development
Coalition. ``You scratch my back and I'll scratch yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the governor is not
influenced by campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Texas know Governor Bush bases his decisions on
what is right for Texas, and he is the first governor who has held
grandfathered companies' feet to the fire and insisted that they
voluntarily reduce emissions,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is pushing legislation that would allow companies with
older plants to voluntarily come into compliance with the 1971
Clean Air Act. The environmentalists want to close a
``grandfather'' loophole and force the companies to abide by the
law.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of environmental groups has argued that companies
that want to keep the loophole have given state elected officials
more than $4.6 million in campaign contributions in the past six
years.
</P>
<P>
   The groups Friday said Bush got $169,400 from polluters in the
first 28 days of his presidential fund-raising, plus $138,900 from
lawyers with Vinson &AMP; Elkins. The law firm's clients include
Aluminum Co. of America, whose Rockdale, Texas, plant is the
grandfathered site with the state's top air emissions.
</P>
<P>
   While state officials cannot take political contributions while
the Legislature is in regular session, Bush can accept such funds
because he is raising money to run for a federal office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans want the higher standard,'' said Robin Schneider of
Public Research Works. ``When the Legislature is in session,
contributions are barred. But because he is running for federal
office, he can take the payoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider, who conducted the campaign contribution study, said
contributions were identified as coming from industry political
action committees, executives, members of their boards of directors
and their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists said Bush should return the campaign money
to the grandfathered industrialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush should give back this dirty money and close this
loophole,'' said Scott Royder, director of Texas Public Employees
for Environmental Responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation that Bush supports would give plants built
before the Clean Air Act took effect until Sept. 1, 2001, to
volunteer for a program to upgrade their equipment to technological
standards no older than 10 years. One study found that plants
grandfathered in 1971 produce about 36 percent of Texas' industrial
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Four environmentalists were arrested at the Governor's Mansion
last week while protesting Bush's stand on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
