<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-BAFFERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT SEEKING DERBY THREE-PEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ D. Wayne Lukas took a turn in the role,
peaking when he won back-to-back Kentucky Derbies. Before that,
Nick Zito played the part, winning two Derbies in four years. But
the star of this production, Saturday's 125th Run for the Roses at
Churchill Downs, is Bob Baffert, who is trying to become the first
to train three consecutive winners of America's greatest race.
</P>
<P>
   Five men have captured two in a row: Herbert Thompson (Burgoo
King, 1932, and Brokers Tip, '33); Ben Jones (Citation, '48, and
Ponder, '49); Jimmy Jones (Iron Leige, '57, and Tim Tam, '58);
Lucien Lauren (Riva Ridge, '72, and Secretariat, '73), and Lukas
(Thunder Gulch, '95, and Grindstone, '96).
</P>
<P>
   Baffert won the Rose Run with Silver Charm in '97 and Real Quiet
in '98, and, if not for the nose of Grindstone, who nipped his
Cavonnier at the wire, he already would have accomplished a
threepeat.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight shines brightly on Baffert because he is
charismatic, witty, and personable, far more so than Lukas or Zito
(who scored with Strike the Gold in 1991, and Go for Gin in '94).
He takes his position as ambassador of racing very seriously. But
the glare of publicity can be hot, and it has now become generally
known that Baffert isn't always Mr. Nice Guy, and can be quite
testy at times.
</P>
<P>
   The most public incident occurred when Baffert got into a public
shoving match with Scotty McClelland, agent for Chris McCarron, at
Clocker's Corner at Santa Anita. McClelland felt McCarron had been
promised the mount on General Challenge in the Santa Anita Derby
April 3, after regular rider Gary Stevens was committed to ride
Real Quiet in the Oaklawn Handicap the same day. (General Challenge
would go on to win the race.) However, Baffert scratched Real Quiet
from the Oaklawn race because he did not like the weight
assignments, and put Stevens back on General Challenge. When
McClelland found out, tempers flared.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert may not be a hero on the backstretch, but there is no
question he is loved by the public, and if any of his three
entrants, General Challenge, Excellent Meeting, and Prime Timber
tally Saturday, he will go through the top of the charts. However,
Baffert claims he is not worried about what course history may take
_ in fact, he says he's not worried at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in position to win another one,'' said Baffert, 46, a
native of Nogales, Ariz., who began as a quarterhorse trainer.
``That's my job, to get 'em in position. I don't really think about
what will happen in the race. I just think about getting them
there. I don't get too excited, because a lot of things can go
wrong. I never think about history. I never thought I'd get this
far. I never set goals. I'm just here day by day. You've got to
keep the excitement down.''
</P>
<P>
   Known as the ``Silver Fox,'' Baffert will send out a powerful
trio in search of the victory that will give him his own page in
the record book. He scratched the outstanding filly Excellent
Meeting from Friday's Oaks, as expected, and she will race as an
entry with General Challenge. The duo, owned by the Golden Eagle
Farm of John and Betty Mabee, noted California breeders, share the
same sire, General Meeting, a son of Seattle Slew. Excellent
Meeting will be ridden by Kent Desormeaux, while General Challenge
will be handled by Gary Stevens, and the entry has been established
as the 3-1 favorite. Prime Timber, a son of Sultry Song, is owned
by Aaron and Marie Jones, owners of a sawmill in Oregon. He will be
partnered by David Flores and is the 7-2 second choice.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who is on the verge of becoming Mr. Derby, has made a
serious study of the race that has made him famous. ``Every time I
come here, I learn a little bit more about the race,'' he said.
``At Churchill, it's not so much getting used to the surface as
getting used to the turns. They are a little bit tighter than the
turns at Santa Anita. General Challenge goes around these turns
like a rat in a barrel, and Prime Timber has been really reaching
out. They've looked great. That's what Derby horses are supposed to
look like, at least the ones I train. When you watch them work,
that separates the men from the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Timber is coming up to a huge race. He's a grinder, he
doesn't give up. General Challenge is the most talented of the
group, but he has to have things his own way. He's a big goof, an
immature horse. He has to get clear and into the right spot. His
stride is so long, it's unbelievable. He takes one stride to the
average horse's two. It's a giant advantage. We need General
Challenge to get away clean, and get into a nice fluid stride.
Excellent Meeting could win the Derby if she gets the trip, but
she's got to get by Prime Timber and General Challenge. If she
wasn't up to the task, I wouldn't run her.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert had clear sailing in 1997 and '98, and the Derby waters
have been calm this year, too. ``I've been so lucky,'' he added.
``The last three years that I've come here, everything has gone so
smoothly with my Derby horses. It's a pressure situation and the
pressure builds up. By the day of the race, I don't really want to
talk to anybody. I get a game face on. But you have to keep
yourself calm at all times. I should probably start drinking, but I
don't drink, so it's a little bit tougher on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a matter of fate. If it's meant to be, it's meant to
be. But it helps to have your horses ready. Then it could really be
meant to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
