<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-ROWLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAGRINED ROWLAND `GUY WHO LOST THE PATRIOTS' AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Just hours after he used space-age bravado to
declare that ``failure is not an option,'' Governor John G.
Rowland, father of this city's soured stadium deal, absorbed his
administration's biggest political defeat Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Few politicians had clambered further onto a political limb than
Rowland had in offering Patriots owner Robert Kraft the nation's
most generous, taxpayer-subsidized playground.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rowland who negotiated the deal in secret with Kraft. It
was Rowland who sold it to the state Legislature. And it was
Rowland who signed the agreement in a celebratory ceremony that he
hoped would signal Connecticut's _ and his _ arrival in the major
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to known as the guy who lost the Patriots,'' the
42-year-old governor said as the gold-plated stadium deal began to
unravel.
</P>
<P>
   But now, almost certainly, he will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The captain of the ship is the one who is noticed when the
ship comes in,'' said Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin B.
Sullivan, a West Hartford Democrat. ``Unfortunately, he also gets
noticed when the ship sinks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He himself said his political future rests on this outcome,''
said State Representative Michael P. Lawlor, an East Haven
Democrat. ``It has to be a major political blow.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been few issues that Rowland, the nation's youngest
governor, has pursued with such passion _ a risk, he said, for
which he has no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get past the shoelace mentality,'' Rowland said in
an interview in his office last week before the stadium deal
collapsed. ``Everybody's looking down at their shoelaces, saying no
one's going to want to come to Connecticut. No one's going to come
to UConn basketball. We can never get an NFL stadium here. We're
not a big enough state. I'm trying to get people to have a little
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Connecticut's high-stakes roller-coaster ride with
Kraft has ended in defeat and despair, the political fallout is
certain to represent the severest test yet of Rowland's well-earned
reputation as his state's most agile politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hurt the state's reputation nationally,'' said Edward L.
Marcus, the state's Democratic state chairman. ``He's spent a lot
of money. This kind of takes the wind out of Rowland's sails. He
was all pumped up acting like he was the king of the world. He
comes out of this looking extremely foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the framed newspaper story headlined ``Touchdown!'' that
hangs in Rowland's outer office now seems a cruel -- and certainly
premature -- bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   The gregarious Rowland, who was voting for Ronald Reagan's MX
missiles at an age when most politicians run for the school board,
insisted he never wanted to be known simply as the man who brought
pro football to the banks of the Connecticut River.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd rather concentrate on trimming taxes, creating
jobs, fighting crime, and _ blessed by the most bouyant economy
since World War II _ helping Connecticut forget the fiscal storms
that ravaged the Constitution State in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland's supporters say he will ultimately emerge bruised, but
not broken, by his quixotic quest for New England's Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   He is, after all, a politician's son from a blue-collar city
whose defining moment came not when he became Connecticut's first
GOP governor in 20 years in 1995, but when he conceded defeat in
his first bid for the governor's office in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, had Rowland not been vanquished in 1990 by
Republican-turned-Independent Lowell P. Weicker Jr., the imperious
governor whose successful support for a state income tax touched
off a political uproar, his political fortunes _ still bright by
all measures _ would certainly have been different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luck is a word that ought to be attached to him,'' said Thomas
J. D'Amore Jr., Weicker's former chief of staff and a former state
Republican chairman. ``Rowland was very lucky to lose in 1990. The
reason he's successful is because of the state income tax, which he
stood against.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether underpinned by luck, timing, fate or diligence, John
Grosvenor Rowland's easy-going style and elastic political
philosophy has propelled him far beyond his own expectations and
past opponents who have underestimated him at their peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I'm an old Waspy, trust-fund Republican,'' said
Rowland, seated in a wing-back chair in his second-floor office.
``I'm more of an Irish-Catholic guy, who grew up in the city _ a
three-decker _ the oldest of five kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland was reared in Waterbury, a working-class city 35 miles
west of Hartford known in Rowland's youth for its brass products
and bare-knuckle politics, where both his father and grandfather
served as city comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waterbury is one of the toughest political places that you can
find,'' said John F. Droney Jr., a former Democratic state
chairman. ``If you can make it in Waterbury, you can make it
anywhere.'' A Republican in a Democratic city, Rowland made it.
</P>
<P>
   After spending a year in his family's insurance business, he
spent $1,300 in 1980 to win a seat in the state House of
Representatives, the first GOP lawmaker from that district in 100
years. Mustached and heavier-set in those days, the backslapping
Rowland quickly moved into the House GOP leadership, railing
against high taxes and trumpeting programs to prop up Connecticut's
sagging cities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, when he was 27, Rowland became the youngest member of
the US House of Representatives, where he won a seat on the Armed
Services Committee, supported Reagan's military buildup, and earned
a reputation as the state's staunchest conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to the other Republicans and Democrats in the
Connecticut delegation I was a stark raving lunatic conservative,''
Rowland said. ``In my own caucus _ I came in with (GOP Texas
conservatives) Tom DeLay and Dick Armey _ they thought I was a
communist. They thought I was the biggest liberal in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland chafed against the conventions of Washington, a city he
called full of self-important automatons, where seniority, not
smarts, counts. ``I hated it,'' he said. ``It was not real. Not
even close to being real. Self-important as can be. It's
Disneyworld. It's a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   When he quit in 1990 to run unsuccessfully for governor, he
tacked to the ideological center, softening his views and acquiring
a reputation as a chameleon _ a criticism that rankles him still.
</P>
<P>
   But Rowland's blend of fiscal conservatism, social moderation
and his open willingness to compromise with the
Democratic-controlled legislature has been enormously popular.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps a plaque on his desk that says it's amazing how much
you can accomplish if you're willing to share the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're better making a bad decision and doing something than
making no decision at all,'' Rowland said. ``You have to create
your own opportunities. You've got to take risks and have guts.
Politicians who have luck are politicians who take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   And in defeat, even Rowland critics are willing to give him
credit for trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ought to be congratulated for making the effort,'' D'Amore,
the former GOP party chairman said. ``There was a lack of
experience, of being too quick to the altar. He should have paid
more attention to details _ everything from the siting to the
finances. But, on balance, it was a good thing to try.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
