<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMANIANS GIRD FOR TURNOVER OF CANAL ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY _ There is more than the usual end-of-school-year
spring fever at Balboa High School. There is also a deep sadness.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, this stately school with its red Spanish-tile roof
will graduate its last class of seniors. By the end of May, it will
say goodbye to the rest of its students and staff and close its
doors forever. And by year's end the school, and the rest of the
American-controlled property in this Central American country, will
belong to Panama.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's lots of mixed emotions,'' said Thomas Price, a
Nebraska native who has been the school's principal for the last
four years. ``There's always some uncertainty at the end of a
school year, especially for seniors. But for the other students,
it'll be a whole new experience. No question.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is for Balboa's graduating seniors, the future for Panama
is both exciting and impossible to predict. Nearly a century after
Theodore Roosevelt carried his big stick into this isthmus nation
to create one of the world's engineering marvels, Panama is
preparing itself for life without los Americanos.
</P>
<P>
   But as the clock ticks toward noon on Dec. 31, when the last
step in the transfer of the canal and its surrounding 100,000 acres
of property will be completed, no one _ Panamanian or American _
knows what to expect next. The predictions run the gamut, from US
officials who warn that the canal's operation will be riddled with
corruption to Panamanians who smugly bet that they will run the
waterway more efficiently than the US government ever has in the
years since it opened in 1914.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the uncertainty is the question of who Panama's next
president will be. More than a million voters are expected to vote
Sunday in a race that looks too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   The two leading candidates are Martin Torrijos, the 35-year-old
son of the late general, Omar Torrijos, who in the late 1970s
negotiated with US President Jimmy Carter for the canal's transfer
to Panama; and Mireya Moscoso, the widow of former President
Arnulfo Arias Madrid, whose term was cut short when he was
overthrown by General Torrijos in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and voters alike have criticized both candidates for
not offering many new ideas for relying more on the ghosts and
legends of their famous kin as they campaigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am trying to make a better life for my family and they
keep reminding me of their family,'' said Octavio Torres, 27, who
is unemployed and lives in the rough tenement slums of Santa Cruz
in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the presidency will have the ceremonial honor of
presiding over the last step in the Canal Zone handover, something
nationalist factions have dreamed about for decades. But Panama's
next leader will face several daunting tasks, chief among them
being managing independence for a country that has never known life
without the presence of an outside force _ first Spain in colonial
times, then Colombia, and until the end of this year, the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge will be absorbing the economic and
psychological blow of the American pullout. The US military, which
has operated seven bases and dozens of schools, airports and
hospitals, have poured more than $300 million a year into the local
economy and provided more than 16,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the independence movements that eventually led to the
canal transfer, the American presence has also offered residents
and foreign investors alike an unspoken guarantee of protection
against rampant crime, invasions and a chaotic government.
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable example of that came during seven days in
December 1989 when US forces invaded Panama and ousted General
Manuel Noriega, who refused to leave office after his term ended.
He is now serving a prison sentence for drug conspiracy in Florida.
After that episode, the country dissolved its military and has been
reforming its police and judicial systems.
</P>
<P>
   There is also concern as to how quickly Panama will be able to
make new use the rich land and 5,000 structures being left behind
by the United States. Already, there is criticism that development
plans for the land, one-tenth of the country's total area, are
driven more by profit motives than by any effort to address
pressing social needs, such as the 40 percent poverty rate.
</P>
<P>
   At the offices of the Inter-Oceanic Regional Authority, the
agency responsible for developing the transferred areas, director
Nicolas Ardito Barletta uses a computer presentation to offer his
vision of a post-US Canal Zone that offers everything from cargo
loading to day spas. At both ends, new ports, developed by Asian
firms, will welcome cruise and cargo ships. There will be shopping
areas to greet passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Areas along the canal that were once military barrracks and
officers' homes will be turned into country club resorts. A ``City
of Knowledge,'' complete with American and Panamanian university
campuses and research-based companies, will become an academic
jewel, planners say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often hear comparisons to Singapore, and we agree,'' Ardito
said, referring to the potential of the canal and the surrounding
lands, whose value has been put at $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   To help pay for the vision, officials have attracted investors
primarily from Asia, Europe and the United States, which is still
the canal's biggest customer.
</P>
<P>
   Panama has already taken virtual control of the canal itself.
Ninety percent of the jobs are now held by locals, and a Panamanian
has directed the canal's governing agency since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   At Balboa High School, many of the 1,100 students are wondering
what life will be like in their new homes. Most will leave with
their families and live in the US for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see if I like living in the US or if I decide to
come back here to Panama,'' said Steve Bowman, 17, a senior who
will study at the University of Virginia next fall. ``We've had
very different lives down here. Maybe even sheltered. A lot of us
see this as home, and the US as a foreign country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
