<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JACKSON (Belgrade) _ The three captive American
servicemen held by Yugoslavia talked on Friday with Jesse Jackson
and said that they are being kept in separate cells, have no
contact with each other or with other prisoners in the same
facility, were able to take a walk outside their cells only twice
during their monthlong imprisonment, but are generally well-fed and
have no medical problems. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Washington) _ An account of the UPI's
interview with President Slobodan Milosevic, in which he charges
that the air war is the United States' attempt to achieve two
goals: to prove its leadership in Europe as well as re-establish
its leadership in NATO. ``NATO believes it can pick on a small
nation and force us to surrender our independence,'' Milosevic
says. ``And that is where NATO miscalculated. You are not willing
to sacrifice lives to achieve our surrender. But we are willing to
die to defend our rights as an independent sovereign nation.'' By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The Yugoslav capital cleans up
after the heaviest night of bombing yet. Army headquarters and the
Interior Ministry were hit. A civilian area of city was
accidentally hit, but no one was killed. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Belgrade) _ Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian
envoy, is to meet Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, today
and perhaps Ibrahim Rugova, an ethnic-Albanian leader. Meanwhile
the Yugoslav Foreign Ministry says that Belgrade could accept an
international force for Kosovo if the U.N. Security Council
authorizes it _ but only an unarmed force. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Military action as reported from
Washington and NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-APACHE (Washington) _ One night, maybe soon, the first
American Apache helicopters are supposed to take off from a
makeshift base in Albania, pause to refuel in the rugged northern
Albanian hills and then, with rockets raining ahead of them, fly
into Kosovo to try to do what NATO's high-flying jets have not:
eviscerate Yugoslavia's armored forces. Such attacks carry enormous
risk, though. And for that reason President Clinton still has not
approved their use in combat in the Balkans. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   This story, budgeted earlier, is now scratched:
</P>
<P>
   KOVOSO-MASSACRE
</P>
