<HEADLINE>
CLEAR WEATHER BRINGS UPTICK IN NATO BOMBING PACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ Aided by the clearest skies since it began attacking
Yugoslavia six weeks ago, NATO said Friday it had conducted its
heaviest night of bombing, targeting army headquarters, the Defense
Ministry and an opulent suburban home of Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Brigadier General Giuseppe Marani, NATO's military spokesman,
said the forecast is for good weather the next few days and that
the number of attacks would be stepped up. Bad weather over much of
the last six weeks had hampered the laser systems used by most NATO
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to their trauma, Belgrade residents were shaken by a
moderate earthquake shortly after the bombing runs ended early
Friday. No one was injured in the earthquake, but a policeman was
reported killed when NATO bombs struck the Interior Ministry, which
controls the paramilitary police accused of atrocities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Shea, NATO's chief spokesman, said that NATO pilots had
flown more than 600 sorties in a 24-hour period ending early
Friday, the most yet in Operation Allied Force. That is about
double the average number of daily sorties. Because of the clear
skies, about half of those missions actually fired missiles or
dropped bombs, Shea said. In the past, bad weather has forced many
fighters to return to base without dropping their payloads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are bringing the air campaign home to where it hurts
most,'' said Shea. ``We are benefitting from much improved
weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea acknowledged that one NATO missile ``went astray and landed
on some houses.'' Belgrade authorities said four people were
injured and a family narrowly escaped with their lives when they
jumped from their home as it collapsed after being hit by the stray
missile.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO vowed to intensify its air war, there was a flurry of
diplomatic activity in Belgrade, as diplomats tried to find a
negotiated end to the bombing and the expulsion of ethnic Albanians
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin met with Milosevic in
Belgrade, and Yugoslav officials repeated their offer to allow an
unarmed United Nations-backed force into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Shea dismissed the offer, saying, ``Those proposals do not come
close to meeting the demands of the international community. They
are not worthy of serious consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
the increased bombing was part of the ``domination phase'' in which
NATO fighters focus on hitting the Yugoslav forces on the ground
that have been forcibly expelling ethnic Albanians from Kosovo in
what is the worst refugee crisis in Europe since the end of World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Among the targets hit Thursday night and early Friday were a
metals plant, a border post, tanks, an oil refinery, surface-to-air
missile sites, the main TV transmitter in Belgrade, the army
headquarters, police stations, and ammunition dumps.
</P>
<P>
   Shea called the target list ``the largest and the most diverse''
of the air campaign so far.
</P>
<P>
   Marani said all of the NATO jets returned safely to base, but
they faced at least 13 missiles fired at them from the ground. He
said they were not encountered by any Yugoslav warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took the battle back to the heart of Belgrade,'' said
Marani.
</P>
<P>
   The TV tower, an imposing 650-foot concrete tower on Mount Avila
just outside Belgrade, was a symbol of Serbian pride when it was
built in the 1960s. Its destruction knocked state TV off the air
for a few hours, as have previous attacks on transmitters, but the
station NATO accuses of being Milosevic's propaganda machine has
proved resilient.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks were not limited to Belgrade. Marani said the mobile
army units on the ground in Kosovo that are blamed by refugees for
driving hundreds and thousands of people from their homes and
commiting atrocities such as summary executions and rape of
civilians were hit Thursday harder than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``All over Kosovo, they have been hit,'' he said. ``They have
been hit where they have been found.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Kosovo Albanian leaders met here Friday with NATO general
secretary Javier Solana to express their appreciation to NATO, but
also to ask the alliance to step up its efforts to force Milosevic
to back down. The Albanians, led by Blerim Shala, the newspaper
editor who was part of the Kosovar delegation at the failed peace
talks in France, were reluctant to criticize NATO's refusal to send
in ground troops to flush out Serb troops and rescue an estimated
700,000 refugees stuck inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vjosa Dobruna, director for the Center of Protection of
Women and Children in Pristina, the Kosovar capital, said that
those stuck inside Kosovo have no access to food or medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she thought NATO needed to do more to help the
refugees, on whose behalf the air war is being waged, Dobruna said
only, ``I wish they would do it very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea disputed reports that suggested NATO's bombs are creating
environmental hazards to civilians, and that the Yugoslav army is
hanging tough. He said stories suggesting longterm environmental
damage in Serbia are exaggerated, and that desertion and low morale
is rampant in the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   Shea also claimed that NATO's efforts to avoid hitting civilian
targets was working, despite the missile that hit the residential
area in Belgrade, and one that went astray Wednesday night and
destroyed a home in a suburb of the Bulgarian capital Sofia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a fraction of one percent,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   But UN High Commissioner for Human Rights Mary Robinson also
criticized NATO, saying its campaign was killing civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, the former president of Ireland, said, ``Large numbers
of civilians have been incontestably killed, civilian installations
targeted on the basis that they are or could be of military
application, and NATO remains the sole judge of what is or is not
acceptable to bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav authorities say more than 500 civilians have been
killed by NATO, while NATO officials insist the number of
accidental deaths caused by errant bombs is closer to 100.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
