no signs of flagging. Despite a decline in auto production and
another sharp deterioration in the nation's trade balance, the U.S.
economy grew at a surprisingly robust 4.5 percent rate this winter,
the government reported. That is the sort of heady pace usually
associated with the first, not the eighth, year of an economic
expansion and hardly the sharp slowdown from last fall's sizzling 6
percent rate that forecasters, including the Federal Reserve, were
