<SLUG> BC-FLEET-ZUCCHINI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNO CHIEF ZUCCHINI TO QUITE FLEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Fleet Financial Group confirmed Friday that its chief
technology executive will retire at the end of this year, the
latest top Boston banker to leave in the wake of the company's
planned merger with BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Zucchini, a 52-year-old Fleet vice chairman who joined
the company in 1987, had overseen the meshing of computer systems
in a number of Fleet's past bank mergers _ not always with flying
colors.
</P>
<P>
   But Zucchini's departure was a surprise given that he had been
slated to share responsibility for the newly merged company's
computer systems with his counterpart at BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   That pairing, which was unique in Fleet's selection of top
executives _ in all cases, so far, one executive from either bank
was named _ may have helped precipitate his departure, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zucchini's retirement, first reported by the Providence Journal,
is the second departure of a Fleet executive this week. John
Hamill, the president of Fleet Bank of Massachusetts and a
prominent face in Boston's business community, also said he would
step down at the end of the year. At BankBoston, executive vice
president Ira Jackson, the man credited with reshaping the
company's image after it was tarnished by scandal in the mid-1980s,
announced his retirement last week.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company is expected to announce more top management
changes, possibly next week, as it carries out the $15 billion
merger announced on March 14. The banks are still awaiting approval
for the combination from federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's spokesman, James Mahoney, said Zucchini is selling his
Rhode Island horse farm in order to move to California with his
family to pursue that interest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger created an opportune time for Mike to make his
move,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is no secret in the banking community that Zucchini's
star had dimmed _ and that the reputation of BankBoston Corp.'s top
computer executive, Joseph Smialowski, was still rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Zucchini had been at Fleet a long time, and they had had
some operating snafus in their history,'' said Nancy Bush, a senior
vice president of Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. in New Jersey. ``Is one event
connected with the other? I can't say.''
</P>
<P>
   Zucchini was loyally supported by chief executive Terrence
Murray during his career.
</P>
<P>
   Zucchini, who was responsible for integrating Fleet's and
Shawmut National Corp.'s computers, took the heat for a check-
processing problem in Connecticut, which delayed the Shawmut
conversion by a few months.
</P>
<P>
   He also was the Fleet executive responsible for a short time in
the early 1990s for the company's embattled operations in the
south, Fleet Mortgage in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Zucchini's mixed reputation is in contrast to that of
Smialowski, whom BankBoston hired last November from a job as chief
technology officer for Sears Roebuck &AMP; Co. in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Smialowski ``is very, very well regarded,'' and BankBoston
regarded his hiring ``as something of a coup,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's said that Zucchini would stay on long enough to help
plan the integration of the two banks' computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be around for the critical decisions about what systems
they'll choose,'' said Gerard Cassidy, a bank analyst with Tucker
Anthony Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
