<SLUG> BC-HPHC-LOSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD PILGRIM POSTS HUGE LOSS; 8 PERCENT RATE HIKE PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, New England's largest
health maintenance organization, Friday posted its biggest annual
losses ever after having vastly underestimated their medical
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the growing ranks of the nation's financially ailing
HMOs, Harvard Pilgrim said it lost $94 million from operations in
1998 on revenue of $2.67 billion. When $40 million in investment
income is added, the HMO's net loss shrinks to $54 million.
</P>
<P>
   To recover, Harvard Pilgrim, which insures 1.3 million patients,
said it will aggressively raise premiums an average of 8 percent,
with some customers seeing double-digit hikes this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to keep premium rates as close to our costs as
possible,'' said Allan Greenberg, chief executive of Harvard
Pilgrim in Brookline. ``To the extent we can control costs,
premiums won't skyrocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating the red ink, Harvard Pilgrim late last year laid
off 100 employees, including Dr. Patrick Mattingly, the No. 2
executive at the HMO. This year, Harvard Pilgrim, which employs
4,200 full-time workers, instituted a hiring freeze in selective
departments and did away with bonuses. In addition, the pay of the
company's top two dozen executives has been frozen for 1999.
Greenberg said no further layoffs are planned.
</P>
<P>
   Other HMOs in Massachusetts have reported losses for 1998,
including Tufts Health Plan in Waltham and Fallon Community Health
Plan in Worcester. Only Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts
and Neighborhood Health Plan, which is owned by Harvard Pilgrim,
made money last year. Tufts lost $12.8 million last year, while
Fallon lost $21 million, in one year wiping out one-third of its
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the past two years have been tough on the managed
care industry. Buffetted by ballooning prescription drug costs and
other expenses, dozens of large insurers have plunged into the red.
Kaiser Permanente in California last year lost $288 million on
revenues of $15.5 billion. Oxford Health Plans in Connecticut lost
$276 million on revenue of $4.7 billion in 1998. Smaller health
plans have been battered, with some going out of business
altogether, including Health Insurance Plan of New Jersey, whose
200,000 patients were stranded in March when the company was forced
to liquidate.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the managed care market is particularly
brutal, as insurers continue to artificially suppress premiums to
maintain market share or gain new customers. While consumers have
benefitted from the stable premiums, insurers are paying the price
with their bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most intensely competitive climates in the
United States,'' said Jack Reichman, a director of Standard &AMP; Poors
Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The solution: raise premiums, say industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty percent of the industry is losing money because the
industry hasn't charged corporate America enough for what their
employees consume,'' said Kenneth Abramowitz, health care analyst
with Sanford Bernstein in New York. ``HMOs have to raise their
rates 10 percent a year for the next three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim's premium increases for 1998 were relatively
modest, even though its expenses swelled, leading to the large
loss. The HMO, for example, spent $300 million last year on
prescription drugs alone, a 17 percent increase over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors for the loss include spending to address the
so-called Y2K problem in which computers cannot recognize the year
2000. It also incurred ``large losses'' in its Medicare business,
though Greenberg declined to specify an amount.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Harvard Pilgrim made a modest net income of $5.4
million on $2.3 billion in revenues, down from $19.3 million in net
income on $2.1 billion in revenues in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim's declining fortunes are reflected in its
Standard &AMP; Poors' bond ratings, which have slid from A in 1997 to
BBB this year, with a ``negative'' outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg said he expected Harvard Pilgrim to break even this
year, but declined to discuss more specific projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real test for them is how well they can implement a
turnaround plan,'' said Standard &AMP; Poor's Reichman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
