<SLUG> BC-CHECKFREE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CheckFree glitch mostly fixed
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CheckFree said Friday it has largely fixed a glitch in
a new software system that disabled electronic banking accounts for
all week.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the system should work fine but 2 percent of
those trying to use it might still have problems.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which provides electronic banking services, said
the glitch affected a new program called Genesis. Genesis is used
by 21 banks nationwide, including SunTrust and FirstUnion.
</P>
<P>
   Many customers of these two banks in Atlanta reported problems
signing onto to their electronic banking accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 500,000 electronic banking customers were affected by the
glitch nationwide, CheckFree said. There were no estimates on how
many customers were inconvenienced in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The glitch, which prevented customers from accessing their
electronic accounts, bedeviled CheckFree all week. It wasn't until
late Thursday that the company found the root of the problem and
began to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of everyone at CheckFree, I want to apologize for
the inconveniences consumers have experienced because of this
issue,'' Chief Operating Officer Pete Sinisgalli said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree Holdings Co. has some 2.8 million customers and helps
to provide electronic payment services at 350 institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
