A9911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TESTDRIVE-TACOMA01-CO     04-30 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-TACOMA01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PreRunner stays with the pack
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Toyota is hardly a leader when it comes to building
and selling compact pickups, but the Tacoma PreRunner is proof that
the company is learning to play follow-the-leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Throw on some options to dress up the exterior and add comfort
to the interior, and the PreRunner can run with other
American-built pickups as long as the going doesn't get too rough.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota does get some things right. The test regular-cab
PreRunner had a high-quality ``imperial jade mica'' green paint job
that gleamed. The fit-and-finish both inside and out reflected the
build quality that goes into Toyota's cars, and there's nothing
cheesy about the cloth and plastic in the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   But that should be expected, because the PreRunner doesn't come
cheap. The rear-wheel-drive test vehicle's base price of $14,768 is
about $10,000 below what you'd pay for a loaded version with
extended cab and four-wheel drive, but dressing it up with options
boosted the bottom line to $17,732.
</P>
<P>
   The powertrain, too, is solid, although hardly a powerhouse. The
standard engine is a 2.7-liter four-cylinder rated at 150
horsepower at 4,800 rpm and a maximum 177 pounds-feet of torque at
4,000 rpm. The engine is responsive, and the four-speed automatic
transmission _ no manual available _ handles the power nicely,
despite a tendency to kick down when all the driver really wants is
just a touch of acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   The ride has been improved, but remains less than carlike. The
PreRunner isn't fond of uneven pavement, and rumble strips can be
felt as well as heard. The handling is good, as long as turns are
met with a little respect.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota wants the regular-cab, rear-drive PreRunner to be
mistaken for a four-wheel-drive model and pretty much succeeds on
that count. The PreRunner's 265/75R15 tires and sporty aluminum
wheels help make it about 70 inches tall, and it's got enough
ground clearance _ nearly a foot _ to make the step up a bit of a
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But while the PreRunner goes well, it lacks the standard
anti-lock brakes of many of its competitors, and two doors are all
you can get. Extra doors are coming, Toyota says, well aware that
more manufacturers and buyers are realizing that third and fourth
doors are a godsend.
</P>
<P>
   In short, don't expect too much of the PreRunner. It's clearly
well-built and has good ergonomics and decent seats, but it's not
the macho truck its option-aided looks suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Toyota PreRunner compact rear-drive pickup
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $17,732 (Includes discounts not always
available. Base price: $14,768)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: side-impact beams, dual air bags with
passenger-side switch
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 2.7-liter four-cylinder engine with 16 valves (150
horsepower), four-speed automatic overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: sport package with 265/75R15 tires and
aluminum wheels, chrome-plated rear bumper, cloth bucket seats,
sliding rear window, center console box, sun visor with mirror and
pocket, $1,670; package with air conditioner, stereo radio with
cassette player, carpeted floor mats, $1,405; package with tilt
wheel, cruise control, tachometer, digital clock, $690; bedliner,
$279; trailer hitch, $295
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 19 mpg regular unleaded city, 21 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
