<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9915 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TENN-HEALTHCARE-470(2     04-30 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TENN-HEALTHCARE-470(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST PRESSURES THREATEN TENNESSEE'S AMBITIOUS HEALTH INSURANCE
PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ In one bold stroke, Tennessee converted its
Medicaid health benefits to managed care five years ago and used
the savings to cover hundreds of thousands of people who could not
afford health insurance of their own or were too sick to qualify.
With 3 million people enrolled, its program, called TennCare,
became the most ambitious and generous government health plan in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But with TennCare's costs rising and Tennessee facing a budget
deficit, the program is under fire and facing probable retrenchment
under pressure from Gov. Don Sundquist. And the people most at risk
are those who benefit most from the state's effort at providing
nearly universal health insurance: those with chronic or even
terminal diseases who have been rejected by private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   To arrest a projected 12 percent increase in TennCare spending
for the year beginning in July, Sundquist, a Republican elected to
a second four-year term in November, has proposed a moratorium on
new enrollments of the uninsurable for six months or a year while
the state explores cutting benefits, raising premiums and
tightening eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, TennCare Director Brian Lapps is suggesting that some
beneficiaries of the program are exploiting it. The poorest
recipients, Lapps said, could help pay for their care if they would
only curb their use of cell phones and cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a spoiled population that wants everything for
nothing,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The program's advocates are stunned. ``Tennessee did something
ahead of the curve, and now it's back to the Okefenokee Swamp,''
said Dr. Stephen Raffanti, medical director of an outpatient AIDS
clinic at the Vanderbilt University Medical Center that opened its
doors when TennCare began and now has 1,500 patients.
</P>
<P>
   TennCare is free for most of its beneficiaries, who are poor
enough to qualify for Medicaid. The better-off beneficiaries pay
premiums, deductibles and fees based on their incomes. Applicants
with debilitating pre-existing conditions, like AIDS or multiple
sclerosis, qualify merely by presenting a letter from an insurance
company denying them coverage.
</P>
<P>
   TennCare's impact has been greatest for that last group, which
the program calls ``uninsurables,'' currently numbering 108,000 of
the 1.3 million enrolled in TennCare. But they are also by far the
most expensive group _ a single patient's medication can cost tens
of thousands of dollars a year _ and the cost of extending coverage
to this group is at the root of TennCare's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Caught between rising prescription costs and growing numbers of
these sickest patients, TennCare has slashed its payments to
doctors and HMOs below what they need to break even, according to a
state-financed analysis by PricewaterhouseCoopers, a consulting
firm.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One day in April, 52 of the uninsurable came to testify in the
small basement conference room of a state office building at a
hearing the state called on the proposal to stop enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a sticker proclaiming, ``We are not the problem,'' David
Tignor, 24, said he has hemophilia. Tignor is hobbled by braces for
ankles that internal bleeding has turned arthritic. He caught AIDS
and hepatitis C from a blood transfusion. The state and federal
government pay for his medicine, which costs more than $100,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my work cell phone,'' Tignor said, pulling one from
his jeans and thrusting it at Lapps, who presided but sat mute,
taking notes. Tignor says he uses it to call for help when he
falls. He said his employer pays for the phone. ``I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Louise McKown, 49, lugged herself up to the microphone on two
canes that she had decorated with bouquets of violets and daisies.
Ms. McKown has a degenerative brain disease that has slurred her
speech and made noodles of her legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day may come when I can no longer speak, write or type,''
she said. She admonished Lapps, ``This was most definitely not
caused by smoking or drinking.'' She added, ``I do not want your
pity, but I do wish that you understand my reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In his one response to his petitioners' comments, Lapps promised
that those who were already enrolled in TennCare would not be
disenrolled.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration allows states to devise variations of
the basic federally subsidized state Medicaid programs that for the
most part cover parents and their children who are on welfare and,
more recently, parents who are moving from welfare to work at low
wages.
</P>
<P>
   In developing Tennessee's variation in late 1993, Gov. Ned
McWerter, a Democrat, and his commissioner for finance and
administration then, David Manning, thought that by using managed
care and health maintenance organizations to cover the state's
800,000 Medicaid recipients, they could both tame the inflation
then raging in health care and generate savings to cover people who
were uninsured, including the uninsurable.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To maneuver around a hostile physicians' lobby and a skeptical
Legislature, then out of session, McWerter and Manning opened the
program overnight, as the new year began in 1994. Health care
institutions and his own administration were ill-prepared, and
abuses, fraud and foul-ups ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was `Who's on first? Where's second?,''' said Gordon
Bonnyman, director of the nonprofit Tennessee Justice Center, a
public policy advocacy group. An influential lawyer and lobbyist,
Bonnyman helped assure TennCare's start by trading his support for
the shift to HMOs for McWerter's promise to cover the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the chaos, McWerter, whose left office in January
1995 and was succeeded by Sundquist, had put the state on the road
to the universal care that President Clinton proposed then and that
Congress subsequently blocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``TennCare showed that if there is a political will, it could be
done,'' Bonnyman said. ``Now that is being casually, cavalierly,
thoughtlessly tossed aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Tenncare is solidly entrenched. It covers 24
percent of the population. Its enrollment includes 768,000 Medicaid
recipients, whose coverage is not threatened, along with the
108,000 uninsurable and 411,000 of the previously uninsured, mostly
workers and their families who either are not offered insurance
through their jobs or cannot afford it if they are.
</P>
<P>
   By some measures, TennCare is succeeding. A survey last year by
the Center for Business and Economic Research at the University of
Tennessee in Knoxville found that 81 percent of the enrollees were
satisfied with TennCare in 1997 compared with 61 percent at the
outset in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollees using hospital emergency rooms, the survey found, had
fallen by half over the three years, suggesting that people are
getting treated before crises strike.
</P>
<P>
   TennCare's advocates say the program has also succeeded in
keeping many of the uninsured self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have patients at five and six years who are working,'' said
Raffanti of the Comprehensive Care Clinic, the one specializing in
AIDS. ``A lot of these patients I'm going to keep from going to
end-stage disease for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officials and health care experts here trace TennCare's
current financial travails to two miscalculations early on. One,
they say, was the McWerter administration's high expectations for
the impact of managed care in reducing costs. Another was a
decision to limit coverage to 1.3 million enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   So appealing was the promise of coverage that the uninsured,
most of them healthy, rushed aboard. The limit was reached within
months, and in late 1994, the state stopped enrolling them, though
it later reopened coverage to uninsured children.
</P>
<P>
   But under agreement with the federal Health Care Financing
Administration, which regulates Medicaid and Medicare, it continued
to enroll the uninsurable. And as their numbers grew, the state
lost more and more of the contribution to the cost of their care
that it had received from the largely healthy uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, we should open enrollment to the uninsured, not wait
for people to get sick,'' said John Ferguson, the commissioner for
finance and administration.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other issues, too, said Lapps, the TennCare
director.
</P>
<P>
   He knows his new terrain: For three years, until last October,
he was an uninsurable TennCare enrollee because of a condition he
declines to disclose, and is now covered by the state employee
health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lapps says he wants to preserve TennCare and that ``we are 60 to
65 percent of having it right.'' Problems he wants to tackle, he
said, include insurance companies suspected of dumping patients on
TennCare, signs of illegal enrollments, excessively generous
benefits and neglecting to verify enrollees' incomes.
</P>
<P>
   But TennCare enrollees are an issue, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of responsible poor out there,'' he said.
``But there's a portion who drive up to the doctor's in a BMW.'' He
said, ``The question has to be raised: What is their purchasing
priority?''
</P>
<P>
   Lapps has some support. The Tennessee Medical Association has
fought TennCare from the start, mostly because of cuts in
physicians' fees, which Lapps would partly restore. ``He's talking
the talk that we've been talking for five years,'' said Russ
Miller, the association's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The HCFA must approve the moratorium during which the governor
and Lapps would look into revising TennCare. Negotiations continue,
and federal officials in Washington declined to comment. But
Ferguson, the state commissioner for finance and administration,
said, ``The reading we're getting is, we could close enrollment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnyman said that would be the demise of TennCare as it has
been known. ``It's like the governor woke up and said, `Why are we
covering all these people when other states aren't?''' he said.
``It's a poignant testimony to our national incapacity to develop a
rational and humane health policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
