u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-30 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS WIDOW WRITING HER OWN HISTORY OF REGGIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The judge in the Reggie Lewis case has twice issued
gag orders to those directly involved, but that didn't seem to
deter Donna Harris-Lewis. Reggie's widow was calling around,
getting puff pieces written about her over the past two weeks in
this paper and ``People'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Are we supposed to think it is just coincidence this all
happened within days of jury selection? Harris-Lewis is now selling
the story that the reason she decided to sue four doctors for
malpractice was triggered by a story in the Wall Street Journal
that tied Reggie's death to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis now has her own version of history. The first one
ever to publicly link Reggie Lewis to drugs was . . . Donna
Harris-Lewis. Shortly after Reggie was released from the hospital
days after he first collapsed, Harris-Lewis, on the Jimmy Myers
radio show on WEEI in Boston, revealed that the doctors on the
Dream Team questioned Reggie about drugs, and she didn't like that.
In response, she moved him out of New England Baptist Hospital to
Brigham and Women's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gilbert Mudge was not part of the Dream Team. He was not
involved with Reggie until Harris-Lewis switched hospitals. When
Lewis died, and well over a year before the Wall Street Journal
story, this writer wrote about the possiblity of drugs being tied
to Lewis's death.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis says in the magazine article that Mudge claimed he
told Lewis that the only explanation for his fatal condition was
cocaine use.
</P>
<P>
   Quote from Harris-Lewis: ``You talk about the shock of losing
your husband, I was even more shocked when he said that.'' How
could it be a shock when Reggie was being questioned about drug
use, in her presence, almost two years before by the Dream Team?
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis, even though she is asking for upward of $100
million in damages, says it's not about the money. This statement
has the same ring of truth in it as one from Roger Clemens: It
wasn't about money. Clemens wanted to be with a winner. His
ultimate goal would be to play in Houston, yet when he had a chance
to be traded to Houston, where he lived, he turned it down when the
Astros wouldn't pay him what he wanted. It's never about the money,
is it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next Fenway Park will retain some of the park's famous
touches, such as the Green Monster in left field and the Pesky Pole
on the right-field line. The team is finishing its financial plan
and hopes to reveal its project intentions sometime this month.
</P>
<P>
   There are some who wonder whether it would be smarter for the
Red Sox to sell the team and the park now, and let the next buyer
worry about getting a new park built. But Sox chief John Harrington
says a sale now would set the project back for several years, and
he feels present management _ representing the Yawkey ownership,
which has been in power since 1932, would have a better chance of
getting something done than some newcomer with no prior investment
with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If he had any options left, I wish the Red Sox would have sent
John Valentin to Pawtucket instead of Lou Merloni. Valentin looks
like he is starting to acquire the dreaded Pillsbury Dough Boy
disease that strikes veteran Red Sox players with big contracts.
They seem to grow larger around the waist as the years go past,
like Mo Money and Clemens. The way Valentin has been running this
year to first base, you could time him with an hourglass. Is there
a bakery in the locker room?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Merloni, what was Nomar Garciaparra supposed to say
when the media asked him about his friend being sent down to
Pawtucket? ``Gee, I think it's great.'' Of course he's going to say
he's unhappy. Merloni's his friend. He's going to speak up for him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before it all started, if Harry Sinden had had his way, the
Bruins wouldn't be playing Carolina in this tough playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a tough matchup for us,'' Sinden said. ``Buffalo is,
too. I think everyone in our conference hoped they could get to
play Ottawa because they were not playing well at the end of the
year. Carolina and Buffalo have similar styles of play, and we have
trouble with it. Their forwards are very quick, and do a good job
of attacking our defensemen in our own end. When that happens, we
have a tough time playing well. Against both teams it is better if
we can slow the game down and control the play at center ice,
rather than having their forwards pounding our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago Dick Radatz, who is terrific on radio,
said in essence the one thing he never liked about Clemens was the
way he took himself out of close games, and left the finish to the
relief pitchers, even when the Sox didn't have a good bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about that last Sunday afternoon when Pedro Martinez
had one out to get against Cleveland and had thrown more than 120
pitches. Martinez didn't come out. He fought to stay in the game
and struck out the last batter to win, 3-2. He didn't want to leave
it up to the bullpen. Roger would have been into his second
cheeseburger by then.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a rumor that the Atlanta Falcons contacted the Patriots
at draft time about making a trade for running back Jamal Anderson.
Anderson, one of the best backs in the league and the reason the
Falcons got to the Super Bowl last year, is in the last year of his
contract and will be looking for a ton of money. Supposedly,
Atlanta would have traded him for a bundle of draft picks . . .
Speaking of draft-day antics, instead of saying that he wasn't up
for trade, why don't the Patriots tell Terry Glenn they put him out
for grabs and that no one was that interested? Then he might wake
up and realize that football is a game you have to love, to work
at, and want to play, if you're going to be great . . . Horse owner
Bill Parcells likes Cat Thief in the Kentucky Derby: ``With this
many horses in a race, the horse that avoids a bad trip has a good
chance to win,'' Parcells said. ``I like his post position. I think
he can get out fast, not get boxed in, and stay with the pace. I
don't see any horse coming from way back in this field, getting
through all the horses in front of him, and winning this race.''. .
. Say a prayer for Leon Hess, the 85-year-old owner of the New York
Jets who is a wonderful gentleman and all class, as he fights for
his life in a New York hospital.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
