<HEADER>
A9922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PROTEST-NYT &LR;      04-30 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.) 
CHINESE LEADERS WARN WORKERS ABOUT FUTURE DEMONSTRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Fearing that members of the Buddhist Law movement
might demonstrate again in coming days, China's leaders issued a
warning this morning to all government officials and employees of
state-run institutions not to take part in any such protests.
</P>
<P>
   The government was clearly rattled and embarrassed by the
surprise appearance last Sunday of some 10,000 followers of the
movement, in the largest public demonstration here since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, who maintained an eerie vigil around the
leadership compound in Beijing, have asked for favorable
recognition of their fast-growing group and an end to negative
portrayals of them in the press.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhist Law, known here as Falun Gong, was established in the
early 1990s by Li Hongzhi, a martial-arts master who is now 48. He
combined elements of the ancient practice of qigong, involving
breathing and meditation exercises said to mobilize energy forces,
with concepts drawn from Buddhism and his own theories of spiritual
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Membership has soared, largely in urban areas. The group has
attracted many well-educated people, including retired officials
and workers, who often embrace it with a consuming passion.
According to various government officials this week, the number of
followers inside China is anywhere from 20 million to 70 million,
although all may not be fervent devotees.
</P>
<P>
   Li, who said he felt pressure from an uneasy government, moved
to New York in 1998 and is building a global network of adherents.
</P>
<P>
   The group's power to mobilize its members was evident last
weekend as thousands mounted their vigil before the police realized
what was happening. Reflecting the gingerly approach it has
generally taken toward the group, the government allowed
demonstrators to stay through the day and depart peacefully, and a
senior official met with leaders to discuss their complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, in a widely broadcast statement, the government
said that differences of opinion about groups like Falun Gong were
permissible, but it sternly warned followers against further
actions that ``jeopardize social stability.'' At the same time, the
official media were instructed to avoid inflaming the situation by
printing any articles about Falun Gong or even, for the time being,
the general subject of qigong.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday morning, leaders of government agencies, research
institutes, publishing companies, newspapers and even state-owned
industrial companies in Beijing and many other cities were given an
urgent message, jointly issued by the General Offices of the
Communist Party and the State Council. These leaders in turn called
meetings of their office heads, who were instructed to pass the
message on to all employees, often including retirees, who were
called at home.
</P>
<P>
   According to an employee of a state publishing company in
Beijing who heard it, the message read: ``It has been learned that
on May 1, 2 or 3, Falun Gong practitioners are likely to stage
large-scale activities nationwide. Government workers must not
believe rumors, spread rumors or take part in such activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Mounting any large protest in coming days will be very
difficult. The Beijing police have been on high alert over the last
week and are certain to remain so over the coming three days, as
China marks the May 1 holiday honoring workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
