<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMOROS-COUP-ART-NYT &LR;      04-30 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMOROS-COUP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY OUSTS COMOROS GOVERNMENT IN COUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The Comoran military announced
Friday that it overthrew the government of the Comoro Islands on
Thursday night. The streets there were quiet Friday after the
apparently bloodless coup, a local journalist said.
</P>
<P>
   The military said it had staged the coup to stop violent
demonstrations on the main island against residents from Anjouan
island, which has been trying to declare its independence from the
Federal Islamic Republic of the Comoros.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Comorans from the main island, Grand Comore,
broke into the houses of Anjouanais, beating them and telling them
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to my house when I was at a conference, but my wife
and children and mother-in-law were at home,'' said Kamardine
Mohammed, a journalist and native of Anjouan who lives in a small
house just off the main road through Moroni, the capital.
``Fortunately a friend of mine who is a gendarme persuaded them to
go away. But my family was highly traumatized.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1,000 people are believed to have left Grand Comore for
Anjouan this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Comoros, a tiny archipelago northwest of Madagascar in the
Indian Ocean, has had 18 coups or coup attempts in the 24 years
since it won independence from France. The volcanic islands are
beautiful but impoverished. Export income comes from vanilla,
cloves and perfume oil from the ylang-ylang, a custard-apple tree.
Tourism, which has enriched Indian Ocean islands like Mauritius,
has never really caught on.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four principal islands, Mayotte, chose to remain a
French colony at independence, and has prospered. About two years
ago, Anjouan and Moheli, feeling bullied by Grand Comore, asked
France to take them back. There is a long history of inter-island
hostility, reflected in a Comoran saying: ``Grand Comore rules,
Anjouan works and Moheli sleeps.''
</P>
<P>
   France declined, and Anjouan and Moheli declared their
independence. A force of 300 ill-prepared soldiers from the main
island tried to invade Anjouan in September 1997 but was beaten
back in a harbor gun battle, with about a third of the force
captured. The Anjounais had plenty of warning because residents of
Grand Comore saw troops commandeering boats in the harbor there for
days.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the separatists on Anjouan have split into two
factions and there have been gun battles in Mutsamudu, the main
city.
</P>
<P>
   Talks in Madagascar to resolve the inter-island crisis led last
week to an agreement giving Anjouan and Moheli more autonomy while
keeping them in the republic. The acting president, Tadjiddine Ben
Said Massounde, signed it, but the Anjouan representatives balked,
saying they had to consult their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Massounde was reported to be at his home Friday. Col. Azali
Hassounani, the army chief of staff, was apparently ruling the
country, and the government was declared dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   No one took responsibility for whipping up sentiment against the
Anjounais, but some members of the old guard, military men who
ruled the country after past coups, went on the radio earlier this
week saying the Anjounais should be driven out, Mohammed said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel safe now,'' he said. ``The inaction of the authorities
was responsible. The Anjounais have taken a deep sigh of relief
since the coup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
