<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9940 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITY-$AD     04-30 1737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITY-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN JUSTICES UNSURE ABOUT DISABILITY LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, May 2) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A one-eyed truck driver, a mechanic on medication
for high-blood pressure and twin sisters who wear eyeglasses tried
to persuade the Supreme Court last week that they had been
illegally rejected for jobs because of those disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   At question was whether Congress, in passing the 1990 Americans
with Disabilities Act, intended to protect from job discrimination
only the most severely disabled or a much broader range of people,
including those with minor, treatable impairments.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by their questions and comments during arguments in the
three cases, the justices themselves are uncertain of the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The three cases involve Albertsons Inc. trucking company, United
Parcel Service Inc. and United Air Lines Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The ADA, a civil rights act for the disabled, has divided the
business and disability rights communities ever since it was first
being debated in Congress 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Companies continue to fear that the law's prohibition on bias
against the disabled will compel them to hire people even with the
most minor ailments, lest the businesses be sued for
discrimination. But advocates for the disabled counter that only a
strong anti-discrimination law, one that covers the gamut of
infirmities, will remove the entrenched stereotype that disabled
people are unable or unwilling to work.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court last week took a tentative step into this
breach between employers and employees, with justices echoing the
companies' anxiety about increased litigation and the advocates'
fear that invidious stereotypes will persist unless the law is
interpreted broadly.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, in each of the cases, pressed the employees'
lawyers on why their clients with common afflictions should be
protected under the statute. But the justices just as vigorously
asked company lawyers whether their clients perhaps ran afoul of
the law by regarding the employees and job applicants as disabled
and, hence, unemployable.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, in particular, expressed concern that a
broad interpretation of ``disability'' _ one that would include
easily treatable impairments _ would enable every rejected job
applicant and fired employee to sue under the law. ``This statute
wasn't meant to apply to all Americans,'' Scalia said during
arguments in a case that addressed whether Albertsons was justified
in firing a driver with vision in only one eye.
</P>
<P>
   But disability rights advocates, in contrast to Scalia's
comment, do seek an interpretation of the law that would embrace
infirmities that can be remedied with corrective lenses or
medicine. The groups argue that the law's goal of debunking
stereotypes about the disabled can best be achieved if the statute
applies to all Americans whose abilities are limited due to
physical or mental impairments.
</P>
<P>
   ``By expanding the class of individuals (covered by the law),
you are assuring that people with high blood pressure, back
problems or severe myopia have the same opportunities that the rest
of us have in the workplace,'' said Patricia Yeager, executive
director of the California Foundation for Independent Living
Centers. ``This is about ending discrimination and leveling the
playing field, plain and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, which supported the employees in the
three cases, argued before the high court that disabilities should
be judged on a case-by-case basis regardless of how easily they can
be treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assessing the existence of a disability without regard to
mitigating measures is most consistent with the ADA's basic purpose
to eliminate the exclusion of individuals from the workplace
because of outdated stereotypes and myths about those individuals'
abilities,'' the government argued in a legal brief to the
justices.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Bokat, a lawyer for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
conceded that Congress intended the disability rights law to
protect many Americans from discrimination, but not those with
minor afflictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress intended to only have the act apply to people whose
disabilities substantially interfere with major life activities,''
Bokat said. Lawmakers never meant for the law to cover
``practically everyone in the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 law to end discrimination against the disabled was
modeled after federal civil rights statutes designed to abolish
bias against minorities and women. The act prohibits employers of
at least 15 people from discriminating against disabled workers and
job applicants, defined in the law as people with a disability that
``substantially limits'' their ability to perform a major life
function, such as walking or seeing.
</P>
<P>
   The statute also prohibits companies from discriminating against
employees and applicants whom the employers regard as disabled. But
the act is largely silent on the breadth of the term
``disability,'' leaving it primarily to the courts to define the
law's contours.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer, during the argument sessions last
week, called the law ``unusual'' in that it is a civil rights act
in which neither the employer nor employee can be sure the worker
enjoys the statute's protection. Other civil rights laws _ which
protect minorities, women and older workers _ cover physical
characteristics, such as skin color, that are easily identifiable,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Sandra Day O'Connor indicated that the confusing
issue of what constitutes a disability might be irrelevant under
the law. The real question judges must answer in resolving whether
someone has suffered discrimination under the act is whether a
company illegally regarded that person as disabled.
</P>
<P>
   What an employer thinks about the physical or psychological
fitness of an employee or candidate ``really hits at the heart of
what the statute was aimed at,'' O'Connor said, noting that the law
seeks to end stereotypes about disabled employees. O'Connor made
her comment during arguments in the case of Vaughn Murphy, who
suffers from hypertension and was fired from his job as a mechanic
for Atlanta-based UPS, a position that requires driving company
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Although the three Supreme Court cases concerned employment in
the transportation industry, the justices asked, often with humor,
whether the disability rights law also applies to them and baseball
players. Scalia, for example, said he is ``close to blind'' but
does not consider himself disabled because his vision is corrected
with glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not do my current job, I could not do many other jobs,
without my glasses,'' the justice said during arguments in the UPS
case. ``A lot of Americans wear glasses and couldn't function
without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter, in a separate case, also addressed the
relevance of poor vision in questioning how substantial a
disability must be before it is protected under the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have difficulty reading restaurant checks in dim light,''
Souter said. He jokingly added that waiters regard this impairment
as substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Souter's comments came in a case brought by Karen Sutton and
Kimberly Hinton, twin sisters who say Chicago-based United violated
the ADA by refusing to hire them as pilots because their vision,
without corrective lenses, fails to meet the airline's safety
standard.
</P>
<P>
   During arguments in the United case, Scalia said the company's
refusal to hire the women might not have been due to their alleged
disability. Rather, the airline might have rejected them because
they were unqualified to be pilots based on their failure to pass a
legitimate vision test, Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The justice, using a baseball analogy to illustrate his point,
said the Boston Red Sox could legally choose Hall-of-Fame slugger
Ted Williams _ the last player to hit over .400 for a season _ over
another hitter with inferior vision without running afoul of the
disability rights law. The Red Sox could not be held liable for
discrimination when they merely opted to retain a player whose
ability to hit, for whatever reason, was better than another's,
Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Souter, picking up on Scalia's theme: ``If there's a .400
hitter out there, I don't want to hire a .200 hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The employers in the three cases are urging the court to read
the ADA narrowly, to count as disabled only those employees whose
disabilities, even after treatment, substantially limit their
ability to perform a major life function. The employees, by
contrast, are pressing for a broad definition that includes workers
whose disabilities, before treatment, are substantially limiting.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the Albertsons case, Hallie Kirkingburg contends
the company illegally fired him as a truck driver because he is
blind in one eye. The U.S. District Court for Oregon dismissed the
lawsuit, saying Kirkingburg had failed to meet federal vision
regulations for truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed, saying that
Kirkingburg is certainly disabled in the major life activity of
seeing and that the company regarded him as disabled. The 9th
Circuit, noting that the Federal Highway Administration had granted
Kirkingburg a waiver from its vision standard, told the district
court to hold a trial to determine if he is qualified to drive a
truck regardless of his disability.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy alleges that UPS violated the rights law when it fired
him after a company nurse concluded that his unmedicated blood
pressure of 160/90 exceeded federal guidelines for truck drivers.
The U.S. District Court for Kansas and then the 10th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals ruled against Murphy, saying he is not disabled
because his blood pressure is treatable with medication.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton and Hinton argue that United illegally rejected them to
be pilots because of their poor vision, even though their sight is
fine when they wear corrective lenses. But the U.S. District Court
for Colorado, followed by the 10th Circuit, ruled for the airline
after concluding that the women are not disabled but merely have a
visual impairment that can be corrected with lenses.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is expected to render its decisions in the three
cases by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORAH-PURCHASE01-COX     04-30 1631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORAH-PURCHASE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web auction brings sacred Torah to Texas congregation
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One hundred twelve years ago, a Jewish
congregation danced through the streets of Yemen's capital,
carrying their new Torah to the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   They had waited years for the Jewish scribe painstakingly to pen
the Old Testament on narrow panels of heavy goatskin parchment sewn
together with catgut. As the synagogue doors parted in Sanaa, the
jubilant crowd paraded in to honor their sacred text _ a Torah that
one day would enter cyberspace, destined for Austin.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, Lynda Baker passed out glasses of kosher
champagne as a small group crammed into the North Austin office of
her husband, Rabbi Kerry Baker, to toast the new Torah of
Congregation Kol Halev.
</P>
<P>
   The guest of honor was dressed in cardboard, a 25-by-24-inch box
stamped with scores of postal cancellation marks and a big red
sticker: Fragile Handle With Care. Cost of shipping: $21.30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a congregation I know buying their Torah over
the Internet,'' Rabbi Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting that the 2-year-old congregation, which has
borrowed Torahs from Congregation Agudas Achim and Congregation
Beth Israel, should find the historic scroll on an Internet
auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our congregation has gone to great lengths to be as electronic
as we can because it goes to inclusivity,'' said Dennis Passovoy,
the congregation's president. ``I think, out of our 124 families,
all but a small handful are on e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 15, the Torah is to be used for the first time as part of
a weekend celebration when Baker is officially installed as Kol
Halev's first and founding rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   A prize on eBay
</P>
<P>
   It was a new congregation member, Samantha ``Sam'' Gerow, who
spotted the Torah on March 11 on eBay, an Internet auction house,
and sent an e-mail to Baker. Early the next morning, a Friday,
Baker forwarded it to congregants Dee Seligman and Errol Stone,
members of the Torah search committee.
</P>
<P>
   Stone e-mailed the dealer who had placed the Torah on eBay. The
next afternoon, Stone sent the dealer's information to Passovoy,
Seligman, Baker and Lisa McCready, the synagogue's administrator.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Seligman went to the symphony wondering how the
congregation could find the money to bid on the Torah. Her answer
came during intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Another couple from the synagogue talked with Seligman during
the break and offered to lend the congregation up to $10,000 to bid
on the Torah. After the concert, Seligman went home and e-mailed
everybody. The last day to bid on the Torah would be Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation knew little about the Torah other than it was
Sephardic, which is associated with Jews whose heritage is Spanish
or Portuguese, and it was in St. Petersburg, Fla. Questions swirled
in their heads: Was the deal legitimate? Was the Torah kosher? Was
it readable?
</P>
<P>
   Baker turned to Rabbi Mark Sack of Tampa, the former rabbi of
Austin's Agudas Achim. Sack, who had a prior commitment, enlisted
the help of St. Petersburg Rabbi Stephen Moch. Moch looked at the
Torah on Monday, giving Congregation Kol Halev the green light.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing I knew on Monday, Dennis Passovoy called me and
said, we are going to bid on it tonight,'' Gerow recalled. Passovoy
asked Gerow to do the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I have this nice, placid little life, and then
Monday it was in a whirlwind,'' Gerow said. ``I've only been a
member of the congregation three months. ... I don't really know
that many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidding on history
</P>
<P>
   An anxious Gerow turned to her best friend and boss, Barbara
Carr, a Christian who had introduced her to eBay a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never bid anything higher than $30,'' Carr said of her eBay
experience.
</P>
<P>
   After the women finished work at the University of Texas
Humanities Research Center, they took off for Carr's home computer.
In fact, many of Kol Halev's members fired up their computers,
including one who was on vacation in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband was on one telephone line, and I was on another ...
two different telephone lines and two different computers watching
it,'' Seligman said.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding was scheduled to end at 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Carr submitted Kol Halev's first bid an hour earlier: $5,300,
just over the minimum bid allowed but well under the seller's
lowest acceptable sales price.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone watched. Would someone else submit a bid?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Carr upped the bid to $7,000. They waited again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very nervous,'' Gerow said. No one counterbid.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Carr's machine was disconnected from eBay. That
made Gerow very, very nervous, Carr said. Calm and relaxed, Carr
quickly reconnected. ``Nothing had changed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Carr entered $7,700 _ the minimum the seller would
take. Would someone, in the final seconds, add 50 cents to their
price, walking off with Kol Halev's Torah?
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept hitting the reload button to see the time expire,''
Carr said. ``It was almost like a New Year's countdown _ 30
seconds; OK, 15 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was zero, Kol Halev had its Torah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bargain,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Most used Torahs sell from $10,000 to $17,000; new ones can cost
from $20,000 up, Passovoy said.
</P>
<P>
   The news got better when the couple who offered the loan decided
to donate the money for the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   Small but precious
</P>
<P>
   Only 15 inches high, this Sephardic Torah is not much larger
than a book. ``In the universe of Torahs, this is a small one,''
Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   For Kol Halev, a congregation without a synagogue building, the
Torah offers the ease of portability.
</P>
<P>
   The most common Torahs in the United States are Ashkenazi,
meaning they come from Jews whose heritage is central eastern
Europe. The cultural difference between the Sephardic and Ashkenazi
is in how they are read.
</P>
<P>
   The Sephardic Torah is held in a hard case with the rabbi
reading from the scroll with his back to the congregation. It
allows the congregation to see the text as it is being read.
</P>
<P>
   The large, cloth-covered Ashkenazi scroll is spread out on an
inclined table as the rabbi _ facing the congregation _ reads from
it. After the reading, the rabbi holds the text up for the
congregation to view. When the rabbi reads from the Torah, the
congregation can follow along from the Old Testament books in the
pew.
</P>
<P>
   In the synagogue, both types of Torahs are stored in an ark, or
niche, that designates its place of honor. The early Christian
church replaced the ark with the crucifix.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, every Torah scroll _ which contains the first five
books of the Old Testament _ is penned by a specially trained
scribe, as it was in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
   Kol Halev's Torah was used in the Yemen synagogue until 1949,
when virtually all of the country's 45,000 Jews boarded planes in a
clandestine mission dubbed ``Operation Magic Carpet.'' They, like
many Jews in Arab countries who fled persecution, landed in the
year-old state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Congregation members at a synagogue in Rosh Ha Ayin, located
east of Tel Aviv, held a celebration to welcome the Torah to its
new home. Twenty years later, the Torah was put up for sale and
purchased by a Yemen family who had emigrated from Sanaa.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the family, which specializes in Torahs _ including
scribing new ones _ sent the Torah to a relative in St. Petersburg,
where it was to be purchased by a Jewish day school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day school was donated a Torah, so this one was
orphaned,'' said Bill Marger, the eBay dealer who specializes in
antique manuscripts and documents. ``The relative of the Israeli
owners ... contacted me to see if I could sell it through the
Internet on eBay.''
</P>
<P>
   The first viewing
</P>
<P>
   In Baker's office, Passovoy used his pocketknife to carefully
break the seal of the box. In an envelope was a note from Marger
asking Baker to use the four crisp $1 bills enclosed to return his
bar mitzvah prayer shawl, which was neatly wrapped around the
Torah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Torah is thought of as a living thing; it's God's living
word,'' Baker said. ``You treat it like a person _ you dress it and
undress it. It's the beautification of God's commandment.''
</P>
<P>
   When a Torah can no longer be used because of torn pages or
flaking text, it is buried in a funeral service.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation is still looking for a vestment, the case that
dresses the scroll. That's the only thing that could delay the
Torah's May 15 debut.
</P>
<P>
   As Baker and Passovoy gently scooped out the foam peanuts and
stripped away the bubble wrap, those in the room became cautiously
quiet. Everyone knew the true test would come when Baker examined
the scroll. Carefully, the prayer shawl was unfolded and the Torah
was exposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful,'' Gerow said, half her voice filled with
excitement and the other with relief.
</P>
<P>
   Baker bent over, parallel to the table, to squint at the small
Hebrew lettering. ``Kerry, you'd better get new glasses,'' Stone
said, breaking into a broad smile.
</P>
<P>
   Under his breath, Baker could be heard reading the Hebrew. The
Torah was opened to the laws of sacrifice in Leviticus.
</P>
<P>
   Lynda Baker used a tissue to wipe her husband's brow. ``This
opening of the Torah is breaking you out in a sweat, honey,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very exciting,'' the rabbi replied.
</P>
<P>
   The Torah was rolled on its two dowels as congregation members
took turns checking the quality of the ink lettering. ``I see no
reason to send it back,'' Baker said. ``It's in good condition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long way from Yemen,'' Lynda Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Passovoy went home to e-mail the good news to the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
