<HEADER>
A9951 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-MASSACRE-BOS &LR;      04-30 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-MASSACRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS TO RECREATE PRECEDENT-SETTING MASSACRE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Law student Anthony Dellorfano will don a black robe
and powdered wig Saturday afternoon, and thrust out his chest with
corpulent pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law will not bend to the uncertain wishes, imaginations,
and wanton tempers of men,'' he will declare, in a voice strong
enough to blow away the cobwebs of history.
</P>
<P>
   At Faneuil Hall, Dellorfano and about 60 other law students and
young lawyers plan to recreate John Adams's defense of the British
soldiers in the Boston Massacre _ one the greatest, but least
remembered, chapters in American legal history.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the growing fervor of Boston in 1770, with the colony
edging to the brink of revolution, Adams stood in the teeth of
local passions and forged legal principles for an emerging nation:
the virtue of reason over mob rule; the absolute right to a defense
attorney; the responsibility of a lawyer to defend even the most
unpopular clients; and the need to erase any reasonable doubts
before determining guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Over the succeeding years, however, the trial of the soldiers
became a footnote to the story of the massacre itself, which was
etched in the public mind through an inflamatory _ and historically
inaccurate _ engraving by Paul Revere. The trial of the soldiers
was chronicled by Superior Court Judge Hiller B. Zobel in his 1970
book, ``The Boston Massacre,'' but otherwise slumbered in the back
stacks of American history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Zobel, Suffolk Law Professor Joseph McEttrick, and the
Bostonian Society, assisted by scores of local luminaries, are
piecing it together again, from a transcript prepared at the time
by journalist John Hodgson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the upheaval, the soldiers got a fair trial in a
public courtroom in Boston,'' says McEttrick. ``That was a triumph
of the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Dellorfano, 32, who did some community-theater acting before
entering Suffolk's night law program, prevailed over 11 other
contenders for the role of Adams. Playing the pigeon-chested
patriot will be a daunting challenge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great combination of erudition and articulateness,
but he was an earthy guy _ stocky, down-to-earth,'' said
Dellorfano.
</P>
<P>
   But for him, the appeal was not the chance to act, but to learn
about the trial itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person studying the law, and an aspiring lawyer, it's not
hard to get up there, even in a silly costume, at a time of such
cynicism about the law, and speak these powerful lines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Adams's summation is replete with famous lines,
including ``Facts are stubborn things,'' but his legal artistry is
even more apparent in the context of the turbulent political
atmosphere in which the trial was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre was the culmination of months of protests by
colonists, chafing under the British military occupation of Boston.
However, as Zobel points out, the troops were oppressors only in
the eyes of certain politically charged colonists; they functioned
as policemen to protect British customs officials, and rarely used
force.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sons of Liberty, led by Samuel Adams, were in the
midst of a campaign to discredit British rule, largely over the
taxes and duties sent back across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The power of Sam Adams's rhetoric unleashed forces he couldn't
control. Mobs of colonists repeatedly taunted and fought with
British loyalists. Just weeks before the massacre, a British
customs official had been chased back to his home. The mob circled
his house, pelting it with enough rocks and debris to knock out all
the windows. Even when he and another man waved shotguns in the
windows, the mob persisted. Finally, he shot back _ and the spray
of pellets struck and killed an 11-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before the massacre, the British official was
convicted of murder and sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   On March 5, King Street _ as State Street was then known _
shimmered in the moonlight under a glaze of ice. A lone sentry
stood outside the Custom House, located near the present-day Court
Street. Inside, a squadron of officers led by Captain Thomas
Preston, 40, were on duty.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the evening, the sentry had scuffled with a group of
young apprentices, leaving an apprentice injured and the sentry
ruffled and angry. As the night wore on, various men and youths
gathered, taunting him. Later, as taverns emptied, the mob grew
louder and more threatening. Soon, the guard was surrounded, unable
even to return to the Custom House.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Preston decided to march his group of seven additional
soldiers out to protect his man. Within minutes, the mob enveloped
the soldiers, threatening their lives and daring them to shoot.
They did. Five colonists died in the volley, and word of their
martyrdom spread throughout Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Most colonists demanded death for the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Blood requires blood,' is the way they referred to it,''
says Zobel.
</P>
<P>
   By one account, Preston appealed directly to Adams, already, at
35, one of the colony's most respected lawyers. Adams, believing
that everyone deserves the best possible defense, agreed to
represent him and all his men.
</P>
<P>
   But Zobel offers another scenario. He found evidence that Sam
Adams, John Adams's cousin but otherwise not particularly close to
him, appealed directly to John Adams's co-counsel, Josiah Quincy,
to take the case. Zobel suggests that Sam Adams was worried that
less prominent defenders would turn the trial into a circus,
putting the victims on trial in a way that would spark such anger
that even he, Sam Adams, would lose control.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sam Adams clearly expected the soldiers to be found
guilty. He even appeared daily at the trial, shoving his way to the
front of the courtroom to offer advice to the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   John Adams, meanwhile, straddled a thin line, suggesting that
the soldiers were reasonably in fear of their lives, but avoiding
pinning blame for the clash on the colonists; in one apparent nod
to prejudices of the time, he steered responsibility away from
Boston, noting that one victim was from Ireland and another was a
``molatto'' from Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Adams's soaring rhetoric framed the issues in a
way that all but compelled the judges to side with the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Preston, who was tried separately, was acquitted of all charges;
six of the soldiers were also acquitted. Two soldiers were found
guilty of the lesser offense of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the trial of the soldiers, Rex v. Wemms, was a
lively affair, featuring many of the most prominent Bostonians of
the day: the Adamses, Josiah Quincy, prosecutor Robert Treat Paine,
and even the future Revolutionary War General Henry Knox, then a
bookseller who happened to witness the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   At the reenactment, three of the judges will be played by
present-day Massachusetts judges: Peter W. Agnes Jr., Robert Rufo
and Paul K. Leary. Zobel will narrate and Congressman Joseph J.
Moakley will introduce the play.
</P>
<P>
   It will be repeated Sept. 8, when Suffolk opens its new campus
on Tremont Street. Directly across from the new building, the five
victims of the massacre lie in the Granary Burial Ground.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for Dellorfano and many other students involved in the
reenactment, it will be Adams's genius that they remember most.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, the law is inexorable to the cries and
lamentations of the prisoners,'' Adams said, in a speech that could
be culled from a present-day trial. ``On the other, the law is deaf
as an adder to the clamors of the populace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
