<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-BIAS01-COX     04-30 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BIAS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke plaintiffs seek halt to e-mail
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ E-mail messages from Coca-Cola Chairman M. Douglas
Ivester to salaried black employees about a discrimination lawsuit
against the company violate a federal rule and should be stopped by
court order, plaintiffs' attorneys said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys, who represent one former and four current
African-American employees, filed a motion in federal court in
Atlanta seeking to bar Ivester and any other company official from
discussing the substance of the suit with any potential plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed last week, seeks class-action status in hopes of
adding 1,500 other salaried African-American employees in the
United States. It alleges Coca-Cola has a ``companywide pattern and
practice'' of discriminating against black employees in pay,
promotions, performance evaluations and terminations.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester has defended the company against these allegations in
two e-mails sent to all 10,000 of the company's U.S. employees,
including potential members of the class-action suit. He has said
the allegations of systematic discrimination are untrue and that
the suit contains ``significant errors of fact.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the plaintiffs' attorneys allege, Ivester has violated a
federal rule for the Northern District of Georgia that prohibits
such communication with potential members of a class-action suit
without prior court approval. As a result, they seek an emergency
hearing and court order banning any future communication about the
lawsuit from the company to potential plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   In his April 28 e-mail, Ivester said he ``plans to continue to
update all associates as information warrants in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' attorneys also allege Ivester violated the
federal rule by meeting with senior African-Amercian employees to
discuss the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Ivester's actions suggest that Coca-Cola believes the
court's rules do not apply to the company,'' the motion said.
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola defends its right to communicate with employees on
this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a legal maneuver by plaintiffs' attorneys typical in
this sort of litigation,'' said Coca-Cola spokesman Robert Baskin.
``There is no validity to the claims in this filing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the plaintiffs' attorneys said they have been
``severely handicapped'' by following the federal rule and not
communicating with nearly 100 potential class-action members who
have contacted them over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys want a court order saying they can now communicate
with these people, even though they want Coca-Cola's communications
with them stopped.
</P>
<P>
   That is because ``interviews with prospective class members are
a critical means for plaintiffs to gather evidence to the existence
of classwide racial discrimination at Coca-Cola,'' the motion said.
</P>
<P>
   It argued that case law supports the right of plaintiffs'
attorneys to talk to potential members of the class they may
eventually represent, even when restrictions are placed on the
defendant's rights to do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' lawyers argue they already have the beginnings
of an attorney-client relationship with potential class members
that the company should not be able to interfere with.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate motion Friday, the lead attorney in the case,
Cyrus Mehri of Washington, told the court he was adding a
prestigious Atlanta law firm to his team. The firm of Bondurant,
Mixson &AMP; Elmore represented many Coca-Cola bottlers in a
decade-long contractual dispute against Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
