<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT SHOWED COURAGE IN DECISION   TO STAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When they had talked it out for four hours,
Connecticut Governor John Rowland looked at Bob Kraft and wanted to
make sure the message he was getting was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me get this straight,'' said Rowland. ``Those politicians
up there (in Massachusetts) dumped on you for years, and gave you a
lousy deal. We've put a billion dollars on the table down here. You
and your kids will never have to worry again about a stadium.
Everything would be in place for another 30 years. And you're
worried about delaying this thing for just one more year? I don't
understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Who could blame Rowland? How many people can walk away from the
richest deal offered by a state to an owner in the history of
sports?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Bob Kraft did Friday, and he deserves all of the
credit in the world for doing it.
</P>
<P>
   No deal anywhere, in any sport, was more lucrative than the one
Rowland put on the line.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of the day, Kraft stayed here for short money.
The Massachusetts deal is just about the worst any owner has had to
accept to stay put in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's hope that everyone involved on this end lives up to
their word. The NFL. The state. The local business community. Gov.
Cellucci, Tom Birmingham, and Tom Finneran all deserve credit for
opening the door for Kraft to come back and keep the franchise
where it has been for the past 40 years, and where it should be for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Kraft has proven for the second time that it is not
about the money, it is time for the state to act as expeditiously
as possible to move this project forward. Time is money in the
construction industry, and the sooner a project starts, the less it
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, when he purchased the team from James B. Orthwein
(who wanted to move it to St. Louis), Kraft turned down millions to
let the Patriots get out of their lease in Foxoboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you like him personally, or whether you like the way he
has run his football team, it shouldn't make any difference. He
deserves all the credit he can get for passing on the money, and
for he way he did it. Kraft could have carried it out, gone to the
league meeting, and made the NFL owners vote him down, which would
have taken some of the heat off him. But he didn't. He took
whatever is coming from Connecticut on himself, even though it was
personally distasteful to turn down Rowland, who had treated him so
well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hidden hero in the Foxboro Stadium play is Dan Rooney, owner
of the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney orchestrated the entire move to get the Boston business
community to work with the NFL to get the state leaders to approve
the plan. Why Rooney? Although he is a Pittsburgh native, he loves
Boston. As president of the Ireland Fund across America, Rooney has
become very good friends with most of the top business leaders in
the city. Boston raises more money each year than any other city in
America for the Ireland Fund, which distributes it to need
organizations all across Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kirk was brought in by commissioner Paul Tagliabue to head
the Boston business push. Kirk and Tagliabue became friends years
ago when Kirk was heading up the Democratic National Committee in
Washington and Tagliabue was working for a top law firm there at
the time. However, it was Rooney who was quarterbacking the deal
from long distance to keep the team in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From one well-traveled NFL owner this week: ``If Connecticut
keeps the deal alive, some other team will move there. I don't know
what team, but with all of that money on the table, someone not in
good financial shape will go after it. With the way this league is
giving out bonuses now, you need to have a ready supply of cash to
compete, and that's what this Hartford deal would do for any
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
