<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do They Have An Annuity for You &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The variable-annuity business may never be the same. TIAA-CREF,
the $255 billion pension plan, has begun offering the public a
no-load, extremely low-cost variable annuity, Personal Annuity
Select, in seven states and is planning to roll it out nationwide.
The fund previously offered variable annuities only to employees of
educational and research institutions as part of their retirement
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The annuity charges a total of just 0.37 percent in expenses,
lower than any other annuity available to the public, according to
Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher. By contrast, the
average total expense for variable annuities is 2.10 percent,
Morningstar said. And there are no surrender charges for investors
who withdraw their money. The fund's plans were reported in Fund
Action, a newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will have a choice of a fixed annuity that currently
pays 5.75 percent, net of expenses, or a portfolio indexed to the
Russell 3000 Index. Tom Pinto, director of media relations for
TIAA-CREF, said the fund would consider offering other options.
</P>
<P>
   The expense ratio includes a so-called mortality and expense
charge of 0.1 percent that insures that heirs at least receive the
value of the amount invested, regardless of the direction of the
market, after the investor's death.
</P>
<P>
   As of early April, the annuity _ which needs states' approval _
was available in New York, Iowa, South Dakota, Arkansas, Ohio,
Indiana, Alabama and the District of Columbia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TEITELBAUM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH
</P>
<P>
   A White-Hot Growth Fund &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Janus 20 fund has closed to new investors, a
less-known fund seems poised to replace it as the most popular
actively managed fund for new money: Alliance Premier Growth.
</P>
<P>
   The fund had the third-highest net inflows of all funds in the
first quarter of 1999, drawing $2.9 billion _ pushing assets over
$10 billion, four times what they were a year ago _ according to
the Financial Research Corp. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with first-quarter net inflows of $4.7 billion and
$4.5 billion, respectively, for the two leaders _ Janus 20, which
stopped taking new money in April, and the Vanguard 500 Index fund.
</P>
<P>
   While having a lower profile than the Janus or Vanguard funds, a
function of the fact that it is mostly sold with a sales charge
through brokers, the Alliance fund posted an impressive 35.5
percent annual return for the three years ending March 31, placing
it in the top 1 percent of its category, according to Morningstar
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   As the flagship offering of Alliance Capital, a growth-oriented
fund company, Premier Growth has no big surprises in its portfolio.
Its top holdings as of March 31, included Nokia, Airtouch
Communications, Dell Computer, EMC and McKesson. (McKesson
contributed to the fund's 4 percent drop last Wednesday, when the
drug wholesaler fell by almost half due to accounting problems).
</P>
<P>
   The fund's success helped propel the Alliance fund family to a
43.4 percent gain in assets in the year ended March 31, to $39.2
billion, the second-best performance of fund families with at least
$20 billion. Only Janus, with a 69.7 percent gain, to $96.1
billion, fared better.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the stock of Janus' parent, Kansas City Southern
Industries, which returned 32.3 percent over the last 12 months,
Alliance Capital Management partnership units have been pretty
sedate, returning 11.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Majority owned by the Equitable Companies, the partnership,
which oversees $301.4 billion in assets and pays out most of its
earnings through dividends, trades for about 15 times earnings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
