s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-AR     04-30 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T'S BIG CHANCE TO OPEN THE DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people call it communicopia. Others call it convergence.
But as AT&AMP;T's $58 billion cash and stock offer for Mediaone Group
amply illustrates, the move toward an intertwined landscape of data
and voice communications, entertainment programming and electronic
commerce also deserves to be called expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T offer, which outstripped the $53 billion stock deal
that Mediaone struck in March with the Comcast Corp., seems to
validate the argument that cable, not the telephone, is the
preferred technology to deliver information, because of its
broad-band capability.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe AT&AMP;T won't win. Salvatore Muoio, a media and
communications analyst who runs SM Investors LP, took some time
last week to discuss developments in the industry, as well as why
AT&AMP;T can't afford to lose. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Did AT&AMP;T's bid for Mediaone surprise you? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I was a little surprised, but I shouldn't have been. Buying
Mediaone is strategically very important for Comcast, but to AT&AMP;T
it is survival.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance telephone service will be open to competition this
year, and at least one company, probably Bell Atlantic, is going to
start offering it. Once that door gets open, AT&AMP;T is going to lose
market share, and they need to reach out and offer local service.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they can't do that without a wire, either a local phone
company or cable. And there is no way regulators will let them buy
a local telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   After they bought TCI they would have liked to have negotiated
agreements with other cable operators, but they were having trouble
doing that. The Comcast/Mediaone deal threatened their national
strategy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. There have been news reports that Comcast has been talking
with Microsoft and America Online about joining it in making a new,
higher bid for Mediaone. Do you think that's possible? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think Microsoft wants to invest that much money in
cable. And I don't think America Online wants to go there, if only
because the chances seem slim they could make a bid that tops
AT&AMP;T's.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a Mediaone shareholder, you want AT&AMP;T, which is a
cheap stock. America Online's stock is not cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Comcast comes back, I think AT&AMP;T would counter by
raising their own bid somewhat. They cannot let someone else own
Mediaone, which is the last of the Mohicans. All of the other big
cable companies, Adelphia, Cox, Comcast and Cablevision, are
family-controlled companies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So competitors, in your view, can't keep AT&AMP;T from completing
this deal. What about the regulators? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Regulatory concerns are the only area where they may run into
some problems, whether it means unwinding some ventures they are in
or putting properties in escrow pending sale. But I think the
regulators understand AT&AMP;T's need to buy local telephone
operations. The regional Bells will be in long distance. So where
is the competition in the local market going to come from? AT&AMP;T is
the only company that could do that on a big scale. So, I am not
sure this will be an issue they can't surmount. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you agree with those who think cable, not the telephone
wire, is the technology of choice for the communications business,
because it is easier and faster to use? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the fight for the broad-band customer has just begun.
Digital subscriber line is the equal of cable modems, and Bell
Atlantic says they will start rolling it out later this year.
</P>
<P>
   People love their local telephone companies. Generally, they get
better service from them than the cable companies. But at the
moment, investors are completely overlooking local telephone
franchises. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Which local phone franchises do you like? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I like to focus on some of the smaller rural telephone
companies. In rural America, they don't have any competition.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone and Data Systems, Cincinnati Bell, Century Telephone
and the AllTell Corp. are great franchises selling at very low
price-earnings multiples.
</P>
<P>
   But my favorite stock is Citizens Utilities, a big local utility
company that in June will be split in two. One company will own
communications, and the other part, which will retain the company's
name, will own gas, electric, water and sewer utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Tow, a cable guy and one of the real entrepreneurs in
the business, runs this company, and it has a lot of great assets.
It is a terrifically underpriced stock with great potential. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about the cable companies? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. As we see with this fight for Mediaone, cable companies are
fabulous franchises. But the stocks have priced in a lot of their
future growth opportunities. Once this consolidation wave ends, we
think that going forward the stocks will be faced with something of
a head wind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
