<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9970 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-KRAFT-BOS &LR;      04-30 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-KRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISION MAKES BUSINESSMAN KRAFT MR. NICE GUY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Almost since he bought the New England Patriots in
1994, Robert Kraft has been engaged in a tug of war over his image.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's decision to choose Massachusetts over Connecticut,
Kraft did more than simply select a home for the team. He also took
a giant step in defining his public image, emphasizing the
soft-hearted public citizen over the hard-nosed businessman.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kraft insisted he was from the start.
</P>
<P>
   When he purchased the team, the Brookline native said he had
done it in no small part because he wanted to keep the franchise in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his boyhood disappointment when the Boston Braves left
town in 1953, Kraft said: ``It really impacts the psychology and
the fabric of the community, and this is my hometown and I just
believe this hometown wouldn't have been the same if this team had
left here.''
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't been the way critics have portrayed the
57-year-old businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Most pointed among them has been House Speaker Thomas M.
Finneran, who variously denounced Kraft as ``a whining
multimillionaire'' and ``a fat-assed millionaire,'' a comment
Finneran later claimed was meant to apply to Baltimore Ravens owner
Art Modell.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, after a long, frustrating search for a new
Masschusetts home, Kraft announced he would take his team to
Connecticut, where the political establishment greeted him with
open arms, Finneran was scathing.
</P>
<P>
   `It is about nothing but money,'' the speaker charged.
``Expressions of loyalty to Massachusetts, affection for the fans .
. . is propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, in word and deed, Bob Kraft demonstrated that that
accusation wasn't true. In doing so, he turned his back on what is,
by all measures, the most lucrative stadium deal in history of
professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut offer would have paid off in ways Kraft could
have scarcely imagined before he opened negotiations with the
Nutmeg State. The state would have spent $374 million in public
money to build the stadium. When various revenue guarantees and
other perks were added in, the package would have been worth more
than $1 billion over 30 years, according to some estimates.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the Massachusetts proposal, on which Kraft has
yet to comment, would require him to spend $250 million or so to
build the stadium _ though a recently approved funding mechanism
from the National Football League could dramatically reduce the
out-of-pocket hit. The Bay State would chip in $70 million for
public infrastructure improvements like roads, sewers, and
pedestrian ways.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some skeptics will say Kraft never intended to go,
that used Connecticut to get Massachusetts to make him an offer.
But others insist the Connecticut deal wasn't so much a matter of
``if'' as it was ``when.'' Even though the new Hartford stadium
would likely have not been ready until 2003, two years later than
originally planned, it will be a rush to get a new facility built
before then in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   By deciding to eschew Connecticut's offer, Kraft has made a
large statement about himself and his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``By taking less money to keep the team here, he is making a
contribution to the community unlike any we have seen in a long
time,'' said Republican political consultant Charles Manning. ``I
think he will be seen as a public hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: status of that sort is important to the Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   A shrewd, tough, and sometimes impolitic businessman he may be
in some endeavors, but as a football franchise owner, the man who
toured the field after victories in a golf cart and who gloried in
exchanging high-fives with Patriots fans, likes to be seen as a
good guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a gregarious guy who likes to be liked, and I think to
be liked in your own hometown is the most important thing,'' said
US Representative Joseph Moakley, who has known Kraft since his
days working in the office of then Senate President Maurice Donahue
in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham, who last year negotiated
an agreement with Kraft much like the deal Beacon Hill leaders
okayed this week, also felt all along that Kraft's was motivated by
much more than money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember an easier negotiation than the one I had with
Bob Kraft,'' Birmingham said of their 1998 talks. ``He clearly
wanted to get to `yes,' and he clearly was willing to sacrifice
more advantageous terms in other jurisdictions because he wanted to
keep the team in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham called Kraft's decision ``a credit to him,'' but
joked his family might not think so. ``I don't know what his heirs
will say about him taking the exit door,'' the Senate president
said. ``They are a family of substantial means right now, but they
would have been enriched greatly had the Hartford agreement come to
fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a conciliatory Finneran offered some praise. ``I think Mr.
Kraft deserves an awful lot of credit for making the decision that
he made,'' said the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Words of that sort will no doubt sound sweet to Kraft. In the
last several years, the Krafts, while readily pleading guilty to
accusations of political incompetence, have chafed under
accusations that they only care about the bottom line. For a family
that gives generously to charity, the mockery as money-grubbers,
like that which Finneran leveled at Kraft at this year's St.
Patrick's Day breakfast, has clearly stung.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, after Robert Kraft signed the deal to take the team
to Connecticut, his son Jonathan took two Globe reporters on a tour
of an elaborate mockup of the club seats and amenities the
organization had built in the basement of BankBoston to pitch their
aborted South Boston stadium plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our vision,'' Jonathan Kraft said wistfully. ``I just
hope it comes across how much effort we put in. It wasn't a fool's
errand. We wanted to spend our own money and keep the team here.''
</P>
<P>
   With his decision not to head to Hartford, Kraft showed that he
was sincere all along. In the end, he decided he'd rather earn
accolades from his home state than millions more from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   And in the debate over whether Kraft is just another bottom-line
businessman or a public citizen truly concerned about his
community, Friday's decision to remain in Massachusetts has to be
considered Exhibit A in support of Kraft as public citizen _ just
what he has said all along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
