<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9974 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0501-C     04-30 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0501-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO LAUNCHES HEAVIEST BOMBING YET, MILOSEVIC USES DIPLOMATIC
CHARM
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0501.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defiant in the face of the most withering NATO
attacks yet, Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic vowed Friday that
he would ``never surrender'' to U.S. and allied demands for placing
a NATO-led peacekeeping force in the embattled province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Milosevic laid out his own terms for ending the
conflict -- a proposal immediately rejected by the United States --
and retaliated with a charm offensive, allowing the Rev. Jesse
Jackson to visit with three American soldiers held captive by
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling pretty healthy, a little mentally drained,'' one
prisoner, Army Spc. Steven Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, told
Jackson during a session broadcast by the Cable News Network (CNN).
``Really miss home and hope to be back soon.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN aired some 20 minutes of Yugoslav-censored footage showing
the soldiers -- clean-shaven, in fair spirits and, by all
indications, relatively good health -- meeting and chatting with
Jackson, who brought them each a bible and words of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was scheduled to meet Saturday with Milosevic, but the
White House has insisted, publicly at least, that Jackson bears no
message from President Clinton and is on a strictly personal
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's visit is being conducted against the backdrop of the
most intensive air strikes since NATO launched its campaign on
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   After flying more than 600 sorties and dropping an estimated 300
bombs Thursday night and early Friday, the alliance was taking
advantage of clear skies to plan at least as many missions
overnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Adding mightily to NATO's firepower, 10 B-52 Stratofortress
heavy bombers were scheduled to fly from U.S. air bases Friday
night, to join the NATO armada with a scheduled arrival at a
British air field on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Air raid sirens sounded Friday evening in Belgrade, cutting
short Jackson's visit with the captives, as NATO bombs struck again
at military targets across Yugoslavia and fielded forces inside
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attacks on fielded forces have intensified,'' said NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea, describing furious allied strikes early
Friday on command posts, tanks, heavy artillery, anti-aircraft
weapons and even individual tanker cars, two of which were
destroyed Thursday night as they sat stranded on railroad tracks
inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With a month of heavy cloud cover lifting, Shea said, Serb
forces in Kosovo would find it difficult to hide from the aerial
onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   ``As spring gives way to summer and despite the excellent use of
camouflage and deception techniques,'' Shea told reporters at NATO
headquarters in Brussels, ``their destruction becomes
inescapable.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO tightened its noose, Milosevic offered to reduce his
forces inside Kosovo to some 12,000 troops, if NATO would withdraw
its forces from the bordering nations of Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do it in one week,'' Milosevic said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic rejected a key element of NATO's terms, however,
saying he would accept lightly-armed United Nations monitors but
not a military peacekeeping force made up by his country's
attackers, even if holding out means accepting prolonged and
escalating air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more day (of bombing) is too much,'' Milosevic said in an
interview with the United Press International news agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what choice do we have if NATO insists on occupying
Yugoslavia? To that we will never surrender,'' Milosevic said. ``We
Serbs are as one on this life and death issue of national honor and
sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia, said his country stood no
chance of prevailing militarily against NATO, but he said he was
heartened by the U.S. aversion to American casualties and the
emerging resistance in Congress to support the ongoing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He portrayed his country as a victim of NATO aggression,
insisted that Serb army troops had not committed widespread
atrocities in Kosovo but conceded that heavy handed methods had
been employed by paramilitary forces.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials blame Milosevic for overseeing a
campaign that has resulted in the execution of at least 4,000
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and has left another 1.5 million
homeless over the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not angels,'' Milosevic said. ``Nor are we the devils
you have made us out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said he would admit lightly-armed United Nations
monitors into Kosovo, but not a military force made up of his
attackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are willing to accept a U.N. presence and are ready to
negotiate its composition,'' Milosevic said in the UPI interview.
``But please understand that after all those crimes
</P>
<P>
   against our nation and its people, we cannot accept
representatives of the countries that committed aggression against
us. We would like to see representatives of neutral countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was immediately rejected by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately for the people of Serbia,'' said State
Department spokesman James Rubin, ``that plan was not serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its NATO allies have insisted on NATO-led
peacekeepers being allowed into Kosovo as a central demand to a
halt in the bombing. Milosevic's plan appeared to fall into the
category U.S. officials have consistently characterized as an
effort to try to split the NATO alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's televised visit marked the first time the American
soldiers have been shown on camera since state-run television in
Yugoslavia showed footage of them April 1, with bruised faces and
downcast eyes, the day after Serb forces captured them near
Kosovo's border with Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The men said they were fed three square meals a day, were housed
separately in small cells with a bed and table and were visited
regularly by Yugoslav officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's adequate,'' said Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of
Smiths Creek, Mich., who turned toward the camera at one point to
address his wife and four-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my wife Tricia and my son Ryan, 'I love you,''' Stone said,
welling up with tears before breaking out with a broad grin.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson told Gonzales, ``You are a hero. People know about you
all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning toward the camera, Gonzales delivered an impromptu
message to the public at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks everybody, for all your thoughts and all your
prayers,'' he said. ``They've been needed and they're a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson prepared to meet with the third captive, Staff Sgt.
Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles, air raid sirens sounded and
Jackson's Yugoslav hosts told him the exchange would have to be cut
short for safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, wearing a dark three-piece suit, white shirt and tie,
urged the men to consider how prison terms had strengthened the
will of the late civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., South
African apartheid foe Nelson Mandela and even the New Testament
Apostle Paul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of people around the world are praying for you and
they're praying for reconciliation so we can all live in peace
together,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can have the tailwind push them, but sometimes in life
there are headwinds and crosswinds and nobody can see the wind,''
said Jackson, admonishing the captives to ``turn pain into power
and use this time wisely . . . time to write, time to think and
time to pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who is scheduled to meet Saturday with Milosevic, told
reporters after the meeting with the American soldiers, ``Our
country should be proud of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
