<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK PRICES FALL AT END OF ROBUST MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Signs that a bustling economy might finally produce a
long-feared bout of inflation sent stock and bond prices tumbling
Friday. But the spring revival of cyclical stocks was still strong
enough to push the Dow Jones industrial average to a gain of 10.2
percent in April, the biggest monthly gain in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   For most of this year, traders have remained satisfied that the
economy, while strong, would continue its path of moderate,
noninflationary growth. But their hopes were fractured, if not
shattered, Friday morning when the Commerce Department reported
that a key inflation indicator rose sharply in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That led traders first to sell bonds, then stocks. The price of
the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 28/32, to 94 5/32. The
bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose Friday to
5.66 percent from 5.52 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Stock followed bonds lower, with the Dow Jones industrial
average falling 89.34 points, or eigth-tenths of 1 percent, to
10,789.04. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 7.65, or
six-tenths of 1 percent, to 1,335.18.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market had spent much of the morning shrugging off the
Commerce Department's report that the economy grew at an annual
rate of 4.5 percent in the first quarter, faster than the 3.4
percent rate that many economists expected. By noon the Dow
industrial average, which barely a month ago passed the 10,000
level, had gained 83 points and was only 40 points below the 11,000
mark.
</P>
<P>
   The worries of bond traders, however, carried the day. Bond
market participants said they were particularly unnerved by the
rise in an indicator known as the GDP price deflator, which
measures inflation across the economy. The deflator rose at a 1.4
annual rate in the first quarter, well above the 1 percent rate
that was expected and the fastest rise since 1997's second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bond markets were further weakened at about 12:30 p.m. by a
spate of heavy selling in the bond futures market. That decline, in
turn, finally convinced stock traders that there might be something
to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   By 3 p.m., the Dow industrials had fallen nearly 300 points from
their peak and were down 200 for the day. Cyclical stocks like
Alcoa succumbed to a quick round of profit taking. Despite
finishing the day down 2 7/16, at 62\, Alcoa gained 51 percent in
April, making it the month's biggest gainer in the Dow Jones
industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   A rebound in the last half hour of the session retraced some of
the losses in the Dow and the S&AMP;P 500. And with technology and
Internet stocks again leading the way, the Nasdaq composite index
moved back into the black, gaining 14.41, or six-tenths of 1
percent, to 2,542.85.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Friday's drop, the Dow had a remarkable month. Powered
by a surge in stocks of cyclical companies like Caterpillar, which
rose 40 percent in April, and International Paper, which gained 26
percent, the bellwether industrial average gained more than 10
percent, its best monthly showing since January 1987, when it rose
13.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the last three years, cyclical stocks have lagged
behind the more popular technology and consumer-product shares that
have been favorites of mutual fund managers and individual
investors. But the cyclical stocks perked up in the first quarter
as it became evident that last year's robust growth had in all
likelihood carried over into 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've definitely had a broadening of the market, with a lot
more stocks participating in the gains,'' said Laszlo Birinyi, of
Birinyi Associates, regarding the Dow's outstanding April
performance. ``While some cyclicals, like Georgia-Pacific and
United Technologies, have been doing OK, they've recently attracted
new buyers,'' whose additional interest has added to the gains.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Dow also benefited from a strong performance by its two
biggest technology components, IBM and Hewlett-Packard. On the
strength of better-than-expected first-quarter earnings, IBM gained
18 percent in April, Friday rising 4], to 209 3/16. Hewlett-Packard
gained 16 percent for the month, Friday rising {, to 78~.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, energy stocks, long in the doldrums, perked up as oil
prices rose and the approach of the summer driving season pushed up
gasoline prices. Exxon, for example, rose nearly 18 percent in
April, even after losing 1 7/16, to 83 1/16 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   YPF, the Argentine oil company which on Thursday received a
takeover offer from Repsol, Spain's largest oil producer, rose 7
15/16 Friday, to 43~. But most of the other big gainers on the last
day of the month were technology stocks. Cisco Systems jumped 4~,
to 114 1/16, and Apple Computer rose 3, to 46.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks, which two weeks ago underwent a sharp but brief
selloff, rallied again, with some hitting new highs. Infospace.com,
whose network of Web sites provide phone listings, maps, stock
quotes and other information, rose 24 11/16, to 143 5/16, after
reporting a smaller-than-expected loss for the first quarter. And
Priceline.com, which sells airline tickets over the Internet,
jumped 24 9/16, to 162].
</P>
</TEXT>
