<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0012 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHSMOG01-COX     04-30 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHSMOG01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South faces strict rules as smog there grows
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Sunday, May 2
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hazy days. Air thick enough to gag on.
</P>
<P>
   The grimy byproducts of mechanized America once hung primarily
over the industrial Northeast and sprawling Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Deep South, cities inundated by new residents,
factories, roads and cars also mark the start of smog season. From
Charlotte, N.C. to Birmingham, Ala., Atlanta to Augusta, the South
goes on alert for ground-level ozone _ the main ingredient in smog.
</P>
<P>
   Areas with too much ozone, which can cause breathing problems
and damage plants, receive the dreaded ``nonattainment'' stamp from
the federal Environmental Protection Agency. Nonattainment
potentially prohibits areas from spending federal money on road
projects until their air is cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   The South's poster child for bad air is Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But other cities, because of stricter federal guidelines this
year, may join Atlanta on the dirty air list.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're predicting large numbers of new nonattainment areas,''
said Linda Anderson-Carnahan, chief of the EPA's Air Planning
branch for eight Southern states. ``Rapid growth in the South is
really generating this. More people need more electricity. Making
electricity causes pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   And dirty air spreads beyond big cities.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee and North Carolina, the Great Smoky Mountains are
becoming the Great Smoggies. Last summer, the national park
recorded 43 days of unhealthy air. Atlanta last year exceeded the
federal ozone standard 22 times.
</P>
<P>
   An advocacy group for national parks lists the Smokies as one of
the 10 most endangered parks in the federal system. Pollutants from
power plants and factories in neighboring states blow through the
Smokies, said Don Barger, Southeast Regional Director for the
National Parks and Conservation Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to illustrate the most extreme threats,'' Barger
said, ``and the Great Smoky Mountains National Park is that in
relation to air pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, the view on a clear day from a park peak averaged
92 miles. Today, it is 22 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Ground-level ozone is a low-altitude version of its helpful,
high-atmosphere cousin. In the stratosphere, ozone screens out
harmful sunlight. Low-level haze emerges when small particles of
pollution and natural matter get baked by the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's new ozone rules allow lower amounts of ground-level
ozone, but measurements are taken for a longer period _ 8 hours now
compared to 1 hour last year.
</P>
<P>
   That puts even small cities on the bubble. In Georgia, Augusta,
Columbus and Macon may fall into nonattainment when the EPA issues
new designations in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Former ozone violators Memphis, Knoxville and Nashville in
Tennessee have cleaned their air within the last six years. So have
Charlotte, Greensboro and Raleigh-Durham in North Carolina. In
Florida, Jacksonville and Miami came clean in 1995 followed in 1996
by Tampa-St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   But ozone in those areas may climb over new limits this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham, a marginal nonattainment city, exceeded healthy
ozone limits just five times last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may change this year with the tighter, 8-hour
standards,'' said Sam Bell, who helps monitor the Ozone Action
Program in metro Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Around Baton Rouge, La., the area has violated ozone caps the
entire decade. Petrochemical plants and oil refineries along the
Mississippi River contribute to the air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry plays a large part,'' said Steve Murrell, an air
monitor for Louisiana's Department of Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   When ozone reaches unhealthy levels, environmental experts
suggest telecommuting, carpooling and postponing activities like
mowing lawns and pumping gas. Some communities, including metro
Atlanta, ban homeowners and developers from outdoor burning from
May 1 through Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce car emissions, gas stations in Atlanta and Birmingham
soon will dispense a low-sulfur fuel this season. The new gasoline
helps a vehicle's catalytic converter more efficiently remove
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA also mandated that 22 states _ including Alabama,
Georgia, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee and Kentucky _
reduce the amount of nitrogen oxides they emit. Alabama and the
Carolinas are suing the EPA over the mandate, disputing the
assertion they are causing pollution downwind.
</P>
<P>
   Factories and power plants with high smoke stacks release
so-called ``NOx'' gases, an ingredient in ground-level ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Gottschalk, an air quality manager for the Georgia
Environmental Protection Division, said power plants can use a
chemical process that ``destroys nitrogen oxides before they come
out of the stacks.''
</P>
<P>
   When the NOx elimination plan is fully implemented in 2003,
smaller cities may return to ozone compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the better steps in the right direction,'' said
the National Parks and Conservation Association's Barger. ``It will
have far-reaching effects.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
