<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPTURED-SOLDIERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON DENIED IN BID TO FREE THREE US SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They prayed for morning to come after their ``long,
dark night'' of captivity. They expressed love for their families.
And after 30 days of solitary confinement in a Yugoslav military
prison, one of the three US soldiers issued a touching apology to
his parents amid the horror of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry I put you through so much pain and agony,'' Army
Specialist Steven M. Gonzales said Friday as his Serb captors
permitted a poignant, videotaped visit by the Rev. Jesse Jackson
with the American prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, stymied in his attempt to free the captive soldiers,
instead brought them Bibles and messages of hope, as he huddled
briefly with the prisoners in a military courtroom in Belgrade
under the constant scrutiny of Serb authorities and a military
judge.
</P>
<P>
   In a rarity of military conflict made possible by modern
technology, videotaped images of the encounter were quickly beamed
around the world, as the soldiers presented themselves as ordinary
men trying to summon the strength to endure their grim ordeal. Serb
military officers cut short the visit when air-raid sirens began to
blare.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my wife Tricia and my son Ryan, I love you,'' said Staff
Sergeant Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., when
asked if he had a message for his family. Stone's face then grew
red and his eyes filled with tears, according to a pool report.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, appeared to have found
solace in Bible verses his parents had sent him through the
International Committee of the Red Cross. ``Thanks for those you
sent,'' he said. ``I know them by heart. I recite them every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his face remained bruised from injuries he suffered
during his capture a month ago, the third prisoner, Staff Sergeant
Andrew A. Ramirez, assured his family he was well. ``I feel pretty
good actually,'' said Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The servicemen told Jackson they have been segregated from each
other and confined to one-room cells since shortly after they were
captured during a routine patrol near Macedonia's border with
Yugoslavia on March 31. They are the only NATO troops to have been
captured since the airstrikes against Serb forces began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no contact,'' Stone said. But he said they have been
allowed to exercise regularly and eat adequately.
</P>
<P>
   All three soldiers, still clad in the camouflage fatigues they
were wearing when captured, said they were in good physical health
and hopeful for their freedom. They met individually with Jackson
and as a group. At one point, they all smiled at the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a great sense of honor for what they are doing for
the country,'' Jackson said told reporters after the visit. ``They
met us today with a great sense of dignity, and their youth
generation should be proud of them, and our country should be proud
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the White House had discouraged Jackson from
undertaking the mission, expressing concerns for his safety and the
prospect that his visit could be used for anti-American propaganda,
the Pentagon credited Jackson for visiting the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contact with the Rev. Jackson is helpful to the POWs, and
it's a good sign,'' spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said Friday. He
renewed the US demand that Yugoslavia release the servicemen on the
grounds that they were not involved in a hostile mission and were
abducted illegally.
</P>
<P>
   With their heads bowed and Jackson's arms around them, the
soldiers prayed with him during the visit. The tape, censored by
Serb authorities, showed Jackson telling the captive soldiers:
``Even though it's dark and stormy, if we hold onto our faith, the
storm will pass away and night will give to day.''
</P>
<P>
   He implored them ``use the time to reflect and think and pray
and be grateful.'' He prayed for their families ``to know that we
are alive and healthy and help is on the way, hope is in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said later that he urged the soldiers ``to hold onto
until the morning cometh because it has been for them a long, dark
night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taught in scripture,'' he explained, that ``weeping may
endureth for a night, but joy cometh in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   He said their ``spirits were lifted'' by the visit. ``They felt
quite good about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's mother, Vivian Ramirez, said she hoped Jackson's visit
will help bolster her son's resolve during the ordeal. In an
interview with CNN, she said she is certain her son ``will hang in
there now that he has gotten our letters and knows everybody in the
whole United States is behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeing him on television, Mrs. Ramirez said, ``He's
looking really good.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Democratic presidential candidate in 1984, Jackson traveled
to Syria and secured the release of Navy Lieutenant Robert O.
Goodman Jr., whose jet was shot down during a raid over Syrian
anti-aircraft positions in Lebanon. He also secured freedom for
prisoners in Iraq and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, he was accompanied to the prison by Representative Rod
R. Blagojevich, an Illinois Democrat who serves on the House
National Security Committee, and several journalists.
</P>
<P>
   To their dismay, members of a delegation of US religious leaders
were not allowed on the visit with the soldiers. The list of
delegates includes the Rev. Raymond G. Helmick of Boston College,
and Landrum R. Bolling, who is associated with the Conflict
Management Group and Mercy Corps International in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Before Jackson's visit, Yugoslavia's Assistant Foreign Minister
Nebojsa Vujovic met with the soldiers, then told reporters ``their
release is not on the agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the delegation will be able to see them and assure
themselves they are in good health,'' Vujovic said.
</P>
<P>
   In stronger terms, Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic insisted
Jackson had no chance of fulfilling his hope of securing the
servicemen's release. ``We outlasted Hitler's bombing,'' Jovanovic
said. ``We survived Soviet pressure ... and we are not going to
capitulate to NATO bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Before visiting the soldiers, Jackson, who hopes to meet
Saturday with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, toured the
scene of an errant NATO missile raid that struck a residential
neighborhood of Belgrade, reportedly killing three civilians and
injuring 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bombing cannot be a solution,'' said Jackson, who appeared
visibly upset by the destruction. ``But the same goes for the
forceful displacement of ethnic Albanians from their homes in
Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
