<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-FEAR01-COX     04-30 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-FEAR01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pranks, absenteeism mar school week in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A fearful week of pranks, high absenteeism and arrests
at Atlanta schools continued Friday with more commotion but no
serious incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Bomb scares prompted the evacuation Friday of Chattahoochee and
Milton high schools in north Fulton County, Forest Park High and
Babb Middle School in Forest Park, Shiloh High near Snellville and
North Cobb High. At each school but Shiloh, no device was found.
</P>
<P>
   At Shiloh, pipes and wires in a paper bag were found behind a
toilet in a boys' restroom, leading administrators to evacuate
students to the gym. The Gwinnett County bomb squad exploded the
item.
</P>
<P>
   In Douglas County, 28 students and one adult have been arrested
for making terroristic threats at schools since the April 20
Colorado massacre. The first student was arrested the day after the
killings when he arrived at Chestnut Log Middle School dressed in a
black trench coat, boasting of having a ``hit list'' of people he
planned to kill. As many as 15 students appeared in Douglas County
Juvenile Court on Friday to face the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these kids have really done damage to their academic
careers,'' said assistant superintendent Donald Remillard, noting
that the students could be expelled or forced to attend an
alternative school.
</P>
<P>
   At Chattahoochee High, the bomb squad was called when a student
heard a ticking sound in a locker. It turned out to be a
voice-activated tape recorder that had inadvertently turned on and
run out of tape.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, days of frightening rumors ended without incident at
Collins Hill High School in Suwanee, where word had spread that
another student ``hit list'' would be acted on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The recurring threats have fueled widespread alarm among
students and parents, many of whom already were on edge following
the slayings last week of 12 high school students and a teacher in
Littleton, Colo. The Atlanta incidents echo similar scares across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the anxiety, absenteeism at area schools was high
Friday, including 51 percent at Woodstock Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Police and school officials have been scrambling to chase down
the rumors and threats.
</P>
<P>
   Punishing the culprits is one way to slow the spate of
anti-social behavior, said John E. Williams, a social psychologist
at Georgia State University. That way students understand they they
cannot pull off these stunts with impunity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb County police arrested Eric Lee Williams after he was
accused of calling in a bomb threat that forced the evacuation of
Chapel Hill Middle School on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Police charged the 25-year-old Decatur man with making
terroristic threats and he was incarcerated at the county jail.
``He thought he was cute,'' said DeKalb school spokesman Spencer
Ragsdale, ``but now he's laughing through bars.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Michael Weiss, Bill Montgomery, Brad Schrade,
Scott Marshall, Will Anderson, Diane Stepp, Chris Reinolds and
Robin McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0032 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONDON-BOMB-ART-660(2     04-30 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-BOMB-ART-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB KILLS 2 IN CROWDED LONDON GAY BAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A nail-bomb ripped through a gay bar in London's Soho
district Friday night, killing at least two people and injuring 73
and leaving the city on edge after two other bomb attacks this
month in minority neighborhoods. The police said Friday that they
believed all three attacks were linked to extreme right-wing
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's fatalities were the first in the series of bombings
that started on April 17 in Brixton, a south London district with a
large Afro-Caribbean population, injuring 39, and moved last
Saturday to Brick Lane, in east London's Bangladeshi community,
wounding seven. Coupled with the still-unsolved murder this week of
a celebrity television presenter, Jill Dando, the attacks have
spread deep foreboding in this normally easy-going capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole community must feel threatened because it was clear
that if it was the black community first, it could be the Jewish
community next,'' said Angela Mason, spokeswoman for a gay and
lesbian rights group. ``Who knows where it's going to stop?''
</P>
<P>
   After extreme right-wing groups took responsibility for the
first two explosions, the police warned gay and lesbian groups that
they might also be targeted, according to Friday's edition of Pink
Paper, a gay newspaper. Paul Condon, head of London's Metropolitan
Police, told reporters Friday night that a London radio station had
received an anonymous telephone call from someone claiming the most
recent attack was carried out by the White Wolves, an offshoot of
the extreme right-wing Combat 18 that has issued threats against
black legislators. Both groups claimed responsibility for the
earlier bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they had no evidence to corroborate the claim of
the radio station. But Alan Fry, a senior anti-terrorist police
officer, said he was linking the three attacks. Like the earlier
two, he told reporters, Friday evening's blast had been caused by a
nail-bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb struck on a limpid spring evening with a breath of
summer in the air. The streets were thronged with thousands of
people anticipating a long, Bank holiday weekend in a district
known for its theaters, restaurants, clubs, sex-shops and bars.
</P>
<P>
   But the scene turned to carnage: 13 of the 73 injured were hurt
seriously and two of them had limbs torn away in the blast,
hospital officials said. ``This is a terrible outrage committed by
people who have no humanity whatever,'' said Jack Straw, Britain's
home secretary. ``We are dealing with people who have warped minds,
right-wing extremists who are obviously racist and homophobic. That
we know.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion went off at 6:37 p.m., the police said, at the
Admiral Duncan pub on the corner of Dean and Old Compton streets at
the start of a holiday weekend that, along with sudden, summer-like
weather, had drawn thousands of strollers, drinkers, foreign
tourists and theater-goers onto Soho's streets. The timing
coincided with what would normally be a relaxed, busy time with
thousands of Londoners stopping to socialize after work in advance
of the weekend. The owners of the Admiral Duncan _ Scottish and
Newscastle Breweries _ said there was no indication of a warning
before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the blast left the injured and dead flattened on
the sidewalk outside the pub. ``I thought they had been blown
apart,'' said James Fullum, an eyewitness.
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate aftermath, wounded with blood running from arms
and faces staggered out of the Admiral Duncan, described by gay
rights advocates as a well-known and almost exclusively gay
meeting-place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the whole front blown out and bodies lying around in the
street,'' said Sean Given, the manager of another bar in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness, Peter King, said, ``It reminded me of my
childhood during the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Londoners said the explosion revived memories of Irish
Republican Army bombings. ``Everyone is just very frightened about
what's going on,'' John Laycock, a restaurateur, told British
television.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Inside the pub, witnesses said people had been hurled to the
ground, their limbs askew. A hospital spokeswoman, Louise Boden,
told reporters most of the injured were young men suffering from
``burns, lacerations, the trauma of being thrown about. When a bomb
goes off, if it's near you, it shreds flesh. It's pretty horrible
really.''
</P>
<P>
   Condon, the London police chief, warned that no one should feel
immune from the bomb campaign. ``They might be targeting
minorities, but these are hate attacks on all of us. The impact of
these bombs will affect all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Condon made no specific reference to London's widely spread
Jewish population, but other police officers said Jewish groups had
been warned to be on their guard against the possibility of similar
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   For miles around, London's streets filled with the wailing of
sirens Friday night as officers in at least 30 ambulances, and many
police cars and fire engines, wove through densely packed Soho to
take away wounded, and seal off the area in case further bombs had
been planted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of glass everywhere, and a lot of confusion and
a lot of walking wounded,'' said Martin Ireland, another witness,
shortly after the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The blast came only hours after police announced they had
arrested a man suspected of responsibility for the Brixton bombing
following the release of photographs taken from closed circuit
television cameras that had overlooked the busy, Saturday afternoon
market. The man on the video images seemed to be in his late teens
or early 20s and wore a light-colored baseball cap. The police said
they believed he had been filmed while reconnoitering the area in
preparation for an attack.
</P>
<P>
   In both previous attacks, the bombs _ described by police as
crude, home-made devices combining explosives with scores of nails
_ were left in sports bags at crowded areas. The casualties last
weekend at Brick Lane, which has a large Asian population, were
lower because a man put the bag containing the bomb into the trunk
of his car to take it to safety at a police station. The targets of
the attack in racially mixed Brixton seemed to be black immigrants
from Britain's former colonies in Africa and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Some Londoners have speculated that the attacks may be connected
to Britain's participation in the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia. The
execution-style murder of Ms. Dando, the television celebrity _
shot in broad daylight by a single bullet to the head outside her
home after she had spoken on air of the plight of Kosovo Albanian
refugees _ fanned the speculation about reprisals by Serbs. But
Condon said investigators were making no such connection.
</P>
<P>
   The groups that have claimed responsibility for the last two
explosions are called Combat 18 _ an extremist, right-wing group
named for the position in the alphabet of Adolf Hitler's initials _
and a more radical breakaway group called the White Wolves. Police
anti-terrorist experts have said the groups may consist of no more
than a handful of extremists operating in small, clandestine cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very small, elite Nazi operation,'' said Gerry Gable
of Searchlight, a private group opposed to violent racist groups.
``They hate black people, they hate gay people and they hate Jews.
They want to spread terror.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
