<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-COPS01-COX     04-30 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-COPS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. governor wants more cops in state's schools
 &HT;    By Lyn Riddle
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Gov. Jim Hodges wants $14 million to hire a
police officer for every secondary school in South Carolina to
``ensure that the tragedy in Colorado'' isn't repeated in his
state.
</P>
<P>
   The money would add 350 officers to the 170 already employed in
schools. In all, 33 of South Carolina's 46 counties have officers
in some schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question on the lips of every South Carolina parent right
now is `What are you going to do to make schools safer?''' Hodges
said.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal was met with enthusiastic support from law
enforcement, including the public safety director and the head of
the State Law Enforcement Division. Richland County Sheriff Leon
Lott said the 23 officers in schools there make schools safer.
</P>
<P>
   But educators say putting police in schools does not guarantee
safe buildings. Two police officers were on duty at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., last week, when two teens killed 12
students and a teacher before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to shy away from making our schools look like prisons
or holding pens,'' said Lenor Hersey, deputy executive director of
the National Association of Secondary School Principals.
</P>
<P>
   Her group has taken no position on stationing law enforcement
officers in schools and she knows of no definitive research done on
its effectiveness. But she believes that hiring police officers is
not a cure-all if a school does not implement programs to deal with
problems that arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heavy duty surveillance equipment and strutting uniforms
around can actually make the situation worse,'' she said. ``There
is no guarantee if they have a whole army that these incidents
won't erupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Nina Brook, the governor's spokeswoman, said Hodges agrees a
total approach to school safety is needed. She pointed to Richland
County, where an officer is available to all schools, including
elementary schools, for assemblies, one-on-one meetings with
students and to help administrators identify troubled youngsters.
In addition, officers can get special training in dealing with
children from the South Carolina Criminal Justice Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``School safety is a total package between parents, teachers and
law enforcement,'' Brook said.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges made improving education his main campaign issue last
fall when he became the first Democratic governor in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Bob Peeler, a Republican, accused Hodges of
politicizing the issue. ``The fallen students in Colorado deserve
better than self-serving politicians scrambling to score political
points in the wake of the tragedy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brook said the governor was responding to concerns he heard
in meetings around the state in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   The governor believed he needed to act fast because the General
Assembly is working on the budget. Some legislators said the
request is too late to make it in this cycle, but Brook said the
governor believes otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total budget is $5 billion,'' she said. ``The General
Assembly surely can come up with $14 million if they want to make
South Carolina schools safe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
