<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH: STEVEN CHAMBERLAIN OF INVESCO EUROPEAN FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A longtime fan of Manchester United, the English soccer team,
Steven A. Chamberlain, manager of the Invesco European fund, can do
something that most other sports enthusiasts can't: control a chunk
of the sports franchise he follows so passionately.
</P>
<P>
   But Chamberlain's strong affection for ``Man United'' is not the
reason he invests in it, or in the two other soccer clubs in his
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   As an aggressive, growth-oriented manager, he is focused on the
fact that soccer is the most popular sport in Britain and across
Europe, and that major clubs are reaping increasing shares of
television advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, these companies are actually very good leisure
plays,'' he said by telephone from his London office.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer club shares account for just 1.75 percent of the fund's
portfolio, which contains 79 stocks. The fund, with $631 million in
assets, has returned 18.7 percent, annualized, for the three years
ended April 23, compared with 16.8 percent for the average European
stock fund, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been problems this year; the fund is down 7.2
percent, versus a decline of just 1.3 percent for the peer group.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain attributes the recent performance to the portfolio's
high-growth stocks, which carry big price-to-earnings multiples.
Manchester United, with a P/E of over 50, is down 12.3 percent this
year. ``These companies have come in for profit-taking as investors
shift to deeper cyclicals,'' he said, referring to oil, chemical,
and some mining and steel companies. Some investors are also
returning to Asian stocks, out of favor until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, 34, grew up near Sheffield in northern England _
not far from Manchester _ and has been with the Denver-based
Invesco Funds Group since 1987, working in a centuries-old complex
in the City of London. He became manager of the European fund in
1990, when he was just 25.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's assets are spread around Europe, mostly in
large-capitalization companies. ``What we really want to do is find
companies that are operating in business areas that are growing,
where they are well positioned to also be able to grow in that
market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To zero in on stocks, he analyzes industries, visits companies
and uses computer screening. He pays special attention to companies
that have shown above-average return on equity over the last six
years. ``If they have a proven record over that sort of time
period,'' he added, ``it usually shows that they're doing something
right.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fund, like others invested in Europe, has been hurt by
slower growth in economies, by the shaky start of the euro and by
negative market sentiment from the conflict in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   One top holding is Vodafone Group of Britain, the wireless
network provider. It took a big step into the American market in
January, announcing its plan to buy Airtouch Communications for
more than $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earnings growth has been strong, but earnings are still at a
low level, because the company is reinvesting lots of capital,''
Chamberlain said. ``This is what we like. We want companies that
are generating cash, hopefully sufficient amounts to be able to
expand their businesses, and they're hopefully operating in markets
where they have lots of room to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain said he first bought Vodafone stock in January 1997
at 2.54 pounds, it closed Friday at 11.45 pounds, and he has a
target of 15.40 pounds for 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller company, Tomra Systems of Norway, specializes in
so-called reverse vending machines. Customers return empty
recyclable bottles and cans to the machines and receive tickets
that can be redeemed at store checkouts. More than half of Tomra's
revenues come from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomra has more than 90 percent market share globally in those
machines,'' he said. ``We liked it because we thought that it had a
big target market in which to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   He bought Tomra stock in August 1995 at about 30 Norwegian
kroner. It now trades at 310 kroner, and his 12-month target price
is 430.
</P>
<P>
   Telepizza, the largest fast-food company in Spain, also has
outlets in Portugal and other European countries. Chamberlain said
Telepizza has a 60 percent share of the Spanish pizza market, ``and
it's a fast-growth market because fast food in Spain is
underdeveloped.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, he said, an average person spends $300 a
year on fast food. ``In Spain, it's about $15,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Telepizza delivers by moped. ``The pizzas themselves are pretty
good, but it's really the fact that they're very good at marketing
and they offer a very good service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He started buying the stock in February 1998 at the equivalent
of 4.95 euros. It now trades at 6 euros; his target is 9.18 by next
April.
</P>
</TEXT>
