<HEADLINE>
KRAFT WOULD BENEFIT FROM NFL FINANCING FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- If New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft accepts
Beacon Hill's new stadium offer, up to half his estimated $250
million construction costs would be offset by money from the
National Football League's ``G-3'' plan.
</P>
<P>
   The financing scheme, approved by NFL owners in February, was
designed to stop the exodus of big-city franchises lured to smaller
markets by sweet stadium deals. The Patriots, whose package with
Hartford was considered the most lucrative in the history of the
league, were candidate Number 1.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how G-3 works:
</P>
<P>
   Teams seeking money to finance stadium costs would give up their
share of revenue from luxury box and club seat sales on away games.
That annual flow of money would go instead to the NFL, to offset
the NFL's borrowing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Teams considered ``large market'' teams could apply to league
owners for up to half the cost of their stadiums (smaller market
cities would be able to apply for 34 percent of their stadium
building costs), and would receive it if three-quarters of the
owners approve it.
</P>
<P>
   This ``loan'' would cost the Patriots between $3.3 million to $5
million a year that they normally would have received in visiting
club seat and luxury box revenue. That figure would fluctuate based
on where the Patriots played on the road in a given year. The team
would still receive 34 percent of the general gate from road games,
but would forgo the more expensive club seating and luxury box
revenue they would normally be entitled to.
</P>
<P>
   The team would pay this for an unspecified amount of time, but
the NFL would, in individual cases, forgo the repayment of the
entire principal of the loan, provided Bob Kraft held on to the
team for at least 10 years after the loan was issued.
</P>
<P>
   While the loan sounds like a great deal, it's still money the
Patriots won't have to pay other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great system the owners came up with to help
one another come up with the money to build these stadiums,'' said
NFL spokesman Greg Aiello.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
