<HEADLINE>
REBUFFED BY GREECE, BOEING PINS F-15 HOPES ON ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Israel now appears to be the last best chance for the
Boeing Co. to keep alive its highly profitable F-15 fighter line in
St. Louis following Friday's announcement that Greece will buy
fighters from the French and Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Boeing executives had been courting the
Greek government to buy the F-15 Eagle, which would have extended
production for at least a year _ time for Boeing to possibly win
still more orders.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Boeing's best hope to keep the line from being shut down,
at least temporarily, is a pending fighter plane order by Israel,
which like Greece is also considering Lockheed Martin's popular
F-16.
</P>
<P>
   But even if F-15 production stops, industry analysts said it
would not have any significant long-term impact on Boeing. That's
because Boeing has the new F-18E/F Super Hornet that it is building
for the U.S. Navy. Production of that plane is just getting
started.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Hornet will more than make up for lost F-15 revenue,
but it will take time for the program to become as profitable as
the F-15, which has been in production since the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   About 5,000 workers in St. Louis build the F-15. The line has
been an important revenue stream for Boeing. The company has said
it would deliver 38 of the fighters this year. The F-15 sells for
about $60 million, so the 39 deliveries will make about $2.3
billion for Boeing in 1999. And that is nearly 20 percent of
Boeing's projected 1999 revenue of $12 billion for its entire
military aircraft and missiles unit headquartered in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing was clearly disappointed in losing the Greek order. The
Greek Air Force reportedly favored the Boeing plane to the end, but
the government decided on the F-16 because it is significantly
cheaper than the $60 million F-15. The Greek Air Force already flys
the F-16.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision by Greece makes the Israeli order that much more
important,'' said industry analyst Peter Jacobs of Seattle's Ragan
MacKenzie firm. ``The good news is that Israel is much more
inclined to buy the F-15 than was Greece.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Israel ordered 25 of the most advanced version of the
Boeing fighter, the F-15I. The last of those planes were delivered
just this week.
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Arens, Israel's defense minister, has been in the United
States since last Saturday, primarily to discuss the next fighter
jet deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our full focus now shifts toward winning the Israeli aircraft
competition and working on other near-term opportunities,'' Boeing
said in a statement. ``We currently have F-15 deliveries continuing
into the early part of next year. An Israeli buy could extend
deliveries through 2000. Additional near-term sales are needed to
ensure deliveries beyond that time frame.''
</P>
<P>
   One potential F-15 customer is Saudi Arabia, which previously
ordered 72 of the jets. The last of thsoe planes will be delivered
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had hoped Greece would buy upwards of 35 F-15s.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Greece announced that it would buy 50 Lockheed Martin
F-16s, as well as 15 Mirage 2000-5 fighters built by France's
Dassault.
</P>
<P>
   The $2 billion order is less than half the estimated $4.2
billion that Greece would have spent to buy Boeing's F-15. The F-15
has greater range and can carry a heavier payload of bombs than the
F-16. But it's about twice as expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Israel plans to spend an estimated $2.5 billion for either 30
F-15 or 60 F-16s.
</P>
<P>
   One issue that could effect the decision is the radar system
used on the F-16. Arens told reporters yesterday that Israel wanted
F-16D jets to be equipped with radars built by Israel's defense
ministry, which he said were superior to the Westinghouse-built
radars now on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   It is U.S. policy for the fighters to come equipped with the
Westinghouse radar.
</P>
<P>
   The F-15I uses a different radar system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
