<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-TOTAL-FUNDS-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FORMULA, YES. BUT IS IT IMPROVED? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot of diversification-minded investors are gravitating toward
a group of indexed stock mutual funds that may seem a far wiser
choice than the familiar version tied to the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   The funds, called total market funds, track several thousand
stocks to mimic the spectrum of American securities, not just a
chosen 500 of the biggest companies. Though the retail assets in
such funds are still relatively small, at $11.1 billion versus
$116.3 billion in S&AMP;P 500 index funds, they have grown more than
14-fold percent since 1994, when only the Vanguard Group had such
an offering.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts, in fact, see total market funds as a kind of
all-in-one solution for investors' stock fund needs, giving them
exposure to all kinds of equities _ large and small, value and
growth. And they have rock-bottom expenses, too. But this is where
investors can go wrong, because the easiest tack is not always the
best.
</P>
<P>
   Investors flocking to total market funds, which track the
Wilshire 5000 index, may not be aware of the funds' limitations.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying the growing popularity of total market
funds, helped by well-publicized endorsements of the Wilshire 5000
by the likes of John C. Bogle, senior chairman of Vanguard, and
Burton G. Malkiel, the Princeton economics professor and author of
``A Random Walk Down Wall Street'' (W.W. Norton).
</P>
<P>
   ``I now believe the best general United States index to emulate
is the broader Wilshire 5000-stock index _ not the S&AMP;P 500,''
Malkiel said in the book.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest and longest-established of this handful of funds is
the Vanguard Total Stock Market Index fund, which began in 1992 and
now has more than $10 billion in assets. Newer entries are Fidelity
Spartan Total Market Index, the T. Rowe Price Total Equity Market
Index and, since Feb. 1, Wilshire Associates' own version, the
Wilshire 5000 Index Portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of such funds is based on a major failing of the S&AMP;P
500: that it contains only large companies and is weighted by
capitalization so that the biggest stocks have undue influence.
</P>
<P>
   When examined, however, the Wilshire 5000 _ now expanded to
include all 7,200-plus publicly traded companies headquartered in
the United States with readily available prices _ has a weight
problem, too. Like the S&AMP;P 500, it is weighted by market
capitalization, so there is not as big a difference between the two
as one might expect.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as much as 80 percent of the Wilshire's value is in
companies that are also part of the S&AMP;P 500. This striking overlap
means that an investor who may think he is getting stakes in a
healthy portion of small and midsize companies is actually looking
at a quite meager side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the price-to-earnings ratios of many big stocks in
the stratosphere, risk-conscious investors may conclude that such
indexing still gives them an uncomfortably large exposure to
expensive stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two kinds of index funds track each other closely:
Vanguard Total Stock Market has returned 19.9 percent annually on
average from its inception seven years ago through April 23, versus
21.4 percent for the Vanguard Index 500, according to Morningstar
Inc., the Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   A better idea may be allocating assets to put more emphasis on
mid-cap and small-cap index funds, thereby balancing the risks of
stocks with high P/E ratios against those whose valuations are less
exalted. That is something you cannot do in a total market fund.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, an investor with a total market fund, or some
combination of benchmark-linked funds, has indexed all his assets.
What's wrong with that? While it is accepted that indexing makes
sense for large-cap stocks, the jury is still out on indexing when
it comes to smaller issues.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the 18.97 percent average annual return of the S&AMP;P 500
for the 10 years ended March 31. That beat every category of
general equity fund over the period, according to Lipper Inc., the
research firm in Summit, N.J. But the average small-cap fund
returned an average of 13.60 percent annually over the same period,
handily beating the 9.68 percent average of the Russell 2000 index
of small-cap companies.
</P>
<P>
   (The average mid-cap fund returned 14.55 percent, annualized,
over the 10 years, versus 17.43 percent for the S&AMP;P 400 index of
mid-cap stocks).
</P>
<P>
   The lesson: A total market index fund is a good core holding.
But if you choose it as an all-in-one substitute for a genuinely
diversified set of stock-market assets, you are likely to pay for
the convenience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
