<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: INDIAN TRIBE ASKS ASYLUM
</P>
<P>
   All 2,500 members of an Indian tribe have asked for political
asylum in Spain, saying their community faces extermination at the
hands of leftist guerrillas and right-wing death squads. The
homeland of the Embera-Katio people in Cordoba Province has become
a battleground for the groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Larry Rohter
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: WORLD BANK LOAN
</P>
<P>
   Barely a month after strikes and protests threatened to topple
his government, President Jamil Mahuad has obtained preliminary
approval from the World Bank and other international lending
agencies for a $900 million economic rescue package. The agreement
is intended to lift Ecuador from its worst financial crisis since
the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Larry Rohter
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: U.S. LIFTS TUNA BAN
</P>
<P>
   Over the objections of American environmentalists, the U.S. has
lifted an embargo on Mexican canned tuna and authorized its sale
carrying the label ``dolphin safe.'' The U.S. imposed the embargo
in 1987, saying dolphins were trapped in the large nets used by
many Mexican fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Julia Preston
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ELECTORAL REFORM BILL
</P>
<P>
   Opposition legislators in the lower house of Congress struck a
blow to the governing party, known as the PRI, by approving a
sweeping electoral reform law. The bill imposes new controls on
government use of the news media during campaigns, permits the 9
million Mexicans living abroad to vote, increases penalties for
vote buying and election fraud and allows for party coalitions. The
reform seems unlikely to pass the PRI-controlled Senate, however.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Julia Preston
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: ANDREOTTI FACES LIFE TERM
</P>
<P>
   A public prosecutor in Perugia asked that former Prime Minister
Giulio Andreotti be given a life sentence if convicted on charges
he conspired in the 1982 murder of a journalist. Andreotti, 80, is
also awaiting a verdict in Palermo, where he is on trial on
separate charges that he was the Mafia's main protector in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: NEW PINOCHET CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   Judge Baltasar Garzon broadened the indictment against Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, adding 12 charges of torture against the former
Chilean dictator, making a total of 72 from the period beginning in
1988. The move came as Pinochet's lawyers said they would appeal
Britain's decision giving the go-ahead to extradition proceedings
that could force him to stand trial in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Al Goodman
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: PREMIER READY TO RUN
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, head of the coalition
government that lost a confidence vote, said he would lead that
same coalition into elections as its prime ministerial candidate.
He also said in an interview with the magazine India Today that
``it might be highly improper'' for his caretaker government to
sign the nuclear test ban treaty by the September deadline if the
election is delayed until then. The date for new elections is not
expected to be set until next week.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Celia W. Dugger
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA: NEW ASEAN MEMBER
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old Association of Southeast Asian Nations achieved
its dream of including all 10 countries in the region. At a
ceremony in Hanoi, the association inducted the final member,
Cambodia, after a two-year delay following a coup in that country.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Seth Mydans
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   LESOTHO: SOUTH AFRICA PULLING OUT
</P>
<P>
   South Africa started withdrawing its troops from Lesotho, but
South Africa and Botswana said they would set up a joint rapid
reaction force that could deal with any further disturbances there.
The two nations sent troops to Lesotho last September in an effort
to restore order after months of political unrest.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
