<HEADER>
A0065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-SAFE01-COX     04-30 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-SAFE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student vigilance urged in rally against violence
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Just like the ``freaks,'' the ``dorks'' and
other fringe groups in their schools, the 1,000 young North
Carolinians who rallied here Friday against violence suffer from
derogatory nicknames.
</P>
<P>
   They're called ``snitch'' and ``narc.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the Center for the Prevention of School
Violence's fourth annual summit in Raleigh hailed the students as
heroes, particularly in light of the school slayings last week in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Moore, secretary of the N.C. Department of Crime Control
and Public Safety, urged the students to become even more vigilant
for tension that could erupt in violence.
</P>
<P>
   Moore noted two recent incidents in which high school students
turned in classmates who had carried handguns to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not ratting on someone,'' he told the elementary, middle
school and high school students from 88 Students Against Violence
Everywhere chapters across North Carolina. ``This is what we are
supposed to do as a collective society.''
</P>
<P>
   Threats, warnings and rumors of bloodshed have swept communities
across the country since the Colorado massacre. That attack, on
April 20, coincided with Adolf Hitler's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, thousands of students around the country stayed home,
and some schools closed because it was the 54th anniversary of
Hitler's suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Classes were canceled for thousands of students around the
country after menacing letters, messages and things that looked
like explosives were discovered. Such devices included something
resembling a pipe bomb in Marathon, Wis., and a propane tank in a
suburb of Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   The device that looked like a pipe bomb did not contain
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have been circulating among students and on the Internet
that something bad would happen on the date Hitler killed himself
in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half the 900 students at Scituate High School and Middle
School in Scituate, R.I., stayed home after someone scrawled on a
wall in the girls' bathroom Monday and Tuesday: ``You die on April
30th.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raleigh-based school violence prevention center has spread
nationwide since its creation in 1993. Its roots go back to 1989,
when high school students in Charlotte gathered to promote
nonviolence following the slaying of a classmate at an off-campus
party.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 400 SAVE chapters in 15 states, the center trains
its 35,000 members to educate their classmates about the
consequences of violence. Working with law enforcement officers in
the schools, the students also mediate conflicts among classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, students led sessions that included role-playing by two
men who were handcuffed by police after they got into a fight.
Another group produced a video depicting the harsh consequences of
drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   Tacked to the walls of an auditorium, T-shirts and posters read,
``Start Saving Lives'' and ``What's your friend packing for
lunch?''
</P>
<P>
   Students and administrators said such messages took on urgency
following the string of school shootings over the past two years,
culminating with last week's shootings in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence on TV is not real,'' said Jennifer Ackiss, 15, a
freshman at H.L. Trigg Community School in Elizabeth City, N.C.
``It was a shock that it really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate having reminders as tragic as this one, but it is
possible in a lull to think that things are getting better when
they are not getting better,'' said Joan Michael, dean of North
Carolina State University's College of Education and Psychology,
where the center is based.
</P>
<P>
   Officials acknowledged that the North Carolina students who
gathered Friday can't be expected to prevent violence in schools,
nor resolve all conflicts among their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   But Riley believes the organization's efforts have contributed
to a reduction of violence in North Carolina's schools. Over the
past five years, the reported possession of firearms on school
campuses has fallen by 65 percent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no guarantee that Littleton, Colo., will not happen
here,'' Riley said. ``We have to remain vigilant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
