A0069 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-THORNTON-B     04-30 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-THORNTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON PERFORMANCE PURE ARTISTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ In a series virtually devoid of artistry, Joe
Thornton has been the Rembrandt amid the crayon splotches.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bruins and Hurricanes have devoted themselves to
meat-and-potatoes hockey, the second-year Boston center has been
one of the few performers who has created something other than
havoc.
</P>
<P>
   The prettiest works in his gallery were a pair of third-period
assists in Game 4 that provided the Bruins with a 4-1 victory and a
2-2 tie in this best-of-seven Eastern Conference quarterfinal
entering Friday night's return engagement at Greensboro Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton helped snap a 1-1 tie Wednesday when he retrieved Ray
Bourque's power-play slap shot from the end boards, worked the puck
to the side of the net, stretched his 6-foot-4-inch, 225-pound
frame to its full length, and poked a cue shot that bounced off the
shoulder of Carolina goalie Arturs Irbe across the crease to Landon
Wilson, who deposited the gimme for a lead the Bruins never
relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   For insurance, Thornton displayed the muscle that complements
his guile. He worked the puck to Anson Carter behind the net barely
five minutes later, setting up a Steve Heinze score.
</P>
<P>
   That came on top of perhaps the Bruins' lone bright moment of a
3-2 loss in Game 3, when Thornton gathered up a loose puck after a
Carolina giveaway and threaded it across the slot for a Sergei
Samsonov goal that forged a short-lived 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the sort of thing he did in junior hockey,'' said
president-general manager Harry Sinden. ``He's a creative
playmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's also a confident playmaker, and the playoffs have
become his personal exhibit after a 16-goal, 41-point regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing really well lately,'' said Thornton, who
missed the series opener with a strained sternum but is
experiencing no ill effects. ``In the playoffs, I feel great every
night.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a heartening departure from last year, when Thornton was
feeling, and looking, lost almost every night. At the end of his
rookie season, he was basically a fourth-line afterthought as the
Bruins bowed out to the Washington Capitals in the first round. Now
he's giving them an auxiliary second-line threat as they make a
legitimate run at Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later in the season as it's progressed, I've felt pretty
good,'' said Thornton. ``I've felt a lot more confident with the
increased ice time. When you have confidence, you can do a lot
better.''
</P>
<P>
   As an 18-year-old rookie in 1997-98, Thornton mostly displayed
bewilderment. After being the top overall pick in the 1997 NHL
draft, he was used like fine china by coach Pat Burns, and the
major highlight of his professional indoctrination was avoiding a
demotion to juniors. Burns insisted that a talent of Thornton's
tender years had to be groomed gradually; critics who witnessed his
play and statistics (3 goals, 7 points in 55 games) wondered if the
Bruins' alleged prize investment had been a colossal waste.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the carping, Sinden never lost faith. ``I had seen so
much in junior,'' recalled the boss, ``that I couldn't discount
what my eyes told me.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Sinden's vision has been proven accurate and
Burns's tutelage has been vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Staying up last year was a big help for me,'' said Thornton.
``I learned a lot just by observing.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach, ever the demanding mentor, grudgingly concedes
Thornton's progress with one caveat: ``You never know that until he
really grows up. I hope there's a lot more to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden is sold already. ``I saw pretty early this year that Joe
was going to be the player we saw in junior,'' he said. ``He's
developed a confidence that's remarkable shift to shift and game to
game. He's got it all, and if all goes right, he should develop
into one of the elite players.''
</P>
<P>
   He's providing glimpses at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was more or less on the fourth line in the
playoffs,'' said Thornton. ``This year I have more pressure to
perform.''
</P>
<P>
   No problem. ``He thrives on competition,'' said Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   And putting on a show.
</P>
</TEXT>
