<HEADER>
A0071 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      04-30 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIDENTIFIED CONSPIRATORS COULD RETURN TO CLASS, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ As frustration mounted about the pace and
progress of their investigation, authorities acknowledged Friday it
was possible that co-conspirators in the Columbine High School
massacre might return to classes Monday among the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also grew increasingly defensive about their
response to warnings that gunmen Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold were
potentially violent, complaining about what they called speculation
based on ``20-20 hindsight.''
</P>
<P>
   They pursued the complaints as far as possible without
developing evidence of a crime, authorities said. Also, they asked
a deputy assigned to the school to keep a watchful eye on Harris
and Klebold, neither of whom acted hostile or aggressive in his
presence. That deputy, Neil Gardner, exchanged gunfire with one of
the killers during the seige.
</P>
<P>
   While defending their actions, authorities acknowledged that
danger signs were either missed or misinterpreted. ``We all learned
a lesson,'' said Lt. John Kickbush of the sheriff's department.
``We need to take these things in a more serious fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, authorities announced a second arrest they said was
peripherally connected to the case, involving a 34-year-old woman
accused of phoning a bomb threat to a nearby high school. One day
earlier, a hardware store clerk was charged with lying to
investigators about having sold propane tanks and other bomb-making
materials to Harris and Klebold before the attack in which they
took 15 lives, including their own.
</P>
<P>
   Although investigators have repeatedly said they believe others
were involved in lugging weapons or planning the attack, there have
been no arrests directly connected to the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Dave Thomas, who earlier had to retract his
prediction of an imminent arrest on a gun-related charge, Friday
said only that ``closure'' of that piece of the investigation was
expected ``in the near future.'' Steve Davis, spokesman for the
Jefferson County Sheriff's Department, said no arrests were
expected during the weekend, and no further media briefings were
scheduled until Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   They have not identified any suspects, but investigators said
privately that other students with advance knowledge of the
killers' intent might be fellow members of the student body.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said investigators had collected 8,000 to 10,000 pieces of
evidence, and were already pursuing 900 of the 1,200 live leads
received to date, none of which dissuaded them from their belief
that Harris and Klebold did not act alone. But Davis reiterated
that the investigation has turned up ``no indication of any third
suspect in the school at the time of the shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus of investigators' frustration was the repeated
insistence by a Littleton couple that the sheriff's department
failed to adequately pursue a complaint about homicidal fantasies
and threats against their son on Harris's Internet web page.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, Randy Brown supplied a sheriff's deputy with 10
pages of printouts from the web page, which authorities released
Friday along with the ``suspicious incident'' report that resulted
from the complaint. Between profane rantings about annoyances
including people who mispronounce words, phone solicitations, car
insurance, and country music, the printouts include a long tirade
about Brown's son, Brooks, and two threats on Brooks Brown's life.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said a sheriff's investigator, John Healy, tried to access
the web site, but the Internet addresses supplied by Brown were
either incorrect or had been shut down. Healy apparently did not
call Brown to ask about the accuracy of the web addresses, and
Davis said he did not know why.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said that in April 1998, Brown's wife Judy called in
another report saying her son had received a threat via e-mail.
According to Davis, Judy Brown said her son tried to respond to the
sender, but the sender was unknown and Brooks Brown had
accidentally deleted the message.
</P>
<P>
   A second investigator, John Hicks, reviewed that report but saw
no evidence the sender had violated any laws. Authorities said the
main reason the investigation stalled was the Browns wanted to
remain anonymous and did not want Harris or Klebold to know about
the report, out of fear for their son's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the ability to speak to a victim, or positively
identify a suspect, elements of a crime could not be established,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, the district attorney, suggested Friday that although
Klebold's parents were cooperating with investigators, Harris's
parents were avoiding police. Thomas said an attorney whom he would
not identify had contacted his office on the Harrises behalf, but
claimed that pressing business elsewhere was preventing him from
putting investigators in direct contact with the couple.
</P>
<P>
   While Littleton investigators prepared to take the weekend off,
authorities in neighboring Denver were cautiously awaiting the
annual meeting of the National Rifle Association. Several marches
and silent vigils were expected to greet the NRA, which refused
requests by city leaders to hold its long-planned convention
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The woman arrested Friday for the bomb threat was identified as
Rae Holt, the mother of a a former student at nearby Pomona High
School. She was charged with filing a false report about explosives
and menacing, both felonies. Thomas said school officials
recognized her voice because they had 40 to 50 contacts with her
previously about her son, who she felt had been treated unfairly by
the school. On Thursday, 50-year-old hardware store clerk Gary
Sowell was charged with making a false report for saying he sold
Harris and Klebold bomb-making supplies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
