<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT TO HOLD WHITE HOUSE FORUM ON YOUTH VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pleading with parents and students to open a
discussion about the causes of youthful rage, President Clinton
said Friday that he would convene a White House meeting on youth
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Friday that he was not singling out gun
manufacturers or the makers of violent movies for criticism or
proposed legislation. Instead, he offered to ``bury the hatchet''
in his long-running feud with the National Rifle Association and
invited Hollywood executives to join in the search for a solution
to violence in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not be fighting about who takes the blame,'' Clinton
said Friday as he announced a May 10 forum at the White House on
guns, youths and popular culture. ``Instead, we should all be
looking for ways to take responsibility, and we should be doing
that together.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders had asked the president to convene a
conference on violence and values. In the wake of a rampage that
took 15 lives at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., last
week, several congressional committees are planning hearings to
address the causes of school killings, including the possible
contributing role of entertainment and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The White House did not specify who would be invited, but said
it would include educators, gun makers, entertainment industry
representatives and Internet providers.
</P>
<P>
   In a plea to hunters and gun advocacy groups like the NRA to
join in the quest for an answer to outbursts of deadly rage,
Clinton said he had no intention of limiting legitimate access to
guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's bury the hatchet and build a future for our children,
together,'' the president said, a day before the NRA opens its
annual convention in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also signaled to Hollywood that his attack on movie
violence would be chiefly rhetorical.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the biggest names in Hollywood, including Saban
Entertainment and Time Warner, which have been criticized for
producing particularly violent movies and television programs, are
among the biggest soft-money contributors to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Saban, creator of ``Power Rangers'' and ``Ninja Turtles,'' is
the second largest producer of children's television programming
and the second largest soft-money contributor to the Democrats. The
company and its executives gave $328,776 to the party in the
1997-98 election cycle, according to Federal Election Commission
records.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, which produced the movie ``Natural Born Killers,''
gave Democrats $211,000 in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   The president gently urged Hollywood to reduce the amount of
violence in its products. Still, entertainment executives were
bracing for another assault on their work in the name of ``family
values.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
