</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-SCHRENKO01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. school leader proposes Mace, Tasers for administrators
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming and Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia school Superintendent Linda Schrenko will seek
a state law authorizing local school districts to arm
administrators with Mace, pepper spray or an electronic stun device
called a Taser, a spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gambill, Department of Education comptroller and Schrenko's
main go-between with the Legislature, said principals and assistant
principals should have the option of carrying these weapons if
their local system approves and if they are properly trained. His
remarks came at a legal and media conference in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, I hope not,'' was the immediate reaction from Juvenile
Court Judge Glenda Hatchett, a panelist at the conference. Another
panelist, Emory University public safety expert Arthur Kellermann,
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in spending dollars on school administration, but
not for weapons or surrogate weapons,'' Kellermann said later.
</P>
<P>
   Schrenko did not return phone calls seeking comments on her
proposal. Asked why she was not available for comment, assistant Ed
Floyd said Schrenko authorized Gambill to speak on the proposal,
had no plan to make any other formal statement and probably felt
that was all that needed to be said at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill said the Littleton, Colo., school shooting gave the idea
more urgency, but that Schrenko had talked about it weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no demands from principals for these weapons,
Gambill said. But ``right now, an irate parent, a belligerent
parent or student, if they start getting hysterical or violent,
there's no way to subdue such an individual other than to try to
physical restraint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Puckett, director of the Georgia Association of Educational
Leaders, which represents principals and other administrators, said
he didn't think administrators would be interested in Schrenko's
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seriously doubt that any of our members are interested in
becoming police officers,'' he said. ``I don't mean that as a
criticism of Linda. We're all searching for ways of making schools
safer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
