<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MORE TO GO: BAFFERT ON A ROLL ENTERING KENTUCKY DERBY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif, Ore.)   (See also RAC-DERBY-BET) 
(rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ On the eve of the Kentucky Derby, this was the
easy part of Bob Baffert's weekend: Silverbulletday winning her
seventh straight race and her 10th in 11 starts, dominating the
Kentucky Oaks at Churchill Downs before a record crowd of 101,034
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The difficult part for Baffert unfolds on Saturday when he
attempts to become the first trainer in racing history to win the
Kentuck Derby three years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But Baffert, who already trains two Derby favorites in General
Challenge and Prime Timber, added another weapon to his powerful
arsenal Friday when he decided to start another star filly,
Excellent Meeting, against colts in the Derby instead of running
her against fillies in the Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   So he will take aim on history with three horses in the 125th
Derby: the entry of General Challenge and Excellent Meeting, owned
by Betty and John Mabee of Golden Eagle Farm in California, and
Prime Timber, owned by Marie and Aaron Jones of Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   If Baffert wins, he will become the first trainer to win both
races in the same year since 1952, when Ben Jones won the Oaks with
Real Delight and the Derby with Hill Gail.
</P>
<P>
   The 125th Derby will be run on a dry, fast track before a throng
that could surpass last year's crowd of 143,215, if Friday's
attendance gives any clue. In its 125th running Friday, the Oaks
shattered last year's record total of 94,415.
</P>
<P>
   The Derby lost one horse from its full field of 20 Friday when
Aljabr, one of the ``mystery'' horses from Dubai, was scratched
with some lameness. But while the 19 Derby candidates were resting
or exercising lightly for their wide-open Run for the Roses, the
Oaks provided little suspense once Silverbulletday got rolling.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-year-old superstar, owned by Mike Pegram, who also owned
last year's Derby winner, Real Quiet, stalked the pace set by
Marley Vale until they reached the far turn. Then jockey Gary
Stevens asked Silverbulletday to run, and she shot forward. At the
close, she had two lengths on Dreams Galore, who had 4} lengths on
Sweeping Story, while Marley Vale under Jerry Bailey faded to
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The winner ran the mile and one-eighth in 1:494/5 and paid $2.20
for a $2 bet to win as the 1-9 favorite in a lopsided betting
situation that cast the rest of the field of seven as far out as
58-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have lost half of my fans if we had lost the race,''
Baffert quipped afterward. ``Now I can relax and go for the double.
Tomorrow will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Asmussen, the trainer of Dreams Galore, put it gallantly:
``She ran a great race, but ran into a bear. They could've gone
around again and not caught the winner. Silverbulletday is a
champion, and she proves it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert ended the suspense about his weekend lineup Friday
morning outside Barn 33, where he unleashed Real Quiet and Silver
Charm onto the Derby scene as winners in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent Meeting will run in the Derby,'' he said, wasting no
time on preliminaries. ``I wanted to see how she trained this
morning. She's been training great, and I think she deserves the
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she got a favorable post, I figured it was fate and she
should run in the Derby. She's one who can take the heat, doesn't
mind dirt in her face and is peaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting, who drew the No. 6 post position for the Oaks
and and has the No. 5 post position for the Derby, has run nine
stakes in a row that were rated Grade I or II. She is a bay
daughter of General Meeting and granddaughter of Seattle Slew and
Chief's Crown, and she has won seven of her 11 starts and finished
in the money in all 11, with earnings of $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to separate these three horses,'' Baffert said.
``General Challenge is probably the most talented of the three, and
I think Prime Timber is ready to run his best race, which he'll
need to win. I just hope that when they're turning for home, I
don't have to say to myself, `I wish I had run Silverbulletday in
there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to cover all bases. I think we're in a position to
win. Now it's a matter of racing luck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
