<HEADLINE>
COLORFUL JAIR HAS ZENGA'S CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They taught Anselmo ``Jair'' Ribeiro a
different way of life when he moved to Roxbury from Cape Verde.
Jair taught his new countrymen soccer.
</P>
<P>
   There is a similar storyline for millions of immigrants in the
United States but Jair has taken things to another level. Not only
did he excel in local soccer leagues as a youngster, he became a
professional with top clubs in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Probably, destiny played a large part in Jair's progress. Anyone
named after a Brazilian national team star might be expected to be
more than competent in soccer. And, since the Revolution were
created for New England, it would seem natural that Jair was made
to play for them.
</P>
<P>
   When the Revolution meet Colorado Saturday night, Jair will
likely be on center stage, in the central midfield position that
fits him best. He played there last week, combining with Kris
Kelderman to give the Revolution their most fluent offensive
performance of the season in a 3-2 victory over D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ready to play wherever I am needed,'' Jair said Friday.
``We have some injuries, so maybe I will have a chance to play in
the center again. I will try to do the same as last week or better.
Hopefully, things will go well because it is important we get the
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this game is totally different than last week. We have to
keep our concentration on Colorado, stay together, play good
soccer, and keep possession.''
</P>
<P>
   Jair and Kelderman accomplished just that against D.C. United.
Their composure on the ball allowed the Revolution to control the
pace of the game, and will be a key in this contest. In fact, the
direction Jair provided, sometimes in an understated way, was
crucial to the Revolution last season. After Jair was injured in
his seventh game, the Revolution won only three games in regulation
time in failing to earn a playoff berth. Jair returned from a
broken left ankle, but did not regain his early-season form and was
benched.
</P>
<P>
   But player-coach Walter Zenga has regained faith in Jair this
year, starting him at an outside midfield position. Jair moved into
the middle and will stay there while Edwin Gorter (stomach virus)
and John Harkes (sprained knee) remain out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more belief in ourselves this year,'' Jair said. ``A
lot has changed. The mentality of the team is changing, we are
understanding what Walter wants. It's a new philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean we are just playing defense, because what we
are doing is combining defending with attacking. This is good for
me, because I want to become a better player. If I can defend well,
it makes me more valuable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of goals, and the first one is to make the
playoffs. If we play together and do well, everyone will be
watching us and it will be better for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Jair is often one of the most visible players on the field
because of his skillful approach. This season, he became more
conspicuous by dying his hair yellow, then changing it to red for
this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a secret why I did it,'' Jair said. ``But if I score a
goal in this game you will see why.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 12,735th spectator to enter Foxboro Stadium will be the
millionth for regular-season Revolution games and will be involved
in a halftime kick on goal worth $1 million . . . Richard Goulooze
(strained calf) will likely return for the Miami game May 8. The
returns of Imad Baba (groin) and Harkes are undetermined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
