<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well Beyond The Rotary-Dial Phone &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever stood and fumed while the person who got to the
airport pay phone ahead of you seemed to tie it up endlessly, you
won't like what AT&AMP;T has done with 20 pay phones in Terminal 4 at
John F. Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   In place of ordinary phones, the company is testing interactive
touch-screen devices called Public Access Links, made by Imagic
Infomedia Technology, a small Hong Kong company. By swiping a
credit card, calling card or smart card through the device and
touching symbols on its screen, a user can call up flight
information and make reservations on airlines that use the
terminal, order flowers, rent cars, book hotel rooms and even send
e-mail, following instructions that can be displayed in five
languages.
</P>
<P>
   Data connections for laptop computers and Internet access are
planned, threatening to stretch the average duration of a single
person's use of the phone even longer.
</P>
<P>
   Imagic and AT&AMP;T certainly don't mind if users of the devices
stick around awhile: They will see more of the ads that often flash
across the phone's screen for Perrier, Hilton hotels and others.
</P>
<P>
   If the phones, already widespread in Hong Kong, catch on at JFK,
Imagic hopes to place them at airports, hotels and convention
centers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the phones' new capabilities, the absence of one
feature may also set harried would-be callers fuming: They do not
take quarters, or any other coins. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ SHARON R. KING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Horror Movie? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compliance officers at brokerage houses think of themselves in
white hats, helping to protect the investing public by making sure
that their colleagues play fair. So it is no small deal in their
world that what is probably the first movie to feature a compliance
officer as a main character makes him one of the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   The film is ``Boiler Room,'' described as a cross between
``Glengarry Glen Ross'' and ``Wall Street.'' Written and directed
by Ben Younger and planned for release by New Line Cinema late this
year or early in 2000, the film is set in a none-too-reputable
brokerage firm in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A cast of glib young men led by Ben Affleck rake in riches by
cold-calling investors and talking them into buying dubious
securities _ the kind of thing compliance officers are supposed to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Compliance Reporter, a newsletter for the profession, put a
report about ``Boiler Room'' on its latest front page and quoted
Younger as saying the film ``does not give a wonderful view'' of a
compliance officer ``in the back pocket'' of the shady firm.
</P>
<P>
   It also quotes real compliance officers saying that taking such
a job would end their careers and wondering whether the film will
appeal to a wide audience, though ``a lot of regulators will go see
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
