<HEADLINE>
WE TRIED TO WARN YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It's going to be really deep around here now that Bob
(``you like me, you really like me'') Kraft gets to say he turned
down the greatest sweetheart deal in the history of sports because
he loves Boston so much.
</P>
<P>
   It's right there on paper. Check the balance sheet. Given the
choice to let Connecticut build him a $374 million playpen, or stay
in Foxboro to construct a stadium with his own money (plus $70
million worth of state-subsidized infrastructure), Kraft Friday
chose to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   What a guy. In the pantheon of local gods, this puts him up
there with Arthur Fiedler, Cardinal Cushing, Ted Williams, Larry
Bird, and Natalie Jacobson. For this, Kraft is granted at least
five years of immunity from criticism. Like Dennis Rodman he can
write a book _ ``Insufferable As I Wanna Be.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of insufferable, need anyone be reminded that some of
us knew all along that Kraft wasn't moving? It wasn't that hard to
deduce, really. When you grow up around here, you know certain
truths: Every construction job will take twice as long and cost
twice as much as originally planned; the Red Sox will choke in the
end; a guy like Kraft wants to be BMOC in Boston, not Yahoo
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   As they wallow in their now-monsterous sense of inferiority, the
good people of Hartford should see this as a victory. They've been
spared the indignity of paying through the snout to make a rich man
richer.
</P>
<P>
   There are other winners, of course. Patriot fans don't have to
make that tedious 200-mile round trip to Hartford eight times a
year. This will save untold thousands in speeding tickets and
sunglasses. (Bird always hated the Hartford ride because the sun
was in his eyes all the way down.)
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts House Speaker Thomas ``Guardian-at-the-Gate''
Finneran gets to say he stared-down the behemoths from the NFL
while protecting Massachusetts taxpayers from corporate welfare.
Finneran should have the ``Battle Hymn of the Republic'' playing in
the background next time he delivers a speech. He's even taking
credit for changing NFL stadium support by-laws. If the league's
new instant replay system succeeds, look for Finneran to claim it
was his idea.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader is a big winner. Nader was one of
the first to expose the Hartford deal as a turkey for Connecticut's
taxpayers. He urged Kraft to ``go back to Massachusetts.'' The
implosion of Hartford's stadium package deal is probably Nader's
best work since he vaporized the Corvair.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kirk, Father Donald Monan and the rest of the Boston
College business posse also deserve a round of applause. They
sparked the new Massachusetts offer and brought Finneran together
with Senate President Thomas Birmingham and Governor Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   The big loser, naturally, is Connecticut Governor John Rowland.
Yeesh. Rowland looks like Flounder of ``Animal House'' fame _ after
the Delta members trashed his brother's car. In this spirit, the
Krafts would be the frat boys who turned to Flounder and said,
``You (expletive) up. You trusted us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland messed up. He trusted the Krafts. He thought a handshake
was good and that a deal was a deal. Instead, he was used like a
rented dump truck. If he'd like, we can supply him with names and
numbers of guys who were burned by Kraft in the past. Maybe they
could form a self-help group. If might make Rowland feel better to
know that he is not alone. The Guv will probably have to sue
somebody to save face.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, forgive me while I revisit some old stories from
Globe library files.
</P>
<P>
   It was fun to look back at those photographs of a smiling Kraft
and Rowland shaking hands while the ever-vigilant Connecticut
legislators stood in the background, applauding.
</P>
<P>
   I came across that phony, mid-December (just in time for the
State House vote) letter Kraft wrote in the Hartford Courant in
which he said, ``In hindsight, relocating to Hartford is something
we should have done years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Another knee-slapper was Rowland's annual Christmas poem to the
local Chamber of Commerce that concluded, ``To the whining masses
in Boston, I just have to laugh . . . We may be a bunch of Yahoos,
but we managed to land the Krafts.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was affable mayor Mike Peters, who said, ``Unlike
what's been written, we've got a lot to offer. And I believe in Bob
Kraft. I don't think anyone would pull on the emotion of these
people and then pull the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa, Mr. Mayor. Can I sell you some authentic moon rocks I dug
out of my driveway?
</P>
<P>
   We tried to warn you guys that you were being used. Nonetheless,
we're gonna miss our friends in the Nation's File Cabinet. Things
won't be the same around here without the rhetoric of Nader, those
Connecticut legislators in Patriot hard hats, the intransigent
steam plant, the forced smiles of the Kraft boys, and daily toxic
waste updates from Yo Adriaen's Landing.
</P>
<P>
   John Rowland is Charlie Brown. Bob Kraft is Lucy. And poor
Charlie Brown is lying on his back because Lucy has pulled the
football away at the last second. Again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
