<HEADLINE>
THE PERILS OF INVESTING ON AUTOMATIC PILOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While stock investors applauded the Dow Jones
industrial average's assault this week on another nice round number
_ 11,000 _ it is likely that few of them were participating in the
profits. That's because most investors have money in stocks listed
not in the Dow but in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, which has risen
only half as much as the Dow this year.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that no investment trend lasts forever, the S&AMP;P is now
the laggard after years of beating the Dow. And this is occurring
just as mutual funds that mimic the S&AMP;P's moves have been flooded
with money.
</P>
<P>
   The turnabout reflects a shift in sentiment among some investors
that began about two weeks ago. Sensing a revival of economic
growth around the world, investors plunged into stocks of
industrial companies, like paper, steel, cement and chemical
concerns, seeing them as likely beneficiaries of the recovery. At
the same time, investors started to exit the technology and health
care stocks that had made the S&AMP;P a star.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Dow, which is weighted by its stocks' prices, the S&AMP;P
500 is weighted by its stocks' market capitalizations.
</P>
<P>
   What does this mean for investors? Just as the impressive
performance of the S&AMP;P has masked a bear market in many smaller
stocks since last summer, its current malaise masks a bull market
in stocks with lower market caps, which are not big contributors to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan D. Abrams, chief investment officer of asset allocation
at Trust Company of the West in New York, said investors should
prepare for a stealth bull market. ``The averages will be in a
trading range,'' he said. ``But within the confines of that trading
range there will be wonderful moves in stocks that will not show up
in the indexes.''
</P>
<P>
   This is already happening. Shares of Dow Chemical, for example,
rose 40.8 percent in April. But because it is such a tiny component
of the S&AMP;P _ 0.267 percent of the index's value _ its rise has had
little impact on the 500. Microsoft, with a weighting of 3.77
percent, fell 9.6 percent in April, producing a significant impact.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P is vulnerable because it is dominated by the companies
investors have been selling in recent weeks. Technology and health
care companies account for 19 percent and 12 percent of the index's
value, respectively. In contrast, chemical companies make up 1.9
percent of the index; paper and forest products account for 0.6
percent, and aluminum concerns represent 0.3 percent. Because these
stocks make tiny contributions to the S&AMP;P, as they have surged, the
index has shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   It may be premature to say that the era of momentum investing is
over. But buying what has been going up is no longer working. Even
the Russell 2000 index of small-capitalization stocks, left for
dead in recent months, was up 8.8 percent in April, versus the
S&AMP;P's 3.8 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey M. Warantz, an equity strategist at Salomon Smith
Barney, reports that even the tiniest stocks have improved. While
companies with less than $250 million in market value were, on
average, down 6.7 percent for the year in early April, they are now
down only 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is very positive for investors whose holdings are
diversified among small stocks and large, value and growth. It is
not good news for those who have placed all their eggs in the S&AMP;P
500 basket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
