<HEADLINE>
TELECOMMUNICATIONS PROBLEM REPAIRED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE HUNT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Repairmen finally fixed Friday a telecommunications problem that
briefly shut down the entire Southern California horse racing
simulcast system Thursday morning, blacked out Santa Anita and
another site and cost Hollywood Park more than $2 million in
handle, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Al Karwackie, general manager of Southern California Offtrack
Wagering Inc., said a worker for one of Pacific Bell's
subcontractors ``snipped the wrong wire'' while working in a
manhole on the perimeter of Los Alamitos Race Course, near
SCOTWINC's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   He said the subcontractor was installing a fiber network for a
newly constructed building near Los Alamitos Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, everybody went down, the system went down,''
Karwackie said. ``At 9:30 a.m., everything went down. Immediately
Autotote started switching over to backup. Santa Anita came back on
line, then they dropped out and we haven't been able to determine
why. At 6 o'clock last night we got Santa Anita up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the National Orange Show (in San Bernardino) wasn't up at
all and we couldn't get them up at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Mooney, director of publicity and public relations at
Hollywood Park, said it was difficult to obtain information about
the problem Thursday. Neither he nor Karwackie said they knew if
anyone would be held liable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure it cost us $2 million minimum in handle yesterday,''
Mooney said. ``Because Santa Anita was down and San Bernardino was
down.''
</P>
<P>
   George Haines, director of pari-mutuels at Santa Anita, said
Friday that 1,767 bettors were at the Arcadia track when the
problem occurred Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure occurred at 12:15 p.m. and we canceled at 1:35
p.m.,'' he said. ``We probably lost about $600,000 in wagers. We
refunded the gate and gave out rainchecks (to patrons).''
</P>
<P>
   Haines said Santa Anita's backup system came on after the
initial problem arose around 9:30 a.m. Neither Karwackie nor Haines
knew what caused the backup system to go out at 12:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a satellite (site) we're so dependent on technology and
telecommunications,'' Haines said. ``The National Orange Show was
never able to come back up, but Del Mar never had a problem all day
long. Barona (Casino) and some of the Indian sites, their lines
were up and down all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Haines said Santa Anita was operating on its backup line as of
1:30 p.m. Friday, but planned to switch over to its primary line
after the running of the Kentucky Oaks at Churchill Downs later in
the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Karwackie said there was great concern about the problem
initially because the Kentucky Derby was only two days away. Last
year on Derby day, the total handle from the Southern California
satellite wagering sites was a record $23.5 million, according to
Mooney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had us all on edge because it was so close to the Derby,''
Karwackie said. ``AT&AMP;T and Pac Bell were involved. We got everybody
on the same page finally. They just finished (at 12:10 p.m.). Thank
God we got it straightened out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
