s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-JAPAN-BANKS-ART-2     04-30 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-JAPAN-BANKS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING A BRAVE FACE ON JAPAN'S BAD BANK LOANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ ``He's Don Quixote,'' said Jun Satoh, chief
manager of credit policy for the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi,
motioning to his senior colleague, Eiichi Haruki. ``I'm Sancho.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Japanese bankers came to the United States on a mission
that some of their peers regard as nearly as crazy and embarrassing
as tilting at windmills, though it is likely to accomplish a lot
more. The quest: enticing institutional money managers, beyond a
small circle of bargain-hunting specialists, to invest in Japan's
mountain of defaulted bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's banks have traditionally hated to sell nonperforming
loans, because acknowledging that some or all of what was owed will
never be recovered is seen as humiliating in a culture that takes
humiliation hard.
</P>
<P>
   When economic times were good, banks could afford to be
unrealistically patient and optimistic about a few bad debts. But
the bursting in 1992 of the country's ``bubble economy'' of soaring
real estate and stock prices and the seven long years of recession
that followed have left the country's banks with nonperforming
loans that by some estimates total $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   By tying up capital that could otherwise be lent anew, they
throttle bank earnings and starve the economy of credit.
</P>
<P>
   The dead weight dragged a few weaker banks into liquidation and
forced others to merge. Ultimately, it prompted the government to
design a $64 billion bailout plan, announced last October, to help
the survivors cope by injecting capital into banks that took
write-offs before the end of the fiscal year, on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Alone among Japan's biggest banks, though, Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi has stood aloof from the bailout and tried to
solve its problems on its own. And that's where the delicate
journey of Satoh and Haruki comes in.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi was among the first Japanese
lenders to start selling its defaulted mortgages on factories,
stores and office buildings. So far it has sold loans totaling $7
billion in face value in 17 deals with Wall Street ``vulture''
funds and hedge funds in Britain and America.
</P>
<P>
   These are the same kinds of investors who moved in early when
the United States had a similar problem, the collapse of the
savings-and-loan industry in the late 1980s, and who made big
profits buying up dud loans at 50 cents on the dollar,
restructuring them and selling them at 60 or 65 cents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the investors who wield money on the scale that Japan needs
_ the big pension fund managers _ came late to the bulk auctions of
S&AMP;L loans by the Resolution Trust Co. This time, Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi wants to lure those managers into the game
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've taken a lead role in reaching out to nontraditional
investors because it will broaden the market and speed
liquidation,'' said Jack Rodman, a managing director of a Los
Angeles accounting firm that specializes in real estate, E&AMP;Y
Kenneth Leventhal, and one of Japan's leading bad-loan deal makers.
</P>
<P>
   Outreach is what Satoh and Haruki were doing in California,
trying to prepare the ground for future sales by preaching the
general advantages of investing in dud Japanese loans on Japanese
terms. They paid calls on two of the United States' largest
institutional investors, the California Public Employees Retirement
System, known as Calpers, and the treasurer of the University of
California.
</P>
<P>
   Squiring the two bankers into the offices of the fund managers
was William J. Popejoy, who has experienced the pain of real-estate
cycles first hand. At federal regulators' behest, Popejoy was
chosen in 1984 to try to forestall the demise of American Savings,
the nation's largest S&AMP;L. It ultimately failed despite his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we aren't here to do a deal,'' said Popejoy, now the
president of Pacific Capital Investors of Irvine, Calif. ``When the
Japanese came and bought assets in the U.S., they bought them the
U.S. way,'' he said he told the portfolio managers. ``We'd like you
to think about buying Japanese assets the Japanese way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Capital has already bet its own money on that kind of
thinking. It recently completed a deal to buy 40 loans with a face
value of $370 million from the bank, and wants to buy another
package of loans five or six times that size, preferably with
pension funds as partners.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Capital's deal with the bank requires it to stick to
nonconfrontational tactics in trying to collect on the defaulted
loans. The aim is to get partial repayment from the debtors without
resorting to repossession, an intense humiliation in Japan that the
bank still wants to spare its customers, even nonpaying ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're concerned with how we treat their borrowers,'' Popejoy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors are likely to consider such a deal
attractive if it includes an American partner to service the loans,
said Martin J. Whitman, chairman of the Third Avenue Value fund,
who has been an outspoken advocate of changes in Japanese law to
ease the bad-debt problem. Spokesmen for Calpers and for the
University of California treasurer would not comment on their
meetings with Satoh and Haruki. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To help it make its case to investors, Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi
discarded its historical ways of analyzing nonperforming loans in
favor of approaches drawn from the RTC's experiences, like valuing
the loans based on cash flow. In the process it pioneered a
secondary market that was new for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, you couldn't liquidate nonperforming loans,''
Haruki said. ``This is very new. The effort was put into finding
out what the investors' appetite is for.'' When the bank's
bulk-sale plan passed muster with Japanese tax authorities, other
banks followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened, the bank is considering securitizing some of the bad
loans, another strategy rare in Asia but common in the United
States. ``In Japan, when you want to change things, it takes a long
time,'' said Sachio Mikumo, a bank executive who accompanied them
on their California trip. ``There were skeptics, but not any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman of E&AMP;Y Kenneth Leventhal estimates that $40 billion of
nonperforming Japanese loans have been sold in the last three years
at prices averaging 10 percent of face value, much lower than was
typical in RTC sales.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers have included CS First Boston, Salomon Smith Barney,
Lehman Brothers and Goldman Sachs. Sales should accelerate this
year as once-hesitant banks, spurred by the bailout, begin writing
off and selling bad loans the way Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi has,
American investors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's waiting for the tap to open,'' said Thomas J.
Barrack Jr., chairman of Colony Capital.
</P>
<P>
   When it does, Satoh and Haruki hope that the pension funds they
are evangelizing will be ready to buy in bulk _ and help buoy
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only way the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi survives,''
Satoh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
