<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Lively Discussion About Executive Pay &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Graef Crystal minces executives, not words. He plans to get the
last one in his feud with Linda J. Wachner, chief executive of
Warnaco Group, a New York apparel company.
</P>
<P>
   In his newsletter, crystalreport.com, Crystal lambasted Ms.
Wachner for receiving $73.8 million last year for ``positively
awful performance.'' Her pay demonstrated that ``complete and utter
greed'' is not confined to men, he said. Comparing Warnaco's size
and shareholder returns with more than 300 other companies', he
said later, she makes almost 20 times as much as she should.
</P>
<P>
   When Thestreet.com reported Crystal's analysis, Ms. Wachner
described it as ``misleading and erroneous and, therefore,
malicious and slanderous,'' and put lawyers on standby. On Friday,
the company noted that its stock had outperformed the industry and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index in four of the last eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal has rallied his supporters. ``We cannot afford to have
our sources silenced,'' said Sarah Teslik, executive director of
the Council of Institutional Investors. Not to worry: Crystal plans
to rebut Ms. Wachner on his Web site Monday. By week's end, she was
tiring of the contest, saying, ``This is not a game of
Ping-Pong.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ REED ABELSON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never Say Die at Intel &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At age 62, Andrew S. Grove sees a big difference between today's
Internet entrepreneurs and the founding team of Intel three decades
ago: himself, Gordon Moore and Robert Noyce. ``At Intel, we never
discussed an exit strategy,'' he said during a recent stop in New
York. Squadrons of Silicon Valley start-ups, he added, think that
if they position themselves to intersect with the ambitions of,
say, Cisco Systems or Microsoft, they will probably be bought out
in 18 months. ``At Intel in the early days,'' he said, ``we had
this naive notion that we were building the next IBM or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE LOHR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They Love New York &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tisch family's latest investment technique is the New York
Straddle. Having bet heavily on a Wall Street retreat, the Tisches
hedged their exposure to further losses somewhat by betting $35
million on a continued New York boom. After finishing the
renovation of the Regency Hotel on Park Avenue, flagship of their
Loews Hotels, Jonathan M. Tisch, the Loews Hotels chief, came up
with the week's best publicity stunt: an ultimate power breakfast,
with politicians like the former Mayors David N. Dinkins and Edward
I. Koch, and business people like Louis Rudin, the New York
builder, to mark 25 years of breakfasts there. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Perpetual Winner &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone annoyed by people who can do several things well, without
sweating, should avoid Pamela Thomas-Graham. The first black woman
partner at McKinsey &AMP; Co., Ms. Thomas-Graham is a Phi Beta Kappa
graduate of Harvard College and Harvard Law School. Harvard
Business School, too.
</P>
<P>
   At 35, she's married to the prolific author Lawrence
Otis-Graham. She works 80-hour weeks, serves on three charitable
boards and plans to help her husband run for Congress. Oh, and she
had a baby, Gordon Julian Thomas Graham, 11 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she had time on her hands. Simon &AMP; Schuster has just
published her second novel, ``Blue Blood,'' a murder mystery set on
the Yale campus. Her editor is Michael Korda. ``I find it really
cathartic,'' Ms. Thomas-Graham said. ``Writing is a way to relax,
and open your mind.'' For her consulting clients, in the media
industry, she has new advice: ``I'm much more in favor of large
author advances now.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some People Refuse to Lose  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks aren't all that's being bid way up in Silicon
Valley. At a March auction for the Menlo School, a prep school in
Atherton, Calif., Emma, a yellow Labrador puppy, fetched $17,000.
The buyer? Robert Swanson, the founder of Genentech. The dog was
donated by a veterinarian, said Maggie Pringle, co-director of the
fund-raiser, which brought in more than $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   Four people bid, but only two continued past $10,000: Swanson
and Eff Martin, a Goldman, Sachs partner. That $17,000 buys more
than a best friend; extras included five training sessions and a
portrait of the owners with their new pooch.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURA M. HOLSON
</P>
</TEXT>
