<HEADER>
A0099 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-JACKSON-ART-60     04-30 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JACKSON-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 CAPTURED U.S. SERVICEMEN MEET WITH JACKSON DELEGATION IN
BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., Mich.)  (js) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE Yugoslavia _ The three U.S. servicemen held by
Yugoslavia described on Friday their days as lonely and monotonous,
interrupted only by perfunctory daily visits from a Serb army
officer and solitary exercise in their cells.
</P>
<P>
   They said they have no contact with each other or with other
prisoners in the same facility. One said he took a walk Friday
outside his cell, only the second time he had been allowed to do so
in his month-long imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Another said he was finally given reading material Friday, but
the books were on Serb history and the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
   With the chairman of the military court monitoring the questions
through a Yugoslav army interpreter and a military cameraman
recording their answers, the three young soldiers were allowed to
speak to the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Congressman Rod Blagojevich of
Illinois, and a reporter from The New York Times. They were filmed
by CNN.
</P>
<P>
   When they were given the opportunity to send messages to their
families, each of the soldiers turned to face the camera directly
and seemed, suddenly, very young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope it's all over soon,'' said Spc. Steven Gonzales, 21, of
Huntsville, Texas. ``Mom, Dad, sorry I put you through so much pain
and agony.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., was
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my wife Tricia and my son Ryan, I love you,'' he said, his
face reddening and his eyes filling with tears. He stopped and
seemed unable to go on.
</P>
<P>
   Blagojevich, a Serbian-American Democrat whose father was raised
in Yugoslavia, seized the uneasy moment, bringing a smile to the
young soldier's face by saying that as a member of the House Armed
Services Committee, he was going to make sure the captives receive
a pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles, could spend only
a few minutes with the visitors because an air raid siren sounded
just before he was brought into the room, and the Yugoslav military
officers tried to hustle the visitors out.
</P>
<P>
   After pleas from Jackson, he was sent in with his two fellow
soldiers for a final photo shoot and time in front of the
television camera. He had time to do little more than send
greetings to his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks everybody for all your thoughts and prayers,'' Ramirez
said. ``They've been needed and they're a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   The members of the delegation that met the soldiers, as well as
the length of the meeting, was decided by the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
   The visit lasted about 40 minutes. The three soldiers, who had
been seen publicly only once shortly after they were captured along
the Kosovo-Macedonia border, were brought one at a time into a room
at the Belgrade Military Court building, just over the Sava River
from downtown Belgrade, at about 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities refused to say where the soldiers are being held
and permitted them to answer only those questions that concerned
their living conditions and their health. The Yugoslav government
also specified that only two journalists and two members of
Jackson's interfaith delegation to Belgrade, which includes several
members of the clergy who had been in contact with the prisoners'
families, could meet the servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers, dressed in their laundered U.S. Army camouflage
uniforms, appeared nervous and anxious and sat straight in their
armchairs. They wore their battered Army-issue boots without the
laces, which they said had been taken away by their captors.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were well-fed and had no medical problems and
appeared fit, if tense.
</P>
<P>
   Stone was the first to be brought into the small office of the
general supervising the visit. He appeared tired, with dark circles
under his eyes, and still had a bruise on his forehead, which he
said ``is a mark from our capture.'' He added that he had received
medical attention for the injury immediately after being taken into
custody.
</P>
<P>
   They are provided with three meals a day and a cell furnished
with a bed and a small table. who received th reading material
Friday, said he has only ``caught sight'' of his fellow GIs briefly
during his captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who appeared more rested than the others, ventured the
most elaborate description of his condition. Responding to a
question from Jackson, he said he was ``okay, considering the
circumstances.'' He added that he is also feeling ``a little
mentally drained.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson told him, ``You are a hero. People know you all over the
world.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The clergy who came from the United States with Jackson, but
were barred from meeting with the soldiers, had brought bibles and
small Orthodox icons for each of the men, as well as five packages
of Chuckles candies for Ramirez, a tape player and cassette tapes
recorded by each of the men's families.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson showed each of the soldiers the pile of gifts, but the
Yugoslav general, who would not identify himself, did not allow the
soldiers to take the gifts with them, saying they had to pass
military censors first.
</P>
<P>
   To each of the servicemen, though, Jackson offered words of
encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many view the jail experience as a time of reflection, a
time to write, a time to think, a time to pray, a time to think
about how they want to build their lives,'' he told Stone, adding
that his imprisonment could be an opportunity to strengthen his
character and faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of our scars,'' he said, ``come our stars.''
</P>
<P>
   The men, members of the 1st Squadron, 4th Cavalry of the 1st
Infantry Division operating in Macedonia, were on patrol when they
were captured at about 4 p.m. on March 31. The government here has
maintained they were seized in Kosovo, although U.S. officials have
accused the Serbs of abducting them and have demanded their
release.
</P>
<P>
   The dazed soldiers, with bruises and dirt on their faces, were
shown on Serb television soon after their capture. The Yugoslav
authorities at first talked of putting the three on trial, although
some government officials have since retracted the threat. However,
the general who supervised the interview with the soldiers
suggested that a trial remains under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The procedure for the indictment has not been in any way
initiated and possible evidence is still being collected,'' he
said, in laying down the limits on what could and could not be
asked of the soldiers. ``And it has to be yet decided whether an
indictment will be raised at all. But until then all matters
pertinent to possible investigation should not be dealt with at
this point.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the general also said the three soldiers are prisoners
of war and are being treated in accordance with the Geneva
Convention. The men received their first visit from the
International Red Cross only this week. The general said a
representative of the European and Balkans branch of the Red Cross
also met them, but he did not say when that meeting took place.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who arrived in Belgrade on Thursday with a group of
American Christian, Jewish and Muslim leaders, said he still hopes
to persuade the Yugoslav government to release the soldiers as a
humanitarian gesture. He said after the interviews with the men
that he still had no indication that they would be freed. Jackson
and his delegation have met twice with the Yugoslav foreign
minister, Zivadan Jovanovic, and are scheduled to meet President
Slobodan Milosevic on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The general's comments indicated that the Yugoslav authorities
may consider it gesture enough to have approved a visit with the
soldiers. He called the arrangement ``out of the ordinary,
especially considering the air raid possibility and air strikes at
any moment.'' Indeed, the interviews with the soldiers were cut
short when an air raid siren wailed outside the window after about
40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are to take this as a gesture of good will by the Foreign
Ministry of our country,'' he told Jackson. ``Because as you are
probably well aware after the aggression by NATO on our country,
three U.S. citizens have been apprehended, having been found on
Yugoslav territory in U.S. uniforms and with arms in hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers' final moment with their visitors was spent in
prayer. With his arm around Ramirez and Gonzales, and with Stone
standing close to his side, Jackson thanked God for watching over
the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help is on the way and hope is in the air and soon, very soon
you will know peace and family,'' he said, before the men filed out
of the room, holding their hands behind their backs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
