<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-ANALYSIS-BO     04-30 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
125TH DERBY ON THE LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Joe Morgan was standing on familiar ground,
the Louisville of his minor league baseball haunts. Morgan has
found wisdom in the 40 years since his baseball days at the old
Louisville Fairgrounds. Especially when it comes to horse racing,
and especially when it comes to the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never go for favorites, and definitely not in this race,''
said the former Red Sox manager, who had just been chatting up Earl
Wilson, a Red Sox pitcher of the 1960s. ``I'm looking for a horse
to pay $110.''
</P>
<P>
   And so should you.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom in recent years has a Kentucky Derby been so competitive,
and it is still to be learned if these horses in this 125th
Kentucky Derby are equally good or equally mediocre. All but a few
seem equal in talent. No horse stands out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Derby field looks pretty evenly matched,'' said Bobby
Barnett, the trainer of Answer Lively and a trainer who's been
winning race after race this week at Churchill Downs. ``You can
make a case for so many horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to this mix two fascinating subplots. It is extremely rare
for a girl to try the boys in the Kentucky Derby _ only 36 fillies
have run against 1,523 colts in the 124 previous runnings of the
Derby, three winning _ but Saturday afternoon not only one, but two
fillies will be running. And both of the girls, Three Ring and
Excellent Meeting, have more than a sporting chance.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the intrigue of Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum's
attempt to capture one of the most American of sporting events, the
Kentucky Derby. Maktoum paid $5 million for Worldly Manner but
Worldly Manner is a most American horse, bred in Kentucky, born to
race on dirt, and trained for his first four races by that most
American of trainers, fast-talking, wise-cracking Bob Baffert. When
Sheikh Mohammed bought Worldly Manner last fall and brought him to
Dubai, Wordly Manner was one of the pre-race favorites for the
Breeders Cup Juvenile race.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, Americans have belittled Sheikh Mohammed for
what they consider his unorthodox training methods. Trainer Nick
Zito has been most visible with the snide remarks, and others have
chimed in. After all, only 13 Derby starters in history have
attempted to win the Derby without having a previous race in their
3-year-old year and Morvich was the last to try the feat. That was
in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Americans have fallen for the snare that there is
only one way _ the American way _ to train for the Derby. ``Worldly
Manner, coming over from Dubai,'' said Barnett, ``you know they
have him ready.'' Or, as Richard Mandella, the trainer of Desert
Hero put it, ``I know not many people are giving him a chance here,
but I still think World Manner could run a big race.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the scenario. And while keeping in mind that post
position is overrated in a race of a mile-and-a-quarter, empty your
mind of all those Derby trends that pass for analysis. That's
because two strong trends will conflict Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert has trained the winners of the last two Derbys and just
missed three in a row when his Cavonnier lost the 1996 Derby by the
shortest of noses. The 140,000 fans who will be at Churchill Downs
are aware of this and are sure to make Baffert's entry of General
Challenge and Excellent Meeting the favorites in the race. No
favorite has won the Derby since Spectacular Bid 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business is to throw out those horses who
have no chance. They are Desert Hero, Ecton Park, Valhol, K One
King, Kimberlite Pipe, Lemon Drop Kid; in other words, the entire
mutuel field. Add Vicar to the toss-outs.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen horses are left and what is clear is this is a most
unusual Derby. Unlike most Derbies there is not an abundance of
oil-burning early (and cheap) speed, which would set up the
late-closing horses very nicely. Indeed, with the late scratch
Friday of Aljabr, the entry-mate to Sheikh Mohammed's Worldly
Manner, there may be only two or three horses with clear early
speed and they are the two fillies, Excellent Meeting and Three
Ring, and possibly Vicar, who is starting far to the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting should have run in Friday's Kentucky Oaks for
fillies but Baffert, her trainer, is wise to the ways of the Derby.
Excellent Meeting clearly is in the race as a rabbit, to ensure
that there is an honest pace to the race so Baffert's other two
horses, General Challenge and Prime Timber, can close late. But do
not dismiss Three Ring, the other filly, who may go off at 30 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Also do not dismiss Worldly Manner, who may go off at 14 to 1 or
so. Sheikh Mohammed and his Godolphin Stable are among the most
powerful in the world and they know how to get a horse ready for a
race, snickering Americans or no snickering Americans. And Jerry
Bailey, Worldly Manner's jockey, is the best. Wordly Manner will be
in the running.
</P>
<P>
   This race is so competitive that the reward must be compatible
with the risk. In other words, go for odds; the payoff must be
generous for a handicapper who takes a stand in a race that has no
clear standout. Baffert's three horses and Vicar will be overbet;
their reward is too little. Look elsewhere. The same with Zito's
two horses, Adonis and Stephen Got Even (the favorite in Friday's
early betting); toss them.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the horses to consider: D. Wayne Lukas has been lying
in the weeds but his horses, Cat Thief and Charismatic, are sharp
and their odds will be high. Menifee is in the mix, as well as
Worldly Manner. Three Ring, Answer Lively, or First American could
finish third and light up the tote board.
</P>
<P>
   This is a scenario: Cat Thief first, Worldly Manner second, and
any of this group _ Menifee, Charismatic, Answer Lively, First
American, or General Challenge _ in the third spot. As usual, go
for the gusto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
