<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0119 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-GUNS01-COX     04-30 1693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-GUNS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Americans debating access and sales in wake of Colorado high
school massacre
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bang! You're dead.
</P>
<P>
   Fun in the spirit of Roy Rogers, when the 1950s television
generation pointed their index fingers at each other in pretend
gunfights.
</P>
<P>
   Horrifying in the late 1990s, when young people take real guns
onto school grounds and murder their classmates.
</P>
<P>
   The images from Littleton, Colo., last week _ like those from
Arkansas, Mississippi, Kentucky and Oregon _ raise difficult
challenges for people of faith who live in a society that says
freedom requires access to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, killed 12 classmates and
a teacher and injured many others before taking their own lives in
Columbine High School. The boys apparently gathered weapons,
including semiautomatic guns, for months before carrying out their
acts on April 20, the birthday of Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   A week after the shootings, President Clinton proposed
legislation that mandates child-safety locks on all guns sold, bans
for life gun ownership by people who commit violent crimes as
juveniles, and makes adults criminally liable for allowing children
access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   Recent public opinion surveys show that a majority of Americans
want restrictions on firearms sales, particularly handguns, and
favor background checks and waiting periods. They also oppose the
sale of assault weapons and the influx of cheap, often imported
pistols known as Saturday night specials.
</P>
<P>
   But the same polls show that most Americans are opposed to an
outright prohibition of handguns and other firearms.
</P>
<P>
   There is a mystique about firearms apparent in the National
Rifle Association, which is planning a meeting in Denver today just
miles from the site of the latest school massacre. It was apparent
earlier this year when more than 1,400 exhibitors displayed their
wares in the Georgia World Congress Center at the industry's
largest trade show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face facts, a large part of the history of man has been
written with some type of firearms,'' says Atlanta history buff and
gun collector Beverly M. ``Bo'' DuBose III, who, with his father,
assembled a collection of more than 200 Civil War arms. ``If we had
not had the right to bear arms, we would never have gained our
freedom from England.''
</P>
<P>
   But guns also evoke passion and raise moral dilemmas, such as
those being played out in debates in Colorado over concealed
weapons and those in Georgia about Atlanta's plan to sue gun
manufacturers. The debates also go on among people of faith.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Clinton Marsh can still feel his horror at the April
1993 newspaper headline that turned him into an activist against
gun violence: ``2 charged in fatal shooting of toddler, 1, in
apartment.'' The article told of the death of Quanesha Smith, who
was shot in the head while sleeping on a sofa in her family's
Carver Homes apartment when someone fired through the window.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh, 82, a retired Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) minister
living in Atlanta, had read many articles about death by gunfire,
but the image of a sleeping child struck him in a way no other had.
He tried to get fellow ministers organized against gun violence,
but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Over the following summer, Marsh watched the news reports, and
the bodies, pile up. In July, four people were shot in a dice game.
In August, a father was killed by his 14-year-old son. In
September, a ninth-grader was shot to death in a high school
lunchroom.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in October of that year, when a 15-year-old girl died
after being caught in cross fire at a bus stop, others started to
listen. Marsh formed Georgians Against Gun Violence with the
support of several civic and religious groups, including the city's
Concerned Black Clergy, the Presbytery of Greater Atlanta and the
North Georgia United Methodist Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The killing of people, whether it's willful or accidental, is
contrary to what Christianity teaches,'' says Marsh. ``We feel
we're trying to save lives, limbs and jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has lobbied unsuccessfully each year in the state
Legislature for stricter gun control.
</P>
<P>
   One of his opponents in influencing the Georgia General Assembly
is a fellow Presbyterian, layman Mark Miller of Cedartown.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 36, says he became a ``life member'' of the Georgia
Sports Shooters Association, the state arm of the National Rifle
Association, about 10 years ago because of the ``assault I saw
taking place on my rights and those of other citizens of this
country.'' The issue that drove him into the arms of the NRA, he
says, was the effort to pass a ban on semiautomatic weapons in
Georgia. The effort failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been quite successful here at stopping almost every
piece of legislation that's come down the pike,'' says Miller.
</P>
<P>
   People with sincere convictions quote conflicting Scriptures,
views of the U.S. Constitution, and even statistics to bolster
their arguments for and against firearms ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Those who oppose any form of gun regulation cite Luke 22:36 in
which Jesus said anyone who has no sword must buy one. Those who
believe guns must be controlled are more likely to quote the
admonition that anyone who lives by the sword _ or the gun _ will
die by it.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to the Bill of Rights, gun rights advocates
maintain that the Second Amendment ensures the rights of
individuals to bear arms. Those who want restrictions on guns say
it applies only to a public militia.
</P>
<P>
   Many who favor restrictions on guns to curb violence use the
numbers in studies by the Center for Injury Control, a part of
Emory University's Rollins School of Public Health. In a study
published last year and including both fatal and nonfatal
shootings, the center found that for every time a gun in the home
was used in a legally justifiable shooting, four were used in
unintentional shootings, seven in criminal assaults or homicides,
and 11 in suicides or attempted suicides.
</P>
<P>
   Those statistics are dismissed by gun rights advocates, who are
more likely to look to the work of Gary Kleck, a criminologist at
Florida State University and the author of a book called
``Targeting Guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Kleck claims Americans use guns 2.5 million times a year in
self-defense. A later national study by one of Kleck's critics
produced a figure of 1.1 million self-defense incidents involving
guns in America each year, including many when guns were drawn but
not fired.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arthur Kellermann of Emory's Center for Injury Control said
studies by his institution and others show that many Americans are
less enamored of guns than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look over a 10- or 15-year time frame, it's pretty
clear that the prevalence of gun ownership _ the percentage of
American households that contain one or more guns _ is dropping,''
said Kellermann. A decade ago, about half of American homes had
guns, he said. Today, that figure is about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, ``gun-owning households have more
guns than they used to.'' And, more of the guns sold today are
handguns than in the past. Whereas in the 1980s, about a third of
new guns were handguns, today closer to 40 percent to 45 percent
are, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kellermann, regarded as a pioneer in the study of gun violence
as a health issue, became interested in the field in 1984 in a
snack bar at the University of Washington, where he was a medical
fellow. While eating a hamburger, he heard over the radio of the
death of Motown singer Marvin Gaye, who had been shot by his father
in a dispute over insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Kellermann had grown up with guns in rural Tennessee, shooting
skeet with his father on weekends. Now, he said, he was hearing of
too many cases of ``a wife or a kid or a brother or a parent''
being killed in a domestic incident or accident.
</P>
<P>
   On a moral and ethical level, Kellermann, an Episcopalian, said
families should ask whether they are making their households and
their communities safer by owning a gun. When speaking to groups,
he makes the point by asking, ``Which would make you feel safer,
the knowledge that everyone in this room is carrying a concealed
firearm or the knowledge that no one in this room is carrying a
concealed firearm?''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether people choose to own guns, Kellermann says
he hopes people will give serious thought to their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choosing to have a gun, whether you hunt or target shoot or
collect or even perceive that that gun might be useful to you for
defense, is an incredibly important decision,'' says Kellermann.
``It should never be taken lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  34,040 people died from firearms in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  That same year, the last year for which such statistics are
available, 18,166 people used a firearm to commit suicide, 1,134
unintentional firearm deaths were recorded and 14,037 murders were
linked to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Americans own guns at 3 times the average of other countries.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Children in the United States are 12 times more likely to die
from firearm injury than are children in other industrialized
nations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  31 states have right-to-carry laws permitting citizens to
carry concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  84 percent of Americans believe citizens are guaranteed the
right to keep and bear arms under the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  As of 1991, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
reported that in the 1900s, more than 211 million firearms were
manufactured in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There are 230 million guns in the United states, including 75
million to 80 million handguns.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The wholesale dollar value of all firearms and ammunition
manufactured in the United States in 1995 was about $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  99.8 percent of firearms and 99.6 percent of handguns will not
be used to commit violent crimes in any given year.
</P>
<P>
   For more on the debate over firearms control, check out:
</P>
<P>
   headlines.yahoo.com/
</P>
<P>
   FullCoverage/US/GunIssues
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
