<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0120 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DALLASAUSTIN02-COX     04-30 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALLASAUSTIN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TLC and Monica are his `babies
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While his musical peers are dancing beside their artists in
videos and rapping along with them on record, Dallas Austin is
still the producer hidden neatly in the liner notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very happy being in the background,'' the
28-year-old Columbus native says. ``If I have to be noticed at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the past three years, he really hasn't been. That's when
Austin, who co-produced TLC's new CD, ``FanMail,'' dropped off the
musical radar to write songs for the Atlanta R&AMP;B trio, the
best-selling female group of all time, and establish his Freeworld
Records label.
</P>
<P>
   His labors have met with mixed results. ``FanMail'' made the
second-highest debut of the year in February, becoming the first
No. 1 album for the threesome _ Tionne ``T-Boz'' Watkins, Rozonda
``Chilli'' Thomas and Lisa ``Left-Eye'' Lopes.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a slower climb for Austin's record label. Freeworld
has signed only one artist, but rapper JT Money's single ``Who
Dat?'' is in the Top 5 on the R&AMP;B and rap charts and debuted at No.
22 on the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   As for other potential artists, well, Austin has been in the
clubs and on the radio asking people to call him if they think they
have talent.
</P>
<P>
   And he's giving them the right number.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost as if Austin is that 16-year-old student at College
Park's M.D. Collins High School again. That's when he got his first
break as a producer with a local R&AMP;B band named Princess &AMP; Star
Breeze.
</P>
<P>
   We caught up by phone with the multi-Grammy nominee _ who made
million-sellers out of bite-size Atlanta hip-hop act Another Bad
Creation and Boyz II Men _ in a Nashville studio.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are you working in Nashville these days?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a music city. Totally. I mean, here it's not uncommon
for the bag boy at Kroger to be a songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Plus there are so many distractions in Atlanta. When we did ABC,
Atlanta was a new, youthful music scene. But now I've been there a
long time and my identity is kind of out there. And it's really
gotten kind of distracting. Every other minute the phone is
ringing, someone is at the door or outside.
</P>
<P>
   So I started coming here about three or four years ago. It's
just felt comfortable ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Three years ago was when people started asking what was
happening to you. You went from the guy Michael Jackson, Madonna
and the Rolling Stones were calling to the guy we weren't really
hearing from.
</P>
<P>
   A: But people weren't exactly coming up to me asking, ``Where
have you been?'' Just like they don't ask the producers in the
videos with the Rolls-Royces, ``Is that all you're about?'' But
that may be what they're thinking.
</P>
<P>
   I've always been making music. During my so-called time away, I
was working on (R&AMP;B vocalist) N'Dea Davenport and (rock act) Bjork
overseas. And writing for (Atlanta R&AMP;B vocalist) Monica and TLC.
Those are my babies. And when you make that kind of commitment to
an act, you can't just accept every other project that's being
offered to you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was with the talk from Lisa ``Left-Eye'' Lopes about
your almost not being a part of this TLC album?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lisa was out of the loop when she was doing all that talking.
Concentrating on her solo record.
</P>
<P>
   Q: She went on Hot-97.5 and said you had gotten too expensive.
More expensive than Babyface.
</P>
<P>
   A: I am expensive. And that's because I don't go off working on
a lot of people's stuff. My value is in my longevity.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were you really asking for $4 million?
</P>
<P>
   A: That was a figure that was out there to do the whole album,
including all the costs.
</P>
<P>
   The back-and-forth about me producing the album came down to
this: I was not coming on to this project to do one single or two.
Not when I've helped build the first two albums. I didn't want to
make `CrazySexyCool' again. Just fill a record with whatever
producer that's hot. I'm glad that `CrazySexyCool' did what it did,
but we want to continue to set trends. Not follow them.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm like the fourth member of TLC. So when ``L.A.'' (Reid,
LaFace co-president) came to me and said, ``We're trying to do this
TLC album. And we want you involved in the whole album,'' we shook
hands on it and left. It wasn't about money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you worry about how having Chilli's vocals up front on
this record would be perceived? Considering you two are
romantically involved.
</P>
<P>
   A: I was just thinking about reinventing the group. Giving the
people something new.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You're also reinventing yourself as record label president.
You started out with Rowdy Records, and had some success. And now
you've got Freeworld Records going.
</P>
<P>
   A: And we're starting all over again. See, to me, the fun is
taking the drive to get to your destination. I love what Puff Daddy
and David Geffen have done, and the level they've gotten to in this
business. But I feel like at a certain point consumers can assume
you're too big and untouchable in a sense. That's when you need to
get back out there, get back on the road and find out what's
driving, or moving, the people.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
