<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PEOPLE OF THE LAW?
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ One of Israel's notable achievements, in the 50
years since the state was reborn, has been the development of a
respected legal system. The Israeli Supreme Court is known for
protecting the civil liberties of citizens. Its judges are esteemed
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   That achievement is at stake in Israel's upcoming elections. To
an extent that is hard for outsiders to appreciate, the very idea
of the rule of law is under attack by substantial forces in Israeli
society.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Avigdor Lieberman, a powerful figure among the one
million Russian immigrants to Israel and the former director
general of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's office. He has a new
Russian party to compete in the election against Natan Sharansky's
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not one iota of faith in the justice system,''
Lieberman said when he launched his party, calling for the system
to be ``overhauled.'' He has made ferocious attacks on the police _
attacks that the police suggest are designed to deter investigation
of international crime syndicates and his possible connection with
them. He called the head of the international crimes unit, Brig.
Gen. Moshe Mizrahi, a ``champion of anti-Semitism.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Orthodox rabbis and their followers also denounce the
Supreme Court. In February, 250,000 Orthodox Israelis held a
protest in Jerusalem against the court.
</P>
<P>
   Judaism over the ages has been a religion devoted to law and its
interpretation by sages. How, then, can one explain Orthodox
antagonism to the Supreme Court?
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down,'' said Mordechai Kremnitzer, professor of law at
Hebrew University, ``many, though not all, want a halachik state''
_ one governed by Jewish law, the halacha. It would be not a
democracy but a theocracy, ruled by rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a straightforward political explanation. Religious
parties have had enormous influence in Israel's multiparty
political system, able to make and unmake governments. They have
used that power to get benefits from the state, such as funds for
their schools and housing.
</P>
<P>
   They view the Supreme Court as a threat to that position: the
one institution that might curb their privileged treatment. The
court lately held, for example, that no statute authorizes the
practice of automatically exempting all yeshiva students from
military service so long as they do not take jobs _ a practice that
has led to many thousands of permanent students, financed by the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the rule of law has come to a head now over the
case of Aryeh Deri. He is the political leader of Shas, a religious
party made up largely of Jews from Morocco. Deri has long been a
kingmaker in Israeli politics, bringing Shas into coalitions in
return for promises of favorable treatment.
</P>
<P>
   After a trial that extended over nine years, Deri was convicted
recently of taking bribes while in office, and sentenced to four
years in prison. His followers responded by claiming he was
victimized because he was Orthodox and Moroccan: ``Deri is
Dreyfus.''
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual leader of Shas, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, said: ``The
words of the Torah are as a thorn in the eyes of all the secular
judges. This accounts for what happened at the trial.'' Deri put
out a video comparing his trial, amazingly, to that of Adolf
Eichmann.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of other politicians to Deri's conviction has been
telling. Netanyahu said he would still negotiate with Deri, after
the election, so long as he remained free during an appeal. The
leading opposition candidate for prime minister, Ehud Barak, said
after some delay that he would not negotiate with Deri.
</P>
<P>
   The taint of possible criminality reaches into the Netanyahu
Cabinet. The police have reportedly recommended prosecution of the
foreign minister, Ariel Sharon, for fraud, bribery and witness
tampering. The minister of justice, Tzahi Hanegbi, is also being
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   All this has brought the rule of law into the election. In the
bribery scandals, and Netanyahu's silence about the Deri
conviction, legal observers see the danger of what one called a
culture of illegalism in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot kill the rule of law with one shot,'' professor
Kremnitzer said, ``the way Prime Minister Rabin was killed. You
kill it with a process _ by showing the public that there's a
different law for a Deri who takes bribes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
