<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      04-30 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S PRIME-TIME POLEMICS HEAT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Interior Ministry is a gray institution, a
well-worn, humdrum place of civil servants, paper piles and rubber
stamps. But this week it grabbed the Israeli public by the lapels
in a way that nothing has thus far in a personality-based campaign
for the election May 17.
</P>
<P>
   In catchy, hard-hitting television commercials, the Russian
immigrant party led by Natan Sharansky demanded that it be given
control of the Interior Ministry, long controlled by the
ultra-Orthodox, Sephardic Shas Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shas is in control? No! We are in control,'' says the slogan,
which rhymes in Russian.
</P>
<P>
   In power circles, the position of defense minister is considered
most important in a security-alert state like Israel. But it is the
job of Interior Minister that is being fought over _ by Shas, the
Russian party and Meretz, the big party on the left.
</P>
<P>
   In a society torn over the relationship between religion and
state, the Interior Ministry controls birth registry, marriage,
divorce and identification cards _ rituals of ordinary life that
define who is a Jew or how Jewish the Jew is.
</P>
<P>
   The ads feature individuals whose right to citizenship was
challenged because the Interior Ministry raised questions about
their Jewishness. A Russian balladeer talks about the songs he used
to write in Russia about the promised land. ``I did not dream of
the humiliation I'd go through in Israel,'' he said, referring to
when his family was forced to take blood tests to prove they were
related _ and Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Aryeh Deri, the leader of Shas, who was recently convicted on
corruption charges stemming from his tenure as interior minister,
proclaimed that it was war between the new immigrants from Russia,
who he said were given ``red-carpet treatment,'' and the Sephardic
immigrants of the 1950s, whose absorption was ``terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   His words made it clear that the Russians have reason to doubt
that they are accepted. ``We absorbed hundreds of thousands of
Russian immigrants with joy, despite my being interior minister,
even though I knew, to my regret, that hundreds of thousands were
goyim,'' Deri said, using a slur for non-Jews. ``We understood
there was no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cities like Ashkelon and Ashdod,'' he continued, referring
to places with large Russian populations, ``there are entire
quarters where you think you are in little Russia _ churches and
shops selling pork, a completely different culture, and we don't
say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   A Spirited Political Moment
</P>
<P>
   It is a shame that Rabbi David Batzri is not running for office,
because his ratings were high this week for the way he went about
getting rid of a dybbuk.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jerusalem yeshiva, Batzri, who specializes in mystical
Judaism, claimed to have coaxed the dybbuk, or spirit, out of
Yehudit Sigvatker, 38. It was said to be her late husband, as
possessive after life as during it.
</P>
<P>
   As if it were a soccer game, the four-hour exorcism was
broadcast live, with commentary, on the pirate religious radio
stations. Clips from a videotape found their way onto evening news
broadcasts. Israel was gripped.
</P>
<P>
   The low voice of a man issued from Mrs. Sigvatker. The voice
said he was floating between heaven and hell ``after three months
in intensive care,'' and discussed his children. When the rabbi
asked whether Deri, the Shas leader convicted of corruption, was
innocent, the voice said he is guilty, until the rabbi grew
agitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave via the small toe on the left foot,'' the rabbi ordered.
</P>
<P>
   A Symbolic Party Battle
</P>
<P>
   The catchiest visuals in this week's political ads came from the
religious parties. The National Religious Party featured a knitted
yarmulke, like a coiled rope, unraveling. The ultra-Orthodox
parties, whose symbol is the Hebrew letter gimel, introduced a
cartoon version of the gimel, bending in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Of Horses, Carts and Apes
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Likud Party have been grumbling that Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu is campaigning solely for himself and not for
the party's Parliament ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Eitan, a leading Likudnik, spoke bluntly, if
metaphorically, about this feeling. The campaign, he said, was
putting ``the horse before the cart without checking to make sure
the cart was well fastened.'' He also criticized Deri, an ally of
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   He got his in return. Doron Shmueli, a Likud colleague, said
Eitan has ``the brain of an ape.''
</P>
<P>
   Propaganda by the Hour
</P>
<P>
   Political advertising is not presented in Israel as it is in the
United States. It runs in a block of time every night for the three
weeks before elections. Israelis sit down and watch ``the
propaganda hour,'' when Labor ads spill into Likud spots, which
tumble into promos for the new marijuana smokers' party (whose
producers seemed to have inhaled).
</P>
<P>
   Likud presents Netanyahu in two poses. First he is Franklin D.
Roosevelt, in an armchair, as if fireside, wearing a V-neck
sweater. Then he is Theodor Herzl, on a balcony, gazing out at
Jerusalem, in an echo of the famous pose of Herzl, the father of
political Zionism, in Basel.
</P>
<P>
   Labor shows Netanyahu in a different light. In their desire to
show him as untrustworthy, Labor partisans use a shot of the prime
minister on the floor of Parliament, swiveling in his chair and
winking at someone off screen. The wink is a recurring motif.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Ehud Barak, the Labor Party candidate and a former
general, is introduced as a ``warrior for peace,'' with many images
of him in uniform and medals. By the end of the week, Ofer Shelah,
a writer for the newspaper Maariv, said, ``If I see Barak
liberating the Sabena airline once again I will open fire in all
directions.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials bore Russian subtitles, indicative of a stark
political reality: in a country where many people are born Labor or
Likud, the swing votes are seen as belonging to the newest
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Early this week, a skit on the satire show ``Hartzufim'' showed
all the candidates in tutus. They were dancing ``Swan Lake'' for
the Russian prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
