<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0501-1     04-30 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0501-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: writethru, recasts top of story to emphasize Jackson visit
with POWs
 &HT;    NATO LAUNCHES HEAVIEST BOMBING YET, MILOSEVIC USES DIPLOMATIC
CHARM
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0501.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One month after their battered faces were beamed
around the world, three American soldiers held captive in
Yugoslavia were shown meeting Friday in Belgrade with the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, bearing encouraging words, the Holy Bible and
letters from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling pretty healthy, a little mentally drained,'' one
prisoner, Army Spc. Steven Gonzales told Jackson. ``Really miss
home, and hope to be back soon.''
</P>
<P>
   His eyes welling up with tears, a second captive, Staff Sgt.
Christopher Stone turned toward a camera recording the meeting to
address his wife and four-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my wife, Tricia and my son, Ryan, 'I love you,''' said
Stone, struggling with his emotions before breaking into a broad
grin.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's visit -- televised by the Cable News Network (CNN) --
appeared to be part of a charm offensive launched by Serb leader
Slobodan Milosevic, the president of Yugoslavia, who also granted
an international news agency an extensive interview Friday in the
face of the most withering NATO air strikes since the campaign
began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's meeting marked the first time the American soldiers
have been shown on camera since state-run media in Yugoslavia
released footage of them April 1 -- with bruised faces and downcast
eyes -- the day after Serb forces captured them near Kosovo's
border with Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The men said they were fed three square meals a day, were housed
separately in small cells with a bed and table and were visited
regularly by Yugoslav officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's adequate,'' Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., said of
their treatment.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Jackson bowed with the two men and the third
captive, Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles, for a word
of prayer, as air raid sirens echoed from the streets of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, whose mission has received no support from the Clinton
administration, was scheduled to meet Saturday with Milosevic, as
allied air strikes continued.
</P>
<P>
   After flying more than 600 sorties and dropping an estimated 300
bombs Thursday night and early Friday, the alliance was taking
advantage of clear skies to plan at least as many missions
overnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Adding mightily to NATO's firepower, 10 B-52 Stratofortress
heavy bombers were scheduled to fly from U.S. air bases Friday
night to join the NATO armada with a scheduled arrival at a British
air field on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Air raid sirens sounded Friday evening in Belgrade, cutting
short Jackson's visit with the captives, as NATO bombs struck again
at military targets across Yugoslavia and at troops, tanks and
staging areas inside the embattled Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attacks on fielded forces have intensified,'' said NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea, describing furious allied strikes early
Friday on command posts, heavy artillery, anti-aircraft weapons and
railroad tanker cars.
</P>
<P>
   With a month of heavy cloud cover lifting, Shea said, Serb
forces in Kosovo would find it difficult to hide from the aerial
onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   ``As spring gives way to summer,'' said Shea, ``their
destruction becomes inescapable.''
</P>
<P>
   Defiant in the face of the onslaught, Milosevic vowed that he
would ``never surrender'' to U.S. and allied demands for placing a
NATO-led peacekeeping force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Milosevic set forth his own terms for ending the
conflict, a proposal immediately rejected by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said he would accept lightly-armed United Nations
monitors but not a military peacekeeping force made up by his
country's attackers, even if holding out means accepting prolonged
and escalating air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One more day (of bombing) is too much,'' Milosevic said in an
interview with the United Press International news agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what choice do we have if NATO insists on occupying
Yugoslavia? To that we will never surrender,'' Milosevic said in
the UPI interview. ``We Serbs are as one on this life-and-death
issue of national honor and sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Belgrade was ``willing to accept a U.N. presence
and are ready to negotiate its composition. But please understand
that after all those crimes against our nation and its people, we
cannot accept representatives of the countries that committed
aggression against us. We would like to see representatives of
neutral countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Mixing the rhetoric of resolve with the softer edge of an
accommodating host, Milosevic gave a green light to Jackson's
personal mission, but declined to release the captives.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, Stone and Ramirez came under
fire, were surrounded and captured on March 31 as they patrolled a
mountainous area along the Kosovo-Macedonia border on what the
Pentagon described as a routine training mission.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces claim the men strayed into the territory of
Serbia -- Yugoslavia's main state. The Pentagon has not said
whether the men, who were part of a larger NATO force stationed in
Macedonia, crossed the border. U.S. officials have said they might
not know for certain what happened until they are able to talk
freely with the captives.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon reiterated Friday the U.S.
position that the men are being held illegally and should be
immediately released.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson offered the men words of comfort and later told
reporters they were bearing up with ``dignity,'' adding, ``our
country should be proud of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Gonzales at one point, Jackson said, ``You are a
hero. People know about you all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning toward the camera, Gonzales told his parents, ``Sorry I
put you through so much pain and agony,'' then delivered an
impromptu message to the public at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks everybody, for all your thoughts and all your
prayers,'' he said. ``They've been needed and they're a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, wearing a dark three-piece suit, white shirt and tie,
urged the men to consider how prison terms had strengthened the
will of the late civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., South
African apartheid foe Nelson Mandela and even the New Testament
Apostle Paul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of people around the world are praying for you and
they're praying for reconciliation so we can all live in peace
together,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can have the tailwind push them, but sometimes in life
there are headwinds and crosswinds and nobody can see the wind,''
said Jackson, admonishing the captives to ``turn pain into power
and use this time wisely . . . time to write, time to think and
time to pray.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO offered no security guarantees for Jackson. President
Clinton's spokesman Joe Lockhart said the administration does not
support Jackson's visit, which Lockhart described as a personal
initiative by the civil rights activist.
</P>
<P>
   In his most extensive interview since the NATO bombing began
nearly six weeks ago,
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said his country stood no chance of prevailing
militarily against NATO, but he said he was heartened by the U.S.
aversion to American casualties and the emerging resistance in
Congress to support the ongoing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He portrayed his country as a victim of NATO aggression,
insisted that Serb army troops had not committed widespread
atrocities in Kosovo but conceded that heavy-handed methods had
been employed by paramilitary forces.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials blame Milosevic for overseeing a
campaign that has resulted in the execution of at least 4,000
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and has left another 1.5 million
homeless over the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not angels,'' Milosevic said. ``Nor are we the devils
you have made us out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
