<HEADER>
A0161 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-MODIGLIAN     04-30 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-MODIGLIANI-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SHE TALKS, STOCKS MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to its advertising, Dean Witter measures its success
``one investor at a time.'' But it might also say that behind each
of its 11,450 brokers is one Leah Modigliani.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Modigliani, among other things, is day-to-day manager of
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's list of 10 stocks it recommends most
strongly for purchase, called its fresh-money buy list. When she
makes a new choice _ on Wednesday, for example, it was the Mead
Corp. _ many thousands of customers get calls from brokers
suggesting they follow her lead.
</P>
<P>
   The chosen company's market capitalization then typically swells
by hundreds of millions of dollars. Mead jumped $4.75, or 12
percent, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But what really distinguishes Ms. Modigliani, 34, a slight,
roller-blade enthusiast, from most Wall Street strategists is
intellectual firepower, no doubt related to one of the best
economic pedigrees this side of Lawrence H. Summers, the deputy
Treasury secretary. (Both his parents are economists and two
uncles, Paul A. Samuelson and Kenneth J. Arrow, are Nobel laureates
in economics.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Modigliani is the daughter of academics _ in social
psychology and education _ and a distant cousin of Amedeo
Modigliani, the painter and sculptor. And her grandfather is Franco
Modigliani, winner of a 1985 Nobel in economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather's enthusiasm for economics is absolutely
contagious,'' she said. ``But I never expected to be particularly
interested in economics. It's just that it was my favorite subject
at Oberlin.'' She is now known for developing, with her
grandfather, a new way to judge the performance of mutual funds and
other portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Byron R. Wien, her mentor and boss, had complained that most
comparisons ignored the amount of risk that managers took. He asked
that she try to figure out why. What Ms. Modigliani found was that
existing methods were either not rigorous or precise enough _ she
cited Morningstar's star system _ or were too difficult to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kept thinking there's got to be a better way,'' she
recalled in an interview in her 11th-floor office in Morgan
Stanley's theater-district headquarters on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Her solution began over the dinner table at her grandfather's
house in Boston, not long after she joined the firm in 1995. He
asked her what she was working on. After a brief discussion, she
said, ``we knew we were on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on her grandfather's pioneering work on corporate
leverage, she developed over the next year a measure that she
called risk-adjusted performance. It soon became well known as
Modigliani-Modigliani, or M-squared.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the approach first adjusts leverage artificially, to
make all portfolios as risky as a benchmark, like the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index. Then it measures returns. It is the kind of
challenge that taps Ms. Modigliani's intellectual heritage _ from
Oberlin College and Harvard Business School as well as her
ancestors _ and also earns people money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really love is combining the two _ taking the academic
ideas and making them applicable,'' she said. ``And it's about
human behavior as well as finance and math.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she follows Wien's prescription to have fun at work,
though nobody would confuse the Morgan Stanley version with, say,
fraternity high jinks. ``My idea of fun is choosing stocks for the
portfolio,'' she said, and ``to think about risk and talk about
risk to investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Her style of living, which must allow for a 7:30 meeting with
analysts each workday morning to discuss stocks, is anything but
yuppie indulgence. Ms. Modigliani, who in June plans to marry
Nicholas McGrane, a venture capitalist for Bankers Trust, lives in
Manhattan's West Village, where, she says, ``I hardly ever run into
people on the street from work.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she is something of an activist. Last week, she was
exulting because Eulia Charles, a young woman she had been
mentoring for four years through a group called the Student Sponsor
Partnership and whose parents never finished high school, had won a
full scholarship to Fordham University.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Modigliani took Ms. Charles to a family reunion of her
Italian-Jewish clan _ transplanted to the United States after Italy
adopted anti-Semitic laws in the 1930s _ in Boston for Passover
last month.
</P>
<P>
   She is also involved with Girls Inc., an after-school program
that teaches girls about money, and serves on the investment
committee of Oberlin's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Since she has had a high income for only a short time and is
repaying large student loans, Ms. Modigliani's own stock portfolio
is relatively modest. Still, she insists on backing her opinions
with her own cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really be advising people what stocks to buy unless
I'm doing it myself,'' she said. ``Byron, he wants me to feel the
pain when the stocks go down _ and I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Between Oberlin and Harvard, Ms. Modigliani worked for six years
at Marsoft Inc. in Boston, where she managed the production of
software for economic forecasting in the bulk-shipping industry.
But she went on to business school, she said, because she wanted to
put her academic background to use in a practical setting.
</P>
<P>
   At Morgan Stanley, she and Wien _ whose job she is likely to
inherit someday _ share the view that the stock market is about 25
percent overvalued. They have been adding some cyclical stocks,
like DuPont, and small-cap companies, like Cyprus Amax, a metals
concern, to the firm's hypothetical model portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Modigliani said she doesn't feel pressure to conform.
``I'm allowed to have my own opinion on whatever I want,'' she
said. ``When I talk to the brokers and the clients, they know I'm
saying what I really think. That intellectual freedom really is
important to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
