<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/30/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) BELGRADE -- April 30, 1999 -- KOSOVO-BELGRADE, 4-30 --
Victor gets a kiss from his father while visiting the Yugoslav
state television building on Friday which was bombed earlier this
week. Victor's parents worked at the building and lost friends in
the explosion. The Yugoslav capital of Friday was cleaning up after
the heaviest night of bombing yet. (Amy Toensing/New York Times
Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) BELGRADE -- April 30, 1999 -- KOSOVO-JACKSON-3, 4-30 --
Rev. Jesse Jackson speaks to Patriarch Pavle, head of the Serbian
Orthodox Church, seated, on Friday. Jackson later met with the
three American POW's being held in Yugoslavia and hoped to meet
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on Saturday. (Amy
Toensing/New York Times Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) TOKYO -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2 --
BIZ-JAPAN-BANKS-2, 4-30 -- To drum up investor interest in buying
defaulted loans on properties like a Tokyo caterer's building, Bank
of Tokyo-Mitsubishi sent some of its executives to California.
Japan's banks have traditionally hated to sell nonperforming loans,
because acknowledging that some or all of what was owed will never
be recovered is seen as humiliating in a culture that takes
humiliation hard. (Stuart Isett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2
-- BIZ-JAPAN-BANKS-1, 4-30 -- To drum up investor interest in
buying defaulted loans on properties in Tokyo, Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi sent Eiichi Haruki, second from right, Jun Satoh,
right, and Sachio Mikumo, second from left, to California. They are
shown meeting with Michael Ray, left, and Ralph Wintrode of Pacific
Capital, which has bought loans. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) CALABASAS, Calif. -- April 30, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-BACKLASH, 4-30 -- David Yarovesky, a Calabasas High
School senior, in his room. Yarovesky said that his mother had been
fairly understanding about his gothic style, but since two
Columbine High School students opened fire on their classmates last
week, she has worriedly asked, ``What's the difference between you
and them?'' (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- April 30, 1999 --
MICHAEL-DOUGLAS-ALUM, 4-30 -- Actor Michael Douglas laughs while
addressing students at the University of California at Santa
Barbara, his alma mater, during a visit on Thursday. Douglas is, in
his way, UCSB's own one-man winning team, having emerged from his
days as a floundering freshman to reach the pinnacle of
superstardom. (Mike Eliason/Santa Barbara News-Press) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) TIRANA, Albania -- April 30, 1999 -- KOSOVO-APACHE, 4-30
-- U.S. Army Apache helicopters fly past soldiers at Rina airport
earlier this week. The first Apache helicopters are supposed to
take off soon to destroy what NATO's high-flying jets have not:
Yugoslavia's armored forces. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) DENVER -- April 30, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS-2, 4-30 --
Charlton Heston, president of the National Rifle Association,
right, listens to NRA officials during a meeting on Friday. At left
is Wayne LaPierre, the organization's first vice president and top
spokesman. The group's annual meeting, planned long before the
Columbine High massacre, is scheduled for Saturday in Denver, some
15 miles away from the school. The NRA has cut back its gathering
from three days to one and cancelled plans where 350 gun makers and
other exhibitors were to sell their wares. (Kevin Moloney/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) DENVER -- April 30, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS-1, 4-30 --
Charlton Heston, president of the National Rifle Association,
during a meeting with NRA officials on Friday. The group's annual
meeting, planned long before the Columbine High massacre, is
scheduled for Saturday in Denver, some 15 miles away from the
school. The NRA has cut back its gathering from three days to one
and cancelled plans where 350 gun makers and other exhibitors were
to sell their wares. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BELGRADE, Yugoslavia -- April 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-JACKSON-2, 4-30 -- Rev. Jesse Jackson, left, meets with Spc.
Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, on Friday. The U.S.
civil rights leader sought freedom for Staff Sgt. Andrew A.
Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25,
of Smiths Creek, Michigan; and Gonzales, but a Yugoslav government
official told him that their release was ``not on the agenda.''
(Susan Sachs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) PALM BEACH, Fla. -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
2 -- SUB-BIZ-WINE-AUCTION, 4-30 -- William I. Koch, with his
daughter Charlotte, selecting wine from his Florida cellar. Koch, a
member of the family that owns Koch Industries, says high wine
prices have encouraged him to sell part of his collection. Other
collectors are doing the same. (Susan Greenwood/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2 --
ABOUT-CARS-MINIVANS-2, 4-30 -- With its optional 3.8 liter V6, the
Ford Windstar is powerful and the handling is good. The minivan is
ingenious because it allows families - or soccer teams - to travel
together while staying separate. There is no better way for adults
or children to make the long haul. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2 --
ABOUT-CARS-MINIVANS-1, 4-30 -- What sets the Honda Odyssey EX apart
from its competitors in the minivan market is the third-row seat
that folds into the floor. The minivan is ingenious because it
allows families - or soccer teams - to travel together while
staying separate. There is no better way for adults or children to
make the long haul. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2 --
BIZ-PROFILE-MODIGLIANI, 4-30 -- Leah Modigliani, right, who manages
a Morgan Stanley buy list, is also mentor to Eulia Charles. Ms.
Modigliani has been mentoring Ms. Charles for four years through a
group called the Student Sponsor Partnership. Though Ms. Charles'
parents never finished high school, she has won a full scholarship
to Fordham University. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) PALM BEACH, Fla. -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
2 -- BIZ-WINE-AUCTION, 4-30 -- William I. Koch, with his daughter
Charlotte, selecting wine from his Florida cellar. Koch, a member
of the family that owns Koch Industries, says high wine prices have
encouraged him to sell part of his collection. Other collectors are
doing the same. (Susan Greenwood/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- April 30, 1999 -- HOFFA-TEAMSTERS-1, 4-30
-- James Hoffa, president of the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters, at his desk earlier this week. Even now, a month after
he took office, there is still a touch of
``I-can't-believe-this-happened'' amazement as Hoffa sits in the
same office his father, Jimmy Hoffa, once used. (Paul Hosefros/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BELGRADE, Yugoslavia -- April 30, 1999 --
KOSOVO-JACKSON-1, 4-30 -- Rev. Jesse Jackson, stands with, from
left, Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez and
Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone during their meeting in Belgrade on
Friday. The U.S. civil rights leader visited Yugoslavia to seek
freedom for the three captive U.S. soldiers, but a Yugoslav
government official told him that their release was ``not on the
agenda.'' (Susan Sachs/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 30, 1999 -- PATTERSON-RACE,
4-30 -- An African-American who teaches sociology at Harvard
University, Orlando Patterson asserts that problems in many black
neighborhoods stem less from white racism than from the breakdown
of the black family and the behavior of black men who impregnate
too many black women and marry too few. ``Once they make that
important decision to explore the broader marriage market, it may
well put more pressure onf Afro-American men to shape up,'' he
says. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2 --
SHOP-ZETA-JONES, 4-30 -- What to wear? Make it clingy, make it
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana. The actress Catherine Zeta-Jones in her suite at
the St. Regis last Tuesday, at the beginning of a publicity parade
that will take her to Los Angeles, Cannes, Madrid, Rio de Janeiro,
Sao Paulo and Buenos Aires. ``I do love clothes,'' Ms. Zeta-Jones
admits. Normally, she says, she just takes a carry-on: ``I'd just
roll up a few essentials, throw in a few books and I'm off.''
(Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) TUSCALOOSA, Ala. -- April 30, 1999 -- GRAHAM-EVANGELISM,
4-30 --Evangelist Franklin Graham in the lobby of a hotel on
Thursday. Graham, son of evangelist Billy Graham and a prominent
evangelist in his own right, is making Tuscaloosa the site of his
only U.S. festival this year. (Porfirio Solorzano/Tuscaloosa News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2 --
PACO-UNDERHILL-FASHION, 4-30 -- Paco Underhill, gathering retail
intelligence at a Banana Republic store. ``Righteous anger is very
much a part of my personal universe,'' he says. In a new book,
``Why We Buy: The Science of Shopping,'' Underhill, 47, reveals
that Americans walk the way they drive - on the right - and so they
habitually veer to the right aisles of a store. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2 --
NITEOUT-CHRIS-EIGEMAN, 4-30 -- Chris Eigeman, the frowning
embodiment of New York angst in the sitcom ``It's Like, You Know,''
during a late- night search for a French door at Home Depot.
Eigeman, 34, though an acerbic cynic in front of the camera, off
camera seems more like a complacent yuppie in an upscale sitcom. In
``Metropolitan,'' they had a name for people like him: Urban Haute
Bourgeoisie. (Rebecca Cooney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LONDON -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2 --
LONDON-PARTY-GIRL, 4-30 -- Tara Palmer-Tomkinson, London columnist,
at a recent party. Her column - originally titled ``The Social
Diary of Tara Palmer-Tomkinson,'' but now, for some reason, called
``Yah!'' - has made the whippet-thin 27-year-old one of this city's
best-known faces. ``A lot of people think I am the person I write
about,'' she says. ``They don't realize that half the time I'm
putting myself down.'' (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- April 30, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-CLINTON,
4-30 -- President Clinton leaves the podium after addressing
reporters on Friday at the White House. Clinton announced that he
is inviting a broad range of leaders to a White House strategy
session to discuss ways of avoiding violence in the nation's
schools. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- April 30, 1999 -- HKN-COACH-MAURICE, 4-30 --
Carolina Hurricanes head coach Paul Maurice behind the bench during
their game 4 loss to the Bruins. Just turned 32, the baby-faced
Maurice has established seniority as the youngest head coach in the
National Hockey League. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- April 30, 1999 --
AMAZON-EXCHANGE-BOS, 4-30 -- Steig Leschley, president of
Exchange.com, an Internet company that brings together buyers and
sellers of rare books and old music recordings, with some items
recently on sale. After struggling to get his company off the
ground, this week was sweet revenge for Leschly. Amazon.com, the
nation's largest Internet bookseller, said it will acquire the
company for a reported $200 million in stock. The move will make
Leschly a multimillionaire in barely seven months. (Janet
Knott/Boston Globe Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) QUINCY, Mass. -- April 30, 1999 -- ONLINE-ARTIST-2-BOS,
4-30 -- Digital Artist Carmin Karasic with one of her artworks on
the Web she titled ``Coderush.'' Over the past four years Karasic
has transformed herself from a white-collar programmer into a
free-spirited artist pioneering work in the wild frontier of
cyberspace. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 2 --
VETS-SYNDROME-COX-B&AMP;W-2, 4-30 -- Maj. Randy Hebert while serving as
a combat engineer in the Persian Gulf war. The Department of
Veterans Affairs is trying to determine why amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis, also known as Lou Gehrig's disease, which has afflicted
Hebert, may have stricken more than 40 other Persian Gulf war
veterans; a rate experts say is several times higher than the
disease's normal incidence. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) EMERALD ISLE, N.C., -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 2 -- VETS-SYNDROME-COX-B&AMP;W-1, 4-30 -- Former Marine Maj. Randy
Hebert, with his wife Kim and children Nicole and Kyle, at his
home. The Department of Veterans Affairs is trying to determine why
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, also known as Lou Gehrig's disease,
which has afflicted Hebert, may have stricken more than 40 other
Persian Gulf war veterans; a rate experts say is several times
higher than the disease's normal incidence. (Chuck Liddy/Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 2 -- HAITI-TROOPS-COX-2, 4-30 --U.S. Army PFC Allen Watts mans
a M249 Squad Automatic Weapon while guarding a visit to village by
dentists with the U.S. Navy on the outskirts of the Haitian
capital. Col. Charles Morris, the commander of U.S. troops in
Haiti, said during a recent interview that American troops in Haiti
are facing increasing dangers because of growing instability and
violence. (Lannis Waters/The Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- April 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 2 -- HAITI-TROOPS-COX-1, 4-30 -- U.S. Navy medical personnel
work on patients at an outdoor dental clinic during a visit to the
village on the outskirts of the Haitian capital. Col. Charles
Morris, the commander of U.S. troops in Haiti, said during a recent
interview that American troops in Haiti are facing increasing
dangers because of growing instability and violence. (Lannis
Waters/The Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- April 30, 1999 -- RUSSIA-INVEST, 4-30 -- Some
of the American products sold in Russia. The economic turmoil last
summer in Russia confirmed American companies' worst fears that the
nation is too unstable. But a number of Western multinationals
including Caterpillar, Nestle, Lucent Technologies and others, have
since decided to go deeper rather than pull out. (Igor
Vishnyakov/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- April 30, 1999 -- STARTOYS-AZR-2, 4-30 --
Opee, top, and Darth Maul; two of the new characters in George
Lucas' s Star Wars prequel, ``Star Wars: Episode I - The Phantom
Menace.'' The new Star Wars playthings, manufactured by Hasbro,
will cost $7 and can talk to each other providing you spend another
$30 on a reader. (The Arizona Republic/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- April 30, 1999 -- STARTOYS-AZR-1, 4-30 --
Stores on Monday will begin selling the new action figures from the
upcoming movie, ``Star Wars: Episode I - The Phantom Menace.'' The
toys will include the characters Jar Jar Binks, left, on his Kaadu,
and the evil Darth Maul. The new Star Wars playthings will cost $7
and can talk to each other providing you spend another $30 on a
reader. (The Arizona Republic/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
