u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     04-30 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PIN PATTER _ BRONCOS' STAR GOES BOWLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Terrell Davis showed up at Bryant Park in Manhattan
on cue Friday afternoon. About 100 children, and a number of
noontime diners, cheered as Davis, the Denver Broncos' All-Pro
running back, hopped up on the elevated bowling lanes that had been
constructed for a clinic as part of the Professional Bowlers
Association's first outdoor championship Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Davis joined Walter Ray Williams Jr., the 1998 PBA player of the
year, and Chris Barnes, the tour's rookie of the year. He addressed
the young students about studying and working hard, being
persistent and respecting one another. They listened and fidgeted.
This was too nice a day to sit still too long for speeches. They
wanted to watch Davis bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is an avid bowler, though admittedly not a super bowler.
``If I didn't play football, I would have tried to become a
bowler,'' he said. ``We have a league we start up every year with a
lot of guys on the team. Players are addicted. When I retire,
bowling might be my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That provided a neat transition into the topic of the hour in
sports: John Elway's retirement announcement Sunday in Denver.
Davis said he knew when last season ended that Elway wasn't coming
back. ``To be honest, I didn't give him much chance of coming back
last year,'' Davis said. ``I knew this year that this was
definitely going to be his last season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos are ending one era and beginning another. ``This is
a huge challenge for us, an uphill struggle for us,'' Davis said.
``It's one thing I never wanted to see, but it's inevitable. I
don't want to see him go, but I think it's the right time for him.
People had to be prepared to live life without John. I'm not
prepared, but I have no choice, so I'll make the necessary
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a sentiment in New York, percolating just below the
surface, that the Jets, who lost to Denver in last season's
conference championship game, are somehow the heirs apparent to the
Elway-less Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a strong squad,'' Davis said of the Jets. ``But I
don't think a team like the Jets should be looking at us and
saying, `All right, Denver's out of the way and we've got easy
sailing.' You have a lot of teams out there. Jacksonville is
strong, Pittsburgh's coming back up, Seattle's going to be strong.
Just don't look at us and focus on the wrong thing. The team you're
not looking at is the dude who's going to hit you in the side of
the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis added: ``Losing John, we're going to lose a lot; I'm not
going to lie to you. I just think it will be a different kind of
team with a different chemistry. I think we will be a very great
team. The team is still going to be good, because we had core
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said when he returns to Colorado, these football-related
issues will become dwarfed by the events that have shaken the
nation and put a new emphasis on young people and family. Davis was
in Washington last week, testifying before a task force for youth
sports and recreation. He was trying to persuade the government to
help refurbish playing fields and recreation centers.
</P>
<P>
   While in Washington, he watched the horrible news coming out of
Littleton, Colo. For the next 24 hours he and Sara Murphy, who runs
his foundation, brainstormed about a way the foundation could help.
Davis flew to Denver and went to the hospital where some of the
wounded Columbine High School students were taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to even describe,'' he said of his visit. ``It was
just so sad, man. These were kids who hadn't done anything to
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, called Terrell Davis Salutes Kids, focuses on
developing a range of after-school programs. Davis wants to bring
Pop Warner football to Denver in the middle schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that maybe we could do a fund, but then I saw where
there were millions of funds already out there,'' Davis said.
``What can you do that's unique but that still gives back to the
kids, without seeming like you're doing it just because you want
publicity. Throwing money at projects is easy. How do you put time
in with these kids? I spoke to a lot of students after the
shooting. When they start healing, maybe that's when I can start
being involved.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how Terrell Davis left it. On this bright, sunny
afternoon in Manhattan, Davis, who turns 27 in October, cut through
a midtown crowd and signed a few more autographs. Saturday he
returns to a sports world without John Elway, a business world with
a fledgling foundation and a state desperately in need of
inspiration.
</P>
</TEXT>
