<SLUG> BC-NJ-SCHOOLS-SCARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. TOWN SHUTS SCHOOLS AFTER E-MAIL THREAT OF MAYHEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILLSBOROUGH TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ Friday may have been a perfect
spring day, but 6-year-old Cynthia Ditunnariello and her friends
weren't going anywhere near the candy-cane-colored jungle gym that
beckoned from across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to get killed,'' said Cynthia, explaining why
her mother was forcing her to play Friday in the parking lot of
their garden apartment complex. ``There are bad people there trying
to hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the distant purr of a lawn mower, the playground and
the adjacent middle school were eerily quiet Friday as students and
teachers stayed away and police officials continued to search
frantically for the author of an e-mail message that promised
mayhem at the school and prompted widespread hysteria in this
central New Jersey suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we think what happened in Colorado was bad, wait until you
see what happens at HMS on Friday,'' read the message _ using the
initials for Hillsborough Middle School _ that was sent to the home
computers of at least five students Wednesday night, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   After word of the threat spread Thursday, the school was emptied
of students, bomb-sniffing dogs were dispatched and police officers
swept through classrooms. But as of Friday night, nothing untoward
had been found. Neither had the person who had sent the nebulous
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without having a crystal ball, it's safe to say that it's
probably a teen-ager and it's probably a prank,'' said Hillsborough
Police Chief Robert Gazaway on Friday afternoon during a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schools Superintendent Robert Gulick, who ordered that
the district's seven schools shut Friday, said they would not
reopen until ``the emergency'' had passed. That move that seemed to
please most parents and students in this expanding town of 40,000,
about 50 miles southwest of from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Although her two children are elementary school students,
Johanna Latocha said she was plagued by the fear that a
grudge-holding gunman might bypass the middle school and go
straight to her children's school nearby, seeking revenge on a
former teacher. ``You never know, some crazy person could just be
lurking out there,'' said Mrs. Latocha, 33, nervously watching
Jake, 7, and Jessica, 8, as they wrestled with fast-melting ice
cream cones. ``I'm so afraid for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Neuweiler, an eighth-grade science teacher, stood in the
middle school's deserted parking lot and tried to fight back tears.
As word of the e-mail message spread from classroom to classroom
Thursday morning, she recalled, many of her students began to panic
and cry. ``I know I need to be strong for the young ones,'' she
said sobbing, ``but this is too much.''
</P>
<P>
   All across the region Friday, the specter of school violence
seemed to be jangling nerves in normally placid communities. In
Cheektowaga, N.Y., students at the middle and high schools were
sent home early after a letter referring to the Littleton, Colo.,
massacre was sent to the principal. In Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., a
13-year-old eighth grader was arrested after writing that he wanted
to ``kill the whole school.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Piscataway, eight Rutgers University students shooting a
film were arrested because they were wearing long black trench
coats and carrying BB guns as props.
</P>
<P>
   In Hillsborough, where horse farms and apple orchards have
recently given way to look-alike housing developments, the low
crime rate and the fact that many people leave their doors unlocked
were all the more reason to be terrified. ``They said it couldn't
happen in Colorado either, but it did,'' said Lillian Rios, 26, a
mother of three school-age children.
</P>
<P>
   School officials seemed to agree with that assessment. Even
before Wednesday's menacing e-mail message, they were preparing
their students for the new era of school-based terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the middle school principal established a new
emergency procedure to deal with Littleton-style incidents.
Although the authorities would not offer details, 11-year-old Eric
Sutherlin described the so-called lock-down mode as follows: ``When
they announce a special code on the intercom, everyone has to get
away from the door and the windows, and get down on the floor,'' he
said. In much the same way as duck-and-cover drills during the Cold
War, students were told that by cowering under their desks, they
might minimize harm from a deadly assault.
</P>
<P>
   All last week at Hillsborough High School, students were
instructed to notify school officials of overheard threats,
bomb-making bluster and even odd behavior. The announcements,
several students said, came daily over the school's public address
system. ``They warned us that anyone who acts strange will get
suspended and the only way they can return to school is to get a
note from a psychiatrist,'' said Melissa Morgan, a ninth grader.
She said talk of death and guns was especially frowned upon.
</P>
<P>
   Most students seemed to agree that the precautions were
warranted. Matt Clark, 15, a ninth grader, said that since the
shooting in Colorado, his head had been swirling with bloody
images. ``I'm always afraid that someone is carrying a gun,'' he
said. ``These days I don't trust people I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the streets that weave through housing developments with
names like Hillsborough Village and Majestic Knolls, it wasn't easy
finding children outdoors Friday. Some parents took their children
to the Bridgewater Commons Mall, while a few teen-agers hung out at
the Taco Bell on Route 206, the community's commercial spine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
