<HEADER>
A0206 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS &LR;      04-30 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Moises Alou, who had surgery in February to repair a torn
anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee, said Friday his
rehabilitation remains on schedule for an August return to the
Astros.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to rush myself to play before I'm ready,'' said
Alou, who made his first appearance with the Astros since last
October prior to Friday's game with the Florida Marlins at Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure I'm 100 percent,'' he said. ``My doctors
won't let me come back. Things are going great. Right now things
are on schedule, if not ahead of schedule. I'm supposed to be back
sometime in August.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou, 32, has remained distant from the Astros since he fell off
a treadmill during a workout in the Dominican Republic. He went
onto the disabled list prior to the start of spring training and
had surgery a week after the initial diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   He has been doing rehab six days a week in nearby Fort
Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros in town for a three-game series, Alou couldn't
resist coming to the ballpark Friday. He sat in the clubhouse
wearing a black brace on his left knee and watching television with
several teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me,'' Alou said. ``As soon as I saw the guys
coming (to Miami), I had to come see my friends. I miss being here.
It just makes me want to come back sooner. I know I can't play
right now. I just have to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou, a key contributor in the Astros' franchise-record 102-win
season a year ago, finished third in voting for National League
Most Valuable Player after a season in which he had 38 home runs,
124 RBIs and a .312 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes he can come back from the fourth major
injury of his career and help the team over the final two months of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I am in the prime of my career coming off a great
year, and I was looking forward to an even better year,'' Alou
said. ``This is a big blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou, who has an offseason home in Weston, Fla., a suburb of
Fort Lauderdale, said he has tried not to keep up with how the
Astros are doing in the standings or watch games on television.
</P>
<P>
   Among the games he has watched: Jose Lima's start in San
Francisco on April 14 and Jeff Bagwell's three-homer game April 21
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The more he watches, Alou says, the more he misses the game.
</P>
<P>
   When he first hurt his knee, Alou did not think the injury would
cause him to miss an extended period. He flew to Houston for a
magnetic resonance imaging test, which revealed the torn ligament.
</P>
<P>
   The first few days after learning he would miss five to six
months were especially difficult, Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week was real bad,'' Alou said. ``I never thought it
was this bad. When they told me, my face fell to the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou has been on the disabled list seven times during his career
for an assortment of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1990, he suffered a torn rotator cuff in his right
shoulder while diving back to first base on a pickoff attempt in
the Dominican winter league.
</P>
<P>
   That forced him to have surgery and miss the 1991 season.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he suffered a dislocated left ankle and a
broken leg when his spikes caught in the AstroTurf as he made a
quick stop after rounding first base. He missed the final three
weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through this so many times,'' Alou said. ``Of all my
surgeries or injuries, I would rank this the third-worst.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the Astros continue to take a cautious approach
with Alou's rehab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put a timetable on it, because it's a serious
injury and there's no sense creating expectations,'' general
manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``The fact is historically the
best-case scenario for an injury like this is coming back in five
to six months. That's how I'm playing it. In my mind, if we have
him back for the month of September I'll be extremely happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens a little quicker, so be it. But I don't think
August is out of the question. But certainly it isn't going to be
before then.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida left fielder Cliff Floyd, who began the season on the
disabled list with a sprained medial collateral ligament in his
left knee, went through rehab workouts with Alou for several weeks
and was impressed with his dedication to return to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks good, real good,'' said Floyd, who was activated
earlier this week and started Friday against the Astros. ``He's
been working hard. His leg is a little weak, but he doesn't think
it will take as long as they say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
