<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-HARTFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT GOVERNOR, TALKING SUIT, VENTS IRE AT KRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. -- Robert Kraft has turned overnight from
community savior to Public Enemy No. 1 here.
</P>
<P>
   With carefully chosen words that dripped with scorn and
disbelief, Governor John G. Rowland said Friday evening it looked
as if the New England Patriot's owner had apparently used
Connecticut in a bid to get a better stadium deal elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let him peddle that this was the wrong site,'' Rowland
said at a state capitol news conference. ``Don't buy this
scheduling difficulties and location stuff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said Connecticut will sue the Kraft family and
``presumably'' the National Football League over the breakdown of
the deal to move to a $374 million publicly financed stadium in
downtown Hartford, after Massachusetts legislators worked this week
to craft a still-undone deal to help Kraft build a new stadium in
Foxboro, next to the current Patriots home.
</P>
<P>
   State lawyers will investigate, Rowland said, whether Kraft
spoke with Massachusetts politicians and others about a new stadium
plan. ``Connecticut is not going to be used as leverage against
other stadium proposals,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always looking for a way out,'' Rowland said, adding
that Kraft never appeared convincingly enthusiastic about the move.
</P>
<P>
   The year-long negotiations reached a denouement on Thursday,
Rowland said, when he gave Kraft 24 hours to ``fish or cut bait.''
Kraft asked for an extension of 30 to 60 days, but Rowland
declined. The Patriots owner had until Sunday to pull out without
financial penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants hired by Kraft are said to have told him the stadium
site on the Connecticut river had environmental and other problems
that could delay completion of the facility a year beyond its
anticipated opening, into 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Friday, about 4:30 p.m., Kraft called Rowland to pull the
plug. The decision appears to have stunned the governor. ``No one
walks away from a $374 million proposal because the plan might
happen a year later then expected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who on Thursday had said that ``failure is not an
option,'' defended his efforts to lure the Patriots to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure on my part is not an option'' Rowland said. ``But
unfortunately, on Mr. Kraft's part, it is an option.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's anger was echoed by House Speaker Moira K. Lyons,
who said, ``I am extremely disappointed in the Patriots and the
lack of good faith and good principles shown by the Kraft family.''
Lyons said she believed that Rowland ``did everything he could to
try to accommodate the team for the benefit of Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere in the ornate capitol turned funereal, as state
officals absorbed the news they had been abandoned by a suitor on
whom they had pinned much of Hartford's hope for revitalization.
</P>
<P>
   When Hartford scribe, Mark Twain, said that the reports of his
death were exaggerated, he was not making a prediction for the
Hartford Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Mike Peters was openly disdainful of Kraft. ``I shook
hands with Mr. Kraft eight weeks ago and he said he would be here
in 2002,'' Peters recalled. ``I'll probably never talk to him
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters said Hartford might join a law suit against the NFL.
``It's almost like defamation of city,'' Peters said. ``We are
going to send a loud message to the NFL and other communities that
have been abused that we shouldn't put up with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Kevin Sullivan said that Kraft's decision was
akin to losing a prize fight. ``Dealing with a major sports
franchise is not for the meek or faint of heart. It is a loss for
Hartford, a loss for Connecticut,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate leader said he sensed the deal had soured after NFL
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue visited Massachusetts' political and
business leaders recently.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Hartford, disappointment was mixed wth a
jilted sense of ``good riddance.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Clements, 46, a stagehand and lifelong Hartford resident,
shouted ``go home Pats!'' as somber state officials gathered at the
capitol across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no match to begin with. Let the Patsies say where
they are,'' Clements said. ``I just can't see where the governor
warrants giving that kind of money to a guy who's got more money
than the Vatican.''
</P>
<P>
   As a father of three and a grandfather of five, Clements said he
would prefer to see the stadium money spent on education and road
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
