<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA WORKING TO UPGRADE SHUTTLE FLEET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., _ Without a replacement ship on the
horizon, NASA managers have begun to accelerate plans for upgrades
to keep the venerable space shuttles launching for at least another
decade and potentially for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle fleet quietly marked the 18th anniversary of flight
operations in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we continue to maintain them as well as we have up
to this point, as long as we continue its evolution, this vehicle
could fly another 20 or 30 years,'' said Jim Halsell, an Air Force
test pilot and shuttle commander who is preparing for a fifth
mission in December.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's staunchest proponents believe that with the
blessing of White House policy makers and major alterations that
bolster safety and lower operating costs, the delta-winged ships
could fly for some time.
</P>
<P>
   NASA plans to spend $100 million in upgrades each year, but
would need a formal directive from the White House to expand that
program. A decision could be made next year.
</P>
<P>
   They may have little choice. A $1 billion effort by the space
agency and Lockheed Martin to offer an alternative to the shuttle
has not unfolded smoothly. The development of the VentureStar, a
technically challenging single-stage-to-orbit, reusable rocket has
been delayed. Early this year, its development team delayed until
mid-2000 the test of a suborbital prototype called the X-33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak officially for the administration, for what the
national space policy should be, but I can tell you as a practical
matter, it's prudent for the shuttle program to assume that for the
next few years we will be it,'' said Elric McHenry, who manages the
upgrade effort from NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a panel of experts enlisted by the National Research
Council endorsed efforts to upgrade the shuttle. In its report, the
research council called it premature for NASA to proceed with a
sweeping change of the launch propulsion system that would replace
the shuttle`s twin solid fuel rocket boosters. Many engineers favor
replacement of the solid rockets with a liquid fuel rocket that
could make an automated landing after being jettisoned by the
shuttle early in its ascent.
</P>
<P>
   At the present time, the cost of developing the ``liquid fly
back booster'' system, at least $5 billion, is not justified, the
research council concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The primary mission for the shuttle is the assembly of the
international space station, a six-year task initiated late last
year. The shuttle likely will support the station's cargo and crew
rotation needs for much of the 10-year operations period that
follows. Demands for the shuttle could rise if Russia withdraws
from the station partnership in response to financial problems or
political considerations.
</P>
<P>
   McHenry and others involved in the shuttle upgrade effort
gathered at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida last week to
preview the latest in shuttle improvements _ a $200 million
electronic cockpit display system that is to fly aboard the shuttle
Atlantis late this year.
</P>
<P>
   Its multicolored displays could replace many of the 2,000
mechanical dials, gauges and switches that protrude from every
surface of the shuttle crew cabin. The glass cockpit, as the new
display system is called, is already standard on the latest
commercial airliners, such as Boeing's 777, and new military
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The new display system will allow each shuttle crews to
customize the cramped cockpit for each mission. Once a crew reaches
space it can electronically store the displays needed for the
launch phase and replace them with those needed just for the
orbital phase. Flashing but silent displays with yellow and red
graphics will alert the astronauts to potential mechanical
problems, replacing a distracting system of audible alarms that
often did not reveal specifically which systems were in difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, when engineers were developing the shuttle a quarter
of a century ago, they were pioneering innovations in flight
control, rather than embracing them.
</P>
<P>
   As Columbia lifted off on the inaugural shuttle mission April
12, 1981, it helped to pioneer another now standard feature on
modern aircraft: fly-by-wire, or computer managed flight control
systems.
</P>
<P>
   McHenry said forthcoming upgrades likely will be focused on
furnishing additional external shielding to protect the shuttle
from micrometeoroids; improving the electrical power generation
system; and installation of more capable flight computers.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers plan to lace the shuttles with a network of fiber
optic sensors that can tip off ground teams as well as shuttle
crews to failing components that do not present a hazard but
require maintenance or replacement once a ship lands.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle managers also will consider replacement of the outdated
hydraulic power system with one that relies on electro-mechanical
devices and the installation of a new orbital steering system. In
each instance, the use of highly toxic chemicals would be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency believes the shuttles are robust enough to
justify the new investments.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the orbiters was designed for 100 flights. Columbia and
Discovery are the fleet leaders with 25 flights each. Endeavour has
logged 13 and Atlantis, 20.
</P>
<P>
   Challenger was lost on its 10th mission during a 1986 launch
accident that killed seven crew members.
</P>
<P>
   The airframes, which undergo regular exhaustive inspections,
have held up well, said McHenry.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 safety modifications followed the loss of
Challenger, most notably the redesign of the solid-fuel booster
that triggered the disaster. Just a few years ago, the orbiters
were upgraded so they could dock with Russia's Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   As that mission was completed, the ships were modified again so
they could assemble the new space station. One of the changes
successfully introduced last year was a new external fuel tank that
shaved nearly 8,000 pounds from the shuttle's launch weight.
</P>
<P>
   Safety assessments commissioned by NASA place the odds of a
shuttle loss during the risky launch phase of flight at one in 438,
a considerable improvement over the one in 70 chance of loss in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the new safety margin was derived from a $1 billion
upgrade of the shuttle's reusable rocket engines. When it is
complete next year, the engines will sport better turbopumps and
combustion chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think this is old technology,'' said Chris Singer,
NASA's chief engineer for the shuttle's rocket engines. ``But it's
modern, cutting edge. Reusable rocket engines are unheard of
outside of this program.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
