<HEADER>
A0223 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT &LR;      04-30 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SEEING MILOSEVIC, RUSSIAN HINTS AT PROGRESS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ A Russian envoy said Friday night that he
had made some progress toward a peace settlement after another six
hours of talks with President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, but
NATO officials were dismissive.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian negotiator, former Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin, told Russian reporters that he had made ``solid
progress'' in his second meeting with Milosevic in just over a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that leaders of the NATO member countries will take
that progress seriously, but I cannot say that they will make a
positive decision,'' Chernomyrdin told the Russian news agency,
ITAR-Tass. Asked whether NATO troops would be part of an
international force to police a Kosovo settlement, Chernomyrdin
replied, ``Let's talk about that later.''
</P>
<P>
   Details were nonexistent. But the progress that Chernomyrdin
spoke about appeared to be a Yugoslav willingness to allow
monitoring of Kosovo by lightly armed U.N. observers from NATO
countries like Italy and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin has made it clear from the start that any
settlement would include armed observers, not simply unarmed
civilians as Belgrade first demanded.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with United Press International released Friday,
Milosevic proposed a U.N. peacekeeping force armed only for
self-defense, and the return of refugees in exchange for a halt to
military activities.
</P>
<P>
   He said that NATO would have to withdraw its troops on the
Kosovo border with Albania and Macedonia, and that he would reduce
Yugoslav forces to as few as 11,000 men from what he said was about
100,000 currently.
</P>
<P>
   However, an armed U.N. presence by itself falls well short of
NATO demands for a force with NATO troops at its core.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright responded, ``I think we are not anywhere near a serious
proposal,'' Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   A Yugoslav Foreign Ministry spokesman, Nebojsa Vujovic, hinted
Friday at some change in the Yugoslav position. He said Belgrade
would accept a solution that passed the U.N. Security Council,
where the United States, Britain, France, Russia and China have
vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Yugoslavia would accept a Security Council decision
that any international monitors for Kosovo be armed, Vujovic said:
``Russia and China are members of the U.N. Security Council too,
and if the U.N. Security Council would move in that direction it
would be supported.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the news conference he again chose not to repeat
Belgrade's earlier line that only unarmed civilians from non-NATO
countries could participate. ``We would never accept military
occupying forces,'' he said, a clear reference to NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials have said that they do not regard the United
Nations as an occupying force, and even before the bombing, the
Serb legislature had approved the idea of a U.N. presence in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Vujovic, pressed later on CNN, stopped dropping hints and
retreated to the previously stated public position. ``We are
speaking about a U.N. international mission, unarmed and
civilian,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, however, expects nearly all Serb forces to be
withdrawn, replaced by a NATO-centered force and a newly formed
local police responsible to newly elected local authorities, not to
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is also talking of an ``international protectorate'' for
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia, meanwhile, insists upon retaining full sovereignty and
says that the bombing must stop before serious negotiations take
place, and that NATO must withdraw its troops from neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
   So there seems quite a long way to go before any settlement is
reached, but there also seems to be new eagerness in both Belgrade
and Washington to use Chernomyrdin to help find one.
</P>
<P>
   While the bombing and the negotiations go on, so far on opposing
tracks, Milosevic pursues his own internal solution to the Kosovo
crisis, and the exodus of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo continues.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has also pointed to an agreement on Wednesday by an
ethnic Albanian leader, Ibrahim Rugova, and the Serb president,
Milan Milutinovic, to set up a temporary executive in Kosovo and
negotiate a wide autonomy for the province. Foreigners would be
invited to observe the talks, but only as guests.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic called the agreement ``the first joint victory for the
Serbs and the Albanians in the search for peace.'' NATO insists
that Rugova is not a free actor and is being manipulated by
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The official Yugoslav press agency, Tanjug, said that Milosevic
and Chernomyrdin ``expressed their joint commitment in favor of a
peaceful solution to the problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
