<HEADER>
A0231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      04-30 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OWNER SPURNS HARTFORD STADIUM DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft walked away
from the richest stadium deal ever in professional sports Friday, a
joyous victory for Massachusetts sports fans but a devastating blow
to Hartford's revitalization dreams.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Governor John G. Rowland, Kraft explained that
the team did not believe Connecticut could finish the proposed $374
million by 2002 as promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we have not seen sufficient evidence to give us
adequate assurance that the planned Hartford stadium can be ready
for the beginning of 2002 season on the terms we contemplated in
our agreement,'' Kraft said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut had struggled to determine how much money and how
much time it would take to prepare the heavily polluted site for
construction. Under his deal with Connecticut, Kraft was free to
back out without penalty by Sunday if he concluded the stadium
could not be completed on time or within budget.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's consultants told him Thursday that it would likely be
2003 at the earliest before the Patriots could play in the new
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, who less than 24 hours earlier stood alongside Kraft
and expressed confidence the Hartford deal would go through,
denounced the Patriots' pullout and threatened to sue the Kraft
family and the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one walks away from a $374 million plan because a schedule
not might hit the exact date he would like to see it happen,'' he
said. ``We'll find out soon enough what the real reason was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let the fear of litigation prevent us from doing our
job,'' said Joseph Brown, an NFL vice president. `'In this case, we
went to Massachusetts to see if a viable alternative existed and to
help make one a reality. It was Mr. Kraft's decision to make.''
</P>
<P>
   The league said it expected to take up the alternative stadium
offer cobbled together earlier this week by Massachusetts when team
owners meet in Atlanta in late May.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's brief statement, which repeatedly praised Connecticut's
efforts over the past year, did not mention the Bay State's rival
bid. But most in Massachusetts thought the message was clear: the
Patriots would stay in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New England Patriots will be playing football in
Massachusetts, where they belong,'' said Governor Paul Cellucci
from California, where he was promoting Massachusetts to the film
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like winning a game in overtime,'' declared Senate
President Thomas F. Birmingham. ``It's a win for Patriots fans, the
state, and taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, who many argued drove the
Patriots into Connecticut's arms by blocking a bid last year to use
state funds to help the team build a new facility in Foxborough,
praised Kraft's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Kraft deserves an awful lot of credit for the
decision he made,'' Finneran said. ``Mr. Kraft is the first to
break a very discouraging _ and what I have said is an
inappropriate _ trend, and that deserves commendation.''
</P>
<P>
   All three Bay State leaders said there would be no problem
passing a bill to keep the team in Massachusetts before NFL owners
meet May 25. Birmingham said he expected the Senate to pass the
measure next week.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the agreement Birmingham, Cellucci, and Finneran
negotiated late Tuesday night, the state would provide $70 million
in funds for roads, sewers and other public improvements around a
new Foxboro Stadium. In return, Kraft would build a privately
financed $250 million stadium, with assistance from the NFL. The
Massachusetts plan would also require him to pay up to $1 million a
year to the state to offset the infrastructure costs.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Connecticut offered not only a taxpayer-funded
stadium, but also a host of benefits, including a promise that the
state would pick up the tab for any unsold luxury or club seats
over the next 30 years. Sports financing experts have said the
guarantees alone would have been worth more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply unprecedented,'' said Marc Ganis, head of
Sportscorp, a Chicago consulting firm specializing in stadium
development firm. ``That's bankable money the team could count on
for the next 30 years. The idea of walking away from that without
having a another deal firmly in hand is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Local business and political leaders said they were confident
Kraft wanted to keep the team in Massachusetts, but many were
stunned that he chose to terminate his deal in Connecticut before
lawmakers formally adopted a counterproposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really a sign that he is committed to his home state in
a way few of us could imagine,'' said former Democratic National
Committee chairman Paul Kirk to whom the NFL turned to orchestrate
a last-minute campaign to keep the team in Foxborough. ``He's put a
lot of trust in the state's political leaders and the business
community living up to their verbal commitments. And I expect all
the parties will.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL tapped Kirk because it wanted to stop the Patriots from
abandoning the nation's sixth-largest media market for Hartford,
ranked 27th. National broadcast revenues, which are split among all
owners, are the lifeblood of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL said it would not comment on Rowland's threat of a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft launched his search for a new stadium because Foxboro
ranks last in the league in the number of premium seats, an
important revenue for team owners. Foxboro Stadium has 39 luxury
suites and no club seats.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said a new stadium on land Kraft already owns in
Foxborough is likely to sport 100 to 125 luxury suites and 6,000 to
8,000 club seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business community's commitment to long-term sales of
luxury boxes is key,'' the source said. ``The Patriots cannot
afford to pay for their own stadium and keep a competitive team on
the field without luxury box sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources said that if Kraft accepts the Massachusetts deal, a new
Foxboro Stadium could be built by 2002, perhaps even 2001, because
the site does not suffer from the pollution woes of the property
offered by Rowland along the Connecticut River. Hartford's proposal
was also hampered by delays in arranging the relocation of a steam
plant and its corporate headquarters from the site.
</P>
<P>
   The aborted stadium was slated to be the centerpiece of
Adriaen's Landing, a billion-dollar redevelopment project that
Rowland and Hartford civic leaders hoped would revitalize the
ailing city. Those project, unveiled in May 1998, included a domed
stadium with at least 35,000 seats for UConn, but were greatly
modified when the Patriots agreed to relocate.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said the project would continue. ``The original
Adriaen's Landing project was very sufficient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft had agreed to invest $75 million in the project, building
a hotel, NFL entertainment complex, and fitness center. But a
carefully crafted contract, negotiated with the aid of his son
Jonathan, gave him the right to pull out by Sunday if he was
uncertain the stadium would be ready by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it slipped to 2003, who could tell if would slip to 2004,''
said one person familiar with contract. ``There was too much
risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
