<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0235 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODGUYS-SFCHRON &LR;      04-30 1604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODGUYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Bad Times at Good Guys
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (c) 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Take a consumer electronics chain. Give it attractive stores,
exciting new gadgets to sell like high-definition television,
well-trained staff, good prices, an Ivy League-educated CEO, a
great economy and what have you got?
</P>
<P>
   If you're Good Guys, which is headquartered in Brisbane, you've
got flat sales, three years of losses and a stock that's plunged
from a high of $29.25 in 1991 to $3.63 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything points to (the conclusion) that these guys should
be doing better than they are,'' said Douglas Gordon, an industry
analyst with NationsBanc Montgomery Securities in San Francisco.
``The question of why they're not doing well is one everybody in
the industry is asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Good Guys chief executive Robert Gunst, who has been with the
company 13 years, the past six as CEO, is throwing in the towel.
Gunst, who is described by those who know him as smart and well
liked, announced last week that he will resign at the end of June,
although he will remain a director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided it was probably time to bring somebody in who could
look at it with fresh eyes,'' said Gunst, who has a bachelor's
degree from Dartmouth College and an MBA from the University of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Good Guys Chief Financial Officer Dennis Carroll also
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers attribute part of the problem to stiff
competition from bigger rivals like Best Buy and Circuit City. Some
shoppers say its salespeople are too aggressive and that it takes
too long to complete a purchase. The company also has incurred
expenses from its store remodeling program, and its
renovation-related closures have hurt sales.
</P>
<P>
   But given all of the pluses, industry watchers say, the chain
should be doing better than it is.
</P>
<P>
   Good Guys, which started in 1973 as a single store in San
Francisco, was not alone in its lackluster performance until
recently.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, the consumer electronics sector was generally
anemic. Prices on staple items like video cassette recorders were
falling and there were no innovative products to pry open
consumers' wallets. Best Buy, a national chain that has just
started opening stores in the Bay Area, was believed to be on the
verge of going under.
</P>
<P>
   But all that has changed _ for some retailers more than others.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at Best Buy stores open at least a year, considered the
best gauge of a retailer's strength, jumped 13.5 percent in 1998
while total sales grew 21 percent to $10 billion. No.2 Circuit
City's sales at mature stores increased a healthy 8 percent last
year while total sales rose 17 percent to $9.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, sales at Good Guys stores open at least a year rose
just 3 percent in fiscal 1998 while total sales grew 4 percent to
$928.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's better than the revenue declines the company faced in
1997. But sales at mature Good Guys stores were also flat in the
first half of fiscal 1999, which ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings have been a disappointment, too. While its competitors
were pumping out hefty profits, Good Guys was hit last year with a
$9 million loss, its third consecutive year of red ink.
</P>
<P>
   And while the national chains open dozens of stores annually,
Good Guys opened only one new store last year. It also renovated
four in its current markets of California, Nevada, Washington and
Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Gunst believes Good Guys' problems are largely cyclical and that
trends are shifting in the company's direction as high-tech gadgets
like digital camcorders, HDTV and digital video disks finally
become popular among middle class consumers.
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly optimistic about HDTV because HDTV owners
usually want a high-end sound experience with their set. Instead of
just buying a VCR, like in the olden days, HDTV shoppers often pick
up a DVD player, a Dolby Digital receiver and high-end speakers to
boot. TVs are Good Guys' largest category, accounting for 35
percent of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of digital merchandise are growing fast at Good Guys, but
still make up a small percent of sales. ``It's offsetting
(declining prices of staples like VCRs), but it is not offsetting
enough,'' said Gunst.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Good Guys, which specializes in audio and video,
has missed out on strong sales of goods like kitchen appliances and
computer games that its rivals carry but Good Guys does not, Gunst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Market research shows that Good Guys ranks lower than its
competitors on convenience, probably because customers must wait
for larger items to be retrieved from a stock room instead of being
able to serve themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But for the new digital products, which require some education,
Good Guys is the place to shop, Gunst said. ``That's a disadvantage
we've had over the last decade that we think will be an advantage
over the next decade,'' when unfamiliar new products will be
driving business.
</P>
<P>
   Good Guys has worked hard to develop a reputation for offering
better quality merchandise and service.
</P>
<P>
   Store managers lead daily training sessions to educate sales
associates about new products and discuss strategies for keeping
shoppers happy. Staff keep copies of the Good Guys' 12 Principles
in their pockets, the first principle of which is to provide
outstanding customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Bonuses of everyone from store managers to the CEO are tied to
the results of shopper satisfaction polls.
</P>
<P>
   To further distinguish itself from its gray-walled,
linoleum-floored rivals, Good Guys is converting locations into
what it calls Audio/Video Exposition stores. The large, luxurious
Expos are decorated in light wood and feature comfortable living
room environments where consumers can try out TVs and stereos.
</P>
<P>
   Good Guys remodeled four stores last year into the new format,
which averages 28,000 square feet, compared to 15,000 to 25,000 for
older stores. This year, it plans to convert at least six stores
into Expos and open two new ones. Thirteen of its 79 stores are now
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at Expo stores are about 20 percent higher than at older
locations, although sales per square foot are lower since much of
the store is used as exhibition space, Gunst said.
</P>
<P>
   Build-out costs per foot are the same as older stores, since the
fixtures are still made of Formica _ they're wood grain instead of
gray in the Expo stores _ and wooden floors cost less in the long
run than tile and carpet since they never need to be replaced,
Gunst said.
</P>
<P>
   Good Guys also operates four so-called Wow Multimedia
Superstores, which adjoin Tower Records outlets. That way shoppers
can buy CDs with their boom boxes _ and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wow store in San Francisco's Stonestown Galleria, an
appearance by pop singer Jordan Knight attracted 2,000 teenagers
one recent morning. ``As far as I'm concerned, the store does
well,'' said Ron Weller, the mall's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The convenience issue aside, shoppers seem to like Good Guys. A
Consumer Reports survey of 6,300 consumers ranked it third among 10
audio-video purveyors, with high scores on selection and courtesy.
</P>
<P>
   Costco and Sam's Club, both warehouse clubs, came in slightly
higher on the strength of their low prices. Circuit City, which is
headquartered in Richmond, Va., and operates 560 stores, was ranked
fifth and Best Buy of Eden Prairie, Minn., with 315 stores, came in
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   But the survey, published last October, found another weakness
at Good Guys: aggressive sales pitches for extended
warranties. &UR;  &LR; That impression was seconded by a Bay Area shopper who
otherwise likes Good Guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to browse there and check out the latest gear, but I
feel there is terrific pressure to buy the warranty,'' said the
shopper, who did not want his name used. ``I guess they have to
sell them'' to make up for their fair merchandise prices.
</P>
<P>
   Gunst counters that, according to independent market research,
people who buy the warranties and do not use them are just as
satisfied as those who do not buy them. People who use their
warranties are the happiest of all.
</P>
<P>
   Gunst declined to say how much the contracts contribute to
profits. But in public filings, the company blamed a drop in
warranty income for thinner gross margins last year. Warranties
account for between 5 and 6 percent of company revenues, the
documents said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, Good Guys faces a new challenge by Best Buy,
which is opening its first six locations here this year. Two are
already operating, one in Santa Rosa and a Marin City store in a
new format that focuses on digital products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best Buy is a formidable competitor, there's no getting around
it,'' said Lewis Alton, managing partner of the San Francisco
investment bank L.H. Alton &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   But Gunst said Good Guys is holding its own against Best Buy in
Marin and other markets. ``When they open, they take some of the
commodity business from us, so we lose some sales dollars, but
frankly we don't loose a lot of profit dollars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Gunst noted that the Good Guys Web site will
begin selling products by the end of September. The site
( &LR; www.thegoodguys.com &LR; ) currently gets about 1 million hits a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest factor in Good Guys' immediate future will
be the anticipated surge in HDTV. Said Gunst: ``The big question is
how quickly is that going to come, and none of us know.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company is looking for a CEO with fresh ideas for
merchandising and presentation. ``People ask me, `What kind of
fresh ideas?''' said Gunst. ``I tell them if I knew I'd be
implementing them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
