u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-     04-30 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS DEADLINE NEARS, PATRIOTS REJECT HARTFORD MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Five months after the New England Patriots
announced a startling plan to move to Connecticut, the football
team said Friday it was walking away from the most lucrative
stadium deal in professional sports now that Massachusetts is
willing to pay to keep the team.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots executives attributed their decision to problems with
the site in downtown Hartford, which is now occupied by a steam
plant and is contaminated with coal tar and other toxins. But the
withdrawal came just three days after Massachusetts legislators,
after years of bitter and unproductive negotiations with the team's
owner, Robert Kraft, promised a subsidy of $70 million to help him
build a new stadium next to his current one at Foxboro, south of
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft's decision turned what had seemed a stunning coup into an
embarrassing and expensive fiasco for Connecticut officials, most
critically Gov. John Rowland, who had brokered the deal that would
have saddled taxpayers with the entire cost of the $375 million
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots canceled the contract with a curt notice to the
state at 4:30 p.m. Friday, just two days before a deadline that
allowed the team to back out without any penalty. Lawyers for the
Patriots had determined that if the team waited any longer, it
could be liable to the state for damages of as much as $100
million, according to a National Football League executive.
</P>
<P>
   Much about the team's future remains uncertain. An executive
close to the Patriots expressed disgust with the current
Massachusetts offer, which would require the team to finance the
entire cost of the stadium, while the state paid for new parking
lots, roads and other improvements. But clearly the team would like
to work something out. ``It's not an option _ it's our home,'' the
executive said. Patriots officials also said Kraft would consider
selling the team, having grown weary of the frustrating stadium
talks he has held with three states _ including a flirtation with
Rhode Island _ ever since becoming the team's fourth owner in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland at first had promised that the stadium site in the
Connecticut capital would be ready for play in 2001, but that
target had slipped to 2002. Then, consultants to Kraft told him
this week that there was a 50-50 chance the stadium would be
delayed at least another year. Team officials said that report
prompted their decision to cancel the contract.
</P>
<P>
   An official who works closely with Kraft said the team had
misgivings about the Hartford site as long ago as February, which
is the reason the exit clauses like the one exercised Friday were
built into the contract.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Rowland, Kraft said: ``The scope of this project
was a mountainous undertaking and much more complex than anyone
anticipated when our discussions originally began. We know that you
have exhausted every effort to meet the deadlines that have been
within your control, but it has become clear to us that the goal of
playing in a new stadium in Hartford by the year 2002 has a
significant degree of uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland angrily challenged the Patriots' explanation, saying he
believed the state had been used as a pawn by Kraft to extract a
deal from Massachusetts. ``No one walks away from a year's planning
and a $374 million package because of concerns of the schedule
being a little bit longer than usual,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford officials had envisioned the stadium as the centerpiece
of a revitalization project that was to include a hotel and
convention center, lifting a city that has suffered through years
of economic decline as manufacturers left and insurance companies
consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often said it's not just about football,'' Rowland said at a
somber news conference Friday night. ``It's about having pride,
it's about creating community spirit. We tasted that, and I think
that that taste is still with us. We're going to find and create
other opportunities and chances for Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   The team, which has played in the Boston area since its birth in
1959 as the American Football League's eighth franchise, now will
be eagerly courted by Massachusetts officials. Gov. Paul Cellucci
of Massachusetts said Friday night, ``The New England Patriots will
be playing in Massachusetts, where they belong.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Zimbalist, an economics professor at Smith College who is
a leading opponent of subsidized stadiums, said: ``You have to be
careful not to invest too much of your political and financial
resources in one of these deals. Rowland took none of the necessary
precautions to protect his state and his city.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland showed his bitterness at his news conference, held in
the same ornate room at the Capitol where legislators had donned
Patriots hard hats for the jubilant announcement Nov. 19 that the
team had agreed to move to Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always that feeling that Kraft was always looking
for a way out,'' he said. ``Everything always had a very cautious
tone. He was not doing somersaults and saying he can't wait to come
to Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor promised lawsuits against the team and the NFL,
which served as a midwife to the Massachusetts proposal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although it initially had voiced little concern about the
Connecticut deal, the league had grown worried in recent months
that by moving from the 6th-largest television market to the 27th,
the Patriots would jeopardize the league's standing to negotiate
with television networks.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland estimated the state had spent ``a few million dollars''
on evaluating the site. ``You can expect legal action, not only
with regard to the Kraft family but presumably with the NFL as
well,'' he said. ``I don't think we'll have any problem recovering
any of these damages.''
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general, Richard Blumenthal, said he would be
``moving aggressively and quickly to take any available action to
assert the state's legal claims and rights.'' Blumenthal asserted
that the NFL has been ``throwing its weight around in a way that
restrains competition and injures consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut politicians poured scorn on Kraft. The speaker of
the House of Representatives, Moira Lyons, a Democrat from
Stamford, condemned what she called ``the lack of good-faith
principles shown by the Kraft family.'' U.S. Sen. Christopher Dodd,
a Democrat, said the state ``gave its word and worked in good
faith, but that effort wasn't returned in kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, though, can expect to be showered with blame in coming
days, since he cut the deal in secret, then said that he would
stake his legacy on its success. Edward Marcus, chairman of the
Connecticut Democratic Party, said stadium preparations had cost
the state millions of dollars but added, ``What may be even more
important is the loss to our reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   On the darkest day of his political life, Rowland joked that he
is now an official New York Jets fan, and indicated that he never
gives up. When asked whether he plans to try to lure another team,
he said, ``I can assure you that I am not _ at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts legislators have promised to enact their offer
before May 25, when NFL owners are scheduled to discuss the
Patriots' stadium plans. Three-quarters of the owners must approve
any relocation by a franchise. Supporters of the Massachusetts plan
have said that if Kraft did not accept their proposal, they would
make their case directly to the other owners.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kirk Jr., a Boston lawyer and former Democratic National
Chairman who is leading the Massachusetts bid, had spent the week
begging businesses to sign up for luxury suites to help make the
deal more attractive to Kraft. On Friday night, Kirk was so
confident of the state's prospects that he said skyboxes now would
be ``first come, first served.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the Foxboro plan is not as handsome monetarily, the
Krafts never lost the emotional bond with Massachusetts,'' Kirk
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft hinted at his future plans and galled Connecticut
officials by using his termination letter to thank them for working
``so hard in this effort to help the Patriots remain a competitive
franchise in New England.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
