<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEAMSTERS-HOFFA-ART-6     04-30 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-HOFFA-ART-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFFA THE YOUNGER HOPES TO PUT TEAMSTERS' HOUSE IN ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In one of his first acts as Teamsters president,
James Phillip Hoffa hung a beloved oil painting of his father, a
colossus posing above a convoy of trucks while looking up toward
Mount Rushmore as if he belonged there.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a very great man _ I don't compare myself to
him,'' said Hoffa, who assumed the presidency of the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters 42 years after his father had.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, little more than a month after taking office, the
younger Hoffa still has a touch of
``I-can't-believe-this-happened'' amazement in his manner as he
sits in the office his father once used.
</P>
<P>
   But one hurdle is that many of the teamsters who worshiped his
father, despite his conviction on charges of fraud and jury
tampering, look to the 57-year-old son as the Second Coming and
expect him to perform some of the same wonders.
</P>
<P>
   In running the union from 1957 to 1971, James Riddle Hoffa _
through a blend of charisma, street smarts and strong-arm tactics _
tripled many truckers' salaries and nearly tripled the Teamsters'
membership, making it the nation's largest, strongest _ and
prosecutors said, most corrupt _ union in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Along with these high hopes, the younger Hoffa has had to
contend with opposite expectations. Many supporters of his nemesis,
the union's former president, Ron Carey, view Hoffa as the devil
incarnate, insisting that he is in bed with crooks and corporate
management and will never give the rank-and-file a fair shake.
</P>
<P>
   In his first few weeks on the job, Hoffa is proving neither
savior nor Satan. Instead, he appears to be simply going about his
job, struggling to unify and rebuild a deeply divided union that
has drifted rudderless for two years, ever since Carey was
sidelined by a campaign finance scandal that led to his ouster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's had time to do much so far,'' said Howie
Redman, president of Carey's old local in Queens, N.Y., which
represents 9,000 United Parcel Service workers. ``But he seems very
sincere in wanting to reach across and make sure the teamsters work
together and move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa's most urgent task is to restore unity to a union where
the Hoffa and Carey factions have resembled the Hatfields and
McCoys. Hoffa has been reaching out to the Carey wing _ even some
Carey supporters acknowledge this _ although he cannot resist digs
at Carey, whose 1996 victory over Hoffa was overturned because of
Carey campaign finance violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing what my predecessor did, raining retribution on
anyone who went the other way,'' said Hoffa, who used to be a labor
lawyer in Detroit. ``The union cannot be successful if it's
divided. We're pulling this thing together, saying, `I'm going to
work with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   But bitter divisions remain, including a power struggle at the
top of the 1.4-million-member union. Tom Pazzi, Hoffa's campaign
manager, who was widely expected to become the union's chief of
staff, appears to have lost out to Carlow Scalf, a Michigan
Teamster official.
</P>
<P>
   A federal election monitor asked an oversight board to
investigate Scalf after the monitor found evidence that he had
illegally helped funnel $30,000 in union money that had been given
out as raises to union officials back into the campaign coffers of
a local union official. Teamsters officials say Scalf did nothing
wrong, noting that the oversight board has not brought charges.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a pro-Carey union caucus, Teamsters for a
Democratic Union, maintains that Hoffa's lieutenants are
threatening to retaliate against Carey supporters who refuse to
support a Hoffa-backed candidate for union vice president in the
South. Hoffa's camp calls those charges political and intended to
weaken him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa is in many ways different from his father. He grew up in
suburban affluence, while his father left school to work at age 14
and organized his first strike at age 17. The younger Hoffa, a
graduate of the University of Michigan Law School, favors navy
blazers and double-breasted suits and speaks smoothly and quickly,
without the snarl or sarcastic anger of his father.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, his office seems frozen in his father's 1950s _
there is dark paneling, blue wall-to-wall carpeting and a bulky
wooden desk with the same blotter his father used.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the loyal son, he steadfastly insists that his father did
not have ties to the mobsters who plundered the union. Saying it
was a time to look forward and not back, he would not discuss what
law enforcement officials had told him about how his father
disappeared in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hoffa works 12-hour days doing the unglamorous blocking
and tackling that union leaders must do if they are intent on
protecting their members' living standards and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He has organized rallies and assigned bargaining experts to
strengthen the hand of 11,000 Northwest Air flight attendants who
have not received a raise since 1993. With a contract expiring May
31 for 12,000 truckers who haul new cars to dealers, he is
overseeing negotiations, speaking at rallies and firing up members,
all to pressure management into agreeing to a good contract.
</P>
<P>
   For Hoffa, the car-haul bargaining is a test of his mettle.
Taking a page from his father, who was famed for knowing when and
where to squeeze employers, he is threatening a strike that can
cripple car shipments and sales at a time when Detroit is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa has defiantly asserted that ``we're not going to do
anything like Carey.'' But letting wisdom trump pride, he has
followed one of Carey's most successful strategies: mobilizing
thousands of members to maximize pressure on management in contract
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Paff, national coordinator of the pro-Carey Teamsters for a
Democratic Union, said: ``The idea that he can go in and pound the
table and tell them who his dad was and the CEO is going to cry
uncle, that happens only in the movies. You have to have a bunch of
angry members and a strong organization on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, Hoffa is charting a different course
from Carey. In the 1970s and 1980s the Teamsters favored
Republicans, but Carey moved the union into the Democratic column,
making the Teamsters among the biggest contributors to Democratic
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, who describes himself as a ``progressive,'' accused Carey
of letting the Democrats take the Teamsters for granted. ``The one
thing we're not going to be is an ATM for the Democratic Party or
the Republican Party,'' he said. ``That's what happened to Ron
Carey _ he became an ATM machine for the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing Reps. Peter King and Jack Quinn of New York as
Republicans whom labor can work with, Hoffa said: ``We're going to
talk to Republicans. We're going to talk to Democrats. We're going
to be very bipartisan in our endorsements.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa wants the union to remain a big-money player in politics,
saying he hoped to make the Teamsters' political action committee
the nation's largest PAC _ it was the second largest in 1997 and
1998, spending a total of $8 million to the $14 million spent by
Emily's List.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build it into a powerful force that will speak out
for Teamster members and for all working people,'' Hoffa said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to tip his hand on a presidential candidate,
although he seemed in less of a rush than other union leaders to
endorse Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A big issue the Teamsters will use to gauge candidates is
whether they pledge to restrict Mexican trucks from hauling goods
north of the border. He said opening the border to Mexican
truckers, as the North American Free Trade Agreement calls for,
would cost thousands of Teamster jobs and would fill U.S. roads
with pollution-spewing trucks with poorly trained drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like to use the word litmus test, but cross-border
trucking is one of the most important issues facing the
Teamsters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, unlike Carey, plans to press the federal government to
end its supervision of the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, when the Teamsters agreed to government oversight to
settle a racketeering lawsuit, the union has spent more than $80
million to pay for an elaborate network of federal monitors. These
monitors have expelled scores of teamsters after finding they had
ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have indicated they are in no rush to end the
supervision because they are still finding wrongdoing, although on
a much smaller scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a meaningful, far-reaching dialogue with the
government about its future role in Teamster affairs,'' Hoffa said.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that most corrupt elements have already been weeded
out. ``I think it's as free of corruption as any great
institution,'' he said. ``Over 300 people have been thrown out of
this union over the past decade. This union is as clean as any
other international union and can take its rightful place in a
leadership role with anyone in organized labor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
