<HEADER>
A0252 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY01-COX     04-30 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley builds support in S.C.
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Vice President Al Gore may have certain
advantages as a native Southerner and the well-funded heir to Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But as resurgent South Carolina Democrats warmly welcomed Bill
Bradley to their annual party dinner Friday, they displayed a
conspicuous lack of enthusiasm for Gore's candidacy in dozens of
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has got the baggage that comes with the
Clinton administration. I believe that Senator Bradley is more
electable than Al Gore,'' said Al Holland, the Democratic chairman
in Lee County.
</P>
<P>
   And with Bradley buttons far more in evidence than those for
Gore, Dick Harpootlian, the state party chairman, said, ``No one
ought to take South Carolina for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is not without support in the Palmetto State.
A new poll for the state party showed that Gore still leads Bradley
by a wide margin among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Georgia, where the Democratic apparatus is
unofficially but firmly behind Gore, South Carolina appears more
receptive to Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's problems are compounded by what many party leaders
believe was a slight toward Gov. Jim Hodges, who upset an incumbent
Republican last year with little help from the vice president and
the national Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Democrats also want to give the state a greater say in
the presidential nominating process. They plan to hold the state's
primary on Feb. 26, 2000, even though the date violates national
party rules that prohibits states other than Iowa and New Hampshire
from selecting convention delegates before March.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley won frequent applause at the state's annual
Jefferson-Jackson fund-raising dinner by talking about the need to
rebuild trust in government and exhorting the crowd to ``dream
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, Bradley said, ``cannot afford to be small thinkers.
We have to think of the big answers.''
</P>
<P>
   He offered few specifics, and told reporters at a news
conference that he would not lay out a detailed agenda until the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   One topic on which the basketball Hall of Famer has been more
expansive is race, which he has pledged to make a focal point of
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question, Bradley said that flying the
Confederate battle flag over the South Carolina Capitol offends
many people. ``I would not fly it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of major issues at this point means Democrats are
evaluating Bradley's personality as much as his politics. Franklin
Ashley, a College of Charleston professor, said he was struck by
how funny Bradley was at a private meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Curry, a union leader in the Greenville area, said he
thinks Bradley's past basketball glory will attract political
support. Responding to the suggestion that Bradley lacks charisma,
Curry said, ``Yeah, but he was a great basketball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, in fact, entertained his audience Friday with stories
of his days as an Olympian and member of the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of Gore at Friday's event acknowledged that the vice
president has been slow to shore up his support in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he needs to get out there and define himself,'' said
Mary M. Greene, a lobbyist for the South Carolina Education
Association who sported a Gore button.
</P>
<P>
   Greene predicted that Gore's support would become more visible
``once he comes here and campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Harpootlian acknowledged that a poll taken for the state party
shows Gore with a wide lead over Bradley among Democratic voters.
But he said he detected ``a certain enthusiasm'' for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley is unwilling to write off the South, at least not at
this early date. He will visit four more Southern states before the
end of May, said deputy press secretary Tony Wyche.
</P>
<P>
   And he appears to be targeting African-Americans, a crucial
constituency in Democratic primaries in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley will meet with Alabama ministers on a tour of Birmingham
and Montgomery next week. ``Most of the clergy are
African-American,'' Wyche said.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever becomes the Democratic nominee will face a tough time in
South Carolina in the general election. No Democratic presidential
candidate has carried the state since Jimmy Carter in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
