<HEADLINE>
USC-UCLA TRACK MEET COULD BE A CLASSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA-USC track meet is back.
</P>
<P>
   The 66th meeting today figures to be a return to the classic
battles of the past rather than the lopsided affairs of the past
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The USC men lead the series, 38-27, but are seeking to end a
20-year losing streak to UCLA. Last year UCLA defeated USC 84-74 in
the closest match since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important to both sides is the adherence to
traditional dual meet scoring on 5-3-1 for first through third
place in lieu of the new NCAA international scoring that calls for
5-3-2-1, with only two athletes from each school scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reward people for just showing up,'' USC coach Ron Allice
said. ``Performance is not important, only the fact that you have
another body in the event.''
</P>
<P>
   Allice and UCLA coach Bob Larsen, among the Pacific-10
Conference's leading proponents of traditional scoring, agreed to
score today's meet under the old system.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had its 51-meet home-winning streak snapped in a 101-99
defeat to Florida earlier this season under international scoring,
which scores the relays 5-3 instead of 5-0. Florida needed only to
jog the meet's final event, the 1,600 relay, to secure the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In quadrangular meets, international scoring makes sense, but
in dual meets it's better to have to beat somebody,'' Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in recent years the UCLA men, 17th in the
Trackwire national rankings, are not heavy favorites against No. 2
USC. There has been speculation that Larsen might retire at the end
of the year after 15 seasons at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to analyze that after the high hurdles on
Saturday,'' Larsen joked.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' prospects hinge on senior sprinters Jerome Davis
and Charles Lee and key members of the Trojans' Pac-10-leading 400-
and 1,600-meter relays.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the defending NCAA 400 champion, also will run in the
200- and 400- meters. In the 1,600 relay at the Texas Relays
earlier this month, Davis led the Trojans to a 1999 collegiate best
3:02.89.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a former Cleveland High and Valley College standout, also
will run in the 100 and 200 today. Lee finished fourth in the 1998
NCAA championships in the 200 and is the Pac-10 Conference leader
at 20.53 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team has responded well when they are the favorites,''
Larsen said. ``Whether they spark even more as the underdog is hard
to say. We're going to have to win a lot of the close events to
stay in the meet. In some events, we won't even make them sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 2 UCLA women are seeking their 61st consecutive dual
meet victory since last losing to No.4 USC in 1992. The 100 will
highlight the women's competition, pitting UCLA sophomore Shakedia
Jones, the 1998 World Junior and Pac-10 champion, against USC's
Torri Edwards, the 1996 Pac-10 champion; Esi Benyarku, the 1997
conference champion, and freshman Angela Williams, the national
high school record-holder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
