<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-BILL01-COX     04-30 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-BILL01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas abortion foes gain ground, poll says
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans are evenly split on whether abortions
should be legal, but four-fifths of them believe that doctors
should have to contact the parents of a minor seeking one,
according to a recent Texas Poll.
</P>
<P>
   The answers to the broader question represent an increase in the
number of Texans who say they oppose abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five percent of the 1,003 Texans surveyed by telephone
between March 30 and April 17 described themselves as
``anti-abortion,'' 45 percent said they were ``pro-choice'' and the
remaining 10 percent were undecided. Three years ago, 52 percent of
respondents said they were pro-choice and 37 percent said they were
anti-abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The poll results show that many who identify themselves as
pro-choice support a parental notification law: 80 percent of the
survey respondents said they either ``strongly favor'' or ``favor''
such a measure. Only 11 percent said they were opposed. The margin
of error for the poll was plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Senate passed a parental notification measure in
March, and several bills are pending in the House State Affairs
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Texas want parents to be connected with their
little girls in these important decisions,'' said Chuck Anderson,
director of the Texas Christian Coalition. ``We need to connect the
laws with the will of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey didn't ask what the exceptions to the parental
notification law should be, which is the issue dominating debate in
the House.
</P>
<P>
   Courts have ruled that parental notification laws are legal only
if they include a ``judicial bypass.'' Under that exception, a girl
who doesn't want her parents to know about her abortion can seek a
court order certifying that she is mature enough to make the
decision herself, or that she has reason to fear that telling her
parents would put her in danger. The judicial bypass is designed in
large part to protect girls who have been sexually abused at home.
</P>
<P>
   At least 87 House members back a bill filed by Rep. Dianne White
Delisi (R-Temple) that would require parental notification with a
judicial bypass. The Senate's parental notification measure,
authored by Sen. Florence Shapiro (R-Plano) is virtually identical.
</P>
<P>
   But other House bills go beyond the judicial bypass. Legislation
filed by Rep. Patricia Gray (D-Galveston) would allow a girl to
notify another relative instead of a parent. It also would allow a
licensed mental health professional or a state social worker to
determine that a girl can make the decision without notifying her
parents or that telling them would put her in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Delisi bill describe it as a ``parental
rights'' measure, and argue that anything beyond a judicial bypass
impinges on those rights. But Gray and notification opponents fear
girls will resort to illegal abortions if faced with the prospect
of having to tell their parents or a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
