<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0262 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-ARCHDEACON-DERBY0     04-30 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ARCHDEACON-DERBY01 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baffert continues to baffle in humble, successful way
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Around Churchill Downs this week, he's had an
almost cult-like following.
</P>
<P>
   Early each morning the crowd would start gathering for him
outside the long, white Barn 33, where two large signs announce
this is where the last two Kentucky Derby winners _ Silver Charm in
1997, Real Quiet in 1998 _ were stabled.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long for the crowd to swell to 70 or 80 people.
Sportswriters and TV crews wait for his usual mix of wisecrack and
wisdom. Fans want his autograph. A pair of exercise riders wait for
his training strategy, a trio of millionaire owners linger to hear
his assurances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There he is,'' gasped an elderly woman who was part of a race
track tour group Friday morning. She had spotted the trademark
shock of white hair and those John Lennon tinted glasses as soon as
the black BMW pulled up near the barn and the door opened.
</P>
<P>
   He has become the most recognizable guy in his sport. He's part
Beach Boys, part Seinfeld, and a little Amazing Kreskin to boot. He
shows extraordinary racetrack insight and precision, yet at the
same time he's hip and comfortable and funny. It's a mix that makes
people embrace him all the more.
</P>
<P>
   Today _ with the 125th running of the Kentucky Derby _ Bob
Baffert is aiming at an unprecedented third consecutive victory in
America's premier horse race. Over the years, five trainers have
won back-to-back Derbys, but none of them had the kind of
three-peat chance that Baffert has today.
</P>
<P>
   He has three entries in today's 19-horse field, including the
3-1 Morning Line favorites in the chestnut gelding General
Challenge and the filly Excellent Meeting. His other colt, San
Felipe winner Prime Timber, was 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   Add in his Silverbulletday, who won Friday's Kentucky Oaks filly
race by two lengths _ and likely would have been the Derby favorite
were she put in against the boys today _ and you see just what a
force Baffert has become.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he's just a nose away from already having three
straight Derby wins. In 1996, Cavonnier, his first Derby horse, was
nipped at the wire by Grindstone. Even more impressive is that last
year he was just as close to becoming the sport's first Triple
Crown winner in 20 years. Real Quiet _ who had added the Preakness
crown to his Derby triumph _ lost by a bob of the head at the
Belmont finish line. The year before Silver Charm lost the Triple
Crown by three-quarters of a Belmont length.
</P>
<P>
   No trainer in history has made such a quick impact at the
Kentucky Derby as has Baffert. Yet the more everyone tried to get
the 46-year-old trainer to talk about what it's like to hold horse
racing firmly by the tail, the more he deflected attention with a
joke or some whimsical, self-deprecating reflection.
</P>
<P>
   And so he talked about showing up at Los Alamitos race track in
1976 with four horses and a goat: ``And the goat was worth more
than all four horses.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was telling you this, he was standing in front of a
Churchill Downs barn that currently houses 33 horses he's training
with his two assistants and 15 stablehands.
</P>
<P>
   Owners now flock to him because they have found the style comes
with true substance. Said Bob Lewis, the top-dollar horseman who
introduced himself to the virtually unknown Baffert at Santa Anita
in 1992:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for compatibility and chemistry and here was a
guy willing to have some fun. But he had this humility, too. One of
the first things he told me was, `I do pretty good with sprints. I
know nothing about going long. I have to take some lessons.'''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert started on racing's bottom rung and had a long and
laborious climb to the top of the sport. He was raised on a cattle
ranch in Nogales, Ariz., and then, because he liked the social life
better than his lessons, he ended up struggling through the equine
program at the University of Arizona in six years. As his dad was
saying the other day: ``Bob's sophomore year was three of the best
years of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while Baffert worked as a substitute teacher and finally
he immersed himself in the blue collar, knock-about world of
quarter horse racing. By 1990, he had become a two-time winner of
one of the sports top races, the Champion of Champions. That caught
the attention of Mike Pegram, the businessman who bankrolled his
initial jump to thoroughbreds and now owns Real Quiet and
Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Baffert said the learning curve was steep, which
explains what happened with Thirty Slews, a sprinter he thought
would be his first Derby horse. He brought it to the Lexington
Stakes and, as veteran trainers snickered, the horse barely made it
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor old Thirty Slews,'' Baffert said. ``I almost ruined that
son of a gun. He got back to the barn that day and he was all hair
and lactic acid. It took about three hours to cool him out. It was
one of those deals where you learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later Thirty Slews won the $1 million Breeders Cup
Sprint. That eventually led to Cavonnier and the string he's put
together now. He said he's succeeded, in part, because he listened
to Charlie Whittingham, the 86-year-old Hall of Fame trainer who
just died: ``He made me realize nobody is bigger than the game.
Charlie's best quote was `Horses are like strawberries. They can go
bad on you at any time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yet from the tenuous nature of the game, Baffert's been able tug
on the strongest fibers. The best thing about Baffert, said jockey
Gary Stevens _ who rode Silverbulletday, Friday, and will be aboard
General Challenge today _ is his ability to spot yearlings who will
have the stamina and mental strength to race the 1 1/4 mile Derby
so early in their three-year-old career.
</P>
<P>
   And so Baffert spent just $85,000 for Silver Charm and a bargain
basement $17,000 for Real Quiet. Such foresight is why an owner
like 76-year-old Aaron U. Jones _ nearly out of the game _ came
back with a vengeance when Baffert got him his first Derby
contender in Prime Timber. It's why 77-year old John Mabee _ also
without a Derby win _ put Baffert in charge of General Challenge
and also let the trainer talk him into running his filly Excellent
Meeting in today's race.
</P>
<P>
   Even though only three of the 36 fillies who ever entered this
race have won, Baffert said the rugged Mabee filly has a shot and
everyone seems to agree.
</P>
<P>
   Yet rather than focus on these days when people hang on his
every word, he again changed the conversation to times more
obscure. And that led to a story about the quarterhorse race he won
one Halloween night in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   As the jockey brought the horse to the winner's circle and the
owners, groom and hangers-on gathered for the traditional track
photo, no one could find Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   That's when a guy came stumbling from the grandstands with a
Jack'O Lantern on his head. He posed with the group, the crowd
cheered and then Baffert pulled the pumpkin from his head.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd stood and howled for him all the more.
</P>
<P>
   And if you were around Churchill Downs this week, you realized
they have not stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
