<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW INDUSTRIAL AVERAGE INCREASED 10.2 PERCENT IN APRIL
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average gained 10.2 percent in April,
the biggest monthly gain in more than a decade, and is up 17.51
percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday the Dow industrial average and Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell on fears that a bustling economy might produce
a bout of inflation. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 89.34
points, to 10,789.04, while the S&AMP;P 500-stock index fell 7.65
points, to 1,335.18. The Nasdaq composite index gained 14.41
points, to 2,542.85.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 5.66 percent,
from 5.52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. ECONOMY GREW 4.5 PERCENT IN QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew at a surprisingly robust 4.5 percent annual
rate during the first quarter of 1999. And America's economic boom
_ already the second longest on record _ shows no signs of
flagging.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE BANK TO BUY MERCANTILE
</P>
<P>
   Mercantile Bancorporation, a St. Louis bank that has been
cutting jobs and expenses after a three-year acquisition binge, has
agreed to be acquired by Firstar, a Milwaukee bank, in a stock swap
valued at $10.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF REPSOL AND YPF SURGE
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Repsol and YPF surged after Spain's largest oil
company expressed confidence that its unsolicited $13.4 billion
takeover offer for the Argentine rival would succeed. Alfonso
Cortina, the chairman of Repsol, announced the bid late Thursday.
If the merger occurs, it would create the world's eighth-largest
oil business. The high price offered by Repsol for YPF and the
support of the Argentine Government for the takeover made the deal
look likely.
</P>
<P>
   IBM MANAGER AGREES TO TESTIFY
</P>
<P>
   A manager from IBM's personal computer business has agreed to
testify in the rebuttal phase of the government's antitrust case
against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE GROUP FAILS TO SELECT A LEADER
</P>
<P>
   The World Trade Organization became leaderless after efforts to
appoint a New Zealander as new director general were blocked by
supporters of his Thai rival.
</P>
<P>
   TRADING ENDS ON TOKYO EXCHANGE
</P>
<P>
   Japan bade farewell to an era as the closing bell rang on the
trading floor of the Tokyo Stock Exchange for the last time.
Computers and cost-cutting put an end to face-to-face trading on
Asia's largest exchange.
</P>
<P>
   SUIZA TO SELL 57 PERCENT OF PACKAGING UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Suiza Foods has agreed to sell 57 percent of its domestic
packaging operations to a joint venture led by Vestar Capital
Partners for $367 million. Vestar, an investment firm, will own 51
percent of Suiza's plastics operations.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND BID FOR BANCA COMMERCIALE
</P>
<P>
   Banca Commerciale Italiana is discussing a merger with Banca
Intesa in a move that could result in a better offer for Banca
Commerciale shareholders than last month's $15.3 billion offer by
Unicredito Italiano. Either transaction would create Italy's
biggest bank.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON APPROVES POLLUTION RULES
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is expected to announce Saturday that he has
approved strict federal rules to control pollution from automobiles
and end the special treatment for most sport utility vehicles. The
rules would force oil companies to make cleaner fuel and compel
auto makers to redesign their engines and install larger catalytic
converters.
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNICATIONS SATELLITE IS LOST
</P>
<P>
   A Milstar communications satellite worth $800 million and a
Titan 4B rocket costing $433 million that was carrying the
satellite in its nose cone were lost after a launch in Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
