<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SHO-HNS &LR;      04-30 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE WOODLANDS _ The record will show that Joey Sindelar has not
won a golf tournament since 1990, when he emerged victorious at the
Hardee's Classic.
</P>
<P>
   But Sindelar, the midway co-leader of the Shell Houston Open
after his second 68, revealed Friday that, in fact, he scored a
major championship just last year.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, however, the PGA Tour doesn't recognize the
Father-Son tournament at Walt Disney World on the official money
list. But Sindelar and his youngest son, 6-year-old Ryan, swamped
the field in the six-hole event last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it was a darn nice trophy, too,'' Sindelar said. ``I keep
putting it in my trophy case, and my son keeps stealing it and
putting it in his.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, after nine years without tasting victory, winning at the
local Putt-Putt would be OK with Sindelar.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that he's halfway toward securing what would be
a significantly more noteworthy triumph after his work during the
first 36 holes at the Tournament Players Course at The Woodlands.
Sindelar played bogey-free golf to join Hal Sutton at 8-under-par
136 for the lead at the halfway mark of the SHO. Jeff Gallagher is
a stroke back at 137. Three players are at 138, and four more,
including David Duval, are at 5-under 139. Duval, the defending
champion, survived a double bogey on No. 15 to stay in contention.
</P>
<P>
   Sindelar said he had a little trouble believing the way he
toured around the TPC during the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to say this, because this is golf and it will
come back to get you, but the first 33 holes were very easy and
nice,'' Sindelar said. ``It must be like what David Duval does on a
medium day. It was fairways and greens and some short birdie putts.
Low stress. On the last few holes, I hit a couple of stinkers. But
for the most time, it was smooth sailing and it felt very, very
good. I feel like I'm in darn good position.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton had posted his 8-under total earlier in the day, but
Sindelar, who started on the back nine, drew into a tie when he
chipped in from the right of the fourth green, his 13th hole. His
approach on the par-4 had drifted about 12 yards right of the pin,
and the chip might have gone a good 10 feet past if the hole hadn't
gotten in the way.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Sindelar had an unexpected birdie, then saved his
round with some savvy play at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of chopped it up Nos. 7 and 9,'' he said. ``On 7, I
skulled a 9-iron over the green and hit another one of those chips
that just kept going and rolled 10 feet by, but I made the putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then on the ninth, I hit a 1-iron off the tee and was in
between clubs. I hit an easy 7-iron, and it went in the right trap,
which was nowhere to be. I didn't even get the trap shot on the
green, although it wasn't a bad shot. It was about 12 feet, and
that putt went in.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I got away with a couple there coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot has changed on the PGA Tour since the last time Sindelar
won. The tournament he won that year has changed names twice in the
subsequent nine years. But when Sindelar entered the interview room
after his round Friday, he noticed other differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been anywhere close to this complex, and it's
nice,'' Sindelar said. ``Press areas have changed a lot since the
last time I used them. Gosh, purses went up and press rooms got
better.''
</P>
<P>
   It has taken awhile, but so has Sindelar's game. He was a
consistent contender through the late '80s, and the win in '90 was
his sixth in seven years on tour. But since that victory, Sindelar
has only one second-place finish to his credit.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, he believes his game is much better now than it was
when he was winning occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean this arrogantly, but nobody has ever won a golf
tournament playing that bad as when I won Quad Cities that year,''
he said. ``It was duck hooks and block-outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But about '93, I made some decisions about my game and found a
few fixes, mainly about getting extension through the swing. That's
the one thing I try to make sure I'm doing when things start going
not as well as they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sindelar would like nothing better than to complete a comeback
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, meanwhile, is trying to extend his. He won twice last
year to break a two-year drought and is looking for his first win
of '99.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game has been good, and I always like coming to Houston,''
Sutton said. ``This is familiar territory for me, and I feel like
the potential is there for me to accomplish good things on this
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton started on No. 10 and birdied Nos. 13, 15 and 17 to get
himself to the top of the leader board before conditions got
breezier in the late morning and afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody overpowered the TPC. The low score Friday was 68, shot by
seven players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little faster and a little firmer out there,'' Sutton
said. ``The course is playing a little harder. It's just harder to
get the ball as close as we did the first day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
