<HEADER>
A0356 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN     04-30 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORRY LIGHTENS LOAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The season was weighing on Los Angeles Lakers
reserve forward Robert Horry, so he lifted his burden by removing
his lifting.
</P>
<P>
   Horry changed his weightlifting routine two weeks ago after
determining the increased muscle mass had altered his shooting
form. Once he lightened the load, his 3-point stroke returned as
though it were an obedient pet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels really good now, better than it has all season,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After making five 3-pointers in a 24-game stretch through March
and half of April, Horry has drained 11 of 19 since adjusting his
lifting routine seven games ago. That includes a watershed 6-of-8
performance in the Lakers' rollicking victory Thursday over
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shoulders are naturally forward, but when I lift a lot of
heavy weight, it strengthens my muscles and pulls my shoulders
back,'' said Horry, who leads the Lakers in 3-point shooting (49
percent). ``That changes how I hold my arms, and it changes my
shoulder position when I shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain, but my whole (shooting motion) is
different. Now, it feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry never lifted weights during his bombardier days in
Houston, when he complemented Hakeem Olajuwon's post presence with
uncanny 3-point marksmanship. Then again, he didn't have to. He was
strong enough to defend opposing small forwards without the
weights.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers use Horry as a power forward, and that requires
additional strength, especially for post defense. He hasn't
eliminated weights altogether, but he has cut back significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to maintain right now,'' he said. ``The other thing
is, I wasn't playing but 15 minutes a game (in March and early
April), so that meant I had to lift more to stay in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all: Horry also benefited from coach Kurt Rambis'
tactical adjustment Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of running cutters through the lane when Shaquille
O'Neal had the ball in the low post, the Lakers stationed shooters
around the 3-point line and dared the Blazers to double-team Shaq
from longer distances.
</P>
<P>
   When they did, he whipped the ball to an open teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Often, that was Horry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we stayed spread out was the way (Horry) played in
Houston,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said he urged the spread formation during the team
meetings Tuesday. His point was this: using cutters does nothing
but clog the lane, which makes it easier for defenses to
double-team him. If the Lakers are spread, the lane stays clear.
</P>
<P>
   The formation is easy to execute and gives opponents two
options: play Shaq one-on-one, or leave a shooter open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to keep it simple,'' O'Neal said. ``We've got to use
what we've got. Utah uses (John) Stockton and (Karl) Malone. If you
double Malone, he kicks it to Bryon Russell.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of meetings: The Lakers didn't limit their Tuesday
meetings to strategy. With Derek Harper (no surprise) and Horry
(big surprise) doing much of the talking, they covered the gamut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about everything,'' Horry said. ``We talked about
getting paid and contracts and plays and what we need to do. It was
the most-productive meeting I've ever seen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-U.S.-NYT &LR;      04-30 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTGOING U.N. DEVELOPMENT CHIEF BERATES U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ With U.S. debt to the United Nations soaring
and contributions to development aid plunging, the outgoing chief
of the U.N. Development Program, the highest-ranking American in
the U.N. system, has accused the United States of ``tragic
shortsightedness'' in failing to support the world body.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has consistently ``undervalued, underutilized
and underfunded'' the United Nations and its agencies in recent
years, said the development chief, James Gustave Speth, a
soft-spoken environmentalist known to be close to Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Speth, who will step down at the end of June as head of the
United Nation's largest agency after six years, was interviewed
Wednesday in his spacious office with a panoramic view of the U.N.
Secretariat and Manhattan's East Side. He is leaving to be dean of
Yale University's School of Forestry and Environmental Studies.
</P>
<P>
   In words laced with frustration, he deplored what he called U.S.
``ignorance'' of the ``extraordinary'' role played by the United
Nations in preventing and containing conflict, sustaining
development and reducing poverty. He criticized not only the
Republican-led Congress, which has been holding $1.6 billion in
past dues hostage to anti-abortion and other domestic concerns, but
also the Democratic administration that had nominated him.
</P>
<P>
   While ``a lot more supportive'' than Congress, the Clinton
administration has also given the United Nations too little
priority, he said, often ``going it alone'' as a superpower and
failing to press for the implementation of its pledge to reward the
reforms it advocated.
</P>
<P>
   A troubling indication that Washington had given up its
leadership here, many United Nations officials said, was the
administration's decision to permit a non-American to replace
Speth, who was the sixth American to hold that post.
</P>
<P>
   Several diplomats and U.S. officials said that Washington had
given up the post in hopes of further reducing its contribution to
U.N. development aid. Last week, the General Assembly confirmed
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's nomination of Mark Malloch Brown,
the British-born World Bank vice president, as Speth's successor.
</P>
<P>
   The UNDP, the world body's main foreign-aid arm, has about 5,000
employees in 130 offices throughout the world and disburses about
$1.9 billion of its $2.2 billion budget to fight poverty and
underdevelopment. Europeans, resentful of the United States for
failing to pay $1.6 billion in assessments, had campaigned for the
UNDP slot.
</P>
<P>
   Although the agency's budget comes from voluntary contributions,
America's portion of the budget has been dropping. In the new issue
of Foreign Affairs, Speth called Washington's aid budgets
``particularly stingy.'' In the interview he noted that while
Nordic countries contributed about $16 per capita to his agency,
America's per capita contribution stood at 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The drop comes at a time of growing poverty amid abundance.
Almost three-fifths of the world's 4.4 billion people in developing
countries live without basic sanitation; almost one-third are
without safe drinking water; a quarter lack adequate housing, a
fifth are malnourished and 1.3 billion live on less than $1 a day,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans have no sense of how desperate the lot of one
half of humanity is,'' Speth said.
</P>
<P>
   Speth said that although the United Nations had made ``dramatic
progress'' in eliminating duplication and waste, and that his own
agency had undergone ``significant restructuring'' _ spending
nearly a fourth of its budget now on projects that promote better
government, democracy and market forces _ the administration's
budget request of $80 million this year was still 20 percent less
than what it requested and Congress approved.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that a weakening of the United Nations' development
efforts would undermine the organization's peacekeeping activities.
``It is the hands-on work of helping people in 160 countries around
the world that builds up the credibility of the United Nations and
gives it access,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Bolton, senior vice president of the Washington-based
American Enterprise Institute, disagreed with Speth's suggestion
that failing to support the world body's development work was
lessening its impact in world diplomacy. But he agreed with those
who criticized the administration for not fighting to keep an
American in the agency's top job. It showed yet again that the
administration was ``spineless'' and ``without vision,'' Bolton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert DeVecchi, a senior fellow at the Council on Foreign
Relations and president emeritus of the International Rescue
Committee, said that the nationality of the administrator mattered
less than his competence. U.S. relief workers were ``delighted''
with Malloch Brown's appointment, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
