<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODEL-SCULPTURES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY IS MODEL OF MODERN MAJOR MODEL SHOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One of the key cradles of Hollywood's show
business resides not on a studio lot but at a former machine shop
in a distinctly unglamorous industrial section of the San Fernando
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   At 7-year-old Rijn &AMP; Reisman, Hollywood's rubber meets the road.
The company in the North Hollywood community of Los Angeles' San
Fernando Valley, usually staffed by fewer than a dozen employees,
is where artistic whimsy is transformed into actual physical form
for the world's leading theme parks and movies such as ``Mars
Attacks!'' ``An American Werewolf in Paris,'' ``Edward
Scissorhands,'' ``Death Becomes Her'' and ``The Postman.''
</P>
<P>
   The building's exterior is topped by a pair of the ``Batman''
gargoyles, designed by co-founder Leo Rijn, and a 4-foot-high
company logo _ a three-dimensional version of the hands from the
Moment of Creation portion of Michelangelo's Sistine Chapel
painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main role is taking a two-dimensional design and making it
three-dimensional,'' said co-founder Andy Reisman, whose background
includes stints as manager at theme park designer Landmark
Entertainment and the model shop at Universal Studios Florida.
``Our logo reflects that plus our philosophy _ hands-on work and an
Old World style.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its humble setting, Rijn &AMP; Reisman's profile is likely
to be on the rise. It recently completed its largest project ever
by cranking out dozens of the characters used at Universal Studios'
upcoming Islands of Adventure, due to open next month in what's
seen as a frontal assault on Walt Disney World's stranglehold on
the Florida theme-park business.
</P>
<P>
   Starting three years ago, the company built models and maquettes
(industry lingo for preliminary models) for four of the five
``islands'' of the new park _ ``Seuss Landing,'' ``Toon Lagoon,''
``Lost Continent'' and ``Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   It staffed up to 25 artists in an effort to work out such
diverse looks as The Cat in the Hat ride, the Green Eggs and Ham
restaurant, Merlin's Magic Shop, Dudley Do-Right's Ripsaw Falls
ride, the Mulberry Street Emporium, Jurassic Park and Popeye and
Bluto's Bilge Rats ride.
</P>
<P>
   The shop eventually created more than 40 maquettes for Seuss
Landing, the first time the Seuss characters have been employed at
a theme park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audrey Geisel (widow of Seuss creator Theodore Geisel) wanted
to know what we were doing at the early stages, so we made a
maquette of the Cat in the Hat in the bathtub,'' Reisman recalled.
``We're now recognized as having our finger on the Cat's look.''
</P>
<P>
   The tricky part was getting all the artists to generate a unique
look, one that would be distinctive from those for Walt Disney
characters. ``The lines for Dr. Seuss characters have wiggles and
are much wonkier,'' Rijn said. ``The Disney lines tend to be fairly
puffy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the characters were digitized and built as full-size
sculptures. ``We often found ourselves in the position of not only
`translating' imagery and ideas originally conceived on paper but
also in the role of problem solvers while crafting the items into
3-D,'' Reisman said. ``Art directors can be amazingly focused on
details that no one else ever sees.''
</P>
<P>
   With no other major theme parks due to open this year,
Universal's $2billion theme park expansion may lead to
significantly higher visibly for Rijn &AMP; Reisman. Among industry
trackers, Islands of Adventure has become one of the most watched
developments in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Universal, which has already opened a CityWalk entertainment
complex next to its Universal Studios Florida, faces a major task
in convincing customers to stay longer and spend more at their
Florida complex rather than at the Disney resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury's kind of out on Islands of Adventure,'' said
entertainment industry analyst Linda Bannister of Edward Jones.
``Universal has done a lot of advertising, and that's bound to have
some impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Rijn and Reisman are looking beyond Islands of Adventure these
days. The founders believe expansion in theme parks and casinos has
slowed, leading them to search for new business such as movies and
toy design.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking to get noticed from Islands of Adventure,''
Reisman admitted. ``Until now, we've mostly stayed in the
background and established a niche as a high-end player.''
</P>
<P>
   In its top years, Rijn &AMP; Reisman has taken in $1.5 million in
revenue annually, but the founders are not looking to augment that
figure significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we did much more than that, we wouldn't be hands-on; we'd
be administrators,'' Reisman said. ``What we do here is by far the
most exciting part of the project because after we're done, it
becomes mostly a bunch of problems to be solved. Once we've done
models and maquettes, the fun part is mostly over.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
