<SLUG> BC-NEWCOM-ACTIVITY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLURRY OF TRADING HURTS NEWCOM STOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shares in modem maker NewCom Inc., based in
Westlake Village northwest of Los Angeles, fell Friday, one day
after exceptionally heavy trading in the stock nearly doubled its
price.
</P>
<P>
   NewCom shares dropped 9.375 cents, or 14.29 percent, to close at
56.25 cents, on volume of 845,000 shares, or five times the issue's
30-day average daily volume. That compared to an 83 percent gain
Thursday on volume of 1.5 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   With no official news either Thursday or Friday, speculation was
rife among investors as to what caused the initial spike.
</P>
<P>
   A message board dedicated to NewCom on Yahoo.com was crowded
with claims that someone _ though no one seemed to know who _ was
``pumping and dumping'' the stock, a practice in which investors
buy shares in a company, sell it to themselves under a different
name and buy it back at a higher price. The expectation is that by
repeating the process several times, it will draw other buyers on
whom the perpetrator can ultimately dump the stock.
</P>
<P>
   The computer modem maker has struggled in recent years as profit
margins in the industry thinned and competition from larger
companies cut into sales. In January, NewCom appointed an interim
president and laid off one-third of its employees after announcing
disappointing earnings. But the company has had no news since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no reason at all'' for the increase in trading, said
Dianne Will of Willstar Consultants, which handles investor
relations for NewCom. ``My phone's been ringing off the hook, but I
have nothing to say.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
