<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-RUSH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guns high on Y2K checklists
 &HT;    By Marc Freeman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Business is booming at area gun and pawn
shops thanks to the specter of a societal meltdown on Jan. 1 _
should the worst computer malfunctioning Y2K scenarios come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't keep a cold AR-15 on the shelf,'' said J.B. Stevens,
who owns Gator Guns &AMP; Pawn in suburban West Palm Beach, referring
to a brand of automatic rifle. ``People don't very well believe the
government, that everything's going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem is a computer programming flaw that businesses
and governments are spending billions of dollars to fix before Jan.
1, 2000. Most older computers can't recognize dates after Dec. 31,
1999, meaning that they will count 2000 as 1900 _ unless they are
reprogrammed in time.
</P>
<P>
   Public officials and major corporations say they're fixing the
flaw and there will be no major problems come New Year's Day. But
doomsday theorists and many average citizens _ some polls say one
out of every four Americans _ expect worldwide financial markets,
international defense systems and communications circuits to crash.
If not permanently, then at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``People honestly believe you'll have looting and everything
else, like after a bad hurricane,'' said Mary Cummings, owner of
Sportsman's Locker in Royal Palm Beach, who said her business is
``absolutely'' on the rise. There's also a run on rifle bullets,
she said. ``They are definitely stocking up on ammunition.''
</P>
<P>
   Some local gun sellers say business is up as much as 10 percent.
National weapons distributors say they are having trouble filling
orders because the public demand has been too much for
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, local gun dealers contacted Friday said
customers seeking to stock home arsenals were repeating a familiar
litany: If the Y2K bug hits, we want to be ready for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Why buy now?
</P>
<P>
   Here's their thinking: When the computers crash and the banks
shut down, we won't be able to get money to buy guns. If the
government's computers are down, they won't be able to run criminal
background checks and we won't get our guns. And our families and
homes will be left unguarded as society descends into utter chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are concerned about their safety and I don't blame
them,'' said Patrick Hayes, manager of Trail Guns in Lake Worth.
``They want to be protected in case computers and everything does
go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Milelli, Palm Beach County's director of public safety,
says residents have nothing to fear and should save their gun and
ammo money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not going to be any major, major catastrophes related
to the Y2K issue,'' he assured. ``Banks, water and sewer systems,
electric utilities, telephone systems, traffic control devices _
all of the computer software that controls those things are Y2K
compliant. Governmental institutions will not collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
