</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SAY THEY DID NOT FOLLOW UP COMPLAINT ABOUT COLUMBINE
KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite 2nd graf and make it more accurate. Inserts new
5th graf. Adds information to 6th graf. Inserts new 11th and 12th
grafs, beginning: It is not clear ... Inserts new 23rd and 24th
grafs, beginning: Gardner told the school's two deans ...) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Law enforcement officials here acknowledged
Friday that they did little to follow up a complaint a neighbor
made last year that one of the teen-agers responsible for the
killings at Columbine High School last week ``talks often of making
pipe bombs and using them to kill numerous people.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials, from the Jefferson County sheriff's office, also
said they told the sheriff's deputy assigned to the school and two
administrators at Columbine about the complaint. The deputy engaged
in ``light conversation'' with the teen-ager, Eric Harris, and his
friends, but did not pick up signs that Harris was engaged in a
year-long plot that ended in a massacre at the school.
</P>
<P>
   In releasing a copy of the complaint Friday, the Jefferson
County sheriff's office said it did not confront Harris or his
parents because the neighbor who made the complaint did not want
the Harrises to know he had done so.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the strongest evidence to emerge that law
enforcement officials had warnings before Harris and a friend,
Dylan Klebold, attacked Columbine with 30 pipe bombs and guns,
killing 13 people and themselves. The March 18, 1998, report also
said that Harris and Klebold made and detonated pipe bombs.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the complaint was filed, Harris began a diary that
laid out the plan to blow up the school and a grand scheme to
attack neighboring homes, hijack a jet and crash in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, sheriff's officials, noting the
volume of complaints involving bombs they received last year,
defended themselves against mounting criticism that they had
ignored signs that the two teen-agers were unstable and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the two-page report were copies of Harris' Web site
delivered to sheriff's investigators by the neighbor, Randy Brooks
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report noted that Harris wrote three times on his
Web site about ``wanting to kill'' Brown's son, Brooks, Lt. John
Kiekbusch said Friday that the investigation did ``not get to the
point where a crime was identified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all learned a lesson on April 20th,'' Kiekbusch said when
asked if his office had mishandled the complaint. ``We need to take
these in a more serious fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether the sheriff's office knew that six weeks
before the complaint, Harris and Klebold were arrested for breaking
into a van.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns, who have complained bitterly of inaction by the
sheriff's office, did not answer a telephone calls Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that they were unable to call up the Web site
on their own computers, apparently because the site was down. They
said they did not contact the parents of the two young men because,
as Deputy Mark Miller noted in his report, Brown ``was very anxious
in remaining anonymous in making this report and did not want
Harris or Klebold to have knowledge about his reporting them.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the report said, had reported Harris to the sheriff's
office in 1997, and now feared that he would take revenge on his
son, a classmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``God I can't wait till I can kill you people,'' a section of
the Web site entitled ``Philosophy'' said. ``I'll just go to some
downtown area in some big ass city and blow up and shoot everything
I can. Feel no remorse, no sense of shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if I live or die in the shootout, all I want to
do is kill and injure as many of you'' as possible, he said in one
of many diatribes laced with obscenities, misspellings and phrases
in broken German.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who was under some type of psychiatric care at the time,
wrote, ``No I am not crazy, crazy is just a word.''
</P>
<P>
   After three and a half pages listing, ``You know what I hate,''
he described the detonation of a homemade pipe bomb: ``Flipping
thing was heart-pounding, gut-wrenching, brain-twitching,
ground-moving insanely cool!''
</P>
<P>
   In a followup complaint, dated April 11, 1998, a sheriff's
deputy reported that Judy Brown had complained that Brooks, her
son, had just received an anonymous threatening e-mail. The
reporting deputy wrote, ``They are very concerned and requested an
extra patrol for the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Browns' plea for total anonymity, the death threats
were reported in the crime column of the March 25, 1998, edition of
The Columbine Courier, a weekly newspaper that serves the school
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father downloaded and printed 10 pages in which the boy
threatened his son three times,'' read the three-paragraph item.
Without naming names, the article related how the father had filed
a complaint with sheriff's office. ``The boy also explained how to
make pipe bombs and use them against people.''
</P>
<P>
   While the complaint languished as an ``Open Lead'' for a
``Suspicious Incident,'' the sheriff's office did talk to deans at
Columbine and to Neil Gardner, the deputy assigned to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner told the school's two deans that ``Eric Harris was
possibly messing around with pipe bombs and explosives,'' said Rick
Kaufman, a spokesman for the county school district.
</P>
<P>
   He said the deans were not informed about the Web site. No
action was taken by the school because, Kaufman said, Gardner told
the administrators that the sheriff's office was investigating the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deputy Gardner, with this knowledge, occasionally engaged
Harris and Klebold, along with several of their friends and
associates in light conversation,'' Steve Davis, the sheriff's
spokesman, said Friday. ``Deputy Gardner made no observations of
inappropriate behavior and has stated that both Harris and Klebold
treated him with appropriate respect.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-30-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990430.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-30 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0370 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-     04-30 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LITTLETON, Colo.: appropriate respect.''   
<TEXT>
<P>
   That respect was thrown to the winds on the morning of April 20,
when Gardner responded to a call of gunfire at the school.
</P>
<P>
   The first police officer to encounter the attackers, Gardner has
described how a man he believed was Harris fired a fusillade of
about 10 rounds of semiautomatic rifle fire at his patrol car. The
sheriff's deputy has said that he fired back four or five shots,
then jumped behind a nearby Blazer and fired another three or five
times.
</P>
<P>
   Before retreating into the school, Harris apparently raked the
Blazer with another volley, shattering the windshield and rear view
mirrors and sending bullets ricocheting underneath the car. The
deputy, one of two policemen to fire at the assailants, was not
injured.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, officials said they had identified the person who
furnished the young men with the semiautomatic handgun, a Tec-DC9.
Dave Thomas, the county district attorney, said that investigators
had interviewed the last owner of the gun, as well as the pizza
store employee who apparently served as a go between.
</P>
<P>
   This high-powered 9mm pistol, the district attorney confirmed,
went from the manufacturer in Miami to a wholesaler in Illinois, to
a gun shop in a suburb north of Denver, to a gun show outside of
Denver last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of a handgun to a minor is a federal offense. Klebold
died at age 17. Harris turned 18 on April 9. The district attorney
hinted that arrests could be made in the gun case in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Crime laboratory technicians are conducting ballistics tests to
determine which guns fired the fatal shots. If bullets fired by the
Tec-DC9 did not kill anyone, the gun seller may face charges only
of illegal gun peddling, rather than being implicated in the
murders.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement authorities said Friday that they still had not
talked to the parents of the two suspects. The parents hired
lawyers the day after the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   For the living, Columbine students picked up their class
schedules Friday at Chatfield High School, long an athletic
archrival. On Friday, a new banner greeted the Columbine students:
``Rivals No More. Friends Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Some high school students have pledged to channel their grief
into a demonstration Saturday morning against the National Rifle
Association, which is holding its annual meeting in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short term, we want to show the NRA that we are not going to
be receptive,'' said Ben Gelt, an 18-year-old Denver high school
senior who has leafleted about 20 area high schools for the
protest. Referring to victims of gun violence, he said, ``If there
are a lot of kids there, it will show them that today's young
people, who are tomorrow's leaders, are not going to stand for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Friday, Wellington Webb, who faces
reelection as Denver's mayor next week, called on the gun group
``to cancel or postpone out of respect for the grieving families of
Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   In the angry atmosphere following the shootings, there have been
a series of threats _ bomb threats to the hotel where the NRA
members arrived Friday for their convention, and death threats to
the Klebold family. Doug Dean, a Colorado Springs state
representative who sponsored a bill this spring to loosen rules on
the granting of concealed weapons permits, has said that he has
received so many telephone threats that he may leave politics.
Dean, a Republican, is the House majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as a cold rain fell on a county park adjacent to the
school, a massive, spontaneous memorial was temporarily wrapped in
long swatches of white plastic sheeting. Famous worldwide, the
memorial has started attracting pilgrims from outside Denver.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Martin Luther King III, a son of the civil rights
leader, quietly walked among the rows of flowers, handmade
placards, artwork, poetry inscriptions, votive candles and teddy
bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``A nation is judged by how it treats its most precious
resource, and our most precious resource are our children,'' said
King, who came here from Atlanta to attend the funeral of Isaiah
Shoels. ``This kind of behavior shows we are not treating our
children justly.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Vice President Al Gore brought a bouquet to the
park. On Tuesday, it was the turn of Sarah Ferguson, the dutchess
of York. She said that the massive outpouring of popular mourning
reminded her of the public response to the death of her
sister-in-law, Diana, the Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly has the feel of Kensington Palace,'' she said as
she surveyed the damp field of bouquets. ``Everyone was there to
pay their respects. It certainly feels like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Historical Society has established an agreement
with county park officials to start removing the memorial on May
10. Each item that can be saved is to be cataloged and warehoused.
Some pieces may go into a traveling exhibit. Others may be
integrated into a permanent memorial at the site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
