<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC, IN INTERVIEW, SAYS NATO HAS `MISCALCULATED'  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS grafs 4, 5, 6 to move up and emphasize Milosevic's comments
on ethnic cleansing and NATO strategy; deletes last 2 grafs from
2nd take and 4th &AMP; 5th grafs from end of 2nd take.) (js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, insisted
in an interview released here Friday that Yugoslavs were ``willing
to die'' to defend their rights but at the same time outlined what
he described as a six point plan for settlement of the war.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparently carefully timed insight into his thinking,
Milosevic rejected outright a military presence in Kosovo composed
of an army but said that the ``United Nations can have a huge
presence if it wishes.'' Questioned more closely by Arnaud de
Borchgrave from United Press International, Milosevic said these
U.N. peacekeepers could bear sidearms for self-defense, and include
troops from non-NATO nations.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic rarely speaks in public, or grants interviews to
foreign media. His interview, which UPI said was given on Thursday
but was not released until Friday, appeared designed to coincide
with proposals aired more privately to the Russian envoy, Viktor
Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who has been called by British officials a ``serial
ethnic cleanser,'' made no reference to the more than 600,000
ethnic Albanians who have been expelled by his forces in the last
five weeks and denied that ethnic Albanian villages had been
torched by Serb forces. He acknowledged that his forces were ``not
angels'' but said they were not the ``devils'' they were made out
to be.
</P>
<P>
   On his interpretation of American strategy, Milosevic was
sarcastic. ``Your leaders are not strategic thinkers,'' he said.
``Short-term quick fixes, yes. They said let's bomb Yugoslavia and
then figure out what to do next. Some said Milosevic would give up
Kosovo after a few days of aggression from the air.''
</P>
<P>
   But NATO ``miscalculated,'' he said. ``You are not willing to
sacrifice lives to achieve our surrender,'' he said. ``But we are
willing to die to defend our rights as an independent sovereign
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement proposal by Milosevic, which included a draw down
of his forces in Kosovo as NATO withdrew its forces in neighboring
Albania and Macedonia, was far from meeting the five demands laid
out at the NATO summit last weekend. NATO has said that it wants an
international security force in Kosovo and that it stands ready to
create such a force.
</P>
<P>
   Giving an idea of the kind of non-military presence he would
accept, Milosevic said: ``There is no job for forces. What would
forces do? Just ruin our roads with tracked vehicles.'' He said
that members of any U.N. presence could carry ``self-defense
weapons'' but ``no offensive weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   De Borchgrave, 72, asked Milosevic few adversarial questions and
allowed Milosevic to ruminate at length unchallenged. UPI said the
two-hour interview took place at a modest house outside Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The interview was conducted in English, according to UPI.
Milosevic was a banker in New York for the Communist government of
Yugoslavia during the 1980s and learned idiomatic English during
that period.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration dismissed Milosevic's ideas on a
settlement as ``falling far short of what's needed to end the
bombing,'' according to David Leavy, a spokesman for the National
Security Council. Leavy described Milosevic's statements as
``propaganda spewing from the highest source.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav leader said that in order for a ``compromise'' to
be worked out with NATO, he would demand that the alliance withdraw
its troops ``now concentrated on our borders in Albania and
Macedonia,'' and at the same time he would draw down Serb forces in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic gave a far higher number of Serb forces in Kosovo _
100,000 _ than NATO has announced. NATO has said that Milosevic has
about 40,000 troops in the province. NATO's supreme commander, Gen.
Wesley Clark, said earlier this week that despite NATO bombing,
Milosevic had managed to reinforce his troops in Kosovo and had a
higher number there now than at the start of the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked specifically by de Borchgrave if he had increased his
troops from 40,000 to 100,000, Milosevic said he had done so after
hearing ``NATO voices urging political leaders to order ground
forces into action.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other points in Milosevic's proposal were ``the return
of all refugees, regardless of their ethnic or religious
affiliation.'' He made no reference to the fact that all of the
refugees now in neighboring countries are ethnic Albanians and that
those Serbs who have left Kosovo during the NATO bombardment
largely went to Serbia proper.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. mission that he proposed would, he said, come to Kosovo
as ``our guests'' and would be there to ``observe that all is
peaceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Many times in the interview, Milosevic said he could not accept
any foreign forces in Kosovo because they represented an
``occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   Listing countries that he he would find acceptable in the U.N.
mission, Milosevic named Ireland as a European country that was not
a member of NATO. He also favored contingents from Russia, Ukraine
and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic described the negotiations at Rambouillet in France,
where Washington, four European countries and Russia failed to
persuade the Serbs to agree to 28,000 strong peacekeeping force, as
a ``diktat.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the peacekeeping force of 28,000, including 4,000
Americans, was planned with tanks, armored personnel carriers and
heavy weaponry and, hence, was unacceptable. ``Aid not arms is what
Kosovo needs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of Milosevic's proposal was what he called the
``political process'' that he said he was conducting with the
ethnic Albanian leader, Ibrahim Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and its NATO partners have questioned
whether Rugova, the head of the moderate political forces in
Kosovo, was acting voluntarily in his talks with Milosevic. A
German newspaper reporter who said she was with Rugova at his home
in Pristina after the NATO bombing began said Rugova was a hostage
of Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said that he would ``continue direct negotiations with
Mr. Rugova in the presence of the international community.'' But he
said the international community could not act as mediators.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing language from the proposed Rambouillet accords,
Milosevic said, ``We want to achieve the widest possible autonomy
for Kosovo within Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, Milosevic fell short of one of NATO's key demands, which
states that Kosovo would be set up as ``an international
provisional administration'' with ``substantial autonomy'' within
Yugoslavia. Serbia is the dominant of the two republics in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Milosevic's most revealing comments came when he
described his version of what had gone on in Kosovo. In some
respects, his descriptions appeared to be the obverse of those
heard in the West.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the Kosovo Liberation Army, the guerrillas of the
ethnic Albanians who make up the majority of the Kosovo population,
as wanting to achieve a ``racially pure state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is precisely the opposite of what is happening in the
world. Ethnically mixed states is the trend in the new global
village,'' Milosevic said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has frequently charged Milosevic with the
``ethnic cleansing'' of Kosovo by expelling nearly half the ethnic
Albanian population in the last five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our regular forces are highly disciplined,'' Milosevic said.
``The paramilitary irregular forces are a different story.''
Painting a picture of the rule of law that Western governments
insist has not existed under Milosevic's authoritarian rule, he
said: ``We have arrested those irregular self-appointed leaders.
Some have already been tried and sentenced to 20 years in prison.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
