<SLUG> BC-WTO-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD TRADE ORGANIZATION DEADLOCKED ON CHOICE OF LEADER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The World Trade Organization will be leaderless on
Saturday, after efforts to appoint a New Zealander as the new
director general were blocked by supporters of his Thai rival.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting of delegates of the 134-nation group, which determines
global trading rules, bogged down in lengthy and heated wrangling
over who would replace Renato Ruggiero, a former Italian trade
minister, whose four-year term expired at 11:59 p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared late Friday that Mike Moore, a former prime minister
of New Zealand, had the edge over Supachai Panitchpakdi, Thailand's
deputy prime minister and commerce minister. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Supachai's supporters rebuffed the recommendation of Ali
Mchumo, Tanzania's trade ambassador and head of the selection
process, that Moore should be chosen because he had the strongest
numerical support, with 62 countries backing him and 59 supporting
Supachai. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mchumo also said that Moore, who was backed by the United
States, France and Germany, had the most widespread geographical
support, and that member countries expressed ``more positive
sentiments'' for him. These criteria were laid out to help the
members of the trade body achieve a consensus on Ruggiero's
successor.
</P>
<P>
   As the meeting stretched into the early morning hours,
Supachai's supporters called for a formal vote to record each
country's position on the candidates, noting that 13 countries had
not declared a preference.
</P>
<P>
   However, 40 countries, including the United States and the
15-nation European Union, opposed such a vote, arguing that it
violated the organization's traditional way of doing business.
Sixteen countries favored a tally.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was created four years ago to replace the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the World Trade Organization has
avoided putting countries on the spot by calling for votes, opting
instead to work to achieve general agreement among the developing
nations and the larger trading powers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the delegates met privately, they left the
consultations to express their views to journalists. Pakistan's
trade envoy, Munir Akram, asked whether Moore had the green light
for the job, said, ``No green light, not even amber.''
</P>
<P>
   Akram, who has been a leader among developing countries that
want one of their own leading the organization, said the vote total
did not represent a consensus. ``It shows it's split down the
middle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing his determination to complete the selection, Mchumo
declared, ``We will be here until the sun comes up, and we have a
new director general.'' But the delegates agreed to adjourn and
reconvene at 4 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The trade organization's struggle to select a new leader comes
just as it is preparing for a new round of trade liberalization
negotiations this November. It is also mediating a number of
fractious trade disputes between the United States and Europe and
grappling with China's application for admission.
</P>
</TEXT>
