<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCANTILE BANCORPORATION, LONG A BUYER, WILL BE BOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Wis.)  (lh) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mercantile Bancorporation, a St. Louis bank that has been
cutting jobs and expenses after a three-year acquisition binge, has
agreed to be acquired itself by Firstar Corp., a Milwaukee bank,
which announced the deal late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The two banking companies signed a definitive agreement for a
stock swap worth $10.6 billion, based on a price of $66 for each
Mercantile share. That is a premium of 29 percent over Mercantile's
closing price of $51.25 a share on Thursday, the day the terms were
agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   Mercantile's shares rose more than 11 percent to $57 in
extremely heavy trading Friday, a result of a swirl of merger
rumors and a report in The American Banker, a trade publication,
that identified Firstar as the most likely buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, which is subject to shareholder and regulatory
approval, Mercantile shareholders will receive a tax-free exchange
of 2.091 shares of Firstar stock for each Mercantile share they
own.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will create a bank with more than $75 billion in
assets, far smaller than the seven largest banks created by the
merger boom of the last few years. Many of the bank deals that
occur over the next couple of years will involve the large cadre of
small and mid-sized banks that still dot the country.
</P>
<P>
   A number of banks, including U.S. Bancorp, Fifth Third Bancorp
and National City Corp., had looked at Mercantile but decided
against acquiring it because they felt the price was too rich,
relative to the bank's profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Mercantile, under its chief executive, Thomas H. Jacobsen, has
made two dozen acquisitions in the last four years, pumping its
asset base up to $35.8 billion from about $15.9 billion. But
analysts said the bank's acquisition spree was overly hasty,
eroding the value of the franchise. The buying binge was not
accompanied by strong revenue growth, and profitability suffered.
That left the bank, which has about 11,000 employees, vulnerable to
a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Firstar's shares plunged 4.75 percent, to $30.0625, in heavy
trading Friday, with investors apparently expecting a deal that
would hurt Firstar's profitability. But Firstar, with $38 billion
in assets, has won investors' respect in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Firstar has a well-regarded chief executive, Jerry A.
Grundhofer, and a very profitable consumer branch network in
several states, including Wisconsin, Ohio, Kentucky, Illinois,
Indiana, Iowa, Minnesota, Tennessee and Arizona. It also has trust,
investment and other financial services units that analysts
consider well run.
</P>
<P>
   Grundhofer will continue as president and chief executive, while
Jacobsen, who will be based in St. Louis, will become chairman of
the Firstar board. Roger L. Fitzsimonds, Firstar's chairman, plans
to retire when the acquisition is completed, which is expected in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The new bank will still be far smaller than the Midwest's
dominant bank, Bank One Corp. of Chicago, which has $261 billion in
assets. But it will be closer in size to other regional rivals like
National City, which has $88 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Firstar may need to tread cautiously if it wants to avoid the
problems that plagued Mercantile. Firstar bought Star Banc Corp.
only about five months ago, and analysts have yet to deem that
merger a success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
