<SLUG> BC-NY-JAILS-HOSPITAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY RAISING STANDARDS FOR PROVIDER OF JAIL CARE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration plans to tighten its standards for
measuring the performance of the hospital that provides medical
care in the city's jails, a top city official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Deputy Mayor Joseph J. Lhota, said the city had
drafted a ``new protocol'' that included additional benchmarks to
be used to judge the quality of jail care provided by the hospital,
St. Barnabas in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Lhota declined to discuss details of the new standards, which
are spelled out in a $342 million managed-care contract that St.
Barnabas took over last year.
</P>
<P>
   However, he described them as ``deeper, broader'' than the 35
specific standards St. Barnabas must now meet, which include
ensuring that clinics are adequately staffed and guaranteeing that
any inmate who needs an HIV test gets one.
</P>
<P>
   For eight months, the Manhattan district attorney's office has
been investigating whether St. Barnabas committed criminal
negligence in its care of five inmates who died and dozens of
others who suffered serious medical setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   That inquiry also includes recent allegations by a city official
that his superior pressured him to water down a quarterly
performance report to make it more favorable to St. Barnabas, said
an official involved in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Lhota defended St. Barnabas' performance in the jails, saying,
``There is no doubt that St. Barnabas is acting in a much better
fashion'' than Montefiore Medical Center of the Bronx, which held
the contract until last year.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the administration had been developing the new
protocol over the last month in conjunction with a number of city
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for St. Barnabas declined to comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The city's jail care contract is being reviewed by City
Comptroller Alan G. Hevesi, who examines all city contracts and
originally had until next week to approve or reject the deal.
Because of the proposed changes, however, city officials said they
had resubmitted the contract, and the comptroller now has an
additional month to issue a ruling.
</P>
<P>
   David Neustadt, a spokesman for the comptroller, said the
additional time would allow the comptroller's office to ``make sure
that this contract has in it appropriate protocols for monitoring
and the implementation of performance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
