<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-134-5-CONNECTOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURBANK TO PRESSURE CALTRANS FOR REASSESSMENT OF EXPENSES FOR 134-5
CONNECTOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK _ Connecting the 134 and 5 freeways in all four
directions would cost too much to justify because of Caltrans'
design standards, according to a report released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But with strong political support for building the ramps to
connect two of the nation's busiest freeways, Burbank city
officials are asking for a second examination and plan to press the
California Department of Transportation to find a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not prepared to accept it and walk away from the
project,'' said Bob Tague, director of community development for
Burbank. ``We know there is strong political interest in building
the ramps.''
</P>
<P>
   A Daily News story outlined the problems caused by the lack of
connectors between the Golden State Freeway south and the Ventura
Freeway west and the 134 Freeway east and 5 Freeway north.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of those ramps is estimated at $80 million, but the
report says it would cost significantly more if the ramps were
built to Caltrans' specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, and Los Angeles County
Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich have said they support building
the ramps. Wildman has pledged to push for building the ramps as
part of a package of freeway improvements for the San Fernando
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Jess Reynolds, a former Caltrans design supervisor who worked on
the original interchange, said he has read the consultant's report
and thinks Caltrans is coming up with excuses rather than
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caltrans went out of its way to find ways not to do something
rather than finding a way to make it work,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if conventional ramps don't work, Reynolds said there may
be other ways to connect the freeways without forcing traffic on to
city streets. He suggested building new roadways between the sites,
which would take the traffic off residential streets and provide an
shorter and easier connection between the two freeways.
</P>
<P>
   The report by consultants Parsons Brinkerhoff Quade &AMP; Douglas is
scheduled to go before the Burbank City Council on Tuesday. The
cities of Burbank, Glendale and Los Angeles jointly commissioned
the study to determine whether it is possible to build the ramps.
</P>
<P>
   The links were left out of the 134-5 interchange when it was
built in 1967 because planners felt the population would not
generate enough traffic to warrant them.
</P>
<P>
   Now residents and officials say the lack of connections causes
too many problems. Motorists must exit the freeway and travel for a
mile along surface streets in a residential neighborhood to make
the connection.
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans officials have said the ramps would require 11 design
exceptions to be built. City officials have estimated that longer,
wider ramps built to Caltrans specifications could cost more than
$120 million and would require demolishing several residences and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans spokesman Jim Drago said design exceptions are allowed
but not if they sacrifice safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time do we shut out looking at ideas? The answer
is absolutely not,'' Drago said.
</P>
<P>
   Although a study of traffic volumes has not yet been done,
consultants said that preliminary estimates show not enough
motorists would use the connections to justify such an expensive
and potentially disruptive project.
</P>
<P>
   Tague said the city wants to convene a ``peer review'' of the
work by the consultants. That panel would include engineers from
Caltrans, the Metropolitan Transportation Authority and area
cities.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
