u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-ATLANTA-NYT &LR;      04-30 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALT LAKE CITY'S OLYMPIC SPIRIT FOUND IN ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first batch of documents made public Friday
regarding the 1996 Summer Olympics revealed that Atlanta bid
officials behaved in the same fawning manner that Salt Lake City
officials did in trying to lure the votes of members of the
International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   There was also evidence that Juan Antonio Samaranch, the
embattled president of the IOC, may have violated the rules
governing visits to bid cities by bringing an excessive number of
guests to Atlanta in the spring of 1990, five months before Atlanta
secured the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of four of the first nine boxes of information
released, however, revealed none of the serious improprieties that
scandalized Salt Lake City's bid, such as scholarship programs,
cash payments and exorbitant medical treatment that exceeded $1
million. Ten IOC delegates have resigned or been expelled.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta officials have acknowledged violating the $150 limit on
gifts to IOC members, and it has previously been reported that
Billy Payne, the chief Atlanta organizer, wrote a memo in 1990
considering scholarships, medical treatment and free plane tickets
as incentives.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta officials have continued to deny offering the lavish
personal and financial favors that disgraced Salt Lake City's
efforts to win the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The documents _ the first of 4,000 boxes _ were released Friday
under pressure by the Georgia attorney general to make them public.
</P>
<P>
   The documents portrayed the metamorphosis of Atlanta bidders
from naive beginners, turned down by Samaranch when they invited
him to dinner, to pragmatists who understood the sense of
entitlement to which visiting IOC members were accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta officials went to the 1988 Summer Olympics in
Seoul, South Korea, to begin their schmoozing with IOC delegates,
they first were given etiquette lessons on how to refrain from
offending their Korean hosts. Don't talk about Japan, communism or
the wife of your host, the bidders were told. Never leave the
concave side of the soup spoon facing down.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, in April 1990, Atlanta bidders knew exactly how
to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   They held a gathering called Springtime in Atlanta for 15 or 20
visiting IOC delegates and their guests. This was the last big push
to sway the members, who voted on Sept. 18, 1990. The visiting
delegates were flown by private jets on a side trip to Savannah,
Ga., the proposed site of Olympic sailing, for a ride on Steve
Forbes' yacht, the Highlander.
</P>
<P>
   Each jet was greeted upon arrival in Savannah by three
trumpeters on the red-carpeted tarmac, and the delegates were
ferried in a police-escorted motorcade to their hotel. Drivers of
the delegates were instructed not to speak unless they were asked a
specific question.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Brennan, a spokesman for the bid committee, suggested in a
memo to Payne that reporters' access be restricted on the boat trip
because there would be drinking and the presence of the news media
might inhibit the IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Teresa Samaranch, wife of the IOC president, brought along
two friends from Spain on the trip to Georgia, according to the
documents. It was not clear whether Atlanta officials paid for
their air fare or hotel accommodations, but if they did, it would
have violated IOC rules, which permit each delegate to bring one
guest per trip.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has previously said he was not restricted by the
gift-giving rules because he did not vote on which cities are host
to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta officials appeared eager to grant the wishes of the IOC.
They arranged a tour of the White House for Wu Ching-Kuo of Taiwan,
paid for Francis Nyangweso of Uganda to connect through London so
he could visit an ailing cousin and arranged a trip to the Masters
golf tournament in Augusta, Ga., for Matts Carlgren of Sweden, who
charged the bid committee $11,120.10 for first-class air fare from
Scandinavia for himself and his wife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
