u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOST-ROCKET-1STLD-WRI     04-30 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-ROCKET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY SATELLITE STRANDED IN A LOPSIDED ORBIT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS lede) 
(ATTN: Fla.)  (rk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A giant rocket failed to carry a communications
satellite into its intended orbit after launching from Florida
Friday, dealing the Air Force a third straight setback in a space
mission that cost well over $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is a very disappointing day,'' Brig. Gen.
Randy Starbuck told an early-evening news conference at Cape
Canaveral, confirming that a Titan 4B rocket costing $433 million
had failed to lift a satellite worth $800 million into proper
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of disappointment was heightened by the apparently
successful beginning of the mission. The 20-story rocket had lifted
off from the cape at 12:30 p.m. with the 10,000-pound Milstar
communications satellite in its nose cone. Mission planners dared
to be optimistic as the solid-fuel main booster rocket burned like
a giant Roman candle, carrying the satellite toward an orbit some
22,000 miles above the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   But an hour later, Air Force officials at the cape canceled a
scheduled news briefing about the mission. Friday evening, Starbuck
confirmed rumors that the upper-stage liquid-fuel booster had
failed to lift the satellite into its orbit over the equator once
the solid-fuel first stage had done its job by placing the
satellite in an initial orbit 3,000 miles up.
</P>
<P>
   The lost satellite was to have been used for military
communications around the globe, ``phones, computers, just about
anything,'' in the words of a Defense Department official who said
he was familiar with the mission. Both the satellite and the Titan
rocket were manufactured by Lockheed Martin Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's failure was the third consecutive disappointment for
the Air Force. Last Aug. 12, a Titan 4 carrying a spy satellite
blew up shortly after launching from Cape Canaveral at a cost of
well over $1 billion. And on April 9, a $250 million
missile-warning satellite was accidentally stranded in the wrong
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Starbuck said the failure of the upper-stage Centaur liquid-fuel
burner had left the satellite launched Friday stranded in a
lopsided orbit thousands of miles below its intended 22,300-mile
altitude.
</P>
<P>
   He said that mission controllers would try to use thrusters and
whatever liquid fuel remains to get the satellite into its proper
orbit, but that they were uncertain of their chances.
</P>
<P>
   The first Milstar satellite was placed in a 22,300-mile orbit in
1994 and a second in 1995. The Pentagon had planned to place six in
orbit altogether to provide secure and jam-proof communications
between commanders and troops.
</P>
<P>
   Starbuck, who is in charge of the Air Force's Cape Canaveral
launch site as commander of the 45th Space Wing, said it was too
early to speculate on causes for Friday's mishap. ``When we have
three failures in a row of any system,'' he told the press
conference, ``something is not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials said Friday's failure, if it cannot be
corrected, would not hamper the military's communications or the
nation's security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
