<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-GAS-PLANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RIGHT PLANT, WRONG PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, May 1: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US Generating Co. has asked New York state for permission to
build a gas-fired power plant near the western shore of the Hudson
River in Green County, an area of breathtaking natural beauty 120
miles north of New York City. From an engineering standpoint, it is
a good place to put a power plant. From any other perspective _
esthetic, environmental, historical _ it is the wrong place. Gov.
George Pataki should deny the application. Failure to do so would
set a poor precedent and tarnish his reputation for environmental
stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   This will not be an easy decision, as even conservationists
concede. In this new age of utility deregulation, aimed at
encouraging competition in an industry long dominated by local
monopolies, out-of-state power companies are romancing New Yorkers
with promises of more efficient plants and lower electricity bills.
Like any smart governor, Pataki wants these benefits.
</P>
<P>
   US Generating has a commendable environmental record, and the
gas-fired plant it proposes would emit far fewer of the pollutants
that cause smog or contribute to global warming than New York's
older oil and coal-fired plants. In terms of costs, the site itself
makes perfect sense. It lies at the confluence of the Iroquois
natural gas pipeline, power lines that can carry electricity to New
York City and New England, and the river, which can provide water
for the plant's cooling systems.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the site is also directly across from Olana, the
ornate 19th century Moorish mansion built by Frederic E. Church, a
central figure in the Hudson River School of painting. One expert
has called Olana ``the most aesthetically and historically
significant artists' residence in the United States'' _ significant
not just for the house itself but for the landscape that inspired
some of the artist's noblest works. The plant and its plumes of
steam would disfigure that view, not only from Olana but from
nearby parks and other historic homes.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also worry that the plant will harm fragile fish
populations. The company insists that the plant will actually save
fish by displacing older power plants along the river that suck in
much more water. But the main fear is that the plant will corrupt
an irreplaceable piece of visual history, an outcome the governor
cannot want. As he himself noted in his January State of the State
Message, ``preserving the historic places that reunite us with our
rich and glorious past is an obligation we must fulfill to the
children of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The final decision is largely controlled by Pataki, who
appointed the six members of the siting board that will rule on the
application, probably in October. The board is operating on a fast
track mandated by a flawed 1992 law designed to encourage
``one-stop shopping'' by utility companies. This law does not
require companies to offer alternative sites, thus requiring an
up-or-down vote on the company's preferred site.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the plant have taken hope from a ruling by the
federal Environmental Protection Agency that the siting board has
no power to issue the permits for discharges into the air and water
that the company will need to begin operation. But that problem
could be fixed by new legislation in Albany. The only certain way
to stop the plant is for the board to vote it down. This is an
important test. US Generating's facility would be New York's first
new power plant in 20 years. There will be more to come. It is
essential to establish the principle that the environment has a
claim in these decisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
