<HEADER>
A0419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     04-30 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW WORLD SYMPHONIES': WHAT EUROPE OWES TO AMERICAN MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(js) 
 BY EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American art music _ commonly called ``classical'' _ is in the
midst of an identity crisis. This is nothing new; such crises
almost define American music. Except that recently the autumnal
atmosphere has led to an unusual amount of self-scrutiny, including
a close examination of American music's origins, in varied studies
of 19th-century American musical life.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jack Sullivan, a professor of English and the chairman of
American Studies at Rider College, takes the subject in another
direction in his new book, ``New World Symphonies: How American
Culture Changed European Music.'' One of the recurrent
recriminations of American concert music is that it is idolatrously
beholden to Europe, which gave America its instruments, its
masterpieces and its concert halls. This is why, the argument goes,
concert music has become so marginal: the true musical life of the
United States is found outside the concert hall, in jazz, rock and
other popular musics.
</P>
<P>
   This argument is deeply flawed _ if applied to museums, novels,
political ideas and other European imports, it would lead to
absurdities _ but Sullivan gives it a piquant twist, showing not
how much American art music owes to Europe, but how much European
art music owes to America. Much of the detail is familiar: the
appeal of jazz to Stravinsky, the influence of black spirituals and
Indian chants on Anton Dvorak, the lure of Walt Whitman to Ralph
Vaughan Williams. But when the details are put together, the
portrait is startling. The spirit of America is inscribed in
20th-century European modernism.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the attraction was the sense that in America almost
anything was possible. The Czech composer Dvorak, who wrote his
``New World'' Symphony in New York while reading Longfellow's
poetry, celebrated the almost naive ``eagerness'' of Americans. In
contrast, Europe seemed stultified, tradition-bound. The most
popular opera of Weimar, Germany, ``Jonny Spielt Auf,'' by Ernst
Krenek (1900-1991), tells of a black American jazz violinist who
single-handedly undermines the ponderous pieties of European
culture.
</P>
<P>
   America almost took on an avant-garde character. The Australian
composer Percy Grainger (1882-1961) thought European music was
``hopelessly sunk in conventionality, sham intellectuality and
parochialism'' and longed for an ``American Messiah.'' The French
composer, Edgard Varese (1883-1965), who celebrated ``new worlds''
in his raucously experimental ``Am/erique'' (which later inspired
Frank Zappa), called for an American music that would reject any
``mummified European formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Even America's darker sides attracted the attention of European
composers. Puccini's American characters in ``Girl of the Golden
West'' and ``Madame Butterfly'' reveal something tragic in the
promise of American liberation. Sullivan's most fascinating example
is how deeply French impressionist composers like Debussy and Ravel
were affected by Edgar Allan Poe. Poe's characters may be steeped
in mummified traditions, but they are severed from that old world,
like envious Americans cut off from their origins, trapped in
isolation and horror. Composers who also felt cut off from their
European past set Poe's texts to music, adopted his esthetic and
emulated his refined despair.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, America's violations of innocence often got as much
attention as its innocence, particularly in its treatment of race.
The English composer Frederick Delius (1862-1934) was haunted by
his experiences living in Florida in 1884. His opera ``Koanga'' _
almost never seen or played _ is the tale of an African voodoo
prince whose curse brings a plague down on the Southern plantation
where he is enslaved. An anthology of black American poetry,
``Afrika Singt'' (``Africa Sings,'' published in the 1920s in
Germany, influencing such composers as Alexander Zemlinsky
(1871-1942) and Wilhelm Grosz (1894-1939); if the slaves found a
resonant mythology in the Biblical stories, these Jewish composers
found similar resonance in the poetry of enslavement.
</P>
<P>
   This is rich and heady stuff, full of oddities pointed out by
Sullivan: ``Koanga'' was a ``Louisiana voodoo opera written by a
native of Yorkshire living in Paris as a way of reinvoking
Florida'' ); Zemlinsky was ``a Viennese Jew setting black American
poems translated into German''; Samuel Taylor-Coleridge's
``Hiawatha'' was ``a setting by an Anglo Negro of a white
American's poem about Indians.'' There is something
phantasmagorical about these relationships with their shifting
identities, rebellions and yearnings.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Sullivan's story is not always felicitously told.
And there are many strands he does not touch on that would have
shown just how wide-ranging the America-obsession was and how
connected it was with Europe's disgust with its own past, and its
own panting desires for new beginnings. Some attention to the
American experimental avant-garde, which was often more celebrated
for its iconoclasm in Europe than in the United States, might have
helped reveal the issues at stake.
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan's descriptions are sure and telling. And his
accumulating anecdotes and portraits end up suggesting something
about our current predicament: the utopian prescriptions of
Europeans who idealized American possibility and derided their own
heritage have now evolved into the prescriptions of Americans who
idealize American popular culture and deride European influence. On
both sides of the Atlantic, the celebration of American promise has
hidden a cornucopia of discontents.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NEW WORLD SYMPHONIES: HOW AMERICAN CULTURE CHANGED EUROPEAN
MUSIC'
</P>
<P>
   By Jack Sullivan
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 262 pages. Yale University Press. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
